<SLUG> BC-BBA-OLNEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN AWESOME PERFECTIONIST WITH THE WILL OF A MULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BBA-RIBKEN)  
(lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Exhausted and emotionally drained, Cal Ripken Jr.
fell into a deep slump in the days after breaking Lou Gehrig's
consecutive-game record of 2,130 games on Sept. 6, 1995. He was a
national icon, a living symbol of dedication to excellence who
graced magazine covers and television screens, but that did not
help him when he was trying to hit fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour after an afternoon game in Detroit two weeks
later, Ripken carried a bucket of balls and a batting tee from the
visitors' clubhouse out to the empty Tiger Stadium field. He set
the tee on home plate, placed a ball on the tee and drove it to the
outfield. He emptied the bucket, walked around the field alone and
gathered the balls. And then he repeated the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken emerged from his slump two days later, and I was among
those watching, covering the Orioles for The Baltimore Sun. I was
in awe of Ripken's will and intelligent play and achievement; and
sometimes I found his allegiance to his own agenda to be appalling.
Like Joe DiMaggio, Ripken is and will forever be leery of the news
media, for it represents the only threat to his image, which he
protects zealously; I believe he ended his streak at 2,632
consecutive games last night because the trickle of criticism
regarding his motives was threatening to become a flood, and the
continuation of the streak had become blatantly superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   But there are unchallenged truths about Ripken: He always played
hard. He always played to win. He always played, in spite of
injuries minor and major. Baseball is lucky to have him.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's record became an albatross for the Orioles the last
three seasons, and his stubborness added to the burden. Ripken's
range at shortstop decreased markedly in 1996 and when Orioles
executives floated the idea of shifting him to third base, he
declared that anyone who thought his ability had lessened knew
nothing about baseball. When Davey Johnson, his former manager,
moved Ripken to third base for a trial period that July, Ripken
stopped speaking to his replacement, Manny Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken maintained that his streak was always at the mercy of his
manager. But he steadfastly refused to endorse any suggestion of
change, and his managers knew that taking him out of the lineup
would invite the wrath of a community devoted to the longtime
Oriole.
</P>
<P>
   He has stayed in separate hotels and exploited the privileges
inherent in being the city's favorite son. More than a month into
Phil Regan's only year as manager of the Orioles, in 1995, Regan
discovered that Ripken had been calling pitches from shortstop,
without telling Regan. Ripken injured his back in 1997, and even as
his production suffered and team officials wondered if he needed
rest, they did not know his true condition; Ripken went to his own
doctor. Earlier this season, Ripken responded testily to columnists
calling for him to end his streak by saying that considering his
age, his production was pretty good. In fact, the Orioles have the
worst third base production in the American League this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's autonomy gradually came to infect the rest of the
organization, with some veteran teammates openly resenting the
special treatment afforded him and others ignoring team rules. The
failure to run out ground balls has become an Orioles epidemic in
recent years, and the strong consensus of the team's management has
been that only Ripken _ who always plays hard _ held the power and
authority in the clubhouse to change the Orioles' often emotionless
approach. Ripken refused to get involved, however, refused to lead;
at the end he was a master of passive resistance. A man cannot play
in every game for more than 16 years without possessing the will of
a mule. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, Ripken will be remembered not for his role in
some disappointing Baltimore teams but for his devotion to
excellence and his invaluable contribution to baseball at a time
when the game desperately needed him. Ripken learned how to play
baseball from his father, Cal Ripken Sr., in a very specific and
regimented manner requiring endless hours of practice. The Oriole
way, as it is known in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Never fleet, Ripken became a Gold Glove-caliber shortstop by
learning the tendencies of opposing batters, anticipating where
they would hit the ball. Never a natural hitter, Ripken has
tinkered constantly with his stance, fighting through slumps and
minor injuries to become the greatest offensive shortstop in the
annals of the game, twice winning Most Valuable Player awards. He
needs 127 more hits to reach 3,000 for his career, and 16 more home
runs to reach 400.
</P>
<P>
   The players' strike of 1994 led to the cancellation of the World
Series that fall, and baseball owners furthered compromised the
credibility of the sport the following spring by attempting to use
replacement players. For baseball, it was the Dark Ages.
</P>
<P>
   But play resumed, and Ripken closed on Gehrig's record,
representing only the good in baseball, and he included fans along
the way. After games, he sometimes sat on the Orioles' dugout here
and signed autographs for more than two hours, thousands and
thousands of them. He paused to chat and engage in conversation and
make everyone _ especially kids _ feel as if they were part of
something special. On the emotional night he broke Gehrig's record,
he circled the park and fans reached out to him, and Ripken reached
back.
</P>
<P>
   With a week left in that season, I left the press box at 1 a.m.
at the same time Ripken began pulling away from the ball park in
his truck. Three fans waited for him in the dark, holding
baseballs. Ripken stopped and gabbed and signed, with the power of
healing that he employed with greater effectiveness than anyone
since another Baltimore son, known as The Babe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
