<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-SCHUMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHALLENGER: SCHUMER ASSAILS D'AMATO ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent in category `a') 
(Eds: Sidebar with NY-CAMPAIGN-DAMATO; see also NY-VALLONE-AD and
NY-PATAKI-AD) 
(nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Charles Schumer fiercely criticized Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato's voting record on gun control Sunday, saying the
Republican incumbent was more interested in collecting donations
from the National Rifle Association than protecting the lives of
New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a Democrat from Brooklyn, who is hoping to unseat
D'Amato in November, held a news conference in City Hall Park to
proclaim that D'Amato's record on gun control was ``one of the
worst in the whole Senate.'' He was surrounded by relatives of
shooting victims who thanked him for sponsoring the Brady bill,
which required background checks and waiting periods for handgun
buyers in most states.
</P>
<P>
   ``On gun control, the issue and the contrast of who sides with
working families and who sides with the special interests couldn't
be clearer,'' Schumer said. ``I have made it one of my life's works
to prevent more people from being behind me like this because
they've lost a loved one to gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato voted against the Brady bill and the federal assault
weapons ban, which outlawed the sale of 19 types of semiautomatic
weapons. Schumer accused him of protecting the interests of the
National Rifle Association, which he said has contributed $36,000
to D'Amato during his 18 years in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand when senators from Mississippi vote against
gun control,'' Schumer said. ``After all, there's a gun culture
there. But a senator from New York constantly siding against gun
control, with the National Rifle Association? We are here to ask Al
D'Amato why he continually does that.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for D'Amato, who was making a campaign swing through
upstate cities Sunday, countered that D'Amato was in fact tougher
on crime than his Democratic opponent. ``Chuck Schumer is trying to
hide his liberal record on crime,'' the spokesman, Harvey
Valentine, said. ``The fact is, Al D'Amato passed legislation in
the Senate for mandatory sentences for criminals who commit crimes
with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   That proposal never became law because it did not pass in
Congress, where Schumer opposed it, Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has railed against D'Amato every day since last Tuesday,
when he won the Democratic primary. D'Amato has complained about
the attacks in recent days, but Schumer said Sunday that he had no
plans to scale them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that Al D'Amato criticizing my comments on him in
this regard is like the British criticizing the patriots who fired
back at Bunker Hill,'' Schumer said. ``Boy, oh boy, let me tell Al
D'Amato: You've made every past campaign a one-sided campaign where
you are attacking your opponents viciously and nastily, and they
haven't answered back.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Chuck Schumer is going to answer back every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
