<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     09-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Two games into this season of their
rebirth, the Cowboys already stand at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   One might call it the intersection of Hope and Despair. The
defense looks shattered. Troy Aikman is broken.
</P>
<P>
   But all may not be lost. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   Not if one is a student of geography and can recognize the
Cowboys' place as smack in the middle of the NFC East, which is to
mediocrity what the Grand Canyon is to holes in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Little-used Jason Garrett begins his tenure as Dallas' starting
quarterback for the next month, maybe two, while Aikman recovers
from a broken left collarbone suffered last week in Denver. And
there could be hope. Really.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the most obvious difference between Aikman and
Garrett _ the former has led the Cowboys to three Super Bowl
titles, and the latter will be making his third NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   What is important to remember is where Garrett will be making
that start _ in Giants Stadium against the Giants, who are not
exactly playing very big these days.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Giants won the NFC East title a year ago. But that is
only because the league rules say somebody has to win and because
the listing ship that had been the Cowboys' own personal Titanic
under former head coach Barry Switzer finally slipped beneath the
waves.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Garrett _ who is actually older than Aikman _ is
greener than an unripe banana? He is not dueling with one of the
great ones in the Giants' Danny Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this statistic about the NFC East: Back in the 1993
season, the five starting quarterbacks for Week 3 play _ Aikman,
Phil Simms (Giants), Randall Cunningham (Eagles), Mark Rypien
(Redskins) and Steve Beuerlein (Cardinals) _ had 374 career starts
tucked under their belts. This year in Week 3, Garrett, Kanell,
Bobby Hoying, Trent Green and Jake Plummer have a total of 33
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Then consider this stat about the NFC East teams in Week 2 of
this season: They all lost, by a combined score of 157-76.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be true that the Cowboys' 42-23 thumping by the
Broncos was thorough, all that it definitely proves at the moment
is that new head coach Chan Gailey's team is not ready to compete
with the defending Super Bowl champs. But nobody in the NFC East is
wearing the jewelry of a title holder.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Michael Irvin had his head hung low at the thought
of playing without Aikman against the Giants. Offensive lineman
Nate Newton talked of being a rudderless ship.
</P>
<P>
   But because of nothing more than the miserable neighborhood in
which they reside, the Cowboys' season does not have to be over
before it could begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a very big blow for our team, no
question,'' said owner Jerry Jones. ``I'd love to be heading into
this game with Troy leading our offense. But I really do have
confidence that we can win with Jason Garrett.''
</P>
<P>
   That will, of course, happen only if the Cowboys can find a way
to plug the holes that were wide enough for Terrell Davis and a
fleet of tractor trailers to run through last week in Denver.
Assuming that not every team in the league has a Davis in its
backfield, maybe that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the Cowboys to have hope is that their
fourth-place schedule _ a souvenir from last year's 6-10 disaster _
does not serve them up a diet of juggernauts in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Following tonight's clash with the Giants, Dallas plays its next
five games against Oakland, Washington, Carolina, Chicago and
Philadelphia, which are a combined 1-13 on the season. The lone win
belongs to the Raiders, who are still as lost in the '90s as Al
Davis' wardrobe. That is hardly a murderer's row.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if Garrett can stay away from costly mistakes, if Irvin
and Emmitt Smith can help him out by making big plays, if the
defense can just put up a passable effort, it is not inconceivable
that the Cowboys could tiptoe through that stretch with a 3-3
record. That would get them to the halfway point in the schedule
with a 4-4 mark, and it's possible Aikman would be ready to return
by then, if he isn't already back. Standing at .500, the Cowboys
would quite likely be in striking distance of first in the NFC
East. Heck, that might even be good enough to have them all alone
in the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   First things first. That means taking care of the Giants, and to
do that means taking care of Garrett with a more controlled, more
conservative offense. It also means filling the gaping holes in a
leaky defense, or whatever problems come from missing Aikman will
barely be noticed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
