<P>
   Schumer has railed against D'Amato every day since last Tuesday,
when he won the Democratic primary. D'Amato has complained about
the attacks in recent days, but Schumer said Sunday that he had no
plans to scale them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that Al D'Amato criticizing my comments on him in
this regard is like the British criticizing the patriots who fired
back at Bunker Hill,'' Schumer said. ``Boy, oh boy, let me tell Al
D'Amato: You've made every past campaign a one-sided campaign where
you are attacking your opponents viciously and nastily, and they
haven't answered back.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Chuck Schumer is going to answer back every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-21 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ It was Sunday, so naturally Jeff Bagwell was feeling
thankful.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Thank God Richard Hidalgo was here,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   It was nice of Shane Reynolds to show up, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo hit a pair of solo homers, and Reynolds pitched seven
resilient shutout innings in the Astros' 2-0 victory over the
Pittsburgh Pirates at Three Rivers Stadium. Jay Powell pitched a
scoreless eighth, and closer Billy Wagner worked the ninth for his
30th save.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo's sixth and seventh homers accounted for two of the
Astros' seven hits, only five of which came against Pirates starter
Jason Schmidt, who didn't get enough help from his offense to
overcome his two mistakes to the Astros' rookie center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a good game,'' Hidalgo, who raised his batting
average to .291, said of Schmidt. ``He only made two bad pitches,
and I was ready for them. I was just able to hit those balls hard
and get two home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was No. 46 for the Astros on the road _ second-best in
the National League behind Atlanta _ and was their 99th overall. It
also pushed Reynolds one victory closer to becoming the first
Astros pitcher to win 20 games since Mike Scott in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory might have tested Reynolds' guile more than any
of the previous 18. The string of zeros across the scoreboard told
only half the story. The veteran righthander spent most of the
afternoon pitching around trouble and working out of jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like they were hitting the ball hard against
Shane,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``But they sure had an
awful lot of baserunners.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 11 of the 29 batters who faced Reynolds (19-8) reached
base. The Pirates advanced a runner into scoring position in each
of the first five innings and had runners in scoring position with
fewer than two outs in four of those innings. Reynolds' only 1-2-3
inning came in the sixth, but he faced more traffic on the bases in
the seventh, when the Pirates stranded two of the nine runners they
left on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some luck going today as far as being able to pitch out
of some jams,'' said Reynolds, who matched Darryl Kile's
team-leading victory total of a year ago. ``Sometimes, part of
pitching is being able to get key outs to get out of jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my best stuff, but you're not always going to
have your best stuff. A few times, it seemed like they were looking
for my off-speed stuff. You have to give the Pirates some credit,
too. They've got a bunch of good hitters who are young, and they're
out there swinging. Plus, they're fast, so if you don't get to some
balls in a hurry, they're going to beat them out.''
</P>
<P>
   An indication Reynolds wasn't working with his ``A'' material
was the fact he struck out only four batters. The Pirates had 10
hits in the game, all against Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give up 10 hits and still pitch seven shutout
innings, that's pitching,'' Bagwell said. ``Shane pitched a heck of
a game, and we needed it, because Schmidt is tough. I read
somewhere that he said he doesn't like to face us, but I sure don't
ever remember beating him up.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a deadly 1-2 punch by Hidalgo, the Astros
didn't put any serious nicks on Schmidt (11-13) this time, either.
Not counting Hidalgo, only two Astros reached second base _ on
leadoff doubles by Bagwell in the seventh and Derek Bell in the
ninth off Pirates reliever Mike Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard was about the only thing we had going on offense, but
that was all it took,'' Dierker said. ``After his second home run,
the guys in the dugout were saying, `When is Richard up again?' He
really gave us a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who also had a two-homer game against the Pirates on
Aug. 30, hit a first-pitch fastball into the left-field seats in
the first inning and a 3-1 heater far beyond the center-field fence
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really good,'' Hidalgo said. ``As soon as I hit those
balls, I knew they were gone. I was seeing his breaking pitches
good and laying off them so that I could try to get the fastball. I
was looking for the fastball both times, and that's what I got.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who threw 97 pitches, fell two innings shy of his
second shutout of the season. He wanted to finish the game, but
Dierker decided to call on his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, I won't take a guy out of a shutout,'' Dierker said.
``I felt he had enough left to finish the game, and I was actually
torn about what to do. But he was close to 100 pitches, and I
didn't want to take any chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell and Wagner each recorded a walk and a strikeout in his
inning. Wagner erased his walk with a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about the walk, because my pitches were
moving a lot,'' said Wagner, who had given up homers in each of his
two previous outings. ``A lot of times, you walk a guy and then
there comes the gopher ball. But it was obvious to me that they
were taking (my fastball) all the way. All I had to do was throw it
right down the middle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
