<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LONESTAR500-HNS &LR;      09-21 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONESTAR500-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
FORT WORTH _ In the summer of 1983, John Paul Jr. was a 23-year-old
rookie in Indy-car racing who ran down Rick Mears on the final lap
to win the Michigan 500.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His future appeared bright, but personal problems caused that
outlook to change, and it has taken Paul 15 years to get back to
Victory Lane. Paul was the surprise winner Sunday in the inaugural
Lone Star 500, a race in which the key to winning was having tires
that could survive the 95-degree heat at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long 15 years,'' Paul said. ``I just thank God
for this opportunity, my wife and kids for standing by me, and
(team owner) Jonathan Byrd for this car. Today, it was just
awesome. I'm as fresh as a daisy. I'm ready to go 300 more laps.
The team did a tremendous job today.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who drives the VisionAire G-Force Aurora, took the lead
for good with 16 laps to go when the three drivers in front of him
_ Jeff Ward, Roberto Guerrero and Buddy Lazier _ all had to stop
for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   An announced crowd of 81,000 watched Paul move up from fourth to
first, and Robby Unser moved up from fifth to second. But it was
questionable whether they had enough fuel to make it to the end
before a caution flag with 11 laps to go enabled both cars to stay
in front until the checkered flag. Paul finished 1.57 seconds ahead
of Unser.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional day for Paul, who has made a long climb back
to respectability after a difficult period in the mid-1980s. He
spent 28 months in prison after being convicted of drug trafficking
in 1985. People close to Paul say he was a victim of his father,
John Paul Sr., who is serving a 25-year sentence for drug smuggling
and attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things are in the past,'' said Paul, who won
$122,500 for the victory. ``I'm just glad to have these chances
again. I expect good things to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some good things happened Sunday to IRL points leader and
Houston resident Kenny Brack, who finished fifth in the Power Team
Dallara/Aurora to extend his lead with one race to go.
</P>
<P>
   With 55 points available for the final IRL race at Las Vegas on
Oct. 11, Brack has a 31-point lead over defending IRL champion Tony
Stewart and a 41-point lead over Davey Hamilton. The IRL Pep Boys
champion earns a $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart believes his chances at that prize ended Sunday. Stewart
had the lead after the first 60 laps, but he was out of the race 20
laps later when he blew an engine. An angry Stewart was asked by a
television pit reporter what he thought happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just gave away a million dollars, I guess,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt Racing teammates Brack and Billy Boat combined to take
home the $150,000 Texas Two-Step bonus by scoring the most IRL
point for the two TMS races this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who won the race at TMS in June, finished 14th Sunday and
was 46 laps down at the end after returning from a crash caused by
a cut tire, but it was good enough to earn the $100,000 bonus and a
handmade pair of cowboy boots. Brack, who finished third in June,
earned $50,000 as the runner-up in the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   But Foyt wasn't thinking about the bonus money during the race
when both of his cars were among several teams that had problems
with their Goodyear tires.
</P>
<P>
   Boat brushed the wall on the backstretch when his right rear
tire went down, which was a theme for the day. At least half of the
field had to make unscheduled pit stops because of problems with
Goodyear tires, but the cars on Firestone tires didn't have the
same problem. Goodyear was using a tire with slight changes for
this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them this wasn't a good tire, and I didn't recommend
it,'' Foyt said after Boat's accident. `` I can't talk about it
right now because I'm too damn mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt was so upset that he hunted down a Goodyear representative
during the race and was seen pointing his finger in the official's
face.
</P>
<P>
   Two drivers with Goodyear tires _ Dave Steele and Davey Hamilton
_ had tires explode off their cars on the frontstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're disappointed with the tire performance
today,'' said Todd Carpenter, Goodyear's lead engineer on the IRL
circuit. ``The track temperature was over 140 degrees, which
diminished the tire's ability to resist cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tire problems and accidents left only 13 of 28 cars running on
the 1.5-mile quad-oval at the end, and only four drivers were on
the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Paul and Unser, Jeff Ward and Roberto Guerrero were
the other two drivers on the lead lap at the end. It was a
career-best finish for Unser, the son of three-time Indy 500
champion Bobby Unser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike most guys (on Goodyear tires), we didn't have any tire
problems,'' Unser said. ``We fought a push all day, but that may
have kept our tires in good shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
