<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-D'AMATO-5     09-21 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-D'AMATO-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO ASSAILS RIVAL IN UPSTATE SWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``p.'') 
(See also: NY-CAMPAIGN-SCHUMER, NY-VALLONE-AD and NY-PATAKI-AD) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In his first major swing of the general election
campaign, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato barnstormed across the
Republican-friendly reaches of northern New York state Sunday,
repeatedly accusing his Democratic opponent, Rep. Charles Schumer
from Brooklyn, of being blithely indifferent to the needs of
upstate residents.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind six-hour trip brought D'Amato, a Republican
seeking his fourth term, to the state's largest upstate cities _
Albany, Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo _ and provided a television
backdrop for his unusually blunt appeal to the regional resentments
that have defined state politics for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the television advertisements with which he and the
state Republican Party have saturated the airwaves in recent days,
D'Amato derisively referred to Schumer as a ``Brooklyn liberal''
and lambasted him for having once quipped that ``the West starts on
the other side of the Hudson River.'' Schumer's aides said the
remark was a joking reference to his friend and former roommate,
Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he thinks that's funny,'' D'Amato said at a news
conference at Buffalo International Airport Sunday afternoon. ``But
take a look at his votes. In his votes, he has demonstrated a
pattern of not only indifference, not only of negligence, but
indeed of outright damage to upstate New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Those damaging votes, according to D'Amato, included Schumer's
support in Congress for reducing price supports for dairy farmers
and for increasing federal gasoline taxes, and in the state
Assembly two decades ago for establishing a state property tax.
D'Amato contended that since many Brooklyn residents do not own
homes or cars, the taxes Schumer voted for would have fallen
disproportionately on upstate residents.
</P>
<P>
   While D'Amato was touring upstate, Schumer took to the steps of
City Hall in New York City to criticize D'Amato's opposition to gun
control. Asked about the senator's criticisms, Schumer returned to
a core theme of his campaign: that D'Amato has been in office for
too long, an attack the Republicans used effectively upstate
against Gov. Mario Cuomo four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask what kinds of concrete things Al D'Amato has done
for upstate,'' Schumer said. ``He's supposed to be the pothole
senator. But upstate New York is one of the three regions in the
entire country that has lost jobs. Al D'Amato has been there 18
years. He's utterly failed in helping upstate New York. And people
in upstate New York, wherever I go, are looking for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign also faxed to reporters information on
D'Amato's record indicating that he had allowed property taxes to
rise in the town of Hempstead, on Long Island, during the 1970s,
when he was town supervisor there, and had voted repeatedly in the
Senate to raise federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Though D'Amato's news conferences were filled mainly with
attacks on Schumer, he did refer to federal aid that he claimed to
have directed to upstate communities, including aid for airport
renovations in Buffalo, a bridge over the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey
Thruway in Schenectady and improvements at the Albany rail station.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh tone of both candidates' remarks Sunday was in keeping
with the negative tenor that has dominated this still-young race
and provided new evidence that it is likely to be a bare-knuckles
affair down to the wire, much like the 1992 race in which D'Amato
defeated Robert Abrams, then the state attorney general, by a
single percentage point.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Democratic politicians said D'Amato's upstate strategy indicated
that he was concerned about the region's lagging economy and
perceived a softening of his support there. ``This is what he does
when he's in trouble: he tries to divide,'' said Josh Isay,
Schumer's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said D'Amato was simply playing a classic
Republican card, one that might work especially well this year
because of President Clinton's problems. Many strategists in both
parties say Democratic turnout in places like New York City may be
particularly low this year because party stalwarts are demoralized
by the inquiry into the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intangibles are looking good for D'Amato,'' said Anthony
H. Gioia, a Buffalo businessman and fund-raiser for the senator.
``He's got a popular governor at the top of the ticket to bring out
Republicans and the president's troubles keeping Democrats at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said D'Amato's efforts to stoke regional
frictions so early was extraordinary. But they said his strategy
was not surprising since D'Amato's chances of re-election depend on
overcoming New York City's strongly Democratic vote with heavy
Republican support in the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0010 </DOCNO>
