<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-VALLONE-AD-NYT &LR;      09-21 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VALLONE-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: VALLONE STRESSES GOVERNOR'S TIES TO D'AMATO 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category code ``a.'') 
(With NY-CAMPAIGN-DAMATO; see also NY-PATAKI-AD and
NY-CAMPAIGN-SCHUMER) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 30-second ad for the campaign of Peter Vallone, the New
York City Council speaker, began broadcasting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Doak, Carrier &AMP; O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The ad opens with a photo of Pataki next to an
image of a the ad attacking Vallone. The words ``Pataki negative
ad'' flash on the screen above the words ``George Pataki is
slinging mud.'' The ad then shows Vallone talking to constituents.
Then it shows photos of Pataki and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato with the
words ``hand-picked by Al D'Amato'' and cuts to the photo of Pataki
flanked by newspaper headlines unflattering to his administration.
The ad ends with an image of Pataki and D'Amato and the words ``so
far right, they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``George Pataki is slinging mud, trying to smear
Peter Vallone on taxes. But Pataki doesn't mention that many of the
votes were to pay for more cops and improve education. And that
Vallone voted to cut taxes more often than raise them. George
Pataki. Hand-picked by Al D'Amato and backed by his right-wing
organization. A man who cut education three years in a row. An
administration under federal investigation for selling state
contracts. A governor who vetoed funds for breast cancer. Pataki
and D'Amato. So far right, they're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The contention that some of Vallone's tax votes were
for police and schools is correct. Whether Vallone voted more often
to cut taxes than to raise them is irrelevant, since, as the City
Council's leader, he can prevent measures from coming to a vote.
The ad's claim that Pataki ``cut education three years in a row''
is misleading, but the truth is no more beneficial to Pataki. He
who tried to reduce education spending, but most of the cuts were
beaten back by the Legislature. Education spending in some areas
declined, but overall it continued to grow. Pataki did veto a
breast cancer education project this year, one of 1,300 budget
items he vetoed. To say that the administration is under
investigation ``for selling state contracts'' prematurely presumes
guilt, and a direct connection, to contract awards by the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The ad shows the Vallone camp's ability to turn
around in short order a response to an attack. And it reiterates
two of his favorite themes: Pataki's close ties to D'Amato, who is
much less popular than his former protege; and the claim that
Pataki is untrustworthy. But Vallone, with far less money than
Pataki has, cannot hope to go toe-to-toe for very long in this kind
of negative, high-decibel campaigning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
