<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-AD-NYT &LR;      09-21 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: NOT SO TAXING AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``a.'') 
(With NY-CAMPAIGN-DAMATO; see also NY-CAMPAIGN-SCHUMER and
NY-VALLONE-AD) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a 30-second advertisement that Gov. George Pataki's
campaign began broadcasting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Chris Mottola
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The ad opens with a picture of the Democratic
nominee, Peter Vallone, against a background of dollar bills, his
name displayed in white letters. When the narrator accuses Vallone
of voting for higher taxes 78 times, the ring of a cash register is
heard, and a tab with the legend ``Voted 78 Times for Higher
Taxes'' pops up. This pattern _ cash register ringing, tab popping
up _ continues four more times, as the narrator says that Vallone
voted for higher property, commuter and sales taxes. At the end,
Vallone's name and image remain, but the tabs are replaced by the
words ``Very Taxing.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``Peter Vallone is very liberal with taxpayers'
money. He voted 78 times for higher taxes. He voted 20 times for
higher income taxes. Vallone voted 18 times to raise property
taxes. Peter Vallone voted 14 times to extend the suburban commuter
tax, and Peter Vallone even voted 20 times for higher sales taxes.
Peter Vallone, very taxing.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Most of the 78 votes cited, some dating to the 1970s,
were not tax increases, but extensions of existing taxes. The
largest of those, a personal income tax surcharge to pay for more
police officers, was enacted in 1991 and extended last year, each
time with Pataki's support, and it was eliminated this year by
Vallone. Some of the taxes cited have since been eliminated. The
reference to property taxes is also misleading, referring, in many
instances, to the city's annual adjustment of tax rates. In this
decade, those adjustments have kept the overall tax burden roughly
unchanged, though it has raised the tax assessment on properties
whose values have risen sharply. In the eight years since the City
Council gained some power over the city budget, the city's tax
collections have risen more slowly than inflation, and more slowly
than the state's.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Pataki is relying on the most tried-and-true
Republican formula, calling Democrats ``liberal'' taxers and
spenders, which surely has worked in the past. And while the ad
does not mention New York City directly, it plays into the belief
of many upstate and suburban voters that politicians from the city,
like Vallone, want nothing more than to bleed them dry through
taxes. But it is unusual for an incumbent with an enormous lead in
the polls to go on the attack first, and so early in the general
election campaign. And while Pataki may simply be trying not to
take anything for granted, negative advertising always runs the
risk, however slight, of backfiring on the attacker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
