A5331 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BACKUPS-TEX     09-21 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BACKUPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPORTANCE OF NFL BACKUP QUARTERBACKS BECOMES PAINFULLY CLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For one of the few times in Babe Laufenberg's career as an NFL
quarterback, the situation allowed for no clowning.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstance: Week 16 of the 1990 season, budding superstar
Troy Aikman unavailable because of injury and the 7-8 Cowboys
readying for a visit to Atlanta with a playoff berth on the line.
If No. 2 quarterback Laufenberg and his mates are successful, the
Cowboys leap from the depths of the previous season's 1-15 record
to a .500 mark good enough to make the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   History recalls that Laufenberg's performance was not
Aikmanesque in a 26-7 loss. The defeat essentially marked the end
of Laufenberg's football career. And it also marked the end of an
organizational philosophy that allowed the club to, in then-coach
Jimmy Johnson's vernacular, ``hang out'' at a certain position.
</P>
<P>
   After going with the rookie tandem of Aikman-Steve Walsh in
1989, and then the unproven tandem of Aikman-Laufenberg in '90,
Cowboys rosters have always included a succession of NFL-tested No.
2's.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Beuerlein had been a starter and winner with the Raiders.
Rodney Peete had been a starter and winner with the Lions. Bernie
Kosar had been an AFC Championship Game standout with the Browns.
Wade Wilson had gone to an NFC Championship Game with the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett, tonight's Cowboys starter in their meeting with
the New York Giants, lacks those sort of credentials. Nevertheless,
he and the rest of the backup QBs called into action in the NFL's
opening weeks of attrition is a veteran in understanding the
intricacies of When 1 Becomes 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a professional, you always focus, always study, always
prepare, no matter what your role is,'' Laufenberg says. ``But when
you're a backup who gets elevated, no matter how many times you
tell yourself to take the same steps as always in preparation, you
know you're kidding yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't act the same way. You're not as relaxed. It's
completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first three weeks of the season, nearly a dozen starters
went down in a flurry of aches, pains and serious injuries.
Stepping into the limelight are the likes of used-to-be's such as
Tennessee's Dave Krieg and Kansas City's Rich Gannon and
never-were's such as Tampa Bay's Steve Walsh and Buffalo's Doug
Flutie and who-knows-what-they-are's such as New Orleans' Danny
Wuerffel and Baltimore's Eric Zeier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepare as if I'm going to start, regardless of the
circumstances,'' Zeier said. ``That's how I train my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That works, in principle. But in reality, say more experienced
hands, the comparison is akin to taking a Driver's Ed class as
opposed to speeding down the Autobahn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a backup quarterback on this team means you get few if
any reps,'' said Krieg, a longtime starter in Seattle and Detroit
who now backs up Steve McNair with the Oilers. ``Oh, you do a lot
of mental preparation, studying, film analysis. But that's it. And
if and when you get out there, it's your first time with the first
group.''
</P>
<P>
   How valuable is a No. 2?
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore traded for 34-year-old Jim Harbaugh to be the No. 1,
but then signed their demoted starter, 26-year-old Zeier, to a
two-year, $2.6 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota insisted the once-retired Randall Cunningham return
for another season because in the estimation of coach Denny Green,
he was the only backup QB in the country capable of picking up the
slack for starter Brad Johnson, who now misses a month with a
broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle spends the money to employ three respected QBs, Warren
Moon, John Friesz and Jon Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Backups must understand that ``guys in this league go down left
and right,'' Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson says. ``If you don't
have a second quarterback who can come in and win _ not just come
in, but win _ you're going to be in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the backup QB situation is mishandled, the entire team
can come apart. In Detroit, there's controversy as Scott Mitchell
has moved from No. 1 to No. 3, with veteran Frank Reich getting
passed over in favor of rookie third-stringer Charlie Batch. In
Washington, Gus Frerotte was benched after Week 1, and when coach
Norv Turner chose Trent Green as his replacement, it upset both
Frerotte and erstwhile No. 2 man Jeff Hostetler.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that's tough is to be demoted without
stepping onto the field,'' says Hostetler, who was persuaded to
swallow his pride and return.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler thought it was over. And an added danger in being a
No. 2 who is called upon to be a No. 1 is that the beginning might
also be the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hang around for a few years, like Jason has, a nice guy, a
smart guy, and everybody likes you for your personality and
smarts,'' Laufenberg says. ``Then you play. And you expose what
weaknesses you might have. And then you're out of a job. For a guy
in Jason's situation, every week might now be his last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0016 </DOCNO>
