u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-ARIZONA-S     09-21 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-ARIZONA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON HOBBLED WITH HUSKERS AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Among Washington's practice priorities this week will
be getting back a key member of the defense that performed
admirably against Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Burton, the senior co-captain at rover, was hobbling in a
protective boot Sunday at the Huskies' light workout, their first
practice in preparation for Nebraska Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one that has not swollen,'' UW coach Jim Lambright said
hopefully. ``I expect him back. It's just real important to get as
much work on the (Nebraska) option as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton's availability is important for the Huskies. At 5-foot-9
and 180 pounds, he is undersized, but this is his third season of
starting, and his backups are unproven.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies list true freshman Andrae Perry as Burton's backup,
but senior walk-on Hakim Weatherspoon took over in Burton's absence
against BYU. Also in the competition is redshirt freshman Anthony
Vontoure, but cornerback Renard Edwards _ recently moved from a
backup rover position _ would give the Huskies more size at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, slotback Dane Looker, whose absence with a thigh
injury hurt a sputtering Husky offense, showed much more mobility
and is expected to start against the Huskers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska-Washington game is the fourth such matchup in the
'90s, and the first in which Nebraska is the higher-ranked team.
Both polls have the 3-0 Huskers No. 2 this week, while Washington
is ranked eighth in the USA Today/ESPN poll and ninth by The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the game's implication for the rankings, Lambright
laughed and said, ``For us, it's Game 3. That's as far as we're
taking this thing right now. I'm still trying to figure out how
many freshmen we're going to take on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be a measure of how each program has rebounded
from heavy losses to the NFL draft. The Huskies had 10 players
taken, more than any school, but Nebraska had more high-end talent
with defensive linemen Grant Wistrom and Jason Peter going among
the top 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'd trade our depth for theirs right now,'' Lambright
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Nebraska was a difficult read a year ago in this spot _
having come off victories against Akron and Central Florida _ so
are the Huskers again something of an unknown quantity with three
victories against outclassed opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit harder because of the coaching change, and
the injuries they've had,'' Lambright said, referring to the
resignation of Tom Osborne and appointment of longtime aide Frank
Solich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you lose a quarterback, you change a little bit, and
changing quarterbacks is something they haven't had to deal with
the past couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Frost graduated, leaving the job to sophomore Bobby
Newcombe. He sustained a knee injury in the Nebraska opener against
Louisiana Tech, but is listed as the starter again. I-back DeAngelo
Evans, whose first snap since 1996 has been long-awaited by Big Red
faithful, is expected back from a knee injury but is not listed on
the preliminary two-deep.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to BYU player comments that they could read Husky
quarterback Brock Huard's audibles at the line of scrimmage,
Lambright said, ``I don't think anybody could pick up in one game
our signals for this year.'' But he said he and his staff would
examine the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-REDSKINS     09-21 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-REDSKINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS RUN PAST WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nine minutes into Sunday's game against the Washington
Redskins, the Seahawks found themselves in unfamiliar and unwanted
territory.
</P>
<P>
   These new Seahawks, the ones who had toyed with and trampled the
Philadelphia Eagles and Arizona Cardinals in their first two games,
were looking too much like the old Seahawks, the ones who had
gotten so used to not having prosperity that too often they played
like they couldn't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins had just scored to make it 7-7. The Seahawks
offense had just gone three-and-out on consecutive possessions. The
league's top-ranked defense was having a difficult time stopping
Redskins running back Terry Allen, wide receiver Michael Westbrook
and quarterback Trent Green, who was making only his second NFL
start.
</P>
<P>
   The voice in Bob Bratkowski's ear was not happy. It was head
coach Dennis Erickson and he was telling his offensive coordinator
he wanted the Seahawks to start putting the ball in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis felt we needed to throw it to get something going,''
said Bratkowski, who watches the game from the coaches box on the
200 level of the Kingdome and communicates through headsets with
Erickson along the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Bratkowski prevailed, and so did the Seahawks, running their
record to 3-0 for only the second time in club history with a 24-14
victory before an announced crowd of 63,336.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys upstairs didn't panic,'' Erickson said. ``I wanted
to throw it every down, but they wanted to stay with the run. So I
let them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' ability to run the ball, and insistence on doing
it, was the thread that held together this game that looked like it
was about to unravel on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams gave the Seahawks a giant shove in the right
direction when Steve Broussard returned the opening kickoff 90
yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The defense gave up too many yards (465) and too many
completions (27 for 383 yards and two TDs), but held the Redskins
in check by intercepting a Green pass at the Seattle 15-yard line,
forcing and recovering an Allen fumble at the Seattle 11 and
stopping Washington twice on downs in the fourth quarter _ once at
the Seattle 34-yard line and again at the Seattle 5.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker David Akers, who was signed Tuesday after Scott Blanton
missed a pair of field goals in the Redskins' loss to the San
Francisco 49ers on Monday night, missed two of his own in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to credit the defense for these wins the last two
weeks,'' said Ricky Watters, who had his second straight 100-yard
rushing game and finished with 181 yards on 30 touches (24 carries
for 136 and six receptions for 45).
</P>
<P>
   While the Seahawks' defense was stretching that old
bend-but-don't-break adage precariously thin, the Seahawks'
offensive line was grinding away at the Redskins. After rushing for
only 53 yards in the first half, the Seahawks made an adjustment
that paid off in 110 rushing yards and two TDs on the team's first
two possessions of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks spent much of the first half trying to run from
their three-receiver package. They went with an extra receiver
because in the Redskins' season-opening losses to the New York
Giants and 49ers, they had matched up with this alignment by
replacing their defensive ends with two linebackers, giving them a
front six that consisted of three linebackers, two defensive
tackles and a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Not Sunday. The Redskins played the Seahawks with their base
defense.
</P>
<P>
   A coaching staff that had been suspect in the past for its
inability to make changes on the run, did just that. The Seahawks
came out in the second half with two backs and two receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' Bratkowski said. ``I guess you can make that
judgment. I think we've done a pretty good job offensively over the
last few years. We just haven't won games. Now, we're winning
games.''
</P>
<P>
   After linebacker Darrin Smith intercepted a Green pass at the
Redskins' 19-yard line, Watters scored on a 13-yard run two plays
later by sweeping to his right and cutting behind a block from
tackle Howard Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a play you only run once or twice a week, then let it
die for a couple of weeks,'' Bratkowski said. ``It has kind of an
element of surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Seahawks got the ball, they went to work
again. Watters ran for 2 yards, caught a pass for 5 and then darted
and spun for 33 yards on third-and-3. Rookie Ahman Green came on to
spell Watters, but the Redskins couldn't break the spell. Green ran
for 5 and then 7 yards. On first down from the 21, quarterback
Warren Moon used a play-action fake to Watters and rollout that
allowed wide receiver Mike Pritchard to run uncovered into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard's TD catch made it 24-7, and the Seahawks were well on
their way to being 3-0 for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are unbeaten, but the victories have come against
three NFC East teams that have one win among them. Now come the 2-1
Steelers in Pittsburgh this week, then the Chiefs in Kansas City
and an Oct. 11 game against the defending Super Bowl champion
Denver Broncos at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the Seahawks have been, they'll have to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it gets good. It gets darn good,'' defensive end Michael
Sinclair said. ``We're going to have to get our game going. I'm not
saying it can't be done, but we're going to have to go in there on
our game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
