<SLUG> BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST IN THE BIZ? SEGUI TABS RODRIGUEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Champagne in a baseball clubhouse in late
September is meant to be sprayed. This bottle, with a piece of
athletic tape carrying the message ``Congrats on 40/40'' attached,
was meant to be savored.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners first baseman David Segui delivered it to shortstop
Alex Rodriguez after Saturday's game, in which Rodriguez homered to
become the third player in major league history with 40 home runs
and 40 stolen bases in the same season. In a year that will not end
in showers of bubbly for the sub-.500 Mariners, the moment was
worthy of a toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pretty much reinforces to me that he's the best ballplayer
in the game,'' said Segui. ``Definitely, (Barry) Bonds and (Ken
Griffey) Junior are up there with him, but the way he plays the
game sets him apart from everyone else, I think. He plays the game
with the intensity of a fringe player, which is a compliment. He
plays the game the way it's supposed to be played, plays to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not alone in this: He's the best in the game. The way he
goes about it day in and day out, with a desire to get better _
it's very impressive. ... Let me put it this way: Most superstars
wouldn't do the things that he does.''
</P>
<P>
   No player has reached 40/40 faster than the 23-year-old
Rodriguez, who is younger by a year than Jose Canseco in 1988, and
nine years younger than Bonds in 1996. Both of those players hit 42
homers and stole 40 bases; with 40 homers and 43 steals,
Rodriguez's totals already represent the most productive 40/40
season in history.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners broadcaster Dave Henderson was a teammate of Canseco's
on the '88 Oakland Athletics, and said he counts Willie Mays and
Bobby Bonds as the only other players in history capable of doing
what Rodriguez, Canseco and Bonds have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to talk about `five-tool' players,'' Henderson
said. ``This puts it way beyond the `five-tool' player.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . Once the league adjusted to him, he made his own
adjustments. That signifies greatness. There's no fluke in the
man's game.''
</P>
<P>
   The only fluke may have been a 10-game homerless stretch between
No. 39, on Sept. 7, and Saturday's No. 40. Rodriguez admits he was
pressing until finally connecting off Angels right-hander Jack
McDowell, and said his mother had been going to church for a week
praying for the 40th homer to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez dutifully thanked ``the man upstairs,'' and his
God-given talents certainly had something to do with his
accomplishment. But so did that desire to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great lesson for me as a young player about the
necessity of hard work,'' said Rodriguez, who hired a personal
trainer and worked out 5-6 times a week last off-season. ``That's
what I attribute this to, all my work. It's probably the thing I'm
most proud of, more than being the batting champion (in 1996). This
is something I'm very, very proud of and something I'll never
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco and Bonds both clinched their 40/40 seasons with a
stolen base. For Rodriguez, the stolen bases came first, and, he
said, he's more proud of the steals than the homers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez displayed his power with 36 homers in 1996, but he
didn't think he'd steal many more than 25 bases in a season. He
averaged fewer than 15 steals in his first three professional
seasons, and stole 29 bases in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Rich Amaral, who stole 50 bases three times in the
minors, encouraged Rodriguez last year to set his sights on 50.
That motivated Rodriguez to concentrate more on base stealing and
gear his workouts toward handling the inherent physical rigors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very fast, quick and he's just a great athlete,'' said
Amaral. ``He's got great instincts. I think the one thing he
probably didn't realize is how many opportunities you'll come
across over the course of a year, if you're looking for them and
playing every day like he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez frequently seeks Amaral's advice _ he called him from
the road the other day when Amaral, who is on the disabled list,
was away from the team _ and Amaral is happy to give it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love talking to him about base stealing,'' said Amaral. ``I
love researching the pitchers, and he and I will go over their
quickness to the plate, what they throw, tendencies. It's been
exciting for me to have him so excited about that aspect of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has also shared that excitement with the all-time
stolen base leader. When Oakland came to Seattle in June, Rodriguez
sought out Rickey Henderson. Henderson, who had power to go with
his speed in his heyday,said inquisitiveness is Rodriguez's best
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding ballplayer, but he's a tremendous
learner,'' Henderson said. ``We spent time talking about base
stealing, and he put it together and learned something. He wants to
learn and be the best he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, no player ever has been better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0047EDT &QL; 
