<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATTERS CARRYING SEAHAWKS' TO HIGHER LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The mark of true studmuffin-hood in the NFL is when
you're so good, the best play of your afternoon is the play that
needs only your smile.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter Sunday with the Seahawks up 17-7 over
the Washington Redskins in a game far closer, the Seattle offense
was lurching and flopping like a 300-pound halibut in a skiff.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Seahawk coaches said they were going to stick with
one thing until the Redskins did something about it. They went all
Ricky, all the time, kind of like a 24-hour specialty cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Watters dive for 2 yards. Watters screen pass for 5. Watters off
tackle for 33 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A momentary switch of backs, but rookie Ahman Green did a nasty
Watters impression. Up the middle for 5. Around left end for 7.
</P>
<P>
   Then Watters returned to the game with the Seahawks on the
Washington 21 with a first down. The entire defense of the nation's
capital, along with the National Guard, President Clinton's lawyers
and Buddy the dog, were poised on tippy-toes ready to pounce on
Watters.
</P>
<P>
   As the lone back, he almost leaped for the handoff from
quarterback Warren Moon, who instead tucked the ball on his hip and
rolled into what the laceheads call a naked bootleg pass. A
grinning Watters, meanwhile, carried the fake to an Oscar
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawk receiver Mike Pritchard could not have been more open if
he had said bad things about Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our safety (Leomont Evans) got caught up in the run,'' said
Redskins coach Norv Turner. ``There's no question he was way, way,
way aggressive, and he just bit. It's not a play they should get
that open on.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard was more in danger of being hit by an asteroid than a
Redskin defender. His touchdown catch was not only the
spirit-breaker in the Seahawks' 24-14 win, it made an eloquent
statement that this is Watters' offense.
</P>
<P>
   And that offense is better than when it was Moon's offense.
</P>
<P>
   When Watters rushes for 136 hard yards (as well a catching six
passes for 45 yards) against a gravelly defensive front and his
most effective play is a play-action fake, the Seahawks are on to
something.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Seahawks had prettier statistics when Moon came
out having to throw. But defenses eventually caught up and forced
him into mistakes. With Watters the marquee event in the Seahawk
theater, defenses can't cheat nearly as much.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that Moon has thrown 77 passes this season without
an interception. While that makes a small point about the
uselessness of training camp for some players _ camp was the last
thing Moon missed _ the larger point is that the Seahawks are
throwing when they want, not when they must.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Seahawks haven't even been behind.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, their 3-0 start entirely has been against the NFC East,
which has collected more treadmarks than the driveway into
Disneyland. But Sunday the Redskins actually introduced an element
of dignity into the season by offering up resistance.
</P>
<P>
   As with Philadelphia and Arizona, Washington also had a
quarterback as green as his name. Trent Green might be the greatest
new quarterback in the NFL _ if the game were played only between
the 30-yard lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskin defenders were a different story, doing the
three-and-out trick against the Seahawks enough times that coach
Dennis Erickson was desperate to go to his instinctive bombs-away
routine.
</P>
<P>
   But offensive playcaller Bob Bratkowski's faith in the running
game prevailed, and the Seahawks ground out a win more notable for
its reduced-mistake efficiency than its spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we want to do it from the beginning,'' said
Moon, apparently unmoved by his lesser role. ``By the second half,
we should have teams worn down enough for our offensive line to
take over. That's how it happened today. You've seen in the first
games a lot of short carries in the first half, and all of a sudden
those carries get to be long runs in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is a workhorse back who gets better as the game goes
along. He's not going to shy away from contact. When the offensive
line sees a back doing that, they're going to give a little
extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving was especially pronounced in the second half, when the
Seahawks responded to their first real pressure situation of the
season by giving the ball to Watters, the high-priced, supposedly
high-maintenance free agent, 14 times for 85 yards. Included was
his 33-yarder that had two broken tackles, a spin move worthy of
Michael Jordan and a relentlessness that is his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing my dad told me last night when I talked to
him,'' Watters said, ``was `You hit that hole fast, and when you
get in that secondary you spin on them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a while back, I was trying to be more powerful. He
said, `I like the way you're hitting the holes, but put that spin
move back in there.' He loves the spin move.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Kingdome fans were howling along with the old man, too.
Even when Watters does nothing more than smile empty-handed, it
puts a fresh spin on the Seahawk offense.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
