<HEADLINE>
MARINERS WASTE CHANCES, FALL TO ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's been six years since Paul Abbott had the
kind of feeling he experienced last night: a sold-out crowd roaring
with their team's pennant hopes on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott played for the pennant-contending Minnesota Twins in
1992, and remembers the eardrum-busting shouts of a packed
Metrodome. A crowd of 42,972 squeezed into Edison International
Field to watch the Anaheim Angels and Mariners Sunday night, and a
win by the home team would even up the American League West
Division race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was really going crazy and getting really loud in
the third inning,'' said Abbott, who worked six innings for the
Mariners. ``I was thinking, this is great. This is really fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun, that is, until the Angels pushed across three runs in the
inning and hung on to win, 3-1. Anaheim now stands tied with the
Texas Rangers for first place, while the Mariners completed their
final road trip with a 6-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had their chances, leaving runners in scoring
position in five of the first seven innings. Each of those runners
got into scoring position with less than two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had many chances tonight,'' said manager Lou Piniella.
``Many, many, many chances that we didn't take advantage of.
Outside of that, it was a good ballgame. Abbott pitched well, and
so did their people.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott (2-1), making his third start after missing most of the
season recovering from a serious elbow injury, gave up four singles
and threw two wild pitches in the Angels' three-run third. He
allowed one hit and no runs in his other five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wild pitches killed me,'' Abbott said. ``We brought the
infield in and I got ground balls; they just got through.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariner Omar Olivares threw six shutout innings before
leaving with two on and no outs in the seventh. A sacrifice fly by
Ken Griffey Jr. off reliever Jarrod Washburn brought home one run,
but Washburn, Pep Harris and Troy Percival took care of things from
there.
</P>
<P>
   It was Olivares' second win of the year against the Mariners,
and the right-hander stands 6-2 against Seattle lifetime. He's been
particularly effective against Griffey, holding him to three hits
in 26 career at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey tried something different when he faced the
sinker-balling Olivares in the first inning. David Bell and Alex
Rodriguez led off with singles, and Griffey bunted, popping to
catcher Matt Walbeck on the second attempt. After an Edgar Martinez
single loaded the bases, Olivares escaped with a strikeout and a
fly out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it in the rule book that I'm not allowed to bunt?'' Griffey
said. ``I'm not allowed to do the little things to help my team
win? I'm not allowed to do that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were pleased Griffey took advantage of his right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I really think he's trying to get 100 RBIs for Edgar
Martinez,'' said Angels coach Larry Bowa. ``He told Walbeck to tell
me on Friday that he was going to lay one down, and I told him to
go right ahead. Tonight, I was saying to him after he bunted,
`Thank you very much.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
