<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SWEPT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ So now, in every sense of the phrase, it comes down to
the home stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Eight games left to be played, all at Fenway Park, the wild card
on the table.
</P>
<P>
   With a four-game lead on the field, it's not going to take
Secretariat to win this race. The Red Sox are proving that a
three-legged pony will do, as long as its heart doesn't come to a
complete stop within sight of the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to preach to this team this week that it's all in
front of you,'' said Mo Vaughn, making plans to try and inspire a
bunch that probably could use a revival meeting after being swept
three straight in Chicago by the White Sox, who won Sunday's series
finale, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to going home, man,'' said Vaughn, who had
three hits, including his 37th home run, and drove in three runs
but couldn't keep the Sox from being swept here for the first time
in eight years. ``That's just what it's all about. We'll be ready,
primed and ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, let it fly, let it fly. I know I'll let it fly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who have won just six of 19 games this month (3-4
on this trip) and Sunday saw their magic number stall at 4, were
grounded Sunday by a confluence of calamities, most of their own
making. Three times they held a lead _ 1-0 on Vaughn's home run in
the first, 3-1 on Vaughn's two-run single in the third, 4-3 on
Darren Lewis's double and John Valentin's single in the fifth. Each
time they gave it back, or once for every error they made Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six runs scored by the White Sox were unearned, a
trend that prevailed on a weekend in which the home team profited
by nine runs tainted by Red Sox errors.
</P>
<P>
   Their last act of generosity came in the seventh. Jim Corsi, the
third Sox pitcher, was an out away from preserving a 4-3 lead when
third baseman Valentin, who has been the most sure-handed of Sox
infielders, made his first error in 65 games, failing to come up
with Mike Caruso's smash right at him.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin was playing on the grass in the event of a bunt by
Caruso, who had bunted a previous pitch foul down the first-base
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit the ball pretty sharply,'' Valentin said. ``I tried to
block it and keep it in front of me. It kind of skipped on me and
didn't really come up. It hit my glove and trickled past me. It was
a tough play, but I'd like to think that nine times out of 10, I
keep that ball in front of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we made three errors, and usually when you make three
errors you're not going to win a ballgame. On key plays, we played
a little erratic. That's why we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cameron, who was on third after what Corsi described as a
``soft-serve'' double and an infield out, scored on Valentin's
error, tying the score at 4. Jimy Williams then called for Dennis
Eckersley, who hadn't given up a run since Aug. 12, but this
clearly wasn't a day for holding form.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley gave up back-to-back doubles to Frank Thomas and
Albert Belle, still the most ferocious pair of righthanded hitters
found in any lineup, even if Belle on his best behavior is regarded
as the anti-Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get out of town,'' said Eckersley. ``Momentum, it's
over. Wake up tomorrow, you're home, it's totally different. You
leave, you go somewhere else, it's like a new beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten these guys out a lot over the years, but they got
me today. It catches up with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored twice in the third inning without a hit. Ray
Durham walked and wound up at third when he stole second and
received a bonus base when Tim Wakefield's pitch tricked Jason
Varitek for a passed ball. After Caruso drew a walk, Thomas hit a
fly ball to shallow right. Lewis's throw home was true and arrived
at the same time as Durham, who met a stone wall in Varitek, who
had sealed off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, to his regret, never saw the ball, which careened past
him. ``I got hit right before the ball got there,'' Varitek said.
``I can tell you that if I had been able to hang onto the ball, he
would have never gotten to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Durham scored on what was charged as an error to Lewis, and when
Wakefield, backing up the play, bounced his throw into left field,
Caruso scored, too, but not without Varitek absorbing another
collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two in about 10 seconds,'' said Varitek. ``Sometimes you've
got to give yourself up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a couple of freak things happening, we had a chance to
win that game. This has to click for us, sooner or later. We're too
good of a team for it not to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are a team that begins its final week with more wins
than any team in the American League outside of the Yankees and
Indians, who already have qualified for the playoffs. A team that
could qualify for its own playoff berth as soon as Tuesday, if it
can come home and win three straight from an expansion team, the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays, while its pursuers lose at least once.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are a team that has lost six of its last eight
series and lost more games than it has won since the All-Star
break, but still is in ideal position to throw a party sometime
this week. At home, where the ghosts may have other ideas, but
where the ghosts should have no say in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way back to Boston,'' Williams said. ``Good
things will happen to us in Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
