<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ADVANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL WEST RACE BEGINS ANEW WITH SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Last Thursday during the seventh inning of the
Angels-Texas Rangers game in Arlington, a television camera zoomed
in on the Rangers' Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   The former Angel had a scowl on his face as he paced in the
dugout and yelled out at Angels pitcher Pep Harris. In turn, Harris
yelled right back.
</P>
<P>
   The two kept it up until the home plate umpire had to go out to
the mound and calm Harris down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to rattle me,'' Harris said of McLemore. ``He
was trying to fire his guys up. So I yelled at him. I was just
trying to get my guys going too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing personal, just a pennant race. And while it seems
few people outside Anaheim and Arlington are paying attention, it's
still the only race for a division title up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Rangers begin a three-game series tonight at
Edison Field that could decide who goes to New York to face the
Yankees in the first round of the playoffs, and who goes home.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will finish up the regular season with four games in
Oakland while the Rangers play four in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played 155 games to come into (tonight),'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``A lot of days we've sat in here and
talked about looking at the scoreboard and worrying about what the
Rangers are doing or who they're playing. Now it's in our yard,
it's in our hands. That's the way you want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Rangers have been buried in the sports pages by
Mark McGwire's and Sammy Sosa's home run duel. Even the National
League wild-card race _ which includes the major media markets of
New York and Chicago _ gets better play on the national sports
highlights shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, I was watching TV and I didn't even know the
Braves had clinched,'' Collins said. ``The Astros _ I managed them
two years ago and I didn't know they clinched. Everything was
centered on Sosa and McGwire. And we're all happy for the two of
them. But believe me, it's not taking away from my concentration. I
hope Sosa and McGwire hit 75 home runs, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Rangers begin the series tied at 83-72, but the
Rangers have an advantage in knowing they swept the Angels in a
two-game series last week in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers beat the Angels' two most effective pitchers _ Chuck
Finley and Steve Sparks _ and won the second game after trailing
4-0. It's the Rangers' lineup, led by Juan Gonzalez, that puts a
scare into any pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight, the Angels have more to contend with than the
Rangers hitters. Todd Stottlemyre held the Angels to one run in
eight innings in the Rangers' 5-3 win last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't seen Stottlemyre in something like three years. Now
guys have got a good read on him,'' shortstop Gary DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too excited about Stottlemyre,'' center fielder Jim
Edmonds said. ``The next day I was more relaxed and it worked a lot
better (he had three hits, including a homer). You can get too
emotional sometimes and it can work against you. You need to relax
and just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, the Angels insist they won't choke. Comparisons to
the collapse of 1995 are not allowed in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we're trying to do is make sure we don't get
uptight,'' Collins said. ``We want to make sure we have fun with
this. We've got a lot of young players. You want these guys to see
what it takes, put 'em in these situations as many times as you
can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
