<SLUG> BC-NY-LIBERALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRIMARY, BEING LIBERAL MEANT LESS THAN BEING RICH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last generation, the most liberal candidate
has always been a good bet to win a statewide Democratic primary in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ideology has often been able to trump money, with a string of
candidates on the left defeating more centrist opponents who spent
far more: Elizabeth Holtzman over Bess Myerson in the 1980 Senate
primary; Mario Cuomo over Edward Koch in the 1982 gubernatorial
primary; Mark Green over John Dyson in the 1986 Senate primary;
Karen Burstein over Oliver Koppell in the 1994 primary for attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's primary turned that pattern on its head. In
races for senator, governor and attorney general, the winners were
the best-financed candidates in their primary races, and arguably
the most centrist.
</P>
<P>
   The results have many prominent New York Democrats wondering
whether the hidebound liberalism of their party's core voters has
softened over the years, if those voters have become more
pragmatic, or if money has simply become an irresistible force in
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the glaring conclusion is the impact that money has in
modern American politics,'' said Robert Abrams, the former attorney
general. ``It buys radio and TV spots, which provide candidates
name and issue recognition, and that's what I think is common in
all of these races.''
</P>
<P>
   He contended that the role of money is greater than ever, not
just because the sums are larger, but also because Democrats, their
party weakened in recent years, no longer have the kind of
grass-roots political machinery they once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out walking with my wife on Saturday,'' Abrams said,
``and here it was the weekend before the big primary, and there was
no street campaign. No tables with pamphlets. No rallies. I saw so
few posters in this campaign. It's not like the old days. It's all
on the airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Schumer, the winner of the Senate primary, lagged
far behind Geraldine Ferraro in opinion surveys until he used his
financial advantage to blanket the airwaves with his face and
voice.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, was roughly
tied in polls with Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross, then pulled well
ahead when he became the first to advertise on television.
</P>
<P>
   The four candidates for attorney general were roughly even until
Eliot Spitzer, clearly the most conservative, far outspent the
others on advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking results last Tuesday was the showing of
Mark Green, clearly the most liberal candidate in the Senate race,
who finished third in his primary, behind Schumer and Ferraro.
Green, New York City's public advocate, had the sort of name
recognition and experience that are crucial to an underfinanced
candidate, yet he received just 19 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Green is the closest thing you have to a strong liberal
movement in New York these days,'' said Cuomo, the former governor.
``You could point to what happened to him as evidence that ideology
does not mean what it used to mean.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the shift might have been under way, little
noticed, for years. ``Look,'' he said, ``Bill Clinton is very
popular among New York Democrats, and he is not a liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, pointed to the role of money. ``Spitzer,'' he said,
``wins only because of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Democrats interviewed said it was harder to draw
conclusions from Vallone's victory. Ross, his main rival, stumbled
badly because of internal problems, and the other two, Charles
Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, and James Larocca, a former
state transportation commissioner, never mounted serious campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, the state party chairwoman, said the primary
results reflected Democrats' desire to beat the Republican
incumbents, fed by the losses of recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a perception by the voters that these
candidates have the best chance to win the general election,'' said
Judith Hope, the state party chairwoman. ``More than ever before,
even among extremely liberal, highly ideological Democratic voters,
there is a new degree of pragmatism. Maybe the Democratic Party has
finally matured and come of age. We've grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   She conceded that voters' judgments of which candidates would be
strongest in the general election were based, in large part, on how
much money they had.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Keith Wright of Harlem, a liberal who supported the
more centrist Vallone, said: ``We got tired of losing. It used to
be the liberal would win the primary and then would get killed in
the general. Maybe we've learned something.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hank Morris, a political consultant who is working for
Schumer, maintained that polls prove that ``people don't vote
strategically, they vote for their favorite candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   And Cuomo offered his own explanation why money matters more
now: Liberalism, he said, is not dead, but it is in hiding. Since
the Republican sweep of 1994, he said, Democrats from Clinton to
local officials have been afraid to voice the left-leaning views
they hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it very hard to keep the liberals motivated,'' he
said. ``They're still out there, but they're quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   In that silence, he said, money is heard more loudly than ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
