<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN FAST REGAINING LOST CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ All week Tennessee Oilers safety Blaine
Bishop kept asking Chris Sanders about his former Ohio State
teammate, Terry Glenn. The question was always the same.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for him, so was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how fast he was,'' the Oilers safety said a few minutes
after he had learned Glenn was too fast for him to tackle when he
most needed to. ``We got Sanders. I kept asking him, `Now, how fast
is he?' He kept saying, `Very fast. Very, very fast. Real fast.'''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was so fast Sunday that when he made a sight adjustment on
an Oiler blitz with just under five minutes to play in a game the
New England Patriots were in danger of losing, he ran away with the
ball and the game after running away from a flat-footed Bishop in
the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's jets turned a short slant into a 51-yard touchdown that
gave the Patriots their first lead in a 27-16 victory and allowed
Oiler running back Eddie George to see a live replay of something
he had hoped to keep only in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing him, when the game is on the line like that, I knew
they'd go to him sooner or later,'' said the Oilers running back,
also a former Ohio State teammate of Glenn's. ``And the nightmare
happened. I saw him catch the ball, and we didn't tackle him. I
knew what he could do with the ball ... and he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's current teammates know what he can do with it as well,
but many of them had grown anxious waiting for it to happen this
season. Frustrated after two long weeks in which he had dropped
four passes, including three last Sunday against the Colts, Glenn
acknowledged that his confidence had begun to wane a bit as he
continued to search for the breakthrough game that could get him
back into the zone he occupied in his miracle rookie season, when
he caught 90 passes for 1,132 yards three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling eluded him much of last season when it seemed one
injury after another dogged him, and this fall it hadn't yet
appeared either, although he and quarterback Drew Bledsoe have been
laboring hard to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game, in Denver, I dropped a ball and then last week
I struggled,'' Glenn said after a day in which he not only went 51
yards for the winning touchdown but finished with four catches for
102 yards, his first 100-yard game since last Oct. 27, when he made
seven catches for 163 yards against the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt like myself yet. In practice, Drew and I have
tried to get it but we haven't quite yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game, Bledsoe approached Glenn and told him this
was to be the day that would change. With a bright sun, clear
skies, and an aggressive defense that loved to blitz and thus made
itself vulnerable to seeing short slants turned into long gains,
Bledsoe assured Glenn the football would be coming his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to him and let him know he could be a key for us,''
Bledsoe said. ``Sometimes you go to a guy and challenge him. Terry
responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to get Terry involved not so much for
him but for our offense. Today I told him it was time for him to
have a big game. They were daring us to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a dare that led to Bledsoe being sacked four times but it
also led to Glenn's score because he read the safety blitz
immediately and knew that meant he should change a deep post into a
quick slant. When Glenn broke off his pattern, he expected to see
the cornerback on his side jump the slant but Tennessee's scheme
called for him to lay back instead, leaving Bishop, the strong
safety, to make the tackle in the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   But almost before Bishop could react, Glenn was angling across
the field and by him, going from left to right so fast he was past
Bishop before the safety was close enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got by Bishop I knew I could go a long ways,'' Glenn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Go he did, continuing almost to the opposite sideline before
Shawn Jefferson blocked cornerback Denard Walker, the last Oiler
with a chance at Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   As Walker fought off Jefferson's block, Glenn accelerated
through his arms and was gone, tumbling into the end zone with the
ball over his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original play was intended to go long,'' Glenn said. ``I
expected that cornerback to come up and take away the slant or just
make the tackle. When he didn't, I was open and Drew led me perfect
so I could catch it on the run at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw when I came across the field that it could go a long
ways. Those are the kind of plays that can go a long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   They can when the ball gets into Glenn's hands in stride, where
Bledsoe put it Sunday. At such a moment, he is one of the most
dangerous pass receivers in the NFL, a player with sprinter's speed
and wide, strong hands that easily can pluck a football out of the
air and deposit it in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since that 90-catch rookie year, Glenn has been dogged
not only by nagging injuries but even more by the number itself, a
number that fans and critics seem to insist he match lest his
season become a failure.
</P>
<P>
   It is an absurd standard considering how few receivers in the
75-year history of the NFL ever have had such a season. Even though
it is one Glenn is well capable of eclipsing when the conditions
are right, numbers can become an albatross if not understood and
carefully analyzed, so they remain numbers and not some false
standard of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   As linebacker Chris Slade said, ``Terry is a great, great
player. He has to have the ball in his hands. But because of his
rookie year and all his talent, people put too much pressure on
him. He's only one man and he's still a young man.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a young man burdened with great expectations, expectations
fueled by those 90 catches in 1996. In some ways, everything came
so easy for him in '96 that his employers and his fans took for
granted that such a year was the floor for Glenn, not the ceiling.
When injuries limited him to nine games and 27 catches last year,
people began to grumble. And when he got off to a slow start this
fall, his name kept coming up followed by question marks, not
exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of thing that began to weigh upon him this
summer until Ben Coates, who in 1994 set a tight end receiving
record with 96 catches and has been judged by that year ever since,
approached him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first year I had, it's kind of hard to accept
anything less,'' Glenn said. ``I was hidden by a lot of things
then. I could just go out and do what I could. Now I'm expected to
do more things. But Ben told me to let the game come to me. He told
me to let it (90 catches) go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Terry Glenn did that, and soon enough he was on his own,
running free with the football in his hand and the game on the
line. At that moment, Eddie George knew what was coming and Blaine
Bishop was just getting an idea how fast ``very, very fast'' can
be.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday it was too fast for the Tennessee Oilers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
