<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGEL FANS SLEEP THROUGH PENNANT RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't exactly a news bulletin to report that Angels fans are
among the most blas in baseball. The Big Ed can sometimes be a lot
colder than the ice at the Pond across the street.
</P>
<P>
   But at this particular intersection of the 1998 season, which
brings the alleged home team and its opposition together at high
speed, the fans' collective coma screams for attention.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the Angels beat Seattle 3-1 to tie the Texas
Rangers for the American League West lead with a week left to play
and the Rangers coming to town for the next three nights. This is
about as delicious as a baseball pennant race can get.
</P>
<P>
   Angel fans apparently aren't hungry. There reportedly were
42,972 of them at the stadium Sunday evening, but one wouldn't know
it by the decibel count. It wasn't until the ninth inning that the
fans got animated, and even then it was with the urging of the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   And by then, maybe 10,000 of them already had called it a night
and left for home. At 7 p.m. On a Sunday. With no traffic concerns.
With Ken Griffey still in the game. If you can't stick around for
that, why bother coming at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty quiet out there at times,'' said Tim Salmon, the
Long Beach product who, with Mike Piazza exiled to New York, is the
best day-in, day-out player in Southern California. ``We had a full
house, but there wasn't that buzz like you get in East Coast
parks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's buzz, as in excitement, as opposed to the ganja buzz at
old Raider Coliseum crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been to the east, you know what the fans can do,''
Salmon continued. ``You come to bat in the ninth inning, with their
closer on the mound, and you can't help but feel the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get that here. I know there are passionate season
ticket holders here. I know a lot of fans who are excited for us.
But even in the ninth inning tonight, it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty for fans to appreciate. The Angels dropped two
games behind Friday night, but pitched the Mariners tough Saturday
and Sunday to draw even in the race and bring the Texas series to a
head.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Olivares stranded nine Mariners in the first six innings.
The Angels ran the Mariners ragged for three runs in the third. Ken
Griffey went hitless. Troy Percival pitched a 1-2-3 ninth. What's
not to cheer?
</P>
<P>
   Considering what this team has endured this season, you'd think
the faithful wouldn't need a goose. The Angels lead baseball in
disabled list transactions this season. They are currently without
Darin Erstad. Salmon has played in 131 games this season despite a
knife in his left foot (plantar fascia).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have used a platoon at catcher and second base all
season, and have stayed in contention with only two pitchers,
Percival and Chuck Finley, with a history of consistent service.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, 5-2 through mid-June, went 0-5 with a 8.38 ERA in
July. Jerrod Washburn, who stymied a rally by retiring Griffey and
Edgar Martinez in the seventh, was making only the third relief
appearance of his pro career. Steve Sparks and his poofball will
throw tonight, and Terry Collins will take applications for
Wednesday's game if Ken Hill can't start.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger fans would be delirious if their team had this kind of
heart and guile. They would donate a kidney to have a closer with
the intensity of Percival.
</P>
<P>
   Angel fans either don't care or are too conditioned to past
failures 1982, 1986, 1995 to get too close. In the seventh, Griffey
sent a fly ball deep to left with two men on, and the deep breath
the crowd took was audible. At least half expected it to go out,
because this is what they've come to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow is why you play this game,'' said Terry Collins,
whose feelings never need prompting. ``To get into the postseason
and be in this situation, the race in our yard, in our hands, is
what it's all about. This is fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are a lot of people who don't think we have a
chance. I'd love to have the fans standing and yelling every inning
the way they did tonight in the ninth. But I don't know if it
really makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon says it couldn't hurt. The Angels got one break Sunday,
when Lou Pinella asked Griffey to sacrifice. He popped a bunt up.
Johnny Oates is unlikely to give the bunt sign to Juan Gonzalez
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a lot of excitement and emotion this week,'' Salmon
said. ``We need that tenth guy. We don't have the luxury of the
league's best lineup or the league's best pitching staff. We need
that intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here will get excited when we get a rally going. But
a crowd can also initiate a rally. That's what we need for the last
three home games of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated, it's put up or shut up time. And the fans have
already shown they can shut up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
