<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OILERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILERS DONE IN BY PATRIOTS' ONE-MINUTE DRILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll looked through the crowd of
reporters toward the podium in the makeshift interview room that
doubles as the Patriots' weight room as Terry Glenn began speaking
in a rare postgame session with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see him up there,'' said the beaming coach.
``It's great to see Terry make a play like that, especially in the
fourth quarter. That was a tough game and we won a tough game. I
think that says a lot for our football team and the people we have
making plays when it really counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was right. The Patriots may have stumbled for parts of
three quarters, ever so fortunate to be tied, 6-6, at the half and
trailing just 16-13 in the final quarter. But in the end, Drew
Bledsoe fired a 51-yard touchdown pass/-run to Glenn for the
winning score. It was topped off by Lawyer Milloy's 30-yard
interception return for a touchdown 18 seconds later as the
Patriots finished off the Tennessee Oilers, 27-16, before 59,973
fans, most of whom didn't leave till the end.
</P>
<P>
   The win enabled the Patriots, who have not committed a turnover
this season, to head into the off week 2-1 having sampled the
cream-of-the-crop Denver Broncos, the pushover Indianapolis Colts,
and the middle-of-the-road Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Drew and Terry really set it off,'' said Ty Law, who
intercepted a pass at the end of the game and did a fine job in
coverage of Yancey Thigpen, an old nemesis of the Patriots. ``Once
they scored, the defense just started to get cranked up. Lawyer
made a big play, Chris Slade made a big hit at the end (on running
back Rodney Thomas), and it really showed how our team can rise to
the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who were anxious to see Bledsoe (18 for 30, 250 yards, no
interceptions for the third straight game) lead a fourth-quarter
drive to bring his team from behind had to be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The defense had pushed the Oilers back from their 20, where
they'd started a drive with 7:47 left to play, to the 13. A big
third-down hit by Tedy Bruschi on Eddie George for a 4-yard loss
was huge.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots took over on their 45 following a punt, and in two
plays they turned the game around.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back Robert Edwards, who later would break a
53-yarder, busted up the middle for 4 yards before Bledsoe and
Glenn connected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slant,'' said Glenn. ``Drew and I were on the same
vibe. He read the blitz and I read the blitz. The key was for him
to get the ball off. He did it. He just got me the ball and I just
ran.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who led Patriots receivers with four catches for 102
yards, caught the pass at the Tennessee 45 and ran past one
defender before getting a key block at the 5 from Shawn Jefferson,
who took out cornerback Denard Walker, allowing Glenn to leap into
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Terry before the game, `Listen, it's time for you to
have a big game.' Terry responded. I wish everybody would not worry
about Terry. Terry's fine,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   For three quarters, the Oilers were content to let George pound
away against a defense that was spending a lot of time on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   If New England's defense was tired _ it spent 36:30 on the field
_ because of the heat and humidity, it wasn't showing it,
especially late.
</P>
<P>
   After the Glenn touchdown, the Oilers took over at their 20.
Steve McNair threw over Willie Davis's head on first down, then
tried to get the ball to Thigpen, but Milloy was there to intercept
a poorly thrown ball and run it back for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the NFL and they (Tennessee) have a lot of heart,'' said
safety Willie Clay. ``It's a matter of gaining maturity for them.''
</P>
<P>
   If it was a matter of the Oilers needing to gain maturity, did
that mean the Patriots had matured?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it says a lot for us,'' said Clay. ``To win a game in
the fourth quarter, that's important to a team after a battle like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Bledsoe-to-Glenn play and the Milloy interception,
another key play was Derrick Cullors's 8-yard gain on a flip pass
from Bledsoe during a 10-play, 77-yard scoring drive that tied the
game at 13 with 5:41 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors caught the flip as Bledsoe was about to be hit on third
and 4 from the Patriots 29, avoided one tackler, and got the first
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He heard me call his name and he threw me the ball,'' said
Cullors. ``He just kind of flipped it to me. At that point everyone
was saying that play changed the pace of things, but I was just
trying to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe connected with Glenn for 27 yards and with Vincent
Brisby for 16. On third and 5 at the 15, Bledsoe connected with old
reliable Ben Coates for a 6-yard gain. On first and goal from the
9, the Patriots, who had the run the ball only six times in the
first half, committed to running it in. Edwards ran for 2 and then
for 7 tough yards and the tying score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed me they believed in me,'' said Edwards, who gained
92 yards on 12 carries for a 7.7-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Al Del Greco, who kicked three field goals, put the Oilers ahead
for the final time with a 45-yarder with 10:54 remaining in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the teams exchanged field goals to make it a
6-6 game at intermission. The Patriots were quite fortunate. The
defense spent 19:50 of the 30 minutes on the field. And though it
allowed the Oilers to go 5 for 9 on third-down conversions, the New
England defense didn't allow them in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they scored, we came back,'' said Brisby. ``That is
how we are. We don't give up. We keep coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
