<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING MISSING FOR HOLYFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was the usual wild and incoherent scene inside the
ring after a Don King-promoted heavyweight title fight.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Bean, a proud and game fighter only moments earlier, was
now irate. Butch Lewis, Bean's promoter, was screaming at referee
Brian Garry. Cameras flashed. King was pushing his way through the
melee to defend Garry. Microphones and videocams were thrust in
front of many a face. Garry was defending himself. Evander
Holyfield was being paraded around the ring, arms raised high in
victory. Much of the boxing world got through those ropes and into
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the one boxer Holyfield apparently needs most of all
_ Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Once again fighting someone other than Tyson Saturday night,
Holyfield looked more decent than dominant, more ordinary than
extraordinary, more an aging boxer than the vibrant heavyweight
champion of the world. ``The Champ Hits Home'' was how King billed
this homecoming bout for Holyfield against the lampooned Bean;
alas, it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was clumsy and awkward,'' said Holyfield of Bean, and that
certainly was true of Bean's footwork. But Bean was far from clumsy
or awkward in how he stood up to Holyfield, taking the champ's best
punches early and even taking a controversial knockdown in the 10th
round. Even then, Holyfield couldn't take out Bean with an
uncontested, unprotected, unexpected short right to the temple as
Bean tried to extricate himself from the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took away my combinations,'' was one Holyfield analysis of
this fight that turned out much, much better than expected. ``He
slipped some jabs on me ... he got some good shots on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was a good left uppercut by Bean in the third
round, a good overhand right by him in the fifth, another solid
right in the eighth, and on and on. Followed by a flurry of shots
from Bean to Holyfield's head in the 12th and final round that gave
Bean the round on all judge's cards, when more than 41,000 fans in
the Georgia Dome were imploring Holyfield for a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the man credit,'' said Holyfield. ``The man
came here to fight and he went 12 rounds. He's a better boxer than
many people give him credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is Holyfield no longer the boxer he was? Or does Holyfield
need Tyson to bring out his best?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they fight the fight,'' boomed King. ``People gave
Bean no chance, but look what he did once he got into the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield complained that Bean was hitting him with rabbit
punches, ``but the ref didn't want to do anything about them.''
Even more, though, Holyfield was frustrated by Bean's style. Bean
was awkward, repeated the champ, ``and I couldn't get off my
combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bean nor Holyfield had the punch to take the other out.
So Bean was left with that impossible situation _ try to win by a
decision over Holyfield in Holyfield's hometown _ and it was no
surprise that Holyfield took a unanimous decision. Two judges
scored the bout 117-110, one 116-111, for Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I won the fight,'' said Bean, an opinion not shared
by any in the media or anyone not wearing a red turban, Bean's
trademark attire. ``I put up a lot of pressure and I brought a lot
of pressure on. I had him on the ropes (several times) and I hit
him with a lot of good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Holyfield tried to argue against the evidence, he was not
old, not rusty, and not overconfident. Holyfield just was not
fighting Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Johnny Ruiz of Methuen, Mass., made an
extremely strong move into the upper echelon of heavyweights by
taking out Jerry Ballard with a TKO in the fourth round. King, who
recently took on Ruiz's contract, was ecstatic, saying that Ruiz
``is now ready to take on Lennox Lewis,'' the World Boxing Council
champ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
