<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH FOR SOSA TO CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ What has happened to Sammy Sosa? On the most important
day of his baseball career he couldn't find a way to dig out of a
rut, and neither could the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and Co. had yet another bad outing Sunday, resulting in a
7-3 loss and a three-game sweep by the Cincinnati Reds. It couldn't
have come at a worse time for Sosa or the crowd of 40,117 lured by
the home run race and the dogfight the Cubs are in for the
wild-card slot in the National League playoffs. The Mets beat
Florida, 5-0, Sunday and now have a one-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa went 0 for 5 on ``Sammy Sosa Celebration Day,'' making him
0 for 17 since he hit home run No. 63 last Wednesday. Some
celebration. He began the day trailing Mark McGwire of the
Cardinals by one homer, but he's now trailing by two after McGwire
hit No. 65 Sunday in Milwaukee against the Brewers. McGwire's home
run, as if an omen, was hit during the middle of the Sosa
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago lost to Cincinnati in part because of three home runs by
Bret Boone, the last of which appeared to be foul down the
left-field line. No matter. The way things went for Sammy and the
Cubs Sunday, finishing at Milwaukee and Houston might be a better
alternative than the pressure-cooker the club has played in for the
last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by one game with five to go, Chicago plays the Brewers
Tuesday and Wednesday, and that could help. Sosa has hit 10 home
runs against Milwaukee this year. Then there are three games in
Houston, and the Cubbies won't have to face Randy Johnson. New York
has two games left at home against Montreal and finishes the season
at Atlanta against Bruce Chen, Tom Glavine, and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The home run race is important. But Chicago's goal is to make
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose sight of the fact the other team is trying to
win ballgames, too,'' said Cubs manager Jim Riggleman. ``They're
not going to give you the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was showered with gifts, including a 1998 Chrysler
convertible. Commissioner Bud Selig presented him with a trophy for
hitting his home runs and beating Roger Maris's record of 61 homers
in a season, set in 1961, even though McGwire was first. McGwire
sent a note of congratulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cincinnati played great,'' said Sosa. ``They came and played
like a first-place team. Every mistake that we made they
capitalized on it. Nothing you can do about it. I had three days
without a hit. I'm coming back. I'm not giving up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa at first tried to deny the distractions had affected him.
But eventually he admitted that he was pressing and swinging at bad
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   At least Sosa was happy for a little while with the festivities,
which were attended by Michael Jordan. After a half-hour program,
he romped around Wrigley Field, a la Carl Yastrzemski in his Boston
retirement party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' he said. ``I did romp around the field to
show the fans how much I love them. I was real happy that the fans
showed me their appreciation today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
