u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LANDFILL-CEMETERY-     09-21 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LANDFILL-CEMETERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES DISCOVER RELATIVES WERE BURIED IN LANDFILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The only comfort that Angel Mendoza could find when
he buried his older brother, Melvin, four years ago was the thought
that he at least had laid him to rest in a beautiful place.
</P>
<P>
   Perched on top of a hill in Cypress Hills Cemetery, a sprawling
200-acre site that straddles Queens and Brooklyn, the elder Mendoza
would own in death something he would have marveled at in life: a
stunning panorama of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   That's why devastated does not begin to describe what Angel
Mendoza felt when he learned a year later that the hill was
actually an illegal landfill made up of construction and demolition
debris. He and hundreds like him were horrified at the thought that
they had buried their loved ones in someone else's trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't believe it,'' Mendoza said. ``How could they do
this to people, especially when they were vulnerable and
grieving?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 1,000 families with loved ones on the hill known as
Terrace Meadow opted to move them. Others decided to let the dead
remain because cemetery officials assured them the mound was
stable.
</P>
<P>
   The relative peace of mind for those who kept their deceased
relatives on the hill was shattered in July when a state Supreme
Court justice ruled that the 50-foot mound was structurally unsound
and ordered nearly 700 families to dig up their dead. Lawyers for
families and the cemetery are trying to negotiate a plan for moving
the remaining graves.
</P>
<P>
   The building of Terrace Meadow reflects two trends in the city's
business of death: the need for more burial space and the drive to
adapt to changing demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Cypress Hills Cemetery realized in 1986 that a hill
would not only add about 5,000 spaces, but would also cater to the
city's growing and aging Chinese population. They learned that
Chinese families would pay top dollar for high ground and
picturesque scenery, two requisites for auspicious feng shui, the
Chinese art of balancing the unseen forces of landscape and people.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest headstones on Terrace Meadow, most of them from
1992, belong to Chinese families. But in 1993, after the mound's
questionable composition was revealed, an Asian burial society that
had steered funeral homes to the hill dissolved, and Chinese
burials there stopped.
</P>
<P>
   There are now relatively few Chinese headstones left on the
hill. Most markers that remain on its two plateaus carry Hispanic
surnames and were placed between 1993 and 1995, when burials there
were banned. Some of those families have accused the cemetery of
discriminating against minorities by selling them plots on the hill
without explaining what it was made of.
</P>
<P>
   Cypress Hills Cemetery, which was established in 1848, is home
to the likes of Gentleman Jim Corbett, the 19th-century
prizefighter, Mae West and Jackie Robinson. In recent years, it has
become a popular cemetery for many immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the tortured history of Terrace Meadow now threatens to
overshadow the cemetery's credits.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits by families and the state attorney general's office are
still pending. State officials said Cypress Hills never got proper
permission to build the hill. And a court-appointed receiver took
over the cemetery's management in 1994 after state officials
discovered financial improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the people who did this to be punished,'' said Eduardo
Landecho, a retired jewelry maker who buried his wife and his
mother on Terrace Meadow and who moved them elsewhere in the
cemetery earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Landecho, who has joined one lawsuit, said he and his family had
scraped together more than $11,000 to pay for the burials. ``I
sacrificed to give them a decent burial, and the cemetery just
disrespected me and my family,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     09-21 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN'S STREAK ENDS AFTER 2,632 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Maybe the Red Sox and Cubs are going to meet
in the World Series, folks. That's the only thing left in this
perfect baseball summer, a holy hardball season in which the
national pastime re-established itself as America's true love.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, on the day that one man hit his 65th (and he should have
had his 66th) home run, another man voluntarily stopped a streak
after playing in 2,632 consecutive games. Orioles third baseman Cal
Ripken, Jr., the man who pulled baseball from the gutter in the
post-strike summer of '95, walked into Oriole manager Ray Miller's
office and said it was time to end the streak. Ripken did this just
a couple of hours after Mark McGwire cranked home run No. 65.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but I can't believe I'm typing these numbers. Sixty-five
homers. Two-thousand, six-hundred, thirty-two consecutive games.
When I was a little kid we had 61 homers and 2,130 consecutive
games, and those records were going to last a lifetime. And now the
homer record is topped on a daily basis, and the consecutive-game
streak has succumbed to a new iron man who finally took a day off
with a week to go inon the next-to-last-day of the stardust season
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken did not call in sick. He could have played. There was no
injury, no family crisis, no subpoena supeona from Kenneth Starr to
take him out of the lineup. No. He just decided it was time. He and
his team had become prisoners of the streak, so Rip did everyone a
favor and put it to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how hard this must have been. The guy played every game
since May 30, 1982, and could have played every game for who knows
how long? But folks looked at his sagging numbers (.273, 14 homers,
61 RBIs) and the Orioles' disappointing season and Ripken got
blamed for letting the streak drag everyone down.
</P>
<P>
   I talked to Ripken (yeesh, I hate it when I sound like Larry
King) about the stress of the streak when the Red Sox visited
Baltimore in July. At that time the streak was cited as the cause
of everything wrong with the Orioles and the iron man and his
manager were defensive about the touchy topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazes me,'' Ripken said July 10. ``At a low point
or a frustrating point, I wonder, `Why do I have to sit here and
actually defend the desire to go out and play?' I think it should
be the people that don't want to play that should have to defend
their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the streak the reason why we're losing? Is the streak the
reason why we won last year? The answer to both is no. It kind of
makes me laugh a little bit the way it is brought up. The issue
should be performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak, like everything else, will take care of itself. If
something happens, it happens. It could end with an injury. It
could end in many different ways. When it presents itself, who
knows? How am I supposed to know how it will end?
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to play every day, you have to be worthy,'' said
Ripken. ``If at some point, you're not worthy, it ends. But so far
it hasn't. When I no longer deserve to be the everyday third
baseman, it'll end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strip away everything and it's simple. I'm a baseball player.
I love being a baseball player. You have a small window in the
grand scheme of things to be a baseball player. You can't play
until you're 65. To me, I'm healthy and I want to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, he caved to the outside pressures and it must have
killed him. Ripken is a proud man, a 38-year-old son of a baseball
lifer. Cal Ripken Sr. never played a day in the big leagues, but he
is one of the toughest Birds to put on a uniform (Rip Sr. once took
a Black and Decker drill to his foot to relieve pressure caused by
an ingrown toenail) and he taught his son to go to work every day,
even when it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   We all could use a dose of the Ripken work ethic. You do your
job, you do it to the best of your ability, and you do it every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken went to work every day for more than 16 seasons, and when
he finally stopped, it was only because of external pressure. Cal's
day off won't cure the Orioles' woes, or his season of mediocrity,
but it does eliminate any speculation that he and the Orioles are
more interested in history than in winning.
</P>
<P>
   There's nice symmetry in the fact that Ripken chose to sit on a
night the Orioles were playing the Yankees (when it became clear
Ripken wasn't playing, all of the 1998 Yankees went to the top step
of the dugout and applauded). Rookie Ryan Minor started in Ripken's
place, and goes down as the new Babe Dahlgren. It was Dahlgren who
stepped in for Gehrig in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   For a little perspective, consider that Ripken beat Gehrig's
record by 502 games, by more than three full seasons. Had Ripken
began his career the day after he broke Gehrig's record, he would
have been the active consecutive-game leader when he sat Sunday
night (now that Cal has hit the pine, Albert Belle is the ranking
iron man with 327 games).
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles come to Fenway Thursday night for the first of four
games. Red Sox fans won't have a chance to see Mark McGwire or
Sammy Sosa this week, but they ought to stand and applaud madly for
Ripken every chance they get. He is a part of baseball history. We
will not see his like again. Someone else might hit 68 or 70 home
runs in our lifetime, but Ripken's record of 2,632 consecutive
games should stand forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
