u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-UNION-CORRUPTION-6     09-21 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UNION-CORRUPTION-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION'S CHIEF IS CHALLENGED ON CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fast-growing dissident movement at District Council
37, the giant union representing 120,000 New York City public
employees, is mounting a major challenge to Stanley Hill, the
union's executive director, demanding that he act decisively to
stop the corruption that has rocked the union.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that the Manhattan district attorney is investigating 12
of the district council's 56 locals, the dissidents assert that
Hill has done little to prevent financial scandals in which, union
investigators say, more than $3 million has disappeared from
various locals.
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents are urging Hill to open the district council's
books and to provide tough oversight of its 56 locals to check
dishonest leaders and to catch them before their misspending or
embezzlement plunges union locals into the red.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents are not mounting an electoral challenge to Hill,
who was re-elected to a new three-year term in January. Instead,
they are pressuring him to make fundamental changes in his
leadership, maintaining that he has adopted an anything-goes
attitude that has encouraged the leaders of some union locals to
overspend, embezzle and commit election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is a cesspool of corruption,'' said Mark Rosenthal,
a leader of Hill's critics and the newly elected president of a
local representing 2,400 city motor vehicle operators. ``We're
trying to save the union before the district attorney marches in
and people get the wrong impression about the union, and everyone
is branded a crook.''
</P>
<P>
   A major factor fueling the movement is the dissidents' belief
that Hill long turned a blind eye when Charles Hughes, head of the
local representing 22,000 school crossing guards and cafeteria
workers, embezzled more than $1.7 million, according to a union
judicial panel. Among the funds that the panel found he took
wrongfully were $685,000 in overtime expenses and $329,000 to pay
his family's personal credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   The critics are also demanding that Hill take a tougher stance
toward Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. They complain that Hill betrayed his
members by accepting a contract with a two-year pay freeze in 1996
and by not battling Giuliani's workfare program over their concern
that welfare recipients in the program are doing jobs once done by
union employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, interviewed on Friday, played down the dissidents'
importance, saying their committee was not very large.
</P>
<P>
   Defending himself against criticisms that he has let corruption
fester, Hill has repeatedly said that he had to respect the
autonomy of the 56 locals in District Council 37, which is part of
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees. But
the district council's executive board is to vote in November on
giving Hill more power to oversee each local's finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making changes,'' Hill said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents, who formed a committee two months ago, have more
credibility than most insurgent groups because their ranks include
the presidents of five union locals, which represent more than
12,000 workers. The group, called the Committee for Real Change at
D.C. 37, says 5,000 workers have signed petitions backing its
platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a tremendous chance of making real change in this
union,'' said Carl Biers, executive director of the Association for
Union Democracy, a nonprofit monitoring group based in New York.
``Their platform is right on the mark for the problems DC 37 has _
financial abuse and a structure that concentrates power in the
hands of the heads of a few big locals. I'm impressed that they've
already forced Stanley Hill to address these issues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Committee for Real Change is demanding that the district
council's executive director be chosen through direct elections by
all members, rather than by a council of delegates that is
dominated by a handful of local presidents. In the committee's
view, one reason that Hill has not moved vigorously against the
presidents of locals suspected of corruption is that he needed
their support to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the committee wants to require all 56 locals to
have a neutral group, like the American Arbitration Association,
oversee union elections. They point to a recent election at the
local representing 7,000 city engineers. After a preliminary count
put an insurgent ahead in the race for the local's presidency,
several ballot boxes disappeared from a locked mail room controlled
by district council officials.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Albano, the local's longtime leader, denied any
wrongdoing, but a new election was ordered, and the insurgent, Roy
Commer, beat Albano by an even greater margin.
</P>
<P>
   Showing growing dissatisfaction with the council's leadership,
union members have voted out incumbents at two other locals this
year. The three incumbents who were voted out remain on the
20-member executive board and receive an $18,000 annual stipend
from the union, which leaders of the Committee for Real Change said
was undemocratic and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   In stressing the importance of financial reforms, the dissidents
point to the investigation of several locals that bought thousands
of turkeys to give to members at Thanksgiving and Christmas. Union
officials say they have told Manhattan District Attorney Robert
Morgenthau that they believe some union leaders received kickbacks
because several locals paid $44 each for turkeys that usually sell
for about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal, the new head of the motor vehicle operators' local,
suspected kickbacks and criticized his predecessor for spending
$91,888 for a Christmas party in 1995. And members of the local
representing City University workers have asked Hill to investigate
how $192,000 disappeared from their union's treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King went to Memphis in 1968, and he died there
fighting for sanitation workers who wanted to have a union and join
the American Federation of State County and Municipal Employees,''
said Tom Dawes, an organizer in the engineers' union and a leader
of the Committee for Real Change. ``I don't think Martin Luther
King went there so that 30 years later a few selfish individuals
could use the union's treasury as a personal piggy bank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
