A5389 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MILLOY-B     09-21 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MILLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLOY PICKS PERFECT MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Once again, just as it was last week against
the Colts, it was Lawyer Milloy's intelligence, his instincts, his
feel for a given situation that led to an interception.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, unlike the gift from Peyton Manning, the
interception saved a game.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight reels will show Steve McNair's pass coming
directly to Milloy, then Milloy will be shown racing downfield,
reaching the end zone, dancing in the end zone, sending the crowd
at Foxboro Stadium into ecstasy. His interception and return for a
touchdown with 4:07 left in a 20-16 game was the height of
defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the quarterback's eyes,'' said Milloy, who was playing
in a zone defense after he saw the Oilers' offensive moves just
after the snap. ``And McNair threw it right to me.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's pass was directly to Milloy _ sometimes the hardest to
catch _ but Milloy said he wasn't even thinking of dropping the
ball. ``What it was,'' he said, ``is one of those plays where it's
hard to look because you're seeing all that green in front of you.
I was thinking it would be a big turnover at that point, even
without the score.''
</P>
<P>
   But once he had the pick, the safety went on, ``from there on I
was thinking, just let your athletic ability take over ... and then
celebrate in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   So much more happened than what will be seen in the highlights.
As the Patriots' other safety, Willie Clay, put it, ``It was like a
chess match out there,'' offensive and defensive coordinators
trying to read the other team's tendencies _ and minds _ with blitz
packages and blitz pickup packages.
</P>
<P>
   As the Oilers lined up on their 20 with a little more than four
minutes left, Milloy was involved in his own chess match.
Afterward, the safety tried to explain what his duties were _
basically to start out in a man-to-man defense if a certain
receiver went one way but to drop into a zone if something else
happened. ``It's hard to explain,'' he said. ``It took me a whole
summer just to learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milloy read perfectly what was happening in front of him,
dropped into a zone, and, as usual with the Patriots' aggressive
defense, ``we're going after the ball and we're going after
turnovers, and when you score a TD on a turnover, it's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   This had happened a week earlier against the Colts. Milloy and
cornerback Ty Law instantly read an Indianapolis formation, swapped
positions seamlessly, and Manning never caught on. His pass went
directly to Law.
</P>
<P>
   This time McNair didn't catch on, or his receivers fled to areas
of the field where the QB never expected, ``because you're doing
something based on seeing all those things going on in front of you
and I was following his eyes the same time,'' said Milloy. ``I was
pretty much in a zone and he pretty much threw it right to me.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, Milloy went on, ``didn't know I was going to be there. I
was hiding inside the defense and then I just jumped out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fourth-quarter play, it was a game-turning play. It was
a play the Patriots' defense will have to make time and again.
Milloy ran his pick back for the first TD of his career, and later
Law would pick off another McNair pass.
</P>
<P>
   Good vibes here _ a Lawyer and Law on the same side of the
ledger. For once.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0144EDT &QL; 
