<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GLOBAL-FINANCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: IS THE GLOBAL CAPITALIST SYSTEM COLLAPSING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, the world's best-known money manager, George Soros,
warned that the global capitalist system ``is coming apart at the
seams.''
</P>
<P>
   His view reflected the fear _ felt more strongly by investment
professionals than by the individual Americans who entrust their
money to the pros _ that the global financial system is under the
greatest strain it has faced in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir Mohamad, the Malaysian prime minister, imposed capital
controls to make it harder for investors to take money out of his
country, saying he acted because the ``free market has failed
disastrously.''
</P>
<P>
   Soros, a hedge fund manager previously blamed by Mahathir for
causing Asia's problems, did not sound all that different when he
testified to Congress. ``Instead of acting like a pendulum,'' he
said, ``financial markets have recently acted more like a wrecking
ball, knocking over one country after another.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be overstating it, but there is no question that
international investors have grown very worried. The Dow Jones
industrial average is down only 15 percent from the peak it reached
in July, but virtually every other market in the world has done
much worse. There is a flight of capital from emerging markets, and
from less solid companies in established markets.
</P>
<P>
   As that has happened, losses have piled up. It should surprise
no one that hedge funds such as those managed by Soros have done
poorly. They make money by using leverage _ that is, by borrowing
money _ and placing big bets. If the bets go wrong, they can lose
big.
</P>
<P>
   But there have also been large losses in established and, one
had thought, more conservatively run, financial institutions.
Hardly a day goes by that some bank or brokerage firm does not
announce it has lost another $100 million or more. The result has
been a fast-fall in the prices of financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses reflect the fact that derivative securities are far
more prevalent than they ever were before. There is nothing
inherently bad in such securities. They simply make it possible to
buy or sell risks _ of currency moves, or interest rate rises, or
lots of other things _ in ways not possible before.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's government and its banks essentially defaulted on
their debts, some Western banks found that they faced big losses
that they thought they had laid off. They had, for example, entered
into trades that would compensate their customers if the ruble
plunged in value. Then they covered that bet by entering into the
opposite trade with a big Russian bank. When the ruble plunged,
they lost money in honoring the first guarantee, and could not make
up the loss through the second transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses have stunned investors and reminded them that the
current accounting system does not allow them to gauge accurately
the risks being taken on with derivatives. Managements of financial
institutions have responded by being much more careful in taking
those risks. There are signs of a global credit crunch, in which
only the safest borrowers can get cash at reasonable rates.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the confidence in the ability of the
International Monetary Fund and the major Western governments to
keep things on an even keel has been shaken. The belief that they
would somehow protect imprudent investors grew after the Mexican
bailout in 1995, and contributed to the flood of money that went
into emerging markets in 1996 and 1997. Now that money is coming
out, the IMF is nearly broke, and Western governments have done
little.
</P>
<P>
   In that atmosphere, it is easy to talk of the disintegration of
the world financial system. But it may also be overdone. In a few
months, investors may become less risk averse if they see the world
has not collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   As for countries, those that most alarmed investors may be
having second thoughts. Russia, which had all but repudiated its
foreign debt, last week said it was looking for ways to treat
foreign investors better. As for Malaysia, after it was done
denouncing the global capitalist system, it hired Salomon Smith
Barney to try to float an international loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
