<HEADER>
A5394 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OILERS-MCNAIR-BOS     09-21 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-MCNAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILERS' MCNAIR ONLY FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The quarterback and running back sat about 5
yards from each other in the locker room, both staring down at the
floor or glancing around the room while teammates put their best
spin on what went wrong Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tennessee Oilers quarterback Steve McNair and running back
Eddie George will make their best attempt to look forward, to put
Sunday's fourth-quarter collapse against the Patriots behind them.
</P>
<P>
   They know they have to. They are the team's cornerstones, McNair
a 1995 first-round draft pick brought in two seasons after Warren
Moon's departure, George a 1996 first-round pick who helped give
the team a reliable ground game.
</P>
<P>
   How soon they vault themselves to the echelon of the best
running back/-quarterback tandems will depend on how well they
respond to debacles like Sunday's. One thing's for certain: Both
have had it with current events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurts,'' said McNair. ``But we just have to fight
back next week. Knowing you had the lead and had a chance to win.
They didn't do anything to stop us. We stopped ourselves. They made
the big plays at the end. We gave up the big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   George agreed. ``When we're in that situation (of finishing a
game strongly), I'm pretty sure we will reflect back on this day
and say this is our chance, this is our opportunity,'' said George,
who had 100 yards on 23 carries and a touchdown catch but wasn't a
factor late in the fourth quarter, when the Oilers fell apart
offensively and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to challenges, said George, ``is nothing you can
prepare for. I think we've worked hard. We've studied. We've done
everything possible. Right now we have to make plays for the full
60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you're going to be able to compete in the
playoffs and the only way you're going to get in the upper echelon
of the NFL is to make plays in crucial moments.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair completed 28 of 38 pass attempts for 202 yards and one
touchdown but also threw two interceptions after the Patriots went
ahead, 20-16. And the noted scrambler ran for only 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On the first interception, McNair and coach Jeff Fisher said
there was miscommunication by McNair and tight end Frank Wycheck,
who cut inside when the quarterback thought he would cut outside.
</P>
<P>
   The second pickoff was much easier to explain. ``I just made a
bad throw,'' McNair said. ``Things like that happen. I just have to
be more patient and take what they give me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like George, McNair said he felt the team didn't make the big
plays when needed. He added that he had hoped wide receiver Kevin
Dyson had been more involved. But he stopped short of agreeing with
a few Tennessee wideouts' assertion that the offense has become too
predictable because of a short-passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say a lot of the things right now because we lost,''
he said. ``If we had won, we would have been glorified. We need to
look within ourselves and do the things to prepare ourselves
better. (Long patterns) are out of my control.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is run the offense they put in each and every
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
