<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     09-21 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYS WERE THING IN PATRIOTS' WINNING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Dave Krieg had nothing to do with the
outcome, but with 19 years of service in the NFL, he knows better
than most what makes the difference in a game like the one the
Patriots played against the Tennessee Oilers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five plays that usually determine who wins the
game,'' said Krieg, the 39-year-old veteran quarterback who backs
up Steve McNair of the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the Patriots made those plays. When all the big plays
came in the final minutes of the game, they made them all. We
didn't make any. Up to that point, we were making the big plays,
and that's why I thought we were going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't to be for the Oilers, who self-destructed on three
critical plays in the last four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With five minutes left, the Oilers led, 16-13, in a game that
had gone the way they wanted most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Then bad things started to happen. The Patriots had second and 6
on their 49, when the Oilers called for a blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had worked well for us all day,'' said coach Jeff Fisher.
``We rolled the safety (Marcus Robertson) up and had him blitz off
the corner. We had the cornerback on that side of the field back
off, because he didn't have any help at the post. They just hit us
with a big play. They had the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he didn't think the Patriots anticipated what the
Oilers were going to do. ``Earlier in the game, we ran the same
kind of defense from the opposite side, and we sacked Drew Bledsoe
on the play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did have the perfect call, a quick slant to Terry
Glenn running across the middle from the left side of the field. As
he was supposed to, cornerback Darryll Lewis backed off at the
snap. Safety Blaine Bishop sat in the middle of the field, and left
cornerback Denard Walker dropped deep on his side of the field. The
three defensive backs were spread across the field about 15 yards
deep. Lewis was 5 yards off Glenn, when Glenn caught the ball in
stride and took off across the field, left-to-right, then cut down
the right sideline and headed for the end zone and a 20-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught us in the right defense,'' said Bishop, one of the
best safeties in the league, ``but we still should have kept him
out of the end zone. He's got great speed, and he ran past us. If
we make the tackle and hold them to a field goal, it's still tied,
and we come down the field at the end of the game with a chance to
win. But they made the play, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the theme in the Tennessee locker room after the game.
``The difference between their team and ours is they make big plays
when it counts, our team has yet to do that. If we want to win, we
have to find some guys who are going to step up and make big
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots weren't finished with their big-play dominance at
the end. When the Oilers got the ball back, trailing by 4 with
plenty of time to play, McNair and his recievers made two poor
plays that resulted in New England interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Milloy grabbed the first one and returned it 30 yards for
a touchdown to put the game away, 27-16, and Ty Law added another
interception with less than two minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``On both of those plays there was a miscommunication between
the passer and the receiver,'' said Oilers offensive coordinator
Les Steckel. ``Steve thought that Frank Wycheck was going outside
and he went inside. Same way on the next one (to Yancey Thigpen).''
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen was especially frustrated at the loss. ``We had a plan
on offense all day and we stuck with it until we got behind,'' he
said. ``Then we started to do other things and they didn't work. I
don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense won this game. The Tennessee defense's
blitz package had stymied Bledsoe and his offensive teammates
almost the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had him off balance,'' said Bishop. ``We came after
him hard in the second quarter and hit him a lot. We wanted to get
him in third-and-long situations with pressure, and then drop into
a zone, make him throw underneath, and then make the tackle (short
of the first down).''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we did until the end,'' said Fisher. ``Then they
made the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston gambles on defense because its line is not that good.
The Oilers do not have a legitimate pass rusher either on the line
or at linebacker. So they have to use their defensive backs to
chase the quarterback. When they do, they leave themselves
vulnerable somewhere in the secondary. Bledsoe could not find that
``somewhere'' until late in the game with Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots could not run the ball. At the end of three
quarters they had just 196 yards of total offense. They wound up
with 322, thanks to Glenn's 51-yard reception and a late 53-yard
burst off tackle by Robert Edwards after the Oilers already had
cashed it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense controlled McNair and kept him in the
pocket until he blew up near the end.
</P>
<P>
   McNair entered the fourth period nearly perfect, with 19
completions in 24 attempts and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point Steve had thrown 98 passes in a row without an
inteception,'' said Fisher. ``But those things happen.'' McNair had
two in his next 10 throws.
</P>
<P>
   Those things will continue to happen to the Oilers until they
find a way to make big plays when the game is on the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
