<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-CAMPAIGN-NY     09-21 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN THIS RACE, IT'S L-WORDS ON BOTH SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-CAMPAIGN-DAMATO, NY-CAMPAIGN-SCHUMER, NY-PATAKI-AD,
NY-VALLONE-AD) 
(lh) 
 ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many races begin with policy debate and end with
name-calling. In this one, the candidates have apparently decided
to skip the preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Rep. Charles Schumer's primary victory on
Tuesday, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato was already on the air with an ad
accusing him of the usual leftist vices: raising taxes, pampering
criminals, perpetuating welfare. The ad invokes the dreaded L-word
not just once but twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Schumer's a New York City liberal,'' the narrator
intones at the start. ``Liberal Chuck Schumer,'' he says again at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   As if anticipating the attack (which is, after all, basically
the same attack D'Amato used six years ago), Schumer quickly hit
back with an L-word of his own. In a pair of television ads, he
insists it is really D'Amato who is to be blamed for higher taxes
and for mollycoddling criminals. Both ads conclude with the same
catchy formula: ``D'Amato _ too many lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and D'Amato are nothing if not knowing about the rules
of the game. They understand as well as anyone in politics how to
play, and how little room there is for fastidiousness. And so while
the Senate race may have gotten ugly early, it would be naive to
suppose that things have somehow got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of both candidates in this contest is clearly to
make it a referendum on the other: D'Amato wants, more than
anything else, a race about Schumer. Schumer, meanwhile, wants one
about D'Amato. And it is quite likely that the winner of this
meta-contest will be the guy with the nastiest ads, the kind voters
tend to remember and the press loves to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have long comforted themselves with the idea that they
could beat D'Amato if they could just get a clean shot at him.
Always in the past, there has been some extenuating circumstance
for them to complain about _ and take comfort in: a three-way race
in 1980, a hopelessly underfinanced candidate in 1986, an
internecine primary in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schumer is among those who insist that D'Amato has never
really been tested. He likes to say the senator has never met a
candidate quite like Chuck Schumer, meaning that he has always had
weaker opposition than he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   He might just as well have said that Al D'Amato has never met a
candidate quite so much like Al D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Like the senator, Schumer is a prodigious fund-raiser who
suffers no romantic illusions about campaigning without cash. Like
D'Amato, he is no pretty face and knows not to rely on a telegenic
smile. And like him, he is an attention hound who likes to claim
credit for achievements early and often. Schumer has watched
D'Amato defeat three Democrats in a row in a nominally Democratic
state, and he has clearly learned from the master.
</P>
<P>
   Even his television commercial accusing D'Amato of fabrication
is, obliquely at least, an homage to the senator's talent. Its tag
line, ``too many lies for too long,'' slyly echoes an ad created by
the senator's media consultants in 1994 for George Pataki, then a
gubernatorial candidate: ``Mario Cuomo _ too liberal for too
long.''
</P>
<P>
   With the original ad, D'Amato and Pataki were obviously trying
to emphasize Cuomo's 12-year tenure, and they successfully framed
that contest as a referendum on whether the governor deserved
another term.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's Senate contest, Schumer SHOULD enjoy the same
challenger's advantage. D'Amato has held office for nearly 18
years, and a logical question is, how well has he performed in it?
</P>
<P>
   But D'Amato has more experience and, arguably, more God-given
talent to draw upon. In all of his Senate races, he has shown a
rare genius for deflecting attention away from himself and focusing
on his opponents' foibles instead. Who, for example, could not help
but admire his maudlin performance of 1992, when he managed to cast
his fumbling rival, Robert Abrams, as a mean-spirited,
hate-mongering bully?
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, D'Amato was once more theatrically aggrieved,
voicing his sorrow, dismay and deep personal hurt at the nasty tone
of Schumer's ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is unfortunate that he has gotten into the
character assassination by the use of the pejoratives and the very
personal,'' he said, once again making his opponent's conduct the
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
