u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CULLORS-     09-21 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CULLORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULLORS CATCH PART OF SUCCESSFUL FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There can be no big plays without ``little''
plays. There can be no 51-yard TD passes to Terry Glenn, perhaps,
without that 8-yard blind pass from Drew Bledsoe to Derrick
Cullors. It's all part of what coach Pete Carroll calls the
``formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Rewind the highlight tape from that short pass from Bledsoe to
Glenn that turned out so long and so large. Go all the way back to
the second drive of the third quarter, back to when the Patriots'
offense was struggling and in a stupor, back to when Tennessee just
had taken a 13-6 lead, back to when prospects seemed so grim.
</P>
<P>
   It was third and 4 at the Patriot 29 midway through the third
quarter. Bledsoe dropped back to pass, the Oilers once again had
coverage, and it seemed the play _ yet another New England
offensive play _ would go for naught. Bledsoe looked upfield and,
once again, saw nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in there on third down and I want to make big plays,''
Cullors would say. ``That's what a third-down back has to do _ make
big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   So Cullors, seeing that Bledsoe was in distress, did the only
thing he could do _ he shouted as loud as he could, ``Drew! Drew!''
Said Cullors, ``I wanted Drew to know that I was out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as Bledsoe would say later, ``Believe it or not, even with
70,000 people out there, I heard him ... and I felt I could chuck
it out to him.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was what Bledsoe would call a ``Meggett-esque
play,'' Cullors catching the short pass in the left flat,
sidestepping a tackler who was sure to bring him down short of the
first down and somehow scooting free for 8 yards and the first
down. ``One of the big plays in the game,'' said Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   But if Cullors had performed a Meggett-esque play, then Bledsoe
had performed a ... what? A Favre-esque play? A Flutie-esque play?
That's because Cullors would say, ``I don't think Drew ever saw me.
He heard me and he threw it to where he thought I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe would concede he threw the ball in the direction of the
``Drew! Drew!'' shouts, even though the QB also would admit, ``I
saw him out of the corner of my eye.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bledsoe also said, ``It was a dangerous kind of pass, but it
was a gamble I thought I could take because nobody was out there
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a play that had to be made if New England was to get back
in the game. And all knew it because, as Cullors said, ``players
and coaches came up to me on the bench and said how big it was,''
how it awoke the offense, how it got things going.
</P>
<P>
   All part of the ``formula.'' The foundation of the formula
``that we've got going for us,'' said Carroll, is that bedrock
defense that should keep New England in most games. That strong
defense leads to the next part of the formula, an offense that does
not turn the ball over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled,'' said Carroll of his offense having not turned
the ball over once this season. ``We've got three games where
they're not taking the ball away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now add to the formula the steady hand of Bledsoe, a liberal
pinch of Glenn making game-breaking catches, and finally a dash of
two of the other players making big plays.
</P>
<P>
   So fast-forward the highlight tape to later in that drive that
Cullors kept alive with the Meggett-esque catch and run. New
England had the ball with a first and goal from the Tennessee 9,
and Robert Edwards was called to run off left guard. The rookie
gained a measly 2 yards, and he pounded his fist in anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad that one guy was able to bring me down,'' said
Edwards. ``The offensive line had done their job and I had one guy
to beat and he brought me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, on second down, the Patriots surprised everybody, including
Edwards. ``We'd been passing the ball downfield,'' he said, ``and
maybe the Oilers thought we'd be passing again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the play called for Edwards to run, and the rookie showed
some of the moves that made the Patriots feel he was worth their
first draft choice, exploding into a large hole and then making a
nifty 360-degree turn near the goal line to escape the final
tackler.
</P>
<P>
   All part of the formula, just as was the fourth quarter _ the
pass by Bledsoe, the catch-and-run by Glenn, the interceptions by
Lawyer Milloy and Ty Law, the strong defense, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a formula going for us,'' Carroll said more than
once. It's a formula that all New England football fans can grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
