<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OILERS-THIGPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIGPEN SHORT OF PATIENCE WITH OILER PASSING SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ As a member of the Pittsburgh Steelers,
Yancey Thigpen was one of the best deep-threat wide receivers in
the National Football League. Three games into his Tennessee Oilers
career, the All-Pro is wondering why his enormous talents aren't
being put to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go from averaging 18 yards a catch to 8 yards a catch?''
said Thigpen, who had three catches for 21 yards against the
Patriots Sunday, the longest a 9-yarder. He now has 12 catches for
159 yards, an average of 13.3 yards a catch. That would be adequate
for some wideouts; for Thigpen, it's unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it me? Have I lost something?'' he asked reporters after
his team's 27-16 loss. ``No, it's just that if you catch a ball on
a stationary route, you're not going to do very much with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on a team which didn't pass the ball very much, but when
we did pass the ball it was very effective and it was down the
field,'' added Thigpen, who scoffed at the notion that the Patriots
defense kept him from being a factor.
</P>
<P>
   In a locker room where many of the Oilers vented frustations,
furious over having blown an opportunity to win, Thigpen was the
most vocal. He questioned the team's short-pass play calling,
adding that it made the Oilers' offense most predictable and
eventually hampered the running game.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics bolster Thigpen's claim: Quarterback Steve McNair
completed 28 of 38 passes for 202 yards, but his two longest passes
were a 27-yard shotgun throw to running back Eddie George and a
22-yard screen pass to George. McNair's longest completion to a
wideout was a 10-yarder to Willie Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Credit also the coverage of cornerback Ty Law, who did a solid
job against Thigpen. ``That's what I get paid for,'' said Law, who
was burned on a late-game fourth-down reception by Thigpen last
season when the latter helped the Steelers shock the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had his passes, but I thought we contained him,''
said Law.
</P>
<P>
   But when a reporter suggested that the Patriots took him out of
the game, Thigpen became irate. ``Who took me out of the game?
Nobody took me out of the game,'' he fired back. ``If you get a guy
for 5 yards, he's still in the core of everything, all the
defensive backs are still behind him. You hit a guy downfield and
it's him and couple of defensive backs. Now you have more of a
chance to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen said McNair has been able to get the ball to the
receivers but the team's patterns are too short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going 2 yards out, 3 yards out because we don't
have the patience to go downfield and defensive backs are just
backing off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now no one in the National Football League, for any
reason whatsoever, should respect our passing game until we start
throwing the ball downfield.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
