<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S CLOUD ANSWERS CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the first three games of the 1998 season, Boston
College has responded well to times of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as BC begins preparations for a nonconference matchup
Saturday at Louisville, the Eagles _ especially senior running back
Mike Cloud _ will have to deal with more adversity after BC coach
Tom O'Brien placed Cloud's backup, Quinton Lee, on indefinite
suspension Sunday for violating team rules. Lee, a junior running
back from Houston, was arrested by Boston police at an off-campus
party early Sunday morning and charged with assault and battery on
an officer and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's indefinite absence will place an added burden on Cloud and
sophomore Cedric Washington of Holyoke, who moves from No. 3 to No.
2 on the depth chart, as they try to keep BC's running game
operating smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   In another roster move, redshirt freshman offensive lineman John
Richardson will move up to backup right guard after Butch Palaza of
Quincy injured his left knee against Temple.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles faced adversity in each of their first three
games, Cloud responded.
</P>
<P>
   In a season-opening 41-31 victory at Georgia Tech, the Yellow
Jackets cut BC's 17-7 lead to 3 with just seconds left before
halftime, but Cloud helped BC maintain control by rushing 34 times
for 200 yards and a pair of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in the third quarter of a 41-14 BC romp, Rutgers'
Reggie Stephens scored on a 28-yard interception return that cut
the Eagles' lead to 20-14. But Cloud answered with a 6-yard TD that
capped a seven-play, 80-yard drive on which he accounted for 73
yards.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's 31-7 victory over Temple, Cloud rushed 27 times
for 196 yards and scored three touchdowns, including a dazzling
85-yarder, to help the Eagles score 31 consecutive points after
spotting the Owls an early 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three games now, I think we're starting to come together
a little bit,'' BC quarterback Scott Mutryn said. ``In the Georgia
Tech game maybe we got a little spoiled, because we played a very
perfect game and we didn't have any turnovers or penalties. Now,
the last two weeks we've gone through a little adversity and we've
responded well to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before, but this team has a lot of character on
it as well as many characters. I think it's really shown the last
couple of weeks, because when the challenge came, guys on this team
stepped up and met that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the challenge of preserving their perfect record
against Louisville, which scored a 35-9 victory at Illinois
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to present us with a different challenge,'' said
junior defensive tackle Mike Willetts, who played a significant
role in holding Temple's rushing attack, which entered the game
rated No. 4 in the nation, to 151 yards (297 total offense) with
five solo tackles, a fumble recovery, and a quarterback pressure.
``We've worked all (last) week on stopping the run and (this) week
it's a pass-oriented team, so we're going to have to be able to
change gears really quickly come Tuesday. It's definitely going to
be a challenge, but we just have to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it gives us great confidence knowing that we're 3-0 and
it's a game that we should win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, BC continued its ascent toward the Top 25 in the polls,
garnering 37 votes in the USA Today/ESPN coaches poll and 31 in the
Associated Press Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of the previews, a lot of people didn't think we were
going to be a talented team or able to win a lot of games,'' said
senior wideout Anthony DiCosmo, ``but I think we're slowly but
surely proving people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mutryn, ``We just have to continue getting better and not
worrying about what the polls say. If we keep winning, then in the
end the polls are going to reflect that. We can't get caught up
with that. We have to let our play on the field determine how good
a team we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
