<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK DAY IN SUNSHINE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forgive the fans of the Florida and Miami football
programs if there weren't a lot of sunny faces in the Sunshine
State Sunday morning. The Gators and the Hurricanes went down to
heartbreaking overtime defeats Saturday night, coincidentally
almost simultaneously on national television.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that last week's loss by Florida State to North Carolina
State and you have the rare occurrence of all three marquee
programs in the state being relegated to the second tier of the
national championship race before the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it had to happen to Florida. The Gators went into
Knoxville with five straight wins over the Vols and no Peyton
Manning to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? The Gators self-destructed with turnovers,
penalties, and ultimately a missed 32-yard field goal attempt by
Collins Cooper, which assured Tennessee of a 20-17 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what monkey everybody's been talking about, but
I'm glad it's off my back,'' said Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   Florida clearly is struggling to find an identity, especially at
quarterback, where coach Steve Spurrier continues to alternate
Jesse Palmer and Doug Johnson on every play.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the penalties that have come with this shuttle
system, the Gators have also turned the ball over _ a lot. They
coughed it up three times in the first half Saturday night, which
meant Florida has lost nine fumbles in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers weren't the sole province of the Gators. Matching the
frustration level of Spurrier and the Gators was Miami coach Butch
Davis, who watched his team turn the ball over on five consecutive
series from late in the second quarter to early in the fourth in
the Hurricanes' 27-20 loss to Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado remains unbeaten but continues to have problems with
penalties _ an ongoing problem for the Buffaloes under coach  &UR; Rick
Neuheisel &LR; . In Saturday's 25-6 win over Utah State, Colorado picked
up 11 penalties for 94 yards. Utah State was even worse, with 15
penalties for 118 yards ... Somebody should check the water supply
in the state of Kansas. A week ago Kansas State scored a record 59
points in the first half en route to a 73-7 romp over Northern
Illinois. Saturday, Kansas tied a school record by piling up a
49-14 halftime lead en route to a 63-14 win over Illinois State ...
Iowa State's 38-0 win over Ball State was the Cyclones' first
shutout in 14 years ... Brigham Young lost at Washington, 20-10,
but that wasn't nearly the worst part of the Cougars' weekend. En
route to Seattle Friday, the Cougars' chartered jet had to dive to
avoid collision with a military jet flying near Boise, Idaho. ``I
know how close cars can be, but this is the closest I've ever seen
two planes,'' said defensive tackle  &UR; Daren Yancey &LR; . The pilot of
the charter told the team that a cockpit radar alarm ordered the
jet to dive 500 feet to avoid collision with an A-10 Warthog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri continues to be frustrated in its quest to beat a No. 1
team. The Tigers, who led, 14-13, over No. 1 Ohio State at
halftime, were bombed by the Buckeyes in the second half en route
to a 35-14 loss. Mizzou is now 0-8 against No. 1 teams and has not
beaten a Top 10 team in 17 years ... Florida State, which had
scored only 30 points in its first two games, took out its
frustrations by pounding Duke, 62-13 ... All of you smart guys out
there who took Rutgers and the 44 points from Syracuse, you lost.
Syracuse won by 56, which proves the Orangemen are back on pace to
make a run at an Alliance Bowl slot, and also proves that Rutgers
might be the worst team in Division 1-A football. It's the most
points Rutgers has given up since 1888. The Knights have been
outscored by Syracuse in the last three years, 162-17 ... Final
score: Army 37, Cincinnati 20. What's the big deal, you say?
Nothing, unless you are an Army fan and realized it was the Cadets'
first conference game in its 109-year history. Who says Conference
USA doesn't have any sense of tradition? ... If you are looking for
a team to come from off the pace in the national race, take a look
at Georgia. The Bulldogs are 3-0 against marginal competition,
including a 16-9 win over Wyoming Saturday. Georgia's defense is
winning the games. In three weeks, Georgia has allowed only 13
points, its lowest three-game total since 1954. If you want a
long-shot Heisman Trophy candidate, try  &UR; Champ Bailey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is
playing defensive back and wide receiver for the Bulldogs, and
doing both very well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So much for Central Florida's 15 minutes of fame. The Golden
Knights finally had the national spotlight they wanted when they
faced Purdue in an ESPN contest Saturday. But it was an opportunity
squandered in a 35-7 loss. ``I don't know how the nation will view
us,'' said coach  &UR; Mike Kruczek &LR; . ``But we're mad at ourselves.''
... Texas, which has been routed by UCLA and Kansas the last two
weeks, is having first-half problems. The Longhorns were outscored
in the first half, 70-3, in the two games ... In a strange way,
Louisville's victory over Illinois was good news for Boston College
fans. The win snapped a 10-game losing streak for Louisville, which
not only takes some pressure off the Cardinals but gives BC coach
 &UR; Tom O'Brien  &LR; a nice tool to motivate his team for next week's game
at Louisville. Facing the Cardinals with a 1-2 record is better
than facing them at 0-3 in terms of the Eagles being overconfident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
