<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION ON COURSE FOR 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution will have many regrets this
season. They have earned 9 points in the last 19 days, shut out
their last three opponents, and converted themselves into one of
the hottest teams in Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But, since the Revolution earned just 20 points during the first
five months of the season, they failed to make the playoffs and
their recent wins have been rendered superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is significant that the team has regained credibility
with Walter Zenga as coach and that fan support has remained
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have established hope for the future, even though
the season has been taken away from us,'' general manager Brian
O'Donovan said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's 3-0 victory over Tampa Bay Saturday night was
their third successive shutout victory. Though the Revolution have
had little success on the field, and mostly failed to establish a
credible or effective style of play, they appear to have
established themselves on the sporting scene, averaging 18,813 in
home attendance at Foxboro Stadium. A 20,000-plus crowd is expected
for the final home match, against the MetroStars Saturday, and
Zenga called it a kickoff match for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution rallied too late in the season, and remain 6
points behind fourth-place Miami with two games remaining. They are
victims of a unique MLS tie-breaking rule in which the first
determining factor is head-to-head competition. In most leagues,
goal difference takes precedent, and the Revolution (minus-12) have
an eight-goal edge over Miami (minus-20).
</P>
<P>
   Miami has won three of four games against the Revolution, and
those matches were indicative of the Revolution's failings, since
they surrendered the deciding goal in those games in the 63d (while
playing with a man advantage), the 79th, and 86th minutes,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   They seldom dictated the tempo of the game, lack of speed was
exposed, and their tactics failed at crucial times. Zenga, who
replaced Thomas Rongen Aug. 24, has revived the team and covered up
the vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Revolution changed coaches sooner, things might have
been different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what I know now, I would have made a bet on the
Kentucky Derby and I would have sold my stocks at the right time,''
O'Donovan said. ``I'm not abrogating responsibility. We would have
done things differently, and Thomas would have done things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to think we might have been in the
playoffs. We would have given D.C. United a run for their money
because we are a team with momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga hopes to extend that momentum, and the Revolution plan to
continue training, along with invited prospects, even after the
season ends. Zenga talked of constructing ``a big team'' for next
year and is considering returning as player-coach. There have been
rumors from England that Italian striker GianFranco Zola of Chelsea
is interested in joining Zenga, but that seems a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are eager to have Walter back but it is premature to think
along those lines,'' O'Donovan said. ``Everyone has worked very
hard this year, and we have little to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter has to make a decision on all players, some very tough
decisions on salaries and who the foreigners will be. We knew
Walter was a leader on the field last year with a significant
personality, and his personality became the team's personality. We
had a hunch he could bring that back for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0159EDT &QL; 
