 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-U.S. (Washington) _ A reconstruction of how a small group
presidential advisers decided to bomb the pharmaceutical factory in
in Sudan. By Tim Weiner and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-IMAGE (Tokyo) _ Japan is often seen abroad these days as
an insouciant bumbler, fiddling while much of the world's economy
burns. But government officials here see things rather differently.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-U.N.-POLICY (United Nations) _ In the annals of American
relations with the United Nations, supporters and critics of the
organization broadly agree, there has never been a more dismal
moment than this. When President Clinton speaks here on Monday, he
will face an organization that is likely to strip the United States
of its General Assembly vote by the end of this year for nonpayment
of dues. Washington owes the organization more than $1.5 billion.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Hanover, Germany) _ If Gerhard Schroeder has
tried to communicate anything during his long quest to unseat
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, it is that he is worldly and modern. But
with elections just one week away, Schroeder's past is coming back
to haunt him. As the premier of Lower Saxony since 1990, he
presides over a state with nearly 11 percent unemployment _ one of
the highest rates in western Germany. The state's budget is a
shambles, groaning under a mountain of debt. Job-training, school
budgets and community programs have been cut back, and bigger cuts
are likely next year. By Edmund L. Andrews. (with graphic)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERINDIAN-TOURISM (Umatilla Reservation, Ore.) _ American
Indian reservations, long considered economic deserts amidst a
landscape of general prosperity, are finding that they have a lot
more to offer the world than casinos and art galleries _ they have
their homes, their backyards, their stories. Visitors, especially a
growing number of Europeans, are traveling to some of the country's
most remote places, like this Indian reservation in central Oregon,
in search of life many Americans overlook on their vacations. By
Timothy Egan. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-CLUSTERS (Undated) _ Many scientists say that cancer
clusters simply don't exist; that there is a lot of cancer
everywhere and neighborhood concentrations of the disease result
from chance, not the environment. But people who live in areas
where the incidence of cancer is higher than expected have rarely
been content with that rationale. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-VOTERS (Chipley, Fla.) _ Wade Jackson, a farmer near
this Panhandle city, remembers traveling to Punta Gorda in the
southwestern part of the state some 15 years ago to visit a nephew.
That was as far south as he has ever gone in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 62, is a native Floridian, but his Florida is the other
Florida, the one that grows peanuts, cotton and timber and calls
itself ``lower Alabama,'' the one of family generations, Democratic
tradition and black-and-white demographics and the one that holds
the votes that can swing elections. By Mireya Navarro. (with photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCENE (Washington) _ Nothing is quite the same for
President Clinton and his senior aides, advisers and friends these
days. They make little pretense that the White House is other than
a shaken, static place, groping for a way to survive. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TELLABS-CIENA (Undated) _ The behind-the-scenes saga of the
busted Tellabs-Ciena merger. By Laura M. Holson. (with graphic)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ACCOUNTING-RULES (Undated) _ The Financial Accounting
Standards Board will vote on new accounting rules for Hollywood
studios. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOODMORNING-MEDIA (Undated) _ For the better part of a
decade, from 1985 to 1995, ABC's ``Good Morning America'' was the
most-watched show in the 7-9 a.m. weekday time period. But in the
past two years, it has seen its Nielsen ratings plummet, losing
more than 25 percent of its viewers. The downturn at ``Good Morning
America'' came almost directly from efforts to improve it, by
making it newsier and more sophisticated. A look at a show in
trouble. By Lawrie Mifflin. (with graphic)
</P>
<P>
   TV-INTERNET-MEDIA (Undated) _ Is the Internet cutting into the
TV audience? That's what America Online and some recent studies
have contended. But now comes a study by Nielsen, commissioned by
the Discovery Channel, that indicates otherwise. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   DEEPTHROAT-MEDIA (Undated) _ New book ``reveals'' who ``Deep
Throat'' was. But should we believe it? By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ A look at how the Federal Trade
Commission is proceeding with its efforts to get the online
industry to follow the privacy guidelines the FTC spelled out
earlier this summer. So far, the industry seems to be moving
further away from the FTC proposal _ making it more likely that
Congress may step in. By Joel Brinkley. (with photo and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MUSIC (Undated) _ After experimenting with audio, video,
live ``webcasts'' and other multimedia technologies, the vanguard
of the new-media recording industry says it is poised to employ the
Internet to radically alter the way tomorrow's artists will be
sold, promoted and even discovered. But like everything on the
Internet, there is no roadmap to profits in online music. On the
Atlantic and Pacific coasts, two very different pioneers are
blazing divergent paths to the future. By Peter Evers
</P>
<P>
   TECH-COLUMN (New York) _ In contrast to politics, in the world
of entrepreneurs, going public has fabulously positive
connotations. It is how entrepreneurs achieve real wealth, if only
on paper. It is the consummate measure of business success or
failure. So consider the anxiety of Silicon Alley entrepreneurs
like Jack Hidary, Todd Krizelman, Stephan Paternot and Alan
Andreini. As the stock market continues to vacillate, all these men
face a quandary: to go or not to go. By Janet Stites.
</P>
<P>
   MULTICULTURAL-AD-COLUMN _ A giant agency company is stepping up
its efforts in multicultural marketing, forming a unit devoted to
encouraging advertisers to keep pace with the changing face of
consumers by increasing sales pitches aimed at ethnic groups. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ In six weeks, a minority of the
nation's eligible voters will decide whether the president is to be
impeached by the House and removed from office by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Few candidates are ready to deal with the gut issue of this
November's election. Republican candidates talk about truthfulness
and Democrats issue fervent pleas to get on with the nation's
business. But nobody will come out and say, ``If elected, I will
vote to impeach that hairsplitting perjurer'' or, contrariwise,
``Those Bible-thumping hypocrites will throw out Bill Clinton over
my dead body.'' By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RIPKEN (New York) _ The Orioles' Cal Ripken sat out the
start of Sunday night's game against the Yankees, the first time he
has not started since May 30, 1982. His streak is the longest in
baseball history, 502 games longer than Lou Gehrig's. By Buster
Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-OLNEY-COLUMN (Baltimore) _ Exhausted and emotionally
drained, Cal Ripken Jr. fell into a deep slump in the days after
breaking Lou Gehrig's consecutive-game record of 2,130 games on
Sept. 6, 1995. He was a national icon, a living symbol of
dedication to excellence who graced magazine covers and television
screens, but that did not help him when he was trying to hit
fastballs. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-BERLIN-MARATHON (Undated) _ Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa ran
the fastest marathon in history on Sunday, breaking the 10-year-old
record by 45 seconds in clocking 2 hours, 6 minutes, 5 seconds, at
the Berlin Marathon. The 28-year-old bettered the previous world
best of 2:06:50 set by Ethiopia's Belayneh Densimo at Rotterdam in
1988. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBRARY (Undated) _ A new British library is a
surprising hit. By Sarah Lyall. (with photo)
</P>
