<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S RATING TOO HIGH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another win, a new week and a different perspective on the
Bruins, thanks to their sloppy play at Houston and Kansas State's
48-7 thrashing of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe UCLA's season-opener wasn't that impressive after all.
Perhaps its No. 4 ranking is too lofty for a team with just six
senior starters. Perhaps the Fiesta Bowl is unrealistic for a team
with its best defensive lineman on crutches and its best playmaker
in a hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   Three things are certain: that UCLA is capable of shifting into
high and pummelling foes on its road to the Pac-10 title; that the
Bruins must compensate for Freddie Mitchell's broken leg; and that
they must secure a defensive line temporarily weakened by Kenyon
Coleman's strained knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have three irreplaceable players: quarterback Cade
McNown, kicker Chris Sailer and safety Larry Atkins, whose value to
the defense far exceed his modest statistics.
</P>
<P>
   On the next tier _ invaluable, but not irreplaceable _ stand
offensive tackle Kris Farris, cornerback Marques Anderson and
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Among a veteran receiving corps, Mitchell's skills were unique.
He was the speed and swagger lacking in the mild-mannered Brad
Melsby, Danny Farmer and Brian Poli-Dixon. He could catch, run and
throw. He was UCLA's No. 1 punt and kick returner, and in his brief
freshman season he accounted for 43.2 percent of UCLA's total yards
(314 of 726).
</P>
<P>
   His absence seemingly reduces the Bruins' offense from a V-8 to
a V-6. Elimimate his playmaking, and you eliminate an entire
dimension. The field shortens. Defenses attack rather than play on
their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we do? We've got receivers who can pick up the slack,
but I don't know if they give us Freddie's big-play dimension,''
said offensive coordinator Al Borges, who, along with coach Bob
Toledo, must now tweak the offense to account for Mitchell's
absence. Watch for more passes to the tight ends, more passes to
the fullbacks _ the Bruins probably will counter with diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's injury (sprained medial collateral ligament, right
knee) forced the Bruins to use true freshman Anthony Fletcher, who
they hoped to redshirt. Although Coleman is not an impact player of
Atkins' class, he's the most talented of UCLA's returning linemen.
Without him, the nine-man line rotation consists of five freshmen
and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   If these guys were any younger, they'd interrupt practice for a
cookie break.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget: defensive line is arguably the most important
position, and elite defensive linemen are the most coveted
commodity in football, pro or college. The Bruins waited decades
for a player of Coleman's size and strength. Now they must wait for
his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenyon is a big part of what we do,'' defensive coordinator
Nick Aliotti said. ``It's tough to lose anybody of that caliber.
Someone else will now have to step up and play for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman is expected to return in 3-4 weeks, and no doubt UCLA
has circled Oct. 10 _ at Arizona _ on his revovery calendar. The
Bruins haven't won in Tucson since Troy Aikman roamed the field.
Each visit, they are beaten and beaten up. Coleman was supposed to
be an antidote for Arizona's physical style. Without him, UCLA's
task is hellacious.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if you combine the sloppiness at Houston with injuries
and inexperience, every game seems ominous, starting Saturday in
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
