<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-MANDELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON MANDELA OFFERS PRAISE FOR A CLERGYMAN AND A CATHEDRAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Boys Choir of Harlem sang in Xhosa Sunday.
``Bayethe Mandela,'' they shouted, in a rousing rendition of the
South African anti-apartheid anthem. ``Hail Mandela. Warrior of
Warriors. King of Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the front row at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine sat
Nelson Mandela and his wife, Graca Machel, their faces all smiles.
Together, to the cries of ``Amandla,'' they raised their fists in
salute.
</P>
<P>
   In what was probably his last visit to the United States as the
president of South Africa, Mandela, 79, came to the cathedral
Sunday to pay homage to Archbishop Trevor Huddleston, an Anglican
monk who became president of the Anti-Apartheid Movement and died
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela described Huddleston, a white Englishman who was posted
in South Africa shortly after he took his vows in 1939, as a man
who ``embraced the downtrodden'' and rejected the privileges that
apartheid afforded him, often at great risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of those rare people, good men and women who make
the world the theater of their operation in pursuit of freedom and
justice,'' Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mandela's first visit to the cathedral, which became
known for its opposition to apartheid. On Sunday, he offered his
appreciation. ``It was important that during our last official
visit to your country before retiring from office next year,'' he
said, ``we should spend time with those Americans who have been so
closely linked with the struggle for freedom and justice in South
Africa. Our victory in defeating apartheid was your victory, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's appearance at the cathedral was part of a weeklong
visit to the United States. On Monday, he is scheduled to address
the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
