<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-AWARDS-NYT &LR;      09-21 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOLLITY AND SOME SERIOUS MOMENTS AT THE BESSIE AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance Theater Workshop and the Danspace Project of
St. Mark's Church presented the 14th Annual Dance and Performance
Awards on Friday night at the Joyce Theater. The awards, chosen by
a panel of judges, are familiarly known as the Bessies, and are
named after Bessie Schonberg, a noted teacher of dance composition.
They honor achievements in dance and performance art, especially in
the downtown cultural world. As always, they attracted an
enthusiastic audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jollity prevailed in the presentation, hosted by Varla Jean
Merman, a singer and comedienne, and Doug Elkins, a choreographer,
both of whom kept turning up throughout the evening in outfits from
formal to funky. Yet there were also serious moments, as when David
White, executive director of Dance Theater Workshop, and Laurie
Uprichard, executive director of the Danspace Project, paid tribute
to the memory of Nancy Topf, an American dancer killed in the crash
of Swissair Flight 111 off Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Village Voice underwrote awards of $1,000 for the
winners in the choreographer/creator category and of $500 in the
performer category. Choreographer and creator awards went to
Charles Atlas; B Team (a group made up of Zesty Meyers, Evan
Snyderman, Thor Bueno, Kelly Lamb and Jeff Zimmerman); Ronald K.
Brown; Jane Comfort; Douglas Dunn; David Neumann; Elizabeth Streb;
Doug Varone; and, for a collaborative venture by Mia Lawrence,
Douglas Henderson, Guy Yarden and Danielle Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   Performer awards were received by Hope L. Boykin; Hope Clark;
Lawrence Keigwin; Jaime Martinez; Pedro Ruiz; and Eddie Taketa.
</P>
<P>
   Special citations went to the Gowanus Arts Exchange for
supporting the arts in Brooklyn; Carla Maxwell for her achievements
as director of the Limon Dance Company since 1978; and to Mikki
Shepard, Laura Greer and Stephanie S. Hughley for presenting a
series of performances called ``Dance Women/Living Legends,'' a
celebration of black female choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   The composer awards honored collaborators: Mark Bennett, Robert
Black, Robert Een, Aska Kaneko and Hiroshi Yoshino, who provided
the music for Yoshiko Chuma's ``Unfinished Symphony''; Fellaheen
(made up of Robert Bonhomme, Patrick Fondiller, Robert Hohl and
Megan Spooner), which composed ``Duck, You Sucker'' for Neumann;
and Somei Satoh and the Kronos Quartet, creators of the music for
Eiko and Koma's ``River.''
</P>
<P>
   Lighting and visual design awards went to David Covey, Jeff
Fontaine, Nari Ward and, working in collaboration, Bill Ballou and
Michael Casselli. The program also included danced excerpts from
Brown's ``Gate Keepers'' and Varone's ``Bel Canto.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
