<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGHHHHH: TOBIN CAN STOP HOLDING HIS BREATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If lawyers can be disbarred, does it follow that
electricians can be delighted?
</P>
<P>
   Can cowboys be deranged?
</P>
<P>
   Models deposed?
</P>
<P>
   Garment workers debriefed?
</P>
<P>
   More to the point what about football coaches? Everyone knows
what happens if they don't win.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobin made the`` Guinness Book of World Records'' on
Sunday night. He joins some remarkable company, like the guy who
yodeled nonstop for 23 days and the woman who grew a 750-pound
turnip.
</P>
<P>
   Vince held his breath for three hours and three minutes. Only
when the last second ticked off the clock _ and the scoreboard read
Cardinals 17, Eagles 3 _ Tobin finally exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   It was like popping the ring top on a cold one. His
``sighhhhhhhh'' was pure bliss. What a relief.
</P>
<P>
   The term must win is overused in sports. But this home opener
fell into that category. In their first two games the Cardinals
were just awful. After lopsided defeats in Dallas and Seattle, the
third-year coach appeared pale and at a loss for words. Tobin
groped for positives in the post-mortem. The man wore defeat on his
face. He looked as if he had been slapped, a cracking open-handed
blow.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lewis says the best gift he ever received was a film of
his wedding. Whenever he argues with his wife, the comedian says he
goes into a room, locks the door, runs the film backward and walks
out a free man.
</P>
<P>
   If only life had a rewind switch. Tobin wished he could start
the season over. But he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cardinals`` had'' to beat the Eagles. They couldn't lose
at home against a winless team that hasn't won a road game since
the end of the 1996 season. The Cardinals aren't very good _ not
yet _ but the Eagles without their starting cornerbacks are worse.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot at kickoff, but the temperature on the field was
pleasant compared with the hot seat that awaited the coach if his
team had started this season of promise 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   If Tobin lost to the Eagles, there would be exit polls.
Grumbling fans would be asked which punishment they favored,
censure or impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals made their coach sweat. After three quarters the
game was scoreless. ESPN which televised the snoozer nationally _
be glad it was blacked out here _ could hear the sets clicking off.
Only contractual obligations prevented the network from dumping the
game in favor of a snooker tournament, a dog show or that world's
strongest man contest in which stout grunting men named Ingemar and
Ernst sprint 50 yards with a water buffalo under each arm.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tedious. The Cards and Eagles wore out the middle
of the field. Finally, the home team, which earlier went 23{
minutes between first downs, awakened from a bad dream. Joe Nedney
nailed a 47-yard field goal (and kept his job) to tie the score,
3-3. Then the blitzing defense made the play that wins close games,
sacking backup quarterback Rodney Peete and stripping him of the
ball. Simeon Rice, who finally resembled the Simeon Rice we
remember, picked up the fumble and gave the Cardinals offense
possession at the Eagles 18. When Jake Plummer connected with
Johnny McWilliams in the end zone, Tobin _ cheeks puffed out, his
face a shade of lavender by now _ nodded with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Next possession, Adrian Murrell ran and ran and ran some more.
With Plummer mixing in short passes, the West Coast offense finally
clicked the the way it is supposed to, the way it must if the
Cardinals hope to compete. The Eagles wilted. The Cardinals went 86
yards and scored again.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't show a lot of emotion. He isn't the guy at the New
Year's Eve party leading the conga line, a lampshade on his head.
But when it was over and Tobin could breath again, the coach felt
himself smile. This was a start for his team. A big win for the
Cardinals, and maybe a bigger win for him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
