<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-EAGLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS SHOW SIGNS OF NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Forgive the Cardinals for being delirious. Kodak
moments have come so infrequently in the last decade, they tend to
lose their heads in the euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   So it's understandable that defensive end Simeon Rice got
confused after his two sacks helped the Cardinals beat the
Philadelphia Eagles, 17-3, on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about making good on his prediction of a multiple-sack
game, Rice said, ``Just call me the great Mussolini.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Houdini, or maybe Nostradamus.
</P>
<P>
   Rice and his defensive teammates are the reason the Cardinals'
season isn't over. They kept the team in the game until the offense
started to click in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (1-2) scored 17 unanswered points in the final 13
minutes after falling behind, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win this game,'' offensive tackle Lomas Brown said.
``Had we lost, we would have been in dire straits.''
</P>
<P>
   They would have been embarrassed. The 39,782 fans at Sun Devil
Stadium would have booed them off the field. Radio talk show hosts
already were planning to bring out the dreaded bags to put over
their heads. The bashing would have lasted all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been inconceivable, such an ugly situation,''
tight end Chris Gedney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who moved within one-half game of first place in
the NFC East, appeared in trouble after Chris Boniol's 29-yard
field goal 40 seconds into the fourth quarter gave the Eagles a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Marc Trestman was preaching patience on
the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can start to run the ball and have that kind of
balance, the passing game will take its course,'' Trestman said.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the 20, running back Adrian Murrell raced
around left end for 28 yards, the team's longest run of the season.
Tight end Johnny McWilliams made two big blocks to free Murrell.
</P>
<P>
   One play later, quarterback Jake Plummer found Gedney in the
right flat for a 5-yard gain. Gedney ran out of bounds, but then
Eagles free safety Brian Dawkins was called for a personal foul for
knocking Gedney over the Philadelphia bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to hold the guy up,'' Eagles Coach Ray Rhodes
said. ``(Dawkins) was not trying to run him into the bench. There
was a real short area between the sidelines and the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-yard penalty gave the Cardinals a first down at the
Eagles' 32 and set up Joe Nedney's career long 47-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   On the Eagles' next possession, middle linebacker Ronald
McKinnon blitzed and sacked quarterback Rodney Peete, who replaced
starter Bobby Hoying, who injured his back, in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon knocked the ball loose, and Rice returned the fumble 10
yards to the Eagles' 18 with 9:49 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great (blitz) call by Coach (Dave) McGinnis,''
McKinnon said. ``I was surprised the hole next to the left guard
was so wide open, because usually the center will block back down.
When you have a hole that wide open, you have to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice thought he might score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping, but my tank was on `E,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Cardinals only five plays to take the lead. On third
and goal from the 7, Plummer rolled right and threw a perfect pass
to McWilliams, who caught it in the end zone while on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a boot(leg) on,'' Plummer said. ``It's something I
love to do. . . . Johnny made a great play, he ran and got stopped
and just settled right in the hole in the end zone. All I had to do
was throw it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals forced the Eagles (0-3) to punt, then got the ball
back on their 14 with 4:51 remaining. After a 26-yard reception by
McWilliams, they let Murrell and their offensive line take over.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, who finished with a game high 145 yards, put the game
away with a 25-yard score around left end with two minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Left guard Chris) Dishman said in the huddle, `We're going to
score on this play,' '' Murrell said. ``I looked him in the eye,
and I told him, `Well, I'm putting this one on you then.' If you
get me out of there on one guy, I'll make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell gained 101 yards on 12 carries in the fourth quarter to
become the Cardinals first 100-yard rusher in 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late in the game, Lomas (Brown) and Dishman were just caving
their guys in, and Adrian was matched up on a defensive back and
making him miss,'' said Plummer, who completed 21 of 35 passes for
137 yards after a slow start in which the Cardinals got no
offensive first downs from 11:18 to go in the first quarter to 41
seconds left before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals stayed in the game because the defense didn't
allow a touchdown for the first time since Nov. 20, 1994. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
