<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES PITCHING GIVES D-BACKS FITS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Diamondbacks need one victory to avoid losing 100
games in their inaugural season. But at their current rate of
productivity _ or lack thereof _ that's no sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Atlanta Braves have what many regard as the best
pitching staff in the majors and perhaps the best overall ballclub.
But for the Diamondbacks to be shut out three times by them in a
four-game series _ the third time by left-hander Bruce Chen (who?)
_ there aren't too many excuses that can be valid.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 10-0 setback also brought another sign of a possible
apocalypse _ there was a smattering of boos among Bank One
Ballpark's brie-and-blush crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter cranked up the Victrola and
set the needle down on the record that has become scratchy from
overuse: ``It's a challenge for us to put together offense for a
consistent period of time. It's something that we're going to have
to improve on.''
</P>
<P>
   Left is not right for Arizona. The Diamondbacks were shut out by
Braves left-hander Denny Neagle on Thursday night, beat
right-hander Greg Maddux on Friday night, but were shut out by
left-hander Tom Glavine on Saturday night and then by Chen on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 16th time that the Diamondbacks (62-95) have not
scored in a game _ second in the majors behind expansion partners
Tampa Bay (17).
</P>
<P>
   Chen was rated by ``Baseball America'' as Atlanta's top major
league prospect in 1997, but when the 1998 season began, he was at
Double-A Greenville. He went to Triple-A Richmond on Aug. 11 and
was called up to the big club on Sept. 11. He was 13-7 with a 3.29
ERA in 23 starts at Greenville and 2-1 with a 1.88 ERA in four
starts at Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Making his third big-league start, Chen limited the Diamondbacks
to three hits in seven innings, walked two and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   He walked two and gave up a hit in the first inning, then didn't
allow a hit through the next four. In the sixth, he gave up a
one-out double to Andy Fox and a single to Tony Batista, but they
were left stranded as Devon White popped out to Marty Malloy at
second base and Matt Williams popped out to Ozzie Guillen at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Chen (2-0) worked one more hitless inning, finishing with 109
pitches, before right-hander Rudy Seanez and veteran left-hander
Norm Charlton wrapped things up.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Chen's approach is similar to Glavine, whose victory on
Saturday night was his 20th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He moves the ball around, changes speeds . . . and has enough
of a fastball to keep you honest,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he shut out the Braves for the first three innings,
Diamondbacks right-hander Amaury Telemaco (6-10) struggled with his
control.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a run in the fourth on a leadoff single by Malloy, a
one-out double to Andres Galarraga and a groundout by Ryan Klesko.
In the sixth, he issued the first two of his four walks. The first
_ Guillen _ scored on a sacrifice fly by Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Telemaco walked two of the first three men he
faced, and both _ Javier Jopez and Michael Tucker _ went on to
score. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
