<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-CANUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANUCKS STOP COYOTES  
 KHABIBULIN SHOWS RUST, ALLOWS 4 GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Weren't the Vancouver Canucks supposed to be the team
with the goalie problem?
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look like it Sunday afternoon at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were the ones starting to scratch their heads about
their situation between the pipes after getting poked by the
Canucks, 4-1, in their preseason home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin showed definite signs of rust, getting beat
for four goals on 22 shots, including one on a goofy mental
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Jimmy Waite, meanwhile, who has looked extremely sharp in
training camp, suffered a pulled groin only seven minutes after
replacing Khabibulin to start the third period. Early reports are
that he will miss at least a week, perhaps longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Khabibulin) wasn't dreadful, but he obviously was
out-goaltended by the opposing goalie,'' Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Garth Snow, who wasn't given much chance of even
staying with the Canucks earlier this summer, let alone contend for
the No. 1 starting role. Vancouver made free-agent pitches to
Curtis Joseph and Mike Richter, and when it couldn't land either,
there was, and still is, talk of a possible major trade.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Canucks Coach Mike Keenan. Not after what he
saw Sunday from Snow, who stoned the Coyotes with 30 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played an excellent game for us,'' Keenan said. ``He looked
very strong in all aspects of the game. He played with a lot of
composure. He played with a great deal of consistency. I thought he
handled the puck exceptionally well, controlled the rebounds well.
He played with a great deal of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like a top-form goaltender tonight. That's a great
sign for us. Hopefully, he'll step up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin got stung twice in a 44-second span in the second
period, putting the Coyotes down, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   First, Mark Messier swooped in and redirected Alexander
Mogilny's long rebound past the Coyotes goalie. Then, at the 8:54
mark, Khabibulin strayed behind the net to try and play a puck that
had been sent in by Dave Scatchard. He never had a chance _ and the
crowd of 12,231 knew it.
</P>
<P>
   It came along the back boards to Josh Holden, who zipped a
centering pass into the slot to an awaiting Matt Cooke. Khabibulin,
never known as a great puck handler, couldn't get back in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little mad about that play, but it happens,''
Khabibulin said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to evaluate his overall play, he said: ``It wasn't too bad
for playing for the first time since April.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can expect goalie coach Benoit Allaire to do some
extra one-on-one fine-tuning with Khabibulin in the coming days.
Playing the puck behind the net, or deciding whether Khabibulin
should try it at all, most definitely will be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be happier to see him do that in the preseason so it
doesn't happen in the regular season,'' Schoenfeld said.
``Sometimes, the lessons you learn have to be explicit. It's a
situation where you have to make sure you get that puck _ or you
don't go. . . . Certainly, you don't want to see a goal scored, but
if it hammers a lesson home, then maybe it's a good lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the extra two feet now (behind the net), it's going to be
difficult for a lot of goaltenders to get out there and make the
play and get back in time.''
</P>
<P>
   After rookie center Trevor Letowski scored Phoenix's only goal,
a slap shot on the power play off a nice feed from defenseman Keith
Carney midway through the second period, Mogilny scored two goals
for Vancouver in the third to ice the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt pretty nice out there,'' Letowski said. ``They gave me
a chance to play on the power play, and that was fun. I got a great
pass from Carney, there was an open side, and I just put it home. I
had the exact same chance about a minute later, and I just didn't
get good wood on it.'' &QL; 
Note &QL; 
The first major wave of roster cuts could come as early as today.
After the game, Schoenfeld huddled with General Manager Bobby Smith
for several minutes. The Coyotes announced only one move afterward,
that they are assigning left wing Andrei Vasilyev to Las Vegas of
the International Hockey League. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
