<HEADLINE>
`THROW IN' PLAYS PREMIUM GAME  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - He was a ``throw in'' in the big summer swap of
draft choices with San Diego, a trade designed to add depth and
still acquire  &UR; Andre
 &UR; Wadsworth, the player the Cardinals wanted to draft, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But when linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller left because of a dislocated
left wrist in the second quarter of Sunday night's 17-3 victory
over the Philadelphia Eagles,  &UR; Patrick Sapp proved a big dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he played all right,'' Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said of
Sapp, a former quarterback turned linebacker. ``It's hard to really
say without looking at films, but I think he made a couple of big
tackles (four in all).
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get better and better, too. He's a quarterback who is
playing linebacker, but he certainly has the size and athleticism
to be good. We've got to keep working with him to get him better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals team physician  &UR; Russell Chick said Miller will see a
hand surgeon this morning to see whether the injury requires
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Mac the receiver &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Gedney is supposed to be the ``receiving'' tight end, and
 &UR; Johnny McWilliams' strength has been his blocking. But Sunday night
it was a sliding McWilliams who was on the end of  &UR; Jake Plummer's
7-yard touchdown pass for the eventual game winner, and it was
McWilliams who caught a 26-yard pass on third and 5 to keep the
drive alive to a clinching touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But his three receptions for 39 yards notwithstanding, his
blocking prowess also stood out. He blocked two players on  &UR; Adrian
Murrell's 28-yard run to help set up the game-tying field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the touchdown pass, I was supposed to slam my man and go
into the flat, but they came up and covered it, so I went to the
hole and Jake put it where only I could catch it,'' McWilliams
said. ``That last drive for the touchdown was all about pride. We
really worked hard and it paid off.'' &QL; 
McKinnon shines &QL; 
Middle linebacker  &UR; Ron McKinnon entered the game with 24 tackles
and on Sunday, he was in on 13, including 10 unassisted. He also
produced a sack, forced a fumble by  &UR; Rodney Peete and knocked
starting quarterback  &UR; Bobby Hoying from the game with a vicious
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting three years to get through clean like I did
when I sacked Peete,'' McKinnon said, smiling. ``I was surprised,
but I thought once I got there I better make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other one (Hoying), I thought he was going to go down
(slide), but he kept running so I had to hit him. I'm sorry he got
hurt. I feel for him, but he's supposed to go down. The way our
front four played, it made my job so easy.  &QL; 
Confusion central &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second quarter, the Cardinals' frustration became
such that Plummer and several lineman were seen in an animated,
finger-wagging conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had some miscommunication, a little confusion on about
who was designated to block who, and we were trying to get it
worked out,'' Plummer said. ``I think they knew our signs. Every
time they were going to blitz, they seemed to know where we were
going to throw. I had some frustration, but I never had a loss of
hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 0319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
