<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-OFFENSE-AZR     09-21 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS COME ON WITH A REAL RUSH IN FINAL QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - In the end, the Cardinals certainly weren't in a
hurry, but they were in a rush.
</P>
<P>
   Unaccustomed as they are to leading late in the fourth quarter,
and having a ground game that has been well criticized, they were
presented with a challenge that could have large-picture
implications for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   They had a 10-3 lead, the ball at their 14-yard line, and 4:53
to burn off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Then Adrian Murrell and his offensive line did what few believed
was possible based on their opening two games. They dominated a foe
at the most critical juncture of a game and not only successfully
ran down the clock but also pounded in an insurance touchdown in a
17-3 win over Philadelphia in their home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, who became the Cardinals featured back the day he was
acquired from the New York Jets for a third-round pick, became the
Cardinals first 100-yard rusher since LeShon Johnson was a one-game
phenom in the fourth game of the 1996 season. Murrell, who had 44
yards rushing through three quarters, added 101 on 12
fourth-quarter carries.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was a 28-yard carry, aided by two downfield blocks by
tight end Johnny McWilliams, that set up a game-tying field goal
early in the final quarter, and later a 25-yard run for the
game-clinching touchdown with 1:52 to go.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that averaged 78 rushing yards in its first two
games _ exactly what it averaged a year ago when it was last in the
NFL on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the defense tired by running outside, then we ran up
the middle _ that was very effective for us,'' said Murrell. ``We
kept their defense on the field most of those last five minutes.
That was really to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin hopes that's a sign of things to come from a
youthful offense that had not picked up coordinator Marc Trestman's
West Coast offense quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrian ran extremely well,'' Tobin said. ``It's been a long
time since we had a 100-yard rusher. In the fourth quarter the
offensive line seemed to get stronger. They marched the length of
the field to get the first field goal, they punched it in for the
go-ahead touchdown, and at the end they ran out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line has taken a lot of criticism, but at the
end it began to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a veteran back who knows what to do with even the
smallest opening doesn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more carries Adrian gets, the better and more confident he
is running behind our line,'' Tobin said. ``It is a new offense to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I want. I want us to become a physical football
team that controls the line and is able to pound out the hard
yards. We did at the end. We controlled the line and picked up the
first downs. Now I would hope we can do that earlier in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the tough yards came around the left side, where veteran
tackle Lomas Brown was cleaning house ahead of Murrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's only one game and we can revert back next week,
but it's been some time since we've been able to come in here after
a game feeling rewarded like this,'' Brown said. ``The guys in the
line took it upon ourselves there at the end to run out the clock
and help Adrian get his yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Outings such as this were commonplace for Murrell while covering
more than 1,000 yards for the Jets each of the past two seasons. He
was aware when the club let Leeland McElroy and Johnson go that he
was being handed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a young team, there are new guys _ I'm one of them _
and we're still trying to get a feel,'' Murrell said. ``We'd like
to have had a better start, but we stayed the course. This is what
we envisioned from this offense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
