</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FIRST STEP TOWARD SOME THING BIG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Simeon limped to his locker, cringing as he tried
to get dressed. He smiled for a moment, and then the moment was
gone, stolen away by a searing pain in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hurts?'' he said. ``Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Two feet away, Eric Swann was in full uniform. A grass stain
above his shoulder pads, gloves on his hands, the glow of victory
dripping from his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first step toward something big,'' Swann said.
</P>
<P>
   If anything is to become of the season, they will remember this.
The night when it all could've exploded, when a mutiny could've
arisen from the disparity, from the frustration, from one side that
refused to do its part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the night when the defense rescued, and in the
end, liberated the offense. A night when the defense saved the game
until it won the game. A night when two parts became one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you become a championship team,'' Swann said. ``No
matter what happens, we're in the foxhole together.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, these were the Eagles. But the defense was on the field
for a whopping 59 plays. They endured an offensive series that
lasted 45 seconds. Another that lasted 12 seconds. An offense that
went nearly 24 minutes without a first down.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of taxation that can easily turn one side
against the other. It's happened to better teams than this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood the fight,'' Rice said. ``And we understood that
there were no rules in the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it all changed in one instant, when a blitzing Ronald
McKinnon separated Rodney Peete from the football. Rice recovered
deep in Eagles' territory. Suddenly revived, the offense scored a
touchdown. And on the next possession, handed a lead for the first
time this season, they simply marched down the field for another.
</P>
<P>
   The sparse crowd of 39,782 _ or 5,000 less than the last-place
Diamondbacks drew on Sunday _ reveled in the moment. Earlier, they
had booed Jake Plummer, booed the offense, booed anyone in red for
an inept attack. Now, they were cheering wildly, rewarded for their
optimism, relieved that a season had been saved.
</P>
<P>
   And inside the Cardinals' locker room, they breathed a heavy
sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle,'' Rice said. ``That team is nobody's
punk.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the defense, neither are the Cardinals. They have won
their home opener for two consecutive years. They are back in the
division race. And after holding the Eagles to a field goal, they
have tasted their destiny, a fearsome defense that opens the door
for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when they knocked Bobby Hoying into another solar
system. When Patrick Sapp filled in admirably for an injured Jamir
Miller. When Rice made good with two sacks and had another
nullified by a penalty. When Swann terrorized the interior like a
mad bull. When Tommy Knight produced eight tackles to spearhead the
secondary. When even a wet-eared Andre Wadsworth got in on the act.
</P>
<P>
   When McKinnon continued a stellar individual season with the
biggest play of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This picks everybody up,'' McKinnon said. ``We were walking
around 0-2, and everybody was trying to find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the offense is still a mystery. They have been
blanked in six of 12 quarters this season, and the new West Coast
attack has been the yawn of a new era. But now the pressure is off,
and they can build on the last two drives.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe now the stadium won't be plagued with empty seats.
Football is king in America. In most cities, you'd have to know
someone special to get a ticket for the home opener. In most
cities, attendance is a civic responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you are waiting for a winner, proof that these aren't the
same old Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a vision for this team,'' Vince Tobin said.
``Before the game, I saw all the people in red. Some day, there's
going to be the whole stadium packed with people wearing red and
cheering and having a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day has to start some place. And maybe this was the first
hurdle. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
