<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SNYDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE PROBLEMS PLAGUE ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - With all due respect to Bruce Snyder's ``One at a
time'' philosophy, it may be time to look at the big picture.
Considering what the Pac-10 did this weekend, Arizona State might
not like what it sees.
</P>
<P>
   The league went 8-0 in non-conference games. In the only Pac-10
battle, No. 18 Southern California beat Oregon State, 40-20, in a
game much closer than the score indicates. The Beavers visit Sun
Devil Stadium Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's 34-15 victory over North Texas gave the team an emotional
lift, but it also demonstrated that the Sun Devils still have
significant problems to address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we've showed flashes of being a real good team,
although we're not consistent enough,'' Snyder said. ``But I like
what we have to work with and think we can be a real good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, I knew it was going to take a while, but we may
be behind where we thought we would be. I like some individual
efforts, but we're not playing real well as a unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils yielded 373 yards after North Texas had managed
just 264 in two previous games. The Mean Green went from 44 rushing
yards a week ago to 192 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ASU, a team many speculated could be a candidate for the Rose or
even Fiesta Bowl, now seems better suited for a trip to Hawaii. The
Nos. 4 and 5 Pac-10 teams will play in Honolulu on Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is ASU's defensive struggles, but conference
parity is also an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling Stanford raised some eyebrows by defeating North
Carolina, 37-34. California has held Nebraska and Oklahoma to 24
and 12 points, respectively. Granted No. 22 Oregon beat up on a
weak opponent, San Jose State, but it did it by 55 points. No. 4
UCLA scored 42 in its win over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a weak link on the schedule anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Even though Oregon State, which visits Saturday, has struggled
in recent years, the Beavers always seem to give ASU a fight. Three
of the Sun Devils' last four victories against them have been by
fewer than 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ASU travels to Los Angeles on Oct. 3 to play USC, a team that is
averaging 34 points a game behind a young quarterback. Notre Dame
visits a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder doesn't even want to think about his team starting 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   He's just trying to keep his team from looking beyond Oregon
State. With good reason. The defense can't afford to daydream.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and his staff tried to answer this question Sunday: Is
the problem execution, or personnel?
</P>
<P>
   ASU hopes it's the former, because that's something that can
improve over time. The Sun Devils' inexperience (eight new starters
on defense) has been evident in the three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing with some real young players,'' Snyder
said. ``That doesn't mean it has to be a problem, but often it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to get tired faster. They tend to not be able to
concentrate as well from one play to another. They're more
tentative than veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is desperate for a leader, or at least a dominant player,
to step forward on defense. Last season, linebacker Pat Tillman and
safety Damien Richardson had a galvanizing effect on the rest of
the unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tillman) could get everybody lined up,'' Snyder said. ``And
Damien Richardson . . . (safety) Mitchell Freedman knew exactly
that Damien would force the ball back to him. He trusted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder was encouraged by some aspects of Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baker averaged 59.5 yards a punt and is ranked second in
the nation. Redshirt freshman Courtney Palmore had a strong outing
in the secondary and on special teams. Wide receiver Kenny
Mitchell, who had a 60-yard touchdown reception, had an impressive
game, and Snyder feels strong safety Christon Rance is improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference I saw is what practice did for us,'' Snyder
said. ``That's what's important to me.'' &QL; 
Notes &QL; 
Tailback J.R. Redmond is nursing a sprained toe.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder inserted Mike Gauthier for one extra-point Saturday night
and is considering using him again for that role, even though Baker
may be asked to kick field goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
