<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TIME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAD BETTER WAYS TO SPEND HIS SPARE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know you're tired of Bill and Monica and Ken and cigars and
all that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so am I, but it looks for all the world as if this story
will continue for days and weeks and months. Or at least until,
say, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa sign a multi-year contract to be a
nude-wrestling tag team on cable TV. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But before you burn your last copy of the Starr Report, let's
ponder _ on the assumption the sex allegations it contains are true
_ the goofy priorities of the president of the United States and
how appalling it is that he chose to have sexual relations with a
White House intern on dates when there were so many other things
going on that should have kept him busy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, their first sexual encounter was Nov. 15, 1995. My
word. What was Bill Clinton thinking? Nov. 15 is the birthday of
the late and great American artist Georgia O'Keeffe. Why wasn't
Clinton celebrating that instead of having enough free time on his
hands to fool around with Monica? Or why, instead of starting down
this long and tawdry road, wasn't he on the phone to Judge Joseph
Wapner, wishing him a happy 76th birthday on that date? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the report says, Clinton and Lewinsky had their
second sexual encounter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why, when I read that, I nearly exploded with rage and
disbelief. Instead of debasing himself in this way, Bill Clinton
should have been celebrating the 51st birthday of pitching great
Tom Seaver. Either that or giving a speech about freedom of the
press to honor famed 18th century journalist John Peter Zenger, who
was arrested Nov. 17, 1734, for libel against the colonial
government in his New York Weekly Journal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zenger was acquitted and, thus, helped plant the idea of press
freedom in the New World, which in turn has led to Matt Drudge. So
there you are. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next time the president and Monica got together in an
intimate sort of way was New Year's Eve of 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, I declare. Any regular person should be busy celebrating
the end of one year and the beginning of another every Dec. 31. But
if that's not enough to keep you out of trouble, what about the
annual nationwide celebration of the opening of the first bank in
U.S. history on Dec. 31, 1781, which raises the question of what
that first bank gave new depositors as gifts _ coal toasters? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough to keep Clinton out of trouble, he could
have been on the phone wishing John Denver a happy 52nd birthday
while Denver was still around to be called. How do you explain such
ridiculous choices? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And who but Bill Clinton would have devoted part of Jan. 7,
1996, to more sex with Monica when he should have been leading the
national celebration of Millard Fillmore's birthday? The more I
think about his lapse in this regard the angrier I get, especially
because of the debt Clinton owes Fillmore, who once ran for
president as a candidate of the ``Know-Nothing Party.'' Which is
exactly what was happening near the Oval Office on that January day
_ a party in which both participants later would claim to know
nothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the sexual encounter dates in the report are just as
disturbing for what the president was NOT doing. On Jan. 21, 1996,
for instance, why wasn't Clinton spending time commemorating the
birth on that date in 1821 of John C. Breckinridge, 14th vice
president of the United States? I certainly was, having just three
days earlier celebrated my own 51st birthday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, he should have been celebrating Sri Lankan
independence day. But here's the worst one: On March 31, 1996, he
was doing his cigar thing with Monica when he should have been
observing Al Gore's 48th birthday with all the rest of us. I tell
you, a good calendar might have prevented all this. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
