<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     09-21 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Struggling with an old secret
 &HT;    (For release, Sept. 23, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife claims she has videotape of it, but I do not believe
her; maybe 8mm movies, that I can believe. But they will be grainy
and, well, no one has one of those 8mm projectors any more.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about possible documentation of something I have
tried to hide for a good while. I'm not proud of it. It is the
skeleton in my closet.
</P>
<P>
   As we are quite aware, skeletons are being pulled from closets
these days at alarming rates. In fact, with so many gays and
lesbians coming out of the closet and, now, all those racy
skeletons coming out of the closets of public officials, there at
last is considerable room in the closets for clothing.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades, I have lived under the shadow of
disgrace. I have admitted my sin on several occasions but warned
those to whom I admitted it that to broadcast it generally would
cause further embarrassment to our family.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing I would want is to have it on CNN; oh, the shame!
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it has become obvious that nothing can be kept
secret in this country any more. We are a nation of voyeurs, and
your turn will come just as surely as there are death and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   So I have decided to go public with it, and try to tell my side
of it before someone else presents the embarrassing details.
</P>
<P>
   The transgression: As a parent of four small children, I would
take them home from the circus at intermission, telling them that
the show had ended! My wife was a co-conspirator of sorts,
protesting what I was doing but smiling all the time.
</P>
<P>
   All four of our children grew up thinking that a circus ended in
about one-and-a-half hours. They never saw the grand finale!
</P>
<P>
   I tried to live with this lie for years but finally broke down
and admitted it, first to my oldest daughter when she told me how
exhausting it was taking her first child to the circus. The shows
are so much longer than when she was a child, she claimed.
</P>
<P>
   My lie would have to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him at intermission that the circus is ended,'' I advised
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awful, Dad,'' she responded. ``Who would do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' I answered sheepishly, ``_ and your mother, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean...?'' her words halted as she conjured an image of
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, dear, we lied to you when we said the circus was over. We
were worn out; there were four of you. All that cotton candy, and
the Cracker Jacks, you guys were a mess. We had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of this conversation, my daughter was in her late
20s. Deeply affected by the confession, she immediately told her
brothers and sister. For a while, it was a terrible thing to live
down.
</P>
<P>
   It was not much later that the tide turned. All four siblings,
now with their own children, and the circus coming to town again,
began to think differently about what we had done to them. Not such
a bad idea, they thought.
</P>
<P>
   None have come to me directly and said they left at
intermission, but I believe several have. At times, it can be seen
as a survival thing.
</P>
<P>
   What is the moral of all this? Not much, other than not to cheat
your children. Or perhaps the moral is not to admit to anything _
until and unless the videotape is produced.
</P>
<P>
   There, I'm out of the closet. Judge me as you will. But before
you do, take a look at the polls. How many other parents would like
to rush their kids out of the circus at intermission?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
