<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TRANSIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING TO LIGHT RAIL CAN BE A CALCULATED BET ON THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ An orange and brown railroad depot, its
gingerbread architecture revealing its 1870s origin, sits on the
east side of Hiawatha Avenue here, a few minutes southeast of
downtown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Known to Milwaukee Road station agents as ``The Princess,'' the
old station is a museum now, a symbol of Victorian days when, as
the historical sign next to it says, ``ladies in bustles and
gentlemen in high collars'' got around town by rail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If things go as planned, five years from now modern ladies and
gentlemen (a projected 24,000 a day) will ride past this spot in
sleek new light-rail cars that will run the dozen or so miles
between downtown and a little south of the Mall of America in
suburban Bloomington. Along the way this $446 million system
(estimated in 1997 dollars) will have stops for the Metrodome
sports stadium, the University of Minnesota, several residential
areas, a VA hospital, Fort Snelling and the international airport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Twin Cities' 22 new light-rail cars will be a small but
crucial part of an improved transit system that will continue to
rely heavily on buses, including some running in dedicated
``busways'' on highways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But light rail clearly represents what Curt Johnson, once an
opponent of this mode of transit but now a supporter and a major
figure in getting it going here, calls a ``breakout strategy, some
way to raise the stakes, some way to lift transit to a different
level in the mind of the public.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This leap of faith to light rail, says Peter McLaughlin, a
Hennepin County government official through whose district the new
cars will run, ``is about changing the image of a major public
service.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As other cities think about whether and how light rail can
become part of their transit mix, the lessons to be learned from
the Minneapolis-St. Paul experience are many. But none is clearer
than this: Committing to a new vision of public transit is
incredibly complicated and fraught with countless opportunities for
failure. It requires brave leadership that understands what it's
doing and can hold together a necessary coalition of public and
private interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of major infrastructure investments are
permanently fragile,'' says Johnson, who heads the Metro Council,
the powerful regional governing body that oversees an agency called
Metro Transit, which runs the area bus system and also will operate
the light-rail trains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The area's journey to having light rail has been a frustrating
milk run, not an express trip. For decades, proponents of light
rail fought with people who argued it was too costly and
inefficient compared with just improving bus service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We paralyzed each other for 20 years,'' says Johnson. ``We
just continued our automobile dependence and let time pass. We
carried out a nearly ritualistic argument in which rail advocates
would resurrect their best theories about what rail would do for
our transportation abilities and our culture. Skeptics, including
myself, would trot out our several arguments about efficiency,
about how little impact it would make on congestion numbers, how
much money would disappear into a black hole. . .'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And because the region enjoyed steady economic growth and no
crises, ``we could afford this exquisite little argument among
elites,'' Johnson says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he says, ``I came to a point where I realized that
impact mattered more than efficiency.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The impact he's talking about is both getting people to think of
public transit as a reasonable alternative to cars and using light
rail as ``a tool for redevelopment'' along the Hiawatha corridor, a
stretch of mostly unattractive small businesses and light industry
along a four-lane street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What turned Johnson around on this question was political
reality. First, he realized the state legislature and other funding
sources would never provide the large influx of cash needed to
improve the bus system radically. Second, he and Peter McLaughlin
made a political deal. Johnson would support light rail if
McLaughlin would push for additional financing for buses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the stars were aligned right for the Twin Cities.
Not only was Hiawatha Avenue, as part of long-planned improvements,
slated for reconstruction, but two Minnesota members of Congress _
Democrats Martin Sabo and Jim Oberstar _ were in key House
positions to help the region get federal funding for light rail if
local leaders could ever get behind one plan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My argument,'' says McLaughlin, ``was, we're dinking around
with $3 million projects and $1 million projects and we're
squandering this incredible opportunity to raise the level of our
transit system. If we blow this now we're going to be stuck for
another generation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many regions count on federal help for 80 percent of such
projects. But the Twin Cities is committed to paying about 50
percent. And federal funding, though not finally assured for the
$200-plus million needed, is now reasonably well lined up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that success falls to McLaughlin for his efforts
to get the seven counties in the metro area to agree on the
Hiawatha corridor as the first priority for light rail _ or, if
money for light rail could not be found, for busways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything like this takes one or more champions,'' says
Johnson. ``Peter put this at the center of his work.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several other transit corridors are on the drawing board now,
and there is some contention over which one will get to be second
and third. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gary Erickson, director of Hennepin County's Department
of Transit and Community Works, says he's ``very concerned that the
fight over who's No. 2 could jeopardize the one they're all
behind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But so far what Johnson calls a permanently fragile coalition is
holding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another threat to transit progress here is the odd manner of
funding it. In addition to bus fares and state and federal
contributions, the region pays for transit with local property
taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dependence on the property tax,'' says McLaughlin, ``is a
huge, huge problem.'' That system, says Johnson, ``desperately
needs to be changed'' because it's ``a guarantee of on-going
political arguments about fairness.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Twin Cities' commitment to light rail, for all its fits
and starts, appears now to be well thought-out and reasonable, even
though many headaches may lie ahead in the inevitably difficult
details. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful transit systems,'' says Art Leahy, general manager
of Metro Transit, ``have used rail to improve the entire transit
system.'' Clearly that's the plan here, along with economic
redevelopment where the rail line will run. Area leaders have
decided to risk higher initial costs to achieve a long-term impact.
It's the kind of calculated bet on the future an area can make when
it has thoughtful, confident leadership with shared vision. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
