<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-TRANSIT-SIDE-     09-21 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TRANSIT-SIDE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1997 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL _ Twin Cities officials are about a year away from
letting a contract for design and construction of a 12-plus mile
light-rail system from downtown Minneapolis to the airport to the
Mall of America and beyond _ all operated by an agency of the
regional governing body, the Metro Council, headquartered here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Construction could begin six to eight months after that, with
the line opening in the summer of 2003. Though no two regions are
exactly alike, here are some lessons other cities can learn from
the Twin Cities' experience: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Creating a light-rail system can be agonizingly slow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These things take a long time _ six to 10 years to get the
first piece done.'' _ Gary Erickson, director of Hennepin County's
Department of Transit and Community Works. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these solutions will be quick and painless.'' _ state
Rep. Myron Orfield, a land-use planning advocate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Forget light rail unless it's an integrated part of a sensibly
balanced regional transit system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't just look at kind of a hot alignment that seems to be
the thing you can get people rallying around initially because
sooner or later you're going to have the detractors to that
alignment that, if you really didn't think it through, could find
the fatal flaw that's just going to knock it out of the water.'' _
Erickson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision here is to have a whole interlocking network of
transit ways all over this region.'' It will include light rail,
commuter rail, regular bus routes and dedicated busways on
highways. _ Curt Johnson, Metro Council chairman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize that (light rail) is only a piece, and if
it's wildly successful it won't serve but 10 to 15 percent of our
ridership.'' _ Stephen L. Morris, director of transit development
for Metro Transit, the Metro Council agency that operates the bus
system and that will run light rail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a unified regional system that's easy for riders to
use. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a seamless system. We're going to have free transfers
from buses to rail and rail to buses. We're going to have a bus
feeder system run by Metro Transit timed to lead to trains as
they're going down Hiawatha Avenue.'' _ Peter McLaughlin, Hennepin
County commissioner and chairman of the Metropolitan Light Rail
Transit Joint Powers Board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Light rail won't solve all transportation problems but without
it the future may be limited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Transit is not going to prevent or cure congestion. There's no
illusion about that. But having a serious transit infrastructure
could eventually give (the residents of) this region choices.'' _
Johnson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to have a 24-hour city, you need transit. You
can't build the appropriate density without the commitment to
transit.'' _ John DeWitt, head of ``Transit for Livable
Communities,'' a community-based advocacy group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Listen to opponents. (Among those historically asking hard
questions about light rail in the Twin Cities have been the
editorial boards of the Star-Tribune in Minneapolis and the Pioneer
Press in St. Paul.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to have naysayers. They are good in the
process. They can bring out things that you might otherwise not
think about.'' _ Erickson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Focusing on light rail doesn't mean you can ignore the rest of
public transit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You establish rail as a flagship. But you should not allow
under any circumstances the bus system to become second class.'' _
Art Leahy, general manager of Metro Transit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand the fundamental characteristics of different
transit modes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rail is powerful but fragile. Buses are very durable.'' _
Leahy, who points out that because light rail, which can haul large
numbers of people quickly, runs on fixed tracks, the whole system
can get stopped when one overhead electrical power line comes down
or another rail car stalls on those tracks. Buses, which carry
fewer people, nonetheless are flexible and can go around trouble. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The devil is deeply embedded in the details. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hire management staff with real rail experience.'' _ Leahy,
who is doing that now and who notes that it takes months of
rigorous training for drivers, maintenance workers and other
employees to learn how to run light rail properly and to prepare
for every emergency from suicides on the tracks to electrical
storms that cut power to the system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Leaders should lead, and not wait too long to imagine the
future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Majority politics will not demand action on the transportation
front until most people find congestion unspeakable. By the time
most people do, it's too late to do anything about it. So you have
to have people running the risks up front, of saying we've got to
begin to build this infrastructure.'' _ Johnson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
