<TEXT>
<P>
   To publish any of the special ``separate buy'' articles listed
below, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2483 -- Sept. 21, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. ITALIAN FUTURES It is just over two years since Romano
Prodi's centre-left coalition came to power on the ruins of Italy's
postwar political system. By joining Emu in the first wave it has
achieved one of its main goals. But will it have the strength to
liberalise the country's deeply conservative corporate order? By
John Hooper. From Prospect magazine. 4,000 words. (N/A U.K.)
_____________________________________________________________2.
PAIN AND POT PLANTS There are many anecdotal reports of the
pain-relieving properties of marijuana. Here is how the active
component of marijuana actually works as a pain killer in the
brain. By Helen Phillips. Nature News Service. 500 words. (N/A
France and Spain. Embargo : 18h00 GMT Wednesday, Sept. 23.)
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
WHAT IS ACADEMIA FOR? The oldest and most widespread view of
academics is that they are really a bit odd. Mastery of the details
of agrarian reform under Tiberius or of Greek imagery in Keats'
letters leaves them ill-equipped to apply sun cream or order a
pizza. But if the heroic age of scholarship is past, what are the
humanities for? To teach us how to lead better lives? By Alain de
Botton. From Prospect magazine. (N/A U.K.) 3,800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   A. BIOARMAGEDDON Sooner or later there is going to be a
biological attack on a major city. Are we prepared to deal with it?
At the moment, the U.S. is one of the few countries taking the
bioterrorist threat seriously. Sweden, France and Israel have
trained emergency teams and stockpiled gas masks. Other countries
do not seem concerned. By Debora MacKenzie. 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   B. GHOSTS IN THE SKY Is the Universe really a giant hall of
mirrors where you can't believe your eyes? Astronomers now know
that there are no copies of our Galaxy nearby. But there could
still be some lurking farther afield, beyond the range of our
existing telescopes. By Hazel Muir. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. DIG THIS ?7_A bizarre burial ground in Illinois (from the
long-lost civilisation that built the Temple of the Moon in
pre-Inca times) could save archaeologists time, money and toil. The
'Controlled Archaelogical Test Site' will help evaluate new sensors
under controlled conditions and eventually may aid
archaeogeophysicists to find 'buried treasure' -- without turning
over a single lump of earth. By Daniel Pendick. 2,000 words.
