<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     09-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR REPORT VIOLATES `HARMFUL TO MINORS' LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, Republican members of the U.S. House began fiddling
around with another version of the unconstitutional Communications
Decency Act _ call it ``Son of CDA.'' The bill (HR 3783) would make
it illegal to post material that is ``harmful to minors'' on the
Internet. The legislators didn't seem to notice their
inconsistency: Only days before, these same House GOP members voted
to put Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr's graphic sex report on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A person who violates ``Son of CDA'' can be fined $50,000 and
spend six months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Any Web site that carries advertising or charges for access is
subject to this law. Most online newspapers carry advertising, as
do a vast number of other Web pages. Many of the Web sites that
posted the Starr report carry advertising. A few specialized sites
charge for access.
</P>
<P>
   According to HR 3783, ``The term `material that is harmful to
minors' means any communication, picture, image, graphic image
file, article, recording, writing, or other matter of any kind that
(ii) depicts, describes, or represents, in a patently offensive way
with respect to what is suitable for minors, an actual or simulated
sexual act or sexual contact, actual or simulated normal or
perverted sexual acts, or a lewd exhibition of the genitals ...''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's sex report certainly fits that definition. If ``Son of
CDA'' were already the law, members of the U.S. House who voted for
posting the report on the Internet could be brought up on charges
of trafficking in material that is harmful to minors.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the House reflect America's hypocritical notions
about sex _ my sexual behavior is right and good, yours is
perverse.
</P>
<P>
   According to the bill, it depends upon who is putting the
material on the World Wide Web and for what reason. HR 3783
contains an exception: The material isn't considered harmful if _
it has political value for minors.
</P>
<P>
   So if 10-year-old Jane clicks on the Starr report, obviously its
political value far outweighs its sleazy obsession with sex.
</P>
<P>
   Would an ordinary citizen be immune to prosecution if he were to
post snapshots and descriptions of Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho,
in her former adulterous relationship? Or details of the affair
involving Republican Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana? Or motel photos of
Illinois Republican Rep. Henry Hyde and his ``friend'' during their
four-year liaison? Would the political value outweigh the sleaze?
</P>
<P>
   Barry Steinhardt, president of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, is quoted in a Sept. 17 email release stating that the
Starr report ``has been blocked by most filtering programs and that
several Internet service providers have ordered their users to take
down mirror sites of the report.'' Steinhardt argues that although
the Starr report is important, the fact that it is being blocked by
filtering software programs indicates that it ``would not pass the
legislation's `harmful to minors' test.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Starr report with its lascivious details should
doom any sweeping legislation aimed at prohibiting sexual speech on
the Internet. Congress can't have it both ways. If Congress is
allowed to post patently offensive sexual materials, so is the
ordinary citizen.
</P>
<P>
   HR 3783 would criminalize speech that is protected by the First
Amendment. It has the same problem that the Communications Decency
Act did. Most Web sites are accessible to anyone on the Internet
without a charge and without age verification necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The technology for verifying the age of someone who wants to
access a Web site is extraordinarily expensive. If the Internet
were limited to only those sites which could afford verifying
technology, most of the best sites on the World Wide Web would
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   In Reno vs. ACLU, a unanimous U.S. Supreme Court struck CDA down
as unconstitutional because it prohibited the protected speech of
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The court said that the government cannot require speakers on
the Internet to distinguish between adults and minors.
</P>
<P>
   HR 3783 will fail for the same reasons that CDA did.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress passes this law, it will cost civil liberties
organizations more than $1 million to challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, and the bill's 58 other co-sponsors
should have to repay these legal costs out of their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that would drive the Supreme Court's decision home: The
government cannot limit adult speech to that of a child's _ anymore
than Starr could have written his report on Clinton at a child's
level of language and understanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5742 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NY     09-21 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH A FULL DECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
 (Eds: Items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
Richard Lederer is the author, most recently, of The Word Circus
(Merriam- Webster). William Safire is on vacation. 
 By RICHARD LEDERER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My son, Howard, and daughter Annie live and move and have their
beings in that windowless, clockless pleasure dome known as Las
Vegas. I'm pleased to report that in May, in a packed room at
Binion's Horseshoe Casino in downtown Vegas, they placed sixth and
seventh in the seven-card stud competition, the only sibling pair
ever to reach the finals in the World Series of Poker in the same
game.
</P>
<P>
   Annie and Howard have also won national tournaments with exotic
names like the Diamond Jim Brady Texas Hold 'Em Shootout and the
Hall of Fame Classic Deuce-to-Seven Lowball Draw No-Limit. If you
can't already tell, I'm proud of my kids, especially because they
possess such passion for what they do.
</P>
<P>
   My children's achievements in the gaming halls inspire me to
play with a full deck of vivid words and phrases that have made the
trip from the poker table into our everyday conversation and
writing. The same color and high-risk excitement of poker that
inspired 352 players to plunk down $10,000 each in the 1998 world
championship event at Binion's have made the language of poker one
of the most pervasive metaphors in our language.
</P>
<P>
   The basic elements of poker are the cards, the chips and the
play of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   From the game of five-card stud descends the expression
 &UR; back-to-back victories &LR; , from a fortuitous ace-down-ace-up as the
first two cards. Be on guard for a cardsharp who will give you a
fast shuffle, in which case you may get lost in the shuffle. You
might call such a low-down skunk  &UR; a four-flusher &LR;  _ a poker player
who pretends to hold a flush (from the Latin  &UR; fluxus &LR; , because all
five cards flow together), but in fact holds a worthless hand of
four same-suit cards and one that doesn't match.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we've laid our cards on the table, let's see what
happens when the chips are down. We call a gilt-edged, sure-thing
stock a  &UR; blue-chip &LR;  security because blue poker chips are the most
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   When we compare the worth and power of two things, we often ask
how one  &UR; stacks up &LR;  against the other, as in ``How do the Knicks
 &UR; stack up &LR;  against the Heat?'' Here, the reference is to the
columns of chips piled up before the players around a poker table.
These stacks also account for the expressions  &UR; bottom dollar &LR;  and
 &UR; top dollar &LR; . Betting your  &UR; bottom dollar &LR;  means wagering the
entire stack, and the  &UR; top dollar &LR; , or chip, is the one that sits
atop the highest pile on the table. Indeed, the metaphor of poker
chips is so powerful that one of the euphemisms we use for death is
 &UR; cashing in one's chips &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The guts of poker is the betting. If you want to call my bluff
on that one, and insist that I put up or shut up, I'll be happy to
put my money where my mouth is.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're involved in a big business deal. You let the other
guy know that you're not a piker running a penny-ante operation.
One theory traces  &UR; piker &LR;  to westward migrants from Pike County,
Mo. These small farmers were less inclined than hardened veterans
to risk high stakes, and the county name came eponymously to
designate penny pinchers.  &UR; Ante &LR; , from the Latin for ``before,''
refers to chips placed in the middle of the poker table before the
betting begins, so a  &UR; penny-ante &LR;  game is fit only for  &UR; pikers &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations continue, and you sweeten the pot by upping the
stakes. You don't want to blow your wad and go in the hole, but you
don't want to stand pat either. Rather than passing the buck, you
play it close to the vest without showing your hand, maintain your
poker face, keep everything aboveboard, and hope to hit the
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The hole in the phrase  &UR; in the hole &LR;  refers to a slot cut in the
middle of poker tables through which checks and cash are deposited
into a box, to be transferred later to the coffers of the house.
 &UR; Stand pat &LR;  refers to the strategy of keeping one's original
( &UR; pat &LR; ) hand in draw poker rather than making an exchange. Because
cardsharps are known to engage in chicanery when their hands are
under the table, or board,  &UR; aboveboard &LR;  has come to mean open
honesty, and  &UR; under the table &LR;  deception.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jackpot &LR;  originally described the reward to the big winner in a
game of progressive poker, in which you need a pair of jacks or
better to ``open the pot.'' Because the stakes grow larger until
the requisite pair is dealt,  &UR; jackpot &LR;  has expanded to include the
pots of gold in slot machines, game shows and state lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pass the buck &LR;  is a common expression that means ``to shift
responsibility.'' But why, you may have asked yourself, should
handing someone a dollar bill indicate that responsibility is in
any way transferred? Once again the answer can be found in
high-stakes gaming halls and riverboats. The buck in  &UR; pass the
buck &LR;  was originally a poker term designating a marker that was
placed in front of the player whose turn it was to deal the next
hand.
</P>
<P>
   This movable object varied the order of betting and kept one
person from dealing all the time, thus transferring the
disadvantages of being the first to wager and cutting down on the
chances of cheating. During the heyday of poker in the 19th
century, the marker was often a hunting knife whose handle was made
of a buck's horn. The marker defined the game as Buckhorn Poker or
Buck Poker and gave us  &UR; pass the buck &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In the Old West, silver dollars often replaced buckhorn knives
as tokens, and these coins took on the slang name  &UR; buck &LR;  for their
own. President Harry Truman adopted the still-famous motto ``The
buck stops here,'' meaning that the ultimate responsibility rested
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The cleverest application of poker terminology that I have ever
encountered appears on the truck of a New Hampshire plumbing
company: ``A Flush Is Better Than a Full House.'' In poker that
isn't true, but any homeowner recognizes its wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Great poker players must have a firm grounding in the statistics
of card distribution and probability but, as my son and daughter
the poker champions explain, ``To play poker at the highest level
is to read people _ their faces, their body language and their
behavior patterns.'' Language and people are inextricably
intertwined. The democratic poetry of poker that pervades our
American language is a vivid emblem of the games that we, as a
civilization, watch and play.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the cards. You can bet on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
