<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-SPOOF-REVIEW-NY     09-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-SPOOF-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOTHETICAL REPLY TO MANUSCRIPT FROM KEN STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TO: Kenneth W. Starr
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Volumnia Valence, Editor-in-Chief
</P>
<P>
   RE: Manuscript Submission
</P>
<P>
   Thank you for the manuscript of ``Referral,'' your story of
romantic intrigue. We had been looking forward to it, given all the
buzz comparing you to Harold Robbins, Jackie Susann and the other
great masters of what those media philistines keep calling the
``trashy novel.'' We eagerly began reading the original draft, plus
each shipment of pages you keep sending (please stop!).
</P>
<P>
   But I'm afraid it's not for us. ``Referral,'' while an ambitious
first effort, simply does not meet the standards we like to
maintain here at Soaring Stallion Press.
</P>
<P>
   First, it needs editing. It is simply not sexy to describe the
same sex act three times, and then follow with five footnotes about
said act. We get the idea the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Actually our senior editor, Jane V.V. Voom, who specializes in
serial-killer romance mysteries, found your constant reiteration of
the same facts ``disturbing and possibly pathological.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, that's just typical Jane! But your repetitions do
destroy the natural rhythms of lust. Sex builds. It arcs. It
climaxes. It is supposed to be fun. You make it sound a bit like
homework.
</P>
<P>
   And so unpleasantly tawdry! During an initial courtship scene,
your Monica character flashes her lingerie: ``In the course of
flirting with him, she raised her jacket in the back and showed him
the straps of her thong underwear, which extended above her
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, we have absolutely nothing against thong underwear. In our
recent best-seller, ``The Golddiggers of Grenada,'' Letitia
Lawrence wears a thong dotted with miniature tropical drinks. Of
course, a good heroine should wear a thong _ but not until much
later!
</P>
<P>
   We would prefer a ``meet cute'' scenario. If she must work in
his office, perhaps one could knock over a filing cabinet onto the
other? Something sudden and less obvious. Have you read our
top-selling title, ``The Empty Duplex''? In this wonderful novel,
Federica and Bartholomew meet when they discover they have the same
real estate agent. We aren't introduced to Federica's thong until
page 300. And Bartholomew finds it even later.
</P>
<P>
   Believe us, if you begin with a thong, you have nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point, Ken: We want somewhere to go. We crave
emotional depths from your characters. We want to believe that
Bill, like Bartholomew, would give up a whole semiconductor empire
for the right girl. Wars come and go, the real estate market
crashes, landlords renege, but passion always triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that when you rewrite moments like this one:
``[They) briefly discussed an antique book that she had dropped
off. . . . With the book, she enclosed a letter telling the
President that she wanted to have sexual intercourse with him at
least once.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken, that's cold! Remember, always show, don't tell. Give us an
inkling of inner life. And for God's sake don't make the woman
plead for sex in a letter; it's undignified. If your characters are
going to resist complete consummation _ a choice I should tell you
does lower your chances of getting published _ at least they should
feel a few pangs of desire.
</P>
<P>
   How about this instead:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The leather bindings cracked beneath his fingers. A first
edition, never read, flown in from a Beverly Hills dealer. He was
no fool. He knew how much such a book would cost. And his office
hadn't even paid her a salary. Thank God she came from money. She
would never need to sell the rights to their story. She would
always buy him thoughtful gifts that neither of them would have the
time to read or fully absorb. He leafed through the yellowing
pages. There was a letter inside, sealed with wax. He looked up.
``I don't care what this letter says, Monica,'' he told her. ``I
must have you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said firmly. ``And if not now, eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We want a hero who doesn't need to read directions or take
polls. We want a heroine who follows her gut. But you give us a
hero who worries about what the world will think and a heroine who
worries about what the hero will think. (Meanwhile, given the close
proximity of Betty the secretary, the reader is distracted with
thoughts of what she must think.)
</P>
<P>
   We want  &UR; passionate &LR;  thoughts, cloaked in  &UR; passionate  &LR; 
language. Although we have been editing risque works of fiction for
years, your lurid yet clinical style upset everyone here
enormously. You tally and clock events as if each encounter were
not unique and timeless. You state there are ``nine incidents''
involving ``breasts.'' Why not just say: ``She held him to her
cleavage again. And again . . .''?
</P>
<P>
   I wonder too: Can't she hold him to her cleavage in a more
rapturous setting? Why set every scene in that irritating office
with all those interruptions? He is powerful. She is rich. You
would think they could get a hotel room. A dusky beach at sunset.
Or at least a bed of some kind. Lovers ought to be wrapped in
silken sheets, or in resilient animal rugs or hearth coverings. The
intern character stays on the floor too much, while the president
sits in his chair for long periods, which makes the reader worry
about his bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, your characters are strange. Your hero does not seem to
know what sexual relations are. Your heroine does not seem to
accept that he is the leader of the free world. Instead of jewels
and vows, they exchange a hat pin, a letter opener embellished with
a frog, an Annie Lennox recording and, ultimately, a series of
tacky souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they seem completely incapable of having a romantic
affair as we at Soaring Stallion Press define romantic affair. And
we have been in the business of defining it for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   I should warn you that yours is not the kind of fare that would
normally be found in a mainstream bookstore. You may want to try a
softcore porn publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps writing is not your vocation after all. Have you
considered law school?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
