<SLUG> BC-LARRYKING-BABERUTH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS LARRY KING. NEXT UP: THE BABE. 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `s' code) 
(editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) After a long silence, Babe Ruth has emerged
for a rare interview on tonight's ``Larry King Live.''(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Larry King: Tonight, a kid so incorrigible his parents threw him
out of the family tavern. Pitcher, slugger, gorger, ladies' man.
George Herman Ruth. The Babe. A great honor to have the
difficult-to-get Babe Ruth in our studio. You've been on our wish
list for years.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth: I figured I had to do this sooner or later. Now I've
got my Playstation Hooters All-Star Babe '99 CD-ROM game to
promote.
</P>
<P>
   King: So many areas to cover. Let's start with Mark McGwire. You
know him?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Sure.
</P>
<P>
   King: Great guy, good friend, frequent guest.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: A 6-foot-6 inch weenie. What's he swing, a 34-ounce bat? I
showed him the stick I hit 60 with. Fifty ounces. Big wimp couldn't
lift it. Whined like Ty Cobb when he didn't get invited to my 50th
birthday party at Nathan's.
</P>
<P>
   King: Amazing. Have you talked to Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Talk to him? He's wearing my lucky cup from 1927.
</P>
<P>
   King: Babe, you played fat. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: I'm an endomorph, kid. It's my body type. I couldn't help
it. Dr. Dean Ornish helped me learn not to hate myself for it.
</P>
<P>
   King: So it wasn't the hot dogs?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Ah, that was a lot of hype. Sportswriters saw me eat a
dozen dogs between innings and thought that was all I ate. Mostly I
ate baby carrots and soy burgers.
</P>
<P>
   King: Supermodel food but still a porker. Amazing. Lou Gehrig.
You hated him.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Only after his mother made me a sauerbraten with cabbage
that put me in a slump in '31. Couldn't lift a bat or a woman for a
week.
</P>
<P>
   King: Slugging and sweet talk with the one and only Babe Ruth.
We'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)(Begin video clip: William Bendix in a scene
from ``The Babe Ruth Story.'')(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   King: Lots of critics think that was the worst sports movie
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Can't disagree. But did you see ``Baseketball''? I had to
hear Bob Costas talk about how hard his nipples were. But I loved
``Happy Gilmore.'' Adam Sandler just kills me.
</P>
<P>
   King: Why has nobody portrayed Babe Ruth well on the silver
screen?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: I thought John Goodman would be great. But talk about
endomorphic! He was 70 pounds too fat playing me when I was 40
pounds overweight. And I'll tell you, I wasn't fat as a kid. But
that movie made me look like a hippo at 15.
</P>
<P>
   King: You were great as you in ``Pride of the Yankees.'' If Babe
Ruth could choose an actor to play Babe Ruth, who would it be?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Pacino. Who else?
</P>
<P>
   King: Great choice. Good friend. Frequent guest. Columbus, Ohio,
you're talking to Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Caller: Hi, Babe. What do you think is the worst trade ever?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: When that bum Steinbrenner traded Jay Buhner for Ken
Phelps. How could he trade a future superstar for a guy who was out
of baseball in two years?
</P>
<P>
   King: Walla Walla, Washington, hello.
</P>
<P>
   Caller: Babe, I hear you were depressed because nobody asked you
to manage in the majors. But you seem happy now. What's your
secret?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: St. John's Wort. And I read the ``Don't Sweat the Small
Stuff'' books.
</P>
<P>
   King: Let's go back. You grew up in Baltimore. Orphanage life
tough?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Nah, I loved it. Learned baseball there. Played the
recorder in the St. Mary's marching band.
</P>
<P>
   King: You were musically inclined?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Kid, you think all I did was hit home runs? I had a
liberal arts education, short as it was.
</P>
<P>
   King: Did you have any quibbles with the Modern Library's list
of the greatest 100 books ever?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: No Toni Morrison. No Wally Lamb. No Dick Schaap.
</P>
<P>
   King: Me, I'd have voted for Wilt Chamberlain's memoir. Babe,
what do you think _ Yankee Stadium on the West Side?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Kid, I live on the West Side and I don't want it there.
Too much traffic. And a billion dollars? Cripes, I built the first
one for $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   King: So you're for keeping it in the Bronx?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: I didn't build it to move it, Larry.
</P>
<P>
   King: You ever meet Rudy Giuliani?
</P>
<P>
   Ruth: Only long enough to sell him a cap with some old sweat on
it for 50 grand. He thought it was mine. It was really Wally
Pipp's.
</P>
<P>
   King: Don't ever be a stranger, buddy. The name is Babe Ruth.
What a mensch. Tomorrow night from Washington, William Bennett and
Little Richard. Good night.
</P>
</TEXT>
