 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Familiar Faces Return to Moscow
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when Mikhail Gorbachev, the last Soviet
president, was tinkering with an ossified Communist economy, he
sought the advice of a group of then-liberal economists who
advocated such notions as a `'regulated market economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in a return engagement that Russian headline writers were
calling ``back to the future,'' the same team of economists has
returned, advising Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov about how to put
the brakes on Russia's pell-mell transition to a free market.
</P>
<P>
   Their point man in the government, First Deputy Prime Minister
Yuri Maslyukov, is another familiar face: in 1991, he was last head
of Gosplan, the giant state planning agency that planned the Soviet
economy into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CELESTINE BOHLEN
</P>
<P>
   A Flash in Time Is Buried in Alabama
</P>
<P>
   People did not throng the streets of Montgomery to see the white
hearse roll slowly by, at least not as many people as might have
been expected. Maybe, some political experts surmised, it was
because George C. Wallace had already passed into history.
</P>
<P>
   The man generations of Alabamians just called ``The Guv'na'' was
buried Wednesday in Montgomery beside his first wife, Lurleen,
after finally giving in to the paralysis and sickness that had
slowly consumed his life. He was 79, and since 1972 _ since Arthur
Bremer fired five bullets into him in a Maryland shopping center _
he had lived in pain, in his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Old friends _ white ones who had always stood by him, black ones
who believed him when he said he was sorry for what he had done to
them as a segregationist, had come to see his body as he lay in
state in the Capitol. Some of them brought their grandchildren, for
one last peek at a man who had personified a hot-flash in time,
only to become what many people came to regard as a tragic figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``God forgave him,'' said John Watkins, a 68-year-old black man,
as eight State Troopers carried the casket from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said he had, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   Familiar Names In Minnesota Too
</P>
<P>
   In a race among men with famous Minnesota names, victory in the
Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party's primary for governor went to the
state's most revered one: Hubert H. Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it was Hubert H. Humphrey III, the son and
namesake of the former vice president, senator and 1968
presidential nominee. Also-rans in the primary included Ted
Mondale, the son of former Vice President Walter Mondale; Mike
Freeman, son of former Gov. Orville Freeman; Mark Dayton, heir to
the Dayton Hudson store conglomerate, which owns the Target chain,
and Doug Johnson, who described himself as the only commoner in the
contest but the one with the most authentic Minnesota name.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey, the state's attorney general, ran a campaign that
boasted of a bringing a lawsuit against tobacco companies that will
net the state $6.1 billion, and vowed to pay two years of college
tuition for Minnesotans.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DIRK JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia's Serbs Reject A Leader the West Liked
</P>
<P>
   As Bosnia conducted elections under the watchful eyes of the
United States and other countries with peacekeeping forces in the
land, the West's diplomatic strategy was clear: isolate the
hard-line Serb nationalists and support those moderates who
appeared most likely to support reconciliation of Bosnia's Serbs
and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy seemed to have been dealt a heavy blow last week
when Biljana Plavsic appeared to have been voted out of office as
President of Bosnia's Serb Republic, according to international
officials monitoring preliminary results. The winner seemed to be
Nikola Poplasen, leader of the Serb Radical Party, who is
considered an extreme nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   From her own offices in Banja Luka, Ms. Plavsic had been
confronting radical Serb leaders in Pale for more than a year, and
a defeat would seem to be a clear repudiation of the West's goals.
```If Poplasen has won, it means the Bosnian Serbs are telling the
West, `We don't care about you or your money or your quaint ideas
about reconciliation with Muslims and Croats,''' a European
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Debt Wiped Out For the House Speaker
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich wiped out a debt he never incurred.
He said he did not need the $150,000 that former Sen. Bob Dole had
offered him to pay off the $300,000 fine that the House had levied
against the speaker last January.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said that Gingrich had made more money than expected on
his book, ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way,'' even though the tome
made the best-seller list for only one week.
</P>
<P>
   The fine against Gingrich _ to repay the government for the
expense of investigating whether he misled the House ethics
committee _ is now being examined as the model for part of a
possible sanction against President Clinton, who misled many
others.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Nominee Is Put on Hold
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous poison-pen letter has left the United States
waiting for a chief delegate at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The letter about Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's nominee
for the post, alleged that the veteran diplomat may have violated
federal ethics laws in his contacts with former colleagues after
leaving the State Department two years ago. It also questioned his
ties to a former ambassador to Switzerland, who gave Holbrooke
rent-free lodging at his home in Washington for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, the architect of the 1995 Dayton peace agreement that
halted the fighting in Bosnia, has denied any wrongdoing and
amended his financial disclosure statements to reflect the gift of
the lodging. The investigation by the Justice and State Departments
is expected to last at least several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Amid the Lost Lives, Also a Loss to Art
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian official who saw the wreckage of Swissair Flight 111
after it crashed into the ocean Sept. 2, killing all 229 people
aboard, said it looked like a pane of glass that had shattered into
a million pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Among those pieces is an original Picasso painting that was
being sent to Geneva and was probably destroyed on impact. In his
later years, Picasso dashed off at least six versions of a painting
called ``The Painter,'' and Swissair has confirmed that one of them
was on Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-fated jet also carried a treasure trove of jewelry, cash
and diamonds, including one piece that had been displayed at the
Museum of Natural History until Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police warned would-be treasure
hunters to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANTHONY DePALMA &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Normal At Northwest Airlines
</P>
<P>
   Air service slowly began returning to isolated parts of the
upper Midwest and South last week after pilots at Northwest
Airlines ratified a new contract, ending their bitter 15-day strike
against the nation's fourth-largest airline. About one quarter of
Northwest's 1,700 daily passenger flights resumed on Wednesday; the
airline said its full schedule would not be back in the air until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Northwest's labor troubles are far from over.
</P>
<P>
   The airline still mustnegotiate contracts with five other unions
representing aircraft mechanics, flights attendants, customer
service agents and other workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN
</P>
<P>
   A New Way to Read The Law at Home
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next month, students will be able to earn a law degree
entirely online.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Educational Centers, a Washington Post Co. subsidiary
best known for its test-coaching services, is opening the Concord
University School of Law, in which students will take all of their
courses over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The school will not be accredited by the American Bar
Association, however, and as a result graduates will face some
limits to where they can practice law. California is one state that
will welcome them.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which began accepting applications last week
(www.concord.kaplan.edu), expects to attract people whose careers,
family obligations or geographic locations make it hard for them to
attend traditional law schools.
</P>
<P>
   The cost, $4,200 a year for a four-year law degree program, will
be far below the cost at most private universities and even less
than at many public ones.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KAREN W. ARENSON
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, Friend. Wanna Bet? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a brilliantly cynical venture, the Palestinian Authority
unveiled last week the first large, for-profit international
investment in Yasser Arafat's territory: a casino catering to
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The Oasis Casino outside Jericho is a $50 million,
Austrian-backed project intended to milk Israelis of their money in
order to generate millions in tax revenues for the cash-strapped
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are barred from entering the glitzy new building by
Arafat, who bowed to the protests of Islamic fundamentalists. Half
of its employees, though, are Palestinians, somewhat sheepishly
working in a house of sin in order to double the salaries they
could have if there were work available as laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat did not attend opening ceremonies. Neither did the
promised guest of honor: the model Claudia Schiffer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   Italian Not Spoken Here &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if in Italy, at least, Private Ryan would not be
saved. A two-month strike by dubbers delayed the release in Italy
of more than a dozen major films, including Steven Spielberg's
latest hit movie.
</P>
<P>
   Italians, far more than the French or Germans, watch television
and go the the movies expecting to hear John Wayne and Jim Carrey
speak the native language. In Italy, some of the most prolific
dubbers are major stars in their own right. Their sudden shutdown
practically paralyzed Italy: panicked network executives were
forced last week to air beloved American soap operas in English
with subtitles. Viewers deluged television stations with angry
phone calls and threats.
</P>
<P>
   That show of force had results. Friday, producers and dubbers
agreed to reopen talks on a national contract and the strikers said
they would return to their sound studios. ``They couldn't take the
strike anymore,'' said Andrea Ward, the Italian voice of Andy
Garcia and David Keith.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALESSANDRA STANLEY
</P>
