<SLUG> BC-BENBEN-TVREVIEW22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dream on if you're looking for another Benben comedy jewel
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's always painful watching talented actors die slow deaths in
shameful comedies. And it certainly isn't funny watching the
normally hilarious Brian Benben straining to get laughs in his
witless sitcom (Monday, 9:30 p.m., CBS).
</P>
<P>
   On The Brian Benben Show, the former Dream On star is, well,
Brian Benben, a veteran Los Angeles TV anchor who gets demoted to
the dreaded human interest beat after the station hires Ken and
Barbie anchor dolls.
</P>
<P>
   So, like, how did the goofy Benben lose his job to Chad (Charles
Esten), a former VH1 veejay who's ``two-thirds hair?'' Well, it
didn't help that audience research showed most viewers wanted to
sleep with Chad and those pearly whites. Hey, viewers know big,
white teeth and helmet hair are more important that something like,
say, credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Now Benben is relegated to interviewing 102-yer-old ladies who
open their blouses and scream the word ``whore'' on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Benben isn't pleased with his new assignment, so he
scams to get his old job back. That means he'll pull silly high
school pranks like changing the teleprompter disc so doofus Chad
sounds like an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   But the only people who look like idiots are the writers of this
series. If The Brian Benben Show turns into a prank-of-the-week
sitcom, that'll get old fast. There's nothing wrong with broad and
silly humor (see That '70s Show or 3rd Rock from the Sun), but it
does have to be funny.
</P>
<P>
   Benben doesn't get much help from his co-stars. There's the
black sports guy (Wendell Pierce) with no groin (don't ask) and the
gay weatherman (Billy Hernandez) who can tell if Chad is straight
or gay by the donuts he eats (don't ask about that, either).
</P>
<P>
   Advice to the producers: ditch the buffoonery, take more pointed
jabs at the local TV news business (it deserves it!) and give
Benben more bite and funny lines. Only then, can that slow death be
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
