<P>
   TV-DEBUTS _ At least 10 new and returning series debut tonight.
The best of the new: ABC's ``Sports Night'' and ``The Hughleys.''
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ An analysis of ABC's ``The Hughleys'' about an
African-American family that moves into an all-white suburb;
roundup involving ``Encore! Encore!'', ``Mad About You,'' ``Just
Shoot Me,'' ``Working,'' ``Home Improvement,'' ``Spin City'' and
``JAG.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTSNIGHT _ ``Sports Night'' may well be the new season's
best sitcom. At least it starts off right with a smart and lively
first episode about a cable sports show and the people who live and
breathe it. (Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BENBEN-TVREVIEW _ It's always painful watching talented actors
die slow deaths in shameful comedies. And it certainly isn't funny
watching the normally hilarious Brian Benben straining to get
laughs in his witless sitcom (Monday, 9:30 p.m., CBS). (Thompson,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HYPERION-TVREVIEW _ You probably won't read this anywhere else:
Hyperion Bay (Monday, 9 p.m.) is the WB's best _ and most
intelligent _ new drama. Period. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOM-TVREVIEW _ Hmmmm . . . is The Single Guy back? You can't
help but think of that mediocre show when watching Conrad Bloom,
yet another ho-hum NBC comedy (Monday, 8:30 p.m.). And, speaking of
NBC, someone needs to send those programming geniuses a nasty
letter saying America doesn't need yet another white-bread,
cookie-cutter sitcom set in a New York office. (Thompson, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE-VISION _ The fall movie season is here. The fall movie
season is here. Might as well get used to seeing double. It's this
autumn's trend out of Hollywood. Herewith a (twin) peek at how the
movies will keep repeating themselves this fall. Read it, or weep
when you find yourself sitting through a third straight movie about
someone who dies in a car crash. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Magazines on the newsstands today. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ I have been cleaning closets. It's a late-summer
ritual for me, but this time I've taken on this daunting task with
a new perspective. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURE-FIGHT _ A fortune in silver from a 17th century
shipwreck is headed to Florida, its journey delayed for more than a
year while treasure salvors battled with Ecuador's government over
the booty of coins. ``We are glad it's over, and we are happy the
split was finally honored,'' said Rob McClung of West Palm Beach,
the expedition leader who recovered nearly 6,000 coins from the
shipwreck in early 1997. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ We are driving away from the
medical laboratory over on 45th Street in West Palm Beach and I am
explaining to a 7-year-old why his mother just behaved like a
raving lunatic. Indeed, I am trying to figure it out myself.
(Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CARREG _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Lester Sanders ``was sitting in
traffic and just happened to cast a look at my registration
(sticker),'' he said. ``And I realized, my goodness, this thing has
expired.'' Sanders said that for the third year in a row, he had
not received a car registration renewal notice from the Texas
Department of Transportation. This year he has plenty of company.
(Daniel, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONKEYS-STOLEN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Florida _ A small,
5-month-old, monkey-like creature with Albert Einstein hair and a
chocolate-colored tail is missing after he and three siblings were
stolen from the Palm Beach Zoo at Dreher Park recently. They were
found later hiding in a bamboo tree near zoo property on Summit
Boulevard. (O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SMOKIES _ FONTANA VILLAGE, N.C. _ It took a village to
make our family's summer vacation a fun one. The Historic Fontana
Village, that is, a sprawling resort in northwest North Carolina.
The nearest town is a 22-mile, twisting, rolling drive to the
south. To the north looms the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.
(Bedinghauszent, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPLANT-THERAPY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ With just one treatment that
kept Charlie Hogg in the hospital one night, his doctors think they
have destroyed the tumors in his prostate, leaving him cancer-free,
perhaps for the rest of his life. The treatment, called seed
implant therapy, offers a quicker, more comfortable and less costly
alternative to surgery or external radiation for some prostate
cancer patients. (Park, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
