<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 20, moved Saturday in the `a' category and are
repeated on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REVIEW _ The government is not necessarily paralyzed by
the Clinton scandal. It has tremendous momentum, and even in times
of war and political crisis it has a way of grinding relentlessly
on. Moreover, the very threat of drift and paralysis in this case
has provided both parties with tremendous incentive to keep pushing
a substantive agenda _ maybe even to push harder than they would
otherwise. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   POLTIICAL-SAGES-REVIEW _ Many Democrats sadly agree that the
time may have long since passed for summoning any of Washington's
fabled wise men, like Robert Strauss, W. Averell Harriman, Clark
Clifford. They were part of an informal cadre of emeritus
politicians and lawyers who occasionally dropped by the city's
floating political crap game at critical moments, in between using
their influence on behalf of paying clients, to lend it some class
and even a touch of realism. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   LEARN-DISABLED-REVIEW _ Over the last decade, learning
disabilities have moved squarely to the foreground of the education
world: more than 5 percent of the nation's students now have
diagnosed learning disabilities. Hundreds of thousands of students
in elementary schools, colleges and graduate schools get special
accommodations like extra time on tests, quiet rooms to work in or
note-takers. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON-REVIEW _ The Japanese are well versed in the art of
fending off U.S. accusations, including perpetual hyperventilating
over Japan's protectionist trade policies. But nothing from the
past could have prepared the Japanese for the latest salvo by
several prominent American economists. They say that the Japanese
government has been insufficiently reckless. By running a tight
monetary policy, wringing inflation out of the economy now and for
the foreseeable future, the government has inadvertently
contributed to a downward spiral of prices and production that has
cost the Japanese nearly a decade of growth. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   FERRARO-REVIEW _ Perhaps more than any other issue, the 14-year
gap since she had been in elective office _ or run for
vice-president, her claim to fame _ dogged Geraldine Ferraro in her
race for the democratic nomination to the U.S. Senate from New
York. She lost last week and declared her political career closed,
which makes this a good time to reflect on what went wrong. By Amy
Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW _ Although the world has focused its
attention on the one-sided battle between the Chinese Communist
government and the political dissidents who press for radical
change, there is also a large population of intellectuals, many of
them scholars or former officials, who work openly to nudge the
system in a more democratic direction. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-AFGHAN-REVIEW _ Who's afraid of Afghanistan? Iran, it
seems. The Islamic Republic has positioned as many as 70,000
Revolutionary Guards and volunteers on its border with Afghanistan.
And perhaps 200,000 regular soldiers are on the way. The Taliban of
Afghanistan have only about 40,000 men under arms, so te primary
threat to Iran is not military. It is instead a threat that is
deeply political, and quite humiliating. Instead of showing Iran a
little respect, the four-year-old Sunni Muslim movement, which
follows a rigid, repressive version of Islamic law and now controls
most of Afghanistan, has nothing but contempt for its neighbor to
the west. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-PLANS-REVIEW _ The 1985 invasion of Libya would now be
in the lesson plans of every high school history teacher in America
if it had actually taken place. Instead, the stillborn invasion is
a classic example of Washington's propensity to gin up contingency
plans for seemingly otherworldly operations that never get the
green light. Indeed, there is a permanent infrastructure in the
United States national security apparatus that does nothing but
plan for every conceivable crisis, often with little or no hope
that the plans will be taken seriously by senior policy-makers or
the president. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-SPOOF-REVIEW _ A spoof on a supposed manuscript submitted
by Ken Starr for publication.
</P>
<P>
   LARRYKING-BABERUTH-REVIEW _ After a long silence, Babe Ruth has
emerged for a rare interview on ``Larry King Live.'' By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
