A5795 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN23-COX     09-21 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bastrop untucked: It isn't heat they're packing underneath
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's fitting that school officials in this small
town 30 miles east of Austin have decided to let the high school
students wear some shirts untucked to school.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning on Main Street here, about half the adults I
saw were walking around with their shirts hanging out. So by going
to school with untucked shirts, the students are conforming to the
community standard, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I do: I leave mine out to cover the fat,''
said retired Navy Capt. Bill Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell didn't have on a pair of those extremely baggy britches
the kids favor these days. You know the ones I'm talking about.
They look like they're fixing to fall off. But he was wearing an
untucked T-shirt that sported a cow skull and an armadillo wearing
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in high school you would have been tossed out of
algebra for wearing a shirt like that.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, more than 100 students walked out of Bastrop
High during classes to protest the dress code rule that outlawed
all untucked shirts. The fear of concealed weapons was one factor
behind the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, school officials have decided students can wear
untucked shirts to school, as long as the shirt is meant to be
untucked and doesn't hang down beyond the kid's fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy is good, if you believe what's good for the goose
is good for the gosling. See, in this town a lot of the older birds
don't tuck in their shirts on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reared in Austin by good, fine parents, and you never
left the house without your shirt tucked in,'' said Chester Eitze,
56. He's the executive director of the Bastrop Opera House, a live
performance theater.
</P>
<P>
   Times change, though. So on Thursday, Eitze was on Main Street
in an untucked T-shirt that had a drawing of a sloth on the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``T-shirts now are a work of art, and art should not be tucked
away,'' Eitze explained.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't anybody around these parts wear a tie? ``Oh sure. We
have bankers,'' Eitze said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wear mine in before I gained 20 pounds; how about a
kolache?'' asked Gail Smith, owner of the Deli Depot on Main
Street. She was wearing a T-shirt that wasn't tucked in.
</P>
<P>
   Marsheila Moore, who works for Smith, was wearing a T-shirt that
wasn't tucked in. While the two of them were working the deli
counter with their shirts hanging out, an older lady walked up to
order something to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The older lady's blouse wasn't tucked in, either.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the start of the revolution. It's not that folks
here are trying to make a dress code statement to support the high
school students. Most of the people I spoke with thought the high
school ought to have a dress code.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dress code is because of that gang (stuff), and
I'm behind 'em, as far as that goes,'' said Jim Dudley, of
Smithville, 15 miles southeast of Bastrop. He was in Bastrop to do
a little furniture shopping with his wife. For the occasion, Dudley
had selected a Hard Rock Cafe T-shirt. Untucked, of course.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt whether any of these people were packing heat. Several
of them mentioned packing gut as a reason for not tucking in their
shirts. But you can't bust someone for a concealed stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody wanted to talk about their untucked shirts,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gawd, I'm gonna be suspended,'' joked one good old boy,
probably 50 years old. He was wearing an untucked sport shirt,
jeans and a gimme hat. He didn't want to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, I'd rather not. My wife's a teacher,'' he
said. ``As it is now, before I can watch the Super Bowl, I have to
pass a geography test.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column on Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
