<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bastrop untucked: It isn't heat they're packing underneath
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's fitting that school officials in this small
town 30 miles east of Austin have decided to let the high school
students wear some shirts untucked to school.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning on Main Street here, about half the adults I
saw were walking around with their shirts hanging out. So by going
to school with untucked shirts, the students are conforming to the
community standard, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I do: I leave mine out to cover the fat,''
said retired Navy Capt. Bill Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell didn't have on a pair of those extremely baggy britches
the kids favor these days. You know the ones I'm talking about.
They look like they're fixing to fall off. But he was wearing an
untucked T-shirt that sported a cow skull and an armadillo wearing
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in high school you would have been tossed out of
algebra for wearing a shirt like that.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, more than 100 students walked out of Bastrop
High during classes to protest the dress code rule that outlawed
all untucked shirts. The fear of concealed weapons was one factor
behind the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, school officials have decided students can wear
untucked shirts to school, as long as the shirt is meant to be
untucked and doesn't hang down beyond the kid's fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy is good, if you believe what's good for the goose
