<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOM-TVREVIEW22-COX     09-21 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOM-TVREVIEW22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's doubtful bland 'Bloom' will blossom
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This guy, Conrad Bloom, has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   You see, there are too many women in his life. But none of 'em
are Ms. Right. And since Conrad (Caroline in the City's Mark
Feuerstein), a budding ad exec, is such a swell guy, most of 'em
are just Ms. Pains-In-The-Rear. Let's see, there's Molly (Lauren
Graham), his needy best friend; Faye, his do-it-now boss (Paula
Newsome); Shelley (Jessica Stone), his harried co-worker; Nina
(Ever Carradine), his activist sister and Florie (Linda Lavin), his
flashy, widowed mom who talks to her dead husband.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad is so nice (he even has pictures of his friends and
family on his desk!), his women call him ``The Fixer.'' Conrad
breaks dates with hot babes to console a teary Molly. He
high-tails-it to jail to bail out his sister, who gets arrested
protecting animal rights and he even goes ballroom dancing with his
mom.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm . . . is The Single Guy back? You can't help but think of
that mediocre show when watching Conrad Bloom, yet another ho-hum
NBC comedy (Monday, 8:30 p.m.). And, speaking of NBC, someone needs
to send those programming geniuses a nasty letter saying America
doesn't need yet another white-bread, cookie-cutter sitcom set in a
New York office.
</P>
<P>
   Don't people live in, say, Detroit? Iowa City? Don't people,
like, work in factories? Post offices? Funeral homes?
</P>
<P>
   Now, Conrad is a likable fellow and Barney Miller's Steve
Landesberg is funny as a burned-out ad man, but that's not enough
to save this bland series. But since Conrad is so eager to please,
he probably won't care when he goes from being Mr. Nice Guy to Mr.
Unemployed Guy after this show is canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
