<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KSU-BISHOP22-COX     09-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSU-BISHOP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kansas State's Michael Bishop may not be piling up the numbers,
but he has the Wildcats on a roll
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There's no mystery surrounding Michael Bishop
these days. The Kansas State quarterback, who was forbidden by his
hyper-sensitive coach from talking to the media for a four-game
stretch in 1997, is now a bona fide Heisman Trophy candidate. For a
brief period each Tuesday and after games on Saturday, Bishop is
allowed to talk to any reporter who asks a question in person or by
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, his Wildcats have so overwhelmed their first two
opponents, outscoring Indiana State and Northern Illinois by a
combined 139-7, 97-7 by halftime, that his teammates have left
Bishop little playing time to pad his statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Heisman candidates need stats that fans can dissect each week.
And Bishop's are not Tim Couch-type numbers. While the Kentucky
quarterback, another top Heisman contender, has thrown for 12
touchdowns, Bishop has three. He has completed 12 of 24 passes for
279 yards and has gained 71 yards on 15 carries, playing about a
half each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too worried about any stats,'' Bishop said earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   He's probably not too worried about the University of Texas
defense he'll face today in Manhattan. The Longhorns have allowed
533.5 yards a game this season, 222 on the ground and 311.5 through
the air. UT did little to control the New Mexico State option in
the second half of its season opener and then boosted UCLA's
hard-throwing quarterback Cade McNown to near the top of the
Heisman heap in a recent game in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is no McNown, who has an endless supply of towering
receivers at his disposal. But McNown, or any other quarterback
besides Syracuse's Donovan McNabb, would be jealous of Bishop's
footspeed. Toss in the facts that Bishop once threw a ball 93 yards
in practice and has lost only one game in his college career, and
you have all the reasons why this native Texan is the most
dangerous offensive player in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can beat you in so many ways,'' said UT Coach Mack Brown.
``He can beat you with his arm. He can beat you with his speed.
He's a running back, he's a quarterback. Kansas State can throw it,
they can out-power you, they can beat you with the option. As a
defense, you've got to figure out what's your best medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown estimated that Bishop, on film, looks like he can run
about a 4.2-second 40-yard dash. Most scouting reports list the
6-foot-1, 205-pound senior at about 4.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's obvious he can run,'' Brown said. ``Let's just say
that every time I've seen him run, no one's catching him. He's
faster than those chasing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Reese, UT's defensive coordinator, said he could use one
player to spy on or ``shadow'' Bishop on every play. ``Then he
could beat that guy, one on one,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely feature him in their offense,'' he said. ``And
they've designed it for him. I think they're about 50-50 run, pass.
They've been pretty basic in their plays. I have seen games where
they have him throw the football. I hope we can get him in
situations like that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bishop's academic situation had been different in high
school, he likely would be playing for the Longhorns today. He grew
up a Texas fan, and he attended two summer camps conducted by
former Coach John Mackovic and his staff. But Bishop did not have
enough core classes from Willis High School to qualify academically
for a Division I scholarship, which is why he ended up at Blinn
Community College in Brenham.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop led Blinn to consecutive junior college national
championships, but he transferred to Independence (Kansas)
Community College in January 1997 so he could earn an associate's
degree _ which he needed to play for a Division I school _ without
having to pass the Texas Assessment of Skills Program (TASP) test
necessary to transfer to a public college or university in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mackovic looked at signing Bishop, but decided against it
because Bishop was unable to attend spring drills (Bishop didn't
graduate from Independence until August 1997) and UT already had
James Brown as its starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop ruled out Texas because he wanted to play for a school
where he could immediately start. He was interested in Baylor for a
short period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I could play quarterback,'' he said. ``But then I
heard rumors they wanted to change my position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop has been a perfect fit for Kansas State, a traditional
safe haven for junior college players. Bishop, in rolling up 2,123
total yards last season, led the Wildcats to a program-best 11-1
record and a Fiesta Bowl victory, where he earned offensive most
valuable player honors with 317 passing yards and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a talented young man,'' understated Kansas State
Coach Bill Snyder. ``He passes and runs equally well. Most people
accuse him of just being a runner. I take issue with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
