r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYPERION-TVREVIEW22-C     09-21 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYPERION-TVREVIEW22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming-home drama is the 'bay' to watch
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably won't read this anywhere else: Hyperion Bay
(Monday, 9 p.m.) is the WB's best _ and most intelligent _ new
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Period.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we've heard about Felicity, the network's other
angst-ridden drama that's getting more buzz than Kenneth Starr's
lurid report. But we still say Hyperion Bay is the better show . .
. mainly because it's not solely targeted for the Clearsil set.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is hardly original. But what is in Hollywood? Dennis
Sweeny (Saved By The Bell's Mark-Paul Gosselaar) is a former high
school geek-turned-corporate big shot who returns to his sleepy
hometown to run a new software division _ and exorcise old family
demons. Things are especially tense with big bro Nick (Dawson's
Creek's Dylan Neal), who's not too happy to see his little bro.
</P>
<P>
   Little bro, you see, is no longer the punching bag misfit he
used to be. He drives a sleek, steel gray Mercedes convertible, has
a head-turning girlfriend (The Thorn Bird's va-va-va-voomy Sydney
Penny) and knows how to stare down penny-pinching city bureaucrats
with the best of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   As his Bill Gates-like boss tells Dennis, ``We didn't fit into
their America, but that's all gone. We're in charge (and) they're
scrambling to fit in with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion Bay is a nuanced and thought-provoking drama. What a
treat hearing twentysomething kids actually talking like they're,
well, twentysomething kids and not worldly 40-year-old former psych
majors.
</P>
<P>
   The juicy drama is also set up beautifully with all the
wonderfully rich characters and relationships. There is the tension
between Nick and Dennis, the unhappy marriage between Nick and Amy
(Christina Moore), the unrequited love between Dennis and old high
school cutie Trudy (Cassidy Rae) and Dennis' stiff-as-a-steel plate
relationship with his dad (Raymond J. Barry).
</P>
<P>
   It all makes for an intoxicating mix _ one we won't mind tuning
in each week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
