<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-BYNUM22-COX     09-21 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-BYNUM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aggies kicker vying for spot
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They weren't long, as field goals go, but in
Russell Bynum's eyes they were big.
</P>
<P>
   Bynum is one of three candidates being scrutinized to replace
departed Kyle Bryant as place-kicker at Texas A&AMP;M, a task that
Coach R. C. Slocum had identified in the spring as the Aggies' most
pressing priority entering the fall. Two games into the season,
though, the situation remains unsettled. But Bynum's field goals of
19 and 23 yards recently in A&AMP;M's 28-7 victory over Louisiana Tech
have left him feeling better about himself.
</P>
<P>
   And, he hopes, it has the Aggies feeling better about him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the team wants me to prove something to them,'' said
Bynum, a third-year walk-on sophomore from La Marque. ``I feel the
coaches want me to show them something. Everyone wants me to prove
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip-shot field goals, even on a wet field with a water-soaked
ball, aren't enough proof for the Aggies, however. So the
competition continues between Bynum, fellow sophomore walk-on
Terence Kitchens and junior punter Shane Lechler. And the sense of
urgency to find Bryant's successor continues to build because the
Aggies know how invaluable a reliable kicker can be, and how costly
not having one can become.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a concern,'' acknowledged special teams coach Tam
Hollingshead. ``This is a situation we aren't used to. We got
spoiled with Kyle Bryant.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, A&AMP;M, which faces a tough intersectional contest today at
Southern Mississippi, has not been accustomed to uncertainty with
its placekickers in recent years. Bryant left as the school's
record holder in field goals made (60), extra points made (145 of
152), scoring (325 points) and field goal accuracy (70.6 percent).
Before him, Terry Venetoulias held the job from 1991-'93.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the job remains up for grabs, Bynum's two recent
field goals notwithstanding. While Lechler has the strongest leg of
the three _ a 51-yarder against Louisiana Tech hooked to the left _
nobody has asserted himself enough to be handed the position
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd envisioned was being settled on a kicker after the
spring _ it didn't happen,'' Slocum said. ``If I felt it was
settled, I'd have put one of those guys (Bynum or Kitchens) on
scholarship, but I won't give a de facto scholarship. I'll save it
and go recruit a kicker out of high school if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bynum, whose 37 field goals at La Marque eclipsed the state high
school record of 30 set by Bryant while he was at A&AMP;M Consolidated,
said his range is up to 55 yards, depending on the conditions.
Hollingsworth said he feels comfortable with both Bynum and
Kitchens up to about 45 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bynum said he received several scholarships from Div. II
schools, but chose A&AMP;M's offer to walk on because of the quality of
both the competition and the education.
</P>
<P>
   While Bynum says, ``I feel accepted by the team now. If they
send me in there, they must have faith in me,'' he conceded it's
not a complete faith _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll take time, mainly, until they realize they have enough
faith in me to send me out there without thinking about it,'' he
said. ``I want them to think that when I go out there, 'He's going
to make this. It's automatic.' But I can't afford to look ahead
like that. All I'm focusing on is the next kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
