r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONKEYS-STOLEN22-COX     09-21 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONKEYS-STOLEN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tamarin taken from zoo might be in danger
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Florida _ A small, 5-month-old, monkey-like
creature with Albert Einstein hair and a chocolate-colored tail is
missing after he and three siblings were stolen from the Palm Beach
Zoo at Dreher Park recently.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the cotton-top tamarins, endangered primates from the
rain forests of Colombia, escaped from the thief or thieves. They
were found later hiding in a bamboo tree near zoo property on
Summit Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said the young primate may not survive long
without a special protein-enhanced diet and the companionship of
his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a strong social bond with their parents,'' said
associate zoo curator Randi Meyerson-McCormick. ``A 5-month-old by
himself in a strange place and an odd diet will be very distressed.
They can get depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous zoo volunteer has offered a $5,000 reward for the
safe return of the animal.
</P>
<P>
   The four juveniles and their parents are part of a worldwide
breeding program to repopulate their rain forest habitat.
</P>
<P>
   The cotton-top tamarins are beginning to become more popular in
the pet trade, but the thief may just have stolen them because
they're cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a concrete motive,'' said West Palm Beach police
spokeswoman Dena Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials couldn't estimate what the tamarin might be worth.
</P>
<P>
   The thief cut the lock on the wire exhibit cage and took the
rectangular nest box that the six tamarins huddle in at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect whoever took the babies may be scratched and bitten
because the fathers are very protective,'' McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   As Detective H.S. Sutton retraced the likely path of the thief,
McCormick heard the distinctive trill of the young tamarins and
found the three in the bamboo tree.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials speculate the thief may have put down the nest box
momentarily, allowing the primates to escape.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the parent tamarins, the trio was coaxed from
the tree.
</P>
<P>
   The theft was the first since 1993, when two golden lion
tamarins and a kinkajou were stolen. The tamarins were recovered.
The kinkajou was beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo erected a 10-foot fence arond the 22-acre property that
year, and guards are on the grounds 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that people are its No. 1 predator,'' said zoo
Executive Director Craig Pugh.
</P>
<P>
   Possession of the tamarins without a permit can result in a
maximum $50,000 fine, a year in jail or both. Anyone with
information should call the West Palm Beach, Florida, police at
(561) 653-3400cq or the Tip Line at (561) 653-3480.cq
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
