<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROTESTOR-KILLED22-CO     09-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTOR-KILLED22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Austinite killed on redwood protest
 &HT;    By John Henrichs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ David Chain would spend his evenings talking
with friends and co-workers about his love of the redwood forests
of Northern California. He would spend his days working to get back
there.
</P>
<P>
   Chain's passion for ``those big, fat trees'' inspired three of
his co-workers at Trudy's North Star restaurant in Austin to follow
him to California two weeks ago to fight to save the redwoods from
loggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so adamant about it. He was very driven, inspired,''
said Gabriel Deutsch, one of Chain's co-workers at the Trudy's,
8800 Burnet Road. ``People in the bar would stop (what they were
doing) and listen to him. We came up here because of his words.''
</P>
<P>
   Chain was killed recently, crushed by a falling redwood as he
and other protesters tried to dissuade loggers with Pacific Lumber
Co. from felling trees at a remote site in Northern California.
Authorities say Chain's death was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Chain was one of four Austinites who went to California to work
with Earth First, an environmental group known for direct action
tactics such as chaining themselves to trees and driving metal
spikes into trees to impede logging.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Chain lived in Austin about a year, his friends
said. Chain's identification had an address from Coldspring, north
of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Chain and his friends were taking part in a 12-day protest
against the logging of an ancient redwood stand along Grizzly
Creek, near the mill town of Fortuna about 300 miles north of San
Francisco. Eight protesters had been arrested Wednesday on
trespassing charges for blocking logging trucks in the area.
Thursday the group engaged in the more aggressive tactic they call
``cat and mouse,'' putting their bodies in front of trees scheduled
to be cut down. Earth First members say the tactic allows dialogue
with the tree fellers.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Garner, one of the Earth First protesters from Austin,
said Chain knew that what he was doing was dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they go up there, they all know what they getting into,''
she said. ``There's a risk of getting arrested, beaten up, falling.
The people involved are willing to give up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chain's death was the first in a decade of mostly peaceful
protests by Earth First against logging, said Gary Philp, chief
deputy with the Humboldt County Sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Philp said the incident appeared to be an accident but his
office is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, president of Pacific Lumber Co., said the logging
crew did not see anyone in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felled a tree and apparently heard some yelling, and then
the feller was cutting the tree into segments when the body was
found under a limb,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Earth First members said they have a videotape of Thursday's
confrontation that will show the loggers knew they were in the path
of the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have been battling for more than a decade in
the great coastal forests of California, home to the cathedral
groves of redwood trees as old as 1,000 years and towering as tall
as a 30-story building. But the Earth Firsters believe in direct
action. They try to stop timber companies from harvesting lumber on
private land _ arguing that the ancient trees are too precious to
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Garner said nature, especially the redwood forests, played an
important role in Chain's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was planning to stay in California for a while, live on the
land,'' Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would count down the days until he could go back. This was
his life,'' Deutsch said. ``I don't think he would have ever done
anything else if he had a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press and The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
