</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTBALLMOMS-ARRESTED22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bogus bill beleaguers softball team
 &HT;    By Seth Mnookin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Vipers made it to the National Softball Association
Fast-Pitch World Series in Stuart this July, it was supposed to be
the pinnacle of their year. This was why the 10-years-and-under
Palm Beach County, Florida, girls' team had endured the months of
practice and 12-hour days on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, within two days of the tournament's opening ceremony on
July 27, two mothers had been arrested for passing a counterfeit
$20 at a concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Zerilli, 33, and Georgina Hill, 31, both of Lake Worth,
are facing felony charges in the case, which is being investigated
by the Secret Service and Stuart police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terrible end to a terrific season,'' said former
Viper assistant coach Jim Skidmore, who resigned from the team
after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the situation has only deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, Brittany Shersty, the Vipers' catcher and the
daughter of Delray Beach police officer Paul Shersty _ who had
alerted tournament officials to the counterfeit bill _ was told she
wouldn't be welcome back when the Vipers suit up next year. That
decision was partially because of Paul Shersty's role as
whistleblower, according to Vipers coach George Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, Zerilli asked Jennifer Shersty, Brittany's
13-year-old sister, to cash what she admits was a bogus $20, police
reports said. Zerilli, who said she received the bill from a Sears
in Boynton Beach two days earlier, had tried to cash the $20 at a
Wendy's and had been told it was counterfeit. After Zerilli learned
that the bill was fake, she did not destroy the bill or alert
authorities as required by law, reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer, being the daughter of a cop, said she'd rather not
pass the bill. But Georgina Hill, the mother of another Vipers
player, took the bill and, according to the report, said, ``I can
get rid of that for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill bought a couple of sodas from a concession stand _ which
was being operated by kids from the tournament to raise money for
expenses _ and returned with $18 in change.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hill nor Zerilli, who were arrested July 29 on charges
of uttering a forged bill, would comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer told her father what had happened. Paul Shersty
returned to the concession stand the next day and told them about
the funny money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had already discovered the fake bill,'' Shersty said.
``They were just totally shocked that a parent of one of the kids
would have knowingly done this. And I was enraged that some parent
asked my daughter to cash this bill. That's contributing to the
delinquency of a minor.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, NSA officials were considering ejecting the Vipers
from the tournament, according to Shersty. Instead, Vipers coach
George Ortiz decided to get rid of 10-year-old Brittany.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz insists it is not only Shersty's commitment to upholding
the law that got his daughter thrown off the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sure had something to do with it,'' Ortiz said. ``And
maybe that doesn't set the best example for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``But her mother was real obnoxious all year,'' he said,
referring to Debbie Shersty. ``And I just wasn't going to put up
with it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore, who was not invited to a team meeting in August about
the situation, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we kicked off every kid who had a parent that had been
complained about, there wouldn't be anyone left on the team,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Stuart police department sent Jennifer Shersty a letter
of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me that some of the parents think we did
something wrong,'' Shersty said. ``Brittany was up crying all night
when she got asked to leave the team. She's been playing softball
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I know that my two girls have more ethics than most
of the parents on that team,'' Shersty said. It's just sad that my
daughter has become a scapegoat. She's an innocent victim in all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
