<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CARREG22-COX     09-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CARREG22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some not getting auto tag notices
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lester Sanders glanced at his car windshield and
had one of those moments that make a man groan out loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in traffic and just happened to cast a look at
my registration (sticker),'' he said. ``And I realized, my
goodness, this thing has expired.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that for the third year in a row, he had not
received a car registration renewal notice from the Texas
Department of Transportation. This year he has plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   The Travis County, Texas, tax assessor's office, which collects
vehicle registration fees for the state, says as many as 30,000
drivers have not received the renewal notices since 1997. The
county blames the problem on a new Texas Department of
Transportation computer network.
</P>
<P>
   The tax office says 900 to 1,300 people a month have called to
complain they didn't get the renewal notices.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints have been steady since last November, when the
county switched to the state Transportation Department's computer
system, Tax Assessor-Collector Nelda Wells Spears said. Travis
County, one of the last to switch to the new state system,
previously recorded completed registration renewals on its own
computer, which officials say was more advanced than the state's.
Registrations are updated on the new network as they expire, so it
takes a year's cycle to process everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to really start to watch that windshield sticker
for the month of inspection,'' Wells Spears said.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening can be attributed to simple growing pains as
the Transportation Department tries to improve its way of recording
and updating vehicle registration data, said Bob Tanner, the
department's director of technical operations in registration and
titling. The new statewide computer network has been implemented in
steps, starting with Williamson County in 1994. Every county has
experienced what Travis County is going through, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, about 25 percent of Travis County's 500,000 vehicle
registrations were incorrectly listed in the Transportation
Department database, Tanner said. Many mistakes were caught before
the notices were mailed, but other notices were sent to the wrong
addresses. The department's database had information that was as
much as five months old before the new computer system was
launched. When the Transportation Department's new computer network
is finished _ next August _ there should be just a 5 percent error
rate for Travis County, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flaws were just magnifying,'' Tanner said. ``There were
more inaccuracies this year than the year before.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who didn't get a renewal notice cannot use that as an
excuse if they are ticketed, however. State and county officials
say vehicle owners must remember when to renew, and they note that
the registration stickers are in plain view on car windshields.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for having an expired sticker are $85 in Travis County,
but if a driver renews his registration within 10 working days and
brings that receipt to municipal court, the fine is reduced to $10.
</P>
<P>
   Missing notices aren't creating more tickets for driving with an
expired registration. The Texas Department of Public Safety has
issued about 9,000 fewer expired registration tickets statewide
this year than last.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle registration revenues have consistently increased, but
state officials do not know if that is because of population growth
or the improved computer network, said Darrel Hunt with the state
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
