<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SODOMY22-COX     09-21 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SODOMY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school assault troubles Texas town
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THORNDALE, Texas _ Behind the angst is the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Prank? Hazing? Sodomy?
</P>
<P>
   At least five people know what happened on an October morning
last year in the high school weight room when four freshmen
football players struggled with another kid. Most people do not
question that something wrong happened _ an assault that violated
privacy, at least _ yet no one but the kids involved knows whether
a plastic bottle was forced where nothing plastic belongs outside a
doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened, allegations flew that the football-crazy town
of Thorndale, Texas, 30 miles southwest of Austin, protected the
ball players involved by covering up the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened in this proud German-Czech farming community
of three state champion Class A football teams and one in baseball
in the last decade, residents believe the mystery ultimately
affects them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something happened,'' says Thorndale school board head Anita
Kasner, ``and then everyone added to it and blew it out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Floyd Zuehlke doubts the worst. But if that's
what happened, he says, ``then these kids should be prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milam Count, Texas, prosecutor last month filed juvenile
charges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   And the town's angst began anew.
</P>
<P>
   To understand some of Thorndale's collective anger, talk with
the new school superintendent, Wayne Calhoun. An outsider in this
close-knit community, Calhoun found himself after three months on
the job embroiled in what he calls a potentially career-busting
controversy. The school district's investigation was not his to
conduct, to be sure _ he was superintendent last year in Rising
Star, near Abilene _ but the investigation has been his to defend
since the allegations blew up again in August.
</P>
<P>
   First came Austin TV news, then aggravating that, Calhoun says,
an Austin radio station talk show highlighted the alleged cover-up
and invited callers to join with their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   One said the kids should be thrown into prison, to be raped
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in Thorndale was characterized as something out of
'Deliverance,' ``Calhoun says.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Milam County prosecutor, Hollis Lewis Jr., in a
hearing earlier this month, accusing the school district of a
cover-up that hindered his own investigation and led to the
10-month delay.
</P>
<P>
   Those allegations are not fair, Calhoun says. The school
district's investigation was good, he says: ``If I were studying
this in grad school, this would have been an ideal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun will not discuss it beyond that. But what irritates him
and others about the cover-up allegation is that everyone in town
knows that the kids involved were removed from regular school
classes and barred from all sports and extracurricular activities.
Calhoun says the district's interim superintendent briefed him on
the case once he took the job last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in case,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Barely inside Milam County, east of the Williamson County line,
Thorndale straddles U.S. 79 and the Union Pacific tracks that
parallel it. The cotton and corn country surrounding this town of
about 1,200 sweeps level from the Balcones highlands, beginning the
great Blackland Prairie that introduces Texas to the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Farming built Thorndale, but these days much of the town makes a
living at the Rockdale Alcoa aluminum plant.
</P>
<P>
   Few are rich or poor in this town.
</P>
<P>
   Thorndale's German heritage can be traced in a Lutheran
population so strong it supports a hundred-year-old church school
with 120 students at the west edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   Along Main Street's block-long business district south of the
tracks, many of the sand-colored or whitewashed brick storefronts
sit empty, losers to the Wal-Marts in Taylor and Rockdale, each 13
miles away, and to the malls in Austin twice as far.
</P>
<P>
   A bank brings life to the middle of one side of the street,
together with Butts Dry Goods on one side and the century-old
weekly Thorndale Champion newspaper on the other. Compared with
many Texas towns of its size, robbed of all but convenience stores,
Thorndale appears _ as with its football legacy _ hardy and
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Even before townspeople split over what happened in the high
school weight room _ whether it was prank or worse _ many were
divided over a proposal to disband the two-person police
department.
</P>
<P>
   An Austin TV news crew rolled into town for the fight. Once
there, they found out about the weight room mystery.
</P>
<P>
   And that charges had never been brought in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The TV reports apparently prompted an Austin radio station talk
show that enticed listeners with the story of a school cover-up
protecting football players in football-mad Thorndale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got PR that we did not deserve,'' says Kasner, the school
board chairwoman. ``There is a question of whether the worst
actually happened or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly covering up the incident, Kasner says, the school
district investigated it, brought in the police and ended up
referring the four kids accused in the attack to a separate
classroom away from the high school for the rest of the semester
and banned them from school sports for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The radio station in Austin just actually tore us up,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
