<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5812 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THORNDALE-TRIAL22-COX     09-21 2143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THORNDALE-TRIAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conflict between officials marring already-controversial trial
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMERON, Texas _ When four Thorndale, Texas, youths go on trial
on charges of sexually assaulting a classmate, there will be more
than the usual adversarial tension in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney who is prosecuting the case and the judge
who is presiding are locked in a remarkably public and bitter
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Far beyond the normal courthouse bickering or small-town
squabbling, the battle over the courts of Milam County, Texas, has
itself wound up in court _ three lawsuits have been filed trying to
have County and District Attorney Hollis Lewis Jr. forcibly removed
from office. Some of the ammunition in those suits came in the form
of court findings by state District Judge Charles Lance and another
judge that said Lewis had suborned perjury, lied to a judge and
committed other wrongs. Lewis denies those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Lance would not comment for this story, but had said in court
findings that Lewis committed misconduct in the courtroom. Lewis
said that Lance, the juvenile probation department and the
sheriff's department have each interfered with his investigations
and unfairly criticized his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is made all the more pointed by the fact that the two
men are old friends who trained together in the Army Reserves
before Lance, a former district attorney himself, persuaded Lewis
to move to Milam County and run for district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But Milam County's hostility encompasses more than these two.
The juvenile probation office, where Lewis' wife worked before she
was firedlast year, is lined up against the district attorney, as
are some at the sheriff's office, where disagreements over cases
have led to muted antagonism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally (the hostility) would be a very big surprise because
each party has a vested interest in seeing that a case moves
along,'' said Jan A. Behr, who preceded Lewis as county attorney.
``But in Milam County things aren't necessarily normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Behr said he has reason to be wary about the politics in Milam
County. He said Lance ran him out of the county.
</P>
<P>
   In Milam County, an isolated pocket of Central Texas that is
just outside the notice of most Austinites, the 25,000 residents
usually enjoy a quiet lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The community's dramas are usually insulated from outsiders. But
charges of sexual assault against four high school students have
thrust the community into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The months-old battle between Lewis and other county officials
went public in June, partly because of the Thorndale allegations.
Eight months had passed since the incident that prompted the
allegations occurred, and Lewis had not decided whether to proceed
to trial or drop the case. By then, the probation office and Lance
were saying they were dissatisfied with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Debra M. Dillenberger, chief juvenile probation officer, wrote
Lewis that month, saying that he could drop the case or refer it
back to juvenile investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I would strongly disagree with either of these
actions, they are available to you,'' Dillenberger wrote. ``What
the statutes do not permit is interminable delay.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, her chief assistant, Pete Ortega, filed a removal
suit against Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The suit presents a list of alleged misconduct by Lewis,
including delays in the handling of 31 juvenile cases and ``failure
to diligently prosecute'' five other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also cites the two court findings against Lewis, one by
Lance and another by District Judge Robert Stem, of neighboring
Falls County.
</P>
<P>
   Lance had found on June 8 that Lewis tried to have an aggravated
sexual assault of a child case dismissed ``based upon a reason that
he knew to be false.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stem found that Lewis violated the defendants' rights
in an assault case by ``intentionally and deliberately suborning
perjury,'' withholding evidence that would help the defense and
withholding the criminal histories of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after Ortega's removal suit, Lewis filed the
Thorndale charges. He said the delay in the case was caused by a
sloppy investigation by the probation office and a cover-up by
Thorndale school officials. His grand jury investigation found
allegations of an attempted sexual assault against a second
student, which was not found in the probation department's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney contends that he's understaffed and being
run out of the county on trumped-up charges. Lewis said the Ortega
suit questions his judgment but doesn't point to misconduct worthy
of removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at their allegations and you look at all the other
cases they're saying haven't been handled properly, many of those
have been disposed of and people are on probation,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the judges' findings, Lewis says they are either untrue or
exaggerate what most lawyers would consider small differences in
interpreting the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know a judge can say anything he wants, and I'm ready to
go into court in front a of a jury and let a jury of citizens with
good common sense look at the facts,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing specifics of what he said was interference by other
agencies, Lewis said the sheriff's department has withheld
information about investigations, including he case that led to the
charge of suborning perjury in Stem's finding. In court documents
in that case, he said the defendants were friends of top
investigators at the sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, juvenile probation officers have shared
information with defense attorneys instead of prosecutors, Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the removal suit filed by Ortega _ the official who had
fired Lewis' wife from her seven-year job with juvenile probation _
two other removal suits were filed in June by a husband and wife
who were defendants in an assault trial that led to Stem's finding.
</P>
<P>
   State law required Milam County commissioners to appoint a
county attorney from an adjacent county to investigate the removal
cases. But the removal cases seem to be something of a hot potato:
After inquiring with county attorneys' offices from all six
neighboring counties, commissioners appointed Williamson County
Attorney Gene Taylor. With Taylor, the removal suits have
themselves run into another prosecutor's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Busy with a removal suit against a constable in his own county,
Taylor said he is reluctant to prosecute a fellow prosecutor and
has his own caseload to worry about. Taylor said some justice seems
to move slowly in Milam County, but added, ``It's real easy for
some department to say: `We're doing our job, you're not doing
yours, go do your job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Toni Chew returned to her home just outside Cameron one
Sunday afternoon, she saw trash hanging out of a window. Tables
were overturned and destroyed. Only shards were left of five
stained glass windows. Water covered the floor because someone had
broken water pipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a piano so smashed you couldn't recognize it was a
piano,'' Chew said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Fred Lundgren, had recently been divorced
and vacated the house on County Road 203 where they had lived for
10 years. Lundgren had moved to the Houston area; Chew and her
17-year-old daughter were moving to an apartment in Cameron. For a
few days after the incident, she feared for her safety and
considered having her daughter stay with relatives in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Then investigators told her who had confessed to the crime:
three of her son's teammates from the high school football team and
a fourth boy, a basketball teammate who is related to a public
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a shock,'' Chew said. ``One of the boys had dated
my daughter; one my son had tutored. They weren't strangers by any
means.''
</P>
<P>
   The house was almost totaled _ damage was at least $67,000. And
when Lewis decided to reduce the charge to a misdemeanor, it
epitomized the conflicts over Lewis's exercise of discretion and
the ongoing power struggle in Milam County.
</P>
<P>
   There are other examples of Lewis' exercise of prosecutorial
discretion, on both sides of the tough-on-crime coin. Some of the
animosity between Lewis and the sheriff's office stems from the
time Lewis tried to have a sheriff's deputy indicted for an assault
charge, and another time when he pursued a case of an aggravated
assault with a deadly weapon that he said the sheriff's department
wanted him to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is the theft of as much as $20,000 in
merchandise from a local department store that led only to a
misdemeanor charge. The defendant in that case is the daughter of
Lewis' secretary. Lance, apparently convinced that the woman should
have been charged with a felony, wrote on a docket sheet that the
misdemeanor charge was ``clearly wrong.'' But the grand jury,
having heard evidence presented by Lewis, returned the lesser
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he decided to prosecute the case despite the fact
that investigators with the store said they were satisfied that the
woman had paid restitution. He also said the grand jury made an
independent decision. The misdemeanor charge is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   In the destruction of Chew's house, Lewis agreed to a plea
bargain for a misdemeanor conviction, 200 hours of community
service and restitution.
</P>
<P>
   But before the deal was finalized, Lance told the local media he
was ``incensed'' and ordered a grand jury to investigate whether to
return felony indictment. After hearing evidence, the grand jury
indicted the crimes as misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis defended the plea bargain, saying, ``If I had gotten them
on a felony, they would never get into the Army'' and would have
had trouble getting into college. He also said the young men were
contrite, had no previous trouble with the law and agreed to make
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Discretion on how to prosecute such cases is one of the
prerogatives of being a prosecutor, Lewis said. ``I can give a
break to someone who deserves a break,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lundgren said he did not want the teen-agers to get a felony
conviction, and said he was more or less satisfied with the
outcome: $25,000 in restitution and $42,000 from his insurance
company, which was also compensated by the boys' families.
</P>
<P>
   Chew was not satisfied. She wanted to take the case to trial and
let a judge and jury decide on the appropriate penalty. ``His
decision was arbitrary. It was capricious.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' exercise of discretion in another case was credited by
one young man with saving his career.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Foster and three other teens stole four cases of beer
from the Cameron Country Club five years ago. Because the boys, who
had just finished their junior year of high school with no criminal
history, confessed to the crime and agreed to perform community
service, Lewis dropped the charges on the condition that they serve
one year of probation and graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, 22, works for an oil field company in Alvin. The other
boys involved in the crime graduated and either work, serve in the
military or attend college, Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fair man _ as fair as I've ever known,'' Foster said of
Lewis. ``He doesn't (make plea bargains) just for certain people,
because my family's not anybody important in Cameron.''
</P>
<P>
   The child of an itinerant military family, Lewis met Lance in
the late 1980s when they were in the same Army reserve unit. Lewis
was practicing law in Bell County and Lance invited him to take
cases in Milam County.
</P>
<P>
   Lance had practiced law with attorney Mark Humble in Cameron,
and for about three years in the early 1980s worked as an assistant
district attorney when Humble was district attorney. Lance himself
was district attorney for four years until 1988, when he was
elected judge for the 20th Judicial District, which covers Milam
County.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, Lance encouraged his lawyer friend to move to Milam
County and run for district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the scenario has a familiar ring.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' predecessor, Behr, said he too moved from Bell to Milam
County at the behest of Lance. And, Behr said, he and Lance
disagreed on how some cases were handled, as well as whether Behr
should keep the same secretary Lance employed in the district
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   And, Behr said, Lance threatened to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he wanted to keep control of the office,''
Behr said. With the recent death of his wife still fresh in his
mind and an offer to work with a friend in Fort Worth, Behr said he
was ready in 1990 to comply with what he said were the judge's
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel forced to leave when a judge says he's going to
remove you from office,'' Behr said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
