<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5813 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-DRUGCRIME22-C     09-21 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-DRUGCRIME22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher, student become partners in crime
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Their friendship began about 15 years
ago at Florida's John I. Leonard High School. One was a shop
teacher, the other his student. Both would go on to bigger things.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, John George, started a construction business and
became one of the largest home builders in western Palm Beach
County, Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His pupil, David Combs, became one of the county's largest
marijuana dealers. He was recently shipped off to federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives seem strikingly divergent, but they remain
intertwined. From 1995 to 1997, George and his company, Majestic
Custom Homes, helped Combs build and sell 38 houses on vacant lots
around Loxahatchee _ some of which, prosecutors say, were used by
Combs to conceal the money he made in the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Combs, 33, of Loxahatchee, pleaded guilty in January to federal
charges of money laundering by using his drug profits to buy three
vacant lots near Royal Palm Beach. Those lots and a fourth, all of
which had houses built on them under George's contracting license,
have been seized by federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Combs, who also pleaded guilty to marijuana
trafficking, bought real estate to conceal $750,000 in marijuana
proceeds from 1991 to 1996. He was a link in a chain that brought
more than 8,500 pounds of pot into the county and has so far netted
10 arrests by federal and local agents.
</P>
<P>
   Over those same years, Combs bought and sold at least 70
properties in the county, most of them vacant lots in the western
areas, property records show.
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners said they found their houses through Majestic's
realty office. Others said they didn't meet Combs until the closing
on their houses _ all of them three-bedroom, usually with white
paint and gray trim. They typically sold for about $90,000; Combs
bought the 1-acre lots at anywhere from $400 to $22,000, property
records show. subhead
</P>
<P>
   George, 47, and Combs met at John I. Leonard High School in Lake
Worth, where Combs was a student (he graduated in 1983) and George
taught shop and construction. Combs' lawyer, Jeffrey Miller, said
George took on the role of mentor for Combs.
</P>
<P>
   ``David didn't have an easy childhood,'' Miller said. ``John
George was his surrogate big brother, parent, confidant, friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is an anomaly. He led a double life. He worked very hard
and diligently and was a very successful builder. He did not have
to be in the drug business, and that was the shame of it.''
</P>
<P>
   George left the school district in 1984 after 10 years of
teaching. Months later, he started his development company.
</P>
<P>
   George received his first permit to build a house in the county
in 1985, building records show. Since then he applied for permits
to build more than 1,000 homes _ 878 of them since 1993, records
show.
</P>
<P>
   George has said his company plans to build about 125 houses a
year. In a deposition for a lawsuit, he said his company owns about
50 acres of land for future home construction. In a separate court
hearing, he declared his company ``the biggest builder in the
western communities.''
</P>
<P>
   While Majestic was growing, Combs was aggressively purchasing
real estate. He often bought lots at foreclosure sales or through
tax deeds, buying the tax debt on a property then suing to claim
the land. He also bought many dilapidated properties and fixed them
up for resale, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Combs' legal troubles didn't come to light until November 1996,
when he was arrested trying to buy 305 pounds of marijuana from his
supplier, who had turned government informant, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Combs pleaded guilty to marijuana trafficking in April 1997 and
was sentenced to two years' probation. By then, the federal
money-laundering investigation was under way, and Combs was helping
authorities nab other local pot dealers, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't slow Combs' real estate ventures. According to
building records submitted by Combs, work on 24 of the 38 homes he
built with Majestic began after his arrest; of those, 16 were built
after he pleaded guilty. subhead
</P>
<P>
   George's lawyer, Brad Beilly, said George didn't know about
Combs' drug and money-laundering charges until he read about them
in a Palm Beach Post story two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Beilly said George withdrew his permits for homes on Combs'
property in September 1997, after Combs' activities fell under the
spotlight _ not for drugs, but for allegations of illegal dumping
on his lots. Combs was seen on television being led away in
handcuffs when sheriff's deputies searched his land.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mr. Combs' legal problems were reported, (George's
company) withdrew all of its permits, and Mr. Combs hired another
general contractor to complete construction,'' Beilly said. ``Since
that point in time Mr. George has had no relationship whatsoever
with Mr. Combs.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the illegal dumping charge, George sent a
letter to some of his customers saying his company was not
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Majestic was not implicated in the illegal dumping
investigation, said Deputy James Pearsall, who investigated the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Pearsall said he plans to ask the State Attorney's Office to
charge Combs with several counts of dumping debris on his sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some homeowners who bought from Combs, like Trish Siford, worry
that they have buried debris on their lots. Siford and her husband
had trouble sinking posts for a fence in their yard because of what
they thought were roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not roots after all; maybe it's the tree itself,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors made Combs pay for underground testing on
the four lots that were seized as part of his plea agreement. Combs
also had to test a handful of lots he sold before turning the money
over to the Internal Revenue Service. subhead
</P>
<P>
   In January, Combs was charged with money laundering; he pleaded
guilty days later. Federal prosecutors seized from Combs $750,000
in cash and property, equalling what they could prove he laundered.
On June 30, Combs began a three-year sentence at a federal prison
in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to his money-laundering charges, Combs
sold or transferred more than 20 properties from his name to his
companies or to friends, property records show. Among those
properties was a 45-acre tract on the Beeline Highway Combs
co-owned with Majestic.
</P>
<P>
   Combs and Majestic paid $100,000 in 1996 for the property, which
is zoned for industrial use. The former owner, Gene Melchiori, said
his father bought the land in the 1960s, but it was limited in its
use because it's largely wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we kind of gave it away. We were caught in a bad
position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, Combs sold his interest in the land for $10,000 to a
company called Wetlands Are Our Friends. State records show the
company was created just five days earlier by his defense lawyer,
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate papers filed with the secretary of state did not
disclose the shareholders of Wetlands Are Our Friends, and Miller
would not say for whom he established the company.
</P>
<P>
   Combs also transferred the deeds for 17 rental properties to a
company called D.C. Rentals of Palm Beach County. Joseph Melchiori,
Combs' friend and the son of Gene Melchiori, was named president of
the company in February, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Melchiori could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said many of his clients' real estate transactions were
legitimate, and federal investigators had free access to his real
estate holdings before deciding which properties to seize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few guys that are in the marijuana business go to the
lengths that David did to amass a real estate portfolio,'' said
Miller. ``He's made amends. David has given back the ill-gotten
gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Several homeowners interviewed for this story said they didn't
know about Combs' drug activities until they were told by a
reporter. Nevertheless, most of those interviewed found Combs
amiable and accessable, though some thought he used cheap material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no complaints about his homes,'' said Rita Wall, who
bought a house from Combs in 1996. ``I definitely would recommend
him.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researchers Lynne Palombo, Sammy Alzofon and Xiao Kai Chen
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
