<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPLANT-THERAPY22-COX     09-21 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPLANT-THERAPY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New treatment may help those with prostate cancer
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Charlie Hogg's prostate cancer didn't exactly go
away in one morning, leaving him the afternoon to play golf or go
fishing, as an overeager doctor might have promised. But with just
one treatment that kept the 65-year-old Austinite in the hospital
one night, his doctors think they have destroyed the tumors in his
prostate, leaving him cancer-free, perhaps for the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment, called seed implant therapy, offers a quicker,
more comfortable and less costly alternative to surgery or external
radiation for some prostate cancer patients, a major reason that
Hogg and about 80 others have chosen it since it became available
in Austin in November. It also shows future promise for treating
uterine and breast cancer in women .
</P>
<P>
   How does it work? Using as many as two dozen long needles,
doctors inject scores of radioactive seeds the size of pencil leads
into the patient's prostate. Over time, they emit enough energy to
destroy the cancerous cells. The procedure has been around since
the early 20th century, but only in the past 15 years have doctors
learned to use ultrasound to guide the seeds into place, making it
a viable treatment for some cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Seattle doctor who helped pioneer the technique
published the results of a 10-year study that showed seed therapy
to be as effective at keeping prostate cancer at bay as surgically
removing the entire prostate _ and more effective than treating it
with radiation from an outside source.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings were partially corroborated in a larger study at
Harvard Medical School. The results, published in the Journal of
the American Medical Association last week, showed that low-risk
prostate cancer patients who opted for seed implant therapy fared
as well as those who chose surgery or external radiation. However,
the seed treatment was found to be much less effective in patients
whose cancer had progressed to more dangerous levels and showed
signs of spreading outside the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, nearly 12,000 Texans will be diagnosed with prostate
cancer and another 2,500 will die of the disease. Nationwide, it is
the second-deadliest type of cancer in men, though it can be
treated effectively if detected early. In fact, treatments help 89
percent of men with prostate cancer survive for at least five
years.
</P>
<P>
   But treating prostate cancer can be a grueling, demoralizing
battle between a man and his body made confusing by the variety of
available treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery is still the surest way to beat back prostate cancer.
But because the prostate plays a key role in male sexual activity
as well as urination, removing it can result in lifelong impotence
and incontinence. Patients also require several weeks to recover
from the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Using beams of radiation from an outside source to destroy
cancer cells in the prostate is a less invasive but less effective
treatment. The radiation can injure other organs, and the rigorous
schedule of treatments _ five-times-a-week visits for six to seven
weeks _ can leave patients racked with fatigue and discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer side effects
</P>
<P>
   Because it is non-invasive and causes less damage to the
prostate and surrounding organs, seed therapy poses fewer of the
side effects of more conventional treatments. .
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two Austin radiation oncologists, Stephen Brown of
Seton's Shivers Cancer Center and Timothy Dziuk of the South Austin
Cancer Center, began thinking about bringing seed therapy to town,
knowing it would be an attractive alternative for some of their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Brown treated his first patient in November, and since then,
about 65 others have been given seed therapy at Shivers. Dziuk has
treated about 14 patients since March.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be easier on patients, seed therapy is not easy to
perform. It requires careful planning to map where the seeds should
go as well as expertise at reading ultrasounds. Brown insists that
a urologist be present whenever he performs the operation.
</P>
<P>
   As the seeds are implanted, the doctor carefully follows the
path of the needles on an ultrasound map of the prostate. To target
the cancerous cells, some areas of the gland will receive more
seeds than others. Dropping them in the correct positions requires
the precision of an expert pool player retracting the cue before
hitting the ball, and without a steady hand, the treatment cannot
be done right, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Precision is also one of the advantages of this technique. When
a patient undergoes external radiation, as much as 90 percent of
that radiation can escape and damage cells surrounding the
prostate, causing serious side effects. That exposure is limited to
about 2 percent with seed therapy, because the radiation is
contained in the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   Impotence still a risk
</P>
<P>
   But seed therapy does have byproducts. Impotence occurs in about
25 percent of patients with implants _ compared with 100 percent of
conventional surgery _ and others will experience problems with
urination. About half of patients will need external radiation to
supplement the work of the seeds .
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Haakon Ragde, the Seattle doctor, found that 64 percent of
his implant patients remained cancer-free after 10 years. His
study, published in the latest issue of the journal Cancer, cited
studies showing that surgical patients had a 10-year survival rate
of between 47 and 73 percent, and patients who underwent external
radiation treatments fared worse.
</P>
<P>
   Ragde's findings have not been universally endorsed by
oncologists, but Brown and Dziuk say the results for all three
procedures are comparable. The problem for implant patients is that
the data does not yet go beyond 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, proper selection of patients is key to the
treatment, doctors say. Not every patient is a good candidate, and
it is a mistake to offer it to those who are not.
</P>
<P>
   Seed therapy works best on patients who have detected their
cancer at an early stage and whose tumors are relatively small.
Hogg was a good candidate: his prostate-specific antigen (PSA), the
test that detects prostate cancer, registered at a safe level and
he was told that he could have deferred treatment for 10 years
before noticing any outward signs of prostate cancer. He decided to
go ahead with the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Seed therapy also may be more appropriate for older men for whom
the early evidence is comforting enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a young guy who wants to use (seed therapy), there has to
be a realization that the results are only 10 years old,'' Brown
says.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Mitchell's prostate tumor had grown to the size of a pea
and his PSA had climbed to 5.4 (anything lower than 4 is considered
healthy) when he agreed to the seed implants early this year.
Mitchell, 74, lives in Wimberley and liked the idea of a treatment
that wouldn't require repeated trips to his doctor in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a one-shot deal,'' says Mitchell, who
spent the night at St. David's Medical Center after the implants
were put in. He ultimately returned to Austin 23 times for external
radiation treatment to fill in spots the seeds had missed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Babaian, a urology professor and prostate cancer
specialist at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston, says patients
should not choose seed implant therapy over surgery or radiation
simply because it is more convenient or comfortable. Drugs such as
Viagra can help with impotence, and incontinence can also be
managed .
</P>
<P>
   ``I counsel them to think not of the short term but of the long
term,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Mitchell and Hogg have reason to be optimistic
today. Hogg's PSA has dropped to 0.5 and Mitchell's to 0.3, early
confirmation of the effectiveness of seed therapy. And their
discomfort has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took about three months to really get my full strength
back,'' says Hogg. ``But now . . . I can't tell anything's been
done to me. If it didn't work, it didn't work, but I still think
that I've made the best choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
