</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Cleaning closets an exercise in self-awareness
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been cleaning closets. It's a late-summer ritual for me,
but this time I've taken on this daunting task with a new
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine inspired me in my closet cleaning duties. She
told me of a technique passed on to her by a friend. You remove
every single item from your closet and then put back only those
things you truly love or that look exceptionally good on you or
that fit perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, you go through each piece of clothing: the tight,
slinky skirt you bought four years ago after losing 15 pounds that
you've worn exactly twice; the heavy wool sweater that you keep
hanging onto just in case Texas experiences sub-zero temperatures
for an extended period; the three pairs of khaki slacks you somehow
ended up with.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is analyzed. The fat clothes, the skinny clothes and
all the in-between clothes. How long are you really going to keep
that size 8 dress when you haven't seen a size 8 since your young
niece came to visit? On the other side of the zipper, do I really
have to keep that pair of size 16 slacks as a warning to myself to
never gain weight again?
</P>
<P>
   I discovered that cleaning my closet in such a disciplined way
was a lot like forcing myself to grow up. As I packed up a Goodwill
box of the clothes that symbolized my insecurities and some false
hopes, I also began doing an inventory of my mental closet.
</P>
<P>
   What am I holding onto in my memory bank that no longer serves
me well, that no longer fits me anymore? Resentments, insecurities,
anger? What seemed perfect to wear for a season now seems outdated
and childish. Am I ready to let it go, pack it up and send it on
its way?
</P>
<P>
   What about some of my beliefs and convictions? Do I believe
today as I did 20 years ago? Isn't it time to put that tie-dyed
dogma and that hip-hugging hype away? They're not my style anymore
and I need to clean the remnants of them out of my system.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items I discarded because they just weren't
comfortable anymore. Like three-inch spike heels, they were an
image I tried to force myself into only to teeter precariously.
What am I trying to prove with that image? Do I really care about
that issue anymore? Who am I fooling?
</P>
<P>
   Other ``clothes'' I discarded because they no longer allowed me
to breathe. Any belief or ideology that constricted or limited me,
I unbuckled, unzipped and unbuttoned. I'm too old to hold my
breath. I need space in which to inhale great gasping gulps of
wisdom and knowledge, as much as I possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning out closets is a tiresome task usually. It confronts
you with your excess and calls you to be a better steward of your
possessions. With my friend's method of closet cleaning, you must
decide what you truly love and need. That can be an amazing
exercise in self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   There is a story Sue Bender relates in her book Everyday Sacred
about an earnest young student who seeks out a Zen monk for wisdom.
The monk asks the student to pour him a cup of tea and he will tell
the student when to stop. The student does so and the cup quickly
overflows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you see the cup is full? It can hold no more!'' the
student exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it is with you,'' the teacher answers. ``Your mind is
full of too many things. Only when you are empty will there be room
for more knowledge to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
