<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREE-VILLAGE22-COX     09-21 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREE-VILLAGE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lost Tree emulated, but not first neighborhood charity
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lost Tree Village, like plenty of other gated communities in
South Florida, offers its residents a country club, beach house,
pro shops, even a chapel.
</P>
<P>
   But what sets it apart is its optional, residential tax
write-off _ an elite, IRS-approved philanthropy, which allows
donors to take a charitable tax deduction for up to 50 percent of
their adjusted gross income in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the money taken up each year from residents such as
golfer Jack Nicklaus or General Electric Co. CEO Jack Welch also
makes the charity all the greater an amenity for the area outside
this exclusive, oceanside golf community nestled between North Palm
Beach and Juno Beach.
</P>
<P>
   With $2.9 million in assets and $712,500 given to 53 nonprofits
in Palm Beach and Martin counties in 1997, the 16-year-old Lost
Tree Village Charitable Foundation is among the best organized and
best known among similar groups that have quietly been springing up
in wealthy enclaves all over Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has developed into almost like a United Way. . . . I told
them, `I wish we could clone you all over Florida,' '' said Dot
Ridings, president of the Council on Foundations in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone feels that way. The creation of each such
neighborhood charity means another contingent of South Florida's
winter residents and wealthy retirees bypasses the local community
foundations, United Ways and Jewish Federations that have
historically been the dominant means for taking up collections and
picking the charities that get the money.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the United Way of Palm Beach County raised $9.2
million in 1997-98, up from $8.1 million in 1996-97, and the United
Way of Martin County raised $1.7 million in 1997-98, up from $1.5
million the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Gated approach: Isolationist?
</P>
<P>
   Though many admire the Lost Tree Village concept for its level
of organization and commitment, some of the established groups view
the further spread of the gated-community approach with mixed
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that it may Balkanize those gated communities and keep
them from getting to know the larger community and operating in a
vacuum,'' said Shannon Sadler, president of the $80 million
Community Foundation for Palm Beach and Martin Counties. ``I just
don't want them to stay behind those gates forever.''
</P>
<P>
   But Palm Beach County United Way Executive Director Scott
Badesch said, ``Anything that brings in money to human services is
something that ought to be applauded.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an all-time high of 151 families each gave at least
$2,500 to the Lost Tree Village Foundation. Overall, residents
pumped a record $724,000 into the charity.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Lost Tree foundation is classified as a public
charity, donors not only can write off 50 percent of their gross
annual income if they give that much, but they can deduct the full
market value of a gift of publicly traded stock.
</P>
<P>
   Those are better breaks than afforded by a private foundation,
whose donors can write off only 30 percent of their gross adjusted
income and, when it comes to stock, can write off only what they
originally paid for the stock. A foundation also must pay a 2
percent tax on its investment income, but a charity doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Tree group changed its legal status from private foundation
to public charity in 1992. While both are Internal Revenue Code
classifications, becoming a charity is tougher because it must meet
the IRS's test for broad public support while a foundation can be
an endowment created by one person.
</P>
<P>
   Giving is not uncommon
</P>
<P>
   Most Lost Tree donors are hardly philanthropic neophytes: Some
have their own foundations and substantial reputations as
philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very thorough operation. I'm impressed with it,'' said
18-year Lost Tree Village resident Leslie Quick Jr., CEO of the
Quick &AMP; Reilly brokerage firm in Palm Beach. ``You've got a lot of
sophisticated people, a lot of people high up in industry and
charity work.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick estimated he has given the Lost Tree group about $100,000
in eight years. He has his own foundation, the Leslie C. Quick Jr.
and Regina A. Quick Charitable Trust Foundation. He said his
foundation, formed in 1988 and with $6.6 million in assets in 1997,
sometimes gives to the same groups picked by Lost Tree Village.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Tree's gifts in 1997 ranged from $1,000 to the
Salisbury-Sexton/Communities in Schools Memorial Scholarship, a
high-school drop-out prevention program, to $50,000 for the Glades
Community Development Corp., to pay for after-school and family
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The grant recipients are picked by the Lost Tree's 50-person
visiting committee, which sends teams of three to five inspectors
on visits to local charities.
</P>
<P>
   Charities date to '40s
</P>
<P>
   While Lost Tree's charity is perhaps the most emulated, it was
not the first neighborhood foundation in the area.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest localized money-raising efforts was the Hobe
Sound Community Chest, formed in 1949. The community chest raised
$290,000 last year from residents of Hobe Sound and Jupiter Island
and gave out $226,000 to 32 organizations. The gifts ranged in size
from $50 for the Hobe Sound Nature Center to $77,000 for the Hobe
Sound Child Care Center. Along with gifts to the Hobe Sound
Volunteer Fire Department, Jupiter Island Garden Club and United
Way of Martin County, the group also gave $100 to the National
Hemlock Society and $5,000 to the Yale School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastpointe Country Club Charity Fund in Palm Beach Gardens
was formed in 1980. It raises money during one week of golf
tournaments and luncheons and distributes it to charities in Palm
Beach County. It raised $64,000 last year and $675,000 since its
formation.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenchman's Creek Charities Foundation, in Palm Beach
Gardens, was created in 1993 and holds one ``Charity Day'' event
each year, usually golf, tennis and card tournaments. In March, its
595 country club residents and some outside donors raised $76,000
and distributed it to 38 charities.
</P>
<P>
   The Abacoa Partnership for Community, in Jupiter, was created in
December and plans to make grants in Abacoa and surrounding
northern Palm Beach County. Unlike other groups, it will raise
money from businesses and commercial property owners. It has
received a $200,000 start-up grant from the John D. and Catherine
T. MacArthur Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   New groups take tips from old
</P>
<P>
   The most recently formed is the Piper's Landing Community Fund.
The Palm City group, just west of Stuart, received public charity
status from the IRS on June 19. Board member Richard Enright said
the board will seek guidance from the Lost Tree and Hobe Sound
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Enright said most residents of Piper's Landing are snowbirds
with a charitable bent but little knowledge of area nonprofits.
They need help sorting through solicitations but also want to make
their philanthropy more engaging than just writing checks to
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of directors will be able to chat about the
activities when they're playing golf,'' he said. ``What you want to
have is the personal connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Money raising by the Lost Tree Village Charitable Foundation
also is deliberately low-key, with members often promoting their
causes on the golf course and at bridge parties, said foundation
President James Gillin. Each year, the group also mails Lost Tree's
500 households a money-raising letter and holds a party for
benefactors who gave at least $2,500 in the past year or $25,000
total.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's soiree honored the largesse of such residents as
Nicklaus; Welch, of General Electric; Lawrence Bossidy, the CEO of
aerospace engineering giant Allied Signal; Bradford Boss, CEO of
pen maker A.T. Cross Co.; Stanley Druckenmiller, top money manager
at Soros Fund Management; and Paul Evanson, president of Florida
Power &AMP; Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the November party _ $7,697 _ was the charity's top
money-raising expense in 1997, according to its tax return. It also
spent $7,076 on printing and mailing annual reports and a
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   That means Lost Tree spends just over 2 percent of its annual
take on raising money. A typical national charity spends around 15
percent to 20 percent of its money to raise money, according to the
National Charities Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Tree Village Charitable Foundation's executive director,
Pamela Rue, is the only paid employee, making $56,000 last year.
Hobe Sound's charity also has a paid employee, and Abacoa's will.
For all administrative expenses, including Rue's salary, the Lost
Tree charity spent about 14 percent of the money it raised last
year. But Rue said no contributions were used to pay any
administrative or money-raising expenses; thatsalaries and
money-raising costs came from investment income.
</P>
<P>
   The United Way of Palm Beach County says it spends about 13
percent on administration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
