<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toys leap to life in action-movie game
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Small Wonders'' was a huge hit in the Farris household, in
Mableton.
</P>
<P>
   The PC fighting game of action toys captivated reviewer Jesse
Farris, 12, and his brothers _ Jacob, 9, and Joseph, 8 _ with its
vivid graphics and fierce fighting action. For hours on end, the
Farris boys and several neighborhood friends waged battle against
enemy forces, knocking off different body parts until the final
blow is struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play it a lot,'' Jesse said. ``It's a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on this summer's popular action-adventure movie ``Small
Soldiers'', the storyline of ``Small Wonders'' is similar to the
film, but different enough to give players a new experience. There
are two different plots that unfold, based on the player's choice.
To win the battle, players must uncover new insights into each
character's strengths and weaknesses. Puzzles are layered within
each mission, requiring players to use their wits and
problem-solving skills. Gamers can create an original Commando or a
Gorgonite by choosing from a variety of bodies, heads, arms and
legs, each with unique battle advantages. New action figures can be
customized from hundreds of textures, colors and decals and
equipped with special battle accessories. Built and dressed for
battle, the soldiers are trained in their new moves, then it's off
to battle in one of five interactive 3-D environments.
</P>
<P>
   Creations can also be saved to disk and imported to play on a
friend's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse said he really liked the graphics, but his favorite part
is that the game offers lots of options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that you not only play with the regular
characters, but you could create your own,'' he said. ``Another
good thing is that you can select different levels of play.''
</P>
<P>
   Recommended ages: 6 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum PC system requirements: Pentium 100 MHz or higher, 16
megabytes RAM, 30 MB free hard drive space, 4X CD-ROM drive, 1 MB
SVGA card, sound card, mouse, DirectX v.5.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Software
</P>
<P>
   maker
</P>
<P>
   adds to
</P>
<P>
   its site
</P>
<P>
   on Web
</P>
<P>
   Children's software maker Humongous Entertainment recently
``flipped the start switch'' on two new features to its redesigned,
award-winning http://www.humongous.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Families visiting the site can discover an exclusive new
``Making of Blue's Birthday Adventure'' feature dedicated to the
creation of the highly anticipated ``Blue's Clues'' CD-ROMs, plus a
new online weather game starring the world's youngest superhero,
Pajama Sam. The new Web site design makes it easy for kids to find
their favorite activities, the latest downloads and new features
every time they visit.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also provides families with fun activities kids and
parents can enjoy together, both on and off the computer, said John
Uppendahl, Humongous Entertainment's vice president of
communications and online business development. Whether playing an
online mini-game, asking questions directly to Freddi Fish in
``Frankly Freddi'' or printing out a putt-putt car to color, cut
out and assemble, there are tons of activities that will keep
families entertained for hours.
</P>
<P>
   `Making of Blue's
</P>
<P>
   Birthday Adventure'
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue's Clues,'' the hit TV show for preschoolers, has made the
leap to CD-ROM. Curious families everywhere want to know, ``How'd
they do it?''
</P>
<P>
   In this new Web site feature, the software giant lets everyone
in on the secret by unveiling ``Making of Blue's Birthday
Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   This feature describes the process behind the collaboration
between Humongous Entertainment and Nickelodeon, which created the
interactive CD-ROM experience for preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue's Birthday Adventure'' combines the unique playability of
Humongous Entertainment's award-winning software with the rich look
and multilayered educational experience of the TV show. It will
have preschoolers going back for more.
</P>
<P>
   `Pajama Sam's Wacky
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide Weather Report'
</P>
<P>
   Kids recently discovered in ``Pajama Sam 2: Thunder and
Lightning Aren't So Frightening'' that weather across the globe is
amok and the world's youngest superhero is on a mission to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with its wacky weather online game, Humongous Entertainment
provides kids a chance to create their own newspapers based on
``Pajama Sam's Wacky Worldwide Weather Report.''
</P>
<P>
   Pajama Sam asks kids to provide him with the names of some of
their favorite things, including food, color and TV show, and then
places the answers into a weather story. Kids can check out and
print these stories as they would appear in the local newspaper.
With a variety of hand-drawn illustrations and one-of-a-kind
stories, kids will have a blast as they prepare their weather
report again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
