<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Sept. 21, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-URANIUM (Washington) _ In a move applauded by Gulf War
veterans, the Pentagon has announced plans to add information about
the hazards of depleted uranium explosions to its ``smart book,''
the manual issued to all soldiers during basic training. By
KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-COPYRIGHT (San Francisco) _ In a lawsuit that experts
say threatens the free-wheeling nature of the World Wide Web, a
photographer claims JC Penney Inc. should be held liable because
its Web site was one of three ``links'' that ultimately led to an
unauthorized display of his photo of movie star Elizabeth Taylor.
By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GUARD (Glenville, N.Y.) _ The decision to base an elite new
anti-terrorist unit at the Stratton Air National Guard Base here is
an example of how this once-sleepy airfield is now a key part of
the state Guard's strategy to rebuild the organization from the
ground up. By BOB GARDINIER.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE (San Francisco) _ Fay Wilborn is one of 522 Bay
Area residents who gave anywhere from $1 to $10,000 this year to
President Clinton's legal defense fund. If Clinton is going to
battle House Republicans to serve out his term, he's likely to need
the support of people like Wilborn. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CANDIDATES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Attorney General Dan
Lungren and U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer stand on different ideological
continents, but both candidates have the same problem: They have
records that can be exploited. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NUDISTS-PROTESTS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Nudists thumbed their
noses at _ and exposed all other body parts to _ Berkeley's
anti-nudity ordinance Sunday in their seventh annual romp in the
raw. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPERIAL-SUGAR (Undated) _ Situated on a piece of land that has
been the site of a sugar mill since 1843, Imperial Holly Corp. is
Texas' oldest business and also one of the fastest changing. But
has recently begun a strategic shift into the food-service business
_ acquiring companies in Florida and Massachusetts _ that doesn't
necessarily involve sugar. By NELSON ANTOSH.
</P>
<P>
   GENENTECH (South San Francisco, Calif.) _ Genentech Inc., a
trailblazer in the American biotechnology industry, is finally
reaping the benefits of a reorganization that began three years
ago. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL-CURRENCY (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Instead of spending standard
U.S. dollars, more and more East Bay residents are using BREAD to
buy everything from produce and candles to legal services and child
care. The number of East Bay BREAD users has gone from 30 to more
than 300 and the alternative cash _ $10,000 of which is now in
circulation _ is increasingly being accepted by local businesses
and restaurants as part of a local currency trend that appears to
be on the rise across the country. By ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CIVILWAR-REVIEW (Houston) _ ``The Civil War'' is composer Frank
Wildhorn's big gamble and, to a large extent, it pays off in the
world premiere unveiled at the Alley Theater. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Bridge Bay, Calif.) _ An osprey zoomed
overhead, locked its wings, then angled and dive-bombed the lake,
like an F-14 on maneuvers. The bird came hurtling down and hit the
water with a tremendous splash _ and a second later, it lifted off,
a rainbow trout in its talons. I only hoped our fishing luck could
be scarcely as good. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLEANUP (San Francisco) _ A letter in an airtight container from
a Ukrainian sailor seeking an American pen pal took first prize
over the weekend as the weirdest thing found in the Bay Area's
coastal cleanup. A troop of Eagle Scouts won $500 for finding the
handwritten letter and photo, apparently tossed from a ship docked
in the Bay. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN _ Where to get excellent sources for books and
plants on habitat gardening. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ What do airport baggage handlers and
security officers, park volunteers, tour bus drivers and cruise
ship busboys have in common? They're all usually under-appreciated
but are significant to the enjoyment of a vacation. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   NORWEGIAN-SEA (Houston) _ Beginning in December, the Norwegian
Sea will replace the much-maligned Norwegian Star on weekly
Texaribbean sailings from the Port of Houston. The Sea is newer and
bigger. But is it better? A preview of what to expect. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Last week I wrote that every age
gets the scandal it deserves, and this is the age of Jerry
Springer. I got to thinking about that, and came up with this
question: How is the Jerry Springer show different from the Ken
Starr show? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Enough wailing over the Clinton
mess. We're stuck with it. As individuals. As a country. The
crucial thing now is, what are we going to do with it? Use it to
learn something? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ After eight months of endless
media coverage of the Clinton sex scandal, the president's job
approval ratings have remained remarkably and consistently high.
The public has been saying clearly, for months, that it draws a
distinction between public policy and personal conduct, and sees
the Clinton affair to be a private matter between Bill and Hillary.
By MARK SOMMER.
</P>
</TEXT>
