<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-BANKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BANK LOSSES ARE BIGGEST COVER-UP EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (EDS: Filed in ``i'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The losses suffered by Japan's banks as a result of bad
debts have now been revealed to be of a magnitude unapproached
since the Italians invented banking nearly 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the Japanese banking crisis is almost unimaginable
if Standard and Poor, the American agency that probes such matters,
is correct. And Standard and Poor doesn't often make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. organization declared Japanese banks' bad
debts are probably as much as $1.1 billion _ nearly twice as great
as any Japanese official has ever acknowledged. Such a stupendous
figure would amount to nearly one-third of Japan's annual
production of goods and services. This makes losses incurred in the
American banking crisis of the 1980s look like small change.
</P>
<P>
   The implications are tremendous. First of all, the extent of the
losses means the task of rebuilding the country's finances, already
regarded as a tough job, will be herculean. Let's not forget that
it is Japan's banking troubles that are at the core of Asia's
economic turmoil, also contributing heavily to the doubts swirling
around Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's only part of the disturbing story.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1990s at the latest, government and financial
authorities in Japan must have had at least an inkling of the sizes
of the losses brought about mostly by a disastrous plunge in the
Japanese real estate market. But they systematically tried to hide
the scope of the crisis from the rest of the world and in the
cover-up were assisted by virtually every public and private
institution in the country. Only little by little were heavier
losses conceded _ when it became impossible to camouflage the
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The devastating consequence has been dangerous footdragging by
Japanese officials about how to deal with this dagger pointed at
the very heart of the world's second largest economy. Even today,
the arguments continue to rage. Government proposals to close the
weakest banks and inject public money into the others have run into
stiff opposition. Washington's pressure on Tokyo to get its act
together has had little appreciable effect.
</P>
<P>
   However, unless decisive action occurs soon, the current fears
of a global recession could be only a mild taste of what's to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
