<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 TRIP INSURANCE: DON'T LEAVE HOME WITHOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    On the second day of their cruise-tour through Alaska, Robert F.
Reiland rushed his wife who was suffering from a life-threatening
breathing problem to a hospital emergency room in Fairbanks.
 &HT;    After four days of intensive care, Mrs. Reiland had recovered
enough to return home to Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., ending the
couple's journey. At the time they wrote us, they had received no
refunds for the portion of the trip that had to be cancelled, for
hotel bills in Fairbanks and for extra airfare _ not a penny from
the tour operator, their travel agent or the airline.
 &HT;    As Reiland says, ``We paid $11,000 up front for what became only
a round-trip to Alaska and a riverboat ride ...''
 &HT;    The truth is that the Reilands hadn't bought trip insurance. In
fact, they didn't even know such a thing existed. And, apparently,
their travel agent didn't tell them, either. As a result, nobody
was required to refund the Reilands' money.
 &HT;    With more mature travelers taking longer and more expensive
vacations, trip insurance is becoming a necessity to protect a
fairly large travel investment _ and it provides peace of mind.
 &HT;    A typical policy costs only 5 percent to 6 percent of the cost
of the trip; some policies cost less. Rates seem to be lower than
they were several years ago, and coverages are better as insurance
vendors expand their claims experience.
 &HT;    On the downside, leading trip-insurance sellers are beginning to
charge rates based on age _ the older you are, the more trip
insurance costs. The higher cost is also a result of the greater
number of claims filed by mature travelers, who have more
experience travelling.
 &HT;    For example, a policy from CSA Travel Protection will insure a
$2,500 trip for a premium of $69 if you are under 55, $105 if you
are 56 to 70, and $135 if you are 70 or older. Even so, those
premiums are a bargain compared with the costs of travel that
aren't reimbursed.
 COVERING THE BIG COSTS  
 &HT;    Make sure you are covered for loses you can't afford to absorb,
and try not to pay high prices for other frills. Make sure, too,
that the policy you choose is an insurance policy and not just an
add-on to a trip offered as an afterthought.
 &HT;    Nancy Hoyt Belcher of Oakland, Calif., was on a trip to Alaska's
Denali Wilderness Retreat on a remote back corner of the national
park, a place where there are no roads, when she suffered a heart
attack. Bad weather prevented a plane from getting in, so she was
helicoptered to the nearest hospital in Fairbanks.
 &HT;    But Fairbanks had no cardiology unit, so she was airlifted to
Anchorage, where she recuperated. Belcher says the bill for that
relatively short evacuation was more than $9,000. Some evacuations
from remote corners of the world to decent hospitals can cost up to
$25,000.
 &HT;    Your insurance policy should cover the following:
 &HT;     _ TRIP CANCELLATION OR INTERRUPTION: This is the primary reason
for all trip-insurance policies. It comes into play when: the death
or serious illness of you, your traveling companion or a close
relative at home requires you to cancel your trip and to stay home;
you have an emergency at home, like a flood or an earthquake; you
miss connections and can't pick up the trip; the ship is disabled
on a cruise the week before yours; your cruise is cancelled; and
your tour operator goes broke and you are stranded overseas.
 &HT;    Insurance reimbursement should cover the cruise fare or cost of
a tour that won't be refunded, any extra meals or lodging bills and
any airfare add-ons to fly home early.
 &HT;     _ EVACUATION:  Emergency medical evacuation insurance (EME) is
also a feature of most trip-insurance policies. Claim it when you
have an illness too serious to be treated on the spot and you must
be airlifted from some remote location to a hospital where you can
get proper care, or you need additional evacuation to a hospital
near your home.
 &HT;    Although evacuation is rarely necessary, it is about the most
expensive thing that can go wrong on a trip _ up to $25,000 for a
long-distance airlift. Clearly, this is an expense most travelers
can't absorb.
 &HT;     _ MEDICAL EXPENSES:  While extra medical or dental expenses may
be covered by your existing health-insurance policies, you should
check your policy to make sure you're covered outside the United
States.
 &HT;    If you've purchased Part B coverage, Medicare will probably
cover expensive options such as medical evacuation under its
provisions for ambulance services _ but only in the United States.
 &HT;    Beware: Medicare does not cover most health-threatening
situations that happen to you outside the country. So you'll need
this supplemental medical/dental coverage when you're traveling
abroad.
 &HT;     _ EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE: Does the policy provide medical
referral to English-speaking doctors overseas (preferably using a
telephone hotline), translation by phone, medical monitoring in a
foreign hospital, prescription help, emergency cash to pay foreign
hospital bills and possible legal assistance?
 &HT;    What you don't need in a trip-insurance policy are items often
already covered by your existing policies or those whose cost you
can handle: for example, coverage for lost or delayed luggage, lost
passports or travelers checks, accidental death or dismemberment,
accident insurance on a rental car.
 &HT;    And make sure you read your policy when you receive it and
understand your coverage. You may want to shop further.
 &HT;    Here are leading companies that provide trip insurance for
mature travelers. All basic policies from these companies provide
coverage for trip cancellation, medical evacuation, extra medical
costs and emergency services:
 &HT;     _ Access America,  (800) 284-8300.
 &HT;     _ American Express,  (800) 758-2639.
 &HT;     _ Berkeley Carefree,  (800) 323-3149.
 &HT;     _ CSA,  (800)348-9505.
 &HT;     _ TravelGuard,  (800) 826-1300.
 &HT;     _ Travelers,  (800) 243-3174.
 &HT;    Of these, ``Consumer Reports Travel Letter'' rated CSA and
Access America policies as best values.
 &HT;    Buy a trip-insurance policy from your travel agent at the time
you book the trip _ most agencies can set you up with these
companies _ or directly from the insurance provider.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
