<HEADER>
A5956 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELCOM-CONGRESS-$ADV2     09-21 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELCOM-CONGRESS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TELECOM MERGERS IRK LAWMAKERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Has the urge to merge in the phone business cut off
the fuel to duel? That's the view of some key legislators and
government regulators who see the ghost of old Ma Bell rising anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that concentration of ownership in the
telecommunications industry is currently proceeding faster than the
growth of competition,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the
ranking Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``We are seeing
old monopolies getting bigger and expanding their reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, concern over how telecom mergers will affect both
business users and consumers extends across party lines. A fresh
legislative look at the entire telecommunications law is likely
when the next Congress meets in January, with at least one chamber,
and perhaps both, still expected to be under Republican control.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consolidation was hardly an issue in 1996 when the
lawmakers approved the landmark legislation. At the time, the act's
chief purposes were said to be fostering competition, cutting
regulations and speeding the adoption of such new technologies as
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After holding four hearings on telecom developments before his
Senate antitrust subcommittee, Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said this
month: ``We need to take a serious look at the Telecommunications
Act to decide how well it is working, how long we should stay with
it and what might be done to improve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision in the 1980s to break up the Ma Bell monopoly left
AT&AMP;T Corp. as the nation's prime long-distance provider while
creating seven regional phone companies to offer local service. But
since passage of the 1996 act, the telecom landscape has undergone
seismic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell has merged with PacTel into SBC Corp. and Bell
Atlantic has merged with Nynex. SBC is now seeking to merge with
Ameritech while Bell Atlantic wants to hook up with GTE, the
remaining large local phone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Even as all this takes place, local competitors still serve
barely 1 percent of the Bells' 178 million residential customers.
And phone rates continue to rise in most states, propelled in part
by ``universal service'' fees mandated by Congress and federal
regulators to subsidize underserved customers.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, AT&AMP;T has spent more than $5 billion seeking, mostly in
vain, to enter local phone markets. In June, the company took a new
tack by moving to acquire Tele-Communications Inc. for about $32
billion. By linking to consumers through TCI's cable system, which
reaches 10.5 million homes, AT&AMP;T intends to bypass the Bells'
copper and fiber networks.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of these moves, the Federal Communications
Commission approved WorldCom's purchase of MCI, another major
long-distance provider, thereby removing the last hurdle for
completion of the $40 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard praises the merger, saying that the
combined company is committed to provide telecom services to
residential areas, ``including our nation's inner cities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennard also said that ``our applause for this combination
should be restrained'' because ``once this merger is consummated,
the industry will again be poised just a merger away from undue
concentration. I dare say that any subsequent merger _ of this or
similar magnitude _ between long-distance firms in the near future
should be judged quite differently than the merger before us
today.''
</P>
<P>
   As these mergers occur, the 1996 overall master plan has yet to
jell. Under that plan, long-distance carriers, local phone
companies, cable companies and Internet service providers were
supposed to freely trample through each other's turf.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some pieces are starting to fall into place, despite
legal roadblocks raised by many of the players _ impediments which
have yet to be fully tested in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ameritech, the Midwestern Bell giant, is making some headway
in the cable business, while Cox Cable, among others, now provides
local dial tones in such large cities as Phoenix and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bell Atlantic appears close to entering the long-distance
market in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An explosion of telecommunications activity is taking place
via the Internet, where voice and high-speed data exchanges are
increasingly available as stand-alone services.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry figures claim that the open protocols that power
the Internet will soon make distinctions such as ``local'' and
``long distance,'' ``voice'' and ``data,'' ``telephone'' and
``computer'' obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   The need to ``enable the delivery of multiple services by
multiple
</P>
<P>
   suppliers'' is the driving force behind the proposed Bell
Atlantic-GTE link, Ivan Seidenberg, Bell Atlantic's president,
recently told DeWine's antitrust panel.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the deal as ``a pro-competitive response to the
</P>
<P>
   revolutionary changes overtaking the telecommunications
industry,'' Seidenberg noted that annual double-digit growth in
telecommunications equipment and services is expected to continue
through 2001. By then, he predicted, communications will be a $1
trillion industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of this growth is coming from sources we could never have
</P>
<P>
   predicted a few years ago, most notably the explosive demand for
high-speed data services,'' Seidenberg said. Data traffic now
doubles every three months, as opposed to every 12 years for voice
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some lawmakers remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Have patience,' we are told,'' said Sen. Sen. Herb Kohl,
D-Wis. `` 'The act is working, but it will take some time for
competition to take root and grow.' Well, there may be some truth
to this notion, but unless we see more tangible evidence that
consumers have real choices, the pressure will continue to re-open
the act and break the stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   IN the meantime, Kohl and DeWine plan to ask the General
Accounting Office, the auditing arm of Congress, to investigate
competitive trends in the phone industry.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
