<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELCOM-CONGRESS-$ADV2     09-21 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELCOM-CONGRESS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TELECOM MERGERS IRK LAWMAKERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Sept. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Has the urge to merge in the phone business cut off
the fuel to duel? That's the view of some key legislators and
government regulators who see the ghost of old Ma Bell rising anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that concentration of ownership in the
telecommunications industry is currently proceeding faster than the
growth of competition,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the
ranking Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``We are seeing
old monopolies getting bigger and expanding their reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, concern over how telecom mergers will affect both
business users and consumers extends across party lines. A fresh
legislative look at the entire telecommunications law is likely
when the next Congress meets in January, with at least one chamber,
and perhaps both, still expected to be under Republican control.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consolidation was hardly an issue in 1996 when the
lawmakers approved the landmark legislation. At the time, the act's
chief purposes were said to be fostering competition, cutting
