<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLLS-BOS &LR;      09-21 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWING' AMERICANS MAY PLAY KEY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mac Magruder and Rosetta Gainey are on opposite sides of the
country and the national conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgid Smith of Missouri is physically, politically, and
philosophically between them: pulled one way by people like
Magruder who want President Clinton to be impeached, tugged the
other way by those like Gainey who want him left alone.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress considers Kenneth W. Starr's report on Clinton's
sexual escapades and alleged coverup, scores of public opinion
pollsters have questioned people like Magruder, Gainey, and Smith
in search of clues to guide lawmakers through the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The clear, yet potentially misleading, consensus that emerges
from polls taken since the release of the Starr report is that, for
the moment at least, a majority of Americans want Clinton to remain
in office. Most national polls have found voters roughly 2-to-1
against resignation or impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But slice through the fog of numbers and a healthy part of that
serve-out-the-term majority is personally repulsed by the
president's behavior; a majority believes he has obstructed justice
and does not share the moral values of most Americans. A majority
also wants Congress to move forward with impeachment hearings, to
investigate Starr's charges.
</P>
<P>
   With those apparent contradictions defining the debate,
pollsters and analysts say Clinton's future may well hinge on
``swing'' or ``pivotal'' Americans like Smith: people who are
disappointed or even disgusted by Clinton personally, but pleased
enough with the job he has done to keep him in office.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts it is an uncomfortable, unstable middle, made
up of perhaps 30 percent of the voting population. And its members
are acutely aware that by supporting the president's
accomplishments but not the man, they are standing over a growing
chasm of opinion, with one foot on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say the possibility that those voters might
eventually jump one way or the other, depending on how many more
shoes are yet to drop, helps to explain why congressional
Republicans have sought the disclosure of even more potentially
damaging evidence against Clinton _ including today's scheduled
release of his taped grand jury testimony and more explicit details
of sex with Monica Lewinsky. Like adding straw to the back of a
burdened camel, the analysts say, the GOP wants to test the spine
of Clinton's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's those Midwestern Democrats at the lukewarm center,'' said
Del Ali, senior vice president of Mason-Dixon Political/Media
Research in Maryland. ``They don't want him to leave, but they're
on the brink. Any more information and they could turn on him. But
they could turn either way, and that's the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup Poll, compared it
to a political campaign that will ultimately be determined by
undecided voters. ``Hard-core voters on the right are unlikely to
change, and the same is true for the hard core on the left. It is
those people in the middle, people who have conflicting opinions of
him at this point, who are more likely to move,'' said Newport.
</P>
<P>
   He said his most recent poll found 63 percent of Americans
approve of Clinton's job performance but only 37 percent have a
favorable opinion of him personally. Newport cautioned, however,
``These numbers might move, and move fast, depending on what comes
next.''
</P>
<P>
   While people at both extremes and in the middle can be found
throughout the country, last week's polls offer insight into what
different types of Americans are thinking, based on region, income,
race, and other features. That makes it possible to identify
individuals who most closely represent the three key streams of
popular thought, using demographic information to find common
characteristics of each, much as police sketch artists use a nose
from here and eyebrows from there to complete a portrait.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of several prominent national polls _ including The
New York Times/CBS and The Wall Street Journal/NBC News polls,
among others _ it appears that those most intent on seeing Clinton
ousted are wealthy, white, older conservative Republicans who live
in the wide-open spaces of the West. That describes Magruder, 58, a
GOP stalwart who owns a dozen McDonald's franchises in Arizona and
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In clear and dramatic contrast, the president's staunchest
supporters are low-income, black, Northeastern, urban, middle-aged
to older liberal Democrats. That describes Gainey, 59, an hourly
wage cashier at a Rite Aid Pharmacy in a tough section of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the conflicted middle, home to the youngest
and oldest voters, mainly from the South and Midwest,
middle-income, independent-minded Democrats or liberal Republicans
who live in the suburbs and midsized cities. That includes Smith,
24, manager of the Boone Tavern in Columbia, Mo., and a graduate
student in education at the nearby University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm one of those people who think the economy is doing
well, I'm making money and I'm happy,'' said Smith, who said that,
like her upper-income parents, she is ``afraid of the Wall Street
impact'' of impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he's done a decent job, and I voted for him twice,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Smith has a nagging sense of discomfort about Clinton's
behavior, his alleged lies and, in a larger sense, his character.
``In the beginning I didn't care about his personal situation, but
now I feel he's tried to weasel out of it. It's his family that
he's ruined, and he'll always have to live with this. It's all just
so disappointing. Can you just imagine how Chelsea feels?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Smith said she is against resignation or impeachment, she
sent an encouraging signal to Clinton opponents whose strategy is
to pluck the president one feather at a time. ``I don't think it's
impeachable right now. But I could imagine, if it never ends and it
seems to be just one thing after another, being in favor of
impeachment. That is, if he didn't resign first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-21 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, YOU IN THE GLASS HOUSE! HANDLE THOSE STONES CAREFULLY! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Kenneth Starr and some Republicans have been busy throwing
rocks at President Clinton, the public has discovered that a few of
those those brick-throwers live in glass houses themselves.
</P>
<P>
   How certain Republicans handle the recent exposures of their own
marital infidelities will determine just how much of a backlash
effect Starr's attempt to humiliate Clinton will have. Based on
early reports, the GOP is not coping very well.
</P>
<P>
   When US Representative Dan Burton, the Indiana Republican who
called Clinton a ``scumbag,'' was found to have fathered a child in
an adulterous affair, he and some of his GOP colleagues placed more
blame on the White House for exposing this than on himself for
having the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Republican chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, Representative Henry Hyde of Illinois, acknowledged that
he, too, had an adulterous affair in the 1960s. Even though the
woman's husband has acknowledged being the source of this
revelation, Hyde and his colleagues are strongly suggesting that a
leak came from the White House. And that, they say, is worse than
the Lewinsky affair in question.
</P>
<P>
   With these arguments, the conservative GOP wing is, in essence,
arguing that it is more acceptable for Hyde, Burton, or any other
Republican to commit adultery than for President Clinton. That is a
double standard.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP may further argue that at least Hyde and Burton did not
perjure themselves by denying these affairs under oath. As they
make that claim, the independent counsel's office goes about its
apparent mission to destroy the president.
</P>
<P>
   There is now widespread suspicion that the decision to release
the entire Starr report to the media was intended not to inform the
public, but to inflict greater damage on Clinton. While the GOP
attempts to justify the action by saying that the public has ``a
right to know'' all the details, the polls say the public is
shouting back,``But we don't want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, can blame no one but himself for his
troubles. But the investigation by Starr is aimed not at truth but
at maximizing the public embarrassment heaped upon Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's efforts may backfire by galvanizing the more than 60
percent of the public that approves of the president's job
performance. And those efforts also may create problems with
parents, whose children can access his lurid, detailed report on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, two key segments of Clinton supporters _ women and
African-Americans _ may be especially offended by the GOP's
excesses. To many, the investigator's tactics are more
objectionable than Clinton's finally-acknowledged relationship with
former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky. Some have noted that
it is no coincidence that GOP congressmen who are in the forefront
of the investigative effort are the same ones who fight against
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has more top African-Americans around him than did any
other president,'' said Atlanta-based pollster Harry L. Ross. ``If
we look at the close advisers to Bill Clinton, we see Vernon
Jordan. The person you have to see before you can go into Clinton's
office is Betty Curry. His chief of security among the Secret
Service is Larry Cockell. And during his difficult days, his
spiritual adviser has been the Rev. Jesse Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with no suggestion of a racial undercurrent to the GOP
campaign, these people help put a face on Clinton's philosophy and
policies, many of which the conservative GOP strongly opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the campaign against Clinton will backfire may be
answered in the November congressional elections. If the Democrats
gain more seats in both the House and Senate, that would be a
message to Republicans that it is time to end its assault on
Clinton _ perhaps with a censure or reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   If the GOP gains seats in both the House and Senate, that would
mean that their strategy is succeeding and impeachment hearings
will proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Clinton's survival rests with the women voters who
have supported his job performance throughout his years in office.
In the coming weeks, those voters may well decide that, although
the are disappointed with Clinton, they've had enough of the GOP's
unrelenting assault on him. If Republicans continue their blind,
bitter assault, they may not see the backlash it has caused _ until
its too late.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING DEEPER AND DEEPER FOR DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The letter dishing on Henry Hyde came to me from
Florida way back in July.
</P>
<P>
   As is strict policy in the only venue over which I have a
modicum of control _ my own writing _ it was immediately put in the
bottom of a locked drawer that over the years has come to contain
about two inches worth of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Not the dark and grimy kind, but stuff passing on rumors or
making accusations about the private lives of public figures; my
collection is nearly all sex and drugs, with a few phony academic
and military service records, child-support misdeeds, business
career scams, and one side-splittingly detailed ``cheats at golf''
allegation.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from Florida was unusual in three respects, not
including the abnormally ugly nature of the tale: The writer signed
his name, included a return address, and printed his phone number.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Norman Sommer really lives in Aventura, south of
Hollywood, and really is a retiree pal of the former husband of the
woman Hyde had a five-year affair with in the late 1960s. What's
more, he really was authorized by his embittered pal to try to put
the story out. The method he chose, sending his letter to several
writers, talking by phone with a few others, and nothing more, was
engagingly naive, serving to buttress his bona fides as an
untutored story manager and free agent.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have touched this story with a 10-foot pole,
believing as I do that private behavior is irrelevant to public
character, always has been and always will be. But after checking
Sommer out, I never forgot his letter the way I do most of this
stuff, because it struck me as a slow-burning fuse that was likely
to blow, given the current absence of standards of any meaning in
journalism and given the white-hot atmosphere of the effort to kick
President Clinton out of office. That the Hyde affair began on the
Internet (Salon magazine) and moved instantly into traditional
outlets was utterly unsurprising.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising, however, was both the intemperate
vituperation of the right's reaction to the unveiling of Hyde's
steamy past and its almost desperate, flailing effort _ without so
much as a shred of evidence _ to accuse senior White House official
Sidney Blumenthal of being the ultimate source or a purveyor of the
story. And even more surprising was the routine willingness of the
press to print smears that had no substance (as in a specific
accusation of a specific act) and no evidence, and are known by
some of us with direct knowledge of the affair to be false.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the likes of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas, slimy ex-DDT pusher that he is, from floating Blumenthal's
name in almost the same sentence he acknowledged having no evidence
of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   But listen to this tortured wreck of a sentence he, Speaker Newt
Gingrich and Majority Leader Dick Armey came up with in a letter to
FBI director Louis Freeh demanding an investigation of a
nonexistent crime:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether ot not that specific story originated with the White
House or its allies, clearly there is credible evidence that an
organized campaign of slander and intimidation may exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's Illinois toady, a no-account Republican congressman named
Ray LaHood, then said he had fingered Blumenthal by ``process of
elimination.'' For emphasis, he added a comment of mind-blowing
idiocy, ``I think this is Sidney Blumen-thal's MO.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from there being no evidence that Representative LaHood
ever thought anything, the fact is that this is not Blumenthal's
modus operandi. I've dealt with him all year during this mess; he
is tough as nails on the subject of Kenneth Starr, but more
interesting than a blunderbuss like James Carville because he is
substantive. The only negative information I have heard him utter
is public record stuff about past misdeeds and related court
sanctions involving senior members of Starr's prosecution team. It
may be chic around town to Blame Sidney when all else fails. But
the fact remains he plays this game square and to my direct
knowledge has not tossed so much as a molecule of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, this latest outburst of silly irresponsibility on
the right is a clue to the shaky knees of the increasingly partisan
Republican Impeachment Crusade. The Hyde story will not hurt Hyde
among the same general public than puts President Clinton's conduct
in perspective, and it certainly won't hurt among tolerant
Democrats. But it will hurt among the Cotton Mather wannabe
fruitcakes of the Crusade who actually think this kind of junk
matters.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Week Two of a supposedly solemn constitutional
exercise. You ready for another year of it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
