<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE COULD HOLD IMPLICATIONS FOR THE WORKPLACE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In mid-August, an adviser to Paula Jones declared that
feminists' reluctance to denounce President Clinton's behavior
toward her was tantamount to permission for men everywhere to
follow Clinton's lead in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the death of sexual harassment,'' the adviser, Susan
Carpenter-McMillan, told television interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   As the country awaits Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony,
it would be difficult to reach that conclusion today. The blaring
headlines about Clinton's liaison and its possible consequences
could not only make would-be sexual harassers think twice, but also
might discourage office romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a more interesting, subtle issue than people have
focused upon before,'' said Jody Newman, a Boston lawyer who
specializes in sexual harassment lawsuits. ``I think the Clinton
and Lewinsky situation will increase both employees' and employers'
awareness of the complications of a relationship in the workplace
and make them approach it more defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists on job-related gender dynamics, as well as
legal analysts, agreed recently on two principal reasons that
special prosecutor Kenneth W. Starr's report on Clinton could alter
workplace behavior.
</P>
<P>
   First, the report focuses such an intense spotlight on the
president's actions that it forces nearly everyone to address the
issues of perceived sexual harassment and office relationships,
particularly those between bosses and their subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, the obsession with the Starr report follows the
pattern of the televised hearings on Clarence Thomas's nomination
to become a Supreme Court justice, at which Anita Hill alleged he
had sexually harassed her. Most specialists said those hearings,
which began seven years ago this month, marked a turning point on
sexual harassment by making it a starkly public concern. The
Clinton-Lewinsky drama, at the least, has thrust the issue even
higher on people's agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back with Clarence Thomas, we started to see a growth in
awareness and sensitivity,'' said Monica Ballard, head of the
California-based Parallax Education firm, which helps companies
nationwide avoid liability in employment litigation. ``In the same
way, only much bigger, I think ... and hope that this is going to
be catapulting us into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report also may influence on-the-job behavior because
Clinton's extramarital affair has had such dire, dramatic, and very
public consequences for him: humiliation, loss of respect, and
possible ouster from a job he cares deeply about. Even if his
affair with an intern does not constitute sexual harassment, and
legal analysts generally say it does not because Lewinsky was a
consenting adult, most people instinctively want to avoid such
repercussions for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, analysts asserted, executives who might otherwise
embark on sexual relationships with fellow employees may now decide
not to, at least until the publicity dies down. And even people
thinking of dating fellow employees may reconsider for fear that,
like Lewinsky, their partners may ultimately make their lives
difficult, even if the arrangement begins consensually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope that it would only chill the inappropriate
instances ... where there is the confusion of direct lines of
authority, but it could spill over into cases that are
reasonable,'' said Maureen Scully, a specialist in business ethics
and diversity at the MIT Sloan School of Management. Still, she
added, it is ``mostly a good thing'' that the Starr report will
highlight questions of appropriate conduct at work.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those interviewed cautioned that, even if the
president's predicament may yield positive effects, the
often-graphic report is itself causing some gender-related tensions
at businesses. ``Everyone's talking about the graphic details, and
that in itself can create a hostile work environment,'' said
Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   She and others said that some employees, most often male, have
been sending colleagues e-mail containing explicit sexual content
from Starr's report, and many recipients, often female, have not
been pleased to receive the messages. Along the same lines, crude
jokes based on Clinton's reported contacts with Lewinsky have been
making the rounds, sometimes with pointedly sexist punch lines or
intent.
</P>
<P>
   Freada Klein, a Cambridge, Mass. consultant who advises
corporations on how to avoid and deal with sexual harassment, said
she feared that the explicit nature of Starr's report might turn
out to be so distracting that people won't consider the larger
lessons seriously enough. Other analysts also expressed concern
that the president's behavior, even if it is punished, might become
a model for some bosses who decide they can get away with similar
actions because it took a special prosecutor and $40 million to get
evidence against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this explosive chapter in American history does have
some positive results, Klein said she expects that it will not last
long without additional education, counseling, and other programs
to fight sexual harassment. ``Eventually ... people act on their
lust,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many employers seem sure to read the Clinton-Lewinsky story as a
cautionary tale. As a result, the analysts said, it could promote
efforts to bring more respect to the workplace. ``Even if this
Clinton thing convinces only one or two people who might take
advantage of their position to change their behavior ... then it's
done a service,'' said Charles Rodger, chairman of Work-Family
Directions, a Boston company that helps large firms improve their
on-the-job conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one more time of being whacked over the head with the
reality that behavior like this is dangerous,'' he added. ``And
because it's the president, and there are so many details, it's
going to get people's attention like nothing has before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
