A6040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-FEMALE-ELECT-BOS &LR;      09-21 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FEMALE-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CAN'T A WOMAN WIN MORE LIKE A MAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the year women stormed political office
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we saw a defeated Lois G. Pines standing on the stage
of a Dorchester union hall hours after the primary polls closed
Tuesday, trying to smile through her contempt and disappointment
after losing the Democratic nomination for attorney general to
Thomas Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only six states in America in which no women serve
in Congress, in the United States Senate, or in statewide office _
Massachusetts, Mississippi, and four other pretty indistinguished
states,'' Pines said to her deflated devotees.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Clapprood, who came in fifth (behind four men) in the
8th Congressional District primary, offered this recollection of
how some voters had responded to her candidacy. ``They said, `We
think you're great but take off those 4-inch shoes before you
speak.' I said, `Did you ask Mike Capuano to take off his
wingtips?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why is this so-called liberal state having such
a hard time electing women, even in a year when eight of them were
running for higher office?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the excuses proffered by those who have tried to figure
it out include: First, politics is a blood sport here, and its
ferocious nature has discouraged many women and taken many out.
Two, local heavily Democratic politics has been influenced by labor
unions, which tend to have ``macho'' traditions not open to female
candidates. Three, the Roman Catholic Church's patriarchal system,
which continues to permeate politics in this corner of the world,
has discouraged women from being important players on the political
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not you buy any of those reasons, there is at least
one more explanation worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has a high incumbency rate, making it harder for
women to crack the ranks at many levels. Those in power tend not to
give it up easily. Further, money is often on the side of the
officeholder. Compare that with California, which not only has term
limits but also has a growing population that enlarges its
congressional delegation, both of which provide more opportunities
for women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   As for those other less-than-distinguished states mentioned by
Pines, less populous states like Massachusetts have always had a
lot in common with Southern states on gender gap issues, according
to Gilda Morales, spokeswoman for the Center for the American Woman
and Politics at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   She cites low turnover and historical conservatism. US Senator
Strom Thurmond, the 95-year-old Republican who has represented
South Carolina for almost half his life, comes first to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts at least has sent three women to Congress, and
you've had one lieutenant governor'' in Evelyn Murphy, Morales
said. ``There are seven states that have never sent a woman to
Congress,'' she said, listing Alaska, Delaware, Iowa, Mississippi,
New Hampshire, Vermont and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Maine and West Virginia are the only two states that have never
elected a woman to high state office, although Maine's two US
senators are women.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Massachusetts _ and this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pines, a state senator from Newton, had experience, money, a
solid campaign organization, a base, and a message, all the things
specialists say a woman needs to compete. She lost by only 6
percentage points to Reilly, the Middlesex district attorney. If
not for her poor showing in their televised debate, perhaps she
might have won.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Kelly Gay turned out a respectable 46 percent of the
vote against state Senator Warren Tolman of Watertown in the
Democratic race for the lieutenant governor nomination, despite
having no money and a low-visibility post at the Governor's
Council. She earned the support by attending countless coffees.
</P>
<P>
   Had the stars been aligned differently for these women, we could
be declaring 1998 another Year of the Woman. And there still are
redeeming possibilities for the year: Shannon O'Brien is running
for treasurer on the Democratic ticket, and Jane Swift will be Paul
Cellucci's lieutenant governor if the Republicans hold onto the
corner office.
</P>
<P>
   But Clapprood and Susan Tracy were demolished in the 8th
District race, trounced by Capuano, the mayor of Somerville, and
Raymond L. Flynn, former mayor of Boston, both of whom held mayoral
office for more than two terms.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Scott Harshbarger topped Patricia McGovern's
bid for the Democratic nomination for governor, leaving the former
Senate Ways and Means chairwoman _ in the private sector for a few
years now _ a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation in both those races probably has more to do with
the power of incumbency _ the value of proving oneself in a public
office in the months (or years) leading up to a campaign _ than it
does with any kind of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of states that don't elect many women: One
are those Southern states like Mississippi and Alabama. And the
other is a group of Northern industrial states, Pennsylvania, New
York, and Massachusetts,'' said Linda L. Fowler, a government
professor at Dartmouth College and director of the Rockefeller
Center for the Social Sciences. ``Incumbency is the single biggest
barrier to women getting into public office ... I think that was
present in this primary.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are other reasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   In that crowded field of 10 Democrats vying to succeed US
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, having a strong base was
crucial. Clapprood drew on the ``women's vote'' in her bid for
Congress (or, as she refers to it, the National Organization for
Men), but women did not provide a strong enough base to elect her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Harshbarger had a base, and Pat McGovern just didn't,''
said Elizabeth Sherman, director of the Center for Women in
Politics and Public Policy at the University of Massachusetts'
McCormack Institute. ``Not only that, but building a base is
extremely hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clapprood, a former state representative from Sharon, moved to
the district just a few months before Election Day; she had no time
to establish herself there. And Tracy, a former state
representative from Brighton, has a base ``the size of a postage
stamp,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who, under former Governor Michael S. Dukakis was the
first woman and only woman to hold statewide office in
Massachusetts, said changing politics takes decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year was a measure with all of the women running _ six
women running for statewide office and two in a congressional
race,'' Murphy said. ``But on the other side, the number of men is
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tina Cassidy is a member of the Globe's State House bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
