<SLUG> BC-MA-GOVERNOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS ISSUE LOOMS AS FACTOR IN GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A host of issues, from taxes to education, will
dominate the next seven weeks of public debate in the race for
governor, but one factor in the campaign will probably not be
mentioned: the issue of class and culture that is the trademark of
Massachusetts politics.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 race may well turn on whether Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger can avoid being labeled an elitist and bridge the gulf
between the liberal/reformist wing of the Democratic Party and the
so-called Reagan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why the Democratic nominee cannot make a campaign
speech these days without referring repeatedly to the ``working
families'' of Massachusetts and his promises to support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, the insistence on working families didn't resonate
with Harshbarger's profile,'' said Lou DiNatale, a senior fellow at
the University of Massachusetts' McCormack Institute for Public
Affairs. ``But it is becoming clear now that he understands that he
has to make the connection.''
</P>
<P>
   DiNatale said Massachusetts' Democratic leaders have been
struggling for years to keep its base intact despite class
divisions that have torn the party apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real concern within the party that there has been a
disconnect at the root level,'' DiNatale said. ``The leadership is
suburbanized and the vote is urbanized.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say that Harshbarger, a Pennsylvania native
and Harvard graduate who built his career as a reformer, has to
convince urban-based Democrats that he is more than a suburban
elitist and can relate to issues they care about.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove to be difficult running against Acting Governor
Paul Cellucci, whose roots are more connected to Massachusetts.
More important, he has learned his politics in Republican campaigns
that have exploited class and culture. In the 1988 presidential
campaign, Cellucci was part of George Bush's inner circle of
advisers who used the class or so-called wedge issues to alienate
candidate Michael S. Dukakis from his Democratic base.
</P>
<P>
   That theme played out at the Democratic unity breakfast in a
Dorchester union hall Wednesday. While there was talk of rallying
behind the ticket, some party leaders, including Boston Mayor
Thomas M. Menino and House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, avoided
expressing enthusiasm for Harshbarger's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Menino, when talking with reporters, could hardly mention
Harshbarger, saying only that he supported the entire Democratic
ticket. But Finneran, a Mattapan legislator and a conservative
Democrat who supported Edward J. King in 1982, took a wait-and-see
attitude, saying he wanted to determine if Harshbarger would be
representing the ``loony left'' wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Payne, a Democratic media consultant, said the outcome in
November may hinge on how well Cellucci or Harshbarger defines the
issues of the campaign. And that, he said, will be played out
against the backdrop of old Democratic battles between former
governors Dukakis and King.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are both going to play for the Ed King Democrats, who
wander in and out of the Democratic Party in the gubernatorial
races,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said Harshbarger is obviously working hard to soften his
reformer/liberal image. For one, he noted, the attorney general has
successfully wooed some factions of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   But Payne said the best antidote to a Cellucci wedge campaign is
forcing other issues into the debate. ``Ed King used the same
issues as Cellucci has, death and taxes,'' Payne said. ``If you
don't have something in place to counter that, it becomes a
referendum on those issues. You have to establish your own
fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Cellucci's rhetoric, while not explicit, does use the
code words that touch on the class issue. Talking with reporters
last week, Cellucci touted his growing up in everyday Hudson and
painted Harshbarger as a liberal elitist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly to the left. I am much more in the
mainstream,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   He also used one of the touchstone phrases that identifies the
liberal elite when he described Harshbarger as hailing from an ``I
know better than you'' wing of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger is obviously sensitive to Cellucci's reverting to a
well-tested GOP strategy to alienate Democratic candidates from
their urban base. ``Paul Cellucci would like to run against the
past, set up all the straw men he can,'' he said. ``But he has to
run against my record. This is about the future. He has to figure
what is more popular, pander to the right wing or stand for
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
