<HEADLINE>
LESSONS CAN BE LEARNED FROM MONICAGATE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Enough wailing over the Clinton mess. We're
stuck with it. As individuals. As a country. The crucial thing now
is, what are we going to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   Use it to learn something? Or continue to point fingers, play
the blame game and separate our chosen villain's actions from those
of the rest of the human race? Worse, must we keep behaving as
though some dark force outside ourselves has made the innocent,
God-fearing people of the United States the victims of a national
disaster?
</P>
<P>
   You can condemn the president, his wife, Monica Lewinsky,
Kenneth Starr or all of them until the end of time. But what has
happened _ every bit of it _ is a fair reflection of our unique and
often contradictory national ethos. We all own it.
</P>
<P>
   There are a slew of truths sticking out of the muck of
Monicagate, some that even the Christian right should love. We can
extract those truths and use them to become better, or at least
more honest people, or we can keep whining about what a shame the
whole thing is.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of whining, if I hear one more parent gripe about how
``unfair'' it is that the Clinton scandal has forced him or her to
talk to a child about ``things like oral sex,'' I may start
breaking windows. Yes, most parents want to control when and how
their children learn the details of that vast and eclectic realm we
call ``sex.'' Life in 1998 rarely cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   And you can't blame only the news media. Sexuality permeates our
culture and shows up in everything from the National Football
League to ``The Little Mermaid.'' Even Pat Robertson rarely misses
an opportunity to show videos of gay and lesbian ``sinners'' on
``The 700 Club.'' Being a '90s parent means always having to answer
questions about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, why don't parents ever gripe about how unfair it is to
have to explain why thousands of human beings sleep on the streets
of the richest nation in the world? Or why one in five American
kids live in poverty? Or why so many daddies beat up so many
mommies yet mommies have so few places to run and hide? Or why
lawmakers still make it easy for the tobacco industry to hook
people on poison?
</P>
<P>
   Why is some aspect of sex always the worst thing we must explain
to a child? Anyway, here's a starter list of lessons from the
Clinton scandal. Feel free to add on.
</P>
<P>
   1. If you're thinking about doing something you know is wrong,
don't ever go ahead just because you figure you won't get caught.
Anybody can get caught. These days, most people get caught. Even
people with executive privilege and Secret Service protection.
</P>
<P>
   2. Oh, what a tangled web we weave when first we practice to
deceive.
</P>
<P>
   3. Girls and young women, if you mess with a married man, you
relinquish all right to truth, justice and dignity _ no matter what
he tells you in the throes of passion. All of us are treated as we
demand to be treated. Behave as though you are just a receptacle
for another person's stress, frustration or bodily fluids, and you
will be treated as such. (Absolute truth: If he talks on the phone
while you perform an intimate physical act upon him, you do not
have his heart.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Despite what fans of the Defense of Marriage Act may tell us,
there is no one-size-fits-all model for a solid, long-lasting
marriage. The glue that keeps people together is often mysterious
and varies as much as bridal dresses do.
</P>
<P>
   5. For all our talk about it and our attempts to legislate it,
sex still confounds many Americans. Every day, recruiting from the
left and right, it makes a whole new army of hypocrites. (Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the straight-arrow patriarch of the House
Judiciary Committee, defends the Starr report and says its author
``belongs to the pantheon of saints.'' Then Hyde terms his own
sexual affair with a married woman, conducted when he was in his
mid-40s and also married, a ``friendship'' and a ``youthful
indiscretion.'')
</P>
<P>
   6. Men whose actions demean women in their personal lives can
paradoxically act to increase the power and status of women in
their public lives. (Bill Clinton has appointed more women to
Cabinet and top administrative posts than any other president in
history and has consistently helped protect all women's freedom to
govern their own reproductive systems.)
</P>
<P>
   7. No matter how cool their exterior, zealots sooner or later
lose control and are consumed by the fire of their mission. (See
Starr's $4.4 million, 465-page report and 18 boxes of supporting
evidence based on one sexual affair between one man and one woman.)
</P>
<P>
   8. When the world's most pervasive information-gathering medium
offers 24-hour, unobstructed views into the bedrooms of strangers,
millions of people look and look and look.
</P>
<P>
   9. As Otto von Bismark noted: ``Politics ruins the character.''
</P>
<P>
   10. Flawed people do good works. Good people have flaws. No one
is perfect. Many pretend to be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
