<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCIFULLY, THE PUBLIC IS ABOVE IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SOMMER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Despite the jubilation President Clinton's
hard-core detractors must be feeling following the release of
special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's X-files, the results of the
latest public opinion polls have to be downright maddening.
</P>
<P>
   After eight months of endless media coverage of the sex scandal
_ what New York Times columnist Frank Rich was the first to dub
``All Monica All The Time'' _ the President's job approval ratings
have remained remarkably and consistently high.
</P>
<P>
   The public has been saying clearly, for months, that it draws a
distinction between public policy and personal conduct, and sees
the Clinton affair, as distasteful as it is, to be a private matter
between Bill and Hillary. They concluded long ago that Starr is
anything but an ``independent'' counsel, and they want the sex
scandal to be put in its proper context _ somewhere far down the
list after issues like education, health care and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, the national media have insisted on shoving the
story down the public's throat. In the process, the shortening of
news cycles due to the Internet and around-the-clock TV news
outlets has led to a shameful erosion of journalistic standards.
</P>
<P>
   The president isn't alone in having been harmed by the scandal;
the national media, particularly television, have become so
corrupted in their reach for ratings that they now seem to have
more in common with Jerry Springer than Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   The initial media frenzy the week the Monica Lewinsky story
broke offered telltale signs of what was to come. ABC's Sam
Donaldson got out of the starting gate to recklessly speculate
about an imminent presidential resignation, possibly coming that
week. CNN and the 24-hour wannabes CNBC, MSNBC and Fox News rushed
to dress up the affair with doomsday titles, catchy graphics and
ominous-sounding countdowns.
</P>
<P>
   As days turned to weeks and then to months, a manufactured
hysteria has continued at a feverish pitch, with the networks and
cable news broadcasts calling on a stable of first-, second- and
even fifth- and sixth-string commentators necessary to feed the
around-the-clock programming. To ensure sparks, the most
opinionated and often extreme partisans, such as Bob Barr, the
obscure Republican congressman from Georgia who seems to have a
pathological hatred for Clinton, have become familiar faces. Many
of these commentators have made a habit of mixing fact and fiction,
or leaving facts out altogether when convenient. Talk radio meets
talk television.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbingly, the national media rejoice in their ``conventional
wisdom'' while remaining oblivious to the free fall of their
journalistic standards.
</P>
<P>
   When habitually unprepared Larry King isn't asking guests about
the scandal, he's pausing to ask them, straight-faced, if the media
are covering the story too much. CNN had the audacity to convene
journalists who have been reporting on the story and call it a
``town meeting.'' ``Meet the Press'' lent respectability to
Internet smut sleuth Matt Drudge by having him on as a guest.
</P>
<P>
   The sorry performance of television is reflected in the title of
Danny Schechter's brilliant new book on TV journalism, ``The More
You Watch, The Less You Know'' (Seven Stories Press).
</P>
<P>
   Schechter, a former producer for CNN and ABC's ``20/20,''
describes how the push for ratings by corporate-owned broadcast
media held in fewer and fewer hands has brought a descent into
info-tainment programming and its fill of gossip, soft news and
celebrities at the expense of stories with substance that are told
with context and nuance. The Clinton sex scandal, like the coverage
of O.J., or the JonBenet Ramsey or Menendez Brothers stories, is
made to order for this kind of tabloid programming.
</P>
<P>
   That's made the public's rebuke of this force-fed story _
reflected in the president's approval ratings _ all the more
astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show almost no change in the public approval
ratings for the president that have been issued regularly since
January. An NBC/Wall Street Journal poll put the president's
approval rating at 67 percent last week. That was followed by the
Los Angeles Times, 64 percent; Gallup/CNN, 63 percent; CBS, 61
percent; and ABC and The Washington Post, 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the dire predictions that the release of Starr's
report would finally send the president's approval ratings south
the way Watergate did for Richard Nixon or Iran-contra had for
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the public is very troubled by Clinton's tryst with
a White House intern and his choice to cover it up by lying. It has
sent his personal approval ratings plummeting. Three recent polls
disclosed that close to 60 percent of the public favors some form
of reprimand. But the same polls show the public overwhelmingly
wants the president to finish his term.
</P>
<P>
   That stands in contrast to the more than 70 newspapers that have
called for the president's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show around 30 percent of the public wants Clinton
impeached, but that number should be seen in some context,
according to Arkansas pollster and longtime Clinton observer Ernie
Oakleaf of Opinion Research Associates. That percentage of the
public has always shown up in the polls with an intense dislike
toward Clinton, whether in Arkansas or the nation at large.
</P>
<P>
   What's striking is after months of being pummeled by a story
that the national media won't let up on, people are thinking for
themselves. So much for the cynical view that if you tell the
public anything long enough, they'll simply go along for the ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
