<HEADLINE>
LIVE FROM BELOW THE BELTWAY: THE KENNETH STARR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I recently wrote that every age gets the scandal
it deserves, and this is the age of Jerry Springer. I got to
thinking about that, and came up with this question: How is the
Jerry Springer show different from the Kenneth Starr show?
</P>
<P>
   1. The fights on the Springer show are fake.
</P>
<P>
   2. Springer features entertaining losers and trailer trash.
</P>
<P>
   3. The obscene language on the Springer show is bleeped.
</P>
<P>
   4. The audience enjoys the Springer show.
</P>
<P>
   5. The Springer show is simply the symbol of the decline of
America, not the downfall itself.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have never seen Springer, but understand
Washington, it works like this:
</P>
<P>
   In front of a howling audience, say Congress, a sleaze in a suit
asks prosecutorial questions of a couple of people with sordid
problems, say, a president and an intern. On the bottom of the TV
screen is a subtitle describing their problems, like ``They had
inappropriate relations.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the show, a new element is introduced, whether
it's a wife, a congressman with his own sordid problems, or a
videotape. Hairpulling and chair-throwing ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Two more differences between Starr and Springer:
</P>
<P>
   6. No one really gets hurt on the Springer show.
</P>
<P>
   7. It ends.
</P>
<P>
   This is never going to end. We're all in Clinton-Starr
purgatory. You can't even escape it in an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday night, Rick Rajecki of Oakland was flying home
from Burbank on Southwest Airlines. The flight attendants passed
out pieces of paper so the passengers could vote on whether
President Clinton should leave office or stay.
</P>
<P>
   One flight attendant, a Clinton fan, offered an extra bag of
peanuts to passengers who would vote in favor of the president. No
one took the bribe. Instead, there was a serious debate among the
passengers, who voted 19 to 17, with two undecided, that Clinton
should stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   The two undecideds must have changed planes at Burbank from a
UFO.
</P>
<P>
   So you think you're tired of Bill, Monica, Ken and all those
philandering members of Congress? You can always turn off the
scandal and watch Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who work at newspapers are forced to follow the
Beltway bad sex show. We have one TV tuned to Springer for relief,
but the sound is turned down and we guess the topic from across the
room by the bad hairdos and piercings.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to guess the topic on CNN. How long can you watch
Greta Van Susteren before she becomes Van Insufferable?
</P>
<P>
   The high road has been washed out by the unending sleaze storm.
We're no longer making jokes. The incoming faxes and Internet
postings are worse than ever. The only printable one I received
last week was from a support group for women named Monica.
</P>
<P>
   How about a support group for those of us called Americans?
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of it all, a fresh bucket of cold slime was thrown
in Republicans' faces by San Francisco's own high-toned Webzine,
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   You have to give them credit for pinning a big scarlet A and H
for ``Adultery'' and ``Hypocrisy'' on House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill. The A and H can be pronounced ``Ah'' or
``Ha.''
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in Salon said they wouldn't have released the
details of Hyde's affair of 30 years ago if this were ``a different
and better world.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, is it not, and never will be.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde referred to his affair as ``youthful indiscretions'' even
though he was in his jowly 40s and the thing went on for years.
Maybe he was referring to his beautician lover, who seemed youthful
in the photo in Salon. Finally, a beautician in Salon.
</P>
<P>
   The latest thing is adding up newspapers calling for Clinton's
resignations. The latest total is that far too many newspapers have
called for Clinton's resignation. Why bother? The old goat will
never resign.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to pick up women when you're on workfare.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I hit the wall. I took two days off from this column
to research and write an upbeat story that has absolutely nothing
to do with politics. A little notice said ``Rob Morse is on
assignment,'' although I wanted it to say, ``Rob Morse is sick of
the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That upbeat story hasn't run yet, because it comes with
photographs, and there's no room in the newspaper because of the
constantly breaking smut from Washington. There may never be room
in the paper, if politicians' sexual affairs keep being revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans think they will gain from this scandal,
particularly if they keep Clinton under a steady water-torture of
leaks. Sorry, the only ones to gain from this will be glass
companies, who'll be rebuilding all the shattered glass houses.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, scandal fans. If you loved Jerry Springer's ``Too Hot for
TV'' video, there's now Bill Clinton's ``Too Hot to Talk to Ken''
video, with dirty words you've never heard on TV before.
</P>
<P>
   You read the book, now watch the video. Try not to throw any
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
