<SLUG> BC-NUDISTS-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS BARE ALL AGAINST ANTI-NUDITY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Nudists thumbed their noses and exposed all
other body parts at Berkeley's anti-nudity ordinance Sunday in
their seventh annual romp in the raw.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by gawkers, warmed by the sun and unhassled by the
police, the small group paraded their bare breasts and bottoms for
2 1/2 hours to the accompaniment of drums, bells and a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   By actual count, there was one naked woman, X-Plicit Players
troupe leader Deborah Moore, two bare-breasted women and a dozen
naked men _ most of them wearing shoes and hats, some with gaudy
adornments and one with a tattoo of flames around his bottom.
</P>
<P>
   They hoisted placards reading ``Our Bodies Are Freedom of
Speech,'' ``Human Nature'' and ``Exalt the Body,'' and they drew a
crowd of about 200 to People's Park and several dozen to street
corners where they stopped to pose and rap.
</P>
<P>
   Some spectators who inadvertently caught the show were offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this naked guy up in a tree, and I asked, `What are
you doing up in the tree?' and he said, `It feels right,''' said
John Hunter of Oakland, shaking his head. ``It's cool to be nude,
but they're not doing it the right way. Besides, they're real
ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become another form of art. We've become sacred
sculpture,'' intoned Moore as she prepared to lead the group from
People's Park to Telegraph Avenue. ``We appreciate the love that
you give.''
</P>
<P>
   The group mantra that evolved during what its organizers call
the Nude and Breast Freedom Parade was ``where else but in Berkeley
can we be free?''
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley hasn't had a lot of success in enforcing an anti-nudity
ordinance enacted in 1993, inspired by a pro-skin activist who
became famous as ``The Naked Guy.'' The ordinance made public
nudity a misdemeanor. The Berkeley City Council amended the
ordinance in July to allow prosecutors to charge violators with
either an infraction or a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Charging naked people with infractions is a means of bypassing
trial by jury and leaving findings and fines of up to $400 to a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and co-performer Marty Kent sued the city last week,
asserting that the ordinance is a denial of their civil rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
