<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INVITRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNIQUE COULD REDUCE MULTIPLE BIRTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With sidebar, SCI-INVITRO-SUCCESS)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON - &UR;  &LR; Though they have given hope _ and babies _ to
thousands of infertile couples, in vitro fertilization clinics have
also been creating many multiple-birth pregnancies that sometimes
end in miscarriages, deaths, or costly medical complications.
</P>
<P>
   But a new embryo transfer technique developed in the past year
may finally allow the IVF enterprise to dramatically reduce the
multiple-birth problem while maintaining, or even improving, the
often frustratingly low rate of successful pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to curb the births of triplets and higher multiples is
being intensified by managed-care insurers, who are beginning to
demand that IVF providers meet performance benchmarks, a process
that may lead to something of a shakeout in Massachusetts and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At one IVF program in Boston, an infertility scientist who has
triplets of her own is almost ecstatic about the newest technique
for reliably getting women pregnant with just one or two embryos.
The breakthrough, called ``blastocyst transfer,'' enables newly
fertilized eggs to be grown in laboratory dishes for five days
instead of three, so they're more mature and likely to ``take''
when implanted into the patient's uterus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny being in the position I am now,'' says Katherine
Rakowsky, director of the IVF lab at Brigham and Women's Hospital,
where about 70 blastocyst transfers have been performed. While
Rakowsky welcomed the birth of her own triplets (now healthy and
happy at age 11) after years of infertility, she says, ``I've seen
the other side of it: A lot of these multiple pregnancies do fail,
and it's not a pretty sight.''
</P>
<P>
   While the successful birth of septuplets last year in Iowa may
have fostered a belief that medicine can create a happy ending to
all multiple births, that's far from the case.
</P>
<P>
   Even twins have a higher rate of prematurity and complications,
resulting in average birth costs of about $40,000 compared to
$10,000 for single births, says Dr. Fredric Frigoletto, an
obstetrician at Massachusetts General Hospital. Triplets send the
costs spiralling to about $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   These expenses reflect additional hospitalization, intensive
care, and other interventions, he says. The risk of fetal death is
12 times higher in triplet births than in singletons, and there are
more complications, such as brain damage, respiratory distress, and
developmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   Edward and Jeannine Shea of Braintree, Mass. have 2-year-old
triplets who were born eight weeks premature following IVF. The
doctors implanted all three of the embryos that resulted from in
vitro fertilization in Jeannine's womb: All of them ``took.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thrilled because I knew there was a big risk until
they got here, and then a lot of work after they arrived,'' says
Edward Shea. The triplets spent 3 1/2 weeks in the hospital, and
one had respiratory problems requiring a breathing machine. ``He is
still developmentally a little slower,'' says the father.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 Massachusetts programs provide in vitro fertilization,
which is about 20 years old in the United States, along with other
infertility treatments. IVF involves harvesting a number of eggs
from a woman's ovaries after they have been stimulated with drugs,
and fertilizing them outside the body with sperm from her partner
or a donor. Sometimes donor eggs are used if the woman is incapable
of producing her own.
</P>
<P>
   The embryos are allowed to develop for two or three days in a
laboratory dish, and then the healthiest-appearing are selected to
be implanted into the woman's uterus. Because not all embryos will
implant in the uterine lining and develop normally, IVF
practitioners have traditionally transferred more than one _ often
several _ in hopes that at least one will implant.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rub: The results can't be predicted, and in many IVF
clinics 20 or 30 percent or even more pregnancies result in twins,
and about 3 percent or so are triplets or greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider that not a success, but a failure,'' says Dr. Vito
Cardone, director of the Fertility Center of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reduce these rates by transferring fewer embryos can
lead to a lower pregnancy rate, making patients and clinic
directors alike unhappy. Conversely, struggling clinics sometimes
boost the number of embryos transferred, achieving higher pregnancy
rates but also producing more twins, triplets, or even quadruplets.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Center for Health Statistics reported a
``remarkable'' increase in triplet and higher-multiple births over
the last two decades, from 1,034 births in 1971 to 4,973 in 1995.
About a third of the increase is due solely to women having babies
at a later age when multiple births are more likely; the remainder
are believed to be due to fertility treatments, including IVF.
Massachusetts, the report noted, had the highest triplet birth
ratio in the country from 1992 to 1994, more than twice as high as
the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Women who develop multiple pregnancies can opt for ``selective
reduction'' _ terminating one or more fetuses _ to improve the odds
that some will survive and be healthy. But such selective abortion
is a tough decision, and many women can't accept it.
</P>
<P>
   IVF specialists are now hoping for a sharp drop in unwanted
multiple pregnancies as clinics here and elsewhere begin to adopt
the blastocyst transfer technique.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, scientists were unable to sustain many embryos
in the laboratory to the 5-day-old blastocyst stage, but a new
culture medium developed by Dr. David Gardner, a Colorado
scientist, has sharply improved success rates. At Brigham and
Women's, about 30 percent of embryos are now grown to the
blastocyst stage, says Dr. Elizabeth Ginsburg, head of the IVF
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   And, she added, about 60 percent of patients whose embryos
become blastocysts are achieving pregnancy _ a substantially higher
rate than with 3-day-old embryos, she says.
</P>
<P>
   No births have occurred yet, but as of last week there were 28
ongoing pregnancies among 53 women who had blastocysts implanted,
she said. Since only two embryos are transferred into each woman,
there are no triplet pregnancies, though so far eight of the
pregnancies have been determined to be twins.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is Melissa Pelletier of Hingham, who, at 27, had
been trying to get pregnant for a year-and-a-half and didn't want
to risk having triplets. In March she had 25 eggs extracted from
her ovaries that, when fertilized with her husband's sperm, yielded
11 embryos. Three of those, the most viable, made it to the
blastocyst stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They implanted two, and two took,'' says Pelletier, who says
she is thrilled with the results.
</P>
<P>
   Because IVF specialists had not been able to accurately predict
how many 3-day-old embryos would result in pregnancies, IVF success
rates and multiple-pregnancy rates have been hard to control. But
in the laboratory, only the strongest embryos appear to make it to
the more mature blastocyst stage, when the embryo has a distinct
layer of cells that help it implant into the uterine lining, says
Rakowsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
