<HEADLINE>
KEEPING YOUR HEAD ABOVE THE WATERLILIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Emerging from the Museum of Fine Arts' marvelous Monet exhibit
you're funneled willy-nilly into the Monet shop, where
Impressionism meets capitalism, and you are overwhelmed and
underwhelmed by a multitude of Monet items, among them:
</P>
<P>
   _the Monet waterlilies wristwatch, $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   _the waterlilies Christmas ball, $36.
</P>
<P>
   _Le Petit Flowers of Monet Flower and Seed Mixture, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   _waterlilies French provincial soap, small $12.95, large $28.50.
</P>
<P>
   There's tons more phonet Monet in the main museum shop, too. The
waterlilies apron, ``with a handy pocket,'' $28. Waterlilies
placemats, set of four, $39.50. Waterlilies pillows, large $79.50,
small $50.95. Waterlilies hostess serving trays (``... the
delightful motif is sure to spark conversation! Made of smooth,
durable melamine''), $26 and $29.95. The waterlilies pencil caddy,
$18.50. And one of my favorites, Monet bottle stoppers (``Top your
favorite bottle of wine or olive oil with the work of an
Impressionist master!'') set of two, $32.
</P>
<P>
   There's Monet memorabilia for the kiddies, too, including
``Phillipe in Monet's Garden,'' $10.95, the illustrated tale of a
frog that finds a home among those famous waterlilies. The
companion stuffed Phillipe will set you back an additional $10.95.
He's very appealing, though, and a bargain, too, which is more than
can be said for some of the other Monet-related stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the Boston museum's retail arm, MFA
Enterprises, haven't thought of everything _ I confess I was
disappointed not to find a Monet oven mitt _ but they have
succeeded in placing Monet on an amazing array of merchandise.
``Monet is so popular as an artist,'' said Elise Germano, public
relations coordinator for MFA Enterprises. ``People just love his
images and want to have something to remember him by that is
beautiful and functional.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an understandable impulse. Alas, some museum-goers are
happy to settle for things that are merely functional. Although who
am I to say that the waterlilies accordian file isn't beautiful? I
will say, though, that at $35 it seems a little overpriced. But one
woman's trash is another's treasure. Wandering alone Friday morning
in the museum shop, I came upon a display of waterlilies playing
cards ($14.95 for two decks and a score pad). ``Oh, God,'' I said
out loud, ``a Monet bridge set.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman nearby said, ``Yes, they make lovely gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Museums increasingly depend upon retail sales for revenue, which
inevitably leads to items like Monet bridge sets. With its popular
catalog and five satellite stores in local malls, the MFA has one
of the biggest museum retail operations in the nation. According to
Germano, sales of museum merchandise were off last year. ``We
didn't have the response to our catalog we'd hoped,'' she said.
``Some years it's really great and some years it's awful.''
</P>
<P>
   This year is bound to be one of those really great years, with
the Monet exhibit packing 'em in through the end of December.
Friday morning, traffic was heavy in the museum shop, and the show
had yet to open to the general public. ``How's business?'' I asked
the woman who rang up my waterlilies salt and pepper shakers, $24,
a must in any civilized home. ``It's been wild,'' she said. ``And
it's going to get wilder.''
</P>
<P>
   At the T-shirt display two women were debating a purchase. The
T-shirts, $15.95, are tasteful, as T-shirts go, and, perversely,
made me wish I could buy a really tacky one emblazoned, ``My
Friends Went to the Monet Exhibit and All I Got Was This Lousy
T-Shirt.'' Compared with a Monet bottle stopper, that doesn't seem
all that tacky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
