<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES THE WIND BLOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How is wind formed?
</P>
<P>
   A.Z., Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Bob Dylan said ``You don't need a weatherman to know which
way the wind blows.'' But a forecaster is handy if you want to know
why it blows.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologist Chris Bedford of Weather Services, Inc. says you
can thank the sun for the winds that blow, from the gentlest zephyr
to the fiercest hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun heats the atmosphere, some air gets warmer than other
air. In warm air, the sun's heat speeds up the random motion of
molecules of oxygen, nitrogen, carbon dioxide and water vapor, and
they spread apart. In colder air, the ``calmer'' molecules stay
more tightly-packed together.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine two boxes of the same size, one around a section of
warm air, one around colder air. The box of warm air contains fewer
molecules. That air literally weighs less, so the pressure it
exerts on anything around it is lower. The box of cold air has more
molecules, weighs more, and exerts higher pressure. That's what
weather people mean when they talk about low pressure and high
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Where air at higher pressure meets air at lower pressure, (what
meteorologists call a weather front) the high pressure air
molecules move toward the area where the pressure is lower and the
resistance is less. That movement of molecules is wind.
</P>
<P>
   The greater the difference in pressure, the faster the high
pressure air moves toward the lower pressure, and the faster the
wind blows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do tornadoes start?
</P>
<P>
   P.C., Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Take one unit of cold, dry air at high pressure and high
altitude and mix it with an equal dose of warm, moist air with
significantly lower pressure closer to the ground. Get the warm air
moving up into the cold, dry air, and you've got the basic
ingredients for a thunderstorm, and possibly a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologist Howard Bluestein of Oklahoma University, a noted
authority on tornadoes, says the chances for a twister increase if
the thunderstorm then develops into a supercell, a storm that
contains something called a mesocyclone.
</P>
<P>
   That can develop when the winds outside the storm vary in speed
and direction as they vary their height, what's called wind shear.
The wind speeds can be as much as four times faster at 20,000 feet
than they are closer to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Even though those twisting winds are outside the thunderstorm,
they sometimes start a column of air inside the storm spinning like
the axle of a car, horizontally, above the ground. That's the
beginning of the mesocyclone, which can grow to three miles long
and five miles high.
</P>
<P>
   Now, remember that warm moist air rising into the storm? The
faster it rises, and the greater the wind shear, the faster the
mesocyclone will spin.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the rising warm air grabs that spinning column and
bends it around from horizontal to a more vertical direction. To
understand how this works, spin a pencil in your hands, level with
the ground. Now imagine warm air hitting the eraser, and pushing it
upward, dropping the point downward. Keep spinning the pencil. When
that vertical column of spinning air descends to the ground, you
have a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms that don't develop mesocyclones also can spawn
tornadoes, however, when very strong updrafts of warm air inside
the storm clash with falling columns of colder air and set things
spinning. These tornados tend to be weaker. Scientists aren't sure
exactly how they develop. Nor do they know why some thunderstorms
develop into supercells and some don't, or why some supercell
thunderstorms spawn tornadoes, and some don't.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has more tornadoes than any other nation _ 75
percent of the Earth's total, in fact _ because of the unique way
the Rocky Mountains and Great Plains bring warm moist air from the
Gulf of Mexico into a region of strong wind shear. The National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration says this country averages
about 800 tornadoes a year, and about 100 tornado-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Bluestein says the fastest tornadic wind ever measured &UR;  &LR;  was
about 280 miles an hour. Incidentally, the Fujita Scale used to
measure the strength of tornadoes rates them not by wind speed but
by the severity of the damage they do. The weakest, F-0s and F-1s,
will rip off loose shingles and take down some branches and small
trees. F-5s destroy large well-built buildings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
