<HEADLINE>
DIGGING DEEPER AND DEEPER FOR DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The letter dishing on Henry Hyde came to me from
Florida way back in July.
</P>
<P>
   As is strict policy in the only venue over which I have a
modicum of control _ my own writing _ it was immediately put in the
bottom of a locked drawer that over the years has come to contain
about two inches worth of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Not the dark and grimy kind, but stuff passing on rumors or
making accusations about the private lives of public figures; my
collection is nearly all sex and drugs, with a few phony academic
and military service records, child-support misdeeds, business
career scams, and one side-splittingly detailed ``cheats at golf''
allegation.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from Florida was unusual in three respects, not
including the abnormally ugly nature of the tale: The writer signed
his name, included a return address, and printed his phone number.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Norman Sommer really lives in Aventura, south of
Hollywood, and really is a retiree pal of the former husband of the
woman Hyde had a five-year affair with in the late 1960s. What's
more, he really was authorized by his embittered pal to try to put
the story out. The method he chose, sending his letter to several
writers, talking by phone with a few others, and nothing more, was
engagingly naive, serving to buttress his bona fides as an
untutored story manager and free agent.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't have touched this story with a 10-foot pole,
believing as I do that private behavior is irrelevant to public
character, always has been and always will be. But after checking
Sommer out, I never forgot his letter the way I do most of this
stuff, because it struck me as a slow-burning fuse that was likely
to blow, given the current absence of standards of any meaning in
journalism and given the white-hot atmosphere of the effort to kick
President Clinton out of office. That the Hyde affair began on the
Internet (Salon magazine) and moved instantly into traditional
outlets was utterly unsurprising.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising, however, was both the intemperate
vituperation of the right's reaction to the unveiling of Hyde's
steamy past and its almost desperate, flailing effort _ without so
much as a shred of evidence _ to accuse senior White House official
Sidney Blumenthal of being the ultimate source or a purveyor of the
story. And even more surprising was the routine willingness of the
press to print smears that had no substance (as in a specific
accusation of a specific act) and no evidence, and are known by
some of us with direct knowledge of the affair to be false.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the likes of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas, slimy ex-DDT pusher that he is, from floating Blumenthal's
name in almost the same sentence he acknowledged having no evidence
of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   But listen to this tortured wreck of a sentence he, Speaker Newt
Gingrich and Majority Leader Dick Armey came up with in a letter to
FBI director Louis Freeh demanding an investigation of a
nonexistent crime:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether ot not that specific story originated with the White
House or its allies, clearly there is credible evidence that an
organized campaign of slander and intimidation may exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's Illinois toady, a no-account Republican congressman named
Ray LaHood, then said he had fingered Blumenthal by ``process of
elimination.'' For emphasis, he added a comment of mind-blowing
idiocy, ``I think this is Sidney Blumen-thal's MO.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from there being no evidence that Representative LaHood
ever thought anything, the fact is that this is not Blumenthal's
modus operandi. I've dealt with him all year during this mess; he
is tough as nails on the subject of Kenneth Starr, but more
interesting than a blunderbuss like James Carville because he is
substantive. The only negative information I have heard him utter
is public record stuff about past misdeeds and related court
sanctions involving senior members of Starr's prosecution team. It
may be chic around town to Blame Sidney when all else fails. But
the fact remains he plays this game square and to my direct
knowledge has not tossed so much as a molecule of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, this latest outburst of silly irresponsibility on
the right is a clue to the shaky knees of the increasingly partisan
Republican Impeachment Crusade. The Hyde story will not hurt Hyde
among the same general public than puts President Clinton's conduct
in perspective, and it certainly won't hurt among tolerant
Democrats. But it will hurt among the Cotton Mather wannabe
fruitcakes of the Crusade who actually think this kind of junk
matters.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Week Two of a supposedly solemn constitutional
exercise. You ready for another year of it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
