<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WILL-GRACE-BOS &LR;      09-21 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WILL-GRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD COUPLE EVENLY MATCHED IN CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WILL AND GRACE 
Starring: Debra Messing, Eric McCormack, Sean Hayes, Megan
Mullally 
On: NBC 
Time: Monday at 9:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no shortage of hand-on-hip flirtation and morning-after
sexuality between all those chiseled men and aerobicized women in
sitcomland, that's for sure. But while former lovers tediously
torment themselves on ``Friends'' and future lovers do their
endless little dance on ``Caroline in the City,'' along comes a
smart new comedy that pays homage to pure friendship between the
sexes. Called ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' it's a TV-sized version of ``The
Object of My Affection'' and ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' in which
the heroine's most uncomplicated and enduring love is for the gay
man who is her best friend. It's the latest entry in NBC's
strangely long line of series about unmarried people.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the post-``Ellen'' prime-time world, where a sitcom
featuring an openly gay central character doesn't need to be hugely
controversial. Nor does it seem necessary for this lead gay
character to fixate on his sexual orientation or spend every week
educating America about its hardships (sorry, Ellen). The first two
episodes of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' are character-based and wonderfully
lesson-free, with Will's gayness treated as a comfortable given, as
one facet of his personality. There are a smattering of gay jokes
and a queeny, more stereotypically gay supporting character, but
it's all part of the show's larger portrait of friendship and
intimacy in New York City. After presenting Will as a gay man, will
the show go on to neuter him? Will he be allowed to have as much of
a dating life as Grace? Let's wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is pretty simple: Can the ideal friendship between Will
and Grace survive the mundanities of living together? The initial
episodes set up the situation. Will is an easygoing lawyer whose
boyfriend recently moved out, and Grace is an insecure interior
designer in the process of leaving her boyfriend, a guy who
high-fives her after sex. By the end of next week's show, the two
are roommates, challenging the notion that good fences make good
neighbors. As Will and Grace, Eric McCormack and Debra Messing are
appealing, if not especially dynamic. They have a pleasing
chemistry: She relies on his advice (even for decorating, despite
the fact that she's a decorator), and he enjoys being relied upon
by her.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks belong to the two strong supporting players. Sean
P. Hayes, recently appearing in movie theaters in ``Billy's
Hollywood Screen Kiss,'' is Will's show-tune-singing pal. He
arrives to stay with Will for a few weeks, carrying a hatbox and a
birdcage, and he can't understand why everyone assumes he likes
men. He tosses tart lines like ``Welcome to Cynical Island.
Population: You'' in Will's direction, and he appears to have a
charged relationship with his mother. He's a gay cliche, except
that Hayes invests Jack with a distinctively runtlike twist. Megan
Mullally plays Grace's assistant, Karen, an aristocratic woman who
wears mink in the office and doesn't quite understand the whole
work thing. Next week's episode includes an absolutely delightful
scene in which Jack and Karen meet and engage in the most curious
and original flirtation I've ever seen. Like any two unique
characters, they ... rub stomachs. You have to see it.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for sexual tension amid the laugh track, or
social and political point-making between the punchlines, then
``Will &AMP; Grace'' may not work for you. It's a sitcom that has the
potential to prove to prime time that attractions between adults
are not always rooted in lust. With its promising little ensemble,
the biggest problem is that it's scheduled opposite ``Ally
McBeal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FARMER-BOS &LR;      09-21 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FARMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUMBLING HUMANITY, RESILIENCE OF A FARMING FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Young Nebraska farmers Juanita and Darrel Buschkoetter, the
hard-toiling parents of three girls, are more than mere survivors.
They are heroes: people-sized, credible American originals. Despite
their frailties, they are unbreakable _ but not unbendable. With
heart and ingenuity, they manage to flex when the fierce pressures
of family farming threaten to bankrupt their business and mow down
their marriage. Somehow, they never finally surrender their love,
their unflinching decency, or their dream, all the more poignant
for its modesty, to endure as small grain and cattle farmers in the
middle of America.
</P>
<P>
   When the characters in a movie or book or play lodge in your
mind and heart, stubbornly taking up residence without necessarily
being invited, you know the artist responsible for them has done
something very right.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with ``The Farmer's Wife,'' David Sutherland's
nonfiction film covering three years in the struggling lives of the
Buschkoetters. Shaping their daily routine into a memorable
narrative is an imaginative feat achieved by Sutherland in this
artfully textured, heart-wrenching film.
</P>
<P>
   Presented by the PBS public affairs series Frontline, the
three-part, six-and-a-half-hour documentary airs Monday-Wednesday
at 9 p.m. This is a big investment of time for any viewer, and some
of the film moves with the kind of deliberate, almost ritual,
slowness of the grinding farm work that can occupy Darrel 15 hours
a day. But this deeply American tale of loss and renewal will repay
your attention in countless ways. To see only sections of it would
diminish the accumulating emotional impact of Part 3. In it, as the
Buschkoetter farm seems miraculously about to flourish, their
marriage teeters on the verge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   That all of this matters so much is a tribute to the vision and
tenacity of Sutherland who, of course, didn't know how his episodic
story would turn out when he began filming in 1994. But he clearly
appreciated the humanity and remarkable resourcefulness of the
extraordinary ``ordinary'' people who are his subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Though articulate, especially describing his love for Juanita _
``my everything,'' he calls her _ Darrel is notable for his
singular sense of purpose. Losing his vocation would, he says, be
like ``cutting off my leg.'' Almost every calorie he burns is
calculated to grow things and bind his family to the land. His
arsenal of skills is a measure of the harsh requirements of
independent farmers (and surely among the reasons so few can
survive today). Darrel is an able car and farm-machinery mechanic
who can operate huge combines and harvesters; something of a
self-taught veterinarian and naturalist; a fence-mending cowboy;
businessman; and dexterous handyman.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita, whose sharp-cut prettiness makes her resemble a Walker
Evans portrait of the Depression, is sweet and tough, gifted with
agile intelligence and keen insight. It's not too much to say she
saves the day: securing loans that prop up the farm, lovingly
minding her daughters, stretching the family's faltering income,
and even in the middle of marital anguish, candidly articulating
and coping with her own shortcomings as well as Darrel's.
</P>
<P>
   The arc of the long film is simple: A farm is besieged by debt
and bad weather and falling commodity prices; a relationship is
assailed by money woes, intergenerational tension, and a painful
shift in the balance of power between husband and wife. Much of it
unfolds on the Buschkoetters' flat, often muddy, leased land, in or
nearby their little yellow house where the daughters share a room
and a big bed.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland employs the peeling house as chief location and
resonant leitmotif. Its deteriorating image, captured in every
season, often under severely beautiful skies, serves as a richly
poetic icon, distilling themes of isolation and despair,
domesticity and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   This is a document about love, and also about sheer toil _
including Darrel's body-busting extra job as a factory laborer and
Juanita's work as a maid cleaning the toilets of more prosperous
farmers. There is little repose or escape: a rare family birthday
celebration, a festive Halloween party for the girls Juanita funds
with five scraped-together dollars. Release is found mostly in
sleep or in the joys of more thankful labor. In the planting
season, Darrel considers his nearly sleepless nights churning up
his fields aboard a huge, clattering planter better than going to a
party.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, the almost mystical stillness you sense when
Darrel and Juanita face the camera during the few semiformal
interviews that interlard the spontaneous, cinema verite footage of
``The Farmer's Wife.'' Even as they argue, they are immobile: Spent
from work, they seem to economize their physical gestures,
conserving energy to invest in their cherished farm.
</P>
<P>
   It would be dishonest to say there aren't moments of tedium in
``The Farmer's Wife.'' On the other hand, it is precisely
Sutherland's patient, unsentimental attention to telling detail
that can alchemize the most ordinary-seeming moment into emotional
gold. In one scene that can only really be appreciated on screen,
Darrel, his back to the camera, lugs a heavy tire from one place to
another. Slightly angled under its weight, he is a humbling picture
of Sisyphean perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Humbling, in fact, is an apt word for the Buschkoetters, and the
ingenuity, resilience, and sacrifice they bring to their love and
work. Their unshakable humanity is humbling, and so, too, is
filmmaker Sutherland's homage to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
