<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WARS-ART-BOS &LR;      09-21 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WARS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESCRIPTION FOR WAR: TOO MANY YOUNG MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A map is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What triggers most wars is not ideology or honor, says a new
theory based on evolutionary biology, but a society bottom-heavy
with young, unmarried and violence-prone males. When their numbers
become too great, this explanation holds, they form ``coalitions''
bent on seizing territory, goods or other resources they need to
marry and have offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is being put foward by researchers probing the
biological roots of war, who say their analysis of population
patterns shows that this evolutionary perspective explains
conflicts from ancient times to today's hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of its political trappings and illusions and cast in
terms more typical of descriptions of animal behavior, what the
theory says is that war is ``a form of intrasexual male competition
among groups, occasionally to obtain mates but more often to
acquire the resources necessary to attract and retain
mates,'' &UR;  &LR; according to two Canadian psychologists who advanced this
theory at a meeting in Boston recently.
</P>
<P>
   The new view challenges the classic belief that old men start
wars and send young men to die in battle. In fact, the authors
write, ``those leaders are probably as much a creation of the
coalition (of young, aggressive men) as they are the instigators''
of wars. However, it may be true at times, they say, that wars have
been a means for older leaders to deal with a surplus of young men
vying with them for a society's resources. Such wars, they add,
usually occur ``when a majority of the population reach some degree
of ideological consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   And since evolutionary theory also holds that women's best
strategy for reproducing _ and advancing their own kind _ is to
choose mates with enough resources to rear children, it's not
surprising that women have historically been the ones over whom the
wars have been fought, rather than the combatants, say the
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothesis is the work of Christian G. Mesquida, a graduate
student, and Neil I. Wiener, a professor in the psychology
department at York University in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   They described their analysis at the Boston conference and said
it could ultimately yield tools for identifying world regions ripe
for conflict before trouble breaks out. Even without further
refinement, the model hints at potential trouble in China, they
say, where a population imbalance favoring young males is fast
building. The evidence they've been gathering is so strong, they
contend, that it may prove that that an abundance of young males is
``a necessary condition for the emergence of violent conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Their hypothesis, presented at a session entitled ``Biology and
War,'' is one of many new approaches to explaining why human
societies are afflicted with war and violence. Mesquida said the
``young male'' explanation ``brings a new way to look at conflict _
from the bottom up instead of top-down.'' Better yet, it could
enable scientists to predict violence-prone areas, much as
geologists can identify areas where building tensions below ground
threaten to trigger earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat: the theory applies to offensive, not defensive,
wars. Thus the young US soldiers cut down during the Normandy
invasion in 1944 were not driven by the same biological imperatives
as the Nazi youth who helped carry Hitler into power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will apply to the Iraqi army, not to the multi-national
force dispatched to contain it,'' say the authors of the study.
``It will apply to the European soldiers who conquered the
Americas'' but not the native peoples who opposed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that rapid population growth shifts demographics so
that the proportion of young males (aged 15-29) rises in comparison
with older males,'' said Wiener. ``When these young males become a
large proportion of the population, violence is frequent and
severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Their study found that conflict was increasingly likely and
severe in countries where young men made up 35 percent to 55
percent of the population. In the US, the proportion is currently
less than 30 percent, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In their presentation to the meeting of the Association for
Politics and the Life Sciences, Wiener and Mesquida said they had
analyzed the conflict history of several groups of nations and
found a strong correlation between violent outbreaks and periods of
growth in the young male population.
</P>
<P>
   They also mapped the population demographics in major countries
of the world and wars and rebellions over the last decade, and
found a strong matching pattern. Most of the conflicts have
occurred in the developing world, where male youths are numerous as
populations expand, making the competition for resources such as
land, food and available mates more intense.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern has been at work in the Congo and Rwanda as well as
in Sudan, Algeria, and the former Yugoslavia, the scientists said.
Mesquida noted in an interview that young male fighters may not be
conscious that what they are doing is seeking resources in order to
compete for wives, but in evolutionary terms, that is their
fundamental motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon Chagnon, a prominent anthropologist at the University
of California in Santa Barbara, said the Canadian researchers'
theory is a new twist on what he's long believed. ``They've focused
on a very important category of individuals _ young unmarried
males, who become problems in all societies &UR; '' &LR;  and can be the
cause of instability and war.
</P>
<P>
   Chagnon said various societies _ including the Yanomamo people
of Brazil, whom he long studied _ have tried to defuse the danger
by creating backbreaking chores for young men or _ in the case of
medieval society _ by sending them off on the Crusades.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the scientists noted, there's been no satisfactory
explanation for war, and many wars have been hard to predict,
including the revolution in Iran, the civil war in El Salvador, and
the invasion of Kuwait by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As horrifying and destructive as war is, some evolutionary
psychologists say it can be seen as an adaptation. As a strategy
for acquiring the resources to mate and produce offspring, warring
against a neighbor furthers the evolutionary mission of preserving
and promulgating your own genetic endowment and that of your
relatives. This fits, the authors say, with the fact that ``all
violent group confrontations are perpetrated almost exclusively by
young males'' of reproductive age, most of them unmarried.
</P>
<P>
   While saying their work is not yet sufficiently developed to
make firm predictions, Mesquida said one country where conditions
may be brewing trouble is China, in part because a preference for
male children is creating a growing imbalance. Soon after the turn
of the century there is expected to be a million more young men
than young women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
