<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CESAREAN-ART-BOS &LR;      09-21 1708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CESAREAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOVATIVE HOSPITAL EFFORT REDUCES RATE OF CAESAREANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mary Beckwith's labor pains started on August 21, the woman
headed straight for Lawrence (Mass.) General Hospital. The staff
sent her home.
</P>
<P>
   Malpractice? No, call it self-restraint _ a new and apparently
contagious attitude among some obstetricians and OB nurses that
might be characterized as ``stop me before I do another unnecessary
cesarean.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice of not admitting women to ``labor and delivery''
until their labors are progressing _ that is, until contractions
are strong, the womb is opening and its cervical neck thinning _ is
only one in a series of surprising recent changes in the policies
of dozens of US hospitals. But, obstetrical reformers say, it's one
of the most effective in reducing cesarean delivery rates, which
soared from an average of five percent in the 1970s to 25 percent
in the 1990s, and higher in some places.
</P>
<P>
   Sending women home until birth is imminent is important
symbolically too. It's a telling admission _ almost two decades
overdue, critics say _ that the American way of birth has become
mischievously over-medicalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were made to give birth,'' says Susan Leavitt, Lawrence
General's nurse-manager of labor and delivery and a national leader
in the movement to reform obstetrics. ``We have a lot of technology
to save moms and babies with, but we don't need to apply it to
every mom who comes through the door.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question of expectations. Admitting a woman to the
hospital starts a clock ticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When patients come into the hospital and sit around for
extended periods with contractions, we feel we have to do
something,'' explains Dr. Roy Bors-Koefoed of St. Elizabeth's
Medical Center in Boston. ``The patient expects it, thinking `I
must be in labor.' So we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt says avoiding premature admissions has been a key factor
in her hospital's four-year reduction in cesarean rates, from 26
percent of all births to 17 percent. So far, nobody has delivered
at home or in the car, as some feared would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we would rarely send patients home once they came
through our doors,'' Leavitt says. ``We were doing a lot of
cesareans on women not even in active labor yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients like it too, as long as they're carefully prepared for
what to expect. ``It's a useful and soothing thing to find out that
there's plenty of time and you can go back home and wait in
peace,'' says Beckwith, who was sent home at 4 p.m., returned at 7
when her contractions were getting strong. She delivered Jacob,
without the need for anesthesia, about 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Memorial is among 10 Massachusetts hospitals which
began four years ago to try to ``change the culture'' of
obstetrics, as Leavitt puts it, under a program sponsored by
Massachusetts Blue Cross/Blue Shield. Those 10 reduced their
average collective C-section rate from 25 percent in 1994 to 20
percent in 1997. The change may appear modest, but it translates
into hundreds fewer surgical births _ with no compromise in good
outcomes, participants say.
</P>
<P>
   During the same four-year period, the average hovered at 25 to
27 percent among a comparison group of 10 Bay State hospitals that
made no attempt to reduce their rates of surgical birth.
</P>
<P>
   As word has gotten around, the collective effort has gradually
expanded, to 27 hospitals by June of this year and 41 institutions
today _ all but 10 of the state's obstetrical units. Vermont, New
Hampshire, and Maine hospitals are engaged in a similar effort.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has gone national as well. So far 56 hospitals,
health plans, and health care provider networks have signed up to
take part in an intensive program to reduce cesareans run by the
Boston-based Institute for Healthcare Improvement.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, half of the 28 institutions that joined the
effort most recently have cut their cesarean rates by 25 percent or
more, reports Andrea Kabcenell, a Cornell University nurse who
directs the project. ``Every team has seen changes, but we've had
some really stellar outcomes _ more than 30 percent reductions,''
Kabcenell reports.
</P>
<P>
   Just as no individual woman's labor can be expected to follow a
textbook scenario, there is no cookbook recipe for reducing
unnecessary cesareans, she and others say. Measures that seem most
effective have emerged through trial and error. Some are simple _
for instance, abandoning the time-honored practice of giving
expectant couples a ``due date'' for the birth. Others are
technical, such as delaying epidural anesthesia or ending the
routine practice of hooking women to electronic fetal monitors
throughout labor.
</P>
<P>
   What the strategies share is a new thoughtfulness about
once-rigid expectations surrounding birth, and an overdue respect
for nature's ways.
</P>
<P>
   Take the due date, for example. It was always based on a
fallacy: the notion that an obstetrician could predict to the day
when the normal human 39-week gestation period would be up. But it
is almost always unclear when conception occurred. Even the wonders
of ultrasound _ which permits a more accurate but still uncertain
estimate of fetal weight and gestational age _ do not furnish the
precision that a due date implies.
</P>
<P>
   Setting a due date frequently leads to what Dr. Bruce Flamm, a
California obstetrician, calls ``a social induction,'' inducing
labor for social, not medical, reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing medically wrong with mother or baby, but maybe
mother is tired of being pregnant, her husband is tired, her mother
has flown in from Minnesota,'' Flamm says. ``So the woman is
brought in, sometimes at her insistence, and they try to induce the
baby. Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   When it doesn't, the result is often an avoidable cesarean, with
risks and costs to the mother (such as surgical mishap, infection,
lengthier convalescence) and the baby (such as immature lungs).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert K. DeMott of Green Bay, Wis., one of the most
outspoken reformers, will only give couples a ``due month.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't dwell on a due date,'' DeMott advised Massachusetts
caregivers at a Blue Cross symposium recently. ``It just gets
everybody saying, `We're late! What are you going to do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody goes along with the idea of a ``due month.''
``Having had a pregnancy, I realize a lot of people can't swallow
that,'' Kabcenell says. ``People have lives to plan: When can I
tell the folks at work that I am not going to be working any more?
When should I tell Mom when she needs to come and help? When should
the baby's room be ready?''
</P>
<P>
   However, many obstetricians are now specifying only a two-week
interval when the birth might take place.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes involve how labor is managed once a woman is
admitted. Many obstetricians and OB nurses now respect the
importance of allow women to walk around during labor and to take
different positions _ even draped over a giant rubber ball in some
cases _ so gravity can assist the fetus's descent.
</P>
<P>
   But ambulation is impossible when the woman is continuously
tethered to electronic fetal monitors, and studies show that
intermittent monitoring is safe for the vast majority of women.
(Some, like DeMott, are even abandoning the monitors in favor of
the old-fashioned stethoscope to check on fetal heart rates.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a woman can't walk around if an epidural anesthetic
has paralyzed her from the waist down. So some hospitals are
deferring epidurals until later in labor, after the cervix has
dilated at least four centimeters. In some cases, a lighter dose of
epidural anesthetic is used when necessary that allows the woman to
walk. Lawrence General has cancelled routine anesthesia
consultations because, Leavitt says, it creates ``a mind-set'' that
anesthesia will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Later and lessened use of epidurals (which can slow labor),
along with increasing ambulation, turn out to reduce the occurrence
of the largest single justification for cesareans, called dystocia
or cephalopelvic disproportion _ meaning the baby is presumed to be
too large to fit through the mother's pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent fallacy of that belief has emerged from studies of
women who successfully delivered vaginally despite a prior cesarean
for cephalopelvic disproportion. ``Our success rate for vaginal
birth after cesarean is 80 to 90 percent,'' DeMott says, ``and
one-third of the babies weigh more than a previous child who
supposedly `got stuck.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite hospitals' success in rolling back cesarean rates,
maintaining lower rates is a constant struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal of ``natural'' or unmedicated childbirth, so much in
vogue during the 1980s, has waned, so many women now need to be
persuaded that they may not need an epidural. ``Today the culture
is, `I want my epidural the minute I get into the hospital,'''
Flamm says. ``You have to change that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal climate is a factor too. Although there is less
tendency to conclude that every case of cerebral palsy or brain
damage is a flag for a cesarean-that-should-have-been-done, a new
development has the reformers worried.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Phelan, a California obstetrician-lawyer, is
campaigning against vaginal birth after cesarean (so-called VBACs)
as inherently unsafe, since in one case out of 100 the woman's
prior uterine scar ruptures. Phelan has persuaded some malpractice
insurers and health plans to circulate ominous informed consent
forms to doctors detailing the dangers, urging that tey get women
to sign the form before trying VBAC.
</P>
<P>
   Flamm says no studies back up Phelan's contention, and that it
is seldom disastrous when uterine scars give way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason this is a big issue is when you look at cesarean
rates over the last 10 years, there are now 100,000 fewer cesareans
each year, and almost all of those are due to VBACs,'' Flamm says.
``If we start going back to the era of `Once a cesarean, always a
cesarean,' we may see that turning around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
