<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MIDLER-BOS &LR;      09-21 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MIDLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDLER GOES BACK TO THE BATHHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The song may be from 1935 or 1955 or 1998, but if Bette Midler
likes it, she's going to sing it. The song could be campy, serious,
sad, or a combination thereof, but it's not going to stop her.
Where other artists might lay claim to versatility, the Divine Miss
M simply defines it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't I have an open mind?'' says Midler, appalled at
the idea of anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for people who only like one kind of music,'' adds
Midler, whose new album, ``Bathhouse Betty,'' sassily spans songs
from '30s standard ``I Sold My Heart to the Junkman'' to
contemporary tunes by pop pianist Ben Folds and singer-songwriter
Adam Cohen, son of Leonard Cohen (who is also represented, with the
``Song of Bernadette'').
</P>
<P>
   Midler, 52, doesn't hesitate to thank her audience for
encouraging her to pursue such diverse styles. ``My audience has
been great about that,'' she says from Los Angeles. ``They like
music. They don't look down their nose at people because they don't
make a certain kind of music. ... They have respect for musicians
and they have respect for arrangers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Midler, like many artists of her
generation, can't fathom the constricting, subset-of-a-subset
formats that constitute many of today's radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the most part that radio stinks,'' says Midler,
whose versatility is surpassed only by her candor. ``All this
demographic stuff and all this marketing stuff where they will only
play a certain kind of music and you can't be older than 25 to get
on the station is nuts. I think it makes for a very ignorant
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new album has a couple of awkward moments, including a
tentative treatment of ``Song of Bernadette,'' but for the most
part, her so-called ``cosmic fabulosity'' is on full,
mind-expanding display. She moves easily from the rib-tickling,
1955 tune ``One Monkey Don't Stop No Show'' (``He left me at 3 in
the morning, I got me a man at 4,'' she wails, backed by the Royal
Crown Revue) to the jazz-swing of ``I'm Hip'' and the dance-funk of
``I'm Beautiful,'' which even has her rapping some phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very little rapping. You even call that rapping?'' she asks
kiddingly.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not going to be confused with Puff Daddy, she's told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now, wait a second. I can rap as well as Puff Daddy. He
can hardly rap. Now that girl, Li'l Kim, she raps. She speed-raps.
I couldn't do that. Well, maybe I could if I had enough practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's diversity is most apparent in a segue from Adam
Cohen's ``Lullaby in Blue'' (a poignant tale of a parent missing a
child) to the hilarious ``Ukulele Lady.'' Perhaps only Midler could
make these two songs work back to back.
</P>
<P>
   The album title, ``Bathhouse Betty,'' refers to her days singing
in gay bathhouses in Manhattan, long before she became a
show-business icon. The title was chosen only after a crazed
incident in which an overzealous fan knocked on the door to her
house in Orange County and started shouting ``Bathhouse Betty!
Bathhouse Betty!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' she recalls. ``He was extremely disreputable.
He looked like he had spent the night in the park. He had picked
some wildflowers, bless his heart, but I didn't let him in. ... I
called the police. I was scared, because I was all alone at the
time. The police couldn't find him, but he left me the title of my
album, so I guess I should be grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Midler has no tour plans, because she's been preoccupied with
finishing her next film, ``Isn't She Great?'' It's the story of
pulp writer Jacqueline Susann (played by Midler) and the romance
between her and Irving Mansfield. It also stars Nathan Lane, with a
script by Paul Rudnick. ``It's very strange, but it's pretty
funny,'' Midler says of the film, due to be released next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play Jacqueline Susann in a long brown wig, but don't tell
anybody it's a wig! They'll never know,'' says Midler, who
obviously still has a few tricks up her divine sleeve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
