<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-INVITRO-SUCCESS-B     09-21 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INVITRO-SUCCESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS TIGHTEN STANDARDS FOR INFERTILITY CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With, SCI-INVITRO)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON - With their eye on the bottom line, medical directors of
managed-care organizations have begun taking a sharp look at
performance of infertility clinics in Massachusetts. Their aim,
they say, is to ensure that patients get the most effective
treatment without high rates of costly multiple pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Tufts Health Plan, New England's second-largest managed
care company, has put three programs on notice that if they want to
win contracts, they'll have to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robin Richman, medical director for fertility services at
Tufts, said that as the plan began looking for potential IVF
providers, ``I noticed that success rates have been very different,
and so has the philosophy on counseling patients, how quickly they
move to different techniques, and, frankly, how honest they've been
with their patients. It's very variable.'' She would not identify
the plans that have been warned.
</P>
<P>
   One frequently quoted statistic, on the odds that a woman will
end up with a live birth, varied from 8 to 21 percent among clinics
according to 1995 data, Richman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tufts plan has devised a set of benchmarks for IVF programs.
They combine a number of figures, including the clinic's success
rate; the number of IVF cycles, or attempts, carried out annually;
the rate of multiple pregnancies; the number of doctors in the
program as well as those who are board-certified; and the
laboratory director's credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Richman said three Massachusetts programs are currently below
the standard but have until Jan. 1 to reach it. Dr. Machelle Seibel
at Faulkner Hospital acknowledged that his program is one of the
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's causing problems for me, and I'm working on solutions,''
he said. ``They have a broad range of requirements that don't
necessarily relate to patient care. I'm simply confused by where
these criteria come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Desmarais, vice president of a physicians' management
company affiliated with Reproductive Science Center of Waltham,
said he welcomes standards. Managed-care companies ``are becoming
enlightened,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
