<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-PATRIOTS-CYBERSPA     09-21 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-PATRIOTS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS EXPAND PRESENCE IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New England Patriots have established the team as
one of the most tenacious gridiron players in cyberspace, and they
are positioning themselves to profit from you clicking on.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to creating what observers say was the first Web
site for a professional sports team in 1995 _ patriots.com _ the
Patriots were the first to launch their own cybercast last year.
Now, in combination with two local firms, the team is building a
market for selling collectibles online; pictures, team symbols and
other products that avid fans will be able to pull down from the
Web and keep in their computer memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy was originally drawn from the fact that we wanted
to give our fans more information than they could get from the
mainstream media,'' said Patriots vice president Jonathan Kraft.
``But as we go on, we realize that there is more and more of a
marketing opportunity for the team here, and we have already built
up a substantial user base for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Patriots first produced the cybercast, Patriots
Live! This year, produced in conjunction with InterVU, a San Diego
company, the program is appearing four times, immediately after
each of the team's prime-time television broadcasts. The team also
now has a daily cybercast at 8 p.m., which is repeated through the
day, as well as Coach Pete Carroll's daily 10 a.m. news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the original Web site has grown dramatically, according
to the team. Last year, it had about 900,000 users. This year,
there were 2.4 million users by the month of August, said Fred
Kirsch, who handles the technology for the team.
</P>
<P>
   And the Patriots are offering a new site that is only about two
weeks old. Developed with Tripod, a Lycos company, and Parable, a
Newton firm, patriots.tripod.com allows fans the opportunity to
pull down pictures and team marks. Fans can build their own home
pages and publish online to a community of other Patriots'
followers with only rudimentary knowledge of the online experience.
Hundreds of fans visited the site in its first week of operation,
Patriots and company officials say. The Patriots will eventually
offer the collectibles for sale from the site, broadening a market
that in the noncyber world is already worth hundreds of millions of
dollars annually in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   While many professional sports franchises, including the Red
Sox, offer a retail service for ordering the delivery of
collectibles on line, the Patriots site would ultimately provide
for virtual collectibles that fans can store in their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although NFL licensing officials impose tough restrictions on
the use of any of its symbols and marks, Parable's new ``Things''
technology makes the collectibles portable while securing the
licensing rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it portable, but at the same time protects it from
being modified,'' said Steve Barlow, cofounder of Parable. ``Their
content can be distributed online, but at the same time it's safe
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are encouraging people just to use it, just to
click on and get used to the technology,'' Kirsch said. ``The
technology will be there soon so we can limit the quantity of the
thing we want to distribute _ like linking a certain collectible to
a player's performance, for example. You know, it's really just
like card collecting, but it's on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   With sponsors like the New England Ford dealers and BayBank
running advertisements on the sites, insiders say the Patriots are
already realizing a revenue stream from their initiatives in
cyberspace that is well into six figures. Tripod and Parable share
in the advertising revenue while taking advantage of the
opportunity to market their wares.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Patriots move towards selling collectibles on the
web, they are bound to realize more revenue. Forecasters expect
sales over the Internet to grow markedly. The Yankee Group, a
Boston consulting firm, says the current world market is at about
$100 billion and could reach $630 billion in just five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will create a market that is two to three percent of gross
domestic product in a couple of years and I think it may be as high
as five percent by 2003,'' said Jim Cash, a professor of business
administration at the Harvard's Graduate School of Business
Administration. ``So, smart companies certainly need to be aware of
it. ``But I would caution that I haven't seen anything that
suggests to me that there is a great deal of overlap between the
avid sports fans and people who spend a lot of time on the Web,
although that may be increasing among younger fans,'' Cash said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft is more than happy with the team's performance online,
and he thinks it rebuts any skepticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
