<HEADLINE>
IS KEEPING RENTAL HOUSE A WISE FINANCIAL MOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are on opposite sides of the fence on an
issue. One of us believes we should sell a rental house that is
next door to our residence. Since we're not stock-market savvy,
we'd find a good mutual fund and leave the money there. The other
believes the house isn't a bad investment, since we can control who
our neighbors are, and if we sold the house, we would have to put
our excess furniture, which is now stored in the attic of the
rental property, in a rental locker at an expense of about $50 a
month (leaving it there until we build our dream house). The house
would sell for just under $100,000. It provides $1,000 a month
income, with the tenants paying all utilities. The house is fully
paid for, and the annual cost of taxes and insurance is $2,000. Is
holding this house worth it, or should we sell it and put the money
in a good mutual fund?
</P>
<P>
   S.S., West Lafayette, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This one would be a lot easier to answer if that hint of
building the ``dream house'' hadn't been tossed in. Let's start
with the easy part _ treating ownership of the house strictly as an
investment. Let's suppose the house is worth $99,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since it gives you an annual income stream of $10,000, after
deducting the expenses, ownership of the property is providing you
a return of just over 10 percent. That's just about what you might
expect as a long-term return from a stock mutual fund investment _
and I think it looks very good in terms of my near-term
expectations from the securities markets.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's consider where you might stand after a sale. If you
sold at $99,000, you would probably pay a real estate agent's fee,
which would reduce your net to $93,060. You would probably have
other closing costs, but we'll ignore them for the purposes of this
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   To get the same value from that $93,060 that you're getting from
owning the house _ including the $600 annual value of storing your
excess furniture in it _ you would have to find an investment that
would give you an 11.4 percent return. That's pretty unlikely, and
also bear in mind that this exercise doesn't include any possible
tax cost of selling the property.
</P>
<P>
   So if you combine that math with my low expectations for market
returns in the near term, it sounds to me as if the argument's all
in favor of hanging on to the house. The only argument for selling:
If you believe the local real estate market is now as strong as
it's likely to be during the next couple of years, and if you
expect to be selling it anyway within the next few years, using the
proceeds for building your dream house, you'd probably be better
off selling into a strong real estate market now, rather than
waiting for an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 50 and 48, respectively, and we have
jobs that are not high paying. We have accumulated $10,000 that we
would like to invest for our retirement. We have been keeping it in
a CD paying 5 percent or so. I would like to know how a person can
become educated about investments. Do you begin with your bank's
resident broker and listen to his advice? Could you take a course
at a local college on the subject? Like most people in our income
level, I am very protective of this seemingly small amount of money
we have saved. I don't feel I could just jump into the market and
trust anyone. What do you think of Disney stock?
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Mount Bethel, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think a college course would be an excellent idea, for two
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious one is the knowledge and understanding of the
markets that you should be able to gain from it.
</P>
<P>
   And the second is that if you resolve to leave your money in a
CD or similar investment until you complete the course, you may
escape one of the most dangerous securities markets of many years.
Whatever else it is, this is no market for the learn-as-you-go
investor.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether it wouldn't be better, and easier, to simply stop
in at your bank, I'm against it.
</P>
<P>
   Banks sell mutual funds to make money. Although they may offer
funds with a variety of fee structures, almost inevitably there
will be a fee in there somewhere. If you were to take that
investment course, it would prepare you to make informed selections
among the many no-load funds that are available, thus saving you
sales charges that might be 3 percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I find that many people who have made inappropriate investments
or investments they do not understand have bought the funds through
a bank. I'm sure many banks have sophisticated and well-educated
officers serving their mutual fund sales; I am equally sure that at
other institutions, the mutual fund department is simply a drawer
in the desk of a harried young officer who has many other duties
and little investment training.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're going to pay a sales charge, pay it to an
investment professional who works with investments all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Since you're interested in investing, I'm sure that you've been
following the market headlines for the last couple of weeks, and
may be feeling even more hesitant than when you started. I don't
blame you if you are.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that once you believe you're ready to begin
investments, you leave that $10,000 in CDs and embark on an
investment program only with additional savings _ putting aside a
little bit every week or month or quarter. This will serve to make
the course of your investment very gradual, and will mitigate the
risks.
</P>
<P>
   As for Disney stock, most investors, and especially beginning
investors, are likely to be better served with mutual funds than
one stock, or even a handful of them. As for Disney itself, while
it certainly deserves the right to retain the designation blue
chip, the years when it could do nothing wrong seem to be behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   Entering last week, the stock sold at 26 times earnings, and
near its 52-week low. Its dividend represented a meager 0.8 percent
yield. I'd wait for lower multiple and better dividend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
