<HEADLINE>
PROPONENTS SAY BARTER SYSTEM IS GOOD FOR LOCAL COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Instead of spending U.S. dollars, a growing
number of consumers here are using BREAD to buy goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD, the Berkeley Regional Exchange and Development, is an
alternative currency and barter system developed a little more than
a year ago by an ecologist who wanted a way to support local
merchants, increase human interaction and cut down on the waste
associated with the commercial economy.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1997, the number of BREAD users has gone from 30 to
more than 300 and the alternative cash _ $10,000 of which is now in
circulation _ is increasingly being accepted by local businesses
and restaurants as part of a trend that appears to be on the rise
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to build up the local economy instead of seeing
money going to multinational corporations who may be clear-cutting
forests or using sweatshop labor,'' said Miyoko Sakashita, 25, the
founder of BREAD. ``It allows us to see the special talents that
exist in our neighborhoods; people can participate in their hobbies
while they're paid to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some 60 barter systems across the United States. While
each exchange program differs, all are based on the idea of
strengthening communities by reinvesting in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   The BREAD system includes its own currency and a directory
listing goods and services of those who will accept BREAD currency.
The currency can be used to purchase goods, or it can add value to
a trade of services or merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Each BREAD dollar is valued at one hour of $12-per-hour labor.
Individuals bartering for goods and services decide independently
how much they will pay and receive for their labor. Sakashita said
she valued the BREAD bills at $12 per hour in an effort to raise
the minimum wage to represent today's cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   Those using BREAD in the last year attest to its social and
economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD user and Oakland resident Allysyn Kiplinger makes hemp oil
soap and runs her own medical-form printing business. Recently her
mother suffered a stroke and needed massage therapy as part of her
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger looked in her BREAD directory and found a licensed
masseuse who accepted BREAD for half of the cost of his services.
Kiplinger used the BREAD she had earned selling soap at the
Berkeley Farmer's Market to dramatically lower the cost of her
mother's therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger said the BREAD system is not only cheaper, it often
results in better quality work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the network is powered by relationships, you want to
do your job and do it well; it motivates you,'' Kiplinger said.
</P>
<P>
   One shortcoming of the barter system, users say, is that it
takes a great deal of personal initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Sakashita said there had been no reports of shoddy work or
poor-quality products. But if there are repeated complaints about a
member's work, that person would be removed from the directory.
</P>
<P>
   The barter concept appears to be growing around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, it looked like a movement was forming and now we know
of approximately 60 (local currencies) in the U.S.,'' said Susan
Whitt at the Schumacher Society in Massachusetts. The Society
publishes the Local Currency News and keeps track of such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Whitt said the most prolific local currency system are in
Ithaca, N.Y., where $65,000 ``Ithaca Dollars'' circulate.
</P>
<P>
   Local currencies are not a new idea, Whitt said, and became
popular with the widespread bank closures during the Depression.
</P>
</TEXT>
