<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``A Merry War''  So-so adaptation of George Orwell's
semi-autobiographical novel, about a hotshot ad copywriter quitting
to become a poet. Richard E. Grant overstates his role, but Helena
Bonham Carter anchors the film as his practical girlfriend.
(Unrated)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FD)(BS)(BS) ``The Mirror''  &LR; A young girl wanders the streets of
Tehran after her mother fails to pick her from school _ or so it
seems in Jafar Panahi's latest work. This very unusual film could
be described as a movie within a movie, except that would still
fail to capture the many layers and nuances on display. (Unrated)
(Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FU)(BS)(BS)(BS) ``One True Thing'' &LR;  Powerful emotions surface when
an ambitious journalist (Renee Zellweger) is called home to care
for her ailing mother (Meryl Streep) because her father's career as
an academic is too important to interrupt. From Anna Quindlen's
novel. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (BS) 1/2 ``Permanent Midnight''  &LR; Boring yuppie drug saga about TV
writer Jerry Stahl, who crashed and burned, then detoxed his way
back to writing the book upon which this superficial Hollywood
wallow is based. Ben Stiller's Stahl is given little more than cold
sweats and motormouth episodes to act. Elizabeth Hurley is a
standout as his green-card wife, who cares more than anyone thought
she could for a sham marriage. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
