<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MODEL-BOS &LR;      09-21 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MODEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAY MCINERNEY CHARACTERS NEVER SEEM TO FIND THEIR DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As almost any Jay McInerney protagonist will tell you, celebrity
is a cheap, fast-acting little poison. It can have you writhing on
the floor of your West Village co-op within weeks of exposure,
regretting the adrenaline thrills of the night before and the
superficial impulses that emerged. It can take what may have been a
mere overblown ego and turn it into cynical self-absorption. Worst
of all is what happens to the talent that elicited the attention.
Tainted by too many high-life Manhattan cliches _ too much White
Horse Tavern, provincial cool, and what Connor McKnight calls
``colonoscopic intricacy'' _ even the purest aesthetic promise can
turn to muck.
</P>
<P>
   A rich-and-famous profiler for the slick pages of CiaoBella!
magazine, McKnight has learned most of this at arm's length, but
his inventor might heed the same instruction. Like the vanity fare
produced monthly by McKnight's employer, McInerney's ``Model
Behavior'' (a short novel and seven stories) suffers from glossy
cleverness; the au courant indifference that seeps from its pages
feels more hollow than sad. All this is at the expense of
McInerney's genuine literary gifts, which have too often been
obscured by his hipster fiction rather than illuminated. An astute
social observer of the cruelties of modern New York, he is also
capable of great tenderness; his finest fiction (the ending of
``Bright Lights, Big City,'' say, or the novel ``Brightness
Falls'') possesses a melancholy depth that justifies and tethers
the witty self-regard. There are signs of these qualities within
``Model Behavior,'' but they're so surrounded by fast-lane
posturing that one's admiration quickly gives way to irritation.
``Model Behavior'' is a male version of ``Bridget Jones's Diary'':
sometimes funny and occasionally sad, and a whole lot less than the
reach of its creator.
</P>
<P>
   The title novel of the collection concerns the fading
relationship between McKnight and his supermodel girlfriend, a
tearful Viking named Philomena, who dresses in white T-shirts and
Versace blazers and seems to have flown the coop. Sick with regret
and desire, McKnight alternates between chasing down Philomena
(she's supposedly off on a shoot) and the latest target of his
interviewing skills (a boy-wonder film star who won't take his
calls). More engaging as a character is McKnight's brilliant,
screwed-up sister, Brooke, who's on extended leave from a
postdoctoral physics program because she's too depressed to leave
her apartment. As is so often the case in a McInerney plot, a few
family-of-origin beasts lurk behind much of the novel's surface
neurosis; here, they're personified by a set of perky,
alcohol-sated parents who turn a Thanksgiving dinner at the St.
Regis into a scene that would make even a turkey blanch.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming among McKnight's first-person and McInerney's third- and
(now infamous) second-person voices, ``Model Behavior'' does manage
to be swift and amusing; the tone of it is just right, capturing
the fey, privately intelligent voice of a freelance journalist who
fears he's slumming but fears worse the notion that he isn't.
Stunned with the usual mix of pathos and obsession that accompanies
a broken heart, Connor takes solace in a great deal of vodka, New
York's ubiquitous social distractions, and his best friend, Jeremy,
an exquisitely literary fiction writer who must endure the barbs of
cruel reviewers. With its self-consciously second-person guidance
(``You have suffered a chronic and massive failure of awareness''),
its parodies of literary culture (a critic disparagingly invokes
McInerney's name in a review of Jeremy's work), ``Model Behavior''
is what you might call meta-McInerney _ a long story whose chief
point of reference is itself.
</P>
<P>
   Spanning the decade-plus arc of McInerney's career, the seven
stories that follow mostly hover around the theme of purists
manque: the dehumanized, successful screenwriter of ``The
Business,'' the junior publishing exec of ``Smoke,'' the coked-out
actor of ``Getting in Touch with Lonnie,'' the would-be songwriter
who winds up on the streets in ``The Queen and I.'' These guys tend
to be English Lit majors who always meant to become somebody, then
looked up from the bottom of Hollywood or a nasty Dilaudid habit
and realized life was a bitch. The two exceptions are ``Con
Doctor'' and ``Reunion''; the first, about a physician who treats
maximum-security prisoners, feels like a young story, but it has an
Old Testament clarity I actually found bracing. Visiting at his
in-laws' home on the North Shore, the man in ``Reunion'' has a
fleeting chance to see the amalgam of character that makes us who
we are. But then maybe I was simply refreshed by these two day
trips beyond Houston Street or the Upper West Side _ or, more
fairly, beyond the inch-deep truisms of those places if you use
CiaoBella! as a Michelin Guide to life, even ironically. The
problem with ``Model Behavior'' isn't that it's set in
post-decadent New York, or that Connor and Philomena are the kind
of people you'd live in Queens to avoid. It's that Jay McInerney
here seems infatuated with his own stock weariness, and has
substituted mere artfulness for the tougher job of depth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell is chief book critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
