<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-LINDBERGH-BOS &LR;      09-21 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LINDBERGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES A. LINDBERGH: THE ALL-AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LINDBERGH 
By A. Scott Berg. Putnam. 628 pp. Illustrated. $30. 
 
 
UNDER A WING 
By Reeve Lindbergh. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 223 pp. Illustrated. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There never was a hero like Charles A. Lindbergh. So perfectly
cast as an adventurer, so handsomely formed as an icon, he was a
flier, an explorer, a crusader, a researcher, even a crank
political philosopher. But most of all he was a symbol _ of
American possibility, of American practicality, of American
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is no coincidence that the great achievement of
Charles Lindbergh occurred on the horizon, where the American dream
has always been richest and most flamboyant. Lindbergh, of course,
in 1927 was the first man to fly from New York to Paris, a test of
human courage and mechanical endurance, a successful struggle
against fear and fatigue and even fog, that consumed 33 1/2 hours
but defined his life and, in a curious way, defined the American
century.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lindbergh's is the ultimate American life, and A. Scott
Berg's new biography is the ultimate, and understated, exploration
of that life. Lindbergh may have heard more cheers than any other
American ever, more than Joe DiMaggio, even more, perhaps, than
Franklin Roosevelt, and he heard more jeers, too, suffering years
of ostracism for isolationist views that, it is often forgotten
today, were shared by more than a few in the country's upper
echelons in the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   But through all those cheers and jeers, Berg is a competent,
comforting guide, never speaking above a whisper, and as a result,
in an astonishing biography of a man who personified the future
tense, no sentence is overwritten, no passage overwrought.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible now, when the felicitous phrase ``frequent
flier'' is on every traveler's lips, to imagine the sheer
improbability of what Lindbergh did. But it is equally impossible
now, when aviation is no longer an adventure but a commonplace, to
escape the influence of Lindbergh, who was present at the creation
of the modern world and who played a central role in three of the
central events of the first half of the century _ his own flight to
Le Bourget, the kidnapping death of his son and the trial of Bruno
Hauptmann, and the debate leading to the nation's entry into World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Berg's story is familiar, of course, but different, deeper, than
the story of myth and folklore. For years Berg mined the 2,000
boxes of the personal papers of Lindbergh and his wife, Anne Morrow
Lindbergh, and interviewed the five Lindbergh children. The result
is a volume that captures not only the heroism but the anguish of
Lindbergh _ the haunting loneliness of being what Berg called ``the
most celebrated living person ever to walk the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's achievement was one of human courage, but it was the
meeting of man and technology that created Lindbergh's celebrity.
He experienced the freedom of the airplane, the imprisonment of the
still and motion-picture camera. ``No man before me had commanded
such freedom of movement over earth,'' he wrote once. The freedom
he had over land did not extend to freedom on land. Like Diana,
princess of Wales, he was hunted throughout his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   And while Lindbergh came to symbolize the restlessness of the
human spirit, he also suffered from that restlessness. He was
known, to be sure, for his feats of travel, but through a long life
what Lindbergh did mostly was travel. He was, not coincidentally,
always in flight, often traveling overseas as a good will
ambassador, often mapping out air routes, often indulging in his
far-flung interests, including medicine and conservation, but
always fleeing something _ the hordes who came to adore him and the
family that never quite did.
</P>
<P>
   So it is poignant that the Berg biography is being published in
the very same season as a very different book, ``Under a Wing,'' an
almost affectionate memoir by Reeve Lindbergh, the youngest of
Charles's children.
</P>
<P>
   Where Berg's volume is thick and imposing, Lindbergh's is slight
and inviting. Perhaps they should be read in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not a typical 1950s suburban family,'' Reeve Lindbergh
writes, and it is probably the understatement of the year. Her
memoir speaks of family journeys to see natural phenomena (the
stars, a skunk near the woodpile) and of Saturday flights with
Lindbergh himself. In these pages are quiet glimpses of the hero at
home: ``He had both the easy confidence and the electrically
charged manner of a person who has often lived with emergency: on
the farm, in the air, and in time of war. He was calmest in
practical crisis, and grew more restless during quiet periods.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the presence of Lindbergh helped define the life of
the United States, his absences helped define the life of his
family. (He missed one son's high school graduation, another's
wedding. When his wife was bedridden for several weeks after knee
surgery, he was nowhere to be seen.) ``When our father left us to
travel around the world, and even when he left the world entirely,
at his death in 1974, there was an element of relief in his
absence, some quietness that we had never known in our lives
before. But he left behind a vast hole in our universe, as great as
the death of a star.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lindbergh was a star _ the first superstar of the century of
superstars. F. Scott Fitzgerald recognized that: ``A young
Minnesotan who seemed to have had nothing to do with his generation
did a heroic thing, and for a moment people set down their glasses
in country clubs and speakeasies and thought of their own best
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   That was what Lindbergh was about: his dreams, other peoples'
dreams. More than 2,000 people sent poems to The New York Times in
the wake of his flight. George M. Cohan wrote a song, Kurt Weill
and Bertolt Brecht wrote a cantata. He earned a parade that was 22
miles long. He went on a victory tour that included 147 speeches
and 1,285 miles of parades. ``He served,'' Berg writes, ``as a
blank screen onto which each person projected his own best images
of man.''
</P>
<P>
   That was fine for a while. But the reverie didn't last, couldn't
last, forever. First he retreated, in part to preserve his sanity.
Then the ``Lindbergh kidnapping'' _ the shorthand phrase endures to
this day _ followed by an investigation and trial, both of which
Berg portrays masterfully. And finally the great debate about
America's role in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh picked the wrong side of that debate, and accepting
the Service Cross of the German Eagle didn't help matters at all.
He was altogether too soft on Hitler, altogether too skeptical of
the ability of the British and the Americans to take on the Europe
of the dictators, altogether too careless in his language. He made
himself vulnerable to charges that he was a Nazi sympathizer, or an
anti-Semite, or a defeatist, inviting commentators such as Ralph
Ingersoll, the publisher of PM, to describe him as ``the spokesman
of the fascist fifth column in America.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Lindbergh never recovered from his romance with
isolationism. Indeed, it stalked him all his days, and unlike Alice
Roosevelt Longworth, Eddie Rickenbacker, and Kingman Brewster _ all
prominent in America First _ Lindbergh was permanently stained by
his views.
</P>
<P>
   Berg points out that Lindbergh ``was never associated with any
pro-Nazi or anti-Semitic organization; he never attended any Bund
meetings; and since more than four months before the outbreak of
war in Europe, he had neither conspired nor consulted with anyone
known to have any connections with the Third Reich.'' No matter.
The stain remained. Combat flights in the South Pacific wouldn't
completely wipe them away.
</P>
<P>
   Today Lindbergh is firmly a figure of the past; what is
astonishing now, at century's end, is that he has been a figure of
the past for four decades. His flight, after all, was seven decades
ago. The 1957 film ``The Spirit of St. Louis'' was a bomb, the
``most disastrous failure,'' Jack Warner said, that his studio ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the problem seemed to be that the phenomenon of
Lindbergh had subsided,'' Berg explains. ``Beside the many who had
grown indifferent or hostile toward him, baby boomers were more
interested in rocket ships and outer space than in some antique
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But Berg knows that the Spirit of St. Louis will never
be just an antique plane, that Lindbergh will never be just a
celebrity with crackpot political views, that his achievement will
never be relegated to the dustbin of history. In his time,
Lindbergh's flight helped America see the future. In ours, it
explains America's past. That is legacy enough for one man and one
machine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
