<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAN-IS-A-STAR-NYTSF &LR;      09-21 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAN-IS-A-STAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MED SCHOOL DEAN IS A STAR, LIKE HER SISTER, DIANA ROSS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Editors: A COLOR SLIDE showing Barbara Ross-Lee with her sister,
Diana, is available.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CHERYL HECKLER-FELTZ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Ross-Lee grew up in the projects of Detroit, put herself
through medical school and became the first black woman to head a
medical school in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Her story could serve as a blueprint for any woman trying to
balance family and career, or for anyone facing overwhelming
obstacles like poverty and isolation.
</P>
<P>
   But she is still strongly identified with her supremely
recognizable sister, pop diva Diana Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Ross-Lee, dean of the Ohio University College of Osteopathic
Medicine, has been featured in People Magazine and USA Today. Many
will tell you she is to the world of medicine today what her
younger sister was to the world of music 30 years ago -- a bona
fide shooting star.
</P>
<P>
   And if, after her years as physician, professor and dean, the
opening line is often, ``So YOU'RE Diana Ross's sister,'' as
children the opposite was true.
</P>
<P>
   Diana would start a new year at school and hear teachers croon,
``So YOU'RE Barbara's little sister!''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara was always seen as the brains of the family and Diana
the brawn.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, when teenager Diana was an aspiring singer,
the family's Detroit apartment pounded with the music of future.
Motown stars Stevie Wonder, Marvin Gaye and Smokey Robinson crowded
around the kitchen table experimenting with the R&AMP;B sound that was
to become a part of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Barbara knew them as friends but showed little
interest in their music, ``Books were my passion,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   While Diana's singing career skyrocketed, and she claimed a
place in the history of American music, Barbara pioneered in other
ways. The first in her family to attend college, Barbara constantly
forged new paths, and today -- by her very position at Ohio
University -- claims an important place in African-America womens'
history.
</P>
<P>
   Born June 1, 1942, Barbara was the oldest of six children born
to Fred Ross, a factory worker and union steward, and his wife,
Ernestine, a homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to both hard work and creative financial problem
solving, Barbara held many different jobs while growing up -- from
ticket sales clerk at the Old Graystone Ballroom in Detroit and
dance instructor to microbiologist at Sealtest Dairy (which
included literally gallons of free ice cream each week for her
relatives) and mistress of ceremonies for Diana's performances with
her pre-Supremes group the Primettes.
</P>
<P>
   She always was a standout science student with a strong interest
in medical school, but didn't pursue it right after graduating from
Wayne State University in Michigan in 1965. Instead, she earned a
masters in education and began teaching junior high science.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970 a friend suggested that Barbara -- by then a divorcee
with two young children -- apply to Michigan State University
College of Osteopathic Medicine, a new medical school in Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, I am of an age in which women,
especially minority women, found it very difficult to be accepted
in medical schools,'' Ross-Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   She was accepted and began a grueling, highly structured,
never-a-moment-to-spare, three-year campaign to become a doctor of
osteopathic medicine.
</P>
<P>
   (Osteopathy emphasizes a hands-on approach in the belief that
the muscles and bones of the body play a significant role in many
diseases. In addition to conventional tests and drugs, the
osteopathic physician's manipulative therapy may be used to correct
a wide range of physical ailments, from migraines to back strains
to Parkinson's disease.)
</P>
<P>
   After graduation and residency, Ross-Lee returned to Detroit and
for 10 years maintained a family practice in a section of the inner
city marked by poverty and a high crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't have many problems with violence, but there
were some tense circumstances,'' she said. ``My patients were as
protective of my clinic as I was, and they helped look out for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One great frustration, however, were the number of people who
sought her out as a physician because of her famous sibling, a
concept she finds appalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never go to a doctor because she was Barbra
Streisand's sister,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Diana appeared in concert in the Detroit area,
patients, friends and even strangers would jam the phone lines to
Barbara's medical office trying to get tickets.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most painful episodes for Barbara happened in a
hospital elevator when her mother was undergoing treatment for the
breast cancer that claimed her life in 1984. Diana was sobbing in
her sister's arms over the impending death of their mother when the
elevator operator touched her on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, aren't you Diana Ross? Could I have an autograph?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 Barbara began teaching family medicine at MSU-COM,
eventually becoming chairwoman of the Department of Family Medicine
and associate dean for health care policy.
</P>
<P>
   She has also completed a fellowship in nuclear medicine, is a
commissioned captain in the U.S. Naval Reserves and -- for good
measure -- was the first osteopathic physician to participate in
the prestigious Robert Wood Johnson Health Policy Fellowship, where
she worked as a legislative assistant to former U.S. Sen. Bill
Bradley for 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   As his legislative assistant for health policy, she was the lead
person representing him in the areas of women's issues, women and
children, immunizations, tobacco, alcohol and substance abuse,
senior citizens and infant mortality.
</P>
<P>
   From her office in the rolling hills of Athens, Ohio, Ross-Lee
promotes an agenda to maintain excellence in education at her
school, to improve healthcare for isolated populations in her
region of the state and -- most ambitiously -- to strengthen
osteopathic medicine's role in the national conversation regarding
primary care physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a rocket scientist to know that we could
easily serve as the model for primary-care education for the rest
of the country,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Typically called ``America's other doctors,'' osteopathic
physicians make up only about 5 percent of U.S. physicians (about
35,000 compared to more than 600,000 allopathic (conventional)
medical doctors).
</P>
<P>
   These doctors are considered the more hands-on cousins of M.D.s,
providing badly needed primary care family practices and
demonstrating dedication to preventive healthcare and service to
poorer populations.
</P>
<P>
   What they DON'T have is the clout, wealth and political power of
the American Medical Association. Ross-Lee -- with her own
history-making achievements and her sister's
internationally-recognized name -- may be uniquely positioned to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being dean of a medical school is of no consequence unless I
can make the way better for those who will follow ... those who
must follow me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was not always a medical school dean. Before this, I was
a medical educator. Before that, I was a family physician
practicing in the inner-city of Detroit. Before that, I was a
grade-school teacher in the inner-city of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``And before that, I was poor and living in the housing projects
of Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Heckler-Feltz is author of ``Heart &AMP; Soul Of The Nation:
How The Spirituality Of Our First Ladies Changed America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
