   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE (Washington) _ President Clinton's videotapes
testimony to the grand jury provided ammunition to both sides of
the debate over whether he should be impeached. Clinton stubbornly
jousted with his interrogators, quibbling over definitions of
``sexual relations,'' attacking independent counsel Kennth Starr's
motives and evading some questions with claims of lapsed memory. He
also exuded empathy for subordinates including Monica Lewinsky and
secretary Betty Currie, and appealed that his personal privacy be
respected. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINKSY-TESTIMONY (Washington) _ Monica Lewinsky told the grand
jury that President Clinton was her ``sexual soulmate.'' She denies
keeping her semen-stained navy blue dress as a ``souvenir,''
explaining that she didn't wear the dress for some time after her
Feb. 28, 1997, encounter with Clinton because she gained weight.
Later, she saw the stain ``and thought to myself `oh no...''' Her
confidant, Linda Tripp, discouraged her from wearing it again. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-VIDEOTAPE (Washington) _ While some Democrats in
Congress criticized Monday's release of the videotape of President
Clinton's grand jury testimony as partisan warfare, some
Republicans said it showed the president lying under oath and
provided grounds for impeachment. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-BANKS (Paris) _ The losses suffered by Japan's banks as
a result of bad debts have now been revealed to be of a magnitude
unapproached since the Italians invented banking nearly 1,000 years
ago. The scope of the Japanese banking crisis is almost
unimaginable if Standard and Poor, the American agency that probes
such matters, is correct. And Standard and Poor doesn't often make
mistakes. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Filed in ``i'' and ``f''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In the first test of the president's
diminished political power, the House this week will defy him by
voting on a tax cut package he has threatened to veto because it
eats into surplus funds he wants to save to protect Social
Security. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
