<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SMOKIES22-COX     09-21 2214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SMOKIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On top of ol' Smokies
 &HT;    By Angel Bedinghauszent
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA VILLAGE, N.C. _ It took a village to make our family's
summer vacation a fun one.
</P>
<P>
   The Historic Fontana Village, that is, a sprawling resort in
northwest North Carolina. The nearest town is a 22-mile, twisting,
rolling drive to the south. To the north looms the Great Smoky
Mountains National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The resort is far from the tourist crowds in Gatlinburg and
Cherokee, which is why we picked it as our springboard for three
days of exploring the Smokies this summer. But there was more to
Fontana Village _ it really was historic.
</P>
<P>
   The name Fontana derives from a 1700s French explorer, but the
village itself is tied to one of the greatest engineering feats in
this country's history _ the Fontana Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the bombing of Pearl Harbor, President Franklin
Roosevelt gave the go ahead for making the atomic bomb, and gave
the Tennessee Valley Authority the job of providing power for it
and other war-time projects.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, thousands of workers converged on this remote
outpost. At the height of the project, 6,000 worked around the
clock. When completed in 1945, it was the largest dam east of the
Rockies. Standing 480 feet high, and three football fields wide at
its base, it holds back the 11,685 acre Fontana Lake.
</P>
<P>
   A spinoff of the project was a village, a couple miles from the
dam, and home to the workers and their families. Complete with
cabins, schools, church, a large hospital, recreation hall,
swimming pools and a ball field, the village was the TVA's way of
keeping workers happy so they would stay with the grueling project.
</P>
<P>
   When the dam was finished, the village was left high and dry.
(The dam is operated by just six employees today.) The TVA turned
to Government Services Inc. for help. They converted it into a
vacation resort. In its heyday in the early '70s, Fontana Village
called itself one of the square dance capitals of the world,
offering 10 festivals a year. In 1985, the property was purchased
by Peppertree Resorts and it still offers several dance festivals
in the fall and spring. It now includes 150 cabins, 94 hotel rooms
and tent camping.
</P>
<P>
   After checking in, we passed by a few well-kept cabins and went
through the village common area. This is where the action is: the
tennis courts, cafe, fishing pond, bike shop and rentals, indoor
and outdoor pools, recreation and game hall, general store, ball
field and a huge central lawn.
</P>
<P>
   A road that seemed nearly vertical to my South Floridian eyes
took us to our cabin. We gambled that the weather would be pleasant
(and it was) and reserved a cheaper cabin (in season $89) without
air conditioning, though it does have heat for the cool fall
nights. The cabin also came without phone or television, which was
fine with us.
</P>
<P>
   Our cabin was a duplex, weathered on the outside but recently
remodeled on the inside. It was built into the side of hill, and we
climbed a long wooden staircase to the front porch. A living/dining
room, kitchenette, two bedrooms and bath made up our simple
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin had none of the extra touches of a hotel. No tiny
bottles of shampoo, bath soap, or even dishwashing soap. Towels are
provided, along with pots, pans, dishes and utensils. Reading the
village newsletter, we learned there was no daily maid service. But
the cabin felt clean and fresh, and though we weren't in the middle
of the woods, the cabins are spread out among shady trees.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter gave a daily schedule of guest activities, some
free. They included bingo, marshmallow roasts, crafts, guided
hikes, mountain bike clinics, softball games, a scavenger hunt, and
trips to white water rafting, the nearby Joyce Kilmer Memorial
Forest and the cabin used in the movie Nell, starring Jodie Foster.
</P>
<P>
   With all these options, it was easy to spend an entire vacation
in and around the village. We had taken two days driving from West
Palm Beach with our three kids ages 7 and under, and it was time to
stretch. We decided to explore the area on bikes, since the
resort's stables, swim club, marina and dam were just 3 miles or so
away.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to realize a Florida mile on bikes is quite
different than a mountain mile! After huffing and puffing up hills
for about a half mile, we turned back for our car. During the next
few days, we discovered driving was the best way to explore this
hilly landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other attractions we explored, and their distance
from Fontana Village:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fontana Dam, about 3 miles from the Village: Even if looking
at a slab of concrete holding back a bunch of water sounds like a
snoozer, you will be impressed. We drove to the base of the dam,
but its massiveness is more apparent from the top. A road, closed
to vehicles, lets you walk out over the dam and look 400 feet
straight down to the spillway.
</P>
<P>
   There is a visitors center manned by a few volunteers, some who
worked for the TVA when the dam was built. From the center, for a
couple of dollars, you can take an incline tram down into the
powerhouse. The exhibits there explain how the dam generates
electricity, plus you see the control room and the dam from the
bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherokee, about 45 miles. The Cherokee Indians have a long
history in the Smoky Mountains. The ones who live on the Cherokee
Indian Reservation now are descendants of Cherokees who hid from
the Trail of Tears _ when American Indians were forced on a journey
to government-owned land in Oklahoma about 160 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The reservation is outside a main entrance to the Smokies. The
main road resembles in many ways a commercialized strip in any
Florida beach resort town. Instead of hocking seashells and
T-shirts, it's moccasins and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped at the Oconaluftee Indian Village, which has an
hourlong guided tour of old Cherokee housing and demonstrations of
traditional crafts.
</P>
<P>
   We learned about Cherokee society, customs and history. A
peaceful nation, the Cherokee never wore warrior headdresses, and
as a farming tribe, they never used tepees, but rather more
permanent dwellings made of mud, wood, and thatch.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Museum of the Cherokee Indian and crafts at the
Qualla Co-op. Each night, there is an outdoor drama called Unto
These Hills about the Trail of Tears.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clingmans Dome, about 25 miles from Cherokee. (Closed Dec. 1-
April 1). This stop was one of the busiest during our trip. At
6,642 feet, Clingmans Dome is the highest elevation in the Smokies
and the third-highest summit east of the Mississippi. With
countless other visitors, we followed the wide, sloping walkway for
a half a mile. A steep circular ramp takes you up the final ascent
to the top of a concrete tower.
</P>
<P>
   On clear days, you can see beyond the Smokies. We picked one
when the sky was heavy with low clouds, so low (or we were so high)
that sometimes we were actually in them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayah Bald, about 50 miles. For the final leg of our drive to
Fontana Village, we decided to take the scenic U.S. 64 to Wayah
Bald, a 5,342-foot peak with a stone observation tower. The long,
winding road led to a turnoff, and then a steeper, dirt road that
climbed another 4 miles to a parking area. After a short hike to
the tower, the kids could see where all that steep climbing landed
us. They were awestruck by their first view from atop a mountain.
Below were the towns we just traveled through and beyond to
Tennessee, Georgia and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   _ White-water rafting, about 35 miles. Several companies offer
guided and self-guided rafting trips down the Nantahala River in
six to eight-person rafts and inflatable kayaks. My husband and son
took a guided trip with the Nantahala Outdoor Center. The company
charges a few more dollars than others, but has a very good
reputation. For an additional fee, they also provide day care for
younger children.
</P>
<P>
   The novice father-son pair were part of a larger group of six
rafts and three guides. A bus took them 8 miles up river to launch.
From there, the current pushed them down river. Paddling was
reserved for maneuvering around rocks and rough waters. Though
there is a 60 pound weight minimum, the tour is perfect for first
time rafters and families. The dam-controlled river is predictable,
but with enough rocks and small drops to make it exciting. The
total time for the 8 mile long adventure is 3 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cades Cove and Parson Branch Road, about 60 miles. Cades Cove
is an expansive, flat meadow within the national park. Around the
turn of the century, it was home to a small but thriving farming
community. An 11-mile, one-way road circles the meadow with
pulloffs at the remaining cabins, churches, a cemetery and fields,
which are still used to grow hay. Deer are often spotted and we
were treated to a doe and fawn ambling across a mown field.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway around the road is a visitor center and old farm
house. A mill, powered by an old wooden water wheel, still makes
corn meal. Check the Smokies Guide for ranger-led programs; several
were listed during our trip.
</P>
<P>
   After stopping at the visitor center, we turned off the cove
road for a short-cut back to Fontana Village on Parson Branch Road,
a one-way dirt passage. This ``unimproved'' road took us deep into
the Smokies, a side of the mountains we wouldn't have seen unless
we did some rugged hiking. We drove slowly for 8 miles alongside a
small creek. Heavy green foliage grew on either side with sunlight
barely filtering in.
</P>
<P>
   As we bumped farther along over rocks and through divots, the
creek grew wider and faster, snaking back and forth over the road.
Remembering the rain earlier in the day, we wondered how much
deeper it would get, but at the next crossing point, a short bridge
took us over the creek.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the creek funneled through large steel tunnels into
the Little Tennessee River, and Parson Branch Road took us to the
highway that would lead us out of the Smokies and back on the road
again.
</P>
<P>
   FALL SOON TO COLOR SMOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Missing the colors of fall? Consider driving up to North
Carolina. The long, dry summer in the Southeast should create ideal
conditions for brilliant fall foliage.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves should start to change color in a couple of weeks and
last into November.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's scenic drives and historic bed-and-breakfasts
will fill with those who want to witness the most colorful season
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   By late September, cool air is expected to bring a bounty of
wildflowers, including asters and goldenrods.
</P>
<P>
   The varying elevations in the state, from the tops of the Great
Smoky Mountains to the flatlands along the coast, will mean many
peak weeks throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   A foliage hot line will begin service late this month.
Meanwhile, call (800) VISIT-NC for information about fall events,
hotels and scenic drives.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKY FACTS
</P>
<P>
   How big: Great Smoky Mountains National Park covers 517,000
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Where it is: The park straddles 60 miles of the North
Carolina-Tennessee state line.
</P>
<P>
   Peak facts: Sixteen peaks inside the park rise above 6,000 feet,
making them the highest mountains east of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors: Ten million people visit the park each year. Summer
and the October fall color season are the busiest times in the
park. Holidays also are busy. The best times to visit include
September, mid-November and late March through May.
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall: The mountains receive about 80 inches of rain each
year _ almost as much as a tropical rain forest. This helps make it
one of the most biologically diverse regions in North America. The
forest contains more than 1,400 species of flowering plants.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Unofficial Guide to the Great Smoky &AMP; Blue Ridge
Mountains, by Bob Sehlinger and Joe Surkiewicz ($15.95, Macmillan).
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO TO THE SMOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Fontana Village, P.O. Box 68, Highway 28, Fontana Dam, N.C.;
(800) 849-2258.
</P>
<P>
   Inn rates: room $69-$79; fireplace rooms $89-$99; sweetheart
rooms $129-149. Cottages from 1 bedroom/1 bath $59-69 up to 3
bedroom/2 bath $159-$189. Campsites opened through Nov. 1: $8 tent
site; $20 sites with hookups. Lower room rates are for shoulder
season (September, November, April and May) and higher for peak
season (October and June-August).
</P>
<P>
   Nearest airports: Ashville (95 highway miles) and Knoxville (65
curvy mountain miles).
</P>
<P>
   Nantahala Outdoor Center, for white-water rafting; (800)
232-7238. Sunday-Friday _ $28 per person guided trip; $17 unguided.
Saturdays _ $29 guided; $19 unguided.
</P>
<P>
   Oconaluftee Indian Village, open 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m. through Oct.
25. Admission is $10 adults; $5 children. Museum of Cherokee Indian
is open year round. Admission is $6 adults; $4 children. Outdoor
drama is nightly during summer months only. Tickets are $11-$14.
Call the Cherokee Indian Reservation Visitors Center, (800)
438-1601.
</P>
<P>
   Great Smoky Mountain Railways, (800) 872-4681. Open daily during
the season. Closed January through March. Reservations necessary in
October. Tickets are $19.95 adults; $9.95 children ages 3-12. Pick
up in Bryson City or Dillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
