<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Ledeall on the Clinton videotape and the
printed Starr evidence released Monday, including reaction both
from Congress and the public. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ WASHINGTON _ In a bizarre display of parallel
presidential universes, President Clinton addresses the United
Nations General Assembly even as his grand jury testimony is being
broadcast to the nation. Clinton's speech and the scene around him.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WORLD _ A wrap-up of reaction from around the world to
airing of President Clinton's videotaped testimony before the grand
jury. (Foreign staff, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAPE _ WASHINGTON _ How President Clinton's words and
demeanor on the four-hour tape of his testimony may affect his
public standing and the congressional impeachment inquiry. (Glass,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONICA _ WASHINGTON _ A portrait of Monica Lewinsky as
she is revealed in her full grand jury testimony; how it compares
with her image from the Starr summary. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ How Democrats and Republicans in
Congress react to Monday's release of evidence. (Carr, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAPITAL _ WASHINGTON _ For four hours on this particular
weekday, it was not business as usual in the nation's capital as
federal workers and others sought a unique peek at a president at
bay. (Moscoso and Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-E-MAIL _ WASHINGTON _ The Starr evidence released Monday
made clear that e-mail, like the telephone, is not a medium for
those who wish their words to remain private. What ordinary people
should know about e-mail. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV _ Analysis of TV coverage of Clinton video, including
whether CBS went with the full 4-hour version and comparisons
between CNN and the other nets. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET _ How did the internet deal with the onslaught
of four hours of Clinton's videotaped testimony and the 2800 pages
of other testimony? (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FORGIVENESS _ Lots of talk of forgiveness in the news,
but what does it really mean? Commentary by Paul Reid. (Reid, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EXPERTS _ What do the professionals _ speech
communication, political and legal types _ say about the Clinton
testimony. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WISDOM _ The wisdom of our senior citizens could be very
valuable in this situation. We visit senior citizens center to talk
with people who may have the luxury of time and have the
institutional experience to put this in context with previous
presidents and standards of decency. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-DROPOUTS _ In 1996-97 in Georgia, the Hispanic dropout
rate was 7.2 percent for students in grades 7-12, according to the
Council for School Performance, while the overall dropout rate in
Georgia was 5.2 percent. The Hispanic dropout rate was greater than
that of other ethnic groups in seven of the 10 school systems with
the most Hispanic students. A look at the problem and how the state
might try to address it with the Hispanic population expected to
double by 2025. (Kurylo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTOR-KILLED _ AUSTIN, Texas _ David Chain would spend his
evenings talking with friends and co-workers about his love of the
redwood forests of Northern California. He would spend his days
working to get back there. Chain was killed recently, crushed by a
falling redwood as he and other protesters tried to dissuade
loggers with Pacific Lumber Co. from felling trees at a remote site
in Northern California. (Henrichs, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-DRUGCRIME _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The teacher, John
George, started a construction business in western Palm Beach
County, Fla. His pupil, David Combs, became one of the county's
largest marijuana dealers. He was recently shipped off to federal
prison. From 1995 to 1997, George and his company, Majestic Custom
Homes, helped Combs build and sell 38 houses on vacant lots around
Loxahatchee _ some of which, prosecutors say, were used by Combs to
conceal the money he made in the drug trade. (Hiaasen, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SODOMY _ THORNDALE, Texas _ Prank? Hazing? Sodomy? At
least five people know what happened on an October morning last
year in the high school weight room when four freshmen football
players struggled with another kid. Whatever happened, allegations
flew that the football-crazy town of Thorndale, 30 miles southwest
of Austin, protected the ballplayers involved by covering up the
incident. The Milam County, Texas, prosecutor last month filed
juvenile charges in the case. And the town's angst began anew.
(McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TRIAL_ CAMERON, Texas _ Following the trial of four
Thorndale High School students accused of sexual assault against
one of their classmates. (Rivera, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES _ Hurricane Georges barreled into the northeastern
Caribbean with 110-mph winds today, flooding roads, toppling trees
and utility lines and forcing thousands to evacuate their homes.
More than 1,600 people sought shelter in schools and public
buildings in the U.S. Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico, where the
full force of the storm was expected to strike later today.
(Emling, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH GRAPHIC showing route
of Georges and Ivan.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-PREDATORS _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ A Border Patrol
agent in Riviera Beach who came across Florida's sexual predator
list on the Internet last December prompted an offensive by the
agency to deport non-citizens convicted of sexual assault on
children. So far, 160 non-citizens have been kicked out of Florida,
including 58 from Palm Beach County. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-ATTYGEN-ADS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Democrat Jim Mattox hits the
airwaves with his first ad of his campaign for attorney general.
Will Mattox, known as the Junkyard Dog of Texas politics, use
disparing remarks in Republican John Cornyn's ad last week to go
negative, or will he take the high road? Democrat John Sharp also
unveils a new ad Monday. (McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-CRIME _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Genetic analysis of DNA that put
Robert Alan Woods behind bars for a murder police say he committed
14 years ago and freed Ben Salazar from a 30-year-prison sentence
for a rape he did not do is too powerful a tool to go unquestioned,
critics say. Defense attorneys like Jeff Senter believe the people
who run crime labs are too certain of their methods and and provide
a look only at the probability, not the certainty, that a suspect's
DNA matches samples at a crime scene. Most scientists, however, say
the testing is a solid, proven and accurate way of linking suspects
to a crime. (Banta, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
