<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 5-page package on the release of
Clinton's grand jury testimony and other developments related to
the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall on the release of the video
of Clinton's testimony and other documents. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RESPONSE (Washington) _ The White House response to the
broadcast of the video. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: As Clinton talks
about sex on one channel and foreign economic issues on another,
R.W. Apple Jr., N.Y. Times chief correspondent, reflects on how
today is but one moment, though a significant one, in the 35-year
deterioration of the connection between the people and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PERJURY (Washington) _ Many people, including members of
Congress, have already made up their minds that Clinton lied. The
question is, is it perjury? Even if it is, is lying to hide an
illicit affair an impeachable offense? By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMAGE (Washington) _ A look at how the president is
coming across on the small screen. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Reaction from Congress to the
day's events.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONICA (Washington) _ A look at Monica Lewinsky's
testimony: What the proffers and immunity agreements and eventual
testimony show about Monica's story and how it may have changed. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HILLARY (New York) _ Mrs. Clinton participates in a
conference on globalization at NYU. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (New York) _ The president's day in New York,
including the NYU conference on globalization with heads of state
like Britain's Tony Blair and Italy's Romano Prodi. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   See also, U.N.-CLINTON, on his speech there, listed under
international.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TACTIC (Washington) _ On Kenneth Starr's perjury trap:
were his aggressive tactics wise? By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WATCH (Undated) _ The reaction of those watching Clinton
on TV, and of those who chose not to watch. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we will have some 700-word reaction stories from
around the country; details to come.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOHL (Frankfurt, Germany) _ German Chancellor Kohl says
public interest in Monica Lewinsky and Clinton makes him want to
``throw up.'' By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Clinton video as theater. A
review by N.Y. Times critic Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA (Undated) _ How the networks and all-news stations
played the video tape. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   We are also planning approximately two pages of exerpts from the
various documents released today; details to come.
</P>
<P>
   However, because of its large size and wide availability, The
New York Times News Service will not move the full transcript of
the Clinton testimony on the news wire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGES (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ Hurricane Georges
bears down on Puerto Rico. The storm was expected to directly hit
the island about noon with the eye crossing at about 6 p.m. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; United Nations &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) _ President Clinton gives a speech
on terrorism as the U.N. General Assembly opens; other
developments. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAN (United Nations) _ The Iranian president addresses the
U.N. General Assembly. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MANDELA (United Nations) _ South African President Nelson
Mandela makes his final U.N. appearance. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-OBUCHI (New York) _ An interview with Japanese Prime
Minister Obuchi the day before his meeting with President Clinton.
By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-BLAIR (New York) _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair goes
to Wall Street to talk about revamping the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GLOBAL-SUMMIT (New York) _ The global summit meeting at New
York University's law school with the appearance of the Clintons,
Tony Blair, etc., is supposed to be the culmination of the school's
efforts to become an international presence. Has their big moment
been eclipsed by the videotape? By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TANZANIA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Two men are charged in
Tanzania in connection with the embassy bombing there. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-SECURITY (Washington) _ The administration asks Congress
for more money for embassy security. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia: Finance Ministry
actions on treasury bills, an opposition leader, Grigory Yavlinsky,
hospitalized with heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO-U.S. (Belgrade) _ U.S. envoy Christopher Hill meets
with Yugoslav President Milosevic to discuss a plan for Kosovo. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-UNREST (Kuala Lumpur) _ Developments: street protests,
government meetings, a visit by Queen Elizabeth. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-SHOPS (New York) _ If it is true, as Disraeli once said,
that the British are a nation of shopkeepers, why is it that they
can't seem to keep shop over here? Many British retailers have
tried their hand in the United States and failed, like Conran's
Habitat, a defunct housewares chain, and Next, a trendy clothing
store. Others made a splash initially but later struggled mightily,
most notably Laura Ashley and the Body Shop. The reasons are many,
ranging from Americans' obsession with bargains to a bevy of real
estate mistakes made by British retail companies to the sheer
vastness of the American marketplace. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks tumble but rebound. Bonds rise
sharply. At 2:15 p.m., the industrial average was up 34 points.
Overseas, prices decreased 2.8 percent in Tokyo and 3.7 percent in
Hong Kong. They fell 4 percent in Frankfurt, 1.9 percent in London,
4.3 percent in Brazil and 2.7 percent in Mexico. On the American
debt market, the long bond was up 28/32 point at midday, with the
yield at 5.09 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Cracks develop in the Japanese bank plan.
By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   See also U.N.-OBUCHI, under international.
</P>
<P>
   COMSAT (Undated) _ How Comsat, which once had a virtual monopoly
in the American satellite communications business, reached the
point where it could be scooped up by Lockheed. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   GUIDANT-SULZER (Undated) _ Two acquisitions of companies that
make cardiology equipment. Guidant buys Sulzer's pacemaker unit for
as much as $850 million (in WSJ). General Electric's medical
systems unit buys Marquette Medical Systems for about $808 million
in stock. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-ALLIANCE (London) _ British Airways and American
Airlines expand their alliance to include Cathay Pacific, Canadian
Airlines and Qantas. The plan will enable the five carriers to feed
passengers onto one another's flights and link frequent flyer
programs. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis' ``Abroad at Home''; details to come.
</P>
