<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      09-21 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANK-AND-FILE DEMOCRATS GIVE THE CLINTONS A HELPING HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fay Wilborn says she wasn't shocked or disgusted
with President Clinton when he admitted having an extramarital
affair with a former White House intern. She was disappointed at
him for being ``foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was too smart to fall for all this,'' the retired
bookkeeper said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilborn, 92, reserves harsher words for others involved in the
nation's great political soap opera: independent counsel Kenneth
Starr (``a horrible man''), the Republicans (``they couldn't beat
him in an election, so they did the next best thing'') and Monica
Lewinsky (``I used to work in offices, and there's one just like
her in every office.'')
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is going to battle House Republicans to serve out his
term, he's likely to need the support of people like Wilborn.
</P>
<P>
   Wilborn is among the Americans who have given anywhere from $1
to $10,000 this year to Clinton's legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has raised $2.2 million to help pay personal legal
bills for the president and first lady.
</P>
<P>
   The list of contributors was headed by Clinton's Hollywood
friends _ Steven Spielberg and his wife Kate Capshaw, Barbra
Streisand, Tom Hanks, David Geffen, Ron Howard and Jeffrey
Katzenberg, each of whom gave $10,000, the maximum allowable under
the fund's rules. But almost 10,000 other contributors gave smaller
amounts _ such as Wilborn, who gave $10.
</P>
<P>
   These and other contributors are Clinton loyalists who supported
him early in the 1992 campaign after the Gennifer Flowers affair
hit the news. They supported him after Paula Jones sued for sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the faithful opened their wallets again and gave to the
defense fund after the Lewinsky story broke and Clinton made his
finger-wagging denial of the affair. But their faith has been
tested in recent weeks, as Clinton admitted lying to the public,
and Starr revealed tawdry details of the affair and laid out
grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I tended to believe him,'' said Helen Howard,
a retired social worker in Mill Valley who gave $50 to the fund
after receiving a letter asking for contributions. But as the
evidence piled up, she began to have her doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more stuff came out, especially when the Starr
report was published, it was clear he had acted inappropriately,''
Howard said. ``I'm disappointed. I think the man has been reckless.
He should have controlled himself a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Howard, a lifelong Democrat, still believes the affair has
had little effect on the president's policies, which she supports.
And she sees a hidden agenda by Republicans pushing for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they want is to get 30 more right-wing
representatives in the House,'' Howard said. ``I think that's what
this is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund, called the Clinton Legal Expense Trust, was set up
when an earlier legal defense fund folded in January after raising
just $1.5 million in 3 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the trust has sent out solicitation letters to
people who contributed to the Clinton-Gore presidential campaign
and to the Democratic National Committee. In an April letter,
former U.S. Sen. David Pryor of Arkansas urged supporters to ``join
other friends of the Clintons in contributing to the trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who have backed the president in his legal battles
are longtime Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are giving because they were Democrats when they were
born and probably will have a Democrat plaque on their caskets,''
said Bob Mulholland, a Democratic Party campaign strategist in
California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But even Clinton's strongest admirers suggested his behavior
showed deeper flaws. Some said that the president seemed to suffer
from sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   June Lamb, a licensed family therapist from San Mateo who gave
$50 to the fund, said Clinton's sexual affair reflected unresolved
issues from his difficult childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sympathetic to the hole he's dug himself into,'' Lamb
said. ``I feel he's really got a problem. It's kind of like a stage
of arrested development. From what little I know about his
background, it's very plausible that he hasn't had time to resolve
these issues. It's very sad that it's become rather serious at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb said Starr's report showed the prosecutor was ``in a state
of totally repressed sexuality ... this has just been an orgy for
him to get out some of his repression.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested both might need counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need (Clinton's) leadership right now,'' Lamb said. ``He
needs to finish his term and then get therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   With his legal bills continuing to grow, Clinton is likely to
need his base of supporters. Anthony Essaye, executive director of
the trust in Washington, said the Clintons' legal bills had grown
from $4 million in February to more than $6.5 million as of August.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions have remained steady since the Starr report was
made public on Sept. 11, Essaye said, though it is too early to
tell whether the report would drive contributions up or down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
