<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUARD-HNS &LR;      09-21 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF COLD WAR MEANS BOOM FOR NATIONAL GUARD UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB GARDINIER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENVILLE, N.Y. _ The decision last week to base an elite new
anti-terrorist unit at the Stratton Air National Guard Base here is
only the latest example of how this once-sleepy airfield is now a
key part of the New York Guard's strategy to rebuild the
organization from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the slippery slope to extinction,'' said Brig. Gen.
William Martin, deputy adjutant general of the state Guard,
describing budget and personnel cuts in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts in recent years to reform the Guard have started to
pay off. And Stratton is riding on the back of the organization's
efforts to turn itself around. Last week, officials announced that
one of 10 new anti-terrorist units, designed to respond to domestic
crises, will be based here.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-terrorist unit, which will add at least 22 full-time
military personnel to the post, is known as Rapid Assessment and
Initial Detection, Martin said. He added that Stratton was one of
10 bases nationwide designated by the Defense Department to receive
the units, which will respond to incidents of biological, chemical
or nuclear terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location of the base made it a candidate for the unit, but
we also lobbied hard to get it,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Guard officials say New York's selection as one of the sites is
recognition that the New York Guard is no longer considered a
second-rate organization.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to identify the building where the
anti-terrorist unit will be located. The unit will be operational
by 2000, said Maj. Robert Bullock, base public information officer.
</P>
<P>
   But the base has seen other expansions in recent years. Massive
new steel hangars are rising and hundreds of jobs are flowing in.
The key to much of the growth is the ability of the Guard to
reshape itself in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in recent years 140 soldiers were assigned to a
counter-drug operation based at Stratton. With a budget of about $6
million a year, the unit uses UH-60 Blackhawk helicopters and
fixed-wing aircraft equipped with night-vision and thermal-imaging
equipment to find marijuana fields. The unit also lends its
high-tech help to police agencies to detect the locations of people
in buildings during larger scale drug raids.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard, like other military forces, has been casting around
in the post-Cold War world for a new mission. And like active-duty
forces, the state Guard has seized on the role of combating drugs
and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard, which reports to the governor, is more suited to some
of these missions. Active-duty soldiers and Marines, for example,
cannot be easily deployed within U.S. borders. The Guard, on the
other hand, can be deployed by the governor and often is during
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   And Guard officials say their troops are more accustomed to
working with civilian organizations, such as police and fire
departments, than active-duty forces.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these trendy new missions, the mainstay of Stratton
continues to be Operation Deep Freeze, an operation to fly supplies
and people from around the world to science outposts in Antarctica.
The mission is expanding and will add 220 additional service
personnel this year, bringing the total to 1,262 active-duty and
part-time troops.
</P>
<P>
   The 109th Tactical Airlift Wing's payroll went from $19.6
million in 1994 to $32.3 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 109th started in the Cold War era by flying supplies to
Greenland, where radar units were set up to give the United States
warning of any Soviet bombers or missiles that may have been
launched.
</P>
<P>
   But the unit made a smooth shift after the end of the Cold War.
Now the 109th works for the National Science Foundation, which
oversees scientific missions to Greenland and Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation, which funds these scientific
missions, is funneling millions of dollars into Stratton in support
of Operation Deep Freeze.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department also is spending money to rebuild
infrastructure. On a recent day the sparks fell from construction
crews welding together the skeleton for a new fuel supply hangar
while nearby crews worked on a four-engine LC-130 ski-equipped
cargo plane parked on the gleaming gray floor of another new
hangar.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the addition of troops, $32 million is earmarked for
hangar, communications center and dining hall improvements, as well
as remodeling and enlarging an operations facility that houses
offices and training facilities for flight crews.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Guard had declined steadily in the late 1980s and
early 1990s. The size of the Army National Guard had fallen to
11,625 troops in 1996 from its high in 1985 of 21,965.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized no one knew or cared about the Guard, and our
self-image suffered because we were like a football team that
practiced but never played,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 a state inspector issued a report saying the Guard was
run from 1983 to 1990 in a ``pervasively corrupt atmosphere.'' Two
Guard officials pleaded guilty to billing the federal government
for thousands of dollars in tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found some guard members secured unearned college
degrees in order to win promotions, and that cronyism and
favoritism had damaged careers. Soldiers were also used by the
brass for personal errands and home improvements and military
aircraft were used for non-military reasons, in one case to
transport Maine lobsters for a high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to sit and wait to be called. Now we act,'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   And now top brass seek out new missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more permanent nature of the Guard has been very good for
attracting these outside missions,'' said Brig. Gen. Archie
Berberian, chief of staff and assistant adjutant general of the
state Air National Guard. Officials said the Guard has also been
able to expand its missions because it can afford to be more
selective, choosing only quality recruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
