</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEATING-HUSBANDS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE CHEATING HUSBANDS
</HEADLINE>
  By ROSANNE ROSEN 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 c.1998 Rosanne Rosen 
 World rights except Columbus, Ohio 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you caught your husband in bed with another woman or learned
about a one-night stand, you wouldn't be the first to find your
mate was a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Or the first who chose to forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   Laura R. Meers, a psychologist in Columbus, Ohio, has observed
during 20 years of practice a change in attitude. ``I used to see
when an affair lead to an immediate divorce,'' she said. ``Now men
and women have become more tolerant. In some ways that is not all
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Meers does not advocate infidelity. However, she thinks the
discovery of infidelity leads directly to issues that drew the
couple apart, and if resolved can lead them back together again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not every wife is willing to forgive and move on,
especially if the lies and cover-up are too damaging, Dory
Hollander, author of ``101 Lies Men Tell Women'' (Harper Perennial,
1997) said in a telephone interview from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Meers says half the women in her practice who have been
confronted with an unfaithful spouse choose to separate. Bonnie
Eaker Weil, author of ``Adultery, The Forgivable Sin'' (Hastings
House, 1994) estimates that about one-third of the couples touched
by infidelity manage to work it out.
</P>
<P>
   Encounters that are strictly sexual are the least hurtful to
wives and less damaging to a marriage. ``If it is only a sexual
affair, a woman can convince herself that her husband is not
rejecting her as a life partner and still values their
partnership,'' Elayne Savage, author of ``Don't Take It Personally
(New Harbinger, 1997), said in a telephone interview from Berkeley,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   How well the indiscretion is kept under wraps may determine a
woman's ultimate decision. ``The public humiliation of an affair is
generally what most people find intolerable,'' said William
Friedman, a family-law attorney in Columbus. ``I don't see many
people who could appear in public like Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Weil said it is old-fashioned love that keeps women like Clinton
and Kathie Lee Gifford in their marriages despite the public
exposure of their spouses' affairs. ``Love is a bond or psychic
connection,'' Weil said. ``It is a journey through good territory
and bad in which two people are able to connect, disconnect and
more importantly reconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Birch, a psychologist in Columbus, has found that
optimism about a marriage is justified so long he sees evidence of
at least one of four key ingredients: love, trust, mutual respect
and passion.
</P>
<P>
   For Meers, the crucial factor is the self-esteem that women
manage to retain in the face of infidelity. She said the women who
keep their marriages intact generally perceive themselves as having
some power over decision making. Despite their initial reaction to
want to scream or punch their spouse, once they distance themselves
from the pain and regroup they can look at the situation more
objectively.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is willingness to take some responsibility for
past failures in the marriage, experts agree. ``The woman who is
able to admit, 'Maybe I wasn't fulfilling enough of his needs,' is
more likely to reconcile than the grudge-holder who reacts out of
pain and anger,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   But if a husband persists in blaming his wife for his
philandering, if he refuses to voice repentance and if he fails to
admit responsibility for a making a bad choice, it is less likely
that a woman will be able to take the last essential step of
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The wife who continues to stand by her man lovingly is a woman
who can forgive him, Meers says. Forgiveness _ the willingness to
let go of any discussion or acknowledgment that the actual affair
took place _ is a tall but necessary order to rebuild the trust
that is essential to continuing in a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive? Absolutely,'' Meers advised.
</P>
<P>
   Forget? Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ( ROSANNE ROSEN is a free-lance writer based in Columbus, Ohio.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
