<HEADER>
A6306 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYBRID-ROSES-LIFEBEAT     09-21 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYBRID-ROSES-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HYBRID ROSES ARE BEAUTIFUL WITHOUT BOTHER
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color slides of ``The Reeve'' and ``Rose Lucetta'' hybrid
roses. 
 By SUSAN MCCLURE 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has grown hybrid tea roses will know that the
beautiful blooms take a lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sun, rich soil with good drainage, regular fertilizing,
careful pruning all through the growing season, and spraying for
pests and diseases may all required to keep the plant in fine
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Rose lovers jumped for joy when a new breed of roses,
collectively called landscape roses, appeared early in the 1990s.
These roses combined durability, bushy growth, and fragrance of
old-fashioned roses with the repeat bloom of modern hybrids. They
were touted as being beautiful without bother.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups of landscape roses have spread across the the United
States. The most widely publicized are English Roses produced by
David Austin, an English breeder. They are romantic, full flowers
available in rich reds and purples or a range of yellows, pinks and
pastels.
</P>
<P>
   More down-to-earth, super hardy roses in the Explorer and
Parkland series have come from Agriculture Canada breeding
programs. Durable parents such as rugosa roses and the native
prairie rose (Rosa arkansana) give the hybrids attractive, bushy
forms and easy-care qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hawke, Chicago Botanic Garden coordinator of plant
evaluation programs, found Agriculture Canada roses to have their
own unique look quite different from Austin English Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Glowing claims surrounding landscape roses have lifted a few
eyebrows. Are Austin roses truly be hardy enough to handle northern
winters? While the Agriculture Canada roses were unquestionably
hardy, were they actually disease resistant?
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Botanic Garden knucked down to find some answers,
testing an assortment of roses under primitive conditions _ similar
to what they might experience in low-maintenace home landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the seven-year study were released in January in
Chicago Botanic Garden's Plant Evaluation Notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We planted in soil that was adequate, but not great as none of
our soil here is outstanding. Then we didn't do anything to the
plants except pruning out dead wood at the end of winter and
picking up fallen diseased leaves,'' explained Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a few roses that you could put out in the landscape
and let go, like a rugosa rose,'' Hawke said. ``But most would be
much better suited if given some winter protection, renewal
pruning, fertilization, and protection from black spot disease.
With that kind of care, there are many good possiblilties here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Austin Rose Results: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of over 90 Austin varieties now available, the Botanic Garden
has tested 31, which were planted in 1990. Hawke was delighted in
the flower quality, reporting, ``The colors and forms of these
blossoms were exquisite gems during the summer months.''
</P>
<P>
   But without regular pruning and shaping, cultivars such as
`Belle Story', `Cymbeline', `Fair Bianca', `Francine Austin',
`Gertrude Jekyll', `Othello', `Perdita', `The Countryman',
`Troilus', `Wise Portia', and `Yellow Button' grew either stubby or
gangly in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Those displaying naturally full, robust, and attractive forms
included `Constance Spry', `Graham Thomas', `Heritage', `Lucetta',
`Mary Rose', and `The Reeve'.
</P>
<P>
   Without a fungicide spray program, all the Austin roses suffered
from black spot to some degree. There was some resistance shown by
`Cymbeline', `Lucetta', and `The Reeve'.
</P>
<P>
   There were no total losses from winter kill during the time of
the trial, proving English roses are indeed hardy. During severe
winters, the plants died back to the ground but reemerged from
roots in spring similar to a hybrid tea rose.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, three English roses rated a hearty recommendation:
`Constance Spry', with large, soft-pink, double flowers; `Lucetta',
with large, blush-pink, semidouble flowers; and `The Reeve', with
dark pink, moderately large, double flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Agriculture Canada Results: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen varieties of Agriculture Canada roses were planted in
1992. They differed from the English roses in producing hips,
bright orange or red fruit that looked attractive deep into winter.
Hybrids derived from rugosa roses such as `David Thompson', `Henry
Hudson', `Jens Munk', and `Martin Frobisher' were highly resistant
to black spot.
</P>
<P>
   With long and lovely stems full of flower, climbing roses such
as `Henry Kelsey', with medium sized red flowers, `John Davis',
with moderately large, pink flowers, and `William Baffin', with
medium sized, dark pink flowers, were among the best roses in the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Other top contenders included `Assiniboine', with moderately
large, purple-red flowers, `Champlain', with moderately large, dark
red flowers, and `Jens Munk' with medium sized pink flowers.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   ( SUSAN MCCLURE is a free-lance writer based in Valparaiso,
Ind.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
