<HEADER>
A6308 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-SKIN-LIFEBEAT-NY     09-21 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-SKIN-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BABY YOUR NEWBORN'S SKIN
</HEADLINE>
  By LEAH INGRAM 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many parents expect their newborn to enter the world looking
like the children on baby food jars. I know I did, and boy, was I
surprised the first time I saw my eldest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't look like peaches and cream. She looked like a prune.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely your baby's skin will be far from perfect during
infancy. From itchy rashes to flaking skin, a number of conditions
can affect your child in the first year of life. The good news is
that most of them can be diagnosed easily by your baby's doctor and
treated at home.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your baby is lucky enough to escape the spots, flakes
and bumps of infancy, you'll still need to remember a few things to
help his skin stay healthy. Until your newborn's circumcised penis
and/or umbilical cord have healed, give him a sponge bath every
other day. Once they have healed, he can start enjoying regular
baths in an infant tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bathing should be done on an as-needed basis,'' says Dr. Julie
Anne Winfield, a pediatric dermatologist at the University of
Minnesota College of Medicine in Minneapolis. ``If your baby has
been inside all day and isn't very dirty, then he might not need a
bath that night.'' However, babies who play outside every day _ or
who find bathing a soothing part of their nighttime ritual _ should
definitely have a daily bath.
</P>
<P>
   While creams aren't necessary after a bath (unless your baby
tends to have dry skin), they're good for other purposes, such as
massage, says Winfield. If you use a moisturizing cream or lotion,
choose one that's formulated for a baby's sensitive skin.
</P>
<P>
   Though most infant skin problems are perfectly harmless, some
can look a bit scary. Always check with your child's doctor if you
notice a new bump or rash to determine the best treatment. What
follows is a guide to identifying and treating the most common
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Facts on Flakes &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both of my children were born looking as if they were shedding
an outer layer. They were each born past their due date, and, like
most postmature babies, they had peeling and flaking skin.
According to Dr. April Douglass-Bright, a pediatrician at the
Children's Regional Hospital at Cooper Hospital/University Medical
Center in Camden, N.J., peeling skin is an aftereffect of prolonged
exposure to amniotic fluid inside the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Early and on-time babies may look like they're molting, too, but
for a different reason: vernix caseosa, ``a whitish, cheesy coating
derived from secretions of the sebaceous glands and the normal
breakdown of a baby's epidermis,'' says Winfield. Doctors believe
it protects the skin in utero and lubricates the baby for the
journey down the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Peeling skin from vernix caseosa or exposure to amniotic fluid
should clear up within four weeks without treatment. But in the
meantime, it's important to prevent your baby's flaky skin from
cracking, which could lead to infection. ``After each diaper change
or bath, apply a moisturizing lotion that's made for babies,''
suggests Douglass-Bright.
</P>
<P>
   Another fairly common source of flakes is cradle cap, a
pinkish-orange scalp rash that's most prevalent in infants up to 3
months old. ``It looks like a baby's scalp has layers of scales or
really bad dandruff,'' explains Douglas-Bright. Cheryl Bogner of
Fairfield, Conn., recalls that during her daughter Ariella's bout
with cradle cap, ``if you touched her head, flakes of skin would
waft off.''
</P>
<P>
   Cradle cap almost always disappears by a child's first birthday.
In the meantime, gently rubbing some mineral oil or cooking oil
into your baby's scalp before shampooing can loosen the scales and
help minimize the flaking, says Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spot Check &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as some kids are born with flaky skin, others are born with
spots. One you may very well notice on your newborn is a cluster of
extra blood vessels known as a salmon patch or stork bite. These
flat, light pink patches that look like splotches of paint can show
up on the eyelids or forehead or between the eyes, as well as on
the neck. Most stork bites fade completely within the first year,
says Winfield, except for those on the nape of the neck, which can
persist into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Intent on Itching &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eczema is one of the most common skin disorders in infants, says
Dr. Amy Paller, head of dermatology at Children's Memorial Hospital
in Chicago. In the beginning, it looks simply like an area of red,
chafed skin, or it can appear scaly, like cradle cap that has
traveled down from the scalp.
</P>
<P>
   In the first few weeks of life, a baby with eczema will not be
able to get her hands to the affected areas to scratch, so she
might try to rub them on your shirt or on the sheet in her crib.
But once babies master the art of using their hands, between 3 and
4 months of age, they will go after eczema-affected skin with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no quick cure for eczema, many children outgrow
the condition within a few years. In the meantime, treatments can
help reduce the discomfort. For a bad case of eczema, your child's
doctor may prescribe a topical steroid cream or an
over-the-counter, oral antihistamine to decrease itching.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rating the Rashes &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every parent must do battle with diaper rash, which
starts off looking like red, sunburned skin covered with tiny bumps
and may develop into a crusting rash if infected. ``Diaper rash is
the result of prolonged wetness and exposure to irritants in the
baby's urine and stool,'' says Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to prevent it, she adds, is to change your baby's
diaper frequently, especially right after a bowel movement. Use a
prepackaged wipe or warm water and mild soap to clean the area.
Follow up with an application of diaper rash cream.
</P>
<P>
   Winfield suggests choosing one with zinc oxide because it acts
as a barrier against moisture and causes the wetness from urine and
feces to bead right off the skin.
</P>
<P>
   If your baby gets diaper rash fairly often, it might be that she
has particularly sensitive skin. According to Paller, this is
probably the case if she always has diaper rash, if a rash usually
develops on her face after she eats, and/or if she get rashes that
seem to come out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   My youngest daughter does, so on my pediatrician's advice, I
switched to a dye- and fragrance-free detergent and stopped using
softener sheets. I tried a lot of different cleansing products to
see which ones were least irritating to her skin (Johnson &AMP;
Johnson's Ultra Sensitive line was the winner for us).
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to report that a little patience and a lot of tender,
loving care helped clear up my daughters' bouts with peeling skin
and kept their diaper rashes and sensitive-skin problems in check.
Now my two little girls have the cherubic complexion that I always
dreamed they would.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (Leah Ingram is a free-lance writer based in Ewing, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
