<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following
 &UR; ScienceTimes &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUPERSTRING (Undated) _ Special report. The theory of
superstrings, physics' leading candidate for the proverbial Theory
of Everything, has been described as a piece of 21st century
physics that fell into the 20th century and will take 22nd-century
mathematics to solve. This summer the quest took a giant step
forward with a breakthrough by an Argentine/Harvard theorist, Juan
Maldacena, that excited physicists to the point of dancing a
version of the Macarena (they called it the Maldacena). A special
report, by George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and two graphics.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAFINA-SHARKS (Off Montauk Point, N.Y.) _ The sea here once
boiled with sharks. The fury provided a semi-factual basis for
``Jaws'' and a whole mythology about seamen and swimmers threatened
by fierce predators with razor-sharp teeth. But today, the sharks
are fewer in number and catching one of the killers can frustrate
even professionals like Dr. Carl Safina, a marine conservationist
who was prowling off Montauk Point here recently to tag the fish
that have become his obsession. To a striking degree, Safina, 43,
has succeeded at turning his ideas into action, at times global
action. Articulate and energetic, knowledgeable and willing to take
a stand, he is something of an eco-warrior ready to fight public
indifference and lax regulators. His role has won him many friends
and foes. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANCIENT-AMERICANS (Undated) _ About 12,000 years ago, people
living in what is now southern Peru camped on the Pacific shore and
feasted on fish, seabirds and shellfish. The remains of stone
tools, hearths and butchered bird bones found at two Peruvian sites
are the earliest known evidence of maritime-based cultures in the
New World, scientists reported last week. By John Noble Wilford.
(1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREDICTIONS (Undated) _ Scientific sages depend not on tea
leaves or the positions of planets but on tools like mathematical
modeling, statistical analysis, complexity theory, celestial
mechanics, geology, economics and epidemiology. Needless to say,
scientists discount the naive paradigms of fortune tellers, ancient
and modern. Alas, rational approaches to prediction also fail all
too often, and it may be that there are some phenomena for which
predictions will remain forever out of reach. An essay by Malcolm
Browne. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ When shopping for a computer
system, the last features that buyers typically consider, if they
consider them at all, are the audio speakers. Most multimedia
computers are equipped with a pathetic pair of plastic-encased
speakers of a fidelity about equal to a clock radio, but now on the
market are systems that rival some of the best in home stereo
equipment. By Rob Fixmer. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) Short takes on science. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: On avian
procreation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAESAREAN-HEALTH (Undated) _ Although hard figures are hard to
come by, some doctors say that more women are asking for elective
C-sections, even when they are not necessary. And doctors are
sharply divided on how to respond. Driving this turnaround are
several recent reports that question the safety of vaginal
deliveries in certain circumstances. By Susan Gilbert. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Growing numbers of Americans are
stepping daily into a potential minefield of substances loosely
referred to as dietary supplements, many of which have little or
nothing to do with the components of foods people normally consume.
And increasingly these pill poppers are getting into trouble,
suffering toxic reactions to deliberate or accidental components of
these products or sacrificing the chance to be helped by
conventional medicine. By Jane E. Brody. (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-POTASSIUM-HEALTH (Undated) _ A study that tracked nearly
44,000 men over eight years has found that those whose diets
included large amounts of potassium had one-third fewer strokes
than those who did not. The benefits appeared to be greatest for
men with high blood pressure. By John O'Neil. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on health.
</P>
