<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEANUP-1STLD-WRITETH     09-21 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEANUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILOR'S LETTER AMONG `TRASH' CLEANED UP FROM BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS 3rdgraf, Kudienko Vladislav, to add letter was
undated)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A letter in an airtight container from a
Ukranian sailor seeking an American pen pal took first prize as the
most unusual thing found in the San Francisco Bay area's coastal
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   A troop of Eagle Scouts helping clean up Angel Island won $500
for finding the handwritten letter and photo, apparently tossed
from a ship docked in the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Kudienko Vladislav apologized in the letter for his poor English
and for causing pollution, but said he didn't want to die without
trying to make an acquaintance with someone with whom he might have
some common interests. The undated letter noted he would return
home in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so cool,'' said Judi Shils of the California Coastal
Commission. ``I just thought it would be amazing if people saw this
and everybody wrote to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scout troop was part of a statewide turnout of more than
40,000 volunteers who scoured the coastline, lakefronts and
riverbanks Saturday under brilliant skies. They picked up at least
400,000 pounds of trash and recyclables.
</P>
<P>
   That's less than was picked up last year. Shils said people are
beginning to think twice before tossing discards in storm drains
and leaving garbage behind on beaches. The annual California
Coastal Cleanup Day, now in its 14th year, is also leaving the
waterways less cluttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is getting out,'' Shils said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
