<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBS-FALL-TEX     09-21 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-FALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS FALL SEASON OFFERS A THOUGHTFUL ALTERNATIVE TO NETWORK FARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besieged by creeping commercialization, privatization,
homogenization and competition, is PBS drifting ever further from
its assigned role as alternative media and becoming your
run-of-the-mill cable channel?
</P>
<P>
   PBS for the 1998-99 season will offer a variety of educational
and enlightening fare _ some good, some great. But does it remain
true that, ``If PBS doesn't do it, who will?''
</P>
<P>
   You be the judge:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Farmer's Wife'' (8-10 p.m. CDT Monday and Tuesday; 8-10:30
p.m. CDT Wednesday) _ ``Frontline'' offers this splendid
independent film focusing on the intimate, real-life saga of
Juanita and Darrel Buschkoetter, a young Nebraska couple trying to
save their farm and marriage. It was shot over a three-year period
and assembled from more than 200 hours of footage. Touching and
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Name'' (9 p.m. CDT Oct. 3) _ Chronicles what happens to
a young man looking for both sides of his family _ descendants of
the white family of slave owners and the black family of slaves.
Engaging, funny, a sad truth about secrets and lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africans in America'' (9 p.m. CDT Oct. 19-22) _ Produced by
Orlando Bagwell (''Malcolm X: Making It Plain'') this six-part,
richly detailed series examines the history of slavery in America.
The 90-minute episodes start with the evolution of slavery,
beginning in 1619 in Virginia, following through its growth and
constitutional demise at the end of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats'' (Nov. 2) _ ``Great Performances'' restages this hit
musical with Elaine Paige, who created the role of glamorous
pussycat Grizabella, returning to sing ``Memory.'' The production
was recorded with the aid of a specially assembled 76-piece
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``America 1900'' (Nov. 18) _ ``The American Experience'' offers
up this three-hour special featuring the voice of David McCullough
and produced by David Grubin (''FDR,'' ``LBJ''). It takes the first
year of what would be called ``the American century,'' a year when
war was building in the Philippines, William McKinley was
president, and that hurricane was devastating Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' (Nov. 10-11) _ Ken Burns takes a crack at
the famed architect in two 90-minute segments, looking at both the
man and American architecture. He features audio recordings,
interviews and commentary from architects such as Philip Johnson
and Maya Lin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice Mummies'' (Nov. 24) _ From ``Nova,'' this three-hour
program digs into the frozen tundra of the Andes, Siberia and the
Alps.
</P>
<P>
   ``India: Land of the Tiger'' (Nov. 15-17) _ This three-part
``Nature'' series takes viewers on a tour that brings to light the
connection between wildlife and Indian life. In the opening
segment, religion and lions of the Gir Forest are intertwined with
a look at animal life of the Ganges and the Brahmaputra _ two
sacred rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerds 2.0.1: A Brief History of the Internet'' (Nov. 25 ) _
Three hours chronicling the growth of the Internet, with PBS Online
columnist Robert X. Cringely (''Triumph of the Nerds''). The
question is whether Net geeks will turn away from their computers
long enough to watch.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
