<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITTING AMID HISTORY: I THINK I NEED A BATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Few would dispute the notion that the Clinton
sex scandal is the biggest political story of the decade. Nor would
any reasonable person deny that we are in the midst of the gravest
constitutional crisis since the original ``-gate'' back in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But I keep going back to those salacious details.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: This does not feel like Watergate. I know I'm
supposed to take it all seriously, particularly being in the news
business. And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   You'll have vO &LR; a Use me if I find it more hilarious than serious
when breathless television reporters scroll down computer screens
to read aloud what sounds like a cross between my seventh-grade sex
education class and an exceptionally low-budget porn movie.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and call me morally loose if I can't seem to get
lathered up about the president's sexual proclivities, or whom he
was talking to on the phone during one of those ``inappropriate''
moments he now regrets.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK. We've got ``obstruction of justice,'' and ``perjury,''
and other ominous phrases being bandied about, reminding us of a
story that once inspired thousands of young college students to go
take journalism classes.
</P>
<P>
   Now we all just want to go take a bath.
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment whether there are any crimes here that merit
impeachment. The fact is, we have somehow gone from Arkansas
cronyism and corruption to a political Theater of the Absurd.
</P>
<P>
   I submit to you that this could only come from the country that
gave the world Elvis, TV talk shows and fat-free potato chips. The
story we're all ignoring is our deep, collective dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   This is O.J. in the Beltway. The United States of Jerry
Springer. Political kitsch at best. If ever there were a match made
in hell, it's the union of Bill Clinton and Ken Starr (although I
admit Lewinsky-Tripp comes close).
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not saying I'm a grizzled old news hound who's seen it
all. Heck, I was just a dumb kid from rural Texas in 1974 when my
dad thrust me in front of the television set and told me to watch
history being made, albeit dubiously.
</P>
<P>
   Nor am I suggesting that we just blow off this story and its
fallout for Texas and American politics. Unfortunately, it's too
late for that.
</P>
<P>
   But I frankly felt more fulfilled after covering the Branch
Davidian standoff near Waco. And, oddly, I have poignantly fond
memories of the devastating 1992 sewer system explosion that I
covered in Guadalajara, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   I also wrote about the federal government shutdown of 1995, and
even though I now know I missed the real story (i.e., Monica's
first tryst with Bill), I didn't feel cheated.
</P>
<P>
   With all its import and gravity, I'm sure that Monicagate
probably fits the stereotype of the big story that every reporter
yearns to get in on. But if this is journalism's finest hour, I'll
gladly declare myself missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's Austin
bureau. You can write him at 1005 Congress Ave., Suite 920, Austin,
TX 78701, or at jroot(at)star-telegram.com, or call him at (512)
476-4294. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
