A6401 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHLEYS-TV-LADN     09-21 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHLEYS-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUESDAY'S SIRCOM SQUEEZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Ever since ``Frasier'' moved there in 1994,
television on Tuesday nights has meant a glut of sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   This season, ``Frasier'' has moved to Thursdays, but that
doesn't mean the emphasis has shifted to drama on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four new sitcoms, ``The Hughleys,'' ``Sports Night,'' ``Encore!
Encore!'' and ``Costello'' (which already premiered) have been
added to an evening that features ``Home Improvement,'' ``Spin
City,'' ``Mad About You,'' ``Just Shoot Me,'' ``Working'' and
``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the three new shows premiering tonight should last
the year. &QL; 
THE HUGHLEYS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   D.L. Hughley is a stand-up comedian with something to say. His
comedy is based on real-life experiences _ and so is his sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life Hughleys moved from the inner-city to West Hills _
and so do their television alter-egos.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl, as he is called in the sitcom, does not want to make any
new friends. He is offended when an elderly neighbor asks him to
help her take out the trash and is torn between his new cushy life
and the world he left behind.
</P>
<P>
   His link to the past is Milsap (John Henton), the head of sales
in Hughley's company, who visits often from the 'hood and accuses
Hughley of losing his ``blackness.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is straightforward in its approach, and the struggles
seem real. Hughley is upset and embarrassed that his daughter
selects a white doll over a black one. As it turns out, the choice
was made because the white doll came with more outfits.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Hughley does a fine job for a television newcomer and
shows timing and charisma. The stories remain solid throughout each
script, and ``The Hughleys'' teaches, not preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled between an admittedly aging ``Home Improvement'' and
rising sitcom ``Spin City,'' we probably will get to know a lot
about the Hughleys during the next few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``The Hughleys.''
</P>
<P>
   What: An African-American family moves into a white suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: D.L. Hughley, Elise Neal, Eric Allan Kramer, John
Henton, Marietta DePrima.
</P>
<P>
   Where: KABC (Channel 7).
</P>
<P>
   When: 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 3{ Stars.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NIGHT &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night,'' the show about the making of a nightly
television sports report, runs the danger of alienating both the
sports fan with its lack of attention to detail and the nonsports
fan with all the jargon thrown into the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   There are constant references to sports stadiums and teams, but
in the pilot you'll find the baseball, football and basketball
seasons are going on at the same time. According to the calendar,
that is an impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   The show tries to be ``Larry Sanders'' meets ``SportsCenter.''
The problem here is that ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' is more
entertaining than this fictionalized version. Even the commercials
for ``SportsCenter'' pack more laughs than a half-hour of ``Sports
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to another problem. The show tries to combine
drama with comedy, which works on hour-long shows but misses in a
half-hour format.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   What: A behind-the-scenes look at the making of a television
sports show.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Peter Krause, Josh Charles, Felicity Huffman, Robert
Guillaume, Joshua Malina.
</P>
<P>
   Where: KABC (Channel 7).
</P>
<P>
   When: 9:30 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 2 Stars. &QL; 
ENCORE! ENCORE! &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Farcical physical humor, annoying characters and a woman who
goes to strangers' funerals for the food and companionship.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the creators of five-time Emmy winning ``Frasier,''
have come up with?
</P>
<P>
   Two celebrated actors _ Tony Award winners Nathan Lane and Joan
Plowright _ can't even make much of this mess. Lane plays Joseph
Pinoni, an abrasive opera star who returns to the home of his
dysfunctional family when his voice becomes strained (we should
only be so lucky). The setup is reminiscent of last year's
short-lived ``Over the Top,'' starring equally obnoxious Tim Curry.
Plowright plays the lead character's mother, Marie, who finds
friendship at funerals.
</P>
<P>
   The story lines are totally implausible. Joseph, an insulting
snob who jabbers away, is somehow able to go with his teen-age
nephew into San Francisco and pick up two beautiful women who can't
get enough of him.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Frasier'' is the smartest comedy on network television,
``Encore!'' falls victim to formula writing: setup, bad joke;
setup, lame joke.
</P>
<P>
   A heralded show on the development slate, ``Encore'' was totally
revamped at one point before it hit the air; it's still a major
disappointment. A little bit of Lane goes a long way, a lot of him
goes nowhere. With an overdose, this could be an early casualty of
the television season.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Encore! Encore!''
</P>
<P>
   What: Nathan Lane, in what must be his biggest acting stretch
ever, plays a pompous womanizer. He is an opera singer with a
failing voice who goes back to his family's Napa Valley winery.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Nathan Lane, Joan Plowright, Glenne Headly, Ernie
Sabella, James Patrick Stuart, Trevor Fehrman.
</P>
<P>
   Where: NBC (Channel 4).
</P>
<P>
   When: 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 1{ Stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
