<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIANO-2ndTake-TEX     09-21 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: FOR $13,295.
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KAWAI
</P>
<P>
   The Kawai line ranges from a console for $3,500 to a concert
grand for $104,000. Like Yamaha, Kawai's traditional strength has
been durability and reliability, and its main markets have been
individuals and schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BALDWIN
</P>
<P>
   Uprights range from about $4,940 to $10,910. Grands range from
$23,630 for a 5-foot-3-inch model to $75,980 for a concert grand.
At these prices, Baldwin is the best bargain on the upper end among
traditional name-brand pianos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG CHANG
</P>
<P>
   With Yamaha and Kawai moving up, a Korean company, Young Chang,
is attacking the bargain-hunters' end of the market, beginning at
$4,000 for a console. If you want a big piano and don't care about
traditional name brands, Young Chang sells a line of grands ranging
from a baby grand for less than $10,000 to a 9-foot concert grand
for $40,000. Though you won't see one on the concert stage anytime
soon, you will find this brand recommended by Consumers Digest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAZIOLI
</P>
<P>
   If you want the world's biggest, most expensive piano, you can
buy an Italian-made Fazioli by calling International Piano
Galleries, an import specialist in North Little Rock, Ark. A
10-foot-2-inch concert grand, meticulously handcrafted, will cost
you $163,400. A less overwhelming 5-foot-2-inch Fazioli grand sells
for a mere $69,200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SILENT PIANO
</P>
<P>
   So you live in an apartment and the urge to practice hits at 1
a.m. What can you do without disturbing the neighbors? Now, you can
silence your piano.
</P>
<P>
   Steinway and Young Chang dealers offer a ``Quiet Time'' option
that can be added to acoustic pianos for $2,000-$2,500, allowing
you to turn off the acoustic sound and turn on electronic sound
that you hear through headphones, but your neighbors don't.
</P>
<P>
   One Yamaha dealer recommends a Midi connection, allowing silence
and a plethora of other electronic and digital options.
</P>
<P>
   And, although electronic pianos will never replace real pianos
completely, Kawai offers an impressive line of electronic keyboards
that very nearly duplicate a real piano touch and offer a huge
range of options at the flick of a switch. Not a bad option for an
apartment-dweller for $1,700-$8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin offers the similar Italian-made Pianovelle digital piano
at $2,390-$10,734.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
