<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPORARY TOUCHES DON'T HELP `HYPERION'S' OLD STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HYPERION BAY  
Starring: Mark-Paul Gosselaar, Dylan Neal, Sydney Penny, Christina
Moore, Cassidy Rae, Bart Johnson, Raymond J. Barry, Cindy Pickett 
On: WB 
Time: Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Please don't say this is the future of the ``Dallas''-styled
nighttime soap. ``Hyperion Bay'' wants to be a newfangled family
saga, a ``Knots Landing'' skewed young to reach the WB's beloved
young-adult audience. And it's got all the standard soap opera
setups: two brooding and battling brothers, a rigid father, a
thriving but mysterious high-tech business, and a trio of women
circling the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But the show is fairly dripping with fashionable angst and
bleakness, as well as some forced efforts to make it contemporary _
lines about how the office is ``very anti-Dilbert'' and how the
town of Hyperion Bay is ``three days ride from the nearest
Starbucks.'' It's not awful, but the scripts and the acting aren't
good enough to bring any life or distinction to the very familiar
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Mark-Paul Gosselaar plays the central character, Dennis Sweeney,
who returns to his small, struggling hometown to start up a branch
of a company that will bring riches to the local economy. He left
years earlier a bullied nerd, but now he's returning as a powerful
figure with just a little bit of revenge on his mind. ``We didn't
fit into their America,'' his boss says to Dennis about the
small-minded locals. ``But that's all gone. We're in charge. Now
they're scrambling to fit it with us.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Dennis's brother resents him, and the girl Dennis had a
crush on in high school is chasing after him _ much to the dismay
of her husband, who happens to be the guy who beat Dennis up in the
old days. Even one of Dennis's former high school principals learns
a small lesson in The New Dennis by the end of the premiere
episode. None of the actors look like they're having much fun amid
all these dark doings _ and it's easy to sympathize with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CONRAD-BOS &LR;      09-21 0294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONRAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH FORMULA FLIP-FLOP, `BLOOM' MIGHT BLOSSOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
CONRAD BLOOM 
Starring: Mark Feuerstein, Linda Lavin, Ever Carradine, Jessica
Stone, Lauren Graham, Paula Newsome 
On: NBC 
Time: Monday at 8:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Conrad Bloom'' flips one of the most overdone TV formulas of
the 1990s. Instead of yet another sitcom about an unmarried woman
in the city surrounded by a whack pack of mostly male supporting
players, this show offers us a single man, the city, and an
ensemble of needy and nutty women.
</P>
<P>
   It just might work. ``Conrad Bloom'' has the potential to become
a small charmer, if it can distinguish itself from the shows that
surround it (``Suddenly Susan'' and the inferior ``Caroline in the
City'') and if it can avoid pushing characters who are quirky for
quirky's sake. It has a breezy appeal, an affable actor _ Mark
Feuerstein _ at its center, and some sharp edges from Linda Lavin,
who brings freshness to the familiar role of guilt-tripping mother.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein's Conrad is an ambitious ad copywriter with a good
heart. He'd love to find romance, but he's a caretaker by nature
and can't stop giving his free time over to the women in his life.
There's his tree-hugging sister; his Lilith Fair-loving
ex-girlfriend and current best friend; his no-nonsense boss; his
ditzy, breast-feeding co-worker; and, of course, Mom, who is
simultaneously manipulative and helpless. The only male in the
ensemble beside Conrad is a legendary Clio-winning ad man, played
by ``Barney Miller'' alum Steve Landesberg, who's still partying
like it's 1969. Along with Conrad's mother, he requires an awful
lot of parenting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
