<HEADLINE>
`BRIAN BENBEN' SPICES UP TYPICAL NEWS-SHOW SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BRIAN BENBEN SHOW 
Starring: Brian Benben, Charles Esten, Lisa Thornhill, Wendell
Pierce, Luis Antonio Ramos, Susan Blommaert 
On: CBS 
Time: Monday at 9:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With their forced segues, fickle teleprompters, and Barbie and
Ken anchors flashing squintingly bright smiles, local news channels
are a ripe subject for ridicule. ``The Brian Benben Show'' is an
energetic go at those daily newscasts, which seem to get more
sensational and less sensible with each passing
weather-crisis-of-the-moment. It borrows freely from TV series like
``Murphy Brown'' and ``NewsRadio'' as it upends the inner workings
of an LA media outlet, but it takes a distinctively bold approach
to its satire. Despite a few juvenile moments, ``The Brian Benben
Show'' has a high-strung charm.
</P>
<P>
   Benben is familiar to fans of HBO's ``Dream On,'' as the book
editor whose romantic exploits were never easy, and whose thoughts
took the form of vintage TV and movie clips. On the new show he
plays a KYLA news anchor whose work life is never easy,
particularly when he's fired and replaced by Tabitha Berkeley and a
slimy fellow named Chad Rockwell, a former VH1 video jockey who
``tested off the charts.'' One of the jokes is that Benben is no
pillar of morality, but next to the demographically correct Chad,
he looks like the good guy. The despairing Benben is rehired by
KYLA, but he's demoted to lifestyles anchor when the previous
anchor is eaten by an ape. ``Now I'm the guy who interviews bearded
ladies,'' he cries, before concocting a plan to undermine Chad with
the help of some bad jokes and a little teleprompter tampering.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Benben is a likable physical comedian who knows how to play
harried and beleaguered, and many of the laughs in ``The Brian
Benben Show'' depend of his facial reactions to the insanity around
him. As long as the writers are willing to goof on him as
frequently as they heap scorn on Barbie and Ken, ``The Brian Benben
Show'' stands a chance to be a wacky winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
