<SLUG> BC-TV-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOCTORS' GIVES MODERN AILMENT CLICHE TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
L.A. DOCTORS 
Starring: Ken Olin, Rick Roberts, Sheryl Lee, Matt Craven 
On: CBS 
Time: Monday at 10 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet Evan Newman, father, doctor, saint. ``I want to treat
patients instead of diseases,'' he gushes with pitch-perfect
sincerity, after paying an impromptu visit to the home of a dying
man and interrupting his tight afternoon schedule to help an
elderly diabetic in a car crash. (And after taking his son to a
basketball game.)
</P>
<P>
   But don't open your phone books and start thumbing through the
``N'' pages just yet. Young and idealistic, Dr. Evan Newman is one
of those prime-time illusions, the sort of fantasy figure that the
more simplistic and manipulative TV shows use to hook viewers
(remember Marcus Welby?). With his freckles and tireless humanity,
Evan is nothing more than one of the four characters on ``L.A.
Doctors,'' an unsophisticated medical drama series. In an era of
HMOs, he's meant to be Dr. Feelgood.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the big button ``L.A. Doctors'' hopes to push. As we
face an age of depersonalized medicine, ``L.A. Doctors'' gives us
the daily conflicts of physicians who have left managed care to
start their own private practice. How will their business concerns
conflict with the business of saving lives? Can the doctors bring
in patients without selling out to the publicity machine? Don't
look to ``L.A. Doctors'' for fleshed-out answers to these
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Rick Roberts's Evan, Ken Olin from
``thirtysomething'' and ``EZ Streets'' is a prominent figure on the
show. He's supposed to be the crass rainmaker of the practice, the
Jaguar owner who commissions avant-garde art for the waiting room.
But by the end of the premiere, he, too, is making house calls and
getting touchy-feely (about not having children). One minute he's
the definitive shark, manipulating Evan into a publicist's hands.
The next he's hanging out at a pier to give some paternal advice to
a pregnant teen. Olin is a very good actor, but even he can't quite
seem to put his finger on his character's true nature. He deserves
better.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Lee, best recalled as Laura Palmer from ``Twin Peaks,''
joins the practice tonight, as a married workaholic who may well be
attracted to Evan. It's not clear where the writers plan to take
her.
</P>
<P>
   While ``ER'' manages to throw its doctors some unusual medical
cases, ``L.A. Doctors'' pulls out all the cliches. With the subplot
about the pregnant teen, the show borrows unimaginatively from
yesterday's news. As one of the doctors points out, we don't want
the girl's newborn to end up in a garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   In order for ``L.A. Doctors'' to survive, its writers _ and not
just the doctors themselves _ will need to avoid mistreating their
caseload.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
