<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING-CLASS `KING' NEEDS MORE IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE KING OF QUEENS 
Starring: Jerry Stiller, Kevin James, Leah Remini, Lisa Rieffel 
On: CBS 
Time: Monday at 8:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try, try, try again. Last season, ABC blended ``Roseanne'' with
``All in the Family'' for a crummy domestic sitcom called ``That's
Life.'' The working-class couple lived in Queens, the husband was
crude and anti-intellectual, the humor was grade-school level and
close to unbearable. Fortunately, it lasted only a few weeks. This
season, CBS gives the same beef-jerky formula another go round with
slight but certainly less painful results. ``The King of Queens''
is a run-of-the-mill family comedy that wants to be the show that
follows it, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' but ends up more like a
wan wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   The star of the series is stand-up comedian Kevin James, who has
had a recurrent role on ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' as one of Ray's
pals. A chunky man, James's Doug Heffernan works for a UPS-like
delivery service and adores only his wife, Carrie, more than his
new 70-inch television. He's a low-level guy's guy, hanging with
his posse of loser sports lovers but snuggling up to his wife
enough to keep her happy. Leah Remini, of ``Fired Up,'' plays
Carrie as a sweet but long-suffering woman who isn't above a little
finagling to get what she wants. She's wifey, 1990s style.
</P>
<P>
   It's all fairly bland, except that Carrie's father and her
sister have just moved into her Queens home, and her father is
played by Jerry Stiller. Originally, the pilot was shot with Jack
Carter as the crusty old guy, but the creators of ``The King of
Queens'' must have recognized the need for the addition of
something distinctive like Stiller's zany, stylized craziness, not
to mention his ``Seinfeld'' cache (he played George's father). Now
``The King of Queens'' is more like ``The Jerry Stiller Show,'' and
Stiller is meant to be the equivalent of Ray Romano's nutty mother.
When he's in the action, the show does perk up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The King of Queens'' will need to intensify its characters,
and not rely solely on Stiller for color, if it wants to achieve
true slice-of-life status. The writers also will need to be more
imaginative and less socially retro. In typical fall-season
fashion, tonight's episode sets up the series' situation, as
Stiller accidentally burns his house down and moves in with his
daughter and son-in-law. But by next week the show is already
struggling for material, as Doug panics when he learns that his
late mother-in-law was a heavy woman, and that Carrie may have a
tendency to gain as she ages. It's stock stuff, and written so
lazily it doesn't even turn the tables to take the King of Queens
to task for his own Henry VIII waistline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
