<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEX-WITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEX' LARGELY STRAIGHTFORWARD AND SENSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SEX WITH CINDY CRAWFORD 
Produced by: Gay Rosenthal 
On: ABC 
Date: Tuesday 10 p.m. 
Rated: TV14, D (frank dialogue)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ABC press release pitching the ``Sex With Cindy Crawford''
hourlong special Tuesday tonight at 10 p.m.) is a comic keeper.
``Sex ... with Cindy Crawford?'' it begins with
quasi-self-deprecation. Then: ``Who better with whom to talk about
sex than a woman with one of the world's recognizable faces.'' Say
what?
</P>
<P>
   Forget the jackknifed syntax and goofy non sequitur: The dopey
point, I'm fairly sure, is that a supermodel sex symbol and
skin-market profiteer is the ideal facilitator for a serious TV
show on human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Then factor in, if you will, the October Playboy, not mentioned
in ``Sex'' but featuring Crawford on the cover and promising 14
pages of new Crawford ``nudes.'' World-class, extravagantly paid
tease as earnest national sex educator. Hello?
</P>
<P>
   The first several minutes of the special, which humorlessly
observe how ``we're bombarded by sexual images,'' do nothing to
relieve doubt about the dreary silliness and shameless cynicism of
``Sex.'' Jerry Springer appears as an expert witness on sex and the
media. Among other things, we learn that ``virtual intercourse,''
which is somehow connected to the popularity of Internet sex, is
just a few years off.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my considerable surprise when the too-coyly titled
``Sex With Cindy Crawford'' finally settled down, relatively
speaking, and talked sense, occasionally with something approaching
sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   The segments are too short and, often, stylishly fragmented a la
MTV to capture the attention of young adults (which is also of
course the rationale for using Crawford as centerpiece). But the
on-camera teenagers speak honestly about the pressures and
anxieties surrounding sex, and have sensible advice for their
peers. The conversations about sex among straight and gay adults at
a Midwestern barbecue convened for the TV show are candid without
being clinical and, if predictable, often reassuringly humane.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate message is that love, candor, and fidelity are
terrific sexual aids. Relationships count, and so does the careful
practice of safe sex, we are gently admonished by a lot of nice
ordinary people and by Cindy, too.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes the unremarkable results of a nationwide
sex survey by the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
