</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH LEADER PLOWS AHEAD UNDER NEW LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Genentech Inc., a trailblazer in the American
biotechnology industry, is finally reaping the benefits of a
reorganization that began three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the South San Francisco-based biotechnology company
received approval to market Rituxan, which cures a certain type of
lymphoma and took seven years to develop. So far, it has grossed
$78 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is awaiting the green light for its vaunted breast
cancer drug, Herceptin. The Food and Drug Administration is
expected to approve the sale of the bioengineered formulation by
December.
</P>
<P>
   And Genentech has a string of other products in late-stage
clinical trials, including drugs that cure allergies and asthma,
and treat nerve damage caused by diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing turnaround story,'' said Meirav Chovav, an
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Genentech had been mired by controversial
marketing tactics and a questionable financial arrangement pursued
by then-chief executive G. Kirk Raab. Both situations detracted
from Genentech's ability to roll-out new drugs, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, however, Genentech has been humming along thanks to
a $2.1 billion investment from Swiss drug giant Roche Holding Ltd.
in 1990. The investment _ which included about $500 million in cash
earmarked for research to maintain the company's long-term product
pipeline _ resulted in Roche acquiring 66 percent of Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Genentech's revenues are robust, analysts said. Last
year, the company passed the $1 billion sales mark. And net income
was $129 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview at Genentech's sprawling, maze-like campus
at One DNA Way, the chief financial officer, Louis J. Lavigne said
that in the next millennium he expects his company's sales to grow
20 percent to 30 percent a year. Profits, he added, should rise to
at least 25 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most exciting times in the company, and the
reason for that is seeing the pipeline moving forward and
recognizing the potential that it has for meeting the various unmet
needs of patients,'' Lavigne said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Genentech scientist makes a discovery in the lab,
pre-clinical tests are conducted to determine whether the discovery
is suitable for humans. If it is, the product goes into the first
of three clinical trials. After the drug passes the last trial, the
company takes its results to the FDA, which must approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech spokeswoman Laura Leber said the time it takes new
drugs to go from the research stage to market is about 10 to 12
years on average for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of developing a new drug, she said, can run into the
hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech was founded in 1976 by venture capitalist Robert
Swanson and molecular biologist Herbert Boyer to commercialize
genetically engineered products.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer held a patent on techniques for splicing genes into
micro-organisms that could be used as ``microfactories'' to produce
large amounts of therapeutic substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Swanson took the entrepreneurial lessons he learned from
Silicon Valley and applied them to biology companies,'' said
Cynthia Robbins-Roth, a former Genentech researcher and now editor
of BioVenture View, a trade newsletter base in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That model (Genentech) has successfully created an industry
with 300-plus companies,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said Genentech's latest upward trend began
with the ouster of Raab in 1995 and the promotion of Dr. Arthur
Levinson to chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Raab, who had been appointed chief executive in 1990, was fired
by the Genentech board after trying to secure a $2 million personal
loan guarantee from Roche.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he was negotiating a personal loan, Raab was in
the midst of hashing out a new financial arrangement with the Swiss
drug maker _ one that gives Roche the option to buy the rest of
Genentech by July 1999 if Genentech's stock falls below $60 per
share at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Raab said he ``never took that loan. But I did something very
foolish. It was inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the discussed loan from Roche may have been the
last straw for Raab, who had previously spearheaded a controversial
marketing campaign for Genentech's human growth hormone drug,
Protropin, that combats dwarfism.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Genentech was accused of pushing the drug to
parents of children considered small for their age but still normal
size.
</P>
<P>
   The company was later sued for allegedly paying $1 million to a
Minneapolis doctor for pushing the use of Protropin.
</P>
<P>
   Raab defended his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Genentech did was wonderful in terms of the
marketing,'' he said. ``I've seen all sorts of children who've
gotten it, and instead of being 4-feet-10-inches, they are
five-feet-four.''
</P>
<P>
   Raab is now on the boards of four biotechnology companies:
Shaman Pharmaceuticals Inc., LXR Biotechnology Corp. and Connetics
Corp., all in California; and Oxford Glycosciences Ltd. in Oxford,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson, who had been head of research and development at
Genentech, immediately replaced Raab and is credited with creating
the company's current product pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1995 we've been in a period that I would call a
reinvigoration of the company,'' Lavigne said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chovav of Salomon Smith Barney put it more bluntly: ``Art
Levinson is probably the best thing that happened to Genentech,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish its production goals, Genentech has been forging
strategic alliances with other biotech and pharmaceutical outfits.
That way, development costs are shared and products get to market
faster because two companies are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech also hasn't cut back on research and development. In
1995, Genentech spent $363 million, or 40 percent of sales, on
research and development. The following two years, the company
spent $471 million, or about 50 percent of revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
