<P>
   WOMEN-RECRUIT _ On the recruiting trail with Georgia basketball
coach Andy Landers. It's becoming more like the men - national
camps, AAU travel squads, round-the-calendar seasons. And it could
be even more cutthroat because the pool of top-notch players is
shallower for the women. Increased recruiting illustrates the
growth of women's hoops. (Schultz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
(With list of recruiting expenses, revenues etc. of state schools
compared to national average.) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBARS
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-CHEAT _ In the Louisville volleyball program, Russian-born
coach Leonid Yelin paid for non-English-speaking prospect Marina
Sinichenko to learn the language so she could enroll in school. It
was a clear NCAA violation, and cheating is becoming increasingly
more common as pressure rises for women's programs to win rather
than just send out a team. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
(With list of men's, women's total violations year by year in the
'90s.) WITH PHOTOS ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-CHONE _ Jim Chones was an All-America basketball player at
Marquette and later played in the NBA as one of the first
underclassmen to leave college. He is surprised to be going through
the rigors of recruiting again _ through his daughter, a rising
senior All-American who is every bit the coveted prospect that her
dad was. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). (With list of
daughters of famous players.) WITH PHOTOS ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BORIS _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Boris Lelchitski is the model for
people who have suddenly found a good living off women's sports. He
came from Russia with no job or ability to speak English but with
an interest in coaching. He got a high school job, which combined
with trips home to Europe gave him an idea. He now serves as an
organizer of college teams playing in Europe and vice-versa, runs
camps, publishes a scouting service and operates as an agent for
players headed to Europe. (Schultz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BUTTS _ First-person woman's voice from high school star
Tasha Butts on recruiting. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8
p.m.
