<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDEBEHAVIOR-BOOK-TEX     09-21 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDEBEHAVIOR-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLY CLYDE'S BACK, STILL UNCOUTH AND HILARIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some books are written to inspire high-toned intellectual
debate. ``Rude Behavior'' is not one of these.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this third installment of the fictional adventures of
Billy Clyde Puckett and friends is Dan Jenkins setting out to
offend as many delicate sensibilities as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Behavior'' is less a structured novel than a series of
politically incorrect one-liners. If you're touchy on the subject
of race, sex, gender (as opposed to sex), politics, football,
economics, low-fat diets, proper grammar and/or religion, do not
read this book; your indignation glands will kick in should you
peruse even a single paragraph at random.
</P>
<P>
   But if you share Jenkins' obvious frustrations with our
homogenized modern society, on every other page or so you'll
probably bust a gut laughing. Tarrant County natives will be
especially entertained by homeboy Jenkins' descriptions of Fort
Worth as it was and as it has become, especially concerning bars
and restaurants. (Billy Clyde, Jenkins' fictional alter ego,
proposes a new north side restaurant called ``Kill 'Em and Eat
'Em.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Behavior'' does include an implausible story line for
those who insist on plot. Billy Clyde and his father-in-law,
wealthy Fort Worth oilman Big Ed Bookman, are in the running for
one of two new teams in an expanded National Football League. Their
competitors are based in London, Honolulu and Mexico City. Big Ed
wants to locate his franchise in the middle of barren West Texas
``between Amarillo and Lubbuck,'' then build a new condo community
around the stadium. Eventually, all four applicants are welcomed
into the NFL, and the West Texas Tornadoes embark on an unlikely
first season that ends with the fledgling franchise in the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   All the other ``Semi-Tough'' characters you've loved or loathed
are along for the ride: Barbara Jane, Billy Clyde's soulmate and
wife who's trying to make the transition from starlet to director;
Shake Tiller, wide receiver-turned-novelist; familiar Billy Clyde
drinking buddies Jim Tom Pinch and Tommy Earl Bruner; plus a new
member of Team Whacko, bartender Kelly Sue Woodley, a Barbara Jean
clone who ends up taming the sexually irrepressible Shake.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Jenkins resurrects T.J. Lambert, the flagrantly
flatulant TCU football coach who follows up a national collegiate
championship run with the Horned Frogs (now there's sensationalist
fiction!) by leading the Tornadoes into the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   All this matters less, however, than scenes Jenkins crafts
sentence by sentence, paragraph by paragraph into hilarious screeds
against social pomposity. Even the most experienced male sexist
pigs will learn new terms for ``cleavage.''
</P>
<P>
   The best scenes are set in the tiny West Texas town of Gully
Creek, where newly appointed Tornadoes general manager Billy Clyde
sets up shop in a trailer and oversees construction of a new
mega-football stadium. The citizens of Gully Creek (pop. 6,700)
already think they have big-time football, thank you very much. As
Jenkins notes, the Gully Creek Fightin' Roosters can even play
their games at night ``if everybody turned on the headlights in the
cars and trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Clyde takes his meals at a cafe called Them Two Women, and
Sunday worship is conducted at one of two churches _ the little
one, ``for Catholics,'' and the big one, ``for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Behavior'' is not going to be among the Pulitzer
finalists. But the open-minded among us will laugh a lot more while
reading it than we did plowing through ``Lonesome Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Rude Behavior'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Author: Dan Jenkins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Category: Politically incorrect fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Doubleday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $24.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is associate books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
