<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-21 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING HOME COMPUTER AUDIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When shopping for a computer system, the last features that
buyers typically consider, if they consider them at all, are the
audio speakers. Most multimedia computers are equipped with a
pathetic pair of plastic-encased speakers of a fidelity about equal
to a clock radio.
</P>
<P>
   These acoustic toys are adequate because many computers sold
today are for offices, where any sound above two decibels is likely
to be too loud and anything that smacks of entertainment is frowned
upon.
</P>
<P>
   But the audio capabilities of today's Macintosh or Pentium-class
computers can match and in some ways exceed good high-fidelity home
stereo equipment. And for many home users, game enthusiasts or
people who use multimedia technologies for sales or other
presentations, a set of true high-fidelity speakers is desirable if
not essential.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, a sizable market has grown up around high-end
speaker systems for computers, with some of the most respected
brands in audio, including Altec-Lansing and Bose, offering
high-fidelity speakers that can transform a standard desktop
computer into a first-rate stereo sound system.
</P>
<P>
   The best of these speaker systems are highly directional in
order to take full advantage of the state of the art in so-called
dynamic or interactive 3-D audio _ technologies that trick the ear
into hearing sounds all around the head though they are coming from
speakers in front of the listener. In contrast, static 3-D audio,
or surround sound, achieves the three-dimensional illusion by
assigning stereophonic sounds to front and rear speakers, a
technology that is often worth the expense and effort in a home
theater environment but impractical for multimedia computer setups.
</P>
<P>
   With dynamic and interactive 3-D audio, spatial and directional
illusions are achieved by manipulating audio signals based on
knowledge of how our heads and outer ears interact with and modify
sounds arriving from different directions. By selectively delaying,
echoing or intensifying certain sounds and creating acoustical
collisions in which sounds cancel each other out to varying degrees
when reaching the ear, these technologies can achieve remarkable
acoustical illusions.
</P>
<P>
   These highly complex manipulations of sound are crucial to
gaming and other virtual reality environments in which every move
of a joystick can result in a different three-dimensional movement
within an infinite sphere of virtual directions. Any latency in the
audio response to such movements will greatly diminish the
illusion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the challenges of reproducing sound faithfully
across the audible spectrum, 3-D technologies require that speakers
be highly directional because real acoustical ambience _ that is,
the reflections and absorption of sound in our environment _
competes with the 3-D illusion at the outer portion of the ear, or
pinna, and muddies the cues interpreted as spatial perception.
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary to eliminate as many environmental variables as
possible, and directional speakers go a long way toward preventing
reflections of sound bouncing off desktops, monitors and walls.
</P>
<P>
   The most advanced design to satisfy all these demands on
computer speakers was introduced by the Sonigistix Corp. of
Vancouver, British Columbia. Its $229 system, known as Monsoon, is
designed to maximize the acoustic illusions of 3-D audio by
employing two highly-directional, flat-panel speakers that are
placed on either side of the user's monitor, plus a subwoofer unit
placed under the desk.
</P>
<P>
   The subwoofer combines bass sounds below 200 hertz from both
stereo channels. This does not impair the spatial illusion because
deep bass sounds are the least directional of all audio cues, which
is why it is much harder to determine the direction of a thunder
clap, for example, than the direction of a siren. For this reason,
almost all subwoofers produce bass in mono, although most make the
cut at 90 to 150 hertz.
</P>
<P>
   While the Monsoon's bass response is respectable, it is the
system's 4-inch by 8-inch flat-panel satellite speakers that are
truly impressive. The flat design _ only a half-inch thick _
projects sounds to the rear as well as forward and prevents most
sound reflections from objects on either side of the speaker. They
are also angled 30 degrees upward to eliminate reflections from the
surface of the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with all computer speaker systems, the Monsoons
provide their own built-in amplifier. But it is impossible to know
how much power you are getting for your money, because Sonigistix
does not rate the output in RMS, or root mean squared, watts per
channel, which is the only honest measurement of power and the only
figure you can use in comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their actual output, in three days of throwing every
audio source imaginable at them, the speakers, consistently
produced sound that rivaled the performance of high-end component
system speakers.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of fidelity, they were impressive within a broad
dynamic range, handling with equal agility the explosive climaxes
of Hayden's Concerto for Trumpet and Orchestra, subtle nuances of a
Yo-Yo Ma performance of Bach's Suite No. 3 for Cello and the
gut-pounding rhythm section of the bassist Ernest Ranglin's reggae
instrumentals.
</P>
<P>
   But where the Monsoons truly differentiated themselves was in
their articulation of 3-D audio. A demo of ``Grim Fandango,'' a
soon-to-be-released game from LucasArts, immersed the player in a
vivid cacophony of urban sounds triggered by the position and
movement of the on-screen character relative to sound sources and
reflective surfaces like buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while the environmental illusions were remarkably
realistic, they were also limited to a relatively small listening
area. Audio fidelity was good anywhere within the room, but to
experience the full effect of 3-D audio, the listeners had to keep
their heads within the speakers' ``sweet spot'' _ the area where
the sounds meet in front of the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The owner's manual offers very precise instructions for speaker
placement, because it is so crucial to the Monsoon's performance.
Yet, every listening environment will be different, so it is
necessary to experiment with the placement of the speakers, trying
several arrangements until the maximum spatial illusion is created
where your head is generally held while working at the computer.
</P>
<P>
   It is best to keep in mind that ultimately this is a matter of
preference. There is really no such thing as spatial fidelity,
because 3-D audio, like many other audio technologies, is as much
psychology as physics.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Electronics recently announced that it was shipping
Monsoons as standard equipment with its top-of-the-line Millennia
desktop systems and as optional equipment with its other computer
lines. Technical specifications and more information on the
speakers are available on line at http://www.monsoonpower.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
