<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Doctors' Qualms About CPR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the doctors at a New York hospital said they
would not give mouth-to-mouth resuscitation to a cardiac arrest
patient, even in the face of low risk of infection and high
likelihood of success.
</P>
<P>
   The CPR survey anonymously questioned 227 residents and 96
faculty members at a 655-bed teaching hospital in Brooklyn. The
results were presented at a recent meeting of the Society for
Academic Emergency Medicine and appeared in Resuscitation, a
monthly journal.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 55 percent of respondents said they would not perform
cardiopulmonary resuscitation in a cardiac emergency without a
protective bag-valve mask, and results varied with the hypothetical
circumstances. Twenty percent to 30 percent were unwilling to
ventilate a newborn or a child, 50 percent to 60 percent an unknown
man and 70 percent to 80 percent a trauma victim or a man they
suspected was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our unwillingness to help other people reflects where we are
as a society,'' said Dr. Barry Brenner, the lead author of the
study and vice chairman of the department of emergency medicine at
Brooklyn Hospital Center. He declined to say whether the study was
conducted at his hospital. ``This dirty little secret bears poorly
on our profession,'' Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
