<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Manhattan from New Jersey, I took my
9-year-old son, Brendan, on the subway. I noticed he looked a bit
nervous walking through the station at Port Authority, as his
subway experience was very limited. As the doors shut on the car, I
could see the uneasiness on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The train started moving, and as we came to a bend in the
tracks, the conductor loudly announced something that was
unintelligible because of the defective speaker system. I noticed
Brendan listening intently, trying to understand the instructions.
The train was screeching around a sharp right turn, and he was
leaning over sideways in his seat, almost as though he were trying
to help steer the train with his body.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him if he was OK, he looked at me frantically and
yelled, ``Did he say `lean right'?''
</P>
<P>
   _ BONNIE TAGGART-QUERN
</P>
<P>
   File under You Know You're No Longer Newlyweds When:
</P>
<P>
   For at least a year, Debra Nussbaum Cohen had been after her
husband, Marc Cohen, to have his hearing checked. Though it had
never been a problem in their eight years together, she now needed
to repeat everything she said, sometimes twice, and it was, in her
words, ``driving me nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of increasingly annoyed nudging, her husband made
an appointment. Before the tests began, the audiologist asked why
he had come, and Cohen explained the reason. The doctor nodded
sagely. The tests were conducted and the diagnosis was that Cohen's
hearing was perfect. The audiologist's advice to Cohen was this:
``Start listening to your wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said that every day he saw at least one man propelled
into his office by a frustrated wife, only to be told that his
hearing was perfect. It seems that inattentive husbands of
long-suffering wives are part of the bread-and-butter of the
audiologist business.
</P>
<P>
   This story took place around 1965 at the Municipal Cafeteria on
Canal Street, between Centre and Lafayette streets.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those cafeterias (a few of them are still around)
where you passed through a turnstile, and in the process picked up
a ticket. As you removed the ticket from the machine, a loud
``bong'' sounded. The tickets were punched by the servers behind
the counters as you selected your meal. There were numeric
increments imprinted starting with 5 cents and progressing to a
dollar, $2, $3, $4, $5 and maybe $10.
</P>
<P>
   One day I was at the coffee and dessert counter, which was
served by an orange-haired, gum-chewing waitress. She was pouring
coffee, pushing Danish across the counter, punching tickets and
shouting, ``Next.'' The four-step progression had a musicality
about it. We crowded around this minor deity, who was elevated by a
behind-the-counter platform, raised our tickets and gave our
orders.
</P>
<P>
   A small man in our midst elbowed his way into visibility and
tried to get her attention. ``Lady, I want a cup of coffee,'' he
called out. Without a word, she continued what she was doing.
``Lady, I want a cup of coffee,'' he said again. She continued to
ignore him. Still louder, there was another ``Lady, I want a cup of
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point she leaned forward and and in a voice of great
condescension responded, ``Tell me, mister, what are you going to
do with three cups of coffee?'' The rest of us were almost as
delighted with the riposte as she was.
</P>
<P>
   _ RAYMOND P. BURGER
</P>
<P>
   Mary Donohue is, according to her daughter, Lorraine Forrier,
``sometimes forgetful.'' During a visit to Ms. Forrier in
Connecticut, the two shopped, lunched and saw the movie ``There's
Something About Mary.'' The mother then telephoned her older sister
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ``I'm having a wonderful time. We're shopping and having
lunch, and we saw a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Aunt: ``Oh, so what did you see?''
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ```Something About Mary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Aunt: ``Can't you remember anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Let's Get Our Priorities Straight Department:
</P>
<P>
   It was halftime at a Knicks game at the Garden earlier this year
and Barry Baum was standing in line at the ATM, in front of four
boys, each around 11 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to buy the Knicks shorts,'' said the one boy with an
ATM card. ``But my mother said I can only use the ATM machine for
emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends had no doubts. They nodded their heads in agreement
as one spoke out. ``But this is an emergency,'' he advised.
</P>
<P>
   Baum finished his transaction, walked a few steps away and
turned back to see the decision. The card carrier was eagerly
typing the code into the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Bellow and his wife were guests at a dinner party held by
our neighbors, Dorothy and Phil Zaro, at their vacation home in
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Some days later, back in Westchester County, Dorothy Zaro was
having her hair done. ``I had Saul Bellow for dinner this past
weekend,'' she said. There was silence for a moment. Then the
hairdresser replied: ``Do you know, I have never had that dish. Was
it good?''
</P>
<P>
   _ BOB GROSSBAUM
</P>
<P>
   The group at the Brooklyn Museum of Art was beginning its tour
of American paintings and Lillian Kanfer, a guide at the museum,
was about to start her lecture. Suddenly a woman in the group
