<HEADER>
A6454 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      09-21 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Finding a Fort: the Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists seeking the elusive remains of Fort Clatsop, the
winter quarters of the Lewis and Clark expedition in 1805-06, are
getting down to basics: They are looking for the camp's privies.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the National Park Service, the Museum of the
Rockies and the University of Washington are analyzing levels of
mercury in the soil at the site, near Astoria on the Oregon coast.
Mercury was a common Army treatment for syphilis; Meriwether Lewis
dispensed it in large doses to the men of the Corps of Discovery,
who contracted the disease from Indian women.
</P>
<P>
   High levels of the metal in specific soil samples would indicate
the site of a privy. ``With 33 men there for 106 days, we should be
able to find some high concentrations of mercury,'' said Cindy
Orlando, superintendent of the Fort Clatsop National Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Because Army regulations at the time stipulated that privies be
located certain distances from encampments, finding signs of one
would make it easier to locate the 50-foot-by-50-foot fort. Only a
few artifacts, including a lead ball and a brass bead, have been
uncovered at the site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead Levels in Ancient Ages &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lead, not mercury, is of interest to scientists from four
European universities who have studied levels of the metal in an
ancient peat bog in Switzerland's Jura Mountains. Their results,
reported in Science magazine, show that the increase in atmospheric
lead levels because of human activity is not just a modern
phenomenon; it began 6,000 years ago, probably when early Europeans
began to clear land for agriculture, raising lead-laden dust from
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists analyzed lead levels in the layers of peat over
14,000 years. (The surface of a peat bog is isolated from ground
water; anything that settles on it as it grows is assumed to come
from the atmosphere.)
</P>
<P>
   The first 8,000 years provided a base level of natural lead
emissions with which to compare rising levels because of human
activity. In addition to the increases that began 6,000 years ago,
the researchers recorded fluctuations that coincided with events
like the flourishing of the Roman Empire and the beginnings of the
Industrial Revolution. They also found that lead levels appear to
be decreasing now, probably because of the removal of lead from
gasoline and other steps to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Raising Dust on Mars Moon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On the Martian moon Phobos, dust has been kicked up for
millions, not thousands, of years. In fact, researchers with NASA's
Mars Global Surveyor project say that the surface of the tiny moon
is covered in a hip-deep layer of the stuff, formed by long-term
bombardment by meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists have studied new close-up photos and temperature
measurements that show the surface rapidly loses heat as it goes
from day to night. Because Phobos does not have an atmosphere, such
a rapid heat loss can be explained if the surface is covered with a
three-foot layer of dust.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorites, the scientists suggest, have acted like a kind
of celestial Cuisinart, grinding the crust of the potato-shaped
moon into a fine powder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Getting the Foe's Picture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Rockefeller University and the National
Institute of Child Health and Human Development have determined the
three-dimensional structure of an enzyme that makes some bacteria
resistant to a certain family of antibiotics. The enzyme catalyzes
the transfer of a molecular fragment, called an acetyl group, from
a donor molecule to the antibiotic, rendering it ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Using X-ray crystallography, the researchers found that the
enzyme resembles a cupped hand wrapped around a cylinder. The
antibiotic binds to the cavity created by the ``hand,'' the donor
molecule binds elsewhere on the enzyme, and the transfer is made.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists can now try to design a drug that would, like the
winner in a game of musical chairs, bind in the cavity in place of
the antibiotic, thwarting the enzyme.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
