</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-POTASSIUM-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTASSIUM-RICH DIET LOWERS STROKE RISK IN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A study that tracked nearly 44,000 men over eight years has
found that those whose diets included large amounts of potassium
had one-third fewer strokes than those whose diets did not. The
benefits appeared to be greatest for men with high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published Tuesday in Circulation, the journal of the
American Heart Association, also found that the rate of strokes was
lower for men who consumed higher levels of magnesium and cereal
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium-rich foods include bananas, tomatoes, spinach and
other fruits and vegetables, explained the study's leader, Dr.
Alberto Ascherio of the Harvard School of Public Health, who
conceded that its recommendations may sound familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways this could seem just the old story _ eat your
fruits and vegetables,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``But
stroke is such a horrible disease that we hope these figures
provide extra incentive for people to change their diets,
especially those with high blood pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that potassium can reduce blood
pressure, and some small studies had suggested that increasing its
consumption could help prevent strokes. The current study tapped
into research begun in 1986, the Health Professionals Follow-up
Study, to see if the preventive effect could be demonstrated in a
large group over time.
</P>
<P>
   The major finding was that men in the top 20 percent for
potassium consumption _ eating an average of nine potassium-rich
servings a day _ had 38 percent fewer strokes than those in the
bottom 20 percent, who consumed less than four.
</P>
<P>
   Men without high blood pressure who had high intakes of
magnesium _ a mineral found in almost all foods, but in greater
amounts in fruits, vegetables and fish _ had a 30 percent lower
risk of stroke. Those who consumed high amounts of cereal fiber had
a 40 percent lower risk than those who did not.
</P>
<P>
   The differences were even more striking for men with high blood
pressure, a risk factor for stroke. Those taking potassium
supplements of one gram a day had a 60 percent lower risk of stroke
than men with high blood pressure who were not taking the
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ascherio cautioned against the general use of potassium
supplements, which are often prescribed to patients whose potassium
levels are lowered by hypertension medication. Too much potassium
can be harmful, especially to those with kidney problems. ``Two
tomatoes and one serving of spinach provide about 1 gram of
potassium,'' he said. ``You can't overdo with fruit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
