u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILWAR-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      09-21 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CIVIL WAR' OVERCOMES OBSTACLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``The Civil War'' is composer Frank Wildhorn's big
gamble _ and, to a large extent, it pays off in the world premiere
unveiled at the Alley Theater in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring popular successes with ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' and ``The
Scarlet Pimpernel'' (despite scant critical approval), Wildhorn
turns to a subject that is inherently more substantial and
prestigious. ``The Civil War'' would seem ready-made, an
exploration of that vast scar at the heart of America's history.
Not a traditional musical but a theatrical concert, it consists of
songs (and a few spoken interludes) based on letters, diaries and
other documents, assembled to express the emotional landscape of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   The risks are built-in, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn likes to keep a contemporary pop dimension in his
theater scores, but when that style asserts itself here, it
inevitably feels at odds with the somber passion of his subject.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Wildhorn, lyricist Jack Murphy and
co-author/production supervisor Gregory Boyd have set themselves a
difficult challenge in their chosen format. As a bookless show,
essentially a revue of individual vignettes, ``The Civil War,''
which runs through Oct. 11, cannot summon the cumulative impact of
a traditional musical. Songs that come out of nowhere, however
strong their emotion, do not wield the same dramatic clout as those
that grow out of sustained character and narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Those challenges notwithstanding, ``The Civil War'' offers so
much that is first-rate and undeniably heart-tugging that it
warrants a salute.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important in a show that is virtually all sung, the
voices are all terrific. This company could hold its own against
just about any current Broadway cast _ and Wildhorn provides a lot
of strong material that showcases them effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The show gets rolling with ``By the Sword/Sons of Dixie,'' a
lusty double chorale for Union and Confederate soldiers heeding the
call to arms in high spirit _ displaying the strong choral
arranging that is one of the show's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Bogart shines in ``Tell My Father,'' a deftly understated
soliloquy of a dying soldier. Michael Lanning is forceful
throughout as a Union captain, especially in his homesick lament
``Northbound Train.'' Gene Miller, as a Confederate captain, sings
an elegy to the pre-war South in ``Virginia,'' its sturdy lyrics
and appealing melody enhanced by Miller's supple, powerful
rendition.
</P>
<P>
   As abolitionist Frederick Douglass, Keith Byron Kirk leads the
yearning ``Freedom's Child'' _ more potent in its quiet opening
than in the later revved-up passages.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Bell does a marvelous job with the aching ``Father, How
Long?'', Wildhorn's melody taking full advantage of Bell's
thundering low notes. Bell and Cheryl Freeman create one of the
show's emotional highlights in ``If Prayin' Were Horses,'' the song
of husband and wife slaves being parted on the auction block.
Lawrence Clayton proves a vocal powerhouse leading a dynamic
ensemble performance of the gospel-tinged ``River Jordan,'' the
first act finale.
</P>
<P>
   David Lutkin brings a plaintive simplicity to the folklike
``I'll Never Pass This Way Again,'' a Confederate soldier's musing
on the evanescence of life. Beth Leavel's dignity and controlled
pathos are ideal for ``Five Boys,'' in which a mother contemplates
the news that all five of her sons have died in battle.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sarah,'' the score's most traditional romantic ballad,
Gilles Chiasson gives a tender rendition of a lovesick soldier's
letter to his wife. Irene Molloy answers in superb voice with the
moving ``The Honor of Your Name,'' expressing her resolve to carry
on after learning of her husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Eder's beautiful voice enhances the distinction of ``I
Never Knew His Name,'' perhaps the score's most original melody,
the song of a nurse caring for a dying soldier. Eder doubles as a
sort of angel of the battlefield, leading fallen soldiers away with
a gentle lullabylike theme. Another highlight in this vein is
``Candle in the Window,'' beautifully sung by Capathia Jenkins as a
citizen reflecting on the burdens of President Lincoln; a slightly
more oblique, less on-the-nose number, this one proves a welcome
respite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War'' allows Wildhorn to show more range than he has
previously. Much of the music is appealing, especially the ballads
in a kind of timeless, folklike vein. It is when Wildhorn shifts
gears to an up-tempo pop vein that the songs fall short of the
gravity and grandeur the theme demands.
</P>
<P>
   Several ensembles for groups of soldiers or slaves (``Judgment
Day'', ``How Many Devils'') start promisingly with brooding, a
capella passages, but then rev up to a pop beat that seems
inappropriate. There also are a few misjudged numbers, like
``Greenback,'' in which snaky Jesse Lenat appears as a scalawag,
camp-following pimp flanked by his two harlots. Sure, the show
needs comic relief, but the number's tone is wrong, the comic point
not sharp enough for the needed payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's vernacular lyrics usually are neat, craftsmanly and to
the point. Fortunately, there are no outright clinkers or bad taste
howlers. But there are some passages in which the words and music
are merely ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   An (almost) all-sung show on such an important theme demands
eloquence and inspiration throughout. As the show stands, about
half of it comes close to that level. The challenge is to bring the
rest up to snuff.
</P>
<P>
   The collaborators have attempted to group the songs in
sequences, sometimes creating an interaction between numbers, as
when the doomed soldier's ``Sarah'' is answered by his widow's solo
about losing him. The team should build on this element. The more
they can suggest connections between the songs and the more they
can use recurring figures in the action, then the more their show
gains in dramatic impact.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Civil War'' is essentially a song cycle or theater
concert, the Alley has mounted it as a full production. The
direction supplies about the right amount of movement to keep the
show from growing static. The musical staging is by George Faison,
the staging by Nick Corley and the production is supervised by
Boyd, so it's a bit difficult to determine just who did what.
</P>
<P>
   The groupings and tableaux are often effective, especially as
enhanced by Wendall K. Harrington's projections of period
photographs: a collage of portraits of soldiers; the text of
Lincoln's letter to Mrs. Bixby (the mother who lost all five sons);
a misty dawn on the battlefield at Gettysburg. Douglas Schmidt's
setting of stately columns and platforms creates a handsome and
functional playing space.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wendland's costumes resourcefully incorporate suggestions
of the period without actually re-creating it. And Howell Binkley's
lighting is a powerful cue for the shifting moods of the
production.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Richardson's sound design makes certain everyone in the
house hears every note. But the singing is too heavily and
unnecessarily amplified _ so that the loud passages bludgeon the
listener. Especially in the relatively small (by musical theater
standards) Alley venue, these strong voices could do the job
without mechanical assistance, and it would be a pleasure to hear
them pure.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it stands in this first public viewing, ``The Civil
War'' is an ambitious piece whose strengths outweigh its
weaknesses. If theaters are going to create bookless shows,
something along these lines is far more interesting than a ``Smokey
Joe's Cafe'' or ``Forever Plaid'' assemblage of oldies. Given the
loose format, you can bet Wildhorn and company will make plenty of
improvements and substitutions before ``The Civil War'' makes its
Broadway bow next spring. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
