<HEADLINE>
HOLLY GETS SWEETER BY THE DAY AFTER SUGAR MAKER BUYS FOOD SERVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Imperial Holly announced Monday its second acquisition
within a week, agreeing to pay $120 million for a food service
company that will further diversify the sugar company into
high-margin business lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Sugar Land, Texas, company will pay $80 million in cash and
$40 million in common stock, plus assume $33.9 million in debt for
Diamond Crystal Specialty Foods, based in Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company supplies nutritional mixes, drink mixes, sauces,
seasonings and desserts to businesses in the food service industry,
which includes hotels, restaurants, hospitals and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Should Imperial Holly decide to pay all cash, the purchase price
will be reduced to $115 million.
</P>
<P>
   President and Chief Executive James C. Kempner described the
acquisition as another step in Imperial Holly's strategy of
increasing its participation in the higher-margin, higher-growth
sectors of the sweetener market.
</P>
<P>
   The company is using its marketing and distribution prowess to
move into food segments allied with sweeteners, Kempner said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Imperial Holly said it was acquiring Wholesome
Foods, a supplier of organic sugar based in Daytona Beach, Fla.
Wholesome's organic sweeteners are produced without herbicides or
insecticides and are sold through health food chains.
</P>
<P>
   The latest acquisition target, Diamond Crystal Specialty Foods,
produced sales of $125.9 million and earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation and amortization of $13.5 million, during the
fiscal year that ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Once the deal is completed, Diamond Crystal's operations will be
combined with those of Imperial Holly's Dixie Crystals food service
division, based in Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are leaders in their segments of the food service
industry with complementary product lines, said Kempner. There are
substantial opportunities for revenue enhancement and cost
reduction in the combination, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wilmington, Diamond Crystal has manufacturing
facilities in Moore, Okla.; Indianapolis; Boudurant, Iowa; and
Mitchellville, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction remains subject to Imperial Holly getting
approval from regulators and certain waivers from its senior debt
holders.
</P>
<P>
   If Imperial Holly decides to pay with the cash-stock
combination, Diamond Crystal has the option of canceling if the
stock price averages below $8 per share during 10 days just prior
to the closing. The stock closed last Tuesday at 7 7/8, up 1/4 in
trading on the American Stock Exchange. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
