<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-21 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CUT FOLLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first test of how far congressional Republicans
can take the legislative edge they gain from President Clinton's
diminished political stature will come this week when the House
takes up a GOP-sponsored tax cut that the president threatens to
veto.
</P>
<P>
   And the president may actually win this tussle.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome would be due to public understanding of the
dangerous and irresponsible nature of the Republican desire to eat
into the projected federal budget surplus for an unneeded
$80-billion tax cut. It does not send a signal that the president's
sagging fortunes can be rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   The president is right to oppose the tax cut on the grounds that
the surplus ought to be used to shore up the Social Security
system, which could run out of money after the massive baby boomer
generation has retired in about 30 years. And Congress would be
right to reject the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of those surveyed by a recent Wall Street
Journal-NBC News poll said any budget surplus should be used to
protect Social Security's long-term solvency or reduce the
accumulated national debt, while just one-fourth say the surplus
should be used to lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee, in approving the tax-cut
package, argued that the tax breaks would erode only about 10
percent of the anticipated surplus and leave the rest for Social
Security. The president and the Democrats counter that Social
Security will need all the reserves it can get.
</P>
<P>
   They also see it as a fairness issue, because 98 percent of the
projected surplus is generated by Social Security payroll taxes in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is that the Republicans want to fritter away
part of a surplus that is not an automatic given; it could vanish
in some subsequent recessionary period. And they want to squander
it on a tax cut that is not essential either to bolster the economy
or correct a major tax inequity.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates there will be a
$1.6-trillion surplus over the next 10 years, based upon an
optimistic economic assumption that the country will continue its
current prosperous growth. But even the CBO warns that if the shaky
world economy produces an American slowdown that becomes a
recession like that of 1990, the total projected surpluses would be
quickly wiped out and big deficits reappear.
</P>
<P>
   Although the CBO is obviously doing a lot of guessing here, its
next adjusted economic assessment is not due until January, after
the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, contends that the
tax cut is needed to correct an imbalance between income taxes
levied against single individuals and married couples, help
self-employed people pay for health insurance, slash the estate tax
and exclude up to $400 in dividend and interest income per tax
return.
</P>
<P>
   Archer also calls it a middle-class tax cut because it would
increase the standard deduction for married couples of all incomes
and ease some taxes on senior citizens, small business owners,
farmers and college students.
</P>
<P>
   But it really would help upper-income individuals _ a basic GOP
constituency but the very folks who need it the least. They are
more apt to have investment income that will now be taxed at a
lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cut in estate taxes would immediately raise the
amount that passes to heirs tax-free from the present $600,000 to
$1 million. That will affect only the richest 2 percent of the
population and represent one-fourth of the entire cost of the tax
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House is likely to approve this abominable giveaway because
it is difficult for Democrats as well as Republicans to vote
against tax cuts. But President Clinton reiterated his promise to
veto the bill twice last week, stiffening the spines of Democrats
worried that Clinton might cut some deal and leave them holding the
bag if they stand firm against it. And Democrats are confident they
have enough votes to prevent a later override.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Senate is not going to rush to judgment on this
issue. This will not become law any time soon. Many Senate
Republicans as well as Democrats are nervous about dipping into a
surplus that could be essential to the future of Social Security
and may prove to be ephemeral anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans feel the president is so weakened they
have a good opportunity to push their agenda this fall. But the
public preoccupation with the president's sexual encounters
interferes with voters' attention to serious subjects like taxes
just as it drowns out his own efforts to change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, actually. The GOP is trying to pull a fast one
here, and ought to be held accountable by all future retirees who
will be dependent upon Social Security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
