<HEADER>
A6501 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     09-21 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR REPORT LEAVES EDITORS WALKING ON A WIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm involved in a lengthy discussion with a frequent critic
about how much and what kind of information needs to be in the
newspaper from the Office of Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The reader argues _ correctly, I believe _ that this has the
potential to become a serious constitutional crisis and that
details, no matter how distasteful, are important.
</P>
<P>
   Balance that against discussions last week with readers angered
by the level of detail even in the highly edited version of the
Starr report that the Fort Worth Star-Telegram printed in its news
columns the day after its release.
</P>
<P>
   Some were supporters of President Clinton who didn't think the
report should have been printed. Others were deeply disturbed about
the detail and language in even that sanitized version.
</P>
<P>
   In this child-centric society, it's easy to use children as an
excuse to do or not do things, and you should be a little skeptical
when people toss around that ``good of the children'' phrase too
easily.
</P>
<P>
   But we at the Star-Telegram do take seriously the concept that
we are a newspaper for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we falter, of course, and push the limits of good
taste because we weren't thinking or didn't see the double entendre
or, in some cases, because we were being a little naughty and
trying to see how far we would push it.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are pretty good about calling our hand when that
happens, and we do listen. We don't always agree, but we pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Sex is an especially touchy issue. The local record for
sensitivity is held by a reader who thought a pile of potatoes
depicted in a grocery ad was pornographic. But there also are
periodic calls about department store ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been reading this paper for 40 years,'' one caller said last
week. ``The last few years, every time I turn to Page 2 you have a
woman there in her underwear. And you're trying to sit there and
read the paper with a half-page of a woman in her underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know you need to sell lots of ads, but put that on Page
Something Else,'' the reader said, ``because every time I turn to
Page 2, my wife says, `What are you looking at?' I say, `Well, I'm
looking at the paper. I can't help it if she's there in her
underwear.' We don't appreciate you putting them women in their
underwear (there).''
</P>
<P>
   Such complaints are relatively common, so you can imagine the
consternation that rippled through the editing ranks when Ken
Starr's report to the House of Representatives became available.
</P>
<P>
   People had been meeting throughout the day about what to do.
There were several factors involved. One was whether we could find
the press time to print the special section that would be required
for the Saturday or Sunday newspaper. Another was the cost. The
third _ and the most important _ was the issue of taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most agonizing decision I've had to make,'' said
Kathy Vetter, one of the managing editors. ``Do we violate all of
our decency standards and publish the entire report, graphic detail
and all? Or do we edit the worst parts, an action that at best
could be condescending to our readers and at worst could leave them
without all the necessary information?''
</P>
<P>
   ``As journalists,'' said Vice President and Executive Editor Jim
Witt, ``our first inclination was to run the entire report and put
it inside every edition of the Star-Telegram as a public service _
the theory being that it was a historical document alleging crimes
by the president, and the people deserved to read the evidence for
themselves exactly as it was written.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the report came in, though, the language and descriptions
in it gave us pause. It wasn't language that we thought our readers
would be comfortable with in their newspaper, especially with the
knowledge that children might be exposed to it,'' said Witt, who
interrupted his vacation to consult with the newsroom by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once ... it became apparent that we were in a no-win
situation,'' Vetter said, ``I showed excerpts to our publisher, Wes
Turner, who told the newsroom to do what we needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   We've come to expect that kind of decision from Turner. He's the
boss, but in situations like this, the person on the ground gets to
make the call.
</P>
<P>
   Printing it all would have been the easy decision. It's
important. It'll be in the history books. We could always defend it
by saying we were simply doing our duty as we understood it in
light of the constitutional privilege we enjoy as a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But our editors did not take the easy route. They decided to
edit an already edited transcript, risking criticism from those who
would cry censorship. They even inserted editor's notes telling you
what they had taken out. And they decided to print the full text of
the report for free distribution at each of our main offices (and
by mail for a handling charge).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to make the descriptions a little less offensive
while leaving as much information as possible for the reader. We
knew that our readers could access the full text if they wished,''
Vetter said.
</P>
<P>
   And something unusual happened: In addition to creating traffic
jams in Arlington and at our printing plant, a number of people
called to thank us for the way we handled the report. We don't
really ever expect to hear from people we have pleased _ that's not
human nature _ so those thank-yous were especially nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you people done an excellent job on that,'' said one
Arlington reader. ``You made it just difficult enough but not very
difficult at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first press run was gone by the end of Monday, the
day we made the full report available, and we printed more. By
Wednesday evening, we had handed out 17,650, with another 225 going
in the mail. Requests are still arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Vetter speaks for all of us, and certainly for the
journalists who have to make these kinds of decisions, when she
says:
</P>
<P>
   ``... Boy, do I hope I never have to read anything like that
again, let alone decide what to include in 240,000 copies of the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is ombudsman for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
His e-mail address is harral &LR; star-telegram.com. You may telephone
him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
