<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWEGIAN-SEA-2TAKES-     09-21 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWEGIAN-SEA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON CRUISE INDUSTRY GETS BOOST WITH NORWEGIAN SEA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The entertainment is more lavish. The pool deck more
spacious. The public rooms more inviting. The dining options more
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   And the air conditioning works like a charm.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Houston's fledgling cruise industry should receive
a major boost in December when Norwegian Cruise Line replaces its
much-maligned Norwegian Star with a newer, bigger and _ by most
standards _ better ship on weekly Texaribbean sailings.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,534-passenger Norwegian Sea, currently based in San Juan,
will arrive at the Port of Houston for an inaugural Dec. 13
departure to Cancun and Cozumel on Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula and
Roatan in Honduras' Bay Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The 42,000-ton ship will depart from the Barbours Cut terminal
each Sunday afternoon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   While the 10-year-old Sea lacks the classic styling and large
staterooms of the 800-passenger Star _ designed in 1973 as a plush
long-distance ocean liner _ its onboard amenities and practicality
are clearly superior.
</P>
<P>
   So is its image.
</P>
<P>
   By filling 90 percent of its beds during a 16-month presence as
Houston's first home-based cruise ship, the Norwegian Star has
provided NCL sufficient encouragement to almost double its weekly
capacity here.
</P>
<P>
   But the Star endured national ridicule last fall and winter when
faulty air conditioning _ attributed to problems with a generator _
resulted in passengers sleeping on open decks during sold-out
Thanksgiving and Christmas sailings. Another fully booked departure
during the New Year's holiday was canceled while the problems were
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the rest of 1998, the Star has sailed trouble-free.
It averaged 99 percent of passenger capacity in the just-completed
third quarter, according to an NCL spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 4, the Star will commence its final Texaribbean
itinerary. The ship will return Nov. 1 to start a 16-day
repositioning cruise through the Panama Canal to San Diego. Then it
will proceed to Australia for year-round itineraries in the South
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   While its replacement here may not represent a ship of the
future _ if, that is, the future is measured by vessels of Goliath
proportions offered by Carnival, Princess and Royal Caribbean, the
Big Three of worldwide cruise lines _ the Norwegian Sea seems
ideally suited to Houston's current needs and for continued growth
within the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain bullish on Houston as a cruise port,'' says NCL
Executive Vice President Art Sbarsky. ``The major factor in the
city's favor is convenience. It's a good drive-in and fly-in
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see three main audiences for the Norwegian Sea: those who
have enjoyed the Texaribbean itinerary and want to return on
another, bigger ship; those who like the Sea and want to sail on it
again with a new itinerary; and potential first-time cruisers.''
</P>
<P>
   One overriding factor in comparing the Sea and Star is that
Houston's newest ship, known as the Seaward until last year, was
built by NCL specifically for Caribbean cruising. The Star was
initially designed for luxury-oriented around-the-world
intineraries, but through ownership changes _ from Royal Viking to
Royal to NCL _ had evolved, for practical effect, into a vessel
with a mishmash of clashing personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ship was built for a different market,'' says Sbarsky,
``and whether you like it or not depends on what you want from a
cruise. It has some wonderful features, but we would not design a
ship like the Norwegian Star to fit the purposes of NCL. With the
Sea, structure fits the strategy; with the Star, at times strategy
had to be adjusted to fit the structure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star arrived here, too, with a history of mechanical
problems; the Sea carries a solid reputation for reliability. New
air conditioning has been installed this year in all its staterooms
and public rooms. And the Sea's chief engineer Jarle Fjordholm
says, ``We have so many backup systems on this ship that it would
take an extraordinary situation to shut anything down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ship reviewers' biggest complaints about the Sea have centered
on its small staterooms and on extensive use of painted metal
instead of teak, especially on a Promenade Deck that wraps around
the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers also will notice higher brochure tariffs than for the
Star. Listed double-occupancy prices (excluding port taxes) for a
one-week sailing in January start at $1,249 per person for an
inside stateroom; $1,549 for an outside cabin; and $2,299 for a
suite. Those prices increase by $200 each for sailings beginning
Feb. 7. Holiday fares are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Don't settle for brochure fares, though. Most travel agents can
secure bookings at considerably lower prices. Be sure to ask about
bargains during the Sea's inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other comparisons formed by sailings aboard both ships:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAVORING THE SUN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sea's vast open deck areas represent a huge improvement and
should prove significant to the enjoyment of an itinerary that
includes three full days on the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's one small pool is hidden behind the main showroom; by
contrast, the Sea features two pools _ one 42 feet by 14 feet _
separated by twin hot tubs and surrounded by hundreds of lounge
chairs. Additional seating on a sun deck overlooks the pools.
</P>
<P>
   Buffets are set up in the Big Apple Cafe _ a name NCL officials
would be wise to change for Texaribbean sailings _ at the rear of
the pool deck; though ample indoor seating exists, many passengers
carry trays outside and dine al fresco. Tables are abundant, and
glass sidings offer protection from wind.
</P>
<P>
   Poolside activities are plentiful. Other open-air areas are
reserved for a basketball half-court, golf driving net and table
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ENTERTAINMENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also an obvious upgrade are entertainment venues that will allow
presentation of full-scale revues featuring up to 15 singers and
dancers while maintaining popular Texaribbean acts such as singer
Jane Powell and comedian/magician Doug Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's lone showroom accommodates only 474; because most
seats are at stage-level, passengers' views frequently are blocked.
The stage is too small for large productions.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the Sea, one lounge accommodates 770 in theater-style
seating; on each sailing it hosts NCL's signature
mini-Broadway-style production of ``Grease,'' two other extravagant
song-and-dance revues and individual acts.
</P>
<P>
   Another lounge, situated at the opposite end of the same deck,
holds 520 and is used primarily for pre- and post-dinner dancing
and late-night comedy and song.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only real difference in formal dining procedures is that the
larger Sea features two main restaurants, the Star only one. The
menus and service routine are identical, and NCL plans to continue
its special Texaribbean dinners _ and 70 varieties of hot sauces _
aboard the newer ship.
</P>
<P>
   What gives the Norwegian Sea a decided edge is its additional
dining options.
</P>
<P>
   In the aforementioned Big Apple Cafe, self-service buffets are
available at breakfast, lunch and dinner. Swimsuit attire is
allowed. On our cruise, a majority of passengers chose this
alternative for midday meals that include an all-you-can-eat
selection of hot entrees, vegetables, salads, cold cuts, breads and
desserts. Especially popular, too, on days in port are
late-afternoon megasnacks: pizzas, quiche, baked potatoes and chili
on a rotating basis. Light selections are available into the wee
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive is Le Bistro, an alternative restaurant
(with the only charge a recommended gratuity) open for dinner on
the highest deck. Except for daily specials, the menu remains
standard throughout a cruise, but it's tempting to dine here
several times given the stellar Continental cuisine, flexible
dining hours and unrushed service, and an ambience of casual
elegance.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Star also features Le Bistro. But on that ship, it
was carved from a corner of the main restaurant as an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Late-night buffets are scheduled on the pool deck or in dining
rooms. Unlike the Star, the Sea does not currently have a pizzeria;
that feature may be added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OTHER PUBLIC ROOMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sea's medium-range size (by current ship standards) is put
to good use.
</P>
<P>
   Among enhancements:
</P>
<P>
   Two small but well-designed rooms _ Gatsby's Wine Bar and
Oscar's Pub _ are reserved for evening piano music. Gatsby's,
situated atop the ship near Le Bistro, also offers sweeping views.
Though touted as the one public room for cigar smokers, ventilation
is good enough that most nonsmokers won't be bothered. Those who
are can relax in an adjacent Observatory Lounge and still hear the
music.
</P>
<P>
   Boomers, a 132-seat disco, draws a lively crowd well into the
early morning. This, too, is a marked improvement; the Star's
sports bar doubled as a disco.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea's casino is bigger (178 slot machines and 11 tables,
seven for blackjack), brighter and more centrally located than its
counterpart on the Star.
</P>
<P>
   The health club, though smaller than on some newer ships, is air
conditioned _ unlike on the Star, where passengers worked up a
sweat even before working out.
</P>
<P>
   A shopping area is better arranged, more conveniently located
and more than twice the size of the boutiques aboard the Star.
</P>
<P>
   Chairs and tables placed beside windows near elevators on
lodging decks are a nice touch, especially for passengers who
relish reading or needlework.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Star's sports bar may be disappointed; no area
aboard the Sea is dedicated specifically to sports memorabilia and
telecasts. But live transmission of events is so limited on the
Star that this loss will barely be noticed. And NCL's new
partnership with Sports Illustrated likely will lead to additional
sports theme cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern _ especially given the three sea days _ is the
absence of a full library aboard the Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Ongoing refurbishments include new carpeting and upholstery and
new, brighter furnishings in some rooms.
</P>
<P>
   As on the Star, NCL's youth programs will operate year-round
(with an increased counseling staff in the peak summer family
season). Separate programs are conducted for teens and preteens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STATEROOMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the tradeoff for all those nice common areas.
</P>
<P>
   During the era of the Norwegian Star's construction _ before
Caribbean cruising gained popularity _ staterooms were spacious and
featured enough storage room for sailings of several months. Today,
the trend again is toward large cabins _ and with balconies _ as
the industry competes with land resorts for business.
</P>
<P>
   But the Norwegian Sea was built during an intermediate period
when the main objective was to get passengers out of their cabins _
by giving those staterooms a compact and uniform design _ and into
casinos, bars and shops where they might be inclined to invest some
money.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea's accommodations include only seven suites. Almost all
other staterooms fall into two categories with dimensions of 122
and 140 square feet _ considerably smaller than many cabins aboard
the Star. About 200 staterooms have no ocean views; several others
have restricted views. Bathrooms are minuscule, with showers (and
no tubs) in all but 25 rooms or suites. Closet space is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms are well-appointed, and twin beds can be arranged as a
double. (A bit of trivia: Duvets are used for covering on the Sea;
the Star uses standard bedsheets). Beds become makeshift sofas
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Four staterooms are designed for passengers in wheelchairs or
with hearing impairments. (Accessibility throughout the ship is
good; elevators serve all decks and room entrances are easily
negotiated.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ITINERARY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only one change will occur in the established Texaribbean
routine, with Cancun substituted for Calica in Mexico. That's an
improvement for two reasons: (1) Cancun offers more enticements;
(2) docking conditions in Calica were so erratic that the Star
missed too many calls. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1659EDT &QL; 
