<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUDAN-ADVISORY-COX     09-21 0228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN NEWS EDITORS, FOREIGN EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin, assistant international editor at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, and photographer Rich Addicks traveled to the
Sudan recently for a special report detailing the catastrophe and
heartbreak of the ongoing famine. The package asks whether America
will confront the tragedy, or turn away.
</P>
<P>
   Stories will move on the international wire on Tuesday; photos
are available now.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The words and pictures in this report are graphic in
nature and may be objectionable to some readers.
</P>
<P>
   For questions, please call CoxNet at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-STARVATION _ More than 700,000 people in Sudan are being
threatened by death from starvation. While the United Nations is
coordinating the largest airlift in the history of Africa, the
suffering continues. Mothers continue to bury their babies and
people stagger for days looking for food. (Melvin, Cox News
Service) WITH PHOTOS, GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-INTRO _ Writer Don Melvin offers his views on the
difficulty of reporting the human hardship being waged as a result
of the famine in Sudan. (Melvin, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-LIST _ A partial list of U.S. agencies accepting donations
to fight the famine in Sudan. (Melvin, Cox News Service)
</P>
