<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARIBBEAN-HURRICANE-0     09-21 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-HURRICANE-0922-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGES POUNDS PUERTO RICO; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, HAITI BRACE FOR
DISASTER
 &HT;    EDs: Story may need to be updated after 6 p.m. EDT.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As if doing battle, Hurricane Georges charged across
Puerto Rico late Monday, packing winds of 110 mph that churned
20-foot seas, knocked out electrical service, and forced families
to huddle in basements and walk-in closets.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people sought shelter in schools and public
buildings in both Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands, and the
U.S. territories declared states of emergency while activating
National Guard troops.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello banned liquor sales, ordered a
price freeze on items such as water, candles and matches, and had
officials prepare more than 300 shelters on this island of 3.8
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really nervous because we remember the damage done
by Hugo,'' said Mary McClintock, a resident of San Juan, Puerto
Rico who planned to take refuge in her cement home's walk-in
closet. ``People have stocked up on food and water, and I'd say
they are scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Hugo killed more than two dozen people when it ripped
through the Caribbean in 1989, and caused billions of dollars in
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Georges began pounding a string of Caribbean islands overnight
on Sunday, starting with the French territory of Guadeloupe, where
the ferocious storm uprooted trees as if they were houseplants.
</P>
<P>
   Georges also ripped off roofs, tore down phone lines, and
knocked out electrical service on the islands of Antigua, St.
Croix, and St. Kitts and Nevis, but no injuries or deaths were
immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   Some cruise ships veered south to get out of Georges' path,
while others changed their schedules and headed to storm-free
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In general, residents on many islands struck by Georges breathed
a big sigh of relief that the damage wasn't more extensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some damage, but it wasn't as bad as expected
because we took precautions,'' said Nevis' deputy premier Malcolm
Guishard. ``The electricity is out but phones are working and the
streets really aren't flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   Georges was expected late Monday to hit Puerto Rico's capital of
San Juan, where nearly half the island's population lives. Anxious
residents stripped supermarket shelves of essentials, and hunkered
down in their homes, while government officials closed the San Juan
airport and ordered people off beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quiet outside, no one is working, there is little traffic
on the streets,'' said Alex Maldonado, a columnist for the San Juan
Star newspaper. ``But people here are used to the threat of
hurricanes and they know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Georges' strength had dwindled considerably since early Sunday,
when the hurricane sustained winds of 150 mph, but the U.S.
National Hurricane Center warned that Georges -- a strong Category
2 hurricane -- was still ``extremely dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida residents grew increasingly apprehensive on Monday even
though forecasters said it was too early to tell how serious a
threat Georges will pose to the southeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning was issued Monday for the Dominican
Republic, which braced for disaster. Hurricane watches went into
effect for northern Haiti, the southeastern Bahamas, the Turks and
Caicos Islands and eastern Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was scheduled to
make her first visit to Haiti and the Dominican Republic, where she
was expected to meet with leaders of non-government organizations
to talk about judicial reform, maternal health, and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, more than a dozen members of Clinton's White House
advance team, including Secret Service personnel, left the
Dominican Republic ahead of the hurricane for fear of being stuck
there.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether the first lady would still make
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dominican Republic dispatched its civil defense,
national emergency committee, the Red Cross, and police to assist
in preparations for Georges' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supermarkets are a little busier than usual, but I think
most people are waiting to see what happens in Puerto Rico before
they take any real action,'' said an official at the U.S. Embassy
in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Puerto Rico, Haiti is woefully unprepared for Georges,
which could send tin and wood shacks toppling down hillsides when,
and if it hits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the less-powerful Tropical Storm Gordon killed
approximately 2,000 residents in floods and mudslides in this
impoverished country.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
