<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN22-COX     09-21 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Now we may never be certain whether we've ever had sex
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think I've had about as much sex as I can take. Why don't we
talk about something else _ capital gains taxes, maybe, or Bobby
Cox's pitching rotation in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that if anything should arouse interest, it would be
sex. Don't you remember how completely absorbing it used to be?
There was nothing like it.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point in our lives, it's an awakening to another
dimension, a little bit frightening but immensely fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   But we ruin it like we ruin everything else. We wear it out
(although I sure didn't think I did) and finally it bores us.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy magazine tried to celebrate sexuality and ended up
making it tiresome and predictable. Kenneth Starr's Grand
Inquisitors don't go around in their pajamas like Hugh Hefner, but
they're making it just as boring.
</P>
<P>
   Define, please, ``sexual relations.'' If those were not the
exact words used by prosecutor Robert Bittman, they were close.
Does it mean, as Monica Lewinsky apparently wrote in one of her
letters to the president, ``the lying down kind,'' or does it
include what used to be called foreplay and petting?
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers don't think like lovers. They think like people who
write instruction manuals, identifying the individual parts,
enumerating the steps whereby part A is attached to part B and both
are inserted into part C and all them are bolted onto Part D and
Part E is somehow or other hooked on to it and the whole thing
eventually takes shape as a tricycle. They take the fun out of it.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, trying to answer a prosecutor's question,
President Clinton said: ``If Jane and Harry had a sexual
relationship, most people would interpret that as sexual
intercourse.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the president of the United States, speaking in the
very room where President Roosevelt and General Eisenhower planned
the invasion of Normandy, and he's having to talk about somebody
named Jane and Harry having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Who are Jane and Harry anyway? Are they going to be deposed,
too? We need to get to the bottom of this.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was giving his deposition, the Dow Jones and
Nasdaq averages flashed intermittently in the lower right hand
corner of the screen, like (as Lance Morrow of Time magazine put
it) an electrocardiogram. How are our vital signs while Kenneth
Starr's prosecutors probe deeper for Truth?
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the century, there was a branch of philosophy called
logical positivism, which held truth to be a matter of defining
terms. A statement was true or untrue depending on what was meant
by the terms that constituted it. Some statements _ five plus five
is 10 _ were true by definition. Those were the easy ones. Others
presented more difficulty. If we said, ``Democracy is the best form
of government,'' we had to be clear about what we meant by
``democracy'' and by ``best.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Clinton's deposition, with the prosecutor's pedantic
voice in the background, I thought about logicians defining sex.
``Sexual relations'' means this, this and this, but not that.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, we knew very well what was meant by ``going all
the way.'' No amount of logic chopping clouded the picture. There
were the preliminaries, and the vernacular described them with more
than adequate precision. No one puzzled over meanings.
</P>
<P>
   Sex still excited, still aroused, still engendered mystery.
</P>
<P>
   But the mystery's gone. Sex is banal and oversaturated. We've
all made it so, of course. Kenneth Starr's gang can't take all the
credit. It's ubiquitous and obligatory. Nothing can be interesting
without it _ not a novel, not a movie, not even, apparently, an
impeachment inquiry. The inevitable happens: Sex becomes boring,
too.
</P>
<P>
   But it has to be said that Kenneth Starr's prosecution of the
president has done for sex what not even Playboy could do. The
centerfolds always were sterile and without the imperfections of
the body that make sex enjoyable. Now come these guys, talking
about it like garage full of Mr. Goodwrenches, and you're not even
sure you knew what it was. Maybe that wasn't actually sex we had,
but only sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   Which one's better?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
