<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER22-COX     09-21 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hughley sitcom humor about life, not race or gender
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When stand-up comic D.L. Hughley was growing up in the Watts
section of Los Angeles, he says he never saw white people until he
was 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched 'Price is Right' and they would say, 'I live here in
L.A.,' and I'd go, 'I've never seen you around here', '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But stand-up paid off for Hughley (pronounced HYOO-glee), and he
moved to an upper-middle-class neighborhood with mostly white
neighbors. And that, in turn, paid off, with a sitcom loosely based
on his own life, ``The Hughleys'' (8:30 EDT tonight on ABC), one of
the better comedies in a rather parched field this seasonal
kick-off week.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second, and better, of the two new sitcoms about black
families moving into all-white neighborhoods, after Fox's ``Living
in Captivity.'' Darryl Hughley, rich off a booming vending machine
business, moves with his wife and two cute but not icky-cute kids,
and then spends most of his time missing the old neighborhood,
vigilantly looking out for racism and worrying that he and/or his
family are losing their African-American identity. And they given
him plenty of cause for concern, from his son, who'd rather listen
to Hanson than Marvin Gaye, to his daughter, who prefers a white
doll to a black one.
</P>
<P>
   One of several things ``The Hughleys'' manages well is to talk
about race in America today without being too in-your-face
provocative (it's a sitcom, not a treatise) or too
can't-we-all-just-get-along. It also doesn't confine itself to
race, being as much about the division between genders. The latter
is much more of a sitcom tradition that we're comfortable with,
just like Darryl's wife Yvonne (Elise Neal), who's the practical
household anchor to his borderline hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the humor isn't as much about race or gender as it
is about just plain life. In an upcoming episode, Darryl gets stuck
driving the kids' carpool to school in the family minivan (the bane
of suburban would-be studs everywhere). That may sound like the 2%
milk of humor, and it's not exactly cutting edge, but Hughley makes
it work, with ample assistance from John Henson (``Living
Single''), who plays his buddy Milsap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys'' isn't blazing any new comedy trails, but it
moves well on the trails it inhabits, and that's saying something
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Are we still mad about ``Mad About You''?
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Paul Reiser's ``Mad About You'' was one of
the better sitcoms on TV. That was about three Emmys, one Oscar and
a Golden Globe ago (all won for this show and ``As Good As It
Gets'' by series co-star Helen Hunt).
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Mad'' season premiere (8 p.m. on NBC (8377)) proves
the show's just coasting now _ its stars apparently resting on
their $1 million-an-episode laurels. He takes a Viagra pill; she
gets caught out on the streets of New York wearing only a towel.
</P>
<P>
   It's every joke you've already heard about the new male wonder
drug. And even a surprise cameo by NBC's once-biggest sitcom star
can't keep this show from going, well, limp.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   No ``Encore'' from this corner
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with network television can be summed up in one
word (spoken, or in this case, exclaimed twice): ``Encore!
Encore!'' (8:30 EDT tonight on NBC).
</P>
<P>
   It's the age-old network ploy of hiring a talented name star
(like Nathan Lane), pairing that celeb with talented name co-stars
(like Glenne Headly and Joan Plowright) and then trying to figure
out the funny parts.
</P>
<P>
   This show smells like it has one writer and about 30 network
suits working on the script. Lane plays American opera singer Joey
Pinoni (in effect, a tenor diva) whose voice is injured. It's then
back to mama (Plowright) and sibling rival Francesca (Headly) in
the family winery in Napa Valley for rest, rehabilitation and
ridiculous hilarity.
</P>
<P>
   Pratfalls, too. In this show, one of Lane's first antics is flop
out of a hospital bed. Loud canned laughter ensues.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of joke you get on this show. Francesca's hot
and bothered because a bored Joey's taken her high school bookworm
son Michael (Trevor Fehrman) out with call girls. She's beating
Joey up. ``Shut up,'' she says. ``This isn't Italy and I'm not some
earthy woman with hairy armpits who doesn't care if her kid grows
up with the morals of an alleycat.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey's zinger: ``Actually, that would be France.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
