<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek reveals that Bill Clinton ignored his lawyers' advice
not to testify before the grand jury.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Published before the president's grand jury videotape was aired
Monday, the newsweeklies were forced to focus on what will happen
next. Time ($2.95) reports that Clinton advisers and top Democrats
have been working behind the scenes to devise an exit strategy
short of impeachment or resignation. Newsweek ($2.95), quoting
sources who had seen the videotape, described Clinton as being
enraged at times and evasive at others. But, as the magazine's Evan
Thomas and Michael Isikoff explain, the president would not have
been viewed twisting in the wind by millions if he had followed the
advice of his attorneys. David Kendall and Robert Bennett opposed
his testifying; Hillary Rodham Clinton urged him to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the first lady, U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95)
profiles Mrs. Clinton and speculates about her chances of saving
her husband. Included is a new poll that shows Americans admire her
but are cynical about her marriage. Forty-eight percent of those
surveyed believe the marriage is basically a political alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In a more literary approach to the scandal, The New Yorker ($3)
offers two original takes on the Starr report. Rebecca Mead
contends that the only sexual abuse that took place was at the
hands of the independent counsel. After pressuring Lewinsky with
threats, Mead writes, Starr then ``compels her, in her grand-jury
testimony, to speak with a specificity somewhere between the
pornographic and the gynecological. ... Starr wanted to see the
President laid low, and Lewinsky got laid low in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Starr report as literature? Adam Gopnik
critiques it as a novel, comparing it to such morality tales as
``The Scarlet Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST HEROES: More than three decades ago, John Glenn and his
fellow astronauts were hailed as heroes with ``the right stuff.''
In its October issue, Life ($3.99) returns to that age of innocence
with a cover story on the eve of John Glenn's space voyage and
revisits the survivors of the Mercury Seven program. Refreshingly,
each of the men rejects the term ``hero'' for himself. Says L.
Gordon Cooper: ``I guess my idea of a real hero is some guy,
knowing he could be killed in a combat situation, still putting
himself down to save his buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   THE NAKED TRUTH: Pamela Anderson bares her soul _ and nearly
everything else _ in a Details ($2.50) cover story that shows her
re-creating the famous Farrah Fawcett swimsuit poster of 1977. On
the eve of her new series, ``V.I.P.,'' Anderson insists she is not
a bimbo, although she has played one on TV.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING CARE OF BUSINESS: Atlantans Jermaine Dupri of So So Def
Recordings and Jeff Arnold, founder of Endeavor Technologies, are
two of the top 50 young entrepreneurs, according to the October
issue of P.O.V. ($2.95). Not surprisingly, most of the 50 are in
high-tech fields. Also of note: a fun first-person account of
writer Nicole Beland's experiences at a Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders
audition. Why, she wonders, would 250 modern young women spend
three days trying out for a job that involves kicking and screaming
and pays $50 a week? Good question.
</P>
<P>
   BIG AUDIENCE: When Camryn Manheim of TV's ``The Practice''
proudly held up her Emmy and proclaimed, ``This is for all the fat
girls!'' she was echoing the motto of Radiance ($6), a magazine
devoted to plus-size women. Manheim is on the cover of the fall
edition. Published for 14 years, Radiance features interviews with
calorically overwhelmed celebrities along with articles on health
and fashion. Now, says publisher Alice Ansfield, ``We're expanding
our focus to include children of all ages. We want to help them
feel seen, loved, and valued for who they are, whatever their size
or shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
