</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOOTME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Shoot Me's' comic aim swings closer to the mark
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time, not too long ago, when a producer could have
gone to NBC pitching a miniseries about a 21st-century Hispanic
time traveler who discovers the lost continent of Atlantis, and it
would have wound up on the air as a sitcom about an attractive
young white woman with a messy love life who works at a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   So when ``Just Shoot Me'' debuted last year, it was easy to
dismiss as another product of NBC's comedy committee. A ``Suddenly
Susan'' wannabe is like a kid who wants to dress up as Donald Trump
for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   But after a rickety launch, ``Shoot Me'' started shooting off in
wonderfully unpredictable ways. It developed a voice, an attitude,
an ensemble and, fairly quickly, an audience. At one point last
season, NBC had it following ``Seinfeld'' on Thursday nights and it
was actually getting better ratings than ``Seinfeld,'' which led to
talk it might be the heir apparent for 9 p.m. ET Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   That honor, of course, went to quintuple Emmy winner
``Frasier,'' but ``Shoot Me'' got NBC's Miss Congeniality prize _
``Frasier's'' old home, 9 p.m. ET Tuesdays, where it comes back
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Laura San Giacomo is still top-billed as Maya Gallo, the
reluctant writer for Cosmoesque Blush magazine, but ``Shoot'' soars
on its near-perfectly pitched ensemble, much as ``Cheers'' did.
George Segal is Jack Gallo, Maya's blustery mogul dad and Blush's
publisher; Wendie Malick is Nina, the neurotic ex-model who dabbles
at being fashion editor between her nightlife and assignations;
Elliott (Enrico Colatoni) is the photographer who's still a bit
unclear _ is he insecure or not?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Dennis Finch, the role of a lifetime for David
Spade. The former ``Saturday Night Live'' player was looking down
the barrel of a career as second banana to Chris Farley in
two-thumbs-down movies when ``Shoot'' beckoned. As Jack Gallo's
assistant, Finch is the ultimate office weasel, a snotty, whiny,
backstabbing, smarmy boy who's so self-absorbed he's like a human
roll of Bounty paper towels. And this in an office where full-blown
narcissism barely gets you into the morning editorial meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the smartest thing about ``Shoot'': When the producers
saw the Finch character taking off, they refused to do a Fonzie and
rebuild the show around him.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's season premiere is just dandy, with Finch betraying
Jack, Nina in the clutches of a cult, Elliott abandoning Maya at a
time of need and Maya extracting a very funny revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The throwaway lines crackle, that funky little bass line loops
through the segues, and ``Just Shoot Me'' hits its marks.
</P>
<P>
   On next year's Emmy Awards, look for it to be at least a
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Shoot Me''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   9 EDT, tonight on NBC
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Just watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
