</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTSNIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Sports Night'' a good show, but its not of championship
caliber
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a sitcom about a nightly sports highlights show be better
than those ESPN commericials?
</P>
<P>
   No. It can't. But it can try. ABC's ``Sports Night,'' a
fictionalized take on ESPN's ``SportsCenter,'' does a better job
than it has any right to at fashioning a sometimes heart-tugging
comedy around the on-air and behind-the-scenes antics of a nightly
sports highlights show.
</P>
<P>
   This is TV sports as the e.r., and a show about TV sports as
``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   They're saving sports fans' lives in that control booth:
</P>
<P>
   ``I need 15 points of sound on Kansas City!''
</P>
<P>
   ``... Give me Green Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand by audio. Stand by VTR.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're live here in 60 seconds!''
</P>
<P>
   A camera drunk on adrenaline roams the ``Sports Night'' booth to
caputre the drama in a bank of monitors, people wearing headsets,
people pushing buttons. Then, just when you think this might be
brain surgery, somebody asks the big question: Is Helsinki the
capital of Sweden or Finland? Fans need to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night,'' airing on a network owned by the same
conglomerate that owns ESPN (Disney), manages to be more than a
bald stab at corporate synergy.
</P>
<P>
   It centers on the lives and personalities of Dan (Josh Charles)
and Casey (Peter Krause), this nightly sports show's young,
likeable anchors. They speak a kind of sport's fan's Esperanto:
that peculiar male mix of sports-as-intimacy and
intimacy-as-sports. When Dan and Casey confront each other about
Casey's impending divorce, and how it's detracting from the show,
they exchange pointed verbal punches _ then slip right into talk
about rugby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's something I don't understand about rugby,'' Casey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute,'' Dan interrupts, ``you understand something
about rugby?''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: I love you, man.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's pilot does a swift, sure-handed job of mixing the
personal with the professional. It's a sitcom with heart _ there
are moments near the end of tonight's pilot and next week's second
episode that aim to make the male ape cry.
</P>
<P>
   But what ``Sports Night'' is really about is the '90s concept of
office as family. Included in the brood here is tough-love producer
Dana (Felicity Huffman), who serves for viewers as a kind of
traffic cop for men who love sports and the women who love them;
executive producer Isaac (Robert Guillaume), the bridge between the
talent's heart and corporate suits' heartlessness; and new-hire
researcher Jeremy (Joshua Malina), a bridge between jocks and
nerds.
</P>
<P>
   It all works well tonight, but heads too greedily toward the
joke pile by next week. This is a tricky concept to pull off: a
sitcom with a dramatic itch; a show about sports that's not about
sports.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the new season's best sitcom. Root for it. Just
don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   9:30 ET tonight on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
