A6632 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-IN-WHA     09-21 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBIN-WILLIAMS-IN-WHAT-DREAMS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN WILLIAMS TACKLES THE FIGHT OF HIS AFTERLIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Robin Williams in a scene from ``What
Dreams May Come.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Naturally, Robin Williams has his own idea of hell.
 &HT;    Think of it as a game show, a celestial version of ``Let's Make
a Deal.''
 &HT;    ``Behind door No. 1 there is a videotape,'' Williams says.
``It's heaven. It's very calm. People are floating around, dressed
in white. I'd say, `It's very nice, but I'd like to see door No.
2.'''
 &HT;    Inside that door waits another video.
 &HT;    ``It's a wild disco! Girls are naked! The Champagne is flowing!
There's kissing! There's fornication! It's wild!''' Williams raves.
 &HT;    Casting everything to the winds, the actor/comedian says, he'd
probably pick that second door.
 &HT;    ``I get in the elevator and go down, down, down. The doors open
_ it's burning hell! The devil says, `You're mine!' I'm going,
`Wait a minute, what about the tape?'
 &HT;    ``The devil says, `Oh, obviously you just saw the pilot.'''
 &HT;    Williams throws back his head and laughs loudly.
 &HT;    ``Oh, this is going to be a good day,'' he says, looking around
his suite at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel. ``We're starting out
right.''
 &HT;    Heaven and hell are on his mind because on Oct. 2 he'll open at
theaters everywhere in the much-awaited fall drama ``What Dreams
May Come,'' about a man who dies and, in an effort to rejoin his
anguished wife (Annabella Sciorra), finds himself forced to
traverse both ends of the afterlife experience.
 &HT;    Don't expect it to look like a game show.
 &HT;    ``The fact that you have to deal with emotional issues of loss
and redemption meant a lot of soul searching,'' the actor admits,
sobering. ``I lost my father a few years ago, and this dredged a
lot of it back up again. It was a hard-core experience.''
 &HT;    One scene, for example, required Williams to walk across a
barren hellscape with human heads sticking up out of the ground,
tormented souls wailing in pain.
 &HT;    ``It was awful,'' he recalls, ``but not for the reasons you
think. These were real people whose heads were popping out of the
ground. And it's strange, because these extras would yell out,
`Hey, Robin, step on me! Do it, man!' I cracked one guy's glasses,
and he started yelling, `Do it again!'''
 &HT;    Nor was life in heaven any picnic.
 &HT;    ``Flying like an angel was torture,'' Williams says, who'd
already done his share of levitation in ``Hook'' (1991). ``You want
real hell? Hell is when you have a rig attached to your lower
regions. This rig would turn any man into a human Ken doll.''
 &HT;    Which isn't to say that the actor/comedian doesn't believe in
heaven or hell.
 &HT;    ``Oh, yes. I do,'' he says readily. ``I think you get coming
attractions of heaven in your dreams. I call them visions. I also
think there are places on earth where, if it's not heaven, it's a
real nice start ... There are days when I look at my kids playing
and I think, `This is heaven.' It's not just a contentment, but a
power surge in your heart.
 &HT;    ``I'm not the fire-and-brimstone type,'' he adds, ``but I know
hell exists. In fact, there is hell on earth. To me that hell is
those videotapes of Kuwait after the wells were on fire and the sky
was so dark. That's the closest thing to hell I've ever seen.''
 &HT;    On a more personal level, he sees a different kind of hell.
 &HT;    ``I think hell is madness or any psychosis,'' he muses. ``People
who are manic depressives have described that condition as being in
hell. Hell is when everything is crashing in on you.''
 &HT;    The core of the film is the idea that everyone has a soul mate _
an idea Williams won't argue with.
 &HT;    ``I found my soul mate in my wife, Marsha,'' he says. ``All I
have to do is look at her and know that we belong together. Our
life together is extraordinary, which just confirms it.''
 &HT;    Williams' life has been extraordinary all around, actually. Last
March, he won an Oscar for his role as a kindly psychologist in
``Good Will Hunting'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``It was a welcome relief after all those years of going,
`Daniel Day-Lewis, I am so happy for you,''' Williams says, blowing
fake smoke into the air.
 &HT;    More seriously, the actor denies being nervous beforehand.
 &HT;    ``The other times I was nominated, I was sure I would lose,'' he
says. ``I was the wild card _ I didn't expect much. This time I
really thought I had a 50-50 shot, which just relaxed me.''
 &HT;    Even so, when his name was announced as Best Supporting Actor,
Williams recalls, ``Marsha had to literally give me a shove. I just
sat there. I was stunned. Finally, Marsha whispered into my ear,
`I'm so proud of you. Now get up there!'''
 &HT;    It was a culmination of sorts for the rich but insecure kid who
grew up in Detroit as the son of a successful auto-industry
executive.
 &HT;    ``I was much shorter than the other kids, so it was about
survival for me back then,'' he recalls. ``I was always this hairy
little guy with white, pasty skin. The other kids would call me
`The Leprechaun.'''
 &HT;    It's hard to picture, but Williams insists he was an introvert.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I was a very shy boy who was slow and awkward,'' he says.
``I walked around afraid of what people would say about me.''
 &HT;    At home, the real Williams would emerge.
 &HT;    ``I would go into my mom's bedroom and do all these skits,'' he
recalls. ``All I wanted to do was make her laugh.''
 &HT;    When the family moved to San Francisco, however, a teen-age
Williams found stand-up comedy, and his place in life.
 &HT;    ``San Francisco in the late '60s was a real wild time _ a lot of
severe medication,'' Williams says. ``To tell you the truth,
everything seemed really funny. Our high-school cheer was `Reality!
Reality! Wow!'''
 &HT;    Club comedy led to guest appearances on television shows,
including a ``Happy Days'' role that led to his hit series, ``Mork
and Mindy.'' From there Williams sought the big screen, forging a
double-headed career as a zany comedian _ in ``Popeye'' (1980),
``Good Morning Vietnam'' (1987) and ``Flubber'' (1997) _ and as a
``real'' actor in such serious dramas as ``Dead Poet's Society''
(1989), ``Awakenings'' (1990) and ``The Fisher King'' (1991).
 &HT;    The serious side seems to be predominant these days. Immediately
after filming ``What Dreams,'' the actor headed off to Poland to
film ``Jacob the Liar,'' set in a Polish ghetto in 1944.
 &HT;    ``The Germans would jam people into these ghettos before sending
them to the camps,'' Williams says. ``And, in the ghettos, people
would carry on this illusion of a normal life. People worked. There
were theater performances. People were still trying to maintain
their human dignity, but this idea of extermination just hung over
them.''
 &HT;    Not that Williams the comedian is done for, of course. He does
have the Christmas comedy ``Patch Adams,'' directed by Tom ``Ace
Ventura'' Shadyac, in the can. And he's pondering a sequel to his
hit 1996 gay comedy, ``The Birdcage.''
 &HT;    ``If Nathan Lane, Mike Nichols and Gene Hackman want to do it,
I'm in,'' he says.
 &HT;    For now, though, this busiest of actors is stepping offstage.
 &HT;    ``I'm taking until February off to just be with my wife and
children,'' says Williams, who lives in San Francisco with his wife
and three kids: 14-year-old Zack, 8-year-old Zelda and 4-year-old
Cody.
 &HT;    ``My heaven is just sneaking around the house late at night and
checking on everyone,'' he says. ``Just knowing that they're fine
and happy makes my heart pound.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
