<HEADER>
A6633 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHOOPI-GOLDBERG-IN-HO     09-21 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHOOPI-GOLDBERG-IN-HOLLYWOOD-SQUARES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOOPI'S GOT A BRAND-NEW GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Whoopi Goldberg in a scene from
``Hollywood Squares.'' 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Growing up in New York's Chelsea housing project, Caryn Johnson
harbored very specific dreams.
 &HT;    She wanted to be a professional actress _ and win an Academy
Award, of course. She wanted to get to know the magnetically
handsome stage and screen star Frank Langella. And she wanted to
meet the president of the United States.
 &HT;    Thirty years later Johnson, now known as Whoopi Goldberg, has
achieved all three _ and then some. A star of both stage and
screen, winner of a Best Supporting Actress Oscar for 1990's
``Ghost,'' she hobnobs with the Clintons and has been romantically
involved with Langella for two years.
 &HT;    Speaking by telephone from her home in New York, the actress
reports that she still has ambitions galore _ but, she admits,
``it's nice to be able to check things off the list.''
 &HT;    Appearing on a television game show may or may not have been one
of those childhood ambitions, but if so, she can cross that one
off. Goldberg is currently starring in _ and executive producing _
the latest revival of ``Hollywood Squares,'' the popular show which
ran from 1966 to 1980 and again from 1986 to 1989.
 &HT;    ``Hollywood Squares'' is basically a giant tic-tac-toe game.
Celebrity guests appear in the board's nine squares, while two
contestants earn their Xs and Os by declaring whether a celebrity
has correctly answered a given question.
 &HT;    Goldberg will be the show's only regular, appearing in the
center square and following in the footsteps of Paul Lynde, during
the show's initial run, and Joan Rivers, during the syndicated
version in the late 1980s.
 &HT;    The actress, who recently graced Broadway in ``A Funny Thing
Happened on the Way to the Forum'' and has appeared in more than 30
feature films, insists she's not out of place in a televised game
show.
 &HT;    ``When `Hollywood Squares' first went on the air,'' she says,
``there was a very clear delineation between performers who did
television and those who did movies. You didn't see movie stars
doing a lot of TV back then, and when stars did do TV it was
assumed there was something wrong in their careers.
 &HT;    ``But today,'' she says, ``with me, Helen Hunt, Glenn Close and
others going back and forth quite easily between film and
television, that line has been erased.''
 &HT;    The show's guest list would seem to bear that out: Robin
Williams, Billy Crystal and Sharon Stone are all scheduled to
appear. Political spinmeister James Carville is also on tap, and
Rosie O'Donnell occupied one of the first week's squares.
 &HT;    The 42-year-old Goldberg reached the center square by a
roundabout route. Though she came to public attention as a
comedian, her first love was acting, which she pursued in New York,
Berkeley, Calif., and San Diego. She was 27 when producer/director
Mike Nichols caught her one-woman show in San Francisco, and
brought it to Broadway in 1984.
 &HT;    There Steven Spielberg saw her, and cast her in ``The Color
Purple'' (1985). That kicked off a film career which has included
``Ghost,'' ``Sister Act'' (1992), ``Corrina, Corrina'' (1994),
``Bogus'' (1995) and the recent ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
She also appeared on the television series ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' and the short-lived ``Bagdad Cafe.''
 &HT;    She's had more than her share of box-office flops among the
hits, but Goldberg insists that she has few regrets.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I've made too many errors,'' she snaps.
 &HT;    If Goldberg seems testy, perhaps it's the early hour _ 9 a.m. _
or perhaps it's her problematic history with the press.
 &HT;    ``You want to keep a private life,'' she says. ``People say,
`This is what you bought into,' but that's not true. I bought into
being a person on a screen who chooses what information they want
to put out. Today you no longer have that choice. And if someone
wants to ruin you, all they have to do is make an innuendo.''
 &HT;    The actress is particularly upset about a 1997 article in New
York magazine, which claimed that Goldberg had admitted fabricating
stories about her past.
 &HT;    ``There is no reason to lie about yourself, particularly if you
have been upfront all the way through,'' she says. ``I had simply
told the reporter that I didn't want to talk about it because I had
talked about it endlessly ... I just didn't want to rehash it. She
didn't like my answer and, instead of saying the boring thing, she
intimated that I was trying to alter my past.''
 &HT;    So no, Goldberg says, she never denied having used heroin as a
teen-ager, dropped out of high school or been on welfare for a
while.
 &HT;    ``They are probably not the best things I could have done, but I
did them,'' she says. ``That doesn't mean other people should do
them. I survived where a lot of other people didn't.''
 &HT;    As a veteran of the tabloid wars _ her 1993-94 relationship with
Ted Danson, for example, provided frequent headlines _ Goldberg
sympathizes with the current ordeal of her friend, President
Clinton.
 &HT;    ``I think the media and some of the folks in office have lost
their minds,'' she says. ``It's not like he's the Dalai Lama and
was born into the job _ he's a regular guy with flaws. I live in a
glass house, and it's very hard for me to understand how it is
immoral to have a sexual relationship with another willing person _
and that is the operative word, `willing.'
 &HT;    ``We hold them up to moral standards that we ourselves couldn't
stand up to,'' Goldberg continues. ``We have to figure out what it
is we want: Do we want a god or a president?
 &HT;    ``I don't think there is a Republican in the world who could
stand up under this kind of microscope,'' she concludes. ``The last
saint was Mother Teresa, and they are few and far between.''
 &HT;    If calls for humane tolerance sound odd coming from a comedian
who has been known for her acerbic commentary, Goldberg says that
it may be because she's mellowing.
 &HT;    ``I think I am becoming more compassionate,'' she admits. ``I
understand a lot more, the older I get. I see that things aren't
black or white. It isn't always easy to accept, and it isn't easy
to say to someone, `Look, I was wrong about that and I'm really
sorry.'
 &HT;    ``It makes life so much easier if you can cop to the mistakes
and say, `Well, this is how I looked at it, but maybe this isn't
the way I need to deliver it to you. Maybe I could talk to you
about it in a way that doesn't require anyone becoming combative in
their response.'''
 &HT;    She may be settling down emotionally, but physically Goldberg is
as up in the air as ever. Or, rather, down to earth, since she's
afraid of flying and goes everywhere by bus. This is particularly
hard on her relationship with Langella, since he remains tied to
the New York stage while she has to tape ``Hollywood Squares'' in
Los Angeles.
 &HT;    She tapes on Saturday and Sunday, the actress reports, then
leaves California Sunday night. She arrives in New York 48 hours
later, and two days later she is back on the bus, heading west.
 &HT;    It's still worth it, she says of the relationship which began in
1996 when the two appeared together in the basketball movie,
``Eddie.''
 &HT;    ``It is good and fun, and we are still together,'' she says
simply. ``And I am very happy.''
 &HT;    Actually, the grandmother of two says, she's pretty happy about
everything in her life.
 &HT;    ``I'm lucky,'' she says. ``I was raised to believe I could do
anything if I was willing to accept the fact that not everyone was
going to like it or be accepting of it. And to believe that that
was OK.''
 c.1998 Jean Oppenheimer  
