</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNA-ELFMAN-IN-DHARMA-&AMP;-GREG-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNA ELFMAN: THE KARMA OF DHARMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jenna Elfman in a scene from ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year ABC's prime-time lineup took more casualties than Tom
Hanks' unit did in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, once the critics, the viewers and _ most ominously _
the Nielsens had had their say, the only two people left standing
were Jenna Elfman and Thomas Gibson, the stars of ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg,'' the hit saga of free-spirited sprite Dharma Finklestein and
her husband, buttoned-down attorney Greg.
</P>
<P>
   As lighthearted as her television character may be, Elfman
proves to be just as much so. She refuses all opportunities to act
like a star. Why, she won't even hire a bodyguard or whine about
the paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the thing: I am responsible for my own condition,'' she
says. ``You don't blame your dad or your second-grade teacher. If
things were done to you, you made it OK for them to do those
things. I'm the one who's playing the game. The more you try to
protect, the more people get to you. If they see you with a
bodyguard, they think there must be something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Stardom is still new to Elfman, whose previous career high was
``Townies,'' a 1996 sitcom that flopped ignominiously.
Nevertheless, she caught the eye of network execs, and before long
industry observers were predicting ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' would be a
smash _ months before it ever hit the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take was, `Oh, well, good, if it'll help people watch,'''
she says. ``It was flattering. With `Townies,' I was not ready to
be a star. It was good to be noticed. The self-esteem thing, I can
pull off. I'm willing to fail _ it's going to get you eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfman says her audition for the part helped shape some of the
mannerisms and traits that have subsequently turned up in Dharma.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see things showing up in scripts that I had done that had
worked,'' she says. ``It has evolved through rehearsal, evolved
through the scripts. I really don't need to have much input _
they're so good, I don't need to have something to say. Everyone
lets everyone wear their hat.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the search for an actor who could hold his own
against Elfman's flights of fancy was a difficult one for
co-creators Chuck Lorre and Dotty Dartland until Gibson took off
his ``Chicago Hope'' scrubs and entered the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the other guys had one thing,'' Elfman recalls. ``One guy
was so hysterical, but there was no chemistry, he could have been
my brother. Others were so handsome, but had no sense of humor _
not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas has so much charm,'' she says. ``Chuck and Dotty said,
`If we're OK watching him kiss you, then he's the one.' The
chemistry was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Both performers understand how well they complement one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Dharma's the wacky one, so he has to be straight,''
she says. ``Thomas realizes that's his role, but he's had some
episodes where he got to be goofy and I got to be the straight man.
We both know our roles in the show _ I'm not funny without a
straight man, and he's not charming without the wacko.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfman is delighted by the positive message ``Dharma &AMP; Greg''
sends its viewers, simply in portraying a happy marriage _ rare in
sitcomland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should set an example if you're on TV,'' she says. ``In
every living room, you should be trying to lift people's spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Her current exuberance notwithstanding, there were plenty of
times along the way when Elfman's spirits needed lifting. Her
initially promising career as a dancer was ultimately ruined by a
chronic ankle injury she had suffered at the age of 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I iced it, the less I danced,'' she recalls. ``I
wanted to do my career, not sit on the sidelines. It was like being
in a playpen in the window, watching your brother and sister play
outside. There's nothing worse for me. When I'm all dressed up and
someone cancels on me, I'm never more crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere eight years ago, Elfman says, she was the polar opposite
of her current sunshiny self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a dancer who didn't want to dance,'' she says. ``It
wasn't going to happen. I wasn't sure of myself as an actress, with
guys, as a person. If I had friends who were successful, I'd feel
even less successful than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Can't picture it? Wait for Ron Howard's upcoming film,
``Ed-TV,'' in which Elfman plays just such a character.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't her first film. She appeared in bit parts in ``Grosse
Pointe Blank'' (1997) and ``Can't Hardly Wait'' (1998), contributed
the voice of the Owl in the summer smash ``Dr. Dolittle'' and
carried on cheerfully through the spring dud ``Krippendorf's
Tribe'' _ ``a huge growing experience, and I was proud to be part
of it,'' she says chirpily.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ed-TV'' will mark her first effort as a serious film
actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Ed-TV' I finally got to put on the tool belt as an
actress, and put everything I learned into it,'' she says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, to be released next year, Elfman plays Shari, an
insecure young woman who finds herself dating Ed (Matthew
McConaughey), the star of his own round-the-clock television show.
Think ``The Truman Show,'' only with Truman liking all the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the voice of sanity, disagreeing with this phenomenon,
while everyone else is in full agreement,'' Elfman explains. ``This
movie shows how people glob into agreement _ if others are
agreeing, then it must be so. That's insanity. Shari is the only
one disagreeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shari's lack of self-confidence rang a bell with Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had more of that side to me a while ago,'' she says. ``It
was fun to be able to play that, since I understand it now, I can
live it fully and it's better for the movie. The happier I get or
more certain, the easier it is to play the other side, because I'm
not in it as much, where you can't see the forest for the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson likewise did some moonlighting over the summer, taking a
part in Stanley Kubrick's marathon production, ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
The highest number of takes for a single scene demanded by the
legendarily obsessive, perfectionist director? A mere 50-something,
Elfman reports, considerably fewer than the 80 or more that stars
Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman often found themselves grinding out.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Bodhi Elfman, also hit the big screen over the
summer, with a small part in ``Armageddon.'' Bodhi was also cast
for, then fired from, Fox's troubled series ``Hollyweird.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why a sense of humor is good, so you don't crumble at
the sight of TV executives,'' Elfman says sunnily.
</P>
<P>
   This year on ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' the couple will adopt a child.
Though Elfman in the past has enthused about the idea of having her
own children, she's currently a bit more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never the right time,'' she says with a sigh. ``When it
does come, it will be the most beautiful thing, it will change our
life hugely for the good. It all sounds good to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to not be there _ though, if I'm at work but my
mind is on the kids, I don't want that,'' Elfman says. ``I have a
film career to consider, too. I don't want to be a parent and an
actress half-assed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a Los Angeles-based senior writer for Canadian
TV Guide.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
