NYT-09-21-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6635 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANLEY-TUCCI-IN-THE-     09-21 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANLEY-TUCCI-IN-THE-IMPOSTORS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY TUCCI TAKES A FLING AT FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Stanley Tucci and Oliver Platt in a scene
from ``The Impostors.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    His career may be catching fire, but Stanley Tucci isn't
catching anything.
 &HT;    ``I went fishing with my dad this morning and, as usual, we
caught nothing,'' Tucci says, his laughter reverberating over the
telephone from his home in Westchester County, N.Y. ``I said,
`Thank God we didn't try to do this for a living, because we'd have
starved to death years ago.'''
 &HT;    Fortunately for Tucci, he got through the last 15 years as a
familiar character actor on television and in films. And, of late,
he's had far bigger fish to fry as the
writer/director/producer/star of his own movies.
 &HT;    Tucci earned acclaim and scored a modest box-office hit in 1996
as the co-writer/co-producer/co-director/co-star of the
food-loose-and-fancy-free comedy/drama ``Big Night,'' and on Oct. 2
he returns to the big screen with ``The Impostors.''
 &HT;    Set in the 1930s, during the Great Depression, ``The Impostors''
stars Tucci and Oliver Platt as unemployed actors whose drunken
mockery of a famous thespian (Alfred Molina) launches them on the
adventure of their lives.
 &HT;    They wind up on a cruise ship, enmeshed in a cheerfully insane
plot. A variety of independent-film stalwarts _ Steve Buscemi,
Billy Connolly, Lili Taylor, Campbell Scott, Dana Ivey, Hope Davis
and Tony Shalhoub _ turn up along the way.
 &HT;    ``I'd always wanted to put a farce on film, and one of the
reasons I wanted to try that was that people said, `You can't do
that. It doesn't work,''' Tucci says. ``When I tried to get the
money for the movie, everybody said that.
 &HT;    ``I also wanted to work with this group of actors,'' he adds.
``and wanted to write roles for them that they'd never played
before, to show people different sides of them that I know.
 &HT;    ``They're all so versatile, and they're the nicest people you'd
ever want to meet,'' Tucci says with real affection. ``They took
the gamble with me on `Big Night,' and I asked them to take another
gamble here.''
 &HT;    ``The Impostors'' will likely face greater expectations than
``Big Night,'' which caught audiences by surprise. More eyes are on
Tucci this time around, and he knows it.
 &HT;    ``While making the movie I wasn't nervous, but I started to get
a little nervous in the editing room, during test screenings,'' he
admits. ``It took a little while to make use of the test screenings
and to let go of the fact that `Impostors' was my sophomore effort
and that people would scrutinize it more.
 &HT;    ``It took awhile to say, `I've made the movie I wanted to make,
without compromise,''' he says. ``That's all there is to it, but
that's a very difficult thing to do.
 &HT;    ``You can't second-guess yourself, and you can't pander or cater
to an audience.''
 &HT;    When ``Big Night'' achieved sleeper status, people wondered
``Who the heck is Stanley Tucci?'' and ``Where'd he come from?''
Nowadays, more people are likely to know the answers.
 &HT;    ``Before `Big Night' I'd done about 25 movies and more than 100
episodes of television series,'' says Tucci, who was born and
reared in Katonah, N.Y., and attended college at SUNY/Purchase. ``I
did an extended arc (as a charming killer) on `Murder One' that got
a lot of attention. That and `Big Night' put me up on another
level.
 &HT;    ``The visibility was so high on both projects, and they were
very different roles and projects,'' he says. ``Millions of people
saw `Murder One,' and `Big Night' crossed over and became a very
talked-about film.
 &HT;    ``The combination of `Big Night' and `Murder One' changed
everything for me.''
 &HT;    ``Big Night' enabled Tucci to give free rein to his inner
control freak.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't until I started writing `Big Night' that it hit me
that all I was looking for, really, was control of my life, and I
didn't have that as an actor,'' he says. ``I was at the mercy of
God knows who.
 &HT;    ``Also, as an actor, I always felt like I languished between
films,'' he says. ``I did everything I could to stay alive
creatively _ I painted and drew and read, whatever _ and I still
wasn't satisfied.
 &HT;    ``Writing and directing, while difficult, are enormously
satisfying.''
 &HT;    Of course, many an actor aspires to write and direct, but few
succeed. Tucci doesn't take anything for granted, but he feels that
he's earned his success.
 &HT;    ``I certainly feel lucky, but I have to say it came out of hard
work,'' he says. ```Big Night' did not just happen. We all worked
very hard to make that film, and it took a long, long time.
 &HT;    ``We didn't compromise our vision,'' he adds, ``and I can't
begin to tell you how glad I am that our vision was so liked by so
many.''
 &HT;    While Tucci waits to see if ``Impostors'' meets a similar
reception, he's put his actor hat back on. He'll appear as a con
artist in a whodunit entitled ``The Alarmist,'' which features Kate
Capshaw and David Arquette and will open in limited release
throughout October and November, and star as the late
journalist/radio commentator Walter Winchell in ``Winchell,'' a
made-for-cable movie airing in late November on HBO.
 &HT;    In what definitely will represent a change of pace, the actor is
also to be seen as Puck in director Michael Hoffman's big-screen
version of Shakespeare's ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' His
co-stars include Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer and Calista
Flockheart.
 &HT;    Tucci's previous films run the gamut from high-profile Hollywood
productions such as ``The Pelican Brief'' (1993), ``It Could Happen
to You'' (1994) and ``Kiss of Death'' (1995) to indie fare such as
``In the Soup'' (1992), ``Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle''
(1994) and ``The Daytrippers'' (1996).
 &HT;    Unlike many laborers in the indie vineyards, Tucci has nothing
bad to say about mainstream films or the people who make them.
 &HT;    ``Some big movies I really love,'' Tucci says. ``I love the
scope of things like the James Bond movies.
 &HT;    ``As an actor, bigger films are fun,'' he adds. ``You get paid.
You often get to work with great people, and sometimes you get to
do a role that's really interesting.
 &HT;    ``It's nice to be able to taste both worlds,'' Tucci says.
``Listen, people give indie actors a lot of s--t about doing a big
movie, and it's really unfortunate.''
 &HT;    Actors, Tucci argues, need roofs over their heads as much as
anyone else does.
 &HT;    ``If you worked for scale all the time on independent films, you
couldn't make a living,'' he says forcefully. ``If you want to have
a family and send a kid to college, forget about it. If you make
scale on four independent features, people may say, `Hey, you're
working all the time,' but you're probably broke.
 &HT;    ``People think actors in movies are getting rich somehow,'' he
concludes. ``Sometimes it's true, but sometimes it's not.''
 &HT;    Tucci recently finished the script for his next directing
effort, ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' based on magazine articles written
by Joseph Mitchell for The New Yorker. Casting will begin soon, and
Tucci expects to shoot the picture as early as January.
 &HT;    ``I'm panicking because I have some time off between now and
then,'' says Tucci, who's 38 and married. ``Steve Buscemi said to
me, earlier today, `Just enjoy it.' But it's weird.
 &HT;    ``I've been working, working, working for two straight years,
and all I wanted was a break,'' the actor/director says, laughing.
``Now I've got a break, and I don't know what to do with myself.
 &HT;    ``I feel so ... unemployed.''
 &HT;    Fishing, anyone?
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
