<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6648 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-VIDEOTAPE-HN     09-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-VIDEOTAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SLAM TAPE'S RELEASE WHILE REPUBLICANS TALK IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While some congressional Democrats criticized
Monday's release of the videotape of President Clinton's grand jury
testimony as partisan warfare, Republicans said it showed the
president lying under oath and could provide grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours of unedited videotape of Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony
detailing his relationship with Monica Lewinsky was broadcast
nationally Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., the House
Judiciary Committee's decision to release the tape as ``very
partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we would show more nonpartisanship that was
pledged,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., ranking Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, denounced the release of ``irrelevant, unnecessary
disclosure of salacious and lurid details'' meant to embarrass the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said it would have been more
appropriate to release the tape after the Judiciary Committee had
finished its inquiry into allegations that the president committed
perjury, abused his power and sought to obstruct justice in
covering up the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi called the release of the videotape ``a blatant political
move on the part of the Republican leadership in the House to
further humiliate the president over an affair that he has already
admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What President Clinton did was wrong,'' Pelosi added. ``It is
grounds for embarrassment, not for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee voted Friday to release the tape and
2,800 pages of documents despite strong opposition from Democrats
on the committee. The vote came a week after the House released
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report detailing the
allegations that Clinton committed impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael McCurry blamed the release on
``rank partisanship,'' and said most of the material being made
public was irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the president's conduct does not rise to the level of an
impeachable offense should now be clear to everyone,'' McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican members of the Judiciary Committee, which will
recommend to the House whether Clinton should be impeached, gave a
harsher review of the videotape and its possible repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said the videotape ``showed the
president doing what he does best, being a very smooth talker.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said some parts of the tape ``do not put the president in
a good light'' because ``they do show him avoiding answering
questions and show him giving answers that are long and
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton read a statement describing his relationship with
Lewinsky as involving ``sexual banter'' and ``inappropriate
intimate contact,'' but refused to go into further detail. At one
point, when asked directly if he had had oral sex with Lewinsky,
Clinton declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the tape also shows the president suspected it might
be made public because most of his responses sound like ``he was
giving a political speech, rather than answering questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith defended the committee's decision to make public Clinton's
testimony, saying ``I assume it's always better to give people the
most complete picture possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican on the panel, Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla.,
said if it is determined Clinton lied under oath, he should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe if the president lied under oath, that is an
impeachable offense,'' Canady said. ``If he commits perjury before
a grand jury he has violated his oath and he has breached his duty
under the Constitution, and I believe that justifies impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The president ``understands the obligation to tell the truth and
the whole truth,'' Canady said. ``And we'll have to make a judgment
about whether he has done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Calif., a former judge who is also a
member of the judiciary panel, was more reserved.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said he was ``disturbed'' by the videotape, but said the
panel has an obligation to ``still give him (Clinton) the benefit
of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a former U.S. attorney
who has repeatedly called for the impeachment of the president,
said the videotape showed Clinton committing a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``After viewing this videotape, no reasonable person could
conclude that the president did not knowingly lie to the grand jury
to the court in the underlying lawsuit,'' said Barr, another member
of the Judiciary panel. ``This is a classic case of perjury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
