<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHASTA LAKE OFFERS SOME INCOMPARABLE FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE BAY, Calif. _ An osprey zoomed overhead, locked its
wings, then angled and dive-bombed the lake, like an F-14 on
maneuvers. The bird came hurtling down and hit the water with a
tremendous splash _ and a second later, it lifted off, a rainbow
trout in its talons.
</P>
<P>
   I only hoped our fishing luck could be scarcely as good.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm evening at Shasta Lake, the water emerald green
and still, broken only by occasional pools from schooling shad
minnows. This is the magic that fishermen and ospreys alike yearn
for all year: Those schooling minnows can activate trout and other
fish into feeding frenzies.
</P>
<P>
   Already, it had started, as the osprey had demonstrated. The
result has been some of the best catches of the year at any lake in
California, not only for osprey, but for fishermen as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Miralles, tackle inventor and guide, had four straight
trips last week where he took 11 people, who caught (and mostly
released) a total of 173 trout, with consecutive days of 32, 38, 45
and 58. That averages out to nearly 16 per person, with the trout
averaging 16 inches, the biggest going 20 inches (caught by my
partner, Stephani Cruickshank), along with a monster fish that was
battled for 20 minutes, but turned out to be an 11-pound squawfish.
And then there was the huge one I had.
</P>
<P>
   You see, when the shad minnows start schooling, everything
starts to bite. At Shasta, that adds up to mind-boggling numbers of
fish, with 22 species here, highlighted by rainbow trout and
spotted bass, but sprinkled with some huge brown trout, including
one we've named Mo. There are even salmon, catfish and sturgeon,
though Mr. Sturgy is often only hooked by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the trout. They love nothing more than shad. That is
why Miralles has invented the Humdinger lure, which is designed to
simulate shad. That is also why the blue-silver and black-silver
patterns work so well in September and October, when shad are
schooling and the trout will approach from below, then attack with
short bursts at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   At Bridge Bay, we launched the boat with Miralles, and then
cruised toward the dam, stopping to troll on the outside the mouths
of small bays.
</P>
<P>
   The shad have been schooling 20 to 35 feet deep, occasionally
making for the surface, so we set up our Scotty downriggers to put
the lures at 40, 60 and 80 feet deep, so they would ``swim'' just
under the schools of baitfish. Note that as cooler nights and even
the first light rains of fall arrive, there is always a period
where all the shad _ and the trout chasing them _ will come right
to the surface, providing the wildest fishing of the year.
</P>
<P>
   That is still to come.
</P>
<P>
   We had fished only 15 minutes when Stephani had that 20-inch
rainbow trout that did everything but get off; zig, zag, dive, jump
and finally, it rushed right into the net. In the next 20 minutes,
Jeremy, 10, got a beauty, and then it was Kris, 7, with another.
The fish just kept biting. They can't help it. The shad are too
much to resist.
</P>
<P>
   It was just before sunset when I finally hooked a big one. It
wasn't Mo, but maybe it was Son of Mo. The big ones often swirl
right on top after being hooked, maybe even give you a tail splash,
then burrow deep on a power dive, and there's nothing you can do
but hold on and pray that the hook holds. And so it was, complete
with prayers, with my rod pulled down like a croquet hoop.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes, the fish came back up to the surface, maybe 45
feet off to the side of the boat, where you could see a small
V-wake from his head and tail, and estimate its length; yeah, at
least a 20, 21-incher, likely bigger, maybe 24.
</P>
<P>
   It was so big that everybody aboard got quiet. The fish was
swimming lateral to the boat now, about 30 feet off, maybe had a
power dive or two left, but then, I figured, it would be in the
net, mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Miralles said, pointing skyward. ``Here comes an
osprey.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, another sharp-eyed predator was coming in like an
F-14, then angled to get a better look at my fish. Hey, I thought,
you've got to be kidding, this fish is way too big for any bird.
</P>
<P>
   But out of the corner of the fish's eye, the trout must have got
a glimpse of that osprey. Because right when that bird was
overhead, the big trout vaulted backwards over his tail, a complete
back flip _ never seen anything like it _ and then burrowed
straight down deep into water. Somewhere amid this circus act, the
hook came out. And yep, that big fish kept right on going.
</P>
<P>
   The osprey just flew on, still looking for dinner, and I stood
there on the boat, my rod now featherlight with the fish gone, with
this empty feeling that only comes when the big one gets away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information about Shasta Lake, phone guide Gary Miralles at
530-275-2278 or Shasta Cascade at 800-474-2782.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SAFINA-SHARKS-ART     09-21 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SAFINA-SHARKS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to change.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He paused. The engine and radio were off. The only sounds were
the gurgle of the chum bucket and the lapping of low waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partly,'' he added about his book, ``I wanted people to feel a
sense of outrage, to know that the people being paid to guard the
hen house are foxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to fishery regulators, who set quotas and are often
seen as cozy with big business, he said: ``They mostly got better
than they deserved. There was much worse that could have been
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Safina was born on May 23, 1955, to a middle-class family
in New York City. When he was 10, his family moved to suburban Long
Island, and his father took him often to its pebbly north shore for
striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that my father and I, with our secret fishing spot,
were very, very lucky,'' he recalled in his book. ``The arrival of
the bulldozers on our shoreline was an unfathomable catastrophe. In
a youngster's world view, the country map is small. Loss of my
beach amounted to expatriation. And no one is so long-remembering
as a refugee.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, he watched as ripples of development spread.
Eventually they moved through the distant fishing grounds he had
come to love off Long Island. In growing alarm, he studied ecology
throughout the 1980s, earning a doctorate from Rutgers in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A turning point came in 1989 while he was fishing about 50 miles
south of Fire Island, off Long Island. The bluefin tuna were thick,
and armadas of fishermen were doing everything in their power to
catch the shimmering gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were getting ridiculous amounts,'' he recalled.
``Somebody got on the radio and said, `Guys, maybe we should leave
some for tomorrow.' Another guy came on and said, `Hey, they didn't
leave any buffalo for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   That image came to haunt Safina.
</P>
<P>
   In his work and writings, he began to refer to global
overfishing as ``the last buffalo hunt,'' a phrase that eventually
joined the lexicon of marine conservation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s he dedicated himself to reversing the trend, mainly
by using his scientific and persuasive skills in the field of
fishery regulation and management. While often succeeding, Safina
had his share of frustrations and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In summer 1993, he set aside his routine by leaving Islip, where
he lived and worked, and renting a room at the Montauk marina where
he kept his boat. There he meditated. Day and night he pored over
notes and ideas, occasionally taking a breather by going out to
sea. Eventually he hit on a book plan that excited him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to preach outside the choir,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   A labor of love, the book recounts his travels to 18 shorelines
around the globe and profiles ongoing battles between fish and
people. The sites, which double as chapter titles, include Ogunquit
in Maine, Yachats in Oregon, Malakal in Palau and Sulu in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   In Sulu, he stumbled into armed battles between local warlords
fighting for political dominance, and at times feared for his life
as he investigated how communities of poor fisherman are trying to
kick the deadly habit of poisoning coral reefs. When squirted into
reefs, sodium cyanide _ the same stuff used to kill prisoners _
stuns fish and allows easy catches, mainly for the aquarium trade.
But corals subsequently die.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific is widely scarred by such poisoning. But in Sulu, a
tropical archipelago that forms the southern flank of the
Philippines, some local fishermen are trying to unlearn
self-defeating chemical tricks and instead make a living with nets
and traps. Safina dived with the men on a reef scarred by cyanide
poisoning and dynamite blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One trainee works for 10 minutes to entrap a single emperor
angelfish,'' he wrote. ``He finally succeeds, carefully removing
the struggling blue booty from the net and slipping it into his
mesh-topped bucket. This little emperor is worth about $12 to him.
Someone in the U.S. will pay about $150 to acquire it.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is often melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   Safina said its title, ``Song for the Blue Ocean,'' reflects not
only the sea's color but also its not-so-obvious state of decline.
Despite the blues, he added, his own song for the ocean contains
hints of optimism. One of his refrains is that the sea has huge
regenerative powers.
</P>
<P>
   He checked off recent successes in fisheries restraint,
crediting the increasingly large and feisty alliance of
environmental groups and sports fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accomplished some real long shots that we had every
reason to be pessimistic about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, after an extended lull, a large school of skipjacks
broke the surface, offering a tantalizing opportunity for Safina,
the sport fisherman, raw and undisguised. He had no tags for small
game.
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed his tuna rod and cast hard, the bright lure falling
into the agitated water that marked the school's leading edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish on,'' he said with a grin as the rod bent over.
</P>
<P>
   He reeled in a glistening, 20-inch skipjack, its sides a rainbow
of colors, its back electric blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very pretty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While still in the water beside the boat, the handsome fish
slipped off the hook and sped away.
</P>
<P>
   Safina looked on contentedly. Earlier, he had used a file to
remove the hook's barb as part of his inconspicuous war on the
mentality of excess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
