<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REVIEW-525&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-21 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENCORE! ENCORE!' AND `THE HUGHLEYS': REGAL AIRS ON NBC, UPWARD
MOBILITY ON ABC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most sitcoms about families pretend to be connected to real
life, though the link is tenuous. Two brash new comedies competing
head to head Tuesday night position themselves on either side of
that big, banal middle ground where most series live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encore! Encore!'' with Nathan Lane as an opera star who
returns home to his California family, is played as farce, a
larger-than-life romp. ``The Hughleys,'' about a successful black
businessman who moves his family to a white-bread suburb, focuses
its wit on the realistic issue of upward mobility, a subject rarely
seen on screen. They are among a handful of shows that deserve to
break out of this season's mediocre pack, and choosing between the
two of them comes down to personal taste, not quality.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode of ``Encore! Encore!'' was recast and reshot,
leading to word that the series was on its deathbed. That is just
where the hero seems to be in the opening scene. Lane, as an opera
star named Joe Pinoni, lies in an Italian hospital wearing his
clown costume from ``Pagliacci.'' His vocal cords have been damaged
by emergency treatment he received after eating a bad clam. ``He
was going to be the Fourth Tenor; now he may never sing again,''
says the doctor (in Italian with English subtitles). He instantly
establishes the series' knowing, self-dramatizing tone, which is
like no other on television and which suits the Pinoni family
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe returns to the winery his family owns, he arrives
dropping names like Placido and Luciano, and expecting his sister
to pay the limo driver. Yet he seems endearingly needy. ``Encore!
Encore!'' takes full advantage of Lane's talent for creating
flamboyant, theatrical characters (in films like ``The Birdcage''
and onstage in ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum'').
He and his co-stars, Joan Plowright and Glenne Headly, form the
most accomplished, high-powered cast on television.
</P>
<P>
   We soon see where Joe's over-the-top personality came from. As
his mother, Ms. Plowright sweeps in and out of rooms with
deliciously regal flair, though her logic is sometimes addled. She
has a common-sensical side that she has passed on to her daughter,
Francesca (Ms. Headly), who runs the winery. The high-culture
allusions and the whiff of an ``Upstairs, Downstairs'' split
between Joe and his modest sister are reminders that this series
was created by the producers of ``Frasier,'' another series that
happily flaunts its lovable snobs.
</P>
<P>
   Some running jokes are overplayed, like Mrs. Pinoni's hobby of
attending strangers' funerals. Then there is the ongoing joke about
Joe's womanizing. When he asks his mother if her neighbors have any
voluptuous daughters, she responds with a pointed line (too good to
step on here), which hints that this theme may not be played
entirely straight.
</P>
<P>
   Though the first show is surprisingly funny, ``Encore! Encore!''
is clearly in flux. Next week's episode is already too predictable,
as Joe and Francesca get reacquainted, leading to many eruptions of
sibling rivalry. But the cast members are such fun to watch, they
can carry the series while it finds its footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys'' arrives firmly tethered to reality, its humor
in place, with barbed remarks that make gentle fun of both black
culture and the foreign territory in which the family has landed.
Stand-up comedian D.L. Hughley plays the fictional Darryl Hughley,
who owns a vending machine company and has moved with his wife and
two children a few miles and a lifetime of experience away from the
all-black Los Angeles neighborhood in which he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   On his first morning in the new house, Darryl goes outside to
get the mail and is accosted by the little old lady next door, who
asks him to take out her trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady, who do I look like, Benson?'' Darryl asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you very much, Benson,'' she says, and disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the show, Darryl's petulance and tendency to see
everything in racial terms is tempered by his wife, Yvonne (Elise
Neal), who makes a smoother transition to their new neighborhood.
``She tells everyone to fetch her trash; she's 88,'' Yvonne says of
the neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   But Darryl fears that his childhood friend Milsap (John Henton)
is right when he warns, ``You on the slippery slope to losing your
blackness.'' Milsap sees Darryl paying his bills on time and
wonders, ``Who are you?''; Yvonne quickly reassures Darryl that
they have always paid their bills on time. ``The Hughleys'' is at
its best when it toys with stereotypes this way, acknowledging and
shattering them with shrewd humor.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley brings just enough of an edge to Darryl, who sometimes
acts like a baby yet is ultimately a reasonable guy. The danger is
that ``The Hughleys'' might lose that edge and give in to typical
sitcom solutions. At the end of Tuesday night's episode, Darryl
overcomes his suspicion that his neighbor Dave is a bigot. Dave
says he thinks of Darryl as ``the n-word: neighbor,'' which seems
too pat. Like its hero, ``The Hughleys'' may be at risk of
surrendering its soul to the comfy land of ``Home Improvement''
(the show it follows on ABC).
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are more hopeful signs than danger signals in this
engaging series. Chris Rock, one of its executive producers, has
stated his affection for ``The Jeffersons,'' the original sitcom
about an upwardly mobile black family that kept its roots alive.
When Milsap enters the Hughley home and sings, ``Movin' on up,''
from the Jeffersons' theme, he might as well be declaring that
``The Hughleys'' plans a long, successful stay.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ENCORE! ENCORE!'
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m. Tuesdays on NBC
</P>
<P>
   David Angell, Peter Casey, David Lee, Anne Flett-Giordano and
Chuck Ranberg, executive producers and creators; Valerie Curtin and
Jon Sherman, producers; produced by Mary Fukuto; Bruce Miller,
theme and music composer. A production of Grub Street Productions
in association with Paramount Network Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Nathan Lane (Joe Pinoni), Joan Plowright (Marie Pinoni),
Glenne Headly (Francesca Pinoni), Trevor Fehrman (Michael), Ernie
Sabella (Leo) and James Patrick Stuart (Claude).
</P>
<P>
   `THE HUGHLEYS'
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m. Tuesdays on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Matt Wickline, Michael Rotenberg, Dave Becky, David Janollari,
Bob Greenblatt and Chris Rock, executive producers. A production of
Greenblatt/Janollari Studio.
</P>
<P>
   With: D.L. Hughley (Darryl Hughley), Elise Neal (Yvonne
Hughley), Ashley Monique Clark (Sydney Hughley), Dee Jay Daniels
(Michael Hughley), Eric Allan Kramer (Dave Rogers), John Henton
(Milsap) and Marietta DePrima (Sally Rogers).
</P>
</TEXT>
