<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CHRISTIAN SLATER ON BROADWAY; MUSEUM THEFT IN
FRANCE; VINDICATION FOR NUREYEV; CHINESE OPERA IN PARIS CANCELED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christian Slater is coming to Broadway, to assume the
demanding role of Clifford in Warren Leight's acclaimed memory
play, ``Side Man,'' for at least three months when it reopens on
Oct. 20 at the Golden Theater. Slater has appeared in films like
``Broken Arrow'' and ``Hard Rain'' and on and off-Broadway in works
like the 1978 production of ``Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   He will replace Robert Sella, who created the role of Clifford,
whose reunion with his jazzman father triggers memories of a
chaotic childhood. Sella has moved to ``Cabaret'' to play the MC.
</P>
<P>
   Stolen Goods
</P>
<P>
   Two hooded gunmen made off on Monday with two impressionist
paintings after invading the home of Jean Fournis, the curator of
the Fine Arts Museum of Nice, France, and forcing him to take them
into the museum, where they overpowered guards. The paintings,
``The Cliffs of Dieppe,'' by Claude Monet, and ``The Alley of the
Poplars,'' by Alfred Sisley, were on loan from the government. The
culture minister, Catherine Trautmann, said both paintings were so
widely known that they would be impossible to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Aftermath
</P>
<P>
   Five years after his death, Rudolf Nureyev has been restored to
the political good graces of Russia. Deputy Prosecutor General
Alexander Zviyaguintsev announced Monday that the ballet dancer,
who was sentenced to seven years in prison in his native Soviet
Union when he defected to France in 1961, had been posthumously
rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law regarding victims of political reprisals, Nureyev
was deemed not guilty of the crimes for which he was convicted. He
was a star of the Kirov Ballet in St. Petersburg, then known as
Leningrad, when he sought asylum on his first trip abroad. He did
not return home for 25 years. He died in Paris at age 54.
</P>
<P>
   Again, No
</P>
<P>
   Autumn in Paris is going to be like summer in New York: no
``Peony Pavilion.'' The Paris Autumn Festival announced Monday that
the Chinese authorities had forbidden the Shanghai Kunqu Opera
Company's production of the 19-hour, 55-scene 16th-century work to
leave for performances in France in November and December.
</P>
<P>
   The festival announced, ``Despite the many endeavors made by the
Paris Autumn Festival and French authorities at the very highest
level, the Shanghai Municipal Culture Bureau, which triggered the
last-minute cancellation of the first performances scheduled in
July of this year at the Lincoln Center Festival in New York, has
maintained its opposition to the production and made it impossible
for the 53 members of the Shanghai Kunqu Company to come to
France.'' Cultural officials in Shanghai deemed the production
``ideologically unsuitable and pornographic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
