<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOHL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN TV DELETES GRAPHIC DETAILS FROM CLINTON TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Two of Germany's national television
networks said Monday that they would not broadcast the most sordid
sections of President Clinton's videotaped testimony, while
Chancellor Helmut Kohl said the release of the tapes ``makes me
vomit.''
</P>
<P>
   NTV, a commercial television news network, announced that it
would replay most of the testimony but would delete the most
``intimate'' and most sexually explicit details.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, a public channel that carries speeches and other public
proceedings, interrupted its transmission of the testimony for live
coverage of Clinton's speech at the United Nations. Network
officials said that they would carry only testimony that did not
``violate ethical and journalistic standards.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Germans who wanted to watch the full testimony had
to listen in English to broadcasts on either CNN and BBC World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will carry four hours of testimony tonight,'' Bernd
Schwintowski, a spokesman for the NTV network in Berlin, said
Monday, ``but when the testimony goes into the private sphere or
the most intimate details of private life, we will not transmit
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwintowski said the network's decision had not been the result
of pressure from Kohl or other German politicians, virtually all of
whom said they were revolted by the release of the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure was nevertheless intense, and several political
leaders openly assailed broadcasters who planned to carry the
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me vomit,'' said Kohl in Bonn on Monday morning. In
an interview on Sunday with the newspaper Die Welt, Kohl expressed
deep sadness and sympathy for Clinton. ``I think the whole thing is
a catastrophe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunda Roestel, a top official in the Green Party who is on the
advisory board of the publicly owned ZDF television network, openly
tried to prevent the Phoenix channel from carrying the testimony.
Phoenix is jointly owned by ZDF and ARD, Germany's other main
public television network.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roestel, asserting that the Phoenix channel would become ``a
voyeur to a political smear campaign,'' appealed to ZDF executives
to block the Phoenix transmission. It was unclear if the pressure
caused Phoenix to change its plans, but the network did break away
from the live transmission shortly after it began.
</P>
<P>
   Oskar Lafontaine, chairman of the opposition Social Democratic
Party, found himself in rare harmony with Kohl. Lafontaine said
that release of the tapes was ``disgusting and revolting.'' He said
that he hoped the American spectacle would ignite a new discussion
about the need for public officials to retain a sphere of privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
