<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and less humid air will enter the Northeast and Middle
Atlantic States Tuesday as a strong cold front pushes toward the
Atlantic Seaboard. Showers will precede the front in eastern New
England in the morning while interior sections will experience
gusty breezes from the north. A secondary disturbance in the wake
of the front will cause a few sprinkles over the mountains of
northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will also cover the upper Midwest and Northern Plains
as the ridge of high pressure representing the center of the
Canadian air mass builds toward Lake Michigan. The flow of
unseasonably cool air over the relatively warm waters of the Great
Lakes will instigate a few showers over northern Michigan while
much of Minnesota and North Dakota are graced by ample sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between the cool air mass to the north and tropical
air to the south will be the focus for showers and thunderstorms
from Virginia to Oklahoma. Over the interior Deep South, hazy
sunshine and high humidity will be punctuated by only isolated
thundershowers. Downpours associated with a weak trough will douse
much of Florida and the central Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Winds ascending the sloping terrain in the foothills of the
central Rockies will result in some showers over Wyoming and
Colorado. Elsewhere, much of the West will be seasonable with ample
sunshine. The exception will be the immediate California coast
where low clouds will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges, with winds up to 110 miles an hour will skirt
the northern coast of Hispaniola.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Wall
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Hurricane Georges weakened as it approached the
invisible wall near longitude 60 degrees that frequently guards the
Caribbean Sea. It is here that westward moving tropical storms and
hurricanes can lose substantial strength as clashing high-altitude
winds interfere with the storm's delicate structure. The wall is a
zone of wind shear created by winds blowing from the east around
the high pressure system in the Atlantic and westerly winds
produced by a high pressure system that develops over hot northern
South America. Upon hitting the wall, a hurricane can literally be
pulled apart. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
