u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INTERNET22-CO     09-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERNET22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet access to Clinton testimony a crash course in
programsBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet users who tried to access President Clinton's grand
jury testimony Monday might have felt as though they'd been through
a grueling four-hour ordeal themselves _ even if they were only
online for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That's because unlike the Starr Report which was simply text,
the President's videotaped testimony required a great deal of
bandwidth _ a measure of how fast data can be delivered on the Web.
By comparison, the entire 445-page Starr report fit on a single
floppy disk, while about one minute of video would fill a single
floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   So, users logging on to the Net yesterday encountered words like
plug-in, NetShow, RealVideo buffer, streaming and ``connection
lost'' as they got a crash course in the advantages and drawbacks
of online video and how far the Web still has to go before
streaming video becomes as common as e-mail or on-demand stock
quotes.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m., it was fairly easy to log onto the Web sites of the
major news organizations streaming (the Web version of
broadcasting) the video. All Web sites had printed notices
indicating the testimony contained graphic sexual content that
might not be appropriate for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   When users choose to see the video, if they've downloaded the
proper plug in a pop-up screen supplied by RealVideo or Microsoft's
NetShow will download and then display the video and accompanying
audio.
</P>
<P>
   AccessAtlanta (http://www.accessatlanta.com) offered the
complete text of the speech as well as highlights of the testimony.
MSNBC.com embedded the video-plug in within its homepage, making it
hard for users to tell if the video was loading or not.
</P>
<P>
   But there were a range of problems accompanying the live,
streaming video, ranging from choppy pictures to video streams
abruptly closing down with an error message appearing on the screen
saying the ``connection to the server'' had been lost. To return to
the video, users had to reload the program, which required a small
amount of wait time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to understand in the offline, analog world, we
interact seamlessly between video, graphics and text,'' says
Jupiter Communications analyst Ross Rubin. ``but when you make
those things digital you have very different requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin says the video testimony served as a sharp contrast to
last week's release of the Starr Report over the Web. ``It goes a
long way toward showing the strengths and weaknesses of the Web as
a distribution medium,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a text-based info such as the Starr Report the web can
meet that need. However, when you talk about rich media text-based
medium, such as video, the Web as it exists today is ill-equipped
to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What works best on the video side is talking heads,'' says CNN
Interactive spokesman Kerrin Roberts. CNN.com is using InterVU,
Broadcast.com and Real Broadcast Network to help serve the live and
on-demand versions of the video. ``InterVU has confirmed that
between 9 a.m. and 11:30 a.m. that the video has been accessed more
than 200,000 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also said that at 11 a.m. Monday nearly 9,500 users were
simultaneously accessing the testimony. CNN also provided an
audio-only version which had about 2,600 users at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, who heads Jupiter's Web technologies group says the
combination of user demand and the Web being unequipped to serve
real time video on demand was the cause of most users' problems.
``Even in the best of traffic conditions on a dial-up connection,
the experience is going to be far inferior to television,'' he
says, adding that the audio portions of the testimony were
excellent quality because both RealAudio and Microsoft have been
making steady advances in Web audio technology.
</P>
<P>
   He says a small black and white Sony Watchman is probably a
better viewing experience, since the frame speed stays fairly even.
``There's only so much you can do with limited bandwidth,'' says
Rubin of the video troubles. ''Most of the Web video usage we are
seeing today is from people who don't have any other way of
accessing the information.''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-day MSNBC, CNN and others had compiled a ``highlights''
page of video and text, which featured audio in smaller snippets
and complete text in a variety of formats. While not as
cutting-edge as the real-time streaming testimony which was
simultaneously available, these presentations were easier to access
and view. MSNBC.com reported heavy but not record breaking
activity.
</P>
<P>
   For those with neither the time, the inclination nor the
appropriate equipment to view the testimony, CNN's sister Web site
All Politics (http://www.allpolitics.com) was offering an ongoing,
minute by minute summary of the main points of Clinton's testimony.
All that was needed to access that site was a Web browser. National
Public Radio also made an audio version available later in the day
on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   America Online offered live video streaming and a chat room for
users to discuss the testimony. By mid-afternoon Monday, more than
10,000 AOL users had posted comments about the live testimony,
which concluded around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
