<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton basked in thunderous
applause at the United Nations on Monday, wary Americans watched
unedited videotape of a pained, embarrassed and combative Clinton
testifying before independent counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury
about his sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. The unprecedented programming produced a mix of
amusement, ridicule and condemnation and hardened the lines drawn
on Capitol Hill over whether the president should be impeached.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ WASHINGTON _ In a bizarre display of parallel
presidential universes, President Clinton addresses the United
Nations General Assembly even as his grand jury testimony is being
broadcast to the nation. Clinton's speech and the scene around him.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAPE _ WASHINGTON _ Americans saw President Clinton
portray himself Monday as a victim of his political foes as he fell
back on tortured legalisms to dodge perjury charges in his
videotaped grand jury testimony. But Clinton's historic, unscripted
four-hour ordeal before a tag team of federal prosecutors left
viewers with no ``smoking gun'' that would clearly lead Congress to
remove him from office. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONICA _ WASHINGTON _ When a friend e-mailed that she'd
lost weight, Monica Lewinsky was properly enthusiastic. ``Okay. I
hate you ...You little-size-6-bitch,'' Lewinsky replied. ``I don't
know if I can be friends with you anymore!!!!! That's nice. I'm a
10-12 so that makes me double your size.'' The portrait of Monica
Lewinsky that evolves in more than 3,000 pages of grand jury
testimony, e-mails, handwritten notes and other documentation
complied by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is that of a young
woman who is sometimes funny, sad, naive, saavy, manipulative,
manipulated, likeable, loathsome, perhaps promiscous but always
profoundly human. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ How Democrats and Republicans in
Congress react to Monday's release of evidence. (Carr, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NEW _ WASHINGTON _ What's new in the 3,183 pages of
evidence released Monday. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WORDS _ WASHINGTON _ The videotaped testimony released
Monday shows President Clinton struggling to define words such as
``sexual relations,'' ``alone'' and even ``is'' in ways that
support his contention that he did not commit perjury. (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAPITAL _ WASHINGTON _ The President's testimony
reverberated through congressional offices Monday morning, but the
rest of the nation's capital was hardly moved by the historic
occasion. At breakfast buffets, barber shops, college campuses and
department stores, few D.C. residents were glued to the tube
anxiously watching their commander in chief under fire. ``I'm fed
up with it,'' said William Ransford, who is a D.C. native and has
worked at the famous Mayflower Hotel for 20 years as a housekeeper.
``How many times is a man going to apologize? I don't want to see
it. This makes him look weak. This makes our country look
disunited,'' he said. (Moscoso and Monroe, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-E-MAIL _ WASHINGTON _ The Starr evidence released Monday
made clear that e-mail, like the telephone, is not a medium for
those who wish their words to remain private. What ordinary people
should know about e-mail. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV _ Analysis of TV coverage of Clinton video, including
whether CBS went with the full 4-hour version and comparisons
between CNN and the other nets. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET _ How did the internet deal with the onslaught
of four hours of Clinton's videotaped testimony and the 2800 pages
of other testimony? (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FORGIVENESS _ Lots of talk of forgiveness in the news,
but what does it really mean? Commentary by Paul Reid. (Reid, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EXPERTS _ What do the professionals _ speech
communication, political and legal types _ say about the Clinton
testimony. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WISDOM _ The wisdom of our senior citizens could be very
valuable in this situation. We visit senior citizens center to talk
with people who may have the luxury of time and have the
institutional experience to put this in context with previous
presidents and standards of decency. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
