<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WALKS INTO STARR'S `PERJURY TRAP,' ATTORNEYS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton may have sealed his fate last
summer when he took the ill-advised step of agreeing not only to
testify before a federal grand jury but to have that testimony
videotaped, according to leading defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton walked right into independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
``perjury trap,'' said William Moffitt, president-elect of the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``No matter what
he did or no matter what he said, Mr. Starr was going to accuse him
of perjury,'' the Washington attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   It is just the nature of the system.
</P>
<P>
   Grand juries belong to the prosecutor. Normally, no defense
attorneys are permitted to be present, although in Clinton's unique
case his personal attorney, David Kendall, was allowed to attend as
Starr and his staff asked intimate questions about the president's
extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour videotape of Clinton's testimony _ aired worldwide
Monday _ shows Clinton testy at times over repeated questions about
specifics details of his relationship with Lewinsky, a former White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The president also appeared to be distinctly uncomfortable as he
sought to explain how his responses in a January deposition denying
a sexual relationship with Lewinsky were legally accurate. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Moffitt said that Clinton, himself a licensed attorney and
one-time law professor, should have abided by the lesson any
first-year law student knows: The last place the target of a
criminal investigation wants to be is before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're in there, you're at the mercy of a prosecutor,''
Moffitt said. ``There's no one there to protect you.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the idea of being videotaped _ every bead of sweat
and nervous tic recorded for posterity _ and it is enough to make a
defense attorney's ``skin crawl,'' Moffitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Those warnings of legal doom usually work with the average
criminal defendant, but the president of the United States is
unlike any other client. He is concerned not only with staying out
of legal jeopardy but preserving his place in history, and that can
be a dangerous mix for the client and his attorney, said Larry
Pozner, president of the lawyers' group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, fearing it would seem unpresidential to be seen walking
into a federal courthouse, agreed to testify via a closed-circuit
television link from the White House to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envy his lawyers as they try to protect a citizen
under investigation while simultaneously serving the president of
the United States whose constituency is everyone in the country,''
said Pozner, a Denver defense attorney. ``I don't want that problem
on my desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Kent Schaffer, president of the Texas Criminal
Defense Lawyers Association, said Clinton's appearance before the
grand jury could have been avoided. The American people would have
understood had Clinton refused to testify or asserted his
constitutional right against self incrimination, Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an adversary like Kenneth Starr who's made a
goal out of ruining your life ... the smart thing to do is use the
constitutional protection that has been given to you,'' Schaffer
said. ``Who among us would not squirm at the type of questions that
were asked?''
</P>
<P>
   But, Schaffer noted, Clinton is unlike any client the veteran
defense attorney has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law doesn't apply,'' Schaffer said. ``Only the law of
politics (applies) in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
