<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LESINSKY'S LIVELY PERONALITY EMERGES IN TESTIMONY, E-MAIL
 &HT;    600&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Eds: Material throughout may offend some readers.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a friend lost weight, Monica Lewinsky was
properly enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay. I hate you ... You little-size-6-bitch,'' Lewinsky wrote
by e-mail. ``I don't know if I can be friends with you anymore!!!!!
That's nice. I'm a 10-12 so that makes me double your size.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky portrayed in 3,183 pages of grand jury testimony,
e-mails, love notes and other evidence complied by Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr is a young woman by turns funny and sad,
naive and savvy, manipulative and manipulated, likeable and
loathsome, and profane and promiscuous _ but always profoundly
human.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly built a rapport with the grand jury hearing her
testimony about her White House affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica, none of us in this room are perfect,'' one juror
reassures her. ``We all fall and we fall several times a day. The
only difference between my age and when I was your age is now I get
up faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The star witness had asked the jurors to call her ``Monica''
rather than ``Miss Lewinsky,'' explaining, ``I'm just 25.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll always be Miss Lewinsky, whether you're 25 or 28 or
...,'' a juror pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if I get married,'' she popped back hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   In the e-mail correspondence with Catherine Davis, a longtime
friend who was living in Japan, Lewinsky emerges as a realist as
well as a romantic _ and clearly a member of a younger generation
than the Baby Boomer president entering his 50s.
</P>
<P>
   She jokes that Clinton can't comprehend that her telephone
caller ID displays ``POTUS'' (president of the United States) when
he calls, and seems proud of himself when he finds a White House
phone that fools the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeez, I hate being called 'dear','' she complains to ``Cat.''
``The creep calls me that sometimes. It's an old person's
saying!!!!''
</P>
<P>
   In pressuring the president for help in finding a job in New
York, she said a news position at MTV would be nice or ``anything
at George magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't as lovestruck as she appeared to be Starr's summary
to Congress. While she professed to love the president, Lewinsky
hardly pined away in her Watergate apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I tell you I had sex with Thomas last week,'' she said in
a 1997 e-mail. ``I know. I am so naughty ... I went over there with
some ice cream and pretty much seduced him in a way that made him
put the moves on me ... cool or what???''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good time at the spa (I did it with the nutrition
guy)!!!!'' she writes another time. ``I kinda don't want to get
into the juicies on e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   She anticipates going to a black tie gala where ``hopefully
we'll meet some interesting people. A cute boy would be VERY
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Weight came up nearly as often as sex in Lewinsky's world.
Indeed, she said her extra pounds are the reason she never cleaned
the infamous semen-stained dress that provided genetic proof of her
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained weight so I couldn't wear the dress and it didn't
fit. And I'm not a very organized person. I don't clean my clothes
until I'm going to wear them again,'' she told the grand jury. When
she dropped a few pounds, she remembered the dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't keep the dress as a souvenir. I was going to wear it
on Thanksgiving and my cousins, who I always try to look skinny for
because they are all skinny,'' she said. But Linda Tripp _ who
brought the affair to Starr's attention and gave him tapes of phone
calls in which Lewinsky discussed it _ discouraged her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brought me one of her jackets from her thinner closet,''
Lewinsky recalled cattily.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors questioned Lewinsky diligently, but over the
weeks of her testimony they seemed to grow more personable and
sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you still love the president?'' one juror asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Monday, I would have said yes,'' Lewinsky, referring to
Aug. 17, when Clinton addressed the nation after being interrogated
by Starr. `` It was very painful for me to watch his speech on
Monday night. It's hard for me to feel that he has characterized
this relationship as a service contract. ...That all I did was
perform oral sex on him and that that's all this relationship was.
And it was a lot more than that to me ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you and the president ever engage in sexual relations
using cigars?'' one juror asked gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay. I'd like to change the subject now,'' said the juror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' said Lewinsky. ``Just once. Just once.''
</P>
<P>
   One juror chided her that Clinton ``was a married man and it
wasn't no secret of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right to have an affair with a married man,''
Lewinsky admitted. ``I never expected to fall in love with the
president. I was surprised that I did.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Lewinsky had clearly established a rapport with the
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you won't have to come back her any more,'' the
foreperson told her. ``But we wanted to offer you a bouquet of good
wishes that include luck, success, happiness and blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
