<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMY-BEACH-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      09-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMY-BEACH-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IS IT ARTISTRY OR WISHFUL THINKING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In pretty much the same way that Shoeless Joe Jackson
and Roger Maris have fans who are passionately devoted to getting
their heroes into the Baseball Hall of Fame, Amy Beach has
advocates who are lobbying to place her in the pantheon of great
composers.
</P>
<P>
   Respected musicians have rallied to her cause: A few seasons
ago, Ransom Wilson conducted her chamber opera, ``Cabildo,'' at
Lincoln Center, and Dennis Russell Davies led the Brooklyn
Philharmonic in her titanic ``Gaelic'' Symphony. There have been
several recent recordings of her Grand Mass. And Joanne Polk, who
is currently recording all of Beach's piano music, offered
highlights at Merkin Concert Hall on Wednesday and Saturday
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons to cheer along this Beach revival. One is a
desire to extend American musical history from the Copland
generation backward into the 19th century. Beach fits that bill.
She lived from 1867 to 1944, established herself as a pianist and
composer before she was 18, composed prolifically _ her catalog
includes more than 300 works, most published under the name Mrs.
H.H.A. Beach _ and had works performed by major orchestras in her
lifetime. She is equally useful, of course, to anyone trying to
construct a repertory of female composers.
</P>
<P>
   But those reasons, however well-intentioned, are historical and
political, not musical, and if room is to be found in the standard
repertory for Beach's music, only musical reasons will matter. Her
time may come. But the recent spate of Beach performances,
including Ms. Polk's, suggest that it hasn't come yet.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Beach's music is without its charms. One
thing that was immediately clear in Ms. Polk's polished, assured
performances was the fluidity and facility with which Beach wrote
for the keyboard. Works like the ``Fantasia'' Fugata (Op. 87) and
the ``Tyrolean'' Valse-Fantasie (Op. 116) demand speed, agility and
the ability to project a grand, rich-textured sound.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Fantasia'' Fugata also showed several of Beach's more
endearing qualities. One is her sense of humor. Updating
Scarlatti's claim to have based one of his sonatas on the sound his
cat made while walking across his harpsichord, Beach said that she
created her fugue theme by placing her cat on the piano. Whether
she actually did is beside the point; the scampering dissonances in
the theme evoked a picture of a cat on the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   That was another of Beach's salient qualities: Here, and in the
Three Pieces (Op. 128) _ musical descriptions of a chipmunk, a
group of young birches and a hummingbird _ she proved to be an
estimable painter in sound.
</P>
<P>
   Several works made their appeal through simple, direct lyricism.
The Piano Quintet (Op. 67), in which Ms. Polk was supported
beautifully by the Lark Quartet, was rich and dark, with soaring
lines and inventive chord progressions. The same qualities
enlivened the Largo con Dolore movement of the Violin Sonata (Op.
34), in which Ms. Polk's able collaborator was Curtis Macomber.
</P>
<P>
   So, why not join the growing Beach appreciation society? There
were moments during Ms. Polk's concerts when the prospect was
tempting, but as those moments came and went, doubts about Beach
remained. It was impossible, for example, to sweep aside the sense
that the influences on her music too often overshadowed her own
voice.
</P>
<P>
   In work after work, one heard gestures borrowed from
Mendelssohn, Schumann, Chopin, Brahms and Strauss. There is also a
grandiose quality to Beach's music that rings false to
late-20th-century ears. Huge chordal flourishes, bombastic themes,
chordal figures running up and down the keyboard and other
varieties of sheer romantic steaminess were meant to make the music
majestic, yet beneath all the clatter, much of it was a not
particularly durable variety of salon music.
</P>
<P>
   If Beach's works cannot satisfy listeners' purely musical needs,
her historical use will be limited as well. Such are the
disappointments of musical excavation.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the turn-of-the-century American repertory, it may
be that the era did not produce much for today's listener; Beach's
music is no less interesting than that of, say, John Knowles Paine
or Horatio Parker.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of female composers, greater discoveries are being
made across the ocean. Hildegard von Bingen is now regarded as a
giant of her time, and Barbara Strozzi, an extraordinarily
inventive early baroque composer, awaits a fuller exploration that
is likely to yield far richer dividends than the current interest
in Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
