<HEADLINE>
IS IT OK FOR BOSS TO DEAL WITH HAIRY SITUATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. I supervise a female salesperson who has hair
that extends to the middle of her back. She is excellent at her job
and is always professionally dressed. However, she wears her hair
loose, and when she leans over to do anything, it covers her face.
Then she throws it over her shoulder in a very distracting manner.
She constantly plays with it when talking, and I have noticed that
strangers are distracted by this. I praise her when her hair is
braided, but this is not often. How should I approach her? M.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Unless you are actively seeking a hair-raising experience,
your best approach is not to approach her on this one. When you
meet with employees to discuss their personal habits or affections,
the most likely outcomes are defensiveness, resistance and
distress.
</P>
<P>
   By approaching her on this matter, you are in essence acting
like a parent and treating her like a child. As a manager, it makes
far more sense to act as an adult and treat your employees as
adults too. This means accepting their uniqueness and diversity,
and staying away from personal habits unless they are clearly
causing problems in terms of safety, health or performance.
</P>
<P>
   You have an excellent employee, and you are currently taking a
professional and adult approach by giving her positive feedback
when you feel that her hair is appropriate. This type of feedback
can have a strong motivational impact, and it may ultimately lead
to a close encounter with a hairstylist. In the meantime, do not
let her hair prevent you from seeing the many strengths that she
brings to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A week ago, I was called into a meeting with my direct
supervisor and her manager. I was shocked when her manager spent
the entire session criticizing me. Her comments were trivial and
had nothing to do with my main responsibilities. My supervisor sat
there and said nothing during the meeting or even afterward.
There's no one I can go to about this, so what should I do? A.P.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds like you are in an organization that is not
organized at all. Part of your direct supervisor's job is to
provide you with regular performance-based feedback so that
problems can be corrected when they occur, leading to no shocking
endings. Her lack of support during the meeting and afterward
raises even more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Feedback should not come from someone who is marginally familiar
with you and your work. And feedback should be premised on clear,
specific and measurable performance factors, and not on trivial
generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you should meet with your direct supervisor and
express your concern over what happened. Indicate that you do not
want a repeat performance, and then suggest that you meet with her
on a regular basis to review your work. Tell her that you would
like such reviews to be documented and included in your file, along
with any written accolades that you may receive.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the big picture, you were unjustly berated by a
senior manager, and your direct supervisor went into hiding. This
does not exactly qualify for one of America's most desirable
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our department was recently reorganized and a well-liked
employee was laid off very suddenly. She received no notice or
severance pay. That leaves the rest of us, approximately 70
employees, nervous about our ``here today, gone tomorrow'' jobs. Do
you have any advice for us? P.W.
</P>
<P>
   A. The real advice is for you to consider giving some advice to
your employer. It is important for your employer to understand
that, as a result of this isolated layoff, there has been a major
decline in trust, loyalty and commitment, combined with a major
increase in insecurity, anxiety and dissatisfaction. This can
further lead to increases in absenteeism and turnover, and
decreases in creativity and productivity.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the actual layoff that caused these problems, as many
companies implement layoffs for any number of legitimate business
reasons. The problem has been caused by the lack of communication
and support associated with the layoff, and the current lack of
information as to future employment objectives.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you and some of your associates should consider
meeting with management to let them know that although you
understand the rationale behind layoffs, the lack of information
regarding the company's plans in this area is creating widespread
problems, many of which could be solved through increased two-way
communication.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs are not pleasant for the employees who are let go, and
it is important for management to understand that they are not
automatically pleasant for the employees who remain.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
