<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6748 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-CANDIDATES-HNS &LR;      09-21 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CANDIDATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING RECORDS EASY TARGET IN CALIFORNIA RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Attorney General Dan Lungren and Sen.
Barbara Boxer stand on different ideological continents, but both
candidates have the same problem: They have records that can be
exploited.
</P>
<P>
   With just seven weeks before the Nov. 3 election, a parallel
dynamic has emerged in the race for California governor and U.S.
Senate, and it's an underground theme that will run through
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Voters can expect Lungren _ the Republican nominee for governor
_ and Boxer _ a Democrat seeking her second term in the Senate _ to
share a common campaign strategy by painting their opponents as
talkers, not doers, as politicians who have never made tough
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren and Boxer also can expect to get hit repeatedly for
their extensive records in Congress, where almost every vote is
posted on the Internet and special partisan committees in
Washington scour official records for political ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Those same records, sometimes distorted, helped savage the
candidacy of Rep. Jane Harman during the Democratic gubernatorial
primary against millionaire Al Checchi, who did most of the
distorting, and Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, who handily beat them both.
</P>
<P>
   It's a theme likely to be played out again Wednesday, when
Lungren and Davis meet in Sacramento for their third televised
debate. Mark Petracca, chairman of the political science department
at the University of California at Irvine, said Lungren's only
counterattack is to ``turn the record into a badge of honor by
saying, `You may not like all of the decisions I've made, but I've
been in a position for years to make the tough calls.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren and Boxer already have been using that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Davis repeatedly has attacked Lungren's record during the decade
he spent in Congress and his eight years as attorney general. And
Lungren has been hitting Davis for doing little while holding
administrative positions like state controller and lieutenant
governor, after serving a scant three years in the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the fact of the matter is, you keep talking and you never
act,'' Lungren pointedly told Davis during their second televised
debate on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   During the first debate, Lungren slammed Davis for missing a
meeting in Mexico of the California World Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't show up, you didn't send anybody there,'' Lungren
said. ``So, I mean, the question is: Do you just talk or are you
going to do something?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lungren ridiculed Davis for having ``17 employees and
nothing else to do.'' In fact, Lungren, who controls about 5,000
employees at the state Department of Justice, mentioned three times
that Davis employs only 17 people as lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise when Boxer met her opponent, state Treasurer Matt Fong,
for the first time in a debate, she carried the same theme, vaguely
deriding his public service when compared to her career in
Congress. A private attorney, Fong joined the Board of Equalization
in 1990, his first political post, and was elected state treasurer
in 1994. In the past 22 years, Boxer has been a Marin County
supervisor, member of the House of Representatives and senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Fong has been a treasurer,'' she said, ``and he's been on
the Board of Equalization, so he hasn't really voted on a lot of
the issues that will come before the Senate. So we've had to read
his speeches and listen to his statements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lungren campaign has seized upon Davis' public record as a
way to sharpen the differences between two similar candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters were told as soon as the primary election concluded
that these two are very much alike in a lot of ways,'' said Dave
Puglia, Lungren's campaign manager. ``Well, it's not true. ... Gray
Davis in his public career has managed to do little and avoid
controversy. Dan Lungren has taken controversy head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Davis, Michael Bustamante, admitted that
Lungren's record in Congress is a ``target-rich environment.''
Lungren cast 4,800 votes while in Congress. During their second
debate together, for example, Davis could quickly cite 14 votes
Lungren made while in Congress on one very specific topic: denying
abortions even in the case of rape or incest.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Davis and Fong campaigns say their candidates have long
public service records from which voters can make informed
decisions. And Bustamante said Lungren doesn't mention Davis'
accomplishments because there is nothing the average Californian
would find objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is the guy (Lungren) is embarrassed
about his record and he's trying to run away from it,'' Bustamante
said. ``Gray's record over the past two decades has been very
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' campaign slogan during the June primary was ``Experience
money can't buy,'' when he faced two wealthy candidates. He has now
changed it to ``Experience that will move us forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fong spokesman Steve Schmidt said Fong was ``the chief financial
officer of the world's seventh largest economy'' and even though he
may not have a long voting record, voters can count on him to keep
his word. ``Voters can expect Matt Fong to follow through,''
Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fong campaign, with the help of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, has amassed a databank on Boxer's voting
career. When Boxer said during the first debate that she supported
a tough sentencing law called ``10-20-life,'' the Fong campaign
immediately produced a roll-call vote from Nov. 9, 1993, on an
amendment to the federal crime bill. Boxer had voted ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A voting record is only a liability if it's a bad voting
record,'' Schmidt said. ``Barbara Boxer has been in Congress for a
long time; she's cast lots of votes. ... We're looking at it very
closely. We're looking for a pattern of flip-flopping and
unprincipled stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Behr, a Boxer campaign strategist and spokesman, said the
campaign must rely on Fong's public statements, and they indeed
take him at his word, as when Fong said he thought Roe vs. Wade,
the landmark abortion-right decision, was wrongly decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters understand that sometimes campaigns can twist a voting
record,'' Behr said, ``so they don't necessarily give more credence
to a vote than a statement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
