<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL-COX     09-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fellow Democrats: Just between us, it's time to let Clinton go
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tapes were a bust.
</P>
<P>
   The video testimony of President Clinton proved that he
committed perjury and probably suborned perjury from his secretary,
Bettie Currie. It also proved that independent counsel Kenneth
Starr has an unhealthy interest in the sex lives of other people.
But we already knew all that.
</P>
<P>
   So let's take this discussion in another direction. Let's see if
we can elevate the debate a bit by focusing on two questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ What is the purpose of politics?
</P>
<P>
   _ What role should principle play in politics?
</P>
<P>
   Before we begin, I'd like to ask all of those folks who have
disliked Clinton from the beginning to find something else to read.
Nothing personal, but I want this to be a little heart-to-heart
among those of us who have voted for Clinton and support his
policies. The rest of us will wait while you guys turn the page. .
. . Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Have they left yet? Good. I bet they're off sticking more pins
in their Bill Clinton voodoo dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we're alone _ remember the joy of Election Night, 1992?
After eight years of Ronald Reagan and four of George Bush, Clinton
seemed like an oasis of sanity. And once the Republican takeover of
1994 elevated Newt Gingrich to the House speaker's job, things got
downright scary. Clinton's presidency became even more important.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, on issues such as the environment, women's rights,
racial justice and maintaining some sense of balance in the
nation's tax code, Clinton is all we've had to cling to. And wily
politician that he is, he's been enough. Time and again he has
beaten the conservatives, usually because they underestimated how
much support his policies really have among the American people.
</P>
<P>
   And the more successful Clinton became, the more the
conservatives hated him. The more they hated him and attacked him,
the more protective the rest of us became. Because at times, it
seemed that Bill Clinton was the only thing standing between us and
the Christian Theocracy of America.
</P>
<P>
   That history makes it all the more difficult now to argue for
Clinton's resignation and perhaps impeachment. Many times, when
discussing this issue with friends, I've heard the same bottom
line: ``But how can we let the Republicans ruin him?''
</P>
<P>
   I understand and respect that. The claim by House Republicans
that the Clinton tapes would be ``devastating'' only proves how
blinded by hatred they have become. Their judgment is gone.
</P>
<P>
   But I too have a question:
</P>
<P>
   If this were a Republican president, what would we be doing?
</P>
<P>
   We'd all be screaming for his head, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   We'd be pointing out that here was a man in power who had used a
young intern like a soulless receptacle, who had reduced his
secretary to little more than a procuress, who had clearly
pressured that secretary to lie under oath and who had weakened the
presidency to conceal a lie.
</P>
<P>
   To support Clinton despite all that requires us to repudiate
what we once claimed to believe about the way men and women should
treat each other in the workplace. At the very least we have to
pretend that such misbehavior isn't really a big deal, that it's
all right to use a woman as long as the woman wants to be used.
</P>
<P>
   So let's talk now about those two lofty questions.
</P>
<P>
   If politics is just a struggle for power between our gang and
their gang, and if principle is simply a convenient hammer to pound
on the other guy's head, then we ought to defend Clinton with every
means available. After all, he's our guy and they're attacking him,
in ways that are clearly unfair.
</P>
<P>
   But what if politics is something more than that? What if
politics is a means of producing a better society, a more decent
society? What if principles are more than just weapons to use
against bad guys?
</P>
<P>
   By continuing to support Clinton, we place ourselves in the
hypocritical position of demanding a higher standard of behavior
from our enemies than we do from our friends. Someday, believe it
or not, this is all going to end. And I'm afraid that on that
glorious day, we'll look back and realize that the price we paid to
save Clinton just wasn't worth it.
</P>
<P>
   (Oh, and for you conservatives who are still hanging around
reading this, shame, shame, shame. Really folks, read the polls.
You gotta stop sticking your nose in other people's private
business.)
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman's editorial commentaries appear in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: jbookman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
