<HEADLINE>
BOSTON POPS FEATURED IN AMERICAN AIRLINES ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In return for free publicity, the Boston Pops and
conductor Keith Lockhart are appearing in American Airlines TV ads
that began running Monday and will continue for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Boston institution has often lent its name to worthy
causes, this will mark the first time in its 113-year history that
the Pops have been involved in advertising for a commercial product
or service, said Mark Volpe, managing director of the Boston
Symphony Orchestra, parent of the Pops.
</P>
<P>
   In return for travel considerations, the Pops have had a
promotional relationship with American for about a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is taking that relationship to the next level,'' Volpe
said of the first appearance by the Pops in a TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the classical music scene with stops in Baltimore,
Minneapolis, and Detroit, Volpe said he was unaware of an orchestra
ever playing so prominent a role in a TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines run the same ads in every city that the airline
serves. But American devotes part of its marketing budget to ads
that highlight individual cities, such as New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The ads using the Pops are the first time that American has
created an ad specifically for Boston, said James K. Carter,
American's regional sales director for New England.
</P>
<P>
   A TV ad opens with scenes of Beacon Hill, a rower sculling on
the Charles River, and Pops musicians moving through an airport.
</P>
<P>
   On an airplane, a Pops musician sits next to her cello as a
flight attendant gets a pillow for the instrument. The cellist
later plays the airlines' theme, ``Something Special in the Air.''
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers think of American as an airline that serves the
South and Midwest, but American has recently ramped up its flights
from Logan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   By including scenes from Paris and San Francisco, the Pops ad
conveys the message that American is a good choice for Boston
travelers who may want to fly to the West Coast or Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was created by Temerlin McClain, a Texas ad agency that
said one reason for using the Pops is to connect American with a
``Boston icon that means quality and dependability.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign includes radio ads as well as print ads that use
such landmarks as the Old North Church and the USS Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to be specific, American said it will spend ``several
hundred thousand dollars'' on the Boston campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Lockhart outdoes Liberace, who once reduced a
Tchaikovsky piano concerto into a four-minute performance. Lockhart
has condensed a Rossini overture into a mere 60 seconds for the
American ad.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Pops musicians were paid union-scale wages to appear in
the American Airlines ad, Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why the Pops agreed to appear in an ad, he said:
``Candidly, this gets the Pops out there in front of the public,
and there's no such thing as overexposure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1848EDT &QL; 
