<SLUG> BC-MA-HMO-RANKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 BAY STATE HMOS GET TOP NATIONAL RANKING BY MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three health maintenance organizations based in
Massachusetts grabbed the top three spots on Newsweek magazine's
third annual list of the 100 best managed care plans in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, Tufts Health Plan and HMO Blue of
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts were ranked numbers one
to three, respectively, on the list published in the Sept. 28 issue
of Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   The news came as a welcome respite to the state's HMOs, who like
their peers nationwide, are under heavy attack by angry consumers
and regulation-minded &UR;  &LR; politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of negative press about HMOs and subsequent
public distrust,'' said Patti Embry-Tautenhan, spokeswoman for
Harvard Pilgrim. ``So, I hope this article and survey reassures
people that, at least in Massachusetts, health care decisions are
being made based on what constitutes quality care.''
</P>
<P>
   New England is home to some of America's premier hospitals and
doctors, so it's no wonder that the state's HMOs also get high
marks, said Susan Connolly, principal at William M. Mercer, a
benefits consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Quality can come at a cost, however. Connolly notes that health
care costs in Massachusetts are higher than in the rest of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're among the most expensive states in the country based on
per capita health care costs,'' said Connolly, who noted that
health plans in Massachusetts have very broad networks of hospitals
and doctors. While that gives patients better access to care, it
tends to deprive health plans of some leverage in bargaining for
volume discounts with health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly premiums in the Boston area are nearly $100 higher for
each family than the national average, according to Modern
Healthcare magazine, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Among top-rated New England plans, Healthsource Massachusetts in
Worcester ranked number eight, United Health Care of New England in
Providence came in at number six and Fallon Community Health Plan
in Worcester number sixteen.
</P>
<P>
   The Newsweek rankings looked at how well health plans kept
members healthy, treat acute illness, and manage chronic illnesses
for adults and children. More than 200 health plans participated in
the survey, although some prominent HMOs declined to participate,
including Aetna U.S. Healthcare, Cigna HealthCare, and Prudential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
