A6766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-NASA-RUSSIA-2TAKE     09-21 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NASA-RUSSIA-2TAKES(900)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA ASKS FOR $660 MILLION TO BAIL OUT RUSSIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worried that trouble in Moscow is threatening its own dreams,
NASA wants to spend up to $660 million over five years to bail out
its Russian partner in building a planned international space
station, agency officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Key members of Congress immediately faulted the proposal as too
expensive, clouding the fate of the biggest science project of all
time. But NASA officials argued that the American and Russian
programs are now linked so intimately that the Russian effort must
be preserved lest the American space program suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In just two months, orbital construction is to start on the
sprawling outpost for astronauts, which is expected to cost more
than $40 billion. But even if the new bailout goes through and
keeps the Russians afloat, the station project is facing another
round of construction delays next year because of Russia's problems
in building a key part. The lag in that work will also have costly
repercussions for the nation's fleet of space shuttles, which are
to carry station elements into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Already, past delays have cut the flight rate of the winged
spaceships to unusually low levels, and NASA officials are
scrambling to find new shuttle payloads to compensate for looming
gaps in outpost construction.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Rothenberg, associate administrator for space flight at
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, said in an
interview that the new bid to save the Russians and the beleaguered
outpost is likely to cost about $1.2 billion, including the new
money for the Russians as well as about $540 million in new
American work such as modifying the shuttles so they can do more
station lifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a plan,'' he said of the Russia aid. ``No commitment
from anybody has been made'' to provide new funds.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said the space agency had already squeezed its own
$13.6 billion budget as far as possible to find emergency funds for
the outpost's rescue, and that it was eager for new money.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Rothenberg said, NASA wants to pay the Russians $60
million this fiscal year for new goods and services and then up to
$150 million a year over the next four years as an aid to station
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.2 billion in emergency money, Rothenberg said, was much
cheaper than losing Moscow's help altogether. ``Any alternative you
look at without the Russians would hit the program hard,''
Rothenberg said. Their absence, he said, would delay the outpost's
construction by years and add up to $2 billion in costs.
</P>
<P>
   But top members of Congress are questioning the new bailout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given NASA's track record, we are justifiably concerned and
skeptical,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, which oversees NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics go further, saying NASA officials should put the
whole station project on indefinite hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to stick with a failed strategy,'' James Oberg,
an American expert on the Russian space program, said in an
interview. He said the station's delays threaten to add billions of
dollars in hidden costs to NASA's shuttle operations. ``Next year's
shuttle schedule is entirely up in the air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, Oberg said, NASA could end up with a half-built
station with the Russians entirely out of the picture if their
downward spiral continues. He said it would be much better to pause
now and rethink the station venture from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for station cooperation arose in 1993 after the Cold
War. The Clinton administration saw Moscow's participation as an
important symbol of new cooperation between East and West.
Supporting the Russian program was also viewed as a way to keep
Russian space scientists employed in peaceful pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of close collaboration, ties between the
Russian and American space station efforts are now so extensive
that repercussions of Russia's financial turmoil have increasingly
roiled American plans, budgets and gear. Last month, for example,
Russia's main spaceport temporarily lost power because of unpaid
bills, postponing a number of rocket launchings and sending shock
waves through Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The situation ``is deteriorating,'' NASA told the White House in
a confidential briefing in late July that was made public by NASA
watch, an internet publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In the briefing, NASA said the Russian Space Agency needs $340
million this year to build parts for its share of the international
outpost, but so far had received only $20 million from its
government. The outlook for improvement ``is bleak,'' the
assessment said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Manber, managing director of Energia Ltd., the American
arm of a top Russian contractor making station parts, strongly
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophical question,'' he said in an interview, ``is
whether you maintain the illusion that the government of Russia can
keep its objectives or do you deal with Russian industry for goods
and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Washington has paid Moscow $742 million for
station-related work, Congressional experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the White House has taken to rejecting NASA requests
for new bailout funds to aid the Russians, so the agency has raided
its own budget. But criticism in Congress, among scientists and in
the aerospace community is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA needs to stop draining other vital programs to feed the
space station's voracious hunger for more money,'' Space News, an
industry publication, said in an editorial last month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The developing crisis in the International Space Station has
been overshadowed in the past year or so by the travails of its
wobbly predecessor, the Russian Mir outpost, which has suffered a
fire, navigation breakdowns and a collision with a supply ship.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, orbital construction of the follow-on station was to
begin in November 1997. But the threadbare Russians kept missing
deadlines. So the starting date slipped to June of this year and
then to November, a year later than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The outpost's first element, 43 feet long, paid for by the
United States and built by Russia, is now scheduled to ride into
space atop a Russian rocket roughly two months from now. Then, over
five or six years, scores of Russian rocket and American shuttle
launchings are to loft 500 tons of parts and supplies. When it is
finished, the outpost of laboratories and living areas nearly the
size of two football fields will orbit hundreds of miles above
earth, powered by huge arrays of solar-energy cells,
</P>
<P>
   Today, the main hurdle is not the station's first element, which
the Russians have ready to go for launching in November, nor the
second, which the Americans have ready to go for launching in
December. Rather, it is the third _ the first element to be
fabricated by Russia on its own. This so-called service module
would provide early living quarters and, more important, would
provide propellant tanks and thrusters to keep the craft in
position. It is officially set for launching in April but is still
unfinished and its fate is increasingly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   American experts say Russia needs up to $210 million to finish,
test and launch the key unit. It might be ready to fly in July
1999, at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, American officials are loath to send up the
first modules without confidence that the vital third one will show
up relatively soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   To aid the Russians, the space agency is now seeking to buy two
lifeboats for the station from Russian at a cost of roughly $100
million, Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will prime the pump,'' he said. Rothenberg insisted that
taking $100 million from other NASA programs was prudent and that
the money would eventually be paid back. The current goal, he
added, is to rush Moscow $60 million by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA is working on its own partial backup to the
Russian service module, a skeleton unit that would periodically
lift the outpost into a safer orbit. The agency is also preparing
to have the shuttles modified so their engines can aid the lifting
job.
</P>
<P>
   Things will be clearer after agency officials meet with the
Russians late this month, after which schedules will be recast, yet
again.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, most shuttle flights that NASA had planned for this
year for station construction. But delays cut this year's flights
from four to one. As a result, by the time Sen. John Glenn rockets
into space in October, there will have been no shuttle launchings
for five months, a silence on the launching pad that NASA officials
say is dangerous. They say the rocket specialists at the Florida
spaceport must loft shuttles regularly or loose their edge.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they are struggling to keep launch teams in Florida sharp
with computer simulations, while they search for alternate
payloads. One developing plan is to have the shuttles send up
logistics materials and supplies ahead of schedule. Another is to
add a science mission unconnected to the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   In the more distant future, Rothenberg noted, demands on the
shuttles will actually soar since Russia has informed NASA it
cannot afford to launch unpiloted resupply ships to the outpost at
the rate it expected.
</P>
<P>
   While 33 Russian supply ships were originally promised to haul
up cargo and propellant, the number has now dwindled to 15 or 17,
and the shuttles will have to take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's put a change into the program,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
