<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLORADO, SOME BLAME REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MONICA,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT,
CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ At the headquarters of the Colorado Republican Party on
Monday, the television set was not working, so some staffers
listened to President Clinton's grand jury deposition on the radio.
Others got a different kind of earful over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about all the complaints were `I can't believe you
Republicans are doing this,''' said Michael Fortinberry, the
party's political director, who moved to another downtown office in
midmorning to watch the video. ``If that is the perception, it
hurts the party.''
</P>
<P>
   While several callers wanted Congress to impeach the president,
others blamed party politics for the airing of the video. ``There
seemed to be a very specific belief that the Republicans were doing
this today,'' Fortinberry said.
</P>
<P>
   At the downtown office, Donald Bain, a former state party
chairman, agreed, predicting that any backlash ``would be over the
release, not over the content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you are going to see a backlash from the
testimony itself,'' Bain continued, after rolling his eyes over one
prosecutor's question about oral sex. Looking to the November
elections, he cautioned: ``The big risk for Republicans is that
they assume that all the votes are in the bank and that they can
rest on the status quo. That's a very dangerous attitude for
Republicans to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Denver area Monday morning, Republican candidates and
campaign managers said they were either avoiding the broadcast or
keeping one eye on the television while working the telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been trying to avoid it,'' said Bob Greenlee, a
Republican who is running for Congress in the 2nd District, a
centrist suburban area that includes Boulder. On Friday, Greenlee
urged local television networks to refuse to air the video, saying
``Airing the tape is a voyeuristic exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is real potential for some kind of a backlash,''
Greenlee said of the broadcast. Although he charged that Clinton
``lied to all of us,'' he added, ``My sense is that the public is
damn sick of this whole thing and would like it to end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
