<HEADLINE>
FOURTH DAY OF PRICE GAINS FOR BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury yields declined Monday for the fourth
consecutive session, with no significant economic reports to move
the market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the scarcity of economic data, many investors
were observing Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year, and trading
volume was down about 11 percent from normal, according to Govpx, a
bond-pricing service.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the 30-year bond was up 12/32 to a price of
105 27/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
slipped to 5.12 percent, from 5.14 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Widening concern among investors that Japan's recession will
worsen and cut into corporate profits, and questions about whether
Japan will be able to overhaul its battered banking system anytime
soon, once again increased the attractiveness of Treasuries as an
alternative investment to stocks, lowering long-bond yields to
levels not seen for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The telecast of President Clinton's grand jury testimony in the
Monica Lewinsky matter appeared to have little impact on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gamba, vice president and manager of taxable fixed-income
securities for SG Cowen Private Client Group, said the market had
been anticipating the videotape since last week and had already
priced in all the negatives, so when the tapes were released,
``There was a relief rally in stocks, and that helped take some of
the flight to safety out of bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the second-quarter GDP report this week, which is
considered important, and a two-year-note auction on Wednesday,''
Gamba said. ``Given the current condition of the global economies
and financial markets elsewhere in the world, I think the two-year
will have no problem getting done.''
</P>
<P>
   In when-issued trading, dealers were offering the new two-year
issue at a price to yield 4.61 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
