<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TAPE22-COX     09-21 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIDEOTAPE OFFERS VIEWERS RARE GLIMPSE AT UNSCRIPTED CLINTON
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Millions of Americans on Monday saw President
Clinton portray himself as a victim of his right-wing political
foes as he fell back on legalisms to dodge perjury charges in his
videotaped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's historic and unscripted ordeal before an invisible
tag team of federal prosecutors left viewers with no apparent
``smoking gun'' ensuring that his scandalous affair with Monica
Lewinsky would lead Congress to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   During four hours and three minutes of mostly polite but often
blunt questioning, recorded by a single camera, the TV audience
witnessed a Clinton they had rarely seen before: by turns
combative, garrulous, philosophical and contrite.
</P>
<P>
   As the Aug. 17 encounter progressed, Clinton proved unwilling to
answer many specific questions about his sexual encounters with the
former young White House aide. He repeatedly refused to go beyond a
prepared single-page, thrice-folded statement that he pulled from
his jacket pocket seven minutes into the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Clinton posed one wry question to the prosecutors
which they left hanging: Whether the need to accommodate an absent
grand juror was ``the only reason ... you have to videotape?''
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the scene in the White House Map Room was a far cry
from the familiar highly scripted, professionally lit circumstances
in which modern presidents normally offer televised ``sound bites''
to huge viewing audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The sole props that relieved the stark backdrop were a small
bowl of flowers over Clinton's right shoulder. Clinton paused on
occasion to sip from a glass of ice water or to drink from cans of
ginger ale or Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   At one juncture, offering the grand jurors a Rashomon-like
aside, Clinton suggested that persons involved in a sexual
relationship can see the same set of facts from entirely different
vantage points.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the president went on, sexuality may be the ``most
mysterious area of human life,'' citing as an example Anita Hill's
sexual harassment charges against Clarence Thomas during the
Supreme Court nominee's 1991 hearings before the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But far more often, in responding to a barrage of questions that
focused largely on whether he might have committed perjury when he
described the affair under oath in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit, Clinton exhibited a steely edge punctuated by
flashes of irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have testified about this three times. Now, I will do it the
fourth time. I am not going to answer your trick questions,'' the
president snapped at one point to Sol Wisenberg, a deputy
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after he began, Clinton wagged his index finger
in a move that evoked his unequivocal Jan. 26 denial that he ever
had ``sexual relations with that woman, Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Clinton went on the attack, charging that
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, was in league with the
conservative forces who the Jones suit against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious and I think by your questions you have betrayed
that the Jones lawyers' strategy in this case had nothing to do
with uncovering or proving sexual harassment,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret to anybody that I hoped that this relationship
(with Lewinsky) would never become public,'' Clinton later added.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that while he had prepared well for the Jones case,
he had not expected that Linda Tripp, a Lewinsky confidante, would
provide extensive details of the affair to his interrogators the
evening before his deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most dramatic moment of the videotaped afternoon
session came when Robert Bittman, another Starr aide, asked a
series of questions, each tied to the same basic theme, that began,
``If Monica Lewinsky says that while you were in the Oval Office
area you touched her breast, would she be lying?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not my recollection,'' Clinton replied, after being
denied a chance to say ``something general about this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My recollection,'' Clinton added, ``is that I did not have
sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky, and I am staying on my former
(written) statement about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared startled when Bittman asked: ``If Monica
Lewinsky says that you used a cigar as a sexual aid with her in the
Oval Office area, would she be lying? Yes, no, or won't answer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will revert to my former statement,'' the president said
again, this time with a clenched jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy prosecutors complained about Clinton's long, often
convoluted answers and pleaded with him in vain to extend the
session beyond the agreed four hours. At one point, the president
said he would think about an extension; another time, he said he
would give Starr's team an extra 30 seconds if they in turn would
allow him make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
