<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLIITCS-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY RUSSIAN GOVERNMENT POSITIONS REMAIN VACANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's leaders offered more assurances Monday that
the country's fiscal crisis could be tamed without provoking high
inflation or social unrest. But with key positions in the
government still unfilled, few people seemed to accord the promises
much weight.
</P>
<P>
   Neither President Boris Yeltsin nor his prime minister, Yevgeny
Primakov, have settled on a choice for finance minister, perhaps
the most important post in the new government next to Primakov's.
The finance minister will carry out many of the government's crisis
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The man who currently holds the post, Mikhail Zadornov, pledged
Monday that foreign investors would receive equal treatment with
Russians in negotiations to reschedule the payment of $40 million
in government bonds that was frozen when the crisis broke last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov also said the government would pay at least 40 billion
rubles in back wages to government workers by the end of the year
without having to print additional money that might spur a new
round of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But both statements more or less contradict policies already
announced by the central bank and one of the new deputy prime
ministers, Aleksandr Shokhin.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin has supported printing money to quickly pay off wage
arrears, and the central bank has already said that it will
purchase government bonds held by Russian banks as a means of
bailing them out of their financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov is one of the few market advocates remaining from the
government that Yeltsin dismissed last month. He refused to say
Monday whether his own job was in jeopardy, but Yeltsin is known to
be looking at other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin said Monday that the government might issue a schedule
on Thursday to pay wage arrears and improve tax collection. He also
suggested that the government would soon unveil new financial
instruments aimed at attracting investors with hard currency and
perhaps guaranteed by a consortium of Western banks rather than the
Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   What little remains of Russia's financial markets took no solace
from Zadornov's or Shokhin's remarks. Trading in the ruble was
suspended at midafternoon Monday as the exchange rate reached as
much as 19 rubles to the dollar, three times the level of barely a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, about 1,000 pro-Communist demonstrators, some
carrying portraits of Stalin, marched through the center of the
city to protest price increases. And in France, the leader of
Russia's Communist Party, Gennadi Zyuganov, said Primakov's
government might represent Russia's last chance to avert a military
dictatorship or civil war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It is important for us to support Primakov's government,'' he
said. ``The Yeltsin era is finished. It is very important for us
not to end up with a civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the men seen as most responsible for Primakov's ascension
to prime minister, the reformist politician Grigory Yavlinsky, was
in a Moscow hospital Monday being treated for what doctors
described as heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Yavlinsky, 46, leads the Yabloko political bloc, which controls
10 percent of the lower house of Parliament. Although a critic of
the Communists and conservatives with whom Primakov is most closely
associated, he urged legislators to support Primakov's appointment
as prime minister as a means of unifying the country behind a
single leader.
</P>
<P>
   The precise nature of Yavlinsky's ailment was not clear. Doctors
were quoted as saying he was already able to work and might be
released by Tuesday or Wednesday. Yavlinsky entered the hospital
over the weekend, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
