<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-0922     09-21 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-0922 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUXTAPOSED AGAINST TESTIMONY, CLINTON CALLS TERRORISM 'THREAT TO
ALL HUMANKIND'; TO ASK CONGRESS FOR $1.8 BILLION
 &HT;    EDs: Optional trims, adds beginning at 600 words.
 &HT;    With CLINTON-0922.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton journeyed to the high church of
global diplomacy on Monday, imploring world leaders at the United
Nations to help combat a new generation of terrorist threats, even
as millions of Americans watched a videotape of the nation's
embattled leader staggering through torturous testimony about his
ill-fated affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic moment that seemed to crystallize the conflicting
forces tugging at his presidency, and the incongruent roles he's
become obliged to assume, Clinton drew a standing ovation as he
entered the U.N.'s cavernous General Assembly Hall to take on the
sobering scourges of car bombs and skyjackings, against the
strikingly discordant background music of his grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president did not watch the
testimony, which was televised by several national networks,
because he was busy honing and delivering his speech to the General
Assembly and conducting one-on-one diplomacy with a handful of his
counterparts behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials made no secret, however, of their
aggravation over the timing of the aired testimony, which largely
occluded coverage of Clinton's annual address to the U.N. General
Assembly and his request, announced later, for $1.8 billion to
buttress U.S. counter-terrorism efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The White House couldn't feel anything but awful about the day
that we have gone through as a nation,'' said Clinton spokesman
Michael McCurry. ``There is a great deal of salacious material; a
great deal of material that is designed, it seems, to do nothing
but . . . exasperate the president and those around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in solemn, almost reverent tones in the expansive U.N.
setting for two generations of debate over issues centered on war
and peace, Clinton told more than 1,100 diplomats and heads of
state that ``Terror has become the world's problem.'' He exhorted
delegates from the 184 other U.N. member-nations to join the United
States in what has been one of the most difficult foreign policy
tasks of his presidency: winning the support of the international
community in trying to isolate, counter and punish terrorist groups
and the regimes that support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a grave misconception to see terrorism as only, or even
mostly, an American problem,'' said Clinton. ``It is a clear and
present danger to tolerant and open societies, and innocent people
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the urgency of the issue, Clinton plans to ask
Congress later this week to approve $1.8 billion in emergency
spending. The money would be used to help rebuild the American
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania that were destroyed last month by
deadly terrorist bombings that killed 12 Americans, shore up
protections for other U.S. diplomatic missions around the world,
and beef up U.S. intelligence and law enforcement capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is overwhelmingly in the national interest,'' said
National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, who said he's
had extensive discussions on the issue with the Republican
leadership in both houses of Congress. ``That's not to say there's
agreement on all aspects of this,'' Berger said, conceding that the
White House still must win congressional approval for the funding.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever long-term impact Clinton's initiatives have on the
global terrorist threat, the drama of Monday's U.N. appearance
centered on his personal troubles over the Lewinsky scandal that
threatens his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton was heartened by the spontaneous, and rare,
ovation he received when he stepped onto the historic sea-green
stage to address the grand global forum, and felt the immensity of
the delegates' response.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins.)
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton strode onto the platform to take his seat in the
formal high-backed ivory-colored chair to the right of the grey
marble podium, an uncharacteristic murmur swept the chamber. Then,
a wave of applause broke the tension and grew until, to Clinton's
left, a small group of delegates rose, quickly followed by more.
Within a few moments, delegates from Angola to Zimbabwe were on
their feet, as Clinton, still seated, acknowledged the
much-welcomed show of support with a nod and a quick wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen that before,'' Berger said of the ovation
Clinton received. ``I think it was an expression by the
international community of the stature and regard in which he is
held, their affection for him personally and their very strong
sense that American leadership, strong American leadership,
continues to be essential.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 21-minute speech, Clinton focused almost exclusively on
terrorism, taking pains to stress that the United States was not
trying to drive a wedge between the Western and Islamic world,
where much of the support for terrorism has been concentrated, and
that he did not see the war on terrorism as a crusade against the
world's 1.1 billion Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans respect and honor Islam,'' said Clinton. ``We will
remain on a course of friendship and respect for the Muslim
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he stressed, the United States rejects the use of any
religion as a justification for terrorism -- ``False prophets may
use and abuse any religion to justify whatever political objectives
they have, even cold-blooded murder,'' he said -- and does not
accept indiscriminate killing as a way of addressing economic and
political ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depravation cannot justify destruction, nor can inequity ever
atone for murder,'' Clinton said. ``The killing of innocents is not
a social program.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Sticking carefully to his scripted remarks, Clinton did not
reply to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's unusually frank
critique of the international community's failure to end months of
bloodshed in the Serb province of Kosovo. There, minority Serbs
have killed hundreds of ethnic Albanians and run thousands more
from their homes through a bloody campaign of terror hauntingly
reminiscent of the violence that killed some 200,000 non-Serbs in
Bosnia before a U.S.-led NATO mission ended the conflict three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo, the international community seems to be watching
impotently,'' Annan said in remarks to open this year's three-month
General Assembly session, shortly before Clinton's address. Annan
compared the situation to years of international failings in
Bosnia, ``something we swore must never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan also took a shot at the refusal by the U.S. Congress to
fund Clinton's request for money to pay some $1 billion in arrears
the United States owes the United Nations, saying the organization
is operating in ``a financial straitjacket,'' with its ability to
function, and even to reform itself along lines favored by Congress
and the White House, sharply impeded by its cash crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stringency is one thing, and a starvation diet is quite
another,'' Annan said, without mentioning the United States by
name. ''There can be no substitute for full and timely payment of
what is due.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   In another stirring moment, South Africa's aging anti-apartheid
crusader and outgoing president Nelson Mandela delivered an
impassioned farewell to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela called on the body to undertake an aggressive campaign
to eliminate nuclear weapons and summed up in disarmingly simple
eloquence an activist career that sustained him through 27 years as
a political prisoner and led him to guide his nation out from the
shadow of its racist past to its first full and free national
elections four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have reached the point in the long walk where the
opportunity is granted, as it should be to all men and women, to
return to some rest and tranquility in the village of my birth,''
said Mandela, who goes to Capitol Hill on Wednesday to receive a
gold medal from Clinton for his life-long fight against oppression.
``It was right that we dreamed and that we toiled to give life to a
workable dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
