<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-SINGER-ART-975&AMP;A     09-21 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-SINGER-ART-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SINGER IS RETURNING TO A STAGE WHERE IT ALL BEGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Krannert Arts Center is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By JO THOMAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   URBANA, ILL. _ Like most beginnings, it was not predictable.
Herman C. Krannert, a wealthy cardboard box maker, suddenly agreed
to endow a performing arts center at the University of Illinois,
far from either bright lights or big city.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Max Abramovitz, who worked on Avery Fisher Hall at
Lincoln Center, was asked to do the design. The eventual cost of
what he called his ``acropolis on the prairie'' was $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   As it approached completion, a young Michigan woman who once
wanted to sing for Motown stopped by for a jazz competition, fell
in love with a student musician and decided to stay. It was 1969.
The building and the singer were elegant and young.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Krannert Center for the Performing Arts,
which has since flourished as a performance hall and as a showcase
for young artists and new works, will celebrate the opening of its
30th season with fireworks and choruses. The jazz singer, Dee Dee
Bridgewater, still elegant and something more, will be onstage for
a sold-out performance. (This year she won a Grammy for her album
``Dear Ella,'' a tribute to Ella Fitzgerald.)
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from France, where she lives outside
Paris, Ms. Bridgewater said her professional career had begun
shortly after the first time she saw Cecil Bridgewater, then a
student at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my mother, `Do you see that man with that big Afro and
that trumpet getting out of that Volkswagen? I'm going to marry
him.' Six months later, we got married.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she was Denise Eileen Garrett, born in Memphis in
1950 and raised in Flint, Mich., listening to jazz and Top 40
songs, hoping to record for Motown. When the two other young women
in her group, the Iridescents, ``became more interested in boys,''
she turned to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier, working with trios my dad would put together,
to do standards,'' she said. ``I sang on weekends, with my father
as my chaperone. I was under age, so I had to sit in the kitchen
between my sets.'' Later, as a student at Michigan State, she
earned money singing with a jazz quintet.
</P>
<P>
   After the competition in Illinois, John Garvey, director of the
University of Illinois Jazz Band, asked the young singer if she
wanted to switch universities and go to the Soviet Union on tour
with his band. With Bridgewater in mind, she said yes.
</P>
<P>
   She sang again at Krannert, but for the most part she performed
with a jazz group, the Bridgewater Brothers, at a Chinese
restaurant near campus and at local clubs. ``It became easier than
going to school, so I dropped out,'' she recalled. In 1970 she and
her husband moved to New York, where their daughter, Tulani, was
born and where Ms. Bridgewater sang at the Village Vanguard with
the Thad Jones-Mel Lewis Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I know about music today, I learned in that band,''
she said. ``It taught me how important it is to sing the melody.
Without knowing the melody, you can never be a good improviser, and
you show a disrespect to the author and composer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also learned how to breathe and project my voice over 15
horns and a rhythm section,'' she said. Jones taught her the
importance of arrangements. ``Otherwise, it leaves things to
chance,'' she said. ``When you don't have a beginning or an ending,
too often you have a cliche ending.'' Ms. Bridgewater's career took
off, but her marriage foundered. In 1974 she quit jazz and took a
role as Glinda the Good Witch in ``The Wiz,'' which opened
off-Broadway. At the time, she was romantically involved with the
show's director, Gilbert Moses. He was dismissed before the show
opened on Broadway, and her role was cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   ``My revenge _ my reward _ is that I got the Tony,'' she said.
But even that experience turned sour. When the show's teen-age star
was not nominated, Ms. Bridgewater said, ``there were all these
rumors that I slept around to get the nomination.'' It was the
beginning of an education in the school of hard knocks that
continued after she moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, after marriage to Moses and her second child, China
Moses, Ms. Bridgewater left California for a national tour with
``Sophisticated Ladies.'' Two magical things happened. She met Ella
Fitzgerald in Tokyo and talked with her backstage. Then the show
went to France, where Ms. Bridgewater was shocked to find she was a
star. She moved to Paris in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best decision I've made,'' she said. ``I feel like
France has been my lucky charm.''
</P>
<P>
   She was married for a third time, to Jean-Marie Durand, who was
working as a bartender at a jazz club in Paris when she met him.
``I saw him coming down the stairs while I was rehearsing,'' she
said. ``I stopped singing and caught my breath. He had on tight
jeans and a ponytail. Three days later, I got up the nerve to talk
to him. He was younger than me, I could tell. He took me home Oct.
14, 1986, and we have literally been together since that night.
Recently, we celebrated our seventh anniversary.'' Their son,
Gabriel, was born in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``I feel more secure,'' she said. ``I've seen people
who were starting out with me who have gone on to become
multimillionaires, and I don't have any remorse and jealousy. I'm
happy with my life. I grew up here. I became a woman here. I lost
my fear of performing and being criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Dear Ella,'' Ms. Bridgewater asked her former husband,
Cecil Bridgewater, to write arrangements for three Fitzgerald
signature pieces, including ``How High the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to devise a way of doing it that would be fresh,'' he
said, ``that would be a challenge to her and would make musical
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In her performance on Wednesday at Krannert, she will bring that
musical sense back to the place where she began. ``I love a
stage,'' she said. ``Give me a stage. Give me a spotlight. I turn
on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The stage in question has weathered the years well. The Krannert
Center is host to more than 300 performances a year. Audiences from
four theaters mingle in a single lobby the size of nine tennis
courts. The vast parquet floor, which consumed the entire U.S.
import allotment of teak in 1968, has withstood millions of high
heels. And the acoustics in the center's Foellinger Great Hall,
once a favorite recording site for the Chicago Symphony, are by all
accounts exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that made Krannert Center so compelling in the first
place was not just the monumentality of the facility,'' said its
director, Michael Ross, who came in 1997 from the Kathryn Bache
Miller Theater at Columbia University. ``It was the notion that
great art could be combined with great education.''
</P>
<P>
   Some big successes, like Ms. Bridgewater, don't graduate, and
some graduates don't succeed. But there is always hope. ``This is
not just a home for road shows,'' said Kathleen F. Conlin, who
oversees Ross and the Krannert staff as dean of the College of Fine
and Applied Arts at the university. ``This is our life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
