<HEADER>
A6787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA     09-21 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS CRITICIZE QUESTIONS AS WELL AS ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MONICA,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT,
CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It might have been from emotion or it might have been
the color control on the itty-bitty television, but President
Clinton's face shone a bright pink through much of his videotaped
grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The six Emory University students who gathered around the
13-inch screen Monday morning in Brian Oubre's campus apartment
said the president looked angry, defensive and dishonest, and if he
was not ashamed of himself, he should have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a colossal ego, to drag your country through
this,'' said Oubre, a 21-year-old senior from Baton Rouge, La., as
Clinton either evaded questions about specifically what sex acts he
engaged in with Monica Lewinsky, or answered with what he and
others in the country now know are untruths.
</P>
<P>
   The students, friends and classmates, had already made up their
minds about Clinton before the airing of the videotape, and saw it
as just more embarrassment heaped on the man, his office, and the
nation he leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not worth what we're paying for this fiasco,'' said
Oubre, a history and economics major.
</P>
<P>
   The six students, a mix of Democrats and Republicans and one
Independent _ Oubre _ passed around a box of Kix breakfast cereal
and alternately hissed, laughed or rolled their at the eyes at
Clinton's definitions of what is, or is not, sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he's lying, or he's an idiot,'' said Chuck Divine, a
21-year-old biology and political science major who is also
president of Emory's Student Government Association. He is a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But though the students were dismayed at Clinton's answers, some
of them were also dismayed at the questions _ questions that seemed
to go far beyond simple fact-finding, that seemed to solicit more
detail than was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about JFK and FDR?'' said Suzann Arnold, a 21-year-old
sociology major from Marion, N.C. ``We didn't ask them these
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   She was the only one of the six who, when asked if they thought
Clinton should resign, was not certain that he should. She is a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   After about two hours of seeing Clinton answer or not answer
questions they thought they already knew the answers to, the
students started to slip away, to class, to naps, or just to get
away from the television.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus seemed to be that it was boring, but a little
painful.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, said Miss Stephens, other generations will be so
disgusted by what happened to this president, by both the scandal
and the salacious way his political adversaries insisted it be
presented to the American people, that they will be spared a
repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
