<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-ART-575     09-21 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSURE AT FIRST, NETWORKS FOR THE MOST PART KEPT TAPE RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MONICA,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER,
CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT,
CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much like television viewers, network executives were unsure
what to expect when the video cassettes of President Clinton's
grand jury appearance were popped into tape machines in Washington
Monday morning, and equally unsure how much of the sometimes
salacious testimony they wanted the country to see.
</P>
<P>
   But very quickly the three major broadcast networks changed
plans and decided to join the all-news cable networks in televising
all four hours of testimony. NBC News briefly cut away from it
twice, because of the explicit discussion of sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so highly unusual,'' Andrew Heyward, the president
of CBS News, said Monday. ``We're in unexplored territory for
everybody, but soon after it started we made the decision to stick
with it. We wanted to get some sense of flavor of material, if it
was substantive as opposed just legalistic, and how graphic it was.
Pretty early on it appeared there would be substance there.''
</P>
<P>
   David Westin, president of ABC News, said the network's original
plan had been to broadcast the first videotape, of 11 minutes,
which included the president's opening statement, and then use
excerpts as the content warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as we got into it we found it very compelling, and we
found it very substantive,'' he said. ``My concern was that it
might be repetitious or a lot of lawyers talking. But there was
certainly news there.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS, NBC and the four cable networks _ CNN, C-Span, Fox
News Channel and MSNBC _ all repeatedly put labels across the
bottom of the screen warning of sexual content or strong language.
Their anchors made such warnings orally, as well, during brief
breaks in the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   While the videotape played on screen, reporters and producers
were reading through the typed transcript of it as fast as they
could, trying to spot testimony that might be offensive so that it
could be excised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got about half an hour ahead'' of the videotape, Bill
Wheatley, vice president of NBC News, said. ``So on the first
excision, we had time to talk it through calmly. The second we made
kind of on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC first cut away at 11:45 a.m., when testimony turned to
details of the president's sexual interactions with Monica
Lewinsky. Tom Brokaw spent the next seven minutes interviewing some
of the network's expert consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that despite the warnings we'd been carrying about
content, some viewers might still be offended about the most
graphic testimony,'' Wheatley said. ``And there was some concern
there might be unsupervised children watching, so at some points we
drew the line.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC also cut away at 12:04 p.m. for about two and a half
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in uncharted territory, and there is no such
thing as a right call or a wrong call,'' Heyward said.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward said he made CBS's decisions in consultation with
colleagues including the anchor, Dan Rather. ``At one point I went
out on the set to talk with Dan about some of the seamier sections
coming up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, only ABC delayed the tape's roll (by five seconds)
for possible editing, but by mid-morning the other two networks
were also using tape-delay, but of slightly different duration. For
viewers, this led to the weird sensation of being able to click
from NBC to ABC to CBS and hearing Clinton say the same words three
times in a row.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All the networks also put the testimony on their Web sites, and
at breaks in the testimony, the television anchormen directed
viewers to their respective web sites for more information. The
entire speech can be downloaded from some sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet was also widely used by people at work, who have
computers but not television sets in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   At some points, it was difficult to get onto certain sites, or
get the video, because of high traffic. Some Web sites, like CNN,
engaged high-tech ``backbone enhancing'' companies like Real
Networks and Broadcast.com to make sure they could handle the
traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
