<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CAPITAL-0922     09-21 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CAPITAL-0922 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN NATION'S CAPITAL AND ACROSS AMERICA, CLINTON'S TESTIMONY WAS
HARDLY RIVETING
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO and NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's video testimony reverberated
through congressional offices Monday morning, but the rest of the
nation's capital was hardly moved by the historic event.
</P>
<P>
   And even on Capitol Hill, few congressional aides were riveted
to television sets that aired Clinton's grilling by attorneys for
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key word here is working,'' said Dave Schnittger (CQ),
spokesman for Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, chairman of the House
Republican Conference. ``It's pretty much business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind almost every open door in House and Senate office
buildings, a small television played the testimony. But staffers
continued to stuff envelopes, answer phones and prepare for this
week's legislative debates.
</P>
<P>
   That business-as-usual attitude seemed pervasive elsewhere in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In the student union at the University of Texas in Austin, about
25 curious students watched silently as the president dissected the
nature of his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tape shouldn't have been released. It's part of a
political with hunt,'' said Jeff Young, a biology senior. ``What he
did wasn't right, but he doesn't deserve public humiliation like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Dayton Mall in Ohio, TV saleswoman Cathy Hockwalt has
seen large crowds drawn to televisions like moths to light, as when
the O.J. Simpson verdict was read or during coverage of Princess
Diana's death. But Clinton's video testimony didn't attract the
same level of interest, said Hockwalt, who added that several
shoppers said they were tired of watching it.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few dozen students quietly watched the testimony in the
lobby of nearby Wright State University's Allyn Hall.
</P>
<P>
   At the Roberd's appliance store in the Dayton suburb of West
Carrollton, where about 100 TVs were playing, only a handful of
shoppers paused to catch Clinton's testimony, said salesman Mark
Florkey. ``They mostly just watched, not saying much of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   At Poppa Rollo's Pizza in Waco, Texas, co-owner Mary Duty
worried that the televised testimony would be bad for business.
``This is not like the O.J. Simpson trial,'' said Duty, who once
worked for a congressman on Capitol Hill. ``This is embarrassing
stuff. It's not really what you want to watch in mixed company.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon, people began crowding into Duty's
restaurant and Clinton jokes began flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of fun,'' a relieved Duty said later. ``We asked
people if they wanted to sit in the non-smoking, G-rated section or
the smoking, R-rated section. And we got parental consent before we
let children sit up front.''
</P>
<P>
   In the TV room at McLennan Community College in Waco, Sarah
Perkins and Brandie Meyer chatted furiously Monday morning,
ignoring Clinton's testimony. ``They ask the same questions, over
and over,'' complained Perkins, 21, a general studies student. ``I
don't care anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said Clinton's testimony shouldn't have been aired on all
three networks. ``Definitely not,'' she said. ``We're missing 'The
Young and the Restless.'''
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast buffets, barber shops, college campuses and
department stores back in the nation's capital, few residents were
glued to the tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fed up with it,'' said William Ransford, a Washington
native who has worked for 20 years as a housekeeper at the downtown
Renaissance Mayflower Hotel. ``How many times is a man going to
apologize? I don't want to see it. This makes him look weak. This
makes our country look disunited.''
</P>
<P>
   It was business as usual Monday morning at the historic hotel,
where world leaders sometimes stay. People sipped coffee, ate fancy
breakfasts and discussed politics and world events in a
flower-filled, lavishly-draped dining area. But there wasn't a
television in sight.
</P>
<P>
   At nearby George Washington University, more than 50 students
gathered in a dining hall. But few paid close attention to the
large television screen. Freshman Margaret Scruggs showed only mild
interest in the president's testimony as she ate breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its just some big soap opera,'' said Scruggs, 17.
``It's amusing in a way, but sad for the country. I think he's
finally telling the truth about what happened. He should stay in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of students, like Stephen Rosenlund, watched more
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is of momentous importance to the country and Mr.
Clinton's presidency,'' said Rosenlund, 18. ``I am skeptical about
why they released all this to the country, though. They claim it
belongs to the people . . . However, I think there could be
stronger political motives.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dean's Beauty Salon near the Howard University campus, the
video of Clinton's testimony served mostly as background noise.
Barber William Phifer said he is still a Clinton supporter and that
the president's relationship with Lewinsky only reveals that he has
human weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony is really irrelevant,'' Phifer said
</P>
<P>
   The video also failed to change the mind of Jackie Eagan, 70,
who co-owns and operates Mr. Eagan's, a restaurant and bar which is
often a hangout for politicos and downtown lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't he have a hell of a nerve telling people what's
appropriate,'' she said, responding to one of Clinton's answers.
``This is no big surprise, though. We already knew he was a liar,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But few others at Mr. Eagan's looked away from their lunch
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Just around the corner from the White House, Michael Black
served breakfast at the Old Ebbitt Grill, one of Washington's most
popular political hangouts. The restaurant decided not to air the
president's testimony out of fear the eatery might appear partisan
and because language in the testimony might be offensive. Black
said it was a good decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a waiter. I work for the public so I know I'll be offended
today,'' he said. ``I don't need any more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to this story was Cox Washington bureau
correspondent Shannon Joyce as well as Angela Shah of the Austin
American-Statesman, Mark England of the Waco Tribune-Herald and a
team of reporters for the Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
