<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE     09-21 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEATTLE, SORROW FOR THE U.S. AND BEGRUDGING RESPECT FOR
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MONICA,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT,
CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(js) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seventy-eight-year-old Margaret Watkins does not like
Bill Clinton, never voted for him and is angry that the leader of
the free world ``basically let his libido get the best of him.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as she sat transfixed before the television Monday
morning, Mrs. Watkins found herself doing something she had never
done before in her life: she was cheering Bill Clinton on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe the way they keep boring in on the man with
all these crazy questions,'' she said after Clinton, for roughly
the eighth time, parried a question from prosecutors about whether
he had received oral sex from Monica Lewinsky. ``I don't know how
he's standing up under all this pressure, but he does it. He must
have nerves of steel. It's amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know,'' Mrs. Watkins said with a rueful chuckle, ``you
do need someone as president who can withstand the pressure. I
don't like him, but I'll say this for him: he doesn't crack. We do
need that in our president.''
</P>
<P>
   As residents of the Ida Culver House, a retirement home in
Seattle's Ravenna neighborhood, gathered around a big-screen
television in the home's main living room Monday morning and
watched the president's videotaped grand jury testimony, a grudging
respect for him was one of the themes that emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Another, even as many residents admitted they found the
testimony to be riveting, was a clear sense of sadness that the
country was being put through the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a different world these days, I guess,'' said Nancy
Cadley, 77, a retired nurse who served in a medical unit in World
War II and the Korean War. ``Could you ever imagine President
Roosevelt being persecuted like that, getting asked questions about
his sex life? I can't imagine that. It's unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sun-dappled morning, Ms. Cadley spent most of the morning
just outside the room, picking flowers for table centerpieces and
restocking bird seed in the courtyard, but even she could not
resist peeking in a time or two to watch the president.
</P>
<P>
   There were certainly a few residents who disliked Clinton so
much they were glad to see him on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reap what you sow,'' said one woman who spoke on condition
that only her first name, Elizabeth, be revealed and who stormed
out of the room after watching for a few moments. ``I think he's a
_ well, I can't say it. He's a dirty rat. He lies, he lies, he
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   But among those who stayed, a much more common sentiment was
anger at the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is a ploy,'' said Robert Kleitsch, 84, a
retired government lawyer. ``It's a fraud. These people are using
our judicial system to try to get rid of a political opponent, in
my opinion, and that's a very very bad thing for our country, for
our whole system. A very troubling thing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Howard Laurine, 85, a retired metallurgist for Boeing who was
visibly angry, said afterward that he believed prosecutors were
crucifying the president and he was infuriated that they were using
his tax money to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he sinned and everything, but this has nothing to do
with his job,'' Laurine said. ``This is just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas C.L. Stockdale, a retired vice president for American
Airlines, said : ``Would you listen to these questions? They're
going into an awful lot of silly details. I think it's a
disgraceful display of bad taste. This man is the president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire Freiheit, 82, a registered nurse who worked in Cleveland
and St. Augustine, Fla., before retiring here after her husband's
death, is a proud Republican who never voted for Clinton. As she
watched Monday morning, though, she forgot all about politics and
simply wondered about the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a nurse, I feel for him,'' Mrs. Freiheit said. ``I think
he has a problem and he needs something, but I don't know exactly
what. He needs a lot of love, but I don't know where he will get
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
