<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Florida Marlins
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight and Wednesday at 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV: TBS will televise tonight. Fox Sports South will televise
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP Kevin Millwood (16-8,
4.16; 0-1, 8.59 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. RHP Rafael Medina (2-4,
6.43; first appearance vs. Braves). Wednesday, RHP John Smoltz
(16-3, 2.99; 7-2, 3.32 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. LHP Kirt Ojala
(2-6, 3.93; 1-1, 4.50 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 40-32 but is
4-12 at Florida since the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The clubs are 5-5 this season. Florida has
compiled a 2-4 record at Turner Field; the Braves dropped three of
four in a July series at Pro Player. In their last meeting, when
the Braves took two of three on Sept. 11-13 in Atlanta, the Marlins
were outscored 17-10. The only Florida victory game in the final
game, when the Marlins riddled rookie left-hander Odalis Perez and
Adam Butler for six runs in the last three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins leaders: Avg.: Mike Redmond (.324); HRs _ Cliff Floyd
(22); RBIs _ Floyd (90); SBs _ Edgar Renteria (41). Wins _ Livan
Hernandez and Brian Meadows (10); ERA _ Matt Mantei (3.08). Saves _
Mantei (9). Strikeouts _ Hernandez (160).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: A season that has been historic for all the wrong
reasons is nearly over for Florida. For the first time in history,
a reigning World Series champion has lost 100 games. Many are to
blame, but few of them ever tasted the champagne. The Marlins have
used 27 rookies this season, 17 on the pitching staff, which the
Elias Sports Bureau says is a record since 1961, which it terms the
Expansion Era. The previous high for rookie participation had been
the 1969 San Diego Padres with 25. . . . Despite the 51-105 record,
worst in the majors, the Marlins just completed a competitive
series in New York. The Mets, in the middle of the wild-card race,
lost the first game 7-6 and struggled out of a bases-loaded jam in
the ninth to win 4-3 Saturday. The Mets won 5-0 on Sunday. The
Marlins, who completed a long 3-10 road trip on Sept. 7, are 4-14
this month and have won consecutive games just once dating back to
Aug. 13. . . . Medina, a rookie who like Bruce Chen is from Panama,
has been somewhat effective since he was restored to the rotation
in late August. He is 2-3 in six starts dating back to Aug. 20,
during which time he has yielded more than four runs only once. The
Marlins scored just one run behind him in three of those losses.
But control is a problem. In his last 16 1/3 innings, Medina has
walked 32 men. . . . CF Cliff Floyd, the club's top run-producer,
hopes to be available tonight after being carted off the field in
New York on Sunday, after a collision with SS Alex Gonzalez while
chasing a fly ball. He was to have an MRI on his right leg Monday.
. . . On the DL: 2B Craig Counsell (compound fractured jaw), RHP
Alex Fernandez (rotator cuff surgery), RHP Joe Fontenot (sore right
shoulder), INF Kevin Millar (broken left wrist).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: Floyd is hitting .381 this month with four homers and
four doubles. RF Mark Kotsay has 25 hits in his last 72 at-bats
(.347) with 12 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Catcher Greg Zaun's average is down to .199, 60
points below his career average. Nine of the 22 pitchers Florida
has used this year have ERAs in excess of 6.00. Sixteen of them
have more hits allowed than innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
