</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORDS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, PROSECUTORS SKIRMISH OVER PRECISE MEANINGS OF WORDS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From an opening skirmish over the meaning of the
``whole truth'' in the oath he had just taken, President Clinton
spent much of his grand jury appearance last Aug. 17 sparring with
prosecutors over definitions of terms.
</P>
<P>
   When does sex become ``sexual relations,'' what it means to be
``alone'' and even the meaning of ``is'' became major points of
contention in the videotaped testimony broadcast to the nation
Monday, as the president tried to head off charges that he perjured
himself in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors pressed Clinton for a concession that he had sat by
silently while his lawyer in a deposition last January read an
incorrect statement that ``there is absolutely no sex of any kind
in any manner, shape or form'' between Clinton and Lewinsky, a
former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what the meaning of the world 'is' is,'' Clinton
told the grand jury. He insisted that the statement was ``correct''
because when he gave the January deposition in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment suit, what he termed his ``improper intimate
contact'' with Lewinsky had already ended.
</P>
<P>
   And was this improper contact a sexual relationship?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was not. ``These encounters did not consist of
sexual intercourse,'' which he said was essential in the definition
given in the Jones deposition last January, when he denied having a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Jones, apparently concerned that the president would
use semantic arguments to dodge questions, had given Clinton an
explicit definition of sexual relations as ``contact'' with
specific parts of another person's body ``to arouse or gratify the
sexual desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by prosecutors before the grand jury, Clinton
acknowledged that touching a breast with intent to arouse, kissing
the breast or touching the genitalia would fit the Jones' lawyers'
definition. But not oral sex, ``if performed on the deponent,'' he
said, using the legal term to refer to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned further, he said that oral sex does not fit the
lawyers' definition of ``sexual relationship'' if he were only the
recipient and not the performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, Paula Jones' lawyers pulled out that definition, not
me,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors working with Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
tried to corner Clinton on whether he had lied in saying earlier
that he had no recollection of being alone with Lewinsky, the
president took refuge in a definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, again, it depends on how you define alone,'' he said.
Admitting that he had been alone with Lewinsky in the Oval Office
suite, he pointed to the many aides and stewards that work around
him. ``So, there were a lot of times when we were alone, but I
never really thought we were,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton complained that deputy independent counsel Sol Wisenberg
had sharply questioned him at the outset on whether he knew was
telling the ``whole truth'' was.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to that topic later, the president said, ``You tried
to get me to give a broader interpretation to my oath than just my
obligation to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
