<HEADER>
A6812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX     09-21 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even with recent slide, Galarraga on brink of new Braves record
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- The certainties of mid-summer have faded upon Andres
Galarraga, who for several months rode hard with Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa but now wonders who moved the fences. He already has
churned out the most productive season by any Braves first baseman,
but while the heavy artillery still rumbles somewhere over the
horizon, Galarraga has cooled in the final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still ranking among the National League's top five home-run
hitters with 43, Galarraga enters the season's last week in his
longest power slide of the year -- 14 games spanning 45 at-bats.
Before his last homer on Sept. 6 off New York's Jeff Tam, Galarraga
had been letting one fly once every 11.5 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   As the Braves conclude their last road trip with a two-game
series with Florida tonight, it nearly has been forgotten he was in
line to break the franchise home-run record. Will this Summer of
the Thumper end with Galarraga muted?
</P>
<P>
   ``How many does he need to get the record?'' Chipper Jones
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Three to tie, he's told.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could do that before we get home,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no idle talk. Fighting through the 3-for-21 slump,
Galarraga found his stroke in the final three games in Arizona,
notching six straight hits in one sequence that included two
doubles and a triple to deepest center at Bank One Ballpark that
probably would have cleared the fence at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   He takes his streak to Pro Player Stadium, one of his fondest
venues where has a .310 career average and has hit nine home runs,
more than any visiting player. So it could happen. With five games
to play and his swing coming around, Galarraga can still catch
Eddie Mathews, who set the record in Milwaukee in 1953, and Hank
Aaron, who tied it in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not having any thoughts to break a record like that,''
said Galarraga, who already has more homers than any
right-handed-hitting Braves player in 11 years. ``I know I've been
struggling a little bit the last two weeks. But (the record) is in
my head. I think about it a little bit. But you can't think about
breaking a record.''
</P>
<P>
   History suggests Galarraga has a chance. He has gone through two
droughts this season that reached double-digit games, and when he
broke out, it was noisy. After going 11 games in late-June without
a homer, he hit back-to-back homers in the 12th game in his first
two at-bats on June 30. It was one of his eight two-homer games
this season. After a second slowdown from July 25 to Aug. 5,
Galarraga homered three times in his next 12 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's that type of guy,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``He's hot
right now and when he gets hot, he can carry you for weeks. He's
already had a solid season.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga surpassed the franchise record for homers by a Braves
first baseman -- Joe Adcock with 38 in 1956 -- after 119 games. His
next RBI, 119, will break a franchise record for first baseman that
has lasted 109 years. Dan Brouthers set the record of 118 in 1889
with the Boston Beaneaters. Galarraga already has more homers than
any Atlanta right-handed hitter since Dale Murphy's 44-homer season
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But the franchise homer record carries its own cachet. Mathews
set the record in 154 games in the club's first season in
Milwaukee, when he finished second to Brooklyn's Roy Campanella in
the MVP voting. Aaron tied it in the same year he reached 600
homers, although he played only 139 games, because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it's a prominent neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are pretty good,'' Jones said. ``If he sees his
pitches, he's going to hit 'em. But I think he was, like everybody
there for a while, struggling for a period. Just a little out of
sync. He seems to be getting it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had just come off his three-day suspension on Sept. 6,
when he homered to lead off the ninth inning at Shea Stadium
against the Mets during Atlanta's worst road trip of the year.
Plenty has happened since then. The Braves clinched their seventh
division title; McGwire and Sosa left for the home-run
stratosphere, and Cal Ripken's streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put any more pressure than I feel right now,''
Galarraga said. ``I've got to get in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   He appears to be already there.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVES 40-HR SEASONS
