<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-BORIS-COX     09-21 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BORIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russian hits paydirt in U.S. soil rich with female athletes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ He is a Marxian nightmare: proletariat turned
entrepreneur. A political system crumbles in one country, women's
athletics booms in another, and Boris Lelchitski spins himself into
something utterly foreign to his former comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He is a coach. He is a talent scout. He is a player agent and a
tour director and an expert in the import-export business _ whether
it be flying a team here or shipping a player there. He says he
isn't swimming in wealth, but he does drive a Lexus and has a
working knowledge of tax deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, mother Russia; hello, mother lode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for even me to believe this,'' Lelchitski said.
``When I go back to Russia, it is hard for me to explain to people
what I do. Being in the service industry, it is hard to explain
that I'm not selling cucumbers on the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   It is only explained by the growth of women's basketball in the
U.S., which has spawned a cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1990, Lelchitski was speaking only his native Russian,
living in historic St. Petersburg and coaching women's basketball.
He was doing what he had always wanted, living a good life with his
wife and two young sons. But the fragmenting of the Soviet Union,
the dissolution of Communist rule and the collapse of the
government-backed sports support system changed the political and
economic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The Turning, as Germans refer to the post-Berlin Wall era, hit
women's athletics particularly hard. ``Women have a very tough time
now because everything is a wild capitalism,'' Lelchitski said.
``If you don't have a sponsor, that's it. There is no Title IX or
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lelchitski did not think he would lose his job, but he and his
wife felt it best to explore other options. That led them far from
St. Petersburg. Natalie Lelchitski went to work at the University
of South Carolina and moved to Columbia with one son. Boris and the
other son came eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was taking a leave of absence,'' he said. ``But
when I came here, I stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   What little English Lelchitski spoke resulted from private
lessons in Russia. And when he arrived here, Southern accents made
it especially difficult to understand his new language. ``I went to
a gas station,'' he recalled, ``and when that (employee) opened her
mouth, I thought, 'Gosh, I must be taking the wrong language.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But he got a job coaching girls basketball. He organized an AAU
program, the Carolina Shooting Stars, which has grown to 100 kids
and six teams, four of them girls.
</P>
<P>
   Lelchitski had intended to pursue a college assistant job.
``Then I realized being 40 years old and a male coach in women's
basketball is a tough sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't a tough sale was Lelchitski's startup business in
1996: the European Basketball Report. His brief involvement with
AAU tournaments and camps, along with the influx of foreigners into
the college game, suggested a need for a scouting service so
coaches could learn about such players seeking scholarships. In the
first year, 35 college coaches paid $425 a year for a quarterly
newsletter detailing 35 to 50 athletes. The rate is up to $475.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players with ties to Lelchitski is Georgia freshman
forward Elena Vishniakova, a St. Petersburg native he coached at
Heathwood Hall in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   One business led to another. When he traveled overseas to scout
players, Lelchitski would notice U.S. coaches doing the same. He
had taken his Heathwood Hall team to St. Petersburg in 1994 for
exhibitions and the Goodwill Games, and now he wondered: If I can
organize one tour for kids, why not organize another for coaches _
and for profit?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he sold 35 coaches on the idea of attending a
tournament in Hungary. Lelchitski figures he pocketed 15 to 20
percent of every $1,490 fee. In July, he took 45 coaches to Moscow
for the World Youth Games and Turkey for the women's world
championships. Cost: $2,490 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty tough to go to places like Turkey if you don't
know where to go or speak the language,'' Lelchitski said.
``Coaches will get to see 350 of the best kids from all over the
world. So for anybody interesting in international recruiting, it's
definitely worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lelchitski played tour guide for the Virginia women's
team, arranging for sightseeing and a few exhibition games in
France and Italy for a week. Twenty-three passengers paid $2,800
each. Approximate profit: $11,000. Georgia, Connecticut, Notre
Dame, Duke and North Carolina have signed up for a tour next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   European women's national teams approached him to set up
exhibition games in the U.S., paying him $1,500 to $3,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Lelchitski is a partner in Global Sports Management in
Hartford, Conn., serving as the agent for about 20 pro players,
male and female.
</P>
<P>
   Lelchitski's company, Sports International Group, is less than
two years old. It consists of Boris and his assistant _ Natasha.
Lelchitski does not operate a monopoly. Other people in his adopted
country have started scouting services or tours. But few, if any,
are as diversified as he is.
</P>
<P>
   None of it would have been possible without the growth of
women's athletics, something inconceivable in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now, when I go back and I talk to people, they don't
believe me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To quote Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma, who subscribes to
Lelchitski's services: ``That's the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
