</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MOORE-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A record for the ages from a guy just doing his job
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, Dad isn't impressed. Just before he left his official home
in Milwaukee for his unofficial one along any fairway, he said
Monday over the phone about Cal Ripken Jr., ending his streak of
consecutive games played at 2,632, ``Out of all the records out
there, this one really doesn't mean as much. You're supposed to go
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Dad can say such a thing. While Ripken took his
first day off Sunday in nearly 16 years, Dad once worked 31
consecutive years without missing a millisecond at AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' said Dad, 66, chuckling, ``It would have been 38 1/2
consecutive years if I didn't have to take a few weeks off to have
surgery on my knees in the early 1980s. All you have to do is stay
healthy. That's what I did, and that's what Ripken did during his
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, sort of. Since I never argue with Dad -- who likes to say
that he only retired because work was getting in the way of his
golf game -- I'll change the subject for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've heard that Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have soared
by Babe Ruth and Roger Maris in the category of home runs for a
season. They've done so with only open skies ahead. Still, somebody
will rise higher than the universe reached by McGwire or Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   As for Henry Aaron's No. 755, even Hammering Hank says Ken
Griffey Jr. is capable of surviving and prospering during the next
decade to own more homers than anybody in history.
</P>
<P>
   On and on, we could go, debating the chances of somebody ever
rivaling everything from Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak to
the number of times Harry Caray sang ``Take Me Out to the Ball
Game.'' But all the debating ends when we're referring to the
events of Sunday, Sept. 20, 1998, in Baltimore's Camden Yards.
There, Ripken told his bosses that he wished not to have his name
on a lineup card for the Baltimore Orioles for the first time since
early during his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   When Ripken's world realized what was happening, it responded
with many of the hugs and kisses that the slugging infielder
received three years ago, when he became better than Lou Gehrig's
2,130.
</P>
<P>
   This time, instead of Ripken taking a victory lap to slap hands
with hometown fans, he tipped his cap to the New York Yankees
applauding in the other dugout in the first inning. Then he
accepted a hearty standing ovation before quickly becoming just
another guy on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really takes a special set of circumstances to get to this
point,'' Ripken said later, always in his soft tones. ``You have to
have a great determination to be in the lineup. There must be a
love of the game. You also have to have a degree of stubbornness.
Everything has to go your way. If I can do it, somebody else can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, baseball can take Ripken's ``2,632'' and chisel it
into the record books forever. All you need to know is that Albert
Belle is the game's new iron man by entering his 328th consecutive
game Monday night. Belle must work 15 more seasons in a row before
having the chance to pass Ripken around Belle's 47th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   To catch Dad, Belle must work every day just shy of an eternity,
and then Belle needs a 6 handicap in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore's column appears in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
