</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-EXEC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New hire completes Delta's top brass
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The new executive lineup at Delta Air Lines is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta on Monday said it hired Robert L. Colman as
executive vice president-human resources, filling the last top
echelon spot opened by Chief Executive Leo Mullin's management
reshuffling.
</P>
<P>
   Colman, 53, comes from a similar position at General Electric
Engines in Cincinnati. He starts work at Delta next month.
</P>
<P>
   He'll oversee personnel issues and labor relations. Key tasks
include continuing efforts to repair morale, keeping peace with the
airline's powerful pilots union and staving off other organizing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will shape our human resource programs and policies to
ensure that Delta attracts and retains the best possible work
force,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Colman is the third executive vice president hired by Mullin
since he arrived at Delta a year ago. The others are finance chief
Warren Jenson and marketing chief Fred Reid.
</P>
<P>
   All three came from outside Delta, which until the early '90s
promoted most of its top executives from within. Of Delta's top
five officers, the only two who still fit that description are
Chief Operating Officer Maurice Worth and operations chief Harry
Alger.
</P>
<P>
   Colman replaces Robert G. Adams, who joined Delta from Pan Am in
1991 and left the airline in May at age 60.
</P>
<P>
   Colman began his career at Ford Motor Co. and had been with
General Electric since 1980. Jenson, the new finance chief, also
came from a GE unit, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Colman brings an impressive academic resume. He has a political
science degree from prestigious Bates College in Maine, a law
degree from Vanderbilt University, and an MBA in industrial
relations from the Wharton School of Business at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
