<SLUG> BC-GEORGES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georges pounds Puerto Rico; Dominican Republic, Haiti brace for
disaster
 &HT;    By Shelley Emling
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Georges charged across Puerto Rico late
Monday, packing winds of 110 mph and churning 20-foot seas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 people sought shelter in schools and public
buildings in Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands, and the U.S.
territories declared states of emergency while activating National
Guard troops. The storm knocked out electrical service and forced
many families to huddle in basements and walk-in closets.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello banned liquor sales, ordered a
price freeze on items such as water, candles and matches, and had
officials prepare more than 300 shelters on the island of 3.8
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really nervous because we remember the damage done
by Hugo,'' said Mary McClintock, a resident of San Juan, Puerto
Rico, who planned to take refuge in her cement home's walk-in
closet. Hurricane Hugo killed more than two dozen people when it
ripped through the Caribbean in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Georges began pounding Caribbean islands overnight Sunday,
starting with the French territory of Guadeloupe, where the storm
uprooted trees as if they were houseplants.
</P>
<P>
   Georges also ripped off roofs, tore down phone lines, and
knocked out electrical service on Antigua, St. Croix, and St. Kitts
and Nevis, but no injuries or deaths were immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   Georges was expected late Monday to hit Puerto Rico's capital of
San Juan, where nearly half the island's population lives.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's strength had dwindled since early Sunday, when the
hurricane sustained winds of 150 mph, but the U.S. National
Hurricane Center warned that Georges _ a strong Category 2
hurricane _ was still ``extremely dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
