<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern buying plant to aid Texas presence
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co., gaining a foothold in Texas, is
purchasing a small electric power plant near Fort Worth to back up
its wholesale energy trading business.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based utility holding company announced Monday an
agreement to purchase an 80-megawatt natural gas-fueled plant from
Wichita Falls Energy Co. Ltd. of Fort Worth. The plant is in
Wichita Falls, 130 miles northwest of Fort Worth, and it supplies
steam to the Vetrotex CertainTeed Corp. fiberglass plant there.
</P>
<P>
   The deal marks Southern's first electricity-generating purchase
in Texas. It also puts the company on the home ground of
Houston-based Enron Corp., which is increasingly Southern's rival
in energy markets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has targeted four regions for the purchase or
construction of power plants to boost its growing wholesale trading
business. The four regions are the Northeast, California and the
desert Southwest states, Texas and the Upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a highly competitive generator and will give us a
presence in the extremely important Texas energy market,'' said
Thomas Boren, president of Southern Energy Inc. That is the
subsidiary making the purchase, and it will also market power from
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The plant consists of three gas turbines and one steam turbine,
fueled by natural gas transported by the Lonestar pipeline.
Southern takes ownership in October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
