<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-DROPOUTS-COX     09-21 1652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-DROPOUTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overcoming barriers: Hispanics look within to curtail dropout
rate
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Guillermo Rodriguez looks at 11-year-old Domingo
Vargas, a bright but shy native of Mexico struggling to adapt to a
new culture, he remembers his own adolescence, when he moved from
Colombia at 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a little awkward and out of place. I had to learn
English and become accustomed to the U.S. culture. There were
difficult times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With support from his parents, he graduated high school and
college, and got a master's degree from Georgia Tech. Today, at 24,
Rodriguez is an industrial engineer at Lucent Technologies in
Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure he does well in school. I want him to know
there are opportunities for him,'' said Rodriguez, who has been a
mentor to Domingo since January.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Rodriguez wants to be sure Domingo doesn't
join the ranks of so many other Hispanic children in metro Atlanta
and throughout the state who have dropped out of school because of
language barriers, the lure of a paycheck or lack of support at
home.
</P>
<P>
   While Georgia's Hispanic population is expected to double by
2025 to 346,000, according to the Census Bureau, no state program
exists to prevent Hispanic dropouts. And in metro Atlanta, which
had 17,742 Hispanic students during the 1996-97 school year, only a
handful of such programs exist, organized by individual schools or
the Latin American Association.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97 in Georgia, the Hispanic dropout rate was 7.2 percent
for students in grades 7-12, according to the Council for School
Performance, a state-funded agency that monitors public schools but
is not under the Education Department. The overall dropout rate in
Georgia was 5.2 percent. The Hispanic dropout rate was greater than
that of other ethnic groups in seven of the 10 school systems with
the most Hispanic students. Most of those schools are in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the Hispanic dropout rate is about 20 percent,
according to the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a problem here,'' said Maritza Keen, executive
director of the Latin American Association. ``In cities like
Atlanta, where the Latino community is growing, we will quickly
reflect what's happening nationally. If we don't stop it when the
percentages are small, it will become a bigger problem later.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hamann, who studied Hispanic students in Georgia public
schools for his doctoral dissertation, said state educators are
still trying to figure out how to cope with the influx of Hispanic
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought process statewde is still at a pretty beginner
stage,'' he said. ``The bulk of the state seems to be only just
beginning to explore what it means to have Hispanics here. In some
cases, educating the parents is critical. In other cases, you have
second and third generation Hispanics with different needs. It is
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few metro Atlanta schools with high Hispanic enrollment,
educators are scrambling to find ways to keep students in school.
</P>
<P>
   At Marietta High School, where 10 percent of the student body is
Hispanic, guidance counselor Dulce Gonzalez helped to organize a
program so that in the past two years, 20 Hispanic students with
good grades and attendance could study U.S. government, act as
mentors and tutors to younger Hispanic children and raise money to
spend a week in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Students who made the trip gained confidence and became more
involved in school because they felt as if they were really part of
the student body, she said. But she doesn't know whether she can
raise enough money to continue the program this year, she said,
because the trip costs each student $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   At Cross Keys High School in DeKalb County, 31 percent of the
student body is Hispanic. ``Our Latino population is growing at a
rapid rate, but it's still kind of new for us,'' said Principal Tim
Freeman, who described several programs designed to help Hispanic
students. Still, he said, ``it's difficult to reach every student
who needs help.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our Latino kids have so many things going on, as far
as having to work to support the family. Some of them work 30 to 40
hours a week and still go to school. Many have significant
responsibilities at home, taking care of brothers and sisters,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics drop out for many other reasons, including language
and cultural barriers, lack of role models, and low expectations
from teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with any child, regardless of ethnic background,
parents are key to the success of children. Marietta's Gonzalez, a
native of Puerto Rico, said she is trying to get more Hispanic
parents involved in school so they understand what is expected of
their children. ``You meet these parents and your heart goes out to
them,'' she said. ``They work two jobs and come home exhausted. Who
has time to ask, `Did you do your homework?'''
</P>
<P>
   Some, she said, do not expect their children to graduate,
because they may not be high school graduates themselves. ``Even
parents when they register say, `All I want is for my child to
learn English.' There is not a long-term goal of a better life that
will impact them in the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American Association's Keen thinks mentoring programs
may encourage more Hispanics to stay in school. The association
hopes to reach 100 students, ages 8 to 21, through internship and
mentoring programs in several Georgia counties this year, she said.
The goal is to match successful Hispanic business people with
Hispanic students who need role models.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said mentoring is a social responsibility. ``I always
wanted to help children because they are the future of our
community,'' said Rodriguez, who meets weekly with Domingo and his
8-year-old sister, Edith.
</P>
<P>
   The internships also help. ``We get kids saying to us, `If I
wasn't doing this internship, I'm not sure I would still be in
school,''' said Keen. ``There are a lot of youth programs out
there, but not for Latinos. They are the forgotten, the invisible
group.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, a national commission appointed by Education
Secretary Richard Riley finished a three-year study of the issue.
The Hispanic dropout rate is ``shockingly and unacceptably high,''
the panel concluded. ``Dropouts diminish our democracy, our society
and their own opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report, called ``No More Excuses,'' the panel said
today's dropout rate for Hispanics is 2.5 times the rate for blacks
and 3.5 times the rate for white non-Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Education officials said they are concerned
about every student who drops out, but they do not believe
Georgia's Hispanic dropout rate is high. One official, however,
said he was surprised at the Hispanic dropout figures for school
systems with high Hispanic enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some areas here that need to be targeted,'' said
Roan Garcia-Quintana, director of the state's English to Speakers
of Other Languages programs and Title I federal programs to assist
low-income students. ``You've got some disparity here.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, he said, is not a program to prevent Hispanic
dropouts, but more emphasis on getting all children to master
reading and math in elementary school. ``Have the same high
expectations for everybody and go in early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within the educational system and among advocates for Hispanic
students, many believe educators and administrators may not be
aware of how many Hispanics are dropping out because they are
tackling so many other issues and this is not a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have an issue like this that's somewhat isolated
in spots across the state, it probably doesn't get on the agenda
the way that more pervasive problems like reading scores do,'' said
Gary Henry, director of the Council for School Performance. Keen
said many schools are preoccupied with other problems, such as
school violence. ``The Hispanic dropout rate is another problem on
top of all the other issues they have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hamann said, some educators think Hispanic students
are here temporarily, so they do not need special help.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Gonzalez, a migrant education counselor in southwest
Georgia, said he has heard educators refer to migrant children,
most of whom are Mexican, as ``your kids'' and all other students
as ``our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic students ``present a special challenge for the whole
school system,'' he said. ``It's easier to push them under the rug.
We're trying to get them (educators) to accept that they are
responsible for all students in their school system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez speaks from experience. The fourth of nine children
born to Mexican migrant workers, he earned straight A's but dropped
out of school in 9th grade. He was 17. ``I was just too old to have
three more years of school,'' he said. ``Besides, with the
lifestyle we had, I had to help provide for the family. The income
was needed.''
</P>
<P>
   A high school guidance counselor encouraged him to get his GED
and enroll in college. He got a degree in criminal justice from
Georgia Southern University, becoming the first college graduate in
his family. This summer, he got a master's degree in education
administration from Columbus State University.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, he has worked in Americus for the
federally funded Georgia Migrant Education Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get them to think about what they want to be doing
two or three years from now. I tell them that it will help them
more in the long run if they stay in school,'' said Gonzalez, 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret dropping out. I missed out on a lot,'' he said. ``Now
I feel like I am contributing something good. I am a
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
