A6824 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-ARREST-BOS &LR;      09-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA LEADER SEEN UNTOUCHED AMID UNREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.  R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The arrest of Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister Sunday night, and a crackdown on his supporters Monday,
may stoke anti-government sentiment for the moment. But many
analysts say the movement is unlikely to threaten the hold of
Asia's longest-serving leader, Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   Government critics Monday denounced the arrest of the sacked
deputy prime minister, Anwar Ibrahim, on sodomy charges. They
described it as a desperate bid by a power-crazy Mahathir to
discredit credible opposition. Anwar allies pointed to protests
that have drawn thousands as proof that Malaysia is ripe for a
movement like the one that pressured Indonesian President Suharto
to step down last May.
</P>
<P>
   But other observers have asserted that Malaysia's economic
problems are not as extreme as Indonesia's, nor is Mahathir an
autocrat to rival Suharto, even though he has a firm grip on
police, courts and the press. Those factors, as well as a
preference among Malaysians for a calm transition through
elections, make people less likely to take to the streets in
prolonged protest _ especially behind a longtime senior official
who only now is calling for ``reformasi,'' the term first used by
Indonesians calling for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is hard to dismiss two days of demonstrations by
thousands in a nation that has not seen such large-scale protests
in at least 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the beginning of a massive change. Anwar's
case has been a catalyst for uprising. A lot of grassroots are
supporting him because they identify with his problems _ a lack of
access to media, to any social space,'' said Tian Chua, a spokesman
for a human rights group known as SUARAM, the initials for the
Voice of the Malaysian People. ``Even if Mahathir uses his usual
tactics of terror and repression, this time it might not be as
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, police chased and fired tear gas at 5,000 people who had
gathered at a courthouse in the capital to protest Anwar's arrest.
Anwar, whose image is that of pious family man, was to be charged
Monday with indecency _ charges he has denied, despite confessions
and convictions of two men who said they participated in sodomy
with him. The accusations first surfaced over a year ago, but
Mahathir defended Anwar until his protege challenged him at a party
congress three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the arrest for sodomy, Anwar was held Monday under the
Internal Security Act, on charges of having led rallies without
police permission since he was removed from office on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, about 35,000 to 50,000 people massed at the National
Mosque to hear Anwar, who is identified with Islam and with
Western-style economic policies. Witnesses said several thousand
listeners marched from Merdeka, or Freedom, Square to Mahathir's
home, chanting for his resignation. Mahathir has been prime
minister for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested top Anwar allies Monday, and detained at least
50 street protesters. Two politicians and four student activists
who supported Anwar were held under the Internal Security Act,
raising fears of a crackdown like one in 1987, when more than 100
government critics were detained without trial. Anwar was a senior
official when the security act was invoked against his former
opposition comrades.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions coincided with a visit by Britain's Queen Elizabeth
II and the close of the Commonwealth Games, hosted in Asia for the
first time. Kuala Lumpur's blue-chip stock index fell 3.8 percent
on anxiety over the unrest.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more important to the future of the protest movement
than the record of Anwar, its main symbol, are the contrasts
between Malaysia and Indonesia, where a popular movement managed to
bring down an autocrat.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts note that the socioeconomic gulf between rich and poor
is far more dramatic in Indonesia than in Malaysia, making an
uprising against economic meltdown less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra Muzaffar, professor of political science at the
University of Malaya, noted that while Indonesia had a
``quasi-military regime,'' Malaysia has had a civilian government,
which has ``made way for democratic space.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mahathir lost an election for parliament in '69, so he's been
in power and out of power. You can't compare that to Suharto who
was never elected. That said, there are concerns about increasing
centralization of power...and some institutions are not being run
the way they should _ the Attorney General's office, courts,'' said
Muzaffar.
</P>
<P>
   But whether a movement to change those institutions can sustain
itself ``is a very big question now that Anwar is out of the
picture,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
