<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE-HNS     09-21 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TESTIMONY BOLSTERS BOTH SIDES IN IMPEACHMENT STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony
fortified both his critics and defenders Monday, with his stubborn
legalistic dueling with prosecutors matched by expressions of
regret for his actions and concern for embattled White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, battling 11 allegations of impeachable offensives
submitted to Congress earlier this month by special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr, jousted with federal prosecutors during four hours
and six minutes of tedious testimony that had been relayed to grand
jurors by closed circuit hookup from the White House on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton quibbled with prosecutors over whether oral sex
performed on him by former White House intern Monica Lewinsky fell
within an agreed definition of ``sexual relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted it did not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contended that he and Lewinsky could truthfully deny
having carried on ``sexual relations'' under a definition endorsed
by U.S. District Court Judge Susan Webber Wright in Paula Jones'
$700,000 civil suit against the president because they had not had
sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to discuss how his semen got on Lewinsky's blue
cocktail dress, telling deputy special counsel Robert J. Bittman:
``That's a question you already know the answer to.''
</P>
<P>
   When the questions zeroed in on sexual details, Clinton refused
to respond beyond noting that his opening statement to grand jurors
had included an elliptical admission that he had engaged in
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Lewinsky during ``certain
occasions'' in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The opening statement said: ``These encounters did not consist
of sexual intercourse; they did not constitute sexual relations as
I understood that term to be defined at my Jan. 17, 1998
deposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would not respond to certain questions because
they would be ``forever in the historic annals of the United
States.'' Clinton added: ``I just think it's a mistake. And so, I'm
doing my best to cooperate with the grand jury and still protect
myself, my family, and my office.''
</P>
<P>
   The president challenged Starr's motives, portraying himself as
a victim of an open ended ``four-year, $40 million investigation''
by Starr that has ``come down to parsing the definition of sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decried a nationwide ``dragnet of discovery'' used by
Jones' lawyers to search for other women to support Jones'
since-dismissed sexual harassment suit against him.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' lawyers were eager to drag in Lewinsky ``so they could
hurt me politically,'' Clinton insisted. ``They just thought that
they would take a wrecking ball to me and see if they could do some
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Clinton claimed lapses in his legendary memory
when Starr's prosecutors politely questioned him. Clinton said he
``didn't have perfect memory of all these events'' that, he said
sarcastically, have ``become the most important matters in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he trusted the recollections of allies such as
lawyer Vernon Jordan and subordinates such as personal secretary
Betty Currie, Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles or Deputy Chief of
Staff John Podesta more than his own memories.
</P>
<P>
   At tense moments during his testimony, Clinton's face flushed
red; his gaze turned steely; his answers narrowed to a single word
or two; his hands struck defensive poses, clasped before his face
or folded with his arms across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sipped a glass of water or a can of Diet Coke at moments
of tension.
</P>
<P>
   The president firmly refused prosecutors' appeals on behalf of
grand jurors to continue the testimony beyond the four hours agreed
to in a deal with Starr that permitted Clinton to remain at the
White House with the support of three lawyers rather than being
forced to appear before a grand jury at a federal court house a
dozen blocks away, without lawyers present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could do it,'' Clinton said. ``But we made an
agreement that was different, and I think I will go ahead and stick
with the terms of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed empathy for his personal secretary, Currie, who had
been called to testify before Starr's grand jury amid her grieving
over the deaths of a sister and a brother. Starr's prosecutors
sought to paint Clinton's dealings with Currie as an effort to
cover up his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt terrible because she had been through this loss of her
sister, this horrible accident (at) Christmas that killed her
brother and her mother was in the hospital,'' Clinton said. ``I was
trying to do _ to make her understand that I didn't want her to be
untruthful to the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended Christmas season gifts to Lewinsky in December,
1997 as an act of friendship rather than an attempt to influence
her upcoming testimony in Jones' law suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had for nearly a year done my best to be a friend to Miss
Lewinsky _ to be a counselor to her, to give her good advice and to
help her,'' Clinton testified.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, claiming that he was being as truthful as he could be
without jeopardizing his privacy, told grand jurors: ``You're
dealing with, in some ways, the most mysterious area of human
life,'' adding: ``I'm doing the best I can to give you honest
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my time and energy in the last five and a half years
have been devoted to my job,'' Clinton insisted, gazing straight
into the television hookup to the grand jury at length for the
first time. ``During this whole time, I have tried as best I could
to keep my mind on the job the American people gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton interrupted his testimony from a straight-backed chair
in the historic Map Room of the White House on six occasions for a
total of 76 minutes during testimony that spanned a period of five
hours 22 minutes. The breaks ranged from 5 to 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after completing his closed circuit testimony to the
grand jury on Aug. 17, Clinton went on late-night television to
abandon seven months of denials to publicly admit for the first
time that he ``did have a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was
not appropriate. In fact, it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton subtly raised questions about Lewinsky's state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The president thanked Starr for granting Lewinsky and her mother
Marcia ``sweeping immunity,'' adding that ``it breaks my heart that
she (Lewinsky) was ever involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton equally undercut Lewinsky, saying that after he
broke off their relationship, ``she felt a need to cling more
closely or try to get closer to me.'' Clinton referred to her at
one point as ``obsessive'' having become ``somewhat fixated on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the notes he received from Lewinsky showed that
``there was sort of a disconnect sometimes between what she was
saying and the plain facts of our relationship'' after he ended
their sexual liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared visibly pained when prosecutors suddenly
injected a question about a conversation that Jordan said he had
with the president in which he relayed Lewinsky's belief that
Clinton would leave Hillary Rodham Clinton after the conclusion of
his presidency in order to be with the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you, sir, is I certainly don't remember him
saying that,'' Clinton said. ``Now, he could have said that,
because, as you know, a great many things happened in the ensuing
two or three days. And I could have just forgotten it. But I don't
remember him ever saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans watching the outset of the telecast saw a president
who appeared at times to be cornered by the proceedings. Clinton,
who has twice raised his right hand to be sworn in as president of
the United States, was forced to raise his right hand again to
swear to ``tell ``the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the
truth'' in the first grand jury proceeding in history targeting a
president for alleged criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's eyes darted around the White House Map Room, where he
faced Starr and six other prosecutors; three lawyers from his legal
team and four others.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton shifted nervously in his straight-backed chair on
several occasions. He put on and took off his reading glasses; he
clutched his reading glasses in his hands as he gestured. At one
point, he waved a black pen.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said that Clinton shook hands with his inquisitors at
the outset and conclusion of the session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
