<HEADLINE>
FOUR FROM BAY STATE AMONG FORBES' WEALTHIEST 100 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four Massachusetts business people are listed among Forbes ASAP
magazine's annual ranking of the technology industry's 100
wealthiest individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The state's richest technology tycoon, the magazine says, is
Alan Trefler, 42, founder and chief executive of Pegasystems Inc.,
a Cambridge, Mass. maker of automated customer service software. He
ranked 23d on the list, with an estimated wealth of $583 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the people on the list, however, much of Trefler's
wealth is tied to the value of his stock holdings, and the magazine
calculated its rankings based on stock values as of August 3. Since
then the stock market has tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Trefler, who owns 75 percent of Pegasystems stock, is now worth
about $375 million.
</P>
<P>
   Others from Massachusetts who show up on the list:
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Egan, 62, founder and chairman of Hopkinton-based EMC
Corp., and his wife, Maureen, 61, worth an estimated $365 million
as of Aug. 3. While EMC shares were hammered along with the rest of
the market earlier this month, they have recovered nicely and the
Egans, who own 14 percent of EMC stock, are now worth an estimated
$380 million.
</P>
<P>
   _Patrizio Vinciarelli, 51, chief executive of Vicor Corp. of
Andover, worth an estimated $264.9 million as of Aug. 3. But based
on Monday's closing price, his 20.9 million shares of Vicor are now
worth just $185.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other New Englanders on the list are Cabletron Systems Inc.
co-founders Craig Benson, 43, with holdings of $216.7 million, and
Robert Levine, 40, with an estimated wealth of $102.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   They are not as wealthy as a year ago, however, because
Cabletron stock has slumped as the Rochester, N.H.-based computer
networking company has struggled to compete with larger rivals such
as Cisco Systems and Bay Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock took a beating over the past month, but has recovered
to about the same level as when Forbes ASAP calculated its
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   This year's list is dominated not only by executives from
established technology companies such as Microsoft and Intel, but
also by more than two dozen Internet millionaires who got rich off
their companies' stock offerings. Chances are, they too are a lot
less rich today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
