<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON `QUITE MOVED' AS U.N. DIPLOMATS GIVE BELEAGUERED PRESIDENT
STANDING OVATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ U.N. diplomats stood together Monday to offer
support for a beleaguered President Clinton who appeared before the
General Assembly minutes after the nationwide broadcast began of
his taped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Aides pronounced the president as moved by the rare display in
the normally staid, and sometimes hostile, world body and clearly
hoped it would quiet concerns that Clinton's international stature
had been compromised by his affair with a former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   The president's annual address at the United Nations opening
came just minutes after the House Judiciary Committee released the
four-hour videotape of Clinton's testimony before the grand jury
investigating his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Cable networks
aired the videotape as they received it.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing, and perhaps politically damaging, release of
the videotape vastly overshadowed Clinton's condemnation of
terrorism and his call for a worldwide response. The White House
throughout the day protected the president from reporters'
questions about the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The world's delegations, which included many heads of state such
as South Africa's Nelson Mandela, rose to give Clinton a standing
ovation as he was introduced, a move that the White House
interpreted as a symbol of support on a difficult day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was an expression by the international community of
the stature and regard in which he is held, their affection for him
personally and their very strong sense that strong American
leadership continues to be essential, particularly at a time when
many things are happening in the world that create great
uncertainty,'' said Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, a White House spokesman, said Clinton was ``quite
moved by the warmth and appreciation that was expressed by
diplomats from around the world.'' Lockhart said Clinton did not
see his testimony being broadcast on television.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the world leaders to make the fight against
terrorism a top priority. The United Nations became an island of
security as New York police officers stationed themselves every few
yards and sanitation trucks filled with sand blocked intersections
for blocks around the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to terrorism there should be no dividing line
between Muslims and Jews, Protestants and Catholics, Serbs and
Albanians, developed societies and emerging countries,'' Clinton
said from the dramatic soaring stage at the United Nations. ``The
only dividing line is between those who practice, support or
tolerate terror, and those who understand that it is murder, plain
and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the world should unite to deny terrorists support,
sanctuary and financial assistance; to pressure states that do; to
cooperate on extradition and prosecution; to clamp down on the
manufacture and export of explosives; to beef up international
standards for airport security and enforce a number of existing
conventions on terrorism and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much each of us does alone, our progress will be
limited without our common efforts,'' Clinton said. He declared
terrorism ``a threat to all humankind'' because of the greater
openness in the world and the explosion of information and weapons
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he planned to ask Congress later this week
for an emergency allocation of $1.8 billion to rebuild the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania and to step up anti-terrorism
efforts. U.S. intelligence sources believe a wealthy Saudi exile,
Osama bin Laden, was behind the bombings in Africa and several
other attacks against U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   The United States in August struck back at bin Laden's shadowy
supports, sending cruise missiles to destroy a pharmaceutical plant
in Sudan and to destroy several terrorist training camps in
Afghanistan where bin Laden resides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his address, also took pains to say the fight
against terrorism was not a fight against Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many believe there is an inevitable clash between Western
civilization and Western values and Islamic civilization and
values. I believe this view is terribly wrong,'' Clinton said,
denouncing the ``false prophets'' who abuse religion for political
objectives. ``Americans respect and honor Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   After his address, Clinton met privately with Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif whose nation challenged India in a nuclear
arms race earlier this year. Both nations exploded nuclear devices
despite international pleas against it. Sharif indicated to Clinton
he will say something ``positive'' about the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban treaty later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Sharif told Clinton that the warm reception he
received ``reflects the love and respect the international
community feels for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton met with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, Italian President Romano Prodi,
Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson and Bulgarian President Peter
Stoyanov to talk about strengthening democracy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
