<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-TESTIMONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY CALLS CLINTON HER `SEXUAL SOULMATE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In raw, emotional language, Monica Lewinsky told
grand jurors that ``there's work I need to do on myself,'' and that
it is ``not right'' to have an affair with a married man.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by one grand juror what sustained her sexual relationship
with President Clinton, Lewinsky boldly declared ``I fell in
love.'' And she described her feelings toward Clinton as ``more
love with a little bit of obsession. But definitely love.''
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 1,000 pages of transcripts from Lewinsky's grand jury
testimony and interviews with prosecutors and FBI agents under
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr were among the 3,183 pages of
evidence released Monday chronicling the Clinton-Lewinsky
relationship, often in explicit detail.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Lewinsky's account reads like a turgid bestseller by
Danielle Steele or Sidney Sheldon. Still, many of Lewinsky's
steamiest descriptions of her White House trysts with Clinton were
blanked out by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There was little in Lewinsky's account to alter the basic story
line unveiled in Starr's report to Congress, which was made public
on Sept. 11. She recounted her early flirtations with Clinton,
performing oral sex as he talked on the phone, exchanging gifts,
her implicit agreement with Clinton to hide the relationship, and
presidential confidant Vernon Jordan's efforts to find her a job.
</P>
<P>
   But the transcripts nevertheless make compelling reading
because, for the first time, the former White House intern is
speaking out in her own words. Lewinsky has not granted interviews
since her name became a household word in January, when the affair
was first reported, and her public appearances have been limited
mainly to brisk televised walks into her lawyers' offices.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that emerges is of a young woman who alternates
between intense romantic feelings toward Clinton, remorse over the
affair, and wisecracking humor.
</P>
<P>
   She said of Clinton, ``he was just sunshine.'' And she describes
the president as her ``sexual soulmate.'' Oral sex with Clinton
resulted from ``the passion of the moment,'' she said. ``We both,
really, just went to ... a whole other place together sexually.''
</P>
<P>
   The two never had sex in the Oval Office, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Clinton's account, Lewinsky described the president
putting his hands on her breasts and fondling her so that she
achieved orgasms. At one point, she said, she bit her hand ``so
that I wouldn't make any noise.''
</P>
<P>
   In one clinical description, Lewinsky said that out of nine
instances when she performed oral sex on Clinton, the president
ejaculated twice. Lewinsky said she believed that by not ``coming
to completion,'' Clinton ``didn't need to feel guilty,'' and it was
``easier for him to rationalize'' their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two times occurred Feb. 28, 1997, after she told him
``it's important to me ... it doesn't seem right.'' Clinton
responded that he didn't want the two to become addicted to each
other, but nonetheless consented.
</P>
<P>
   A stain on the navy blue dress that Lewinsky wore during that
encounter provided Starr with a DNA match to Clinton proving the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some media speculation, Lewinsky insisted she did
not keep the dress as a souvenir. Rather, she explained, she kept
it in her closet after gaining weight and only contemplated wearing
it again nine months later on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the dress, ``I kind of thought, oh, this is dirty.''
Then she remembered when she had worn it last and ``I thought to
myself, oh, no.'' Her confidante, Linda Tripp, urged her not to
wear it on Thanksgiving, providing Lewinsky with alternative
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tripp, who worked with Lewinsky at the Pentagon after
Lewinsky's 1996 transfer from the White House, who secretly
recorded Lewinsky and turned the tapes over to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky recalled her discussions with Clinton on concealing or
denying the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I could always _ I would always deny it. I would
always protect him,'' Lewinsky said. Asked about Clinton's
response, she said: ``I'm seeing him smile and I'm hearing him
saying `that's good,' or _ something affirmative. You know. Not _
not _ `don't deny it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts at humor punctuated her testimony. Lewinsky talked
about how a ``bad hair day'' led her to wear her ``infamous''
beret, the same one she is wearing on the television news clip
showing her hugging Clinton in a White House receiving line.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, she said she and Clinton had a ``running
joke'' that she lacked the dexterity to ``unbutton his pants.'' And
when grand jurors asked her for embarrassing sexual detail, she
joked: ``Can I hide under the table?''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the predominant emotions of the transcripts are
regret, remorse and bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded by one grand juror that she had a previous affair with
a married man, Lewinsky responded that ``obviously ... there's work
that I need to do on myself,'' adding that ``normal,
quote-unquote'' single women don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people have issues and that's just how mine
manifested themselves... It's not right to have an affair with a
married man.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled feeling ``annoyed'' and ``jealous'' at television
footage showing Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton being
playfully romantic on a winter break in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   And she reported feeling hurt and offended by Clinton's
reference to her as ``that woman'' in his public denial of the
affair in January. In defending Clinton, White House aides
``trashed'' her and ``maligned'' her family. ``I had wanted him to
say I was a nice, decent person and that he was sorry this had
happened because I ... I tried to do as much as I could to protect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky won over several of the grand jurors, with a few
referring to her as ``Monica'' during questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica, none of us in this room are perfect,'' one said. ``You
have my forgiveness,'' another said. ``Because we all fall short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
