<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PERJURY-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HE LIED, MOST AGREE, BUT ARE THOSE LIES IMPEACHABLE
OFFENSES? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Fla., S.C., N.Y.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MONICA,
CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER,
CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE,
CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) (JT) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the nation watched President Clinton on
videotape Monday, many members of Congress on both sides of the
aisle had already decided that he lied under oath. Now the
question, which Congress is already starting to debate, is whether
that is grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, certainly
seemed to think so. In his report to Congress, he held that perjury
and obstruction of justice by any citizen ``are profoundly serious
matters'' and that ``when such acts are committed by the president
of the United States, we believe these acts `may constitute grounds
for an impeachment.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the Constitution's description of an impeachable offense as
treason, bribery and other ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' is
subject to continual reinterpretation.
</P>
<P>
   That profound constitutional ambiguity has sent Congress looking
through precedent, law, public opinion polls and Clinton's parsings
to decide whether his attempt to cover up his affair with Monica
Lewinsky should lead to his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said Monday: ``The president cannot
go before a grand jury and say things that are not true. What will
happen to the rule of law if he did that?''
</P>
<P>
   But he is only one member of the House Judiciary Committee,
which is in the vanguard of impeachment deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   And while many members of the committee now say they are certain
to recommend that the House open a formal impeachment inquiry, the
spectrum among its 36 members, all but one of them lawyers, also
shows that the ultimate decision on whether to impeach Clinton is
not likely to be clear or easy.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the preponderant view in Congress that Clinton lied.
But is that perjury? Not every committee member agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do all members of the Judiciary Committee put the same
weight on the president's deposition in the sexual harassment case
brought by Paula Jones as on the four hours of grand jury testimony
aired Monday. In fact, some members of Congress are asking whether
this is a perjury case that any prosecutor would bring to court.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., draws a distinction, for example,
between Clinton's testimony before the grand jury and his earlier
deposition in the Jones case. The civil case was ultimately
dismissed by U.S. Judge Susan Webber Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always bothered me,'' said Graham, a Judiciary
Committee member who was once an Air Force prosecutor. ``Would I as
a prosecutor spend time and money to prosecute a guy who lies in a
deposition in a case that was dismissed?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal, he said, ``is to set the standard that if the average
citizen engaged in like conduct they would have severe legal
consequences.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, one of Graham's Republican colleagues, does
not share his qualms about the Jones deposition. ``I have no doubt
in my mind, based on other cases,'' the Florida Republican said,
``that it doesn't make any difference if the case was thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the other side, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., is not even
certain that a prosecutor would bring a perjury case against
Clinton based on the grand jury testimony the country watched
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `he said, she said,''' said Nadler. He noted that Starr
has presumed that Ms. Lewinsky is the one telling the truth, when
her testimony deviates from the president's. ``It's all based on
Monica Lewinsky's testimony,'' he said. While Starr found that Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony matched contemporaneous accounts she gave to
11 friends of her affair, Nadler said that she may have been
exaggerating to all her friends.
</P>
<P>
   To sort through precedent and the framers' intent, the
Republican and Democratic staffs of the Judiciary Committee have
independently given their members extensive legal research.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's members say they are studying the writings of legal
scholars, the report on impeachment drawn up by the Judiciary
Committee staff in the 1974 Watergate proceedings, a primer on
impeachment written by Charles L. Black Jr. of Yale Law School in
1974 and the case histories of the impeachment of judges.
</P>
<P>
   But impeachment proceedings have been so infrequent that even
these materials can take lead to different interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, who was an aide to the House Judiciary
Committee in 1974, has posted on her Web site the 1974 report on
Constitutional Grounds for Presidential Impeachment. In a sign of
her own thinking, she pointed her constituents towards its
observations and its conclusion as ``pretty relevant today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all presidential misconduct is sufficient to constitute
grounds for an impeachment,'' that 1974 report concluded. ``Because
impeachment of a president is a grave step for the nation, it is
predicated only upon conduct seriously incompatible with the either
the constitutional form and principles of our government on the
proper performance of constitutional duties of presidential
office.''
</P>
<P>
   That might seem to suggest that evasions about illicit sex would
not rise to the level of impeachment. But Canady looks elsewhere
for a model _ the precedent set by Congress in the impeachment and
conviction of U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi in
1989 for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was convicted of lying to a grand jury about his talks
with a prosecutor in a marijuana smuggling case. He was accused of
concealing his attempt to help the son of a business partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was impeached and removed from office because he committed
perjury,'' Canady said, ``and the interesting thing is he committed
perjury before a grand jury on matters where if he simply told the
truth there would have been no legal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet should a judicial impeachment be considered relevant to a
president? Federal judges are not elected but under the
Constitution have lifetime tenure subject to ``good behavior'' in
office. ``It's certainly the case that impeaching a judge and
impeaching a president has two different standards,'' said Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
