<SLUG> BC-CLINTON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAPE SHOWS CLINTON CLINGING TO CLAIM OF TRUTHFUL TESTIMONY
 &HT;    1030&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans viewed raw videotape footage Monday of
President Clinton delivering legally artful and combative grand
jury testimony about his sexual relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was shown somberly acknowledging an ``improper
intimate'' relationship with Lewinsky but forcefully refusing to
characterize it as ``sexual'' despite evidence of oral and phone
sex. He steadfastly clung to narrow legal definitions to bolster
his claim that he did not lie in earlier sworn testimony about the
affair.
</P>
<P>
   The historic broadcast came as Congress, setting the stage for
possible impeachment proceedings against the president, released
3,183 pages of evidence that chronicled the relationship in graphic
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread predictions that the tape would shift
opinions about Clinton, the first reactions indicated that it only
served to harden previously held positions _ both in Congress and
among the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   The two volumes of material compiled Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr included the full text of both Clinton's and Lewinsky's
testimony to the grand jury investigating the president _ much of
it at odds both in tone and substance.
</P>
<P>
   It also contained notes and e-mail about Lewinsky's sexual
encounters with the president and others, plus a dizzying variety
of supporting material, from White House phone and visitor logs to
photos of Lewinsky's family in the Oval Office with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While Lewinsky's testimony is occasionally light-hearted _ ``Oh,
you really want to embarrass me, don't you?'' she says at one point
when prosecutors ask for details of sex with Clinton _ the
president's frequently falls back on legal defenses and technical
jousting over the definitions of ``sexual relations,'' ``alone,''
and even the verb ``is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony contradicts Clinton's assertions on three
key points: that he never touched her body to arouse her sexually,
that he never advised her to sign a sworn statement denying their
affair and that their relationship began in January 1996 when she
was a paid employee of the White House. She claims he touched her
breasts and genitalia, she discussed her sworn denial of the
relationship with him and that the relationship began in November
1995 when she was an intern.
</P>
<P>
   And while she says that the president never instructed her to
lie to prosecutors about their relationship, ``I'm seeing him smile
and I'm hearing him saying, 'that's good,' or something
affirmative'' when she told him that she would ``always protect
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the videotape of his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony
from the Map Room, the same room from which he somberly addressed
the nation to acknowledge his relationship with Lewinsky,
reiterated what he has said before: that he never instructed
Lewinsky or any of his White House aides to lie to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape pre-empted news coverage of Clinton basking in
thunderous applause as he addressed the United Nations General
Assembly in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Networks began broadcasting the unedited four-hour videotape at
9:30 a.m. EDT, preempting soap operas for what was expected to be
much steamier fare. But despite the graphically direct questions of
prosecutors and Clinton's occasional defiance, the broadcast
produced little information that had not already been leaked to
news organizations or included in Starr's report to Congress
released two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   It will be days before public reaction to the broadcast can be
adequately gauged. But one indicator, the stock market, responded
positively. When the broadcast began, the Dow Jones industrial
average quickly shed nearly 200 points. When it ended, the average
had climbed back into positive territory, closing the day with a
gain of just over 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, however, the tape of Clinton's grand jury
testimony appeared to harden the lines between Republicans and
Democrats. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, said Clinton's testimony was a ``classic case'' of
perjury and therefore an impeachable offense. But Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich., the ranking minority member of the committee,
decried the release of ``irrelevant'' details about Clinton and
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, White House press secretary Mike McCurry complained
that the release of the videotape and other evidence gathered by
Starr constituted ``rank partisanship.'' McCurry said Starr and his
assistants tried to ``browbeat and badger'' the president during
the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on the videotape, makes a similar charge in refusing to
answer some of the prosecutors' questions about the details of his
sexual encounters with Lewinsky. ``I'm not going to answer your
trick questions,'' he says at one point.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, he suggests to one of Starr's assistants that
``from the tone of your voice and the way you're asking questions
here, it's obvious this is the most important thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is most animated when he talks about the sexual
harassment lawsuit filed against him by Paula Jones, contending
that his political opponents tried to use the lawsuit, which has
since been dismissed for lack of merit, as ``a wrecking ball''
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has charged that Clinton committed perjury when, in a Jan.
26 deposition in the Jones lawsuit, he testified that the he did
not have a sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted to Starr's grand jury that his testimony was
truthful under the narrow definition of ``sexual relations'' used
in the Jones lawsuit. He said oral sex did not fall under that
definition, but did not specifically acknowledge whether he had
received oral sex from Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visibly bristled when Starr's prosecutors asked whether
the narrow definition upon which the president relied in his Jones
testimony would ``include sticking an object into the genitalia of
another person in order to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of
another person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the answer to that,'' the president replied.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has testified that she used one of the president's
cigars as a sexual aid during one of their encounters.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed remorse for Lewinsky being subpoenaed as a
witness in the Jones lawsuit. ``It breaks my heart that she was
ever involved in this,'' he said. ``It wasn't her fault. It was
mine.'' He even thanked Starr for granting Lewinsky immunity to
testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Lewinsky is ``basically a good girl ...a good young
woman with a good heart and a good mind'' who is ``burdened by some
unfortunate conditions of her upbringing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of ``her psyche,'' he said, he anticipated that
eventually Lewinsky have to talk publicly about their relationship.
However, he denied that used his longtime friend, Vernon Jordan, to
try to ``buy her silence'' with a job after she left the
government.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he saw nothing improper in exchanging gifts with
Lewinsky. He said he gives and receives lots of gifts from friends.
He denied any role in trying to hide his gifts to Lewinsky from
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the differences in his and Lewinsky's testimony,
Clinton harkened back to the contrasting testimony of Anita Hill
and Clarence Thomas in the 1991 Senate confirmation hearings on
Thomas's nomination to the U.S. Supreme Court. Hill accused Thomas
of sexual harassment. Thomas denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard both of them testify, what I believed after it
was over, I believed that they both thought they were telling the
truth,'' he said. ``You're dealing with, in some ways, the most
mysterious area of human life. I'm doing the best I can to give you
honest answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, in her testimony, called the president her ``sexual
soul mate'' and said he had ``a beautiful soul.'' She added, ``I
just thought he was just this incredible person and when I looked
at him I saw a little boy. I don't know what the truth is any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
