<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6871 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMAGE-615&AMP;ADD     09-21 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMAGE-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SIDES OF CLINTON EMERGE ON VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-PERJURY,
CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC, CLINTON-WATCH-NY,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER,
CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE,
CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton has always loved nothing better than a
tough audience and, in the end, that is how he treated Kenneth
Starr's grand jury, starting shakily, then warming to his task,
unspooling every thread of wounded dignity, controlled anger and
confident elaboration at his command in a performance filled with
trademark touches.
</P>
<P>
   Like the lawyer he is, Clinton complained about trick questions
but sometimes finagled. Like the politician he is, he filibustered,
holding down the score and running out the clock. Like the fighter
he is, he tossed off veiled insults and condescending putdowns.
Like the pedagogue he is, he lectured. Like the scarred, tired,
defensive man he has become, he sometimes bridled and sometimes
just seemed to sag.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nowhere in the four hours and three minutes of his ordeal in
the Map Room on the afternoon of Aug. 17 did Clinton display any
emotion rawer than the anger he unleashed in his televised speech
to the nation that night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in muted and mournful tones in supposedly secret
testimony that he made clear he knew would become public, Clinton
actually said, ``I'm sorry,'' for misleading his senior aides about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky _ two words that it took him
18 more days to utter in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have been misleading,'' Clinton said of his initial
denials to his aides. ``And if they were, I have to take
responsibility for it, and I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Clinton also said, ``I'm sorry to say for
reasons I don't entirely remember,'' he once asked his secretary,
Betty Currie, to wait in the dining room off his private study
while he talked to Ms. Lewinsky. Mrs. Currie testified that she
waited on a night when the president and Ms. Lewinsky were in the
study, a night when Ms. Lewinsky says they had the fateful
encounter that stained her dress.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, most of the Bill Clintons the world has come to know
make at least a cameo appearance in this record that the president
himself at one point ruefully acknowledges ``will be forever in the
historic annals of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   With unsparing clarity, the videotape captures Clinton the
shameless charmer, acknowledging that prosecutors could be forgiven
for thinking that the president must have acute recall about such
``embarrassing and personally painful'' events, and wishing that he
had more time to take grand jurors' questions.
</P>
<P>
   It also shows Clinton the cheapskate, confessing that gifts he
gave Ms. Lewinsky _ like a blanket from Radio City Music Hall _
were meaningless leftovers he had received as gifts from others.
</P>
<P>
   There is the empathetic son of a violent, broken home, who says
that Ms. Lewinsky is ``a good young woman with a good heart and a
good mind,'' who is ``burdened by some unfortunate conditions of
her, her upbringing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, there is the gimlet-eyed appraiser of human
motivation who says he had no doubt that once their sexual
interaction was over, Ms. Lewinsky would not be able to help
talking about it, because ``it was a part of her psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the quibbler who argues about the meaning of the words
``is'' and ``truth,'' who draws distinctions about whether somebody
told him something on the phone or in a meeting, who describes his
conduct with Ms. Lewinsky by directly acknowledging only which acts
he had not performed, who contends that he was trying to keep his
aides ``out of trouble'' by telling them untruths.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the sheepish cookie-thief caught red-handed who,
when asked to describe how Ms. Lewinsky's dress might have been
stained, says, smiling faintly: ``You know what the facts are;
there's no point in a hypothetical.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have long known that he makes his worst speeches
early in the day, and as he began his testimony at 1:03 p.m.,
Clinton seemed groggy and feeling his way. As he unfolded a piece
of paper and slowly read his blanket statement acknowledging
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky, peering over
half-glasses, he looked ashen, crumpled, flat.
</P>
<P>
   But as he took the measure of his interrogators, Clinton's
confidence grew. As they pressed for graphic details about sexual
acts, his anger grew too, though its visible, audible
manifestations were confined to a flexed jaw, a jabbed finger, a
spit-out ``sir,'' a terse and husky proclamation that he
``deplored'' what Paula Jones' lawyers were doing in their sexual
misconduct lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   But as the president himself said in explaining an outburst at
Secret Service agents who had once told Ms. Lewinsky of a female
guest visiting him in the Oval Office, ``As I usually do when I'm
mad, after a while I wasn't so mad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton did his best to get even, at several points
larding his answers with parenthetical asides about the cost of
Starr's investigation, the political motives of his enemies, and
the ``pretty well shattered'' credibility of Kathleen Willey, the
former White House volunteer who has accused Clinton of making a
crude sexual advance to her in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   After denying that he had made any sexual advance to Ms. Willey,
who continued to write him affectionate notes after the purported
encounter, Clinton said she had asked for a meeting with him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a prosecutor whether she had made a sexual advance
to him, Clinton casually replied, ``On that day, no, she did not.''
Asked to elaborate, the president said coolly: ``I wouldn't call it
a sexual advance. She was always very friendly. But I never took it
seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
