<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET BOUNCES BACK FROM STEEP OPENING DROP  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks weathered a sharp selloff on European markets
Monday and finished modestly higher, led by strong gains among
bellwether technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average overcame an early 185-point
deficit to close up 37.59 points, or 0.5 of 1 percent, at 7,933.25.
The advance leaves the Dow with a small gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, however, traders reacted with alarm to developments in
foreign markets, particularly in Europe, where prices on most major
exchanges tumbled on renewed worries about Russia and Japan, as
well as concerns over President Clinton's videotaped grand jury
testimony in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sense of foreboding about Clinton didn't help the European
markets,'' said one block trader, who insisted on not being
identified. ``And in our market the testimony was a big
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Every major stock market in Europe fell Monday, with drops of
more than 5 percent on the Swiss, Italian and Dutch exchanges. The
CAC-40 index in France was off more than 3.5 percent, the Dax index
in Germany fell 3.98 percent, and the FTSE 100 index in London lost
1.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were also sharp drops in Asia and in Brazil. In Japan, the
Nikkei index fell 2.76 percent, and the Hang Seng index in Hong
Kong dropped 3.70 percent. The Bovespa index in Brazil lost 3.87
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The selling continued when trading shifted to New York. But the
early losses were reversed as the session progressed, and by late
in the session the Dow moved into positive territory.
</P>
<P>
   Some broader market indexes also had modest advances. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 3.80, or 0.4 percent, to 1,023.89.
And the Nasdaq composite index was up 16.66, or 1 percent, to
1,680.43. But the Big Board's composite index fell 0.11, to 507.43,
and the Russell 2000 index dipped 0.68, to 362.58.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered those that gained by a margin of 4
to 3 on the New York Stock Exchange. Volume fell to 609.9 million
shares, from 793 million shares on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the observance of Rosh ha-Shanah, the Jewish New
Year, and the broadcast of Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony helped
depress the level of activity.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders did say, however, that they were encouraged by what
has happened recently. ``We are climbing the infamous wall of
worry,'' one said. ``And with interest rates where they are, there
is no way stocks can go down. They can trade off for a while, but
then they will bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which played a critical role in the climb of
the market averages and have had a leading part in the recent
selloff, were impressive performers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola gained 2, to 48{. IBM was up 3{, to 128 3/16. Microsoft
closed at 107~, up 2{. And shares of the 3Com Corp., the
second-largest computer-networking company, rose 1|, or 5.3
percent, to 32 1/16, on optimism that it will meet Wall Street's
expectations when it releases quarterly results Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although many companies have already braced investors about
coming earnings reports, traders remain nervous about the numbers
that will be announced in the next few weeks. And they are quite
willing to punish companies that have unexpected bad news.
</P>
<P>
   An example yesterday was Praxair Inc. The company, the
third-largest supplier of industrial gases, said that earnings for
its 1998 fiscal year would be less than expected because of slower
domestic sales.
</P>
<P>
   Traders responded by pounding Praxair's stock, pushing it down
by 2 13/16, or nearly 8 percent, to 32 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   And Praxair was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The American depository receipts of Philips Electronics fell 5,
or 9.8 percent, to 46, after the Dutch company warned that its
third-quarter results would be lower than expected. And shares of
Xerox lost 4, to 79 9/16, after analysts at Lehman Brothers cut
1998 earnings estimates, citing the company's exposure in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is in a recovery that began at the start of the
month,'' said Phil Roth, chief technical analyst at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter. ``But it has not really demonstrated sustained
strength. We have had shake-outs, and it has held. But we are not
seeing genuine investment demand. I don't think the selloff is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
