<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL SPECIALISTS SEE DEFENSE POSSIBILITIES IN TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He went into his deposition in the Paula Jones case
wanting to be truthful but ``not particularly helpful.'' He relied
on hair-splitting distinctions to avoid admitting a sexual
relationship. He freely took refuge in saying ``I don't recall''
when a fuller answer would have yielded embarrassing details.
</P>
<P>
   After watching President Clinton spin a web of legalistic
explanations for his evasions in the Jones case, some specialists
Monday came away convinced that, by the narrow standards of the
courtroom, he could mount a plausible defense to charges of perjury
and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Technical defenses might not play well in an impeachment
inquiry, where a higher standard of truthfulness might apply, they
warned, and their effect on the public at large is also a question
mark. Still, the president's explanations to the grand jury,
tortured as they may be, could end up satisfying a crucial
constituency in the court of public opinion _ those who are
inclined to support him so long as he did not violate his oath to
uphold the law.
</P>
<P>
   To prove perjury, for example, a prosecutor must show that the
president intended to give false statements. If he truly set out to
give evasive answers, and only slipped into falsehoods
accidentally, like a gymnast sliding off the balance beam, he might
not be legally culpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question is do you believe that that's what he was
trying to do, trying to walk a very narrow line?'' said Gerard
Lynch, former chief of the criminal division of the US attorney's
office in Manhattan. ``Then, if he fell over the line and said
something specifically false, it was based on misunderstanding, not
an intent to say something deliberately false.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bruce E. Yannett, a former Iran-Contra prosecutor, ``The
issue is not whether a reasonable person believes the president had
a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky. The issue is whether
the president's application of the definition of sexual relations
that was given to him indicates that he meant to commit perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Such distinctions might satisfy a court, Lynch and Yannett said,
but, asked Lynch, ``Is this appropriate behavior for a president?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long maintained that he deliberately answered
questions in the Jones deposition narrowly. Some people, knowing
his tendency to take refuge in explanations like he ``didn't
inhale'' when he smoked marijuana, have argued that Clinton's
parsing of the truth is a character flaw. Ironically, if he were a
habitual trimmer of the truth, it could weigh against the notion
that he deliberately set out to lie in this case, legal specialists
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in his grand-jury testimony, Clinton sought to lay out a
more sympathetic context for his evasions in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   He was convinced, he said, that Jones's lawyers wanted to ``hurt
me politically'' and ``take a wrecking ball to me.'' Therefore, he
resolved to be truthful but not helpful. He offered answers that
were technically true, but not revealing. Point by point, the
president explained that he wasn't trying to lie or obstruct
justice, merely cast his actions in the most politically palatable
light:
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton denied in the deposition having sexual relations with
Lewinsky because the definition of sex offered by Jones' lawyers
covered oral sex only if the person being deposed was the active
participant. He was not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, however, has testified that the president touched her
breasts and genitals, suggesting Clinton had sex with her even by
his own narrow interpretation of the definition. Clinton, however,
parsed the definition even further in his grand jury testimony. The
president claimed at least six times that the definition only
covered the touching of certain body parts ``with the intent to
arouse or gratify.''
</P>
<P>
   _Clinton affirmed, under oath during the Jones case deposition,
the accuracy of Lewinsky's own affidavit in the Jones case, which
broadly denied any sexual relationship. In his grand-jury
testimony, Clinton suggested that Lewinsky had been truthful if her
definition of sex was limited to intercourse. Even by a broader
definition, he said, the denial was true ``at the present time,''
because they were not in an intimate relationship when she was
deposed in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton's lawyer Robert Bennett claimed during the president's
deposition in the Jones case that Lewinsky had denied a sexual
relationship ``in any manner, shape or form.'' Before the grand
jury, Clinton said he wasn't paying attention to Bennett's
statement and that, in any case, defendants aren't legally
responsible for their lawyers' statements _ which is strictly true,
specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton testified in the Jones deposition that he ``didn't
recall'' whether he had ever been alone with Lewinsky. To the grand
jury, he explained his fuzzy memory by noting that presidents are
always liable to be interrupted by stewards, aides, or guards, and
that he couldn't remember if any such interruptions occurred during
Lewinsky's visits.
</P>
<P>
   --After giving his deposition, Clinton acknowledged, he spoke to
his secretary, Betty Currie, about whether she had ever seen him
and Lewinsky alone together. Currie testified that Clinton's
comments to her were more like statements than questions. Clinton
explained that he was trying to gather all the facts in
anticipation of media leaks. At the time, there was no criminal
investigation of the matter, and Currie wasn't a witness in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Clinton noted, Currie testified that once she was
subpoenaed, he asked her to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, conservatives like Washington attorney Stephen Smith,
a former clerk for Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, predicted
that Clinton's defenses would not bear fuller scrutiny. For
example, he said, the judge in the Jones case, Susan Webber Wright,
took great pains to make sure the president wasn't subjected to
unfair questions, and later sealed his deposition. Thus, Clinton's
explanation that he gave narrow answers out of a fear of leaks was
implausible, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Concluded Smith, ``Perjury laws would be useless if this kind of
hair-splitting could be justified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
