<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ENCORE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATHAN LANE'S MODEST TV `ENCORE!' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's laid out in his ``Pagliacci'' clown suit at an Italian
hospital, where a bad clam and bad doctoring have ended the
glittering career of opera star Joseph Panini (Nathan Lane).
</P>
<P>
   The doctors have managed to screw up his vocal cords. As a prima
donna, he's a gona. And that is how ``Encore! Encore!'' begins
Tuesday night on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Now he'll have to crate himself and his ego home to the family
vineyard in Napa County and nurture his other sizable talent _
grandly afflicting all within his path.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nifty premise, backed by pedigreed personnel. Lane, the
glory of ``The Birdcage,'' is the star. Joan Plowright, a Tony
winner and Oscar nominee, plays his mother. Glenne Headly, whose
resume includes ``Lonesome Dove,'' plays his sister, who runs the
winery. And ``Encore! Encore!'' is from the producers who brought
us ``Frasier.'' Encore!
</P>
<P>
   So what a disappointment to find a sitcom that's modestly
entertaining at best, instead of a comedy gem that would make you
want to fling bouquets at the Sony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encore! Encore!'' spent its summer at TV medical spas _ a
script lift here, a cast tuck there _ and still doesn't seem
comfortable in its own skin. Most of the problems are with the
central character.
</P>
<P>
   Lane can digest more scenery before breakfast than most actors
consume in a lifetime. He can make Joseph Panini broad, somewhat
operatic and rogueish, but he can't make him charming and
sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Lane was adorable in his most famous role, as the drag queen
performer and surrogate mother in ``The Birdcage,'' because under
all the fussbudget mannerisms, that character was lovably innocent.
</P>
<P>
   But while Joseph Panini has the same theatricality, he's also
monotonous, selfish and demanding. These are seldom the propellants
of a successful TV show. And, to be honest, Lane is not smashingly
convincing as the womanizer his character is supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   The show isn't an absolute dud. David Angell, Peter Casey and
David Lee could do a better series in a collective coma than most
TV producers could imagine on their best days. But ``Encore!
Encore!'' doesn't rate the second ``Encore!'' NBC gave it over the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   This, finally, for trivia lovers. It's Lane's second network
series. The first, also on NBC, was called ``One of the Boys'' and
survived for about two months in 1982. Its star was Mickey Rooney,
and a pre-``Saturday Night Live'' Dana Carvey played Lane's
roommate.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Sports Night'' (Tuesday on ABC) is probably the wrong
vehicle for some genuine talent, beginning with series creator
Aaron Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin wrote the scripts for ``A Few Good Men,'' ``Malice'' and
``The American President.'' Here, his fellow executive producers
include Brian Grazer and Ron Howard. ``Sports Night'' has class.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the pilot better the second time I watched it, but its
mix of comedy and dramatic tension won't work for viewers who like
their TV genres straight. Remember the dramedy? The sports theme
might also pare down the prospective audience.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Krause (``Cybill'') and Josh Charles (``Dead Poets
Society'') co-star as the anchors of a late-night sports show that
is, in all but its fictional name, ESPN's ``SportsCenter.'' Robert
Guillaume is their acerbic executive producer, Felicity Huffman
their harried producer, and Sabrina Lloyd plays the associate
producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' never leaves its Manhattan studio setting
Tuesday and consequently feels a bit cramped in an episode about
Krause's character wavering from his duties in the wake of a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't insist on deep laughs, and appreciate a scarcely
utilized laugh track, you might give ``Sports Night'' a chance. But
it just doesn't have that gleam that suggests hit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does ``The Hughleys'' (Tuesday on ABC), the season's
second new series about a black family moving into a white suburban
bastion. Fox's ``Living in Captivity'' is the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys'' is supposed to be based on the actual
experiences of its creator and star, stand-up comic D.L. Hughley.
One of his producing partners is comedian Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's pilot, Darryl Hughley (Hughley) is fretting that
his move has put him, in the words of his best friend Milsap (John
Henton), ``on the slippery slope to losing your blackness.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole show is a string of trumped-up race jokes tied to that
theme. At a store, a black saleswoman advises Hughley not to use a
certain ballpoint pen because it contains black ink.
</P>
<P>
   Slim show. Long odds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
