<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LETTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERS REVEAL BITTERNESS BETWEEN STARR AND CLINTON'S LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After spending more than a month in a fruitless
effort to get President Clinton to agree to testify voluntarily
before the federal grand jury, Robert Bittman, one of Kenneth
Starr's deputies, was fed up with what prosecutors had come to view
as stalling tactics by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully acknowledge that the president has immense and
weighty responsibilities,'' Bittman wrote on March 2 in a letter to
David Kendall, Clinton's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want in every way to take fully into account those grave
duties of state,'' he continued. ``Yet since this matter arose, the
president has _ with all respect _ found time to play golf, attend
basketball games and political fund-raisers, and enjoy a ski
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, the independent counsel's office and lawyers for
Clinton exchanged letters that provide a window into how the two
camps maneuvered warily around one another. At times their
exchanges, which were released Monday by the House Judiciary
Committee, were businesslike. But at many points they were
frustrated and angry, betraying a deep suspicion on the part of
each side about the motivations of the other.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Bittman on March 18, Kendall said he and the
president had dealt in good faith with Starr's investigation for
four years. But since the investigation was widened to include the
president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Kendall said, the
situation had changed.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's actions in the previous weeks, Kendall
said, ``lead me to believe that your investigation may not, in
fact, be an even-handed search for justice but rather may be, for
whatever reason, a campaign to embarrass and harass the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters, written from February through August, covered a
range of issues, including the White House's assertion of executive
privilege, its complaints about leaks from Starr's office and the
independent counsel's request for a blood sample from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But on no issue did the two sides clash more heatedly than on
the question of whether and when Clinton would appear before the
grand jury. And the main combatants were Bittman and Kendall, who
had represented Clinton in the Whitewater investigation since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Between Jan. 28 and early March, Bittman invited Clinton six
times to tell the grand jury his story, citing the president's
public pledge to cooperate fully with the investigation, according
to the correspondence. In some cases Kendall did not reply, and in
others he cited Clinton's heavy workload as the reason the
president would not be able to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Iraq continues to be dangerously volatile,
and this has demanded much of the president's time and attention,''
Kendall wrote on Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was so busy, Kendall wrote, that his own legal team had
not had enough time to prepare him for a grand jury appearance.
Moreover, Kendall said, Clinton's lawyers had been forced to spend
much of their time dealing with ``prejudicial and false leaks of
information about your investigation'' that the White House was
blaming on Starr and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, lawyers for the White House and Clinton regularly cited
leaks as a reason why they were suspicious of Starr's motives. As
Starr pressed for Clinton's testimony, Kendall suggested, in a
letter on March 4, that the grand jury could learn all it needed to
know about Clinton's side of the story from his deposition in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit. In that deposition, Clinton
denied having a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bittman's mounting frustration showed through in a letter to
Kendall on March 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, now eight weeks into the investigation, your
claim that the president continues not to have time to prepare his
testimony about Ms. Lewinsky is increasingly difficult for us to
understand,'' Bittman wrote. ``We now question whether the
president ever intends to cooperate with this investigation, as
promised, and testify.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, Bittman again asked if Clinton would agree to appear
before the grand jury. ``Having tried and tried, I will now try
once again,'' he wrote to Kendall. ``Please give me a
straightforward yes or no answer to the following question: Will
the president ever agree to testify voluntarily about the matters
involving Ms. Lewinsky?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers, Kendall replied two weeks later, ``have
serious objections to the origin and conduct of your Lewinsky
investigation, and until they are satisfactorily addressed, we
cannot, as a matter of professional duty to our client, allow the
president to give you further testimony at the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally in mid-July, Starr subpoenaed Clinton to appear before
the grand jury. After the White House then proposed that Clinton
voluntarily appear in September, Bittman suggested that the
independent counsel's office was suspicious of whether the White
House team was still stalling. Because the president had not
appeared voluntarily, ``we are currently not inclined to withdraw
the subpoena'' and negotiate a date, Bittman wrote on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Starr eventually withdrew the subpoena, and Clinton testified on
Aug. 17, an appearance broadcast around the world Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
