<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRIES TO MAINTAIN PRESIDENTIAL DECORUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a morning speech to the United Nations and an
afternoon panel on the global economy, Bill Clinton struggled to
maintain some semblance of presidential decorum Monday in the face
of near-continuous broadcasting of his videotaped grand jury
testimony about his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Although the president made no mention of the testimony in
public appearances during the day, its release haunted his every
step, at times creating almost unbearably awkward juxtapositions.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton strode into UN headquarters for a speech on
international terrorism at about 10 a.m., television sets all over
the building were carrying a picture of him defending a claim his
lawyer had made in January that the president and Lewinsky were not
having sex. ``Well,'' Clinton told off-camera prosecutors,
``actually in the present tense that was an accurate statement.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president reached the crescendo of his UN speech, the
power of his words seemed blunted by double meaning. ``It is not
necessary that we agree on all the world's issues to have
confidence in each other,'' he told the UN General Assembly. ``It
is not even necessary that we understand every single difference
among us to have confidence in one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surrealistic,' said Raghida Dergham, senior diplomatic
correspondent for Al Hayat, the leading daily newspaper in the Arab
world, who covered the UN session. ``It is hard for the world to
understand how Americans allow such embarrassing details to be
discussed in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was Clinton's second visit to New York in as many weeks,
and his second sustained effort to shift public attention from sex
and impeachment threats to international events, especially the
global economic crisis. White House aides pronounced themselves
satisfied with the effort late Monday, but observers across the
political spectrum expressed doubts about the president's ability
to do much about the public's near O.J.-like obsession with the
Lewinksy scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be an adage in politics: `When in trouble,
travel,' '' said Karlyn K. Bowman, a fellow with the generally
conservative American Enterprise Institute in Washington. ``Maybe
New York isn't far enough,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The White House sex scandal ``is sucking the oxygen out of any
other issue, and that's going to be a problem for Democrats in the
fall,'' said Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to focus on foreign policy is a plausible approach, but
it's a terrible mismatch today,'' added John Marttila, a Democratic
Party strategist from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uproar over the Lewinsky affair in recent weeks and
Clinton's videotaped testimony about it Monday, the public greeting
the president received here was comparatively mild.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of protesters carried placards reading ``Visualize
Impeachment'' and ``Get Your Pants Up and Get Out'' during a
morning protest at 42nd Street and Third Avenue near the UN and
they staged a second event in the afternoon outside New York
University Law School, where Clinton joined British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and others in a panel discussion about the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters seemed about equally balanced with defenders,
among them, Sherri Adams, who carried a sign outside the afternoon
event that read ``Unwavering Support for the Clintons'' and
dismissed the charges against the president as ``not very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both the UN and NYU gave the president unusually
warm receptions. As Clinton entered the General Assembly, Mexico's
Foreign Minister Rosario Green rose from her chair and led the
audience, which included South African President Nelson Mandela, in
a standing ovation. NYU Law School Dean John Sexton was almost
beside himself with adulation, calling Clinton's recent speech on
global issues ``sources of great inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind such kind words, however, there were signs of deep
nervousness Monday, especially among foreign officials.
</P>
<P>
   A senior UN official issued a statement after Clinton's speech
that appeared to warn both the president and his critics that a
United States preoccupied with the Lewinsky scandal could be a
danger for the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is widespread resentment among the UN membership
that the UN is being denied leadership by what is going on in
Washington,'' said John Ruggie, a senior adviser to the UN
Secretary General. ``There is a deep sense of anger about the US
squandering its potential leadership role ... at a time when the
world desperately needs leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Colum Lynch contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
