<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTYRS-STATUES-785&AMP;A     09-21 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTYRS-STATUES-785&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABBEY INSTALLS STATUES OF FOREIGN MARTYRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNY E. HELLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Life-size statues of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr., Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero and other 20th-century figures
who died for their beliefs now fill the 10 niches above Westminster
Abbey's main entrance that had remained empty for 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   The American civil rights leader, assassinated in Memphis,
Tenn., in 1968, is shown with outstretched palm turned up in
welcome and a girl crouching at his feet. To his left, Romero, the
liberal cleric who was gunned down in El Salvador in 1980 while
celebrating Mass, smiles serenely, his eyes almost closed behind
heavy-rimmed glasses. In his arms, he cradles a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The monuments, carved in French Richemont limestone, stand in a
row along a stone archway towering some 20 feet above visitors.
Nearly five years in the making, they were unveiled in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Since William the Conqueror's ascent in 1066, England has
crowned its kings and queens and often witnessed royal weddings and
funerals in Westminster Abbey, most recently last summer, when
Prince William and Prince Harry followed the coffin of their
mother, Diana, princess of Wales, through the doors above which the
new statues now stand.
</P>
<P>
   Installation of the new statues, intended to honor Christian
martyrs, marks the end of a 25-year renovation of the abbey, most
of which dates from the 14th century.
</P>
<P>
   Architects speculate that the niches were originally intended to
hold sculptures of England's monarchs and Westminster Abbey's
deans. Alterations to the abbey's west front, which had been
unchanged since the time of Henry VIII, provoked more discussion
than most other parts of the restoration and required the approval
of Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   In an abbey filled with plaques and monuments to illustrious
British royal figures, writers and politicians, the 10 figures are
the only 20th-century people represented by full-length statues.
The abbey librarian, Tony Trowles, said the figures were the
``first major statues'' to be installed since one of Prime Minister
William Gladstone was unveiled in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing British about the new statues, the abbey's
first commemoration of people unrelated to England. ``They are
representative of the major areas of persecution and representative
of all continents in the world,'' said the Rev. Dr. Anthony Harvey,
the subdean of Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   The chief architect for the abbey, Donald Buttress, a proponent
of the new monuments, argued that the church was a piece of living
art that should evolve with the times rather than remaining a
shrine to the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gothic architecture has niches which are part of the design;
without them being filled, the architecture is incomplete,'' said
Buttress, whose official abbey title is surveyor of the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures stand in the facade between the abbey's twin
towers, designed by Sir Christopher Wren and built in the 18th
century. Each of the niches resembles an ornate throne: A length of
stone above bears royal insignia colored in the characteristic red
and gold of England's monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to King and Romero, there are statues of the Polish
priest Maksymilian Kolbe, who gave his life for another prisoner at
Auschwitz in 1941 and is a Roman Catholic saint; a South African,
Manche Masemola, who was killed in 1928 by her animist parents for
her Anglican faith on a site that has become a point of pilgrimage;
and a Ugandan Anglican evangelist, Janani Luwum, an archbishop of
Uganda who is believed to have been assassinated in 1976 by the
Ugandan army.
</P>
<P>
   Statues were also raised in memory of the Grand Duchess
Elizabeth of Russia, who was killed by the Bolsheviks and is a
saint in the Russian Orthodox Church; the German Lutheran
theologian Dietrich Bonhoeffer, who was executed by the Nazis in
1945; Esther John (born Qamar Zia), the Indian teacher and
evangelist who was found brutally murdered in her bed at a mission
compound in 1960; Lucian Tapiedi, an evangelist of Papua New Guinea
who was killed by a villager when the Japanese invaded and incited
the murder of Christians in 1942, and Wang Zhimeng, who lived among
3,000 Chinese Christians in Yunnan province and was executed in
1973 during the Cultural Revolution's drive against religion.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century, with its totalitarian regimes, mass executions
and many civil wars, has produced more Christian martyrs than any
other century, Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This says something of great import,'' he added, gesturing
toward a photograph of the facade in his study. ``In this century,
the profession of the Christian faith has carried a greater cause,
and that is continuing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Church officials who sat on the committee to select the martyrs
said that placing the statues above the abbey's main entrance would
send a message to those around the world being persecuted for their
faith. Some choices were simple for the committee, Harvey said, but
for others it became necessary to consult local church authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These 10 statues are of individual martyrs; but they are
intended to represent all those others who have died (and continue
to die) in similar circumstances of oppression and persecution,''
Harvey wrote recently.
</P>
<P>
   None of the martyrs are given more prominence than others, and
the order of the statues is purely architectural. ``There is a
certain rhythm between them,'' Buttress said.
</P>
<P>
   The architects and the sculptors studied photographs and
pictures of the martyrs when possible and talked to surviving
relatives. There were no photographs of the South African martyr
Manche Masemola, but the carvers reconstructed her likeness from a
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The architects could also find no descriptions of Lucian Tapiedi
of Papua New Guinea, so sculptors based his likeness on pictures of
typical people of the time and place. A team of four sculptors led
by Tim Crawley, who has been working on the abbey for a decade,
carved the figures.
</P>
<P>
   While the people depicted are modern in appearance and dress,
the statues blend with their Gothic surroundings. Only the color of
the new limestone against the weathered gray of the facade sets the
sculptures apart, and in decades to come it should become
indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   To accompany the martyrs, the abbey simultaneously filled two
niches on each side of the great doors of its main entrance with
Gothic-style statues of women representing truth, justice, mercy
and peace, virtues on which abbey officials say the martyrs based
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling ceremony, conducted by the archbishop of
Canterbury, the Most Rev. George Carey, was attended by Queen
Elizabeth and by the families of most of the martyrs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
