A6892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-BUTTS-COX     09-21 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BUTTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One woman's voice: Tarsha Butts
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She worked hard for the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Tasha Butts,15, will be a junior guard this season at Baldwin
High School in Milledgeville, Ga., and plays in the Atlanta-based
Georgia Dream AAU program. She talks about her budding basketball
career:
</P>
<P>
   I was about 10 years old when my dad started making me go to the
recreation center near us to play basketball with the boys. I never
played with girls growing up, and I think that helped me. My
brother played high-school basketball, and he helped toughen me up.
He used to elbow me in the head. If I cried about it, he'd tell me
he didn't want me to be a punk.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I was 13, I was pretty good. I started getting
letters from colleges when I was in the eighth grade. I've gotten
letters and questionnaires from over 80 different schools. They
can't really talk to me yet, so they write stuff like, ``I saw you
play. You looked great.'' At first, I got real excited about it.
</P>
<P>
   Now I look at it and say, ``Well, it's only another letter.'' It
won't really become a big deal until I start thinking about making
a decision about where I want to go.
</P>
<P>
   I know there's a lot of coaches watching me, but I try not to
focus on it. If I just went out there and tried to impress them, I
wouldn't play my game, so I have to block them out. I like the
attention, but I feel like I worked hard to get here. So why not
get attention?
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad women now have a chance to play in the pros. At first,
I thought I would have no place to go after college, and I knew
there would be a slim chance to make the Olympic team. Now, I have
a chance to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-CHEAT-COX     09-21 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-CHEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women in sports: growing pains
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In search of volleyball talent, Louisville women's
coach Leonid Yelin returned to his homeland in the former Soviet
republic of Uzbek two years ago and brought back Marina Sinichenko.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, Sinichenko lacked the necessary English language
skills for admittance to the university. So one of Yelin's
assistants funneled $2,000 from a volleyball camp account to a
local women's group, which in turn awarded Sinichenko a scholarship
for an ``English as a Second Language'' course the summer before
her enrollment. Coaches arranged for her transportation and
persuaded a local Russian Orthodox priest to provide lodging in his
home. Even her dental bill was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Yelin says he was just treating Sinichenko like family. That's a
defense made popular by men's coaches who also break NCAA rules,
and it held little sway with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Any day, Louisville officials expect to get slapped with a stiff
penalty after appearing in August before the NCAA infractions
committee to answer the allegations. Hoping to lessen the blow, the
school suspended Yelin for a month without pay and canceled the
team's preseason exhibition series in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville's case is no longer an isolated one in women's
college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you see the competition rise dramatically, people are
always going to look for an edge,'' said athletics director Tom
Jurich, who was hired after the violations occurred.
</P>
<P>
   That justification long has been the tiger pit of big-time
athletics, which advocates of women's sports hope to bypass.
</P>
<P>
   But with lucrative contracts and shoe endorsement deals for
coaches ratcheting up the pressure to win, women's sports is
fighting its way through the traps that have snagged and embarrased
their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Including secondary violations, the more common form of
rules-breaking, an Atlanta Journal-Constitution review of NCAA
cases since 1992 reveals a nearly 300 percent jump for the women,
with 644 reported last year alone. If football is removed from the
equation, women's transgressions are virtually the same as those
for the men, who committed 655 violations in that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women's programs have grown in the same direction as the
men's programs in every other way, so I don't know why I would
think that would be different,'' said David Berst, NCAA chief of
staff for Division 1 and former executive director of enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Berst partly attributes the rise in secondary cases to women's
sports coaches and administrators more dilligently reporting the
small stuff. But the gender ratio is similar for more serious
violations _ in which gifts and benefits are offered to athletes,
or coaches are deemed to have acted unethically.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the NCAA handed out penalties in nine cases of major
infractions. Three were solely men's athletic programs, three were
exclusively women's and three were a combination.
</P>
<P>
   The women have come a long, if unenviable, way from a decade
ago, when a single major violation was found. It was against the
Kenyon College women's swim team for practicing more than 100 miles
from campus.
</P>
<P>
   Not until around 1980 did coaches of women's college teams first
hit the recruiting trails in competitive pursuit of talent. Even
then, they generally stayed within a four-hour drive of campus.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with top programs fueled by bulging recruiting budgets,
coaches hustle coast to coast, dealing with their peers from high
schools, summer leagues and AAU programs, and even an occasional
street agent trying to broker a star player. For someone of WNBA
star Lisa Leslie's stature, the process begins when she's an
eighth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   It's a '90s phenomenon that has resulted in such established
basketball coaches as Andy Landers of Georgia and Pat Summitt of
Tennessee earning as much in base salary, if not more, than the
men's coach on their campus .
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just as much pressure on women to win as there is
men,'' said Marianne Stanley, coach at California-Berkeley. ``It's
very real. People are getting fired for not winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches have contacts with kids that they shouldn't have. I've
seen more minor than major (violations), sure. But do I believe
people are getting paid (to attend certain schools)? Yeah. I don't
think it's pervasive, but I believe it happens. Some people will
resort to unscrupulous means to accomplish whatever it is they feel
pressure to accomplish. ``
</P>
<P>
   Jody Conradt, Texas basketball coach and women's athletics
director, said, ``I don't think we're buying cars'' for players,
but she cited cases of schools or their boosters buying a prom
dress for prospects.
</P>
<P>
   When her Penn State team played in the women's basketball NIT in
March, Rene Portland said, she learned of another coach skirting
the rulebook by putting her team up for a weekend at her parents'
house on the New Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   Portland accuses schools or their supporters of paying for
parents' travel, another NCAA infraction. There are kids, . . . you
go to their homes (on recruiting visits), they don't have a
thing,'' she said. ``Then they (enroll at) another school, and
their parents are at games, and it's a long distance (from home).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an (NCAA) recruiting rule that you can only call a kid
one time a week. Well, you're talking to a high-school athlete and
she says, 'I've talked to the coach of this college program the
last three nights.' ``
</P>
<P>
   One violation that has not knowingly occurred _ yet _ is a
player signing with a professional agent before her eligibility has
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Late in her sophomore year at Tennessee, the calls first came
for Chamique Holdsclaw, the premier basketball player in college.
It was the friend of a friend, a woman wanting to represent
Holdsclaw when she turned pro. When the woman followed Holdsclaw to
the national team tryouts last summer in Colorado Springs, Colo.,
Lady Vols assistant coach Mickie DeMoss flew there to shoo away the
aspiring agent.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee might be the first program to screen agents, checking
to see if they are registered under the state's agent law and
clearing them to talk with seniors on the team. The first year,
they heard from three agents. This past season, it grew to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the safeguards, hungry agents cannot always be warded
off.
</P>
<P>
   Vols star freshman Tamika Catchings was signing autographs for
young girls at the NCAA Final Four when a woman slipped her a
business card and said, ``Call me sometime.'''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Pat Summitt, admittedly paranoid about agents, passed
the card on to a school administrator who wrote the woman a note to
explain that agents in Tennessee must register and meet
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to come across like this woman knew she was doing
something wrong,'' said Donna Thomas, the Volunteers' compliance
director. ``It's so new in the women's game, a lot of people may
not know the ins and outs of it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamika's father, former NBA center Harvey Catchings, predicts
such incidents offer the first glimpse of the recruiting horrors
and agent dirty-dealings that have afflicted big-time men's sports
for two generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be that situation where you have that fish bowl
once again,'' said Catchings, who has another daughter playing at
Illinois. ``You're going to have your cream of the crop, the people
coaches look at and say, 'I want to build my team around this
particular person. So what is it going to take for you to come to
my school?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
