<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-CHONES-COX     09-21 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-CHONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recruiting game seems like old times for Chones
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dad takes it all in stride. A former NBA star, Jim
Chones is experienced in how college recruiters, sharks circling in
the waters, come after a highly rated prospect with low-post
skills. ``Don't let it go to your head,'' he cautions Kaayla, his
16-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Mom is new to the recruiting spiel, so her take on it is
different. She is amused by the flattery shown Kaayla. ``It might
be better to say who (BEGIN ITAL) hasn't (END ITAL) she heard
from,'' Elores Chones says, marveling at the college courtship.
</P>
<P>
   It's relentless. Since coaches could begin calling high-school
seniors-to-be in July, the telephone in their suburban Cleveland,
Ohio home has rarely stopped ringing. All the brand-name schools:
North Carolina, Duke, Penn State, Connecticut, Ohio State. ``Is
Kaayla there, please?'' they want to know.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday, Christmas and Valentine cards have flowed in
steadily since Kaayla's freshman season, filling a half-dozen
orange plastic crates. Michigan is the creative leader, having
already dubbed her Ms. Windex and addressing their letters to
Kaayla ``Rebound Queen'' Chones. The runover is stashed in the
bedroom of her older sister, Kareeda, a recent Marquette University
graduate and basketball team captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at a point where we know the UPS and Federal Express guys
on a first-name basis,'' Elores says.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fine time to be one of the top school-girl basketball
recruits in the country, especially if you're a 6-foot-3 1/2 center
with the reach of a 6-8 player. You averaged 22.7 points and 19.5
rebounds while earning all-state honors and a 3.8 grade-point
average last year at Eastlake North High. Your father, who is
partial and knowledgeable, says you have the best hands on a
youngster he's ever seen, boy or girl.
</P>
<P>
   In ninth grade, you played on a state high-school championship
team. You made second-team all-state as a sophomore and first-team
last season. You have your pick of colleges, all free. You're a
ball girl for the new women's pro team in town, the Cleveland
Rockers. You jetted to Russia in July for the World Youth Games,
where you earned a bronze medal and were third on the U.S. team in
scoring and second in rebounds while sharing time with Cheryl Ford,
daughter of NBA star Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   You are living your mother's dream, and a lot of other women's
dreams. You finally can look up to role models of your own gender,
such as Lisa Leslie and Cynthia Cooper. They are women who
encourage you and promise that you, too, can be a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just seeing them out there, playing in a professional league
in front of a crowd that big, it's inspired me to work harder,''
Kaayla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation right now, we're right on schedule. With the
women's pro leagues starting the last two years, by the time I get
out of college, it'll just be booming. Almost like the NBA is. It's
just a great time to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Your father says you have (BEGIN ITAL) pro (END ITAL) written
all over you, and he should know. In a generation preceding teen
wonders Kevin Garnett and Kobe Bryant as famous NBA teens, there
was Jim Chones. He joined Spencer Haywood in the first wave of
players who turned pro before their 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Chones had lost his college eligibility when, during the 1972-73
season, he was leading Marquette to a No. 1 ranking and news
surfaced that an attorney representing him had engaged in
negotiations with the New Jersey Nets of the upstart American
Basketball League. With coach Al McGuire's blessing, the
19-year-old junior bolted for a five-year, $2.5 million contract.
The 6-foot-11 Chones played 11 seasons, bowing out with an NBA
title in Magic Johnson's rookie season with the Los Angeles Lakers.
In Chones' adolescence, a teenage girl didn't lift weights three or
four days a week during the off-season like Kaayla does now. She'd
have been called a freak, or worse. There was no opportunity to
hone one's game on the summer-league circuit, auditioning for
clipboard-carrying college coaches at events funded by shoe
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Elores Chores says, as best she can remember, Cleveland's John
Adams High didn't even have a girls' team when she was coming up in
early '70s . ``I would have loved the opportunity they have now,''
said Elores. At 5-9, she probably could have been a player. Jim
describes her as ``a great athlete,'' recalling she used to run him
into the ground while helping him get ready for training camp late
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   And here was their daughter in the eighth grade, the top player
on her Police Athletic League team, telling her father: ``Dad, I
want to be good.'' She tagged along as a go-fer at the Jim Chones
Basketball Camp, listening and learning, not far from the knee of
his former NBA cronies.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Campy Russell, suggested incorporating the George
Mikan drills, repetitive techniques named after the NBA's first
standout big man, to improve her coordination and cut down on
missed layups.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an easement right next to our house, and it's 60 yards
long,'' Chones said. ``I'd have her run 'suicides.' Up and down was
one. I'd have her run five of them. Then, I'd have her do more
'Mikans.' That's where she learned her touch around the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, she's incorporated a little Kevin McHale. She'll
step out, step back through and bank it off the glass. I just
showed her how to do it, but a lot of it was her initiative,
getting out there and working hard on her own. Everybody says, 'Oh,
she got it from her dad.' And she really didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was Dad's decision to switch her from a
``high-powered'' private-school program to a public school after
ninth grade, he acknowledges that Mom deserves more credit than he.
Jim is overseeing the rest of this mother lode of basketball talent
_ triplet 13-year-old sons Kendall (6'-4 1/2''), Kyle (6'-4'') and
Kameron (5'-10''). Elores, also Kaayla's best friend, takes her to
practice and travels to her games. She helps sort through the
recruiting letters. She enforces the long-established house rule:
Good grades or you don't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm her biggest critic and biggest fan,'' said Elores,
a fixture in the stands above her daughter's team bench. ``We have
a system, and have had since she was a freshman. If she is not
rebounding, I have certain hand signals to let her know. It's two
thumbs up. Or if she's not being aggressive, there is a sign. I'll
cross my arms and lift them up. Or I'll point to my brain, and that
means focus more. Play smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows them all right off the bat, and that helps get her
game together without everyone else knowing what I'm telling her to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is a girl thing. With opportunity denied her, Elores
Chones stands watch over her daughter to ensure that Kaayla's shot
isn't missed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
