<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-RECRUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recruiting budgets: Nothing to huge
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rental car heads west on I-20 toward Birmingham
carrying the head coach of the Georgia women's basketball team, a
bottle of Mountain Dew, two cheap cigars for chewin' and spittin'
and road money from a recruiting budget that has grown from zero to
$60,000, give or take a drive-through-window meal. A weekend in the
spring. Six hundred teenage girls on 48 teams playing 120 games on
six courts in two gymnasiums over 44 hours, not including a
midnight all-star game that has one punchy, bleary-eyed coach
cracking, ``These poor kids actually think we're watching them
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And this was the (BEGIN ITAL)first (END ITAL) Deep South
Classic. Imagine when the tournament grows.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Landers can blame himself in part. Nineteen years ago, he
came to the Georgia athletics department, which consisted of a
football team and minor sports, and persuaded them not only to hire
its first full-time women's basketball coach but to fill the
position with a junior-college coach from some Tennessee outpost.
After Landers got the job, he tried importing a concept foreign to
women's basketball: recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you where things were,'' Landers said. ``When I
took the job, I called the coach at Lowndes County High School,
which at the time was in the midst of, like, a 160-game winning
streak. So the coach, Charles Cooper, answers the phone and I said,
`Hi, I'm Andy Landers, University of Georgia, and I'm interested in
a couple of your players.' He says, `Really? This is the first time
we've ever gotten a call from Georgia.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm thinking, `I got a problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   That autumn, Landers set out to build bridges with state
high-school coaches. He drove up to Dalton, down to Rome, through
Worth County, over to Lowndes, then hooked back north. He would
walk into a school and stay five minutes or an hour. (BEGIN ITAL)
Hi, I'm Andy Landers. Have any good players? Seen any good players?
(END ITAL) Then he returned home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days later,'' Landers said, ``I'm in my office, and my
athletics director at the time, Liz Murphy, comes in and says, `I
got a call from another coach in the state who said you're
cheating.' I said, `I am?' Liz says, `Yeah, they said you're going
around talking to people. You can't do that.' I said, `Liz. That's
not cheating. That's called recruiting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
