<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Are there any factory-outlet stores or other discount stores
in Italy that sell the wonderful silk fabric that can be made into
ties? _ Patricia Tracy, Blacksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you want printed silk to make neckties, the best place to
shop is in and around Como, about 30 miles north of Milan on the
southwestern tip of Lake Como, in the heart of the Italian silk
country. Trains depart hourly from Milan's central station, and the
trip takes about 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Many producers have outlets at or near the factory that sell to
the public at a discount. The city of Como also has numerous stores
that sell silk by the meter (a little more than a yard), but it
costs about 10 percent to 15 percent more at these stores.
</P>
<P>
   One silk factory with an outlet is Ratti, 19 Via Cernobbio, Como
22100, telephone (39-031) 233 111. Maureen Fallon, the personal
assistant to the president, said that factory outlets typically
sold remnants from the end of bolts of silk. She estimated that one
meter of silk, which is about a yard wide and would sell for about
$20 in the outlet store, would be enough to make four neckties.
</P>
<P>
   The store also sells scarves and neckties ith famous labels like
Versace. A Valentino scarf, she said, would cost about $60 at the
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   For a list of outlets, contact the Como Tourism Office, 17
Piazza Cavour, Como 22100, fax (39-031) 240 111. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to explore the Intracoastal Waterway. Which
states does it pass through? Do you know of any cruises on the
waterway? _ Lee M. Spangler, San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   A. The Intracoastal Waterway consists of two main parts: the
Atlantic and Gulf intracoastal waterways. The former extends from
Boston to Key West, Fla.; the latter from Apalachee Bay, Fla., to
Brownsville, Texas In total, they provide a 2,500-mile network of
channels for barges and other light-draft vessels along the
Atlantic and Gulf Coasts, often following rivers, bays, coastal
sounds and canals.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the relatively shallow waters (as little as 12 feet
in some places), intracoastal cruises are on smaller ships, like
the American Canadian Caribbean Line's 100-passenger Grande Mariner
and Grande Caribe.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-day Intracoastal Waterway cruise travels from Warren, R.I.,
to Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. (or in the reverse direction, depending
on the date) with stops in Baltimore; Norfolk, Va.; Belhaven,
Beaufort and Southport, N.C.; Georgetown and Charleston, S.C.;
Savannah and St. Simons Island, Ga.; and St. Augustine, Titusville
and Hobe Sound, Fla. Southbound departures are Oct. 30 and Nov. 1
this year and May 26, Oct. 31 and Nov. 7 next year; northbound
April 25, May 9 and June 12 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rates are $2,255 to $2,795 a person, double occupancy, depending
on the cabin. Air fare and sightseeing excursions are extra.
Contact American Canadian Caribbean, 461 Water Street, Post Office
Box 368, Warren, R.I. 02885; (800) 556-7450, fax (401) 247-2350;
www.accl-smallships.com.
</P>
<P>
   Clipper Cruise Line, 7711 Bonhomme Avenue, St. Louis, Mo. 53105;
(800) 325-0010 (on the Web: www.clippercruise.com), also offers
cruises on the waterway on its 100-passenger Nantucket Clipper and
122-passenger Clipper Adventurer. The Nantucket Clipper has
eight-day Antebellum South cruises Oct. 31 and Nov. 7, 14 and 21
this year and March 6, 13, 20 and 27 and April 3 and 10 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The ships travel one way between Jacksonville, Fla., and
Charleston, S.C., with stops in St. Marys, St. Simons Island,
Savannah and Beaufort. Rates, per person double occupancy, are
$1,950 to $3,495. Air fare is extra.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-day Colonial America and Civil War Battlefields cruise Apr.
17, 1999, goes from Jacksonville to Baltimore, with stops including
New Bern, N.C., and Norfolk. Rates: $3,800 to $6,560.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket Clipper also has a 15-day cruise including the
Chesapeake Bay and New England ports departing May 15 ($3,900 to
$6,990).
</P>
<P>
   But the grand tour of the Intracoastal Waterway is a 22-day trip
from Halifax, Nova Scotia, to Port Everglades, Fla., departing
Sept. 2, 1999, on the Clipper Adventurer. The tour, known as the
Great North American Odyssey, costs $6,920 to $11,200 a person,
double occupancy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be in Melbourne sometime in January and we would like
to know what's on the schedule for various performing-arts centers
and companies, including the Sidney Myer Music Bowl, the Australian
Ballet and the Melbourne Concert Hall. Can you help us? _ William
E. Claypool, Steilacoom, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, the bad news: The dancers for the Australian Ballet,
telephone (61-3) 9684-8600, will be returning from their holiday
break about that time and will be in rehearsal for ``Don Quixote,''
which begins Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be a busy schedule at other performing-arts spots
around the city. At the Sidney Myer Music Bowl, 21 Linithgow
Avenue, (61-3) 9281-8360, there will be an Australia Day concert on
Jan. 26, although details have not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Australia Day is comparable to Independence Day here, and the
music bowl typically holds a concert with prominent Australian
performers (last year's stars were a rock group). Seating is
outdoors, with 2,000 permanent seats and room for 11,000 more
people on its lawn. You'll be there during the Southern Hemisphere
summer, a good time for alfresco music. Best of all, admission to
the Australia Day concert will probably be free.
</P>
<P>
   At the Melbourne Concert Hall, part of the Victorian Arts
Center, 100 St. Kilda Road, the Scottish comedian Billy Connolly,
who was the co-star with Judi Dench of the 1997 movie ``Mrs.
Brown,'' will be performing his stand-up routine on Jan. 18 to 20,
22 to 28, and 30 and 31. Call (61-3) 9281-8000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy Tonight'' seems to be the theme at the arts center. ``A
Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum'' will be playing at
the State Theater, another part of the center complex, Jan. 1 to
Feb. 7. Call for times and ticket prices. Rounding out the arts
center's schedule, the Playhouse will feature ``Master Class'' from
Jan. 4 to 30.
</P>
<P>
   You can book tickets for the Victorian Arts Centre in the United
States through ATS Tours at (800) 423-2880, fax (310) 643-0032. Or
you can call directly at (61-3) 9281-8000, fax (61-3) 9281-8381, or
try www.artscentre.net.au.
</P>
<P>
   For other questions on Melbourne, contact Tourism Victoria, 2049
Century Park East, No. 1920, Los Angeles, Calif. 90067; (310)
229-4892.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
