<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-CO     09-21 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shock for cynical era
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the exact moment when it seemed that nothing else could
possibly come as a shock, as CNN was airing the leader of the free
world's taped quibbling over the meaning of the word ``is,'' a
bulletin flashed onscreen, a bulletin that caused even this most
jaded of jaws to drop:
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence Griffith Joyner dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost exactly 10 years after her golden Olympiad, the greatest
female athlete of the age died in her sleep. Her heart stopped
beating. She was 38. In any form, death tends to make little sense.
This made none.
</P>
<P>
   Sleek and elegant sprinters aren't supposed to die, not at 38.
The heart that makes a runner invincible isn't supposed to stop
arbitrarily. Whenever a great athlete dies, at any age under any
circumstances, it slaps those who live on unusually hard, offering
the grim reminder that conspicuous health carries no guarantee,
that each life has its own unknowable expiration date. But FloJo?
The utter essence of grace and vitality? Gone not 10 years after
Seoul? Just what kind of world is this?
</P>
<P>
   We Americans tend to ignore track and field except when shining
superiority demands that we look. FloJo made us look. In 1988, she
was the pre-eminent athlete on the planet, an extravagantly garbed
joy at a time when it was revealed that the world's fastest man was
a cheat. Ben Johnson had steroid-discolored eyes. FloJo had
one-legged unitards and abundant fingernails. Johnson left Seoul a
disgrace. FloJo came home the Queen of the World.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's 1998 and she's dead.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe an autopsy will help sort out the unfathomable. Probably
not. Joyner had what now seems a similar seizure two years ago, but
that didn't really register with the masses. And it wasn't as if
she appeared old and infirm. On the contrary, we could still view
her in upscale magazines, lending her upper lip to those milk
promos.
</P>
<P>
   The records she set in the 100 and 200 still stand. At the 1988
Olympic trials, she cut .27 seconds off the existing mark, a
slashing of exponential proportion. Joyner's time was 10.49. No
woman has since run even a 10.6. In a Pentium II age in which
everything runs faster, nobody has yet outrun FloJo.
</P>
<P>
   Because she was so dominant in such a catty sport, FloJo had to
deny that her speed was drug-enhanced. It was easy to believe her,
for hers was such a sunny story. Born and raised in L.A., she
graduated from UCLA and won a silver medal at the 1984 Games in her
hometown. Two years later, substantially over her running weight,
she was working at a bank and braiding hair on the side. Then she
married Al Joyner, himself an Olympian, and resumed serious
training. Her coach was Bobby Kersee, husband of the great
heptathlete Jackie Joyner-Kersee and Al's brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   They were the First Family of American sport, elating in one
another's triumphs. JJK was practical, FloJo exotic yet demure.
Together they graced the cover of Sports Illustrated in 1988, five
Olympic golds between them. In 1996, Joyner-Kersee took bronze in
the long jump at what is now Turner Field. Today her sister-in-law
is dead. What kind of world is this?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
