<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flo Jo had `a certain flair'
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her colorful bodysuits and and six-inch decorated
fingernails, Florence Griffith Joyner made it fashionable to look
good and run fast. Other female athletes have come along to fill
the glamor role, but no one has matched the breathtaking speed of
the woman known as Flo Jo, who grabbed three gold medals while
turning the 1988 Seoul Olympics into a personal showcase.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after her heroics, the world's greatest female sprinter
was found dead Monday of an apparent heart seizure at her home in
Mission Viejo, Calif. She was 38.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County, Calif. sheriff's office said it received a
911 call early Monday from her husband, former Olympic triple
jumper Al Joyner, who reported his wife was ``unresponsive and not
breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had passed away during the night,'' spokesman Lt. Hector
Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Griffith Joyner suffered a heart seizure during a
flight. Still, news of her death was met with shock and disbelief
within the sport's community, which three years ago witnessed her
induction into the National Track and Field Hall of Fame during
ceremonies in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Florence Griffith Joyner had had some heart
problems in recent months, but didn't think that it was anything
really serious,'' said Primo Nebiolo, head of the international
track federation. ``I will never forget this extraordinary athlete
who stunned the world in Seoul. . . . Sadly, her life has passed as
rapidly as her races.''
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, Griffith Joyner, raised in the Watts section of Los
Angeles, captured the 100-meter gold medal in a wind-aided 10.54
seconds and later shattered the world 200 record in the Olympic
final, clocking 21.34. At the Olympic Trials two months earlier,
she had crossed the 100 finish line in 10.49, wiping out Evelyn
Ashford's world record of 10.76.
</P>
<P>
   Not until this summer, with the emergence of Marion Jones, has
either record been seriously challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a certain flair, a flamboyance the rest of us didn't
have with the fingernails, the hair, the outfits,'' Ashford said.
``She attracted people to the sport who probably wouldn't otherwise
watch a track meet.'' ``Understand, track had long been a
male-dominated sport, and with style and grace she showed you can
be a female and compete,'' said Sandra Farmer-Patrick, a former
Olympic hurdler. ``She used to say, `You can look beautiful, feel
beautiful and compete beautiful.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
