<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE BANK COMPROMISE FRAYS ALREADY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A broad-based banking compromise measure that Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi had hailed as the foundation for Japan's
economic recovery began to fray Monday, just as Obuchi prepared to
meet with President Clinton in the United States on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The banking deal, which Obuchi had pursued intensely in advance
of his meeting with Clinton, at the Rockefeller estate near
Tarrytown, N.Y., had been many weeks in the making. It was intended
to help stabilize Japan's shaky financial system and to be the
basis for legislation to restore international confidence in the
nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese markets reacted to the development negatively. Stocks
fell sharply here Monday, with the benchmark Nikkei index of 225
issues dropping by 385.82 points, or 2.76 percent, to 13,597.30, a
12{-year low. The exchange value of the yen declined against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a major bond-rating agency, Fitch IBCA of London,
lowered Japan's long-term foreign currency debt rating from AAA to
AA plus. It said that with the nation's deteriorating banking
system, increasing government debt and slow response by
policy-makers, the risks of lending to Japan by overseas investors
could no longer be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The banking agreement was supposed to forge a sweeping plan that
ranged from a framework for rescuing Japan's very large, very weak
banks to a sharp reduction in the power of the Finance Ministry,
which had been the nation's most influential bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The central dispute Monday concerned whether an old fund to
rescue weak banks _ which Obuchi promised to dissolve _ would still
be used. Since the government had agreed to abandon old financing
devices, many people had assumed this would not be used.
</P>
<P>
   But Obuchi's aides now say that they may use the old system
anyway because it is necessary to prevent a disruption in the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current scheme will be effective until a new scheme is
formed,'' the top government spokesman, Hiromu Nonaka, said. ``The
government will need to cope without disturbances.''
</P>
<P>
   Another top official, Yoshiro Mori, general secretary of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party, suggested over the weekend that
the old system could be used to assist the Long-Term Credit Bank of
Japan, which is floundering and may need assistance in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As the government appeared to backtrack from the agreement,
opposition leaders warned that the entire accord might be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the main opposition Democratic Party, Naoto Kan,
objected on Sunday to the government's interpretation. In
particular, he rejected the idea of using tax money to bail out the
Long-Term Credit Bank under the current setup. Kan was reported in
the Japanese news media to have said that he was braced for the
collapse of the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreements will have to be resolved when Prime Minister
Obuchi returns to Tokyo from the United States. And the opposition
groups do not seem to be in a mood to give in and allow the use of
public funds to help the Long-Term Credit Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``That constitutes a clear violation of our agreement,'' said
Motohisa Ikeda, a member of Parliament who was chief negotiator of
the agreement for the Democratic Party, in an interview Monday.
Asked whether it was possible that the agreement would totally
unravel, he replied, ``I cannot exclude the possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats and banking officials have suggested that the
Long-Term Credit Bank could face a severe upheaval toward the end
of this month, when the bank settles its half-year accounts.
Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest-circulation daily, carried a
report containing charges that the bank had covered up huge amounts
of bad debt. The bank, denying this, said there had been no
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Comments by Mori, the governing party's secretary-general, also
suggested that the Liberal Democrats might be backtracking on the
issue of stripping financial regulatory power from the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   But Ikeda, the opposition legislator, said it was more likely
that the Liberal Democrats would go back to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the heated exchanges underlined the confusion over the
agreement, which was marked by the kind of ambiguity that led one
Democratic Party official to describe Friday's deal as ``tamamushi
iro'' _ the color of a Japanese insect that seems different
depending on the angle from which it is seen.
</P>
<P>
   Party politicians on both sides of the argument acknowledged
that a great number of details needed to be ironed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
