<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-BRUINS-OFFERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS REPORT LITTLE MOVEMENT   ON OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President/general manager Harry Sinden thought at the
end of last week that free agent defenseman Kyle McLaren was close
to being back in the fold. However, as of Monday afternoon, Sinden
had heard nothing from McLaren's representative, Doug Messier. The
club had pitched a one-year proposal to the young blue liner, who
is not eligible for arbitration for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Messier) was supposed to call Friday but he didn't,'' said
Sinden. ``I thought we were rather close to doing a one-year deal.
I was kind of hopeful. We were more receptive to a one-year deal
with him because if he has a good year again, we can talk about a
long-term deal. When we last talked, (Messier) didn't indicate he'd
take my offer but he said to let him talk to Kyle.''
</P>
<P>
   As for free agents Jason Allison and Anson Carter, Sinden said
assistant GM Mike O'Connell was awaiting word from Bob Gerow,
Allison's representative, while the Carter situation was pretty
well dead in the water as the sides remain far apart.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he amended the team's offer to Allison. While the
length remained the same (one year with a club option for a
second), the Bruins added performance bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to Ted Donato, Sinden had yet to hear from him or
his agent, Mark Witkin. Donato has requested a trade and the Bruins
are trying to accommodate him, but so far there are no takers.
Donato and Witkin sent a memo out across the league, with the
Bruins' blessing, to let teams know how much it would cost to sign
him if they were to deal for his rights. It hasn't had the desired
effect of greasing the skids for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason is that all the teams are wondering if they
should take on an extra contract until they see what they've got,''
said Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   It would make more sense for Donato to be in camp, working out
and playing in exhibition games so other clubs can take a look at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've advanced those same thoughts,'' said Sinden. ``But they
haven't budged.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato seems to feel he has a better chance of being traded by
sitting out so that he wouldn't be used by the Bruins as an
insurance policy for Allison and Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's discouraging when young players are not at training
camp,'' Sinden said. ``It doesn't take long until their whole game
gets off track.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three players in contract disputes _ Donato's
holdout isn't financially motivated _ has arbitration rights. But
according to Sinden, they want to be paid as if they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying, `If we had arbitration, we'd kick the hell out
of you but since we don't, we want you to kick the hell out of
yourself,''' he said. ``They want us to act as if we'd be a
generous arbitrator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
