<HEADLINE>
NOTES ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 Taliesin West Offers Special Look at Wright  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The documentarian Ken Burns, whose PBS series have dissected
topics as all-American as baseball and the Civil War, will now
tackle another native subject: Frank Lloyd Wright, whom Burns calls
America's greatest architect.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour biography is to be shown in two parts on PBS on
Nov. 10 and 11, and in conjunction with it, Taliesin West _ the
architect's winter home, studio and architectural campus in
Scottsdale, Ariz., from 1937 until his death in 1959 _ will present
four days of events from Oct. 8 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the four days, ``Celebrate the Legacy,'' will
be a dinner with Burns and Lynn Novick, co-producers of the
documentary, and a preview screening of a shortened version of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Taliesin West, a National Historic Landmark in the foothills of
the McDowell Mountains, is the site of the Frank Lloyd Wright
Foundation, Archives and School of Architecture. Participants will
be able to talk with former Wright associates, view the
``shelters'' designed by apprentices to house themselves, and visit
several Wright buildings in the Phoenix area, including the Price
House, First Christian Church, the David Lloyd Wright house and
Grady Gammage Memorial Auditorium at Arizona State University, and
explore the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Featured speakers include David Elgin Dodge, a faculty member of
the Frank Lloyd Wright School of Architecture, who will discuss
Wright's influence on the Arizona Biltmore Hotel in Phoenix; Bruce
Brooks Pfeiffer, director of the Wright Archives, and Kathryn
Smith, author of several books about the architect, including
``Frank Lloyd Wright: America's Master Architect.''
</P>
<P>
   Most events cost $10 to $40, the reception and dinner with Burns
and Ms. Novick $150. For information, call (602) 860-2700,
extension 481. A limited number of discounted rooms have been
reserved for the foundation at the Arizona Biltmore at $250 a
night; for reservations, call (800) 950-0086.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Shattuck &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Willy Moves to Iceland, A Little Freer &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world's most famous killer whale may be gone, but Newport,
Ore., hopes tourists will keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, Newport, a town of 9,700 on the central Oregon coast
about 95 miles from Portland, bade farewell to Keiko, the
10,000-pound star of the ``Free Willy'' movies, when he was flown
to Iceland, the site of his capture in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   While he resided at the Oregon Coast Aquarium in Newport _ after
his removal from a cramped, overheated tank in a Mexico City
amusement park _ the black and white orca boosted tourism in
Newport, which has a quaint waterfront and nearby beaches. Keiko
was brought there in 1996 with the hope that he would learn to
survive in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   While Keiko is gone, Newport has a new coastal interpretive
center at the lighthouse, and the recently renovated Hatfield
Marine Science Center of Oregon State University; call (541)
867-0100 for information. Construction continues on an oceanfront
hotel, while the aquarium itself plans to convert Keiko's
2.1-million-gallon tank into shallow- and deep-ocean habitats
through which visitors would walk in a clear tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium is open daily. Admission is $8.75, $7.75 for those
65 and older, and $4.50 ages 4 to 13. Information: (541) 867-3474.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko's new Icelandic home is a large pen in a bay just off the
Westmann Islands, a popular summer destination for Reykjavik
residents, about four hours by ferry or 20 minutes by plane from
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may get lucky and see Keiko through binoculars from a
600-foot cliff, but it is not likely, according to the Save
Willy-Keiko Foundation, the entity that will decide whether the
orca can be set free. Bob Ratliffe, the executive vice president of
the foundation, said it was highly questionable whether Keiko can
be released. Information on Keiko is available on the Web at
www.keiko.org.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hall &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In Hartford, Landscapes From Two New Worlds &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago, as the new United States and the new
British colony in Australia confronted their vast wildernesses,
expanses never imagined in their mother country, what kind of
landscape art did they produce? How was it similar, how different?
``New Worlds From Old: 19th-Century Australian and American
Landscapes,'' which opened at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford
this month, offers some answers.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition brings together about 120 Australian and American
landscapes from the 1800s. They are drawn from 32 American museums,
11 in Australia and 2 in Europe. They include paintings by Frederic
Church, William Merritt Chase, Winslow Homer and 34 other
Americans, as well as 23 Australian artists.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was co-organized by and first shown last spring
at the National Gallery of Australia in Canberra. It then traveled
to the National Gallery of Victoria in Melbourne. The exhibition
continues at the Atheneum until Jan. 3. Its final stop will be at
the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington, from Jan. 26 through
Apr. 18.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the exhibition, the Atheneum has planned a
symposium, ``Crosscurrents: Fresh Perspectives on 19th-Century `New
World' Landscape Painting.'' Robert Hughes, the Time magazine art
critic and an Australian, will give the keynote lecture at 5 p.m.
on Oct. 23 at The Bushnell, a theater at 166 Capitol Avenue,
Hartford; tickets are $25 from the Bushnell's box office, (860)
246-6807. The symposium continues on Oct. 24 at the Atheneum.
</P>
<P>
   The Wadsworth, at 600 Main Street, is open Tuesday through
Sunday. Admission, with a $2 surcharge for this show, is $9, $8 for
ages 60 and up and college students, and $5 ages 6 to 17.
Information: (860) 278-2670.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In another effort by Iran to show greater hospitality toward the
United States, Americans will be able to visit Iran by ship for the
first time in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in November, the 56-passenger Monet will offer 22
seven-night cruises in the Persian Gulf out of Dubai in the United
Arab Emirates, with 11 including a call at Bandar Abbas in Iran, an
ancient maritime center on the Strait of Hormuz with antique
monuments and fortress ruins. Other ports of call include Muscat,
Oman; Manama, Bahrain, and Abu Dhabi and Sharjah in the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   While the cruise is a sign of Iran's new openness, the State
Department still warns Americans to defer travel there. It says
there is ``evidence that hostility to the United States remains in
some segments'' of the population and government.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilt Monet offers staterooms with color TV, videocassette
recorders, hair dryers and telephones, and all have outside views.
The cruise package costs $3,297 a person, double occupancy,
including air fare from the East Coast and all excursions. Call Sea
Air Holidays, (800) 732-6247. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Jackson Hole Fancies Up With a New Hotel &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a case of East goes West, Amanresorts, the Hong Kong-based
chain of elegant retreats, is opening its first American resort, in
Jackson Hole, Wyo., on Thursday. And like many elements of the
company, the resort's name, Amangani, is a cultural mix _ ``Aman''
is Sanskrit for ``peaceful'' and ``gani'' is Shoshone for ``home.''
</P>
<P>
   This peaceful home out West is anything but a simple frontier
ranch, though. Amangani offers 40 suites of sandstone, cedar and
redwood, built into the side of East Gros Ventre Butte, 7,000 feet
above sea level, with the town of Jackson below and the Grand
Tetons stretching to the north. Each suite comes with a mini-bar,
CD player, television with VCR, data lines for computers, sunken
tub, and terrace or deck with mountain or valley views.
</P>
<P>
   The resort's centerpiece, set on the 1,000-acre Spring Creek
Ranch, is a three-story building whose central area includes a
library, lounge, bar, restaurant and fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   There are two wings of suites stretching along the butte. Guests
have the use of a 115-foot heated outdoor pool, two tennis courts,
stables and cross-country skiing trails on the property. Among the
activities available nearby are golf, hunting, fly-fishing, rafting
and, of course, alpine skiing (about 25 minutes by car).
</P>
<P>
   Nightly rates till Dec. 19 are $400 to $600 plus tax, then $450
to $750. Reservations: (877) 734-7333, fax (307) 734-7332.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Cormier
</P>
</TEXT>
