<HEADER>
A6906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NEW22-COX     09-21 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEW22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOCUMENTS OFFER A WEALTH OF SCANDAL TRIVIA
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE and ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of new details, ranging from the
salacious to the hilarious, emerged Monday from the 3,183 pages of
documents released from Independent Counsel Kenneth Star's
investigation:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Starr hired a professional appraiser to establish the ``fair
market value'' of gifts to Lewinsky from the president. They
included a sculpture depicting ``Spirit of the Grizzly Bear,''
$200; a coverlet depicting the ``Radio City Music Hall Christmas
Special'' starring the Rockettes, $50; a White House paperweight,
$10; a hat pin, $3; a gold-plated brooch, $5, and a silver-plated
brooch, $3.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In March 1997, after Clinton injured his knee on a visit to
Florida, Lewinsky sent him a ``care package'' including a ``Hi ya
handsome!'' card, a license plate with ``BILL'' for his wheelchair
and kneepads with the presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Vox,'' the Nicholson Baker novel about phone sex that she
gave to him, was listed on the inventory of the library in the
White House study between Frederick Talbott's ``Churchill on
Courage,'' and ``UFO Crash at Roswell'' by Kevin D. Randle and
Donald R. Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Linda Tripp, who taped telephone conversations in which her
co-worker Lewinsky described sexual escapades with Clinton, kept
the filled tapes haphazardly stored in a bowl in her Maryland
suburban home. Those tapes are now the object of a Starr inquiry
because nine of them were found to be duplicates, not originals.
</P>
<P>
   The documents state that ``if Ms. Tripp duplicated any tapes
herself or knew of their duplication, then she has lied under oath
before the grand jury and in a deposition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  After Lewinsky placed an anonymous Valentine's Day classified
ad with a quote from ``Romeo and Juliet'' in the Washington Post of
Feb. 14, 1997, Tripp e-mailed her that ``It read beautifully,
placement was great, typeface totally effective and text
superlative. ... good job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lewinsky's computer e-mail messages indicate that she was not
paralyzed by grief after Clinton broke off their relationship in
the spring of 1997. In early summer, she wrote of a brief affair
with a nutritionist at a spa in Connecticut, although she wrote
that they avoided each other on her second trip to the spa.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Writing in early August 1997 about an encounter with another
man, she wrote, ``I am sooooooo naughty. It was fun and good. I
went over there with some ice cream and pretty much seduced him in
a way that made him make the moves on me ... cool or what????''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monica Lewinsky's feelings for President Clinton cooled
considerably after she watched his address to the nation on Monday,
Aug. 17, in which he acknowledged a relationship that was
inappropriate but did not mention her.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in her grand jury testimony whether she still loved the
president, Lewinsky said, ``It was very painful for me to watch his
speech on Monday night. It's hard for me to feel that he has
characterized this relationship as a service contract and that
that's all this relationship was. And it was a lot more than that
to me ...''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lewinsky gave the president some ``gummy boobs'' candy from
Urban Outfitters at their last meeting on Dec. 28, 1997, during
which she was given a ``Christmas kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inventories included in the records showed that Lewinsky kept
her size-10 blue dress from the Gap on a hanger in a plastic
cleaner's bag. On why she failed to clean it after it was stained
with semen during a session with Clinton, she explained: ``I gained
weight so I couldn't wear the dress and it didn't fit. And I'm not
a very organized person. I don't clean my clothes until I'm going
to wear them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers Washington correspondent Bob Dart also
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
