<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SHRUG OFF CLINTON NEWS; PRICES GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US stocks rebounded strongly Monday after plunging in early
morning trading as relieved investors decided that President
Clinton's video testimony on the White House sex scandal offered no
new bombshells that could spur impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A jittery Wall Street, which awoke to sharply lower markets
around the globe, sent the Dow Jones industrial average down 185
points in the first half-hour of trading before bargain hunters
came out to lift the index nearly 38 points to close at 7933.25.
The bounce was enough to bring the 30-share Dow back to where it
started 1998. But the blue-chip index, full of household-name
stocks that are industry leaders, is still 15 percent below its
July 17 peak of 9337.97.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing political instability in Washington, D.C., and
shuddering at Tokyo's failure to pass finance reform measures
designed to pull Japan out of its worst economic crisis since World
War II, global stock exchanges &UR;  &LR;  took a drubbing. London closed
down 1.3 percent to a nine-month low, Frankfurt fell 4 percent, and
Paris slipped 3.5 percent. Tokyo stocks skidded to a 12-year low.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, early selling came mostly from foreign investors,
who had seen no good news the night before in Asia or Europe. Wall
Street's drop began only minutes after US television networks began
broadcasting Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; US mutual fund managers, worried about having to raise cash to
meet redemptions for nervous shareholders, may have simply sat on
the sidelines before jumping in to buy later in the day, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon, when networks finished airing Clinton's
four-hour grand jury testimony, investors were ready to shop.
Buying by bargain-hunting fund managers and computer-driven program
trading gave many shares, especially in the healthcare and
technology sectors, a boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market tracked perfectly the closing of the
(Clinton) &UR;  &LR; tape,'' said Ned Riley, BankBoston's chief investment
strategist. ``Clearly, traders' greatest fear was not realized.''
</P>
<P>
   With fewer fears that impeachment could distract Clinton from an
extraordinary bout of global financial &UR;  &LR;  volatility, investment
strategists are focusing their attention on the outlook for
corporate profits. Economists are also busy calibrating fallout
from Asia and Russia, whose financial and political instability has
whacked &UR;  &LR;  emerging markets worldwide, especially in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said estimates by First Call, a financial data firm, that
fourth-quarter US corporate earnings would rise 17 percent and
level off to 13 percent in 1998 were too high. ``We are still under
pressure,'' he said, adding that earnings over both periods would
be flat or down 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that mutual fund investors are also taking a more
cautious view, investors put nearly $4 billion into US stock funds
last week, according to Trim Tabs Financial Services of Santa Rosa,
Calif. The bulk of the cash went into conservative growth funds,
the fund tracking firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Other US market measures also showed gains Monday. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index, the broadest market proxy, ticked up 0.37
percent to close at 1023.89, while the technology-heavy NASDAQ
composite index gained 1 percent to close at 1680.43. The Russell
2000, full of smaller stocks, lost 0.62 percent to end at 362.64.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was light due to the Jewish New Year holiday, with three
issues declining for every two advancing on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
