<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-TUESDAYS-SPI &LR;      09-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-TUESDAYS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 YOU PROBABLY WON'T WANT AN ENCORE OF `ENCORE, ENCORE!'
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the title, there might not be a nationwide clamor for a
curtain call from ``Encore! Encore!''
</P>
<P>
   With marquee names like Nathan Lane and Joan Plowright and the
delightul Glenne Headly behind it, one is tempted to assume the
result will be a slam-dunk piece of first-rate entertainment. But
the new NBC comedy starring Lane as a faded opera star has had a
long and trying gestation, complete with retooling and recasting of
characters, and its birth tonight is still a difficult one. Bottom
line: When the material is weak, famous names don't mean diddly.
</P>
<P>
   By placing it between ``Mad About You'' and ``Just Shoot Me,''
NBC is saying that ``Encore! Encore!'' is a favored child. Never
mind that ``Mad About You'' is well past its prime and ``Just Shoot
Me'' hasn't reached it yet. The shows do reasonably well in the
ratings, which should mean nice numbers for the new kid.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they're deserved is always the big-money question, and
based on tonight's premiere episode and a second one provided
critics in advance, ``Encore! Encore!'' will have a hard time
making it to a smattering of applause in New Haven, let alone a
standing ovation on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's portrayal of retired tenor Joseph Pinoni, whose voice
went south and forced him to move west to the family vineyards in
the Napa Valley, is much too mannered to be funny. And Plowright,
as his widowed mother, Marie, is overly theatrical in a Julia Child
warble. Granted, exaggeration, especially Joseph's uncontrollable
need to be in the spotlight, is part of the story line here, but
only Glenne Headly, as Joseph's sister, Francesca, seems grounded
in some sort of reality. Which brings to mind the broad ``realism''
of the people in ``Frasier,'' a show that manages to make its
characters believable in spite of ridiculous situations and absurd
personal traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encore! Encore!'' is from the people who created ``Frasier,''
so there may still be hope. But where the writing on ``Frasier'' is
so original that I sometimes slap my forehead in amazement, the
first couple of scripts from ``Encore! Encore!'' make me want to
slap someone at NBC. Again and again.
</P>
<P>
   A better bet at 8:30 tonight might be ``The Hughleys'' on ABC,
in which comedian D.L. Hughley doesn't have to stretch too far to
play Darryl Hughley, an upwardly mobile African American
businessman who moves his family to a new house in a new
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The new neighborhood isn't at all like the old one, and it's
taking a while for D.L. to find his comfort zone. For example, he's
ill at ease in a place where you can pump your gas without having
to pay first. And people being neighborly _ that is, white people
being neighborly _ cause him to doubt their intentions and suspect
they're up to something.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, his best friend and sales manager Milsap (John Henton)
is no help, offering constant reminders that Darryl is on the
``slippery slope'' to losing his blackness.
</P>
<P>
   What makes ``The Hughleys'' appealing isn't anything
particularly mysterious. D.L. Hughley is a very funny guy. Perhaps
more salient for a lot of white folks: He is non-threatening, in
the Bill Cosby style. Elise Neal, who plays his TV wife, Yvonne, is
immensely appealing, and their well-meaning neighbors (Eric Allan
Kramer and Marietta DePrima), strike just the right combination of
warmth and skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Like any program with a message, ``The Hughleys'' plays up
stereotypes in order to expose them, but it avoids descending into
30-minute sermonizing or, worse, crude buffoonery. Instead, it
manages to point out the folly without losing the jolly. With a
little more polishing, ``The Hughleys'' can be a delicious treat,
even though it reminds us how far we have to go before people stop
making comedies about race relations.
</P>
<P>
   The fear among some TV types is that ``Sports Night'' is too
``inside baseball'' to appeal to mainstream America. The fact is,
``Sports Night'' isn't about sports, just as ``MASH'' wasn't about
the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a lot of sports jargon tossed about in ``Sports
Night,'' which takes place in the studios of an ESPN-style daily
sports program. But a show like ``ER'' doesn't seem to be
alienating too many viewers when it tosses around terms like
``gastric lavage'' and ``cross-table C-spine.'' Just a guess here,
but America's non-sporting public can probably handle a few
jock-ular references without panicking.
</P>
<P>
   And well they should. ``Sports Night'' is a terrific new show
from Aaron Sorkin, the guy who wrote the films ``A Few Good Men''
and ``The American President.'' Sorkin is expert at going for a
lump-in-the-throat, tear-in-the-eye reaction, but I'll take his
kind of manipulation over the standard sitcom setup in a Hollywood
minute, which is the same as a New York minute, only three hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Krause, Josh Charles, Felicity Huffman, Robert Guillaume
and a marvelous pack of supporting players lend a palpable pulse to
the most stylishly produced workplace/relationship series to arrive
in some time.
</P>
<P>
   Though packaged like a comedy, ``Sports Night'' isn't always
funny. It's just seriously good TV. Sign up for season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encore! Encore! Half-hour comedy about an opera singer who
retires to the quiet of his family's California winery. Premieres
Tuesday, NBC. Check local listings. Parental guideline rating:
TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _The Hughleys. Half-hour comedy about an African American family
that moves into a mostly white suburban neighborhood. Premieres
Tuesday night on ABC. Check local listings. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Sports Night. Half-hour series set behind the scenes of a
network sports show. Premieres Tuesday on ABC. Check local
listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send an e-mail
message to: tvguy &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
