<HEADLINE>
NEGATIVE ADS BEGIN EARLY IN GOVERNOR RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After just a few days of forswearing personal attacks,
the candidates for governor turned negative and released TV ads
that deride each other's record.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci fired the first shot at Democratic
nominee Scott Harshbarger Friday with an ad that says the attorney
general opposes mandatory testing for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Harshbarger,'' the ad intones. ``We can't afford to take
the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger struck back Monday with a 30-second spot that shows
him in shirtsleeves attempting to set the record straight. He says
he does support teacher testing, then jabs the Republican Cellucci
for his vetoes of expanded health care for children and tax cuts
that mostly benefit the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The negative ads, while coming a bit earlier than expected, are
symptomatic of a campaign in which the candidates do not have sharp
differences of opinion on many of the major issues. Both support
tax cuts, increased spending for education, and more day care. Both
are tough on crime. They differ on the death penalty, which
Cellucci supports and Harshbarger opposes, but that has rapidly
receded as a major issue since the Legislature voted it down last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Both ads are partly true. But both are veer substantially from
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Harshbarger supports teacher testing but has opposed firing
teachers solely on the basis of test results. He says tests should
be used as part of a comprehensive, meaningful evaluation but said
in a televised debate last month that he would fire teachers who
fail the tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cellucci says Harshbarger has caved to union pressure on
teacher testing. But Harshbarger differs with the Massachusetts
Teachers Association, which opposes testing.
</P>
<P>
   In Harshbarger's spot, he makes two claims _ that Cellucci's tax
cuts go to the wealthy while his are targeted at the middle class
and the elderly, and that Cellucci supported tobacco companies and
vetoed children's health care.
</P>
<P>
   _ On tobacco, Governor William F. Weld vetoed a measure in 1996
that would have provided health care for 168,000 low-income
children through a 25-cent-a-pack tax increase on cigarettes,
arguing that he supported the goal but not the tax hike. But last
year, a massive increase in the Medicaid program boosted health
coverage for low-income children, including all children whose
families earn twice the federal poverty limit or less. An estimated
50,000 children remain uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The argument on tax cuts centers around Harshbarger's contention
that his proposed cuts, which would come mainly in the form of
deductions, more directly benefit the middle class. The
Weld-Cellucci tax cuts, he argues, included capital gains cuts that
favor the wealthy, and cuts for the mutual fund and insurance
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has maintained that the administration's economic
policies have contributed to a 3 percent unemployment rate and a
robust economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harshbarger and Cellucci Monday continued their
battle over fiscal issues, squabbling over figures and cost
calculations for various proposals put forth by the Democratic
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The flare-up began with the acting governor accusing the
Democratic nominee of paving the way for new tax hikes because of
his new spending proposals, a persistent theme of Cellucci's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts cannot afford Scott Harshbarger,'' Cellucci
said. ``He would be a governor who would outspend the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger aides said Cellucci is using ``distortions and
inaccurate statements'' to promote his ``campaign of fear'' over
state finances and taxes. They also said Cellucci is wrong in
concluding Harshbarger has proposed $1.1 billion in spending for
new programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Harshbarger has proposed $400 million in new spending on
initiatives important to working people,'' said Dwight Robson,
Harshbarger's campaign press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Warren Tolman of Watertown, Harshbarger's running
mate, announced a three-point plan to improve the state's tracking
of education reform spending. The centerpiece of that plan is a
software program that will monitor spending in each school
district, at a cost of about $5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
