<HEADLINE>
MID-AMERICA DEPLORES LATEST CLINTON PROGRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ At Henry's on High restaurant Monday, the
owner, Henry Tran, offered a lunch special featuring thick &UR;  &LR; slices
of bologna. He swore it wasn't a sly commentary on the airing of
President Clinton's taped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Tran and most of the lunchtime patrons at his
downtown eatery seemed to wish they could turn the television
behind the bar back to its usual fare of daytime talk shows and
soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be behind closed doors,'' said Tran, a Vietnamese
immigrant, seeming pained by the spectacle unfolding on the 20-inch
screen behind him. ``It's embarrassing to this country in the eyes
of the world. It makes me feel sorry for everybody. And I feel
sorry for Clinton, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people don't respect the president, it is like the
children don't respect the parent, and that is terrible,'' Tran
said.
</P>
<P>
   At a nearby table, Darlene Edwards and Sherry Wilkie, accounts
payable clerks on their lunch hour, did their best to ignore the
president but now and again were drawn to the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's immoral what he did, but I don't need to see
this,'' said Edwards, who indicated her bologna sandwich was an
appropriate choice for the day. ``This should be between him and
his wife, but they probably just want to humiliate him further and
drag it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkie, though, saw a purpose to release of the grand jury
video: ``They're trying to make him resign, and I think that's
really the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Front and center at the bar sat Tom Swisher, a deputy clerk at
the Franklin County Courthouse, his head bobbing up and down
between the screen and his plate of American chop suey. ``It sounds
like to me he's trying to convince everybody he's telling the
truth. I don't know if he is, but we're all human and I feel this
has gone too far,'' Swisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher said he would like to see Monica Lewinsky's testimony as
well, because ``we all know it takes two to tango.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it would have been better if President Clinton had just
taken out his tenor sax and played, `Who's sorry now?''' Swisher
said, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   But fellow court clerks Mike Cherry and Tammy Van Gundy weren't
ready to let it go at that. ``The part about what he did doesn't
bother me,'' Cherry said. ``It's the lies. The American people will
never believe him again, and nothing he is saying to the grand jury
will change that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy agreed, but like others was squeamish about airing on
national television, during the day, a tape with the president
being asked about explicit sex acts. ``Little kids are going to
pick up words they don't understand and shouldn't understand, and
they're going to ask questions. This isn't good for the children,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As court veterans, Cherry and Van Gundy were quick to point out
what they saw as flaws in Clinton's testimony demeanor. ``He's
sweating bad, he's just flat-out lying,'' said Cherry, just as
Clinton was being asked about a tie given him by Lewinsky. ``I've
just never seen anyone dodge a question the way he does.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really edgy,'' added Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street at the Gentlemen's Book Store, there were plenty
of sexually explicit videos available. Yet neither the patrons nor
the clerk seemed to have any interest in watching or hearing the
president's testimony. The television was on, but the video being
shown had very little talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should leave the guy alone,'' said the clerk,
declining to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the sparkling Center City Mall, there were more than a
dozen impressive televisions on display at The Home Theater Inc.,
an electronics store. But the only thing showing was the movie,
``George of the Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   A salesman said he had tuned in to Clinton's testimony earlier
in the morning, but then switched to the movies. ``This (movie)
shows off the picture better on the TVs,'' he said. ``Maybe I'll
read about Clinton's testimony tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
