<HEADLINE>
STARR'S GRAND JURY TACTIC WAS TO PROVE CLINTON A LIAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-PERJURY,
CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-NY, CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA,
CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA,
CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) (af)  
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the camera never once showed even a
glimpse of Kenneth Starr or his team of inquisitors, the
prosecutors' mission remained clear throughout President Clinton's
grand jury testimony: to prove that the president of the United
States is a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the videotape only as disembodied voices, the
prosecutors pressed the president harder and harder in an effort to
pin down his answers to their relentless questions about his
intimate contacts with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
and his efforts to hide their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with hours of vivid descriptions from Ms. Lewinsky about
specific sexual encounters she said she had with the president, the
prosecutors aggressively set out to prove that the president
repeatedly lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The first lie the prosecutors set out to expose was Clinton's
denial of having sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky last January in
the Jones sexual misconduct case. And then, when the president
continued to insist that his testimony in the Jones case had been
``legally accurate,'' they appeared to be trying to build a much
graver offense, lying to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' tactics ranged from courteous interchanges with
Clinton, to going back four or five times to the same line of
inquiry, to the same sexual act, to the same quotes from the Jones
deposition. Clinton expressed his frustrations with the repetitive
nature of their queries and with the impression his answers had on
the jury: ``Look, I'm not trying to be evasive here. I'm trying to
protect my privacy, my family's privacy, and I'm trying to stick to
what the deposition was about. If the deposition wasn't about this
and didn't cover it, then I don't believe that I should be required
to go beyond my statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragging a witness before a grand jury primarily to force false
testimony is known in legal parlance as a perjury trap. Prosecutors
use this technique when proving a predicate crime is more difficult
than proving subsequent false statements made under oath.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic perjury trap, prosecutors call a suspect before a
grand jury for the primary purpose of obtaining false testimony in
order to later prosecute him for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Clinton, some of the previous acts under
investigation by Starr were alleged false statements made in the
Jones civil suit that was later dismissed, and his prosecution has
been considered unusual by some legal experts. But among the
thousands of pages of material from Starr's investigation released
Monday were legal references on perjury statutes in which the
independent counsel concluded, ``The Department of Justice often
prosecutes for perjury that occurs during the course of civil
proceedings,'' citing eight cases.
</P>
<P>
   E. Lawrence Barcella, a former federal prosecutor, said Starr's
techniques were intended to trap the president. ``This was the
classic situation where you dig a hole, cover it with leaves and
twigs and then beckon someone to walk towards you,'' Barcella said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradford Berenson, a white-collar criminal law expert, said,
``This wasn't a perjury trap. It was a slam-dunk perjury case.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the grand jury session released on videotape Monday,
Starr clearly attempted to assemble the strongest possible perjury
case, one that later served as the backbone of his 445-page report.
During a crucial confrontation with Solomon L. Wisenberg, a former
assistant U.S. attorney in San Antonio, Texas, the president
insisted that he did not have sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky as
it was defined in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The president told Wisenberg, ``You are free to infer that my
testimony is that I did not have sexual relations, as I understood
this term to be defined.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the president stressed how seriously he took the
definition of sexual relations in the Jones case, which outlined,
``contact with the genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner thigh, or
buttocks of any person with an intent to arouse or gratify the
sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to acknowledge, because of this definition, that under
this definition I had actually had sexual relations once with
Gennifer Flowers, a person who has spread all kinds of ridiculous,
dishonest, exaggerated stories about me for money,'' the president
testified. ``And I knew when I did that, it would be leaked. It
was. And I was embarrassed. But I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I tried to read this carefully,'' the president continued.
``I can tell you what I thought it covered, and I can tell you that
I do not believe I did anything that I thought was covered by
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and his lawyers knew going into his grand jury
appearance that he would be grilled about graphic descriptions
given by Ms. Lewinsky, and physical evidence, including a dress
possibly stained with the president's semen.
</P>
<P>
   With his lawyers, the president constructed a strategy that
tried to bend around Starr's evidence: The president would admit to
an ``inappropriate intimate'' relationship with Ms. Lewinsky but
insist that their affair did not fit the Jones case definition of
sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   This sophisticated but somewhat tortured legal dodge was one the
prosecutors were determined to shatter. The definition of the Jones
case clearly did include contacts with Ms. Lewinsky's breasts and
genitalia and Ms. Lewinsky testified that the president had touched
and kissed her breasts in nine incidents and that there were four
contacts with her genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   Wisenberg, who took the lead in questioning the president about
his sexual encounters with Ms. Lewinsky, pressed Clinton when he
denied having sexual contact with Ms. Lewinsky that fell within the
scope of the Jones case. ``Including touching her breast, kissing
her breast, or touching her genitalia?'' Wisenberg asked. The
president tersely responded, ``That is correct.'' During this
exchange, the president also said that he understood that the
physical contact had to be ``direct.'' Lawyers familiar with his
testimony have said that could exclude contact through clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Making a second approach, Wisenberg posed another series of
sexually explicit questions, asking the president whether Ms.
Lewinsky would be lying if she contradicted his testimony about
intimacy. During these protracted exchanges about sex, Clinton
became combative and refused to elaborate on his opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides tried to sway the grand jurors during the four hours
of testimony. The president appealed to their common sense and
decency: ``I'm not trying to evade my legal obligations or my
willingness to help the grand jury achieve their legal
obligations,'' the president testified, adding later, ``And I
believe you can achieve that without requiring me to say and do
things that I don't think are necessary and that I think, frankly,
go too far in trying to criminalize my private life.''
</P>
<P>
   As Wisenberg tried repeatedly to elicit answers to the most
incendiary sexual questions, he warned Clinton that the grand
jurors, not just prosecutors, wanted more detail: At one point, he
threatened the president, saying: ``I need to inform you, Mr.
President _ we'll go on at least for now. But I need to inform you
that the grand jury will consider your not answering the questions
more directly in their determination of whether or not they are
going to issue another subpoena.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Starr cited five instances where he alleged that
Clinton had lied under oath in his impeachment report to the
Congress. The first and second items of that referral cite Clinton
for lying in the Jones case ``regarding his sexual relationship
with Monica Lewinsky'' and lying a second time about it before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The three other perjury charges involve other evasive answers
the president gave in the Jones case, about having ever been alone
with Ms. Lewinsky, about talking with her about her testimony in
the Jones case and efforts to help her get a job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
