</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIPP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBERS EXAMINING TRIPP TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The office of the independent counsel is
investigating Linda Tripp, one of its key witnesses, for possibly
lying under oath after an FBI analysis indicated that nine tapes of
her recorded conversations with Monica S. Lewinsky had been
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp said in both a deposition and grand jury testimony that
the tapes she made of her friend were originals.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 16 tapes analyzed had been recorded on a different
tape recorder than the machine Tripp said she used, according to
the evidence gathered by Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr and
released by the House Judiciary Committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's veracity is important because she triggered the
independent counsel's investigation of the Lewinsky affair when she
contacted him on January 12 to say she had more than 20 hours of
taped conversation with Lewinsky. She also provided the information
to the lawyers for Paula Jones, the former state employee from
Arkansas who sued Clinton for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes moved Starr to enlist Tripp to record further
conversations with Lewinsky, and provided the grounding for
questions about the Lewinsky affair posed to Clinton during his
deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case. They may well
have also been used by the counsel to help win authorization from
Attorney General Janet Reno to expand his probe to include the
sexual scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But the independent counsel became suspicious about Tripp's
truthfulness after the tapes were examined by the FBI Audio Signal
Analysis Unit in Quantico, Va., according to evidence gathered by
Starr and released Monday by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Before questions about the authenticity of the tapes emerged,
Starr had already granted Tripp immunity from prosecution and
promised he would try to persuade the state of Maryland not to
prosecute her for violating the state's wiretapping law, which
prohibits such secret tape recording. Maryland prosecutors have
proceeded with their investigation of Tripp, and that probe is
ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ms. Tripp duplicated any tapes herself or knew of their
duplication, then she has lied under oath before the grand jury and
in a deposition,'' the document said. ``The (Office of Independent
Counsel) continues to investigate this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's lawyer, Anthony Zaccagnini, would not comment on the
report.
</P>
<P>
   In Starr's report to Congress last week, he charged that the
president lied under oath in responses to questions Jones's lawyers
in a Jan. 17 deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp testified before the Starr grand jury for two weeks,
longer than any other witness. Moreover, the Lewinsky tapes
initially were used by prosecutors to establish the sexual
relationship between president and the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes in question contain conversations about Tripp's
meeting with her lawyer after receiving a subpoena in the Paula
Jones sexual-harassment case; Lewinsky's discussions with UN
Ambassador Bill Richardson about a job; Lewinsky's meetings with
Clinton friend Vernon Jordan; and Lewinsky's subpoena in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   In one tape, Tripp tells Lewinsky to speak to her mother, Marcia
Lewis, about ``their plan'' to avoid the Jones subpoenas. Lewinsky
reports back that her mother found the plan ``brilliant.'' The plan
reportedly called for Lewinsky to move to New York to avoid
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary examination by the FBI found that eight of the
tapes that Tripp gave Starr's investigators appeared to be
authentic. But nine others ``exhibit characteristics that are not
consistent with being recorded on the Radio Shack CTR107 tape
recorder Ms. Tripp says she used to record the original tapes,''
the document said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine, two contain inaudible recordings. ``For the seven
tapes which contain audible conversations and which exhibit signs
of duplication, the Office of Independent Counsel cannot exclude
the possibility of tampering at this time,'' the document said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of the tapes that appeared to be duplicated
also seemed to have been stopped and reactivated during the
recording process, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp purchased a voice activated tape recorder from Radio Shack
on October 3, 1997, and attached it to a telephone in the study of
her Maryland home. She used it to record many of her telephone
conversations with Lewinsky from October 3, 1997, until January 15,
1998. After a tape was filled, she would not catalog it but store
it unmarked in a bowl on a piece of furniture, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, the independent counsel's office
went to some lengths to verify the dates the tapes were made,
cross-referencing them with independent sources and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   After making the first two tapes, Tripp met with Lucianne
Goldberg, a New York book agent, and Goldberg's son and business
associate, Jonah, and Michael Isikoff, the Newsweek magazine
investigative reporter. Goldberg made copies of the original tapes
in New York. She handed over the originals to the prosecutor last
January. Tripp was working with Goldberg on a possible book deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, a secretary in the counsel's office at the White House
during the Bush administration, remained in the White House for the
first year of the Clinton administration but eventually transferred
to the Pentagon. There she met Lewinsky, who had been transferred
from her White House job.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp also took two sets of notes on her conversations with
Lewinsky between May 23, 1997, and July 1997. Tripp told the
prosecutor that Lewinsky was aware of the first set of notes but
not the second. Lewinsky told prosecutors she never knew her friend
was taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   The information released Monday only includes a summary of the
Tripp-Lewinsky conversations. The actual tapes and transcripts are
contained in another box of evidence that has not yet been released
by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
