<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COIN-ROBBER-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKING METER COLLECTIONS OFFICIAL CHARGED WITH POCKETING
QUARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The official in charge of collecting quarters from
the city's 65,000 parking meters stands accused of pocketing
thousands of the coins himself.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Ginter, the acting chief of meter collections for the
city's Department of Transportation, was stuffing handfulls of
pilfered quarters into a coin redemption machine, authorities said,
when he was arrested on Saturday at a Waldbaum's supermarket in
Forest Hills, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   He had put 1,086 quarters into the Coinstar machine _ worth
$271.50 before the system took a 7.5 percent surcharge to convert
the coins into paper money _ when he was arrested, according to the
Queens district attorney's office. When searched, Ginter had
another 295 quarters in his pockets.
</P>
<P>
   All told, said Commissioner Edward Kuriansky of the city
Department of Investigation, Ginter was accused of making off with
as many as 14,400 quarters _ $3,600 _ from parking meter proceeds
by siphoning off from 800 to 1,200 quarters at a time on 12
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Ginter's haul put only a small dent in the roughly $70 million
in coin revenue the city takes in from parking meters.
</P>
<P>
   And as New York City parking corruption cases go, it was a
low-budget version of the Parking Violations Bureau scandal of the
1980s, a bribery and kickback scheme that brought down some of the
city's most powerful Democratic politicians and raised the profile
of a Republican prosecutor named Rudolph Giuiliani.
</P>
<P>
   Ginter, 40, had served as acting collections chief, at a salary
of $45,810, for the last two years. He supervised a staff of 166 at
the Transportation Department's meter collection facility in
Queens. He has been suspended without pay and, if convicted, could
face a prison sentence of up to four years on charges of grand
larceny and official misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   A call to Ginter's home was unanswered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The city's parking meters are emptied by removing the metal
cylinders containing coins, which are released into a locked
strongbox. The strongboxes are then brought to the central
collection facility.
</P>
<P>
   At the Queens headquarters, the quarters are put into counting
machines that tally them for deposit into municipal coffers. The
machines, however, reject some quarters because they are bent,
chipped or otherwise damaged. Those quarters are put into a
`'reject pile'' and are eventually redeemed by the U.S. Mint.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that pile, investigators said, that Ginter found his
booty.
</P>
<P>
   He converted the coins to paper money, Kuriansky said, by using
Coinstar machines at supermarkets near his office and his Queens
home.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began with an anonymous tip that someone was
making off with coins from the collection center. It soon focused
on Ginter. The supermarkets cooperated with the investigation,
officials said, furnishing surveillance tapes showing Ginter
diligently feeding the Coinstar machines.
</P>
<P>
   In a search of Ginter's office, officials said, they found a
stash of 2,827 quarters.
</P>
<P>
   `'I guess you could characterize him as a two-bit thief,'' said
the Queens district attorney, Richard Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those parking their cars may not have been on the level
either. In Ginter's own car, investigators found 758 Garden State
Parkway tokens, 124 Delaware Bridge tokens, and 9 Roosevelt Island
tram tokens, apparently deposited in meters and rejected by the
city's counting machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
