<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DAMAGE-BOS &LR;      09-21 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SMOKING GUN   SEEN, WHITE HOUSE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not the smoking gun.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony, which aired
Monday on national television, was neither the bombshell that White
House aides had feared, nor the revelation that would end debate
over whether he should remain in office, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe any objective observer would conclude that
they saw anything approaching the kind of high crimes and
misdemeanors that the Constitution requires for removing a
president from office,'' said James Kennedy, a White House lawyer
and spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Michael D. McCurry said ``that the
president's conduct does not rise to the level of an impeachable
offense should now be clear to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, he condemned the ``unprecedented violation of
grand jury secrecy'' and ``rank partisanship'' by Republicans on
the House Judiciary Committee who voted last week to release the
videotaped testimony along with nearly 3,200 pages of documents.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry and other White House aides acknowledged that it may
take several days to measure the impact of the president's
testimony on public opinion, and that those views are likely to be
shaped by the media, since most Americans are unlikely to have seen
the more than four-hour videotape in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, White House aides rushed to put the best face on
Clinton's testimony while assigning the worst motives to
Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr and Republican House Judiciary
members.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that ``the facts sometimes don't match the
breathless anticipation.'' Another senior aide said flatly that
Republicans had ``dramatically oversold'' how damaging the
videotape would be to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Several aides, who were expecting to see Clinton lose his
temper, were surprised that he projected as much calm as he did,
although he was clearly irritated and angry. ``It looked
presentable image-wise, and the president came across quite
naturally, given the circumstances,'' a senior aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the videotape was being carried live on television, Clinton
was in New York speaking on the threat of international terrorism
to the United Nations General Assembly, where he was greeted by
warm applause and a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his lawyers were making plans to sift through the
newly released documents from Starr, while his aides geared up for
more outreach to House and Senate Democrats, whose support the
president will need to head off possible impeachment preceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster, said he doubted that the
president's testimony would change public perceptions on either
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be more confirming for people on both sides
of the question _ rather than transforming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is seen as a battle between the president on one side and
the Republicans and Starr on the other,'' he continued. ``I don't
think there are any big winners today, each side may have lost a
little bit of ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican House Judiciary members Charles T. Canady of Forida
and James E. Rogan of California, said they were disturbed by
Clinton's legal hair-splitting in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people go before the grand jury, they have a
responsibility to answer the questions that are put to them, or
plead the Fifth Amendment,'' Canady said. ``The president had that
choice, like any other person, but he chose another way, and that
was simply not to answer the questions, and engage in an extended
process there of presenting what he wanted to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said that ``watching 4 1/2 hours of the president continue
to parse, in minute detail, areas of the law, which to the average
person just sound absolutely ludicrous and silly, is not a proud
day for our legal system. It certainly isn't a proud day for our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   On the latter point, McCurry agreed. He called the release of
the president's testimony and its airing on television ``arguably
an unnecessary day in the life of our country, an awful day.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``How people react ... will be judgments that are going
to be made in living rooms and at dining tables around the country
tonight. There's no way that we can predict what people will
think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV22-COX     09-21 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton video delivered a mortal president to a watching nation
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (w) Washington and (e) Entertainment
categories.)By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was not TV as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was fuzzy and an annoying hiss made it hard to hear
President Clinton's taped testimony before the federal grand jury
investigating his relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But what Monday's seminal TV event lacked in glitzy production
values, it more than made up for in high-stakes drama and low-ball
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, pundits had described the tape of Clinton's Aug. 17
testimony as ``historic'' and ``unprecedented'' and in many
respects they were right: no other sitting president has been
questioned so publicly about a sexual indiscretion on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's hard to remember when history looked this small.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grave implications for the fate of his presidency,
the same unifying medium that brought Americans the aftermath of
the Kennedy assasination, a moon-walking Neil Armstrong and the
final episode of ``Seinfeld'' struggled to put Clinton's more than
four hours of testimony in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   As the tape began airing at 9:25 a.m., Clinton, wearing a dark
suit and a gold-toned tie, seemed almost lonely sitting in a
non-descript room in the White House, an arrangement of orange and
blue flowers in the distance over his right shoulder. His lawyer
David Kendall was off-camera.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Clinton's inquisitors were miles away at a federal
courthouse and could be heard only on the videotape as faint,
disembodied voices who deferentially referred to the president as
``sir'' even when asking the most intimate, and embarrassing
questions.
</P>
<P>
   It had all started just two minutes earlier. The simple act of
slipping a tape into a VCR seemed to take on new meaning as it was
handed to a technician ``laboring in the bowels of Congress'' as
CNN's Candy Crowley described it.
</P>
<P>
   Several moments later as the tape cued up, a picture of Bill
Clinton jerked into focus. John King, a White House correspondent
for CNN claimed that Americans ``have never seen anything like
this, the president raising his hand and taking an oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly true since Clinton has taken an oath of office twice
during his inauguration ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   However the tape did show Clinton to be more mortal than ever.
Before the questioning began, the president could be seen cleaning
his ear with his finger. Later, he gulped down a can of ginger ale
and a diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're usually watching `Teletubbies' ( a PBS children's
show) right now you shouldn't be watching this,'' warned Dan
Rather, the anchor-philosopher of CBS before the president began
answering questions from prosecutors. ``If you are, go ask mommy
for permission.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, CNN and Fox News followed their game plan to run the tape
in its entirety without editing details of the sexual aspects of
Clinton's testimony. They continuously aired parental warnings
about content.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC, CBS and ABC which had considered running only edited
excerpts, shifted gears and decided to run the tape ``wall to
wall'' pre-empting their daytime programming of soaps and talk
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to say with the testimony because it was so
compelling and interesting,'' said Alex Constantinople, a
spokeswoman for NBC News. The network cut away from the videotape
on two occassions for a total of six minutes because ``we were
concerned that children might be watching and that some of the
graphic material that was being discussed might offend our
viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC also aired the testimony in full, but employed a 5-second
delay which would have enabled the network to edit offensive or
graphic material, said spokeswoman Eileen Murphy. It wasn't
necessary, but anchor Peter Jennings repeatedly warned viewers
about the tapes contents, she said. CBS played it even safer, and
used a 30-second taped delay.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's coverage which started at 7 a.m. _ more than two hours
before the tapes were released _ seemed to be taking a toll on
anchors trying to keep track of the network's cadre of field
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie and I have been at this awhile and we're both losing
it,'' said CNN anchor Judy Woodruff when co-host Bernard Shaw
flubbed a seque long after the tape had concluded.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Congressional reporter Joe Johns also had a difficult time
early in the morning, even though he appeared to be the first of
the journalistic pack to get his hands on the tape's supporting
documents. As he began reading excerpts, Johns suddenly disappeared
from the screen, and anchor Tom Brokaw explained later that the
network had suffered ``an electronic meltdown.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone on TV was having a Monica meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   In a cheesy bit of counter-programming on WAGA, talk show host
Sally Jesse Raphael aired a special segment that seemed to fit the
theme of the day: ``Office Affairs Exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris is a TV critic for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0434 </DOCNO>
