<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-WASHI     09-21 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-WASHINGTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE'S $5.7B TOBACCO SUIT ABOUT TO BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jury selection begins Tuesday in a $5.7 billion
lawsuit against the tobacco industry as Washington becomes the
fifth state to try to recover medical costs to treat the poor for
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   None of the previous cases in Texas, Florida, Mississippi and
Minnesota made it to a jury. All were settled for billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But the legal landscape has shifted in the tobacco companies'
favor since they settled with Minnesota in May.
</P>
<P>
   A national tobacco agreement collapsed in Congress and cigarette
makers have won a string of victories in smaller cases around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Washington, tobacco lawyers won the right for the first
time to use a new legal weapon to defend themselves: putting the
state on trial by portraying it as a partner in cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   They will argue that the state's licensing of cigarettes and
collection of millions of dollars in tobacco taxes undercuts its
case.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement has allowed Washington to collect far more in
tax revenues than it has spent on health costs, according to
tobacco lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will put on evidence the state has profited . . . from the
sale of tobacco products, even if one assumes the states incurred
the health-care expenses it incurred,'' said James Milliman, an
attorney for one of the defendants, Brown &AMP; Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 alone, the state collected $270 million more in tobacco
taxes than it paid out in Medicaid costs, Milliman said. Washington
collects 82.5 cents in excise taxes _ one of the highest rates in
the nation _ on each pack of cigarettes, which sells for about
$3.20 plus sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But that argument may never come before a jury. Even as
Washington state prepares to go to trial, its attorneys and those
from 37 other states continue to seek a negotiated settlement with
some cigarette producers in talks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever comes of those talks, state lawyers dismiss the tobacco
industry's latest legal salvo.
</P>
<P>
   No one, they note, should be rewarded for illegal conduct
because they are a taxpayer. To do so would be like rewarding a
motorist who refuses to pay a speeding ticket because he also pays
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they will focus on testimony from former tobacco
company insiders and on stacks of internal industry documents that
they claim show that cigarette makers conspired for decades to hide
health hazards of their products from smokers.
</P>
<P>
   They also will attempt to prove that the companies targeted
children with sophisticated marketing campaigns and sought to hook
consumers by manipulating the nicotine levels in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The state, which filed suit two years ago, is seeking
reimbursement for $3 billion in Medicaid and insurances costs
related to tobacco illnesses. Jurors also could award $2.7 million
in punitive damages and possibly more.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also asks that the tobacco industry be directed to
issue broader warnings about the health risks of their products,
take steps to prevent minors from obtaining cigarettes and halt
deceptive and unfair advertising practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our case is based on marketing to kids, the intentional
withholding of adverse affects, that they lied and a conspiracy not
to market safe products,'' said the state's lead attorney, John
Hough, a veteran assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In response, tobacco lawyers will deny the allegations, arguing
that state officials have known for years about the risks
associated with smoking, particularly since the surgeon general's
1964 warning on the dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Hough said the state won't spend a lot of time trying to prove
that tobacco is harmful because most people already know that.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman said the companies won't deny the risks of smoking, but
will adhere to their longstanding claim that no link has been
scientifically proven.
</P>
<P>
   But before 12 jurors begin to hear testimony, the scope and
shape of the case could be altered, depending on the outcome of the
settlement talks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The talks include Philip Morris, the nation's largest cigarette
maker with brands such as Marlboro and Virginia Slims, whose
actions often set the agenda for the industry. Also participating
is Lorillard Tobacco Co., the fourth-largest cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major manufacturers, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. and
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., have declined to join in the
negotiations and vowed to defend themselves against the suits.
</P>
<P>
   But both have left open their options, raising the possibility
they could be part of a settlement. The two companies joined with
other tobacco makers in the $6.6 billion deal struck with
Minnesota, just before that state's case was to go to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the long-awaited trial in the Washington
case began gearing up Sept. 14 with pretrial maneuvering in King
County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th-floor courtroom _ the largest in the King County
Courthouse _ is normally used for pretrial matters but was set
aside for the tobacco case to accommodate about a dozen attorneys
on each side and the throngs of spectators expected for the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   It has been wired with video equipment, a big screen and
computers for multimedia presentations. Two large speakers have
been placed in front of the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Each side also has been assigned a ``war room'' in the
courthouse to house files and provide extra room for additional
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Yet until now, with the questioning of prospective jurors about
to begin, there has been little sparring in the courtroom, except
for some last-minute legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lull isn't unusual before a major trial gains speed,
the lack of activity has contributed to widespread speculation that
some sort of multistate deal will be struck soon.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, lawyers for the tobacco companies asked for a
one-month delay of the trial, arguing that a settlement involving
some of the defendants could prejudice those who remain in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys objected and King County Superior Court Judge
George Finkle, who is presiding over the case, denied the motion
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, cigarette makers agreed to pay $38.5 billion to
settle with Minnesota, Texas, Florida and Mississippi. Except in
the Minnesota case, deals were struck before trials.
</P>
<P>
   As of 1996, the tobacco industry's gross sales were listed as
$45 billion annually, and the payouts cover a 25-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Since those deals, the tobacco industry has scored several court
victories.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a Florida appeals court overturned a $1 million verdict
against Brown &AMP; Williamson brought by the family of a smoker who
died from lung cancer. Judges in several states have dismissed
labor union cases seeking reimbursement for health costs associated
with tobacco illnesses. And a federal judge in North Carolina ruled
that a 1993 Environmental Protection Agency study overstated the
proven link between secondhand smoke and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's decision to portray Washington state as a partner
in cigarettes sales also reflects its new confidence. Finkle ruled
that the companies may use the tax issue as a defense, something
they weren't allowed to do in the earlier cases. But Finkle
reserved a ruling on whether the argument can be applied to
damages.
</P>
<P>
   A victory in the Washington case would give cigarettes makers
leverage in the other state suits.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies also risk the first adverse verdict in a state
tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of law, a verdict in Washington's favor could be
applied to all or some of the pending cases on liability, leaving
only damages to be decided in each suit.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman, the Brown &AMP; Williamson attorney, calls that
possibility remote because of what he describes as the ``unique''
consumer fraud and antitrust claims incorporated in Washington's
case.
</P>
<P>
   But the pending suits generally mirror those filed in Washington
and the other four states that reached settlement. Each has
contended under various legal theories that they were defrauded of
Medicaid and insurance costs for tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Washington's case will follow what occurred in the
Minnesota trial, where state attorneys produced reams of internal
industry documents to buttress allegations that cigarette makers
deceived the public.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there will be some new twists. For the first time in a
tobacco case, the state plans to call a former lawyer for the
Liggett Group, a cigarette maker that broke with the industry. In a
settlement with 21 states, including Washington, the company agreed
to waive attorney-client privilege, provide documents to settle
state tobacco lawsuits and pay about $25 million, plus 2.5 percent
of its pretax profits over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Meyer, who advised Liggett in the 1970s and 1980s, is
prepared to testify that the company was pressured by other major
cigarette makers to drop development of a safer cigarette, which it
did.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials feared ``Liggett's sale and marketing of a
safer cigarette could result in infinite liability in civil
litigation as it would constitute a direct or implied admission
that all other cigarettes were unsafe,'' according to a proffer
submitted by Meyer's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Milliman downplayed the significance of Meyer's assertions,
saying test marketing of a safer cigarette that heated rather than
burned tobacco was a huge flop.
</P>
<P>
   But Hough, the state attorney, said the industry has never
mounted a strong marketing campaign for a safer cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last three to five months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
