<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEPAK'S LOVING FEELING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celebrity doctor/philosopher/spiritual adviser  &UR; Deepak Chopra &LR; 
is calling himself only  &UR; Deepak  &LR; on ``The Gift of Love,'' an album
to be released in November by Rasa Records.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in New York magazine, the album is billed
as a ``musical tribute to the act of love,'' and features
contributions from  &UR; Madonna &LR; ,  &UR; Demi Moore &LR; ,  &UR; Debra Winger &LR; ,
 &UR; Blythe &LR; 
 &UR; Danner &LR; ,  &UR; Goldie Hawn &LR;  and  &UR; Martin Sheen &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   They will be reading the poetry of the 13th century Persian
mystic  &UR; Rumi &LR;  while a beat plays in the background to create the
``experience of ecstasy.'' Deepak says this will fill the ``missing
love'' voice in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONICA'S LOVING FEELING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A barmaid said she was there, and Australian TV and newspapers
ran a grainy shot of a dark-haired woman in the tropical resort of
Port Douglas, Australia, on Friday, setting off a media hunt for
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , who was said to be visiting somebody or other
who may or may not have been there. She wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington Post reports that five publishers have
been approached about a book by the former White House intern, and
their reactions have ranged from nope to maybe. ``I'm as big a
whore as anyone,'' one publisher said, ``but I'd rather die
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the Starr report, with so many smutty details, is
said to have taken the edge off interest in a tell-all book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE WALKED RIGHT IN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the New York premiere of the new  &UR; Ben Stiller &LR;  movie,
``Permanent Midnight,'' the star's father, actor  &UR; Jerry Stiller &LR; ,
described to  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  his first date with  &UR; Anne Meara &LR; , who
became his comedy partner and wife:
</P>
<P>
   ``I took Anne out to dinner, and I was very surprised to see her
start putting the restaurant's spoons and knives into her handbag.
I guess they matched the forks she had at home. The restaurant was
Longley's cafeteria. ... Anne had already impressed me by offering
to go Dutch treat, but when I saw her sticking that silverware in
her purse I was really excited, and I guess a little scared....
</P>
<P>
   ``When she invited me over to her place for a spaghetti dinner,
which was our next date, I was pleased to see the little `L' on the
spoons and knives, but I still made no comment. ... I think I fell
in love with Anne when I saw her swipe those spoons. It made me
feel so on the edge. I respected her for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE SIGNED RIGHT ON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nancy Capulet &LR; 's new book, ``Putting Your Heart Online''
(Variable Symbols; $18.95), describes how Tom, a computer
programmer, met Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom downloaded the profiles of all women in Northern
California using Lynx. Then he ran a program that he wrote in a
computer language called AWK, which prints out a summary of the
profiles. ... He could easily scan the summary and see which women
meet his criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``For each profile, there are 16 fields: match, handle, age,
low-age-want, high-age-want, height, height-want, gates, score,
keywords. The first field is either ``y'' for yes, ``no'' for no,
or ``m'' for maybe. ... The final number on a line is the score,
which is a weighted sum of the values of the gates. ... Tom is now
happily involved in a relationship with Mary, one of the women he
met online.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ David Greenlee &LR;  was entranced by the bumperfellows ``Honda of
Tempe _ We Deal,'' alongside ``Rage Against the Machine!''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nancy Kerrigan &LR;  has accepted an ``undisclosed sum of more
than $10,000'' from Marvista Computing Co., which runs a Web  &LR; site &LR; 
that showed fake porn pictures of Kerrigan by using photos of her
face grafted onto someone else's body. Kerrigan had sued for
emotional distress, invasion of privacy, defamation and unfair
trade practices; Marvista officials had said the pictures were
obvious fakes, intended only for entertainment purposes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I married my real male masculine strong equal, which permits
me the space to really be the girl. Because I'm so strong, and
because I really like sensitive insane people ... I find that
sometimes I don't have a lot of room to be the gal, and I'm really
liking the girly part of my marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharon Stone on ``Entertainment Tonight Online,'' as cited in
Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
