<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV-REVIEW-NYT     09-21 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STARS IN MADE-FOR-TELEVISION TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language in second-to-last graf.) 
(See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-PERJURY,
CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-NY, CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA,
CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE,
CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(nk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was political theater of the purest sort, adapted for the age
of video. And there was little doubt, watching Bill Clinton's grand
jury testimony, that he knew he was making a movie. Refusing to
provide sexually explicit details, he said, ``I am right to answer
all the questions about perjury, but not to say things which will
be forever in the historical annals of the United States because of
this unprecedented videotape, and may be leaked at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   This videotape broke many of the rules of film and television,
and it was all the more fascinating for those lapses. Most notable
was the way it violated a Hollywood truism: Films are made, broken
and often saved in the editing room. The unedited nature and the
static, mid-distance camera focused on the president, were what
made the testimony so exceptional as television. To watch it in a
four-hour-plus gulp, as it was presented by the all-news cable
channels, brought the tremendous relief of having the spinners on
both sides finally be quiet. Here, at last, was a chance to see
Clinton and the prosecutors go mano-a-mano.
</P>
<P>
   It was decidedly Clinton's show. Alone on camera, he had the
advantage over his several questioners, with their disembodied
voices. In a situation he didn't control, his was a high-wire act
of improvisation, however well-coached he might have been.
</P>
<P>
   And after a tight-lipped start, he seemed to warm up and give a
vehement, even gripping, performance. Addressing two conflicting
audiences, the prosecutors and the public, at times he assumed the
role of lawyer in his own defense and just as frequently appeared
to be the speech-making politician. Above all, he was the Bill
Clinton who knows how to play to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   However cinematic the situation, though, it was also unique. No
movie analogy quite fits, though several near-matches came
fleetingly to mind. The tape had an unlikely resemblance to ``My
Dinner with Andre,'' with its small scale, back-and-forth
conversation, and observations that seemed positively ruminative.
``You're dealing with, in some ways, the most mysterious area of
human life,'' Clinton said about the ``he said, she said'' aspect
of sexual behavior. (The testimony's details were so intimate that
the tape came with on-screen warnings about graphic content.) ``My
Dinner With Andre,'' of course, is far too benign a model to suit
the combative nature of the prosecutors' questions and Clinton's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The tape had qualities of cinema verite, turning viewers into
eavesdroppers in that inherently false situation, as the subjects
usually pretended not to notice the cameras. But most documentaries
don't unfold in real time the way this did.
</P>
<P>
   What the Clinton tape decidedly did not resemble was a courtroom
drama old or new (neither ``Witness for the Prosecution'' nor ``Law
and Order''). The setting, in the Map Room of the White House,
guaranteed that the president looked like a president, not a
witness on the stand. The bowl of flowers visible over his left
shoulder onscreen would reappear later that night, when the
president gave an address from the same room. That visual echo made
the grand jury tape seem like a prequel, explaining why Clinton
sounded so angry at Kenneth Starr in that speech.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tape was abundantly excerpted, only in the full
four-hour version was it possible to see a dramatic structure
taking shape. Clinton appeared tight-lipped, almost ashen at the
start, putting on his glasses to read a statement that made it
clear he would not provide sexual details. His eyes were turned
down as he and the prosecutors wrangled about the definition of
sex, but he remembered to look directly into the camera when
saying, ``I regret'' the involvement with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining energy, he spoke with more conviction than any of his
surrogates had when doing the linguistic acrobatics that are his
legal defense against perjury, explaining why ``sexual relations''
does not mean oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was taking every opportunity to get his political
message beyond the grand jury to the big wide world he assumed
would one day watch. The Paula Jones sexual harassment case was
``funded by my political opponents,'' and has since been tossed out
of court, he noted more than once.
</P>
<P>
   By the third hour his performance had peaked and a viewer's eyes
tended to glaze over (a common third-act letdown). Clinton's
refrain was ``I don't remember,'' his answers were more evasive and
the questions more repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day and on the evening new programs, excerpts of
the testimony were played, and it became easy to predict what they
would be. There was the president's opening statement; there was
his most vehement moment, when he glared and gestured with his
hands and said of the Jones lawyers, ``I deplored what they were
doing''; there were pieces of the wrangling about what he told his
secretary, Betty Currie; there was the president calling Ms.
Lewinsky ``a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   But through it all, the winding routes offered revealing details
and unrehearsed moments all too likely to be left on the cutting
room floor in the news reports. You can see the president trying to
stay calm when asked persistently about whether Ms. Lewinsky ``said
she loved you'' in a note.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raises an eyebrow and offers the hint of a smile when
saying, ``Ms. Lewinsky has a way of getting information out of
people when she's either charming or determined.'' That eyebrow
alone could be subjected to hours of debate. It looked as if the
memory of her attractions was passing through his mind, but maybe
he was just calling her a flirt.
</P>
<P>
   And he actually recoiled at the most explicit question, about
whether he had used ``a sexual object.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't remember giving Ms. Lewinsky ``cherry
chocolates'' as a gift, but did recall giving her a Rockettes
blanket that he'd had for a couple of years. In such pathetically
revealing details was a real-life movie told by one of the two
people who knows it whole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
