u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-UNREST-NYT &LR;      09-21 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIAN POLICE BREAK UP PROTESTS ON ARREST  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Acting to quell the biggest show of
dissent faced by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad in his 17 years in
office, riot police officers fired tear gas and water cannon on
Monday to disperse thousands of people protesting the arrest of his
former deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Federal police said the former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim, 51, who
was arrested late Sunday, was being held under the Internal
Security Act, which allows the indefinite imprisonment without
charges or trial of people deemed to be a threat to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The street protests on Monday suggested the extent of Anwar's
popularity as a more liberal foil to Mahathir, 72, who has imposed
an autocratic style of rule.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several days _ and up to an hour before his arrest
_ Anwar had gathered huge crowds to hear him denounce the man he
previously called his father and his teacher.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats and other analysts said they doubted that the
opposition posed a threat to the prime minister. He controls the
levers of government and continues to enjoy wide respect as the
creator of a modern Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Once he moved against Anwar, dismissing him on Sept. 2, almost
all public figures supported the action, even those who had been
longtime colleagues and allies of the deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were angry crowds in the streets on Monday, the
protests appeared to be diffuse and leaderless.
</P>
<P>
   The most eloquent complaint against Anwar's arrest came from his
wife, Azizah Ismail, who said: ``If Dr. Mahathir thinks that by
ordering the police to act like gangsters he will frighten the
people from supporting this reform movement, he is dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I feel very sad because Dr. Mahathir is a great
leader, but now he has become a political desperado who is willing
to suppress his own people just to keep power.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that at least 50 protesters were arrested and
that a number of others were injured as the police dispersed the
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Even as tear gas drifted through the streets on Monday, Mahathir
maintained an air of smiling serenity as he played host to Queen
Elizabeth II of Britain, who arrived for a visit Sunday, and
presided over the closing ceremony of the Commonwealth Games.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, demonstrators ran after the queen's motorcade as
it passed them on the streets and she waved from the window.
</P>
<P>
   But the tens of thousands of people watching the closing
ceremony at the stadium dwarfed the numbers of protesters. In the
stands, they held up a huge sign reading: ``Thanks for the great
moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's lawyers have said that they expect him to be charged
with sexual misconduct after two of his male friends said, while in
custody, that he had sodomized them.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have also hinted that he might be charged with
sedition and disturbing public order after a series of large
rallies at which he called for Mahathir's removal.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations on both sides have been particularly harsh. It
had been an edgy but successful alliance of different generations
and political philosophies. Now, as in a bitter divorce, both men
have now found the most hurtful things to say about each other.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of a continuing sweep against Anwar's supporters, a
seventh ally, Ahmad Zahid Hamidi, head of the youth wing of the
ruling party, was arrested Monday. He was also charged under the
Internal Security Act.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests and charges appeared to be a particularly vigorous
form of politics by a leader who brooks no challenges. Foreign
diplomats said Anwar's real offense, in the eyes of the prime
minister, was forgetting his place as an obedient No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   As Malaysia's economy has collapsed over the last year, Anwar
has increasingly taken center stage in what seemed a sober contrast
to a leader viewed by some as eccentric and economically misguided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
