   MALAYSIA-ARREST (Kuala Lumpur) -- Protests erupt after the
arrest of former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim by Prime
Minister Mahathir. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CLINTON SCANDAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EVIDENCE (Washington) -- President Clinton is shown
attempting to fend off embarrassing and painful questions during
grand jury testimony over his relationship with White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. By Brian McGrory. (1700 words.) (w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DOCUMENTS (Washington) -- The more than 2,800 pages of
evidence provide a much fuller picture of Monica Lewinsky, her
fascination with the president and her path to the witness box
against him. By Bob Hohler. 1400 words. (w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAMAGE (Washington) _ There was palpable relief at the
White House that President Clinton's videotaped grand jury
testimony was hardly the bombshell aides had feared. By Ann Scales.
(w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIPP (Washington) _ Documents reveal the independent
counsel is investigating Linda Tripp for possibly lying under oath
and tampering with the secret tapes she made of Monica Lewinsky. By
Chris Black. 1200 words. (w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEGAL (Washington) _ After watching President Clinton's
testimony, some specialists now say he could mount a plausible
defense to charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. By Peter
Canellos. 1100 words. (w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUSINESS (New York) _ President Clinton sticks to the
world's business, addressing the United Nations and NYU Law School
about global economic crisis and terrorism. By Peter G. Gosselin.
(a)
</P>
