<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-JOYNER-HEALTH-COX     09-21 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart disease strikes fit, too
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Athletes _ no matter how young, fit, fast or strong _
have a weak spot just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Florence Griffith Joyner, 38, from an apparent
heart attack again offers proof, Atlanta-area cardiologists said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being athletic absolutely does not prevent young people from
having heart disease. It can certainly occur in people in excellent
physical shape,'' said Dr. Randy Martin of the Emory Clinic and a
health reporter for WBS-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Because details had not been released, doctors were reluctant to
speculate on exactly what may have triggered her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sudden death from cardiac causes in younger people is not
unheard of,'' said Dr. Neal Scott, Emory Clinic cardiologist and
associate professor at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   In general, cardiac deaths in people younger than 40 are caused
by a congenital condition, such as an irregular heart rhythm,
sudden infection or hardening of the arteries. Griffith Joyner
joins the names of Hank Gathers, Reggie Lewis, Flo Hyman and Sergei
Grinkov, all top athletes felled by sudden cardiac events at the
top of their game _ and in some cases, while playing their game.
</P>
<P>
   Gathers (1990) and Lewis (1993) were basketball players believed
to have died from myocarditis, an inflammation of the heart
muscle.Hyman, a top U.S. Olympic volleyball team member, collapsed
during a game in 1986 when the main vessel carrying blood from her
heart to her body ruptured. She suffered from a condition called
Marfan's Syndrome. Grinkov, the Russian ice skating pairs partner
of his wife, died in 1995 from a severe blockage of his coronary
arteries. He had probably actually suffered a heart attack in the
previous 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Although the public may find it difficult to accept that even
the most finely tuned bodies are susceptible to heart attacks and
cardiovascular disease, doctors know athletes can be easily felled
by conditions of complicated names such as hypertrophic
cardiomyopathy, the inherited condition causing irregular heart
rhythm. They also know that all of the exercise on earth does not
make one immune from clogged arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worry a lot about athletes if they develop chest pain,''
said Martin. ``Just as with anyone else, it can be a sign of
something very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
