<HEADER>
A6980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-JOYNER-REACT-COX     09-21 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Track world crushed by news of death
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The news struck Sandra Farmer-Patrick like the death
of a relative. She couldn't believe her former mentor and friend,
Florence Griffith Joyner, was dead. Not at 38. Certainly not of a
bad heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she's in a coma,'' Farmer-Patrick had told her husband,
David. ``Finally, when I saw it on CNN, it hit me. I just lost it.
I started screaming. My body was, like, paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like sisters. We had trained together, gone to (UCLA)
together, roomed together. I competed for her track team, FloJo
International, for a couple years. Here is this wonderful, young,
healthy person. How could this happen?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the question in the minds of the track and field world
as it coped Monday with the sudden death of the unparalleled female
sprinter, the woman who stole the Seoul Olympic spotlight with a
rare combination of fashion and record-smashing speed.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow athletes and officials remembered her long, colorful
fingernails, her stylish hair, her stunning bodysuits _ especially
the purple one with a turquoise bikini brief over it and only her
right leg covered. She had referred to the outfit as a
``one-legger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She got me to wear the one-legger, and then she helped me
design a little skirt thing that I wore,'' Farmer-Patrick recalled.
``She stepped out and said, `Let's try and have some prominence.'''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio McKay of Atlanta, a teammate on the 1984 and '88 Olympic
teams, said she sold the sport unlike few other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing you think about is beauty,'' McKay said. ``She
was such a beautiful person. She was real nice, but yet quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In track and field, it's so tough to have a female role model.
Evelyn Ashford was great with that, but then FloJo came along and
was real flashy, but real quiet. She was so powerful and so fast,
but when she spoke, it wasn't `I'm this and I'm that.' She let her
running do most of the speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kingdom, the 110-meter hurdles gold medalist in Seoul,
remembered being awed by a Griffith Joyner performance three months
before the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joked around about who was going to break the world record
first,'' Kingdom said. ``So I bet her 20 bucks. It was a friendly
bet, really, but every time I'd see her, she'd point her finger at
me and ask about the 20 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner attempted a comeback in 1992 as a distance
runner but failed to make an impact. Four years later, she signed
up for the Olympic trials but did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   Other reaction from friends, rivals and peers:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What Florence brought to track was a flash and a flair that
we didn't have, which was probably good for the sport and got
attention for us,'' said Ashford, an Olympic sprint gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``People are still trying to catch the records she set more
than 10 years ago. It's an amazing legacy. Many have tried and all
have failed in terms of her records,'' said Carl Lewis, a nine-time
Olympic gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``She had speed even back then. She was very focused. I used
to race against her and she smoked me,'' said Will Burnett,
football coach at Jordan High in south Los Angeles, where he and
Griffith Joyner were classmates.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``She was a role model for girls and young women in sports,''
said Bill Hybl, U.S. Olympic Committee president.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``She was very, very determined. There was no impossibility to
anything. She really tried to live that,'' said Jeanette Bolden,
1984 Olympic relay gold medalist and UCLA women's head track and
field coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The beauty of her was that she never changed. She was the
same FloJo before (she became a star) and she was the same FloJo
after,'' said track coach John Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Derrick Adkins, the 400-meter hurdles champion at the
1996 Olympics, best summed up the sport's reaction: ``It's just a
very sad tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
