A6981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-JOYNER-STEROIDS-C     09-21 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-STEROIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steroid rumors will haunt sprinter
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even in death, Florence Griffith Joyner could not
escape the steroid question.
</P>
<P>
   Her incredible showing at the 1988 U.S. Olympic Trials and Seoul
Games, coupled with her abrupt retirement before the advent of
mandatory random drug testing the following year, long fueled
suspicions in the track and field community about her indelible
marks.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, some performers, officials, media members and the
public have questioned whether she used performance-enhancing
drugs. ``It's offensive to look on the Internet and see stuff like
that today,`` Sandra Farmer Patrick, a close friend of the sprinter
and an Olympic hurdler, said Monday. ``This is a sad time.``
</P>
<P>
   FloJo passed drug tests at the trials and the Olympics in Seoul.
But seven years later, when she was elected to the National Track
and Field Hall of Fame, she finished only fifth on the ballot and
secured the minimium number of votes for election _ shockingly low
for the greatest female sprinter who still owns the 100- and
200-meter world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't concern myself with that,`` Griffith Joyner
said at the induction ceremony in Atlanta. ``I'm blessed to have
been chosen.``
</P>
<P>
   What pained her more, she said, were comments from some sprint
rivals linking her retirement after the Seoul Games to the
introduction of out-of-competition testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that I disappeared (for that reason) is such a
ridiculous thing,`` she said.
</P>
<P>
   But news of her death again raised the issue.
</P>
<P>
   When he was informed the cause of her death, Antonio McKay,
FloJo's 1984 and 1988 Olympic teammate, said he became concerned
people would link it to the effects of steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it was a car accident,'' McKay said. ``Being in
sports as long as I've been in there, knowing that people cheat,
you hope (any steroid use) had nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it had been any other (cause of) death besides that.
The first thing I hear on ESPN is about steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Ashford, the runner-up in Seoul and the sprint queen
before Griffith Joyner, spoke thoughtfully Monday of closure to the
lingering drug suspicions out of respect for Griffith Joyner but
indicated she is uncertain about their validity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's true, maybe it will come out now,`` she said. ``If it
isn't, then maybe that will come out, too. Maybe the secret has
been buried with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest thing is after all she has done ... it will always
be a question. The asterisk will always be there. That is the
saddest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta sprinter Gwen Torrence could not be reached for comment.
The Olympian has railed against drug use among her peers and has
expressed suspicion about Griffith Joyner's records but never
directly accused her.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Journal-Constitution staff writer Karen Rosen contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
