<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-OBITUARY-JOYNER-B     09-21 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-OBITUARY-JOYNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORENCE GRIFFITH JOYNER, 38; FLASHY SPRINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florence Griffith Joyner, the stunning sprinter whose one-legged
track suits and flashy fingernails remain as etched in memory as
her two world records and three gold medals, died Monday at her
home is Mission Viejo, Calif. She was 38.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County sheriff's office said a 911 call was received
early Monday morning from her husband, Al Joyner, who reported his
wife was ``unresponsive and not breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had passed away during the night,'' said spokesman Lt.
Hector Rivera. An autopsy was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Foster, the three-time world champion in the 100-meter
hurdles and a longtime friend of Griffith Joyner, said she suffered
an apparent heart seizure, although the official cause of death has
not been determined. Despite being hospitalized overnight two years
ago after suffering a seizure while on a flight from St. Louis to
California, Foster said, she had shown no subsequent signs of heart
problems and had not been in ill health.
</P>
<P>
   Foster was told of the death by Griffith Joyner's sister-in-law,
Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who with her husband Bobby rushed to
California when they heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   Her family was one of talent and fame: Joyner-Kersee's brother,
Al, married Florence Griffith in 1987. Besides Griffith Joyner's
five Olympic medals, Al Joyner was the 1984 Olympic triple-jump
gold medalist, while Jackie Joyner-Kersee won six Olympic medals in
the high jump and heptathlon before retiring this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dazzled by her speed, humbled by her talent, and
captivated by her style,'' said President Clinton after learning of
her death. ``Though she rose to the pinnacle of the world of
sports, she never forgot where she came from, devoting time and
resources to helping children -- especially those growing up in our
most devastated neighborhoods -- make the most of their own
talents.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago this week that Griffith Joyner won triple
gold in the 100-meter dash, 200-meter dash and and as part of the
4x100-meter relay in the 1988 Olympics in Seoul. She barely missed
a fourth gold medal when the 4x400 team finished second.
</P>
<P>
   The world records she set en route -- an amazing 10.49 in the
100 at the Olympic Trials followed by an astounding 21.34 in the
200 at the Olympics themselves -- not only made her the fastest
woman ever, but have yet to be seriously challenged despite the
spectacular rise of Marion Jones, whose times of 10.65 and 21.62
this year are as close as anyone has come in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost one of the great track and field athletes in
history,'' said Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Although later known simply as ``FloJo,'' she was born Delorez
(cq) Florence Griffith on Dec. 21, 1959. Raised with her 10
brothers and sisters in a housing project in Watts, a rough section
of Los Angeles, the youngster was competing in, and winning, the
50- and 70-meter dashes at the Sugar Ray Robinson Youth Foundation
by the time she was seven. By 1973, she had one the first of two
consecutive Jesse Owens National Youth Games.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't prevent her from finding time to pursue her
other love: playing dress-up, experimenting with hairstyles, trying
out the concept of wearing one color kneesock on one leg and a
different color on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put on my own clothes and turn them this way and that,''
Griffith Joyner said in a Los Angeles Times interview in 1988. She
would smash crayons into her nail polish, seeking a more
more-dramatic look. If she couldn't afford, or even find, the
clothes she wanted, she would design and sew them herself.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she started running for California State University
at Northridge, it was obvious that Griffith Joyner had a flair for
both fashion and speed. What she didn't have was money, and when
she ran out she quit school and went to work as a bank teller.
Kersee, her track coach at Northridge, got her back into college
with financial aid, and she followed him to UCLA when he got a job
there in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Griffith Joyner almost made the Olympic team at 200
meters; in 1982 she won the NCAA championship at that distance and
the next year won again, this time at 400. It was all a buildup to
making the team for the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles, where she ran
for a silver medal in the 200 behind teammate Valerie Brisco.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed with her second-place finish, Griffith Joyner went
back to work for a bank during the day, working in the evenings as
a hairdresser and nail stylist. Her training fell off, and she
began to gain weight. But she never gave up, and with the support
of her new boyfriend, Al Joyner, she struggled to get back into
shape. Knowing that her reaction time out of the blocks had always
been a weak point, she watched tapes of sprinter Ben Johnson's
takeoff out of the blocks and Carl Lewis's relaxed style. She hit
the weights, the fire rekindled as she sharpened her focus on
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very, very determined,'' said Jeanette Bolden, a
teammate at UCLA and now women's track coach there. ``There was no
impossibility to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In her quarterfinal heat of the 100 at the 1988 Olympic Trials
in Indianapolis -- wearing a purple body suit with the left leg cut
off, topped by a pair of turquoise bikini briefs -- Griffith
Joyner's 10:49 shattered the world record. Then, a few months
later, she captivated the rest of the world with her Olympic
triumphs and dazzling track suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Florence brought to track was a flash and a flair that we
didn't have, which was probably good for the sport and got
attention for us,'' said Evelyn Ashford, one of her competitors and
herself an Olympic sprint gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   The combination helped cement her as one of the most-recognized
female athletes ever. ``She had that rare combination of glamor,
individuality and being a gold medalist, a champion,'' Donna
Lopiano, executive director of the Women's Sports Foundation, said
Monday of the 1998 nominee for the foundation's prestigious
International Hall of Fame. ``She reinvented the track and field
uniform for women. It seemed like she invented the designer
fingernail, and with a gold medal that's a pretty potent
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner's melding of speed and style ``repopularized
track and field among young girls,'' said Lopiano. ``At a time you
were looking for the next hero, there she came: not with the soft
steps of a Wilma Rudolph, but with a bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Her success, however, did not come without controversy. Even
after a decade, questions persist about the validity of wind gauge
at the Trials, which read 0.00 despite swirling winds recorded at
the same time elsewhere in the stadium; indeed, the 1998 track and
field annual puts an asterisk for ``probably strongly
wind-assisted'' next to the mark. And given the seemingly rapid
development of Griffith Joyner's muscular physique between 1984 and
1988, steroid rumors were probably unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the rumors are about me, and they are not true,''
she once said. ``I have never used drugs, I will never use drugs
and I don't need to use drugs.'' The sprinter never failed a drug
test.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1989, without a single post-Olympic race, Griffith
Joyner retired to pursue endorsement opportunities and her dreams
of writing and acting. She designed a line of clothing for Starter,
marketed a line of artificial fingernails, recorded several popular
exercise videos and -- without question her proudest accomplishment
-- gave birth to a daughter, Mary, now 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had her hand in on something to do with kids,''
said Foster, insisting she wasn't always as flashy as she looked.
``She was very quiet, very humble, not outgoing at all. She was a
homebody, more or less.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite flirtations with comebacks in the marathon and 400
meters over the past decade, Griffith Joyner's main contribution to
athletics since 1988 has been as co-chair since 1993 of the
President's Council on Physical Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence was ... a kind and caring human being, a model for
the youth of the world,'' remembered Craig Masback, chief executive
officer of USA Track &AMP; Field.
</P>
<P>
   Primo Nebiolo, head of the International Athletic Federation,
perhaps spoke for many when he said Monday: ``I will never forget
this extraordinary athlete who stunned the world in Seoul 10 years
ago with her amazing sprints and spectacular outfits. Sadly, her
life has passed as rapidly as her races.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service and Globe file material, and quotes from the book
``Great Women in Sports,'' were used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
