<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-BOS &LR;      09-21 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS REACTS ALONG POLITICAL LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats questioned the fairness of the process
and Republicans expressed skepticism about President Clinton's
truthfulness in congressional reaction to the release of Clinton's
videotaped grand jury testimony Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republicans are overreaching,'' said Senator John
F. Kerry. ``I think they are in great danger of abusing the process
in a way that will invite retribution by the American public, and
they need to stop this nonsense and come up with a streamlined
process to bring this to a close,'' said Kerry, who called on the
president Sunday to volunteer immediately to testify before the
House Judiciary Committee to spare the nation a protracted
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 p.m., Kerry's office had received 1,400 telephone calls
from constituents, and 80 percent ``want the president to be left
alone,'' said Jim Jones, Kerry's spokesman. Early last week the
calls to Kerry's office ran against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Charles Canady, a Florida Republican and a member
of the House Judiciary Committee that is considering an impeachment
inquiry, said lying under oath would constitute grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president understands the meaning of an oath,''
Canady said. ``I think he understands the obligation to tell the
truth. I do believe that if the president lied under oath before
the grand jury that is an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The House was not in session Monday because of Rosh Hashanah,
the Jewish New Year, and few were present in the Senate, which
convened for debate but scheduled no roll call votes.
</P>
<P>
   The deeply divided Judiciary Committee voted Friday in favor of
Monday's release of the Clinton videotape and more than 3,000 pages
of evidence collected by Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr. The
committee is expected to meet later this week to determine what
they will not release in the remaining 16 boxes of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Representative William Delahunt, the Massachusetts Democrat,
said that he will attempt to delay the release of the rest of
Starr's evidence evidence beyond next Monday's deadline so
Judiciary Committee members can review it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people want us to take a look at it. They don't
want the staff to examine it for us,'' Delahunt said. ``Let's get
it done, but let's not sacrifice fairness and thoughtful
deliberation. ... This is simply too important. It is a matter of
gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative James Rogan, a California Republican, described
himself as ``disturbed'' by Clinton's videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a long way to go,'' said Rogan. ``We have to
give him the benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, said
Congress needs to find a way ``to admonish the president's behavior
and at the same time put this behind us....If we can find a way to
spare the country that process (of impeachment), that would be in
the best interests of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said he is concerned the president
``is being treated unfairly by the Republican majority in Congress.
The videotape and other materials are a one-sided account of what's
happened _ it's the prosecutor's version,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they chose the wrong day to do it,'' said Senate
Democratic Leader Tom Daschle during a news conference called to
announce a Democratic proposal to help farmers. ``They didn't have
to release this today. The president is making a major foreign
policy address, and it's a major Jewish holiday. ''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Patrick Kennedy, the Rhode Island Democrat,
attended Clinton's address on the threat of international terrorism
at the United Nations Monday. He described the warm reception that
greeted Clinton as a ``spontaneous expression of good will and
solidarity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall impression today was one of pure joy when the
whole congress of the United Nations stood and gave the president a
standing ovation when he came into the hall,'' Patrick Kennedy
said. ``Despite all the pundits and the critics, the common sense
of everybody tells us that what is going on, albeit serious, is a
charade when compared to the world's real problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
