<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DAY-720&AMP;ADD-N     09-21 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADDRESSES WORLD LEADERS WHILE VIDEO AIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-NY, CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA,
CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA,
CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a day of high-minded indifference to the
disclosure of his grand-jury testimony, President Clinton passed
his time Monday in the consoling company of admiring fellow world
leaders, contemplating terrorism, Social Security, the degradation
of the oceans, and the social safety net in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention his grim-faced testimony, and he did not
watch any of it either, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   After a speech to the United Nations and lunch with assorted
heads of state, Clinton went to the New York University School of
Law to discuss how to strengthen democracy as global markets blur
national boundaries. In a room full of aspiring lawyers and
accomplished professors, he was not asked about his grand-jury
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the president chewed over connections among domestic
politics, social issues, economic development, environmental change
and other matters with his friend Tony Blair, the prime minister of
Great Britain; Romano Prodi, the prime minister of Italy; and Petar
Stoyanov, the president of Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of kitchen-table, peripatetic, highbrow gab that
Clinton pioneered in Arkansas and has tried to translate to the
world stage as president.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he and Blair have conducted these sorts of
earnest conversations before, but privately, with advisers in
Washington and just outside London. This was the first time they
treated the public _ for two hours _ to their earnest search to
identify the world's looming problems and to define what they call
a ``third way'' in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in activist government, but highly disciplined,''
the president said, in trying to explain the concept to the
audience in front of him and to that slice of the television
audience that was not preoccupied with replays of his grand-jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said, ``We are witnessing, in effect, the rebirth of
progressive politics,'' which he described as an eagerness for
progress combined with a commitment to justice. Blair credited
Clinton, whom he called Bill, with giving the world ``hope and
confidence'' that powerful nations would intervene to prevent
humanitarian disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The four leaders sat in red leather armchairs, with a round
wooden table in front of them and an antique,
here-there-be-monsters globe at their left. Clinton led the
discussion, sinking back casually in his seat and pointing a finger
as he posed questions to his fellow leaders. Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who sat in the front row, did not participate, as she had
in the private sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The president quickly warmed to the discussion, describing the
social safety net in the Netherlands, the needs of the Social
Security system in the United States, and one Ugandan village's
attempts to use ``microcredit,'' or tiny loans, to build the
``infrastructure of civil society.'' At one point, Clinton recalled
former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo's maxim that people may campaign
in poetry but must govern in prose, as he turned to Prodi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romano, what's your biggest domestic challenge?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi replied in his gravelly baritone, ``My prose, my prose.''
</P>
<P>
   Grinning, the president returned, ``Italians never have to speak
in prose.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got so casual by late in the session that Clinton was
waving his hands as he offered breezy examples of his efforts to
address the degradation of the oceans or to increase financing for
research and development into the environment. Sucking on a candy,
he said that in response Republicans in Congress ``say that it's a
communist plot, and they hold hearings on it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the audience laughed, Clinton said that he was trying to make
a serious point, that too many policy-makers ``see an iron law
between how much junk you put in the atmosphere and how much your
economy grows.'' Until politicians are convinced that the economy
can grow with environmental protection, he said, ``we are playing
Russian roulette with our children's future.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a quick, one-day trip to New York to
address the United Nations. But the White House has stretched it
into two and a half days of parlays with heads of government. The
response Clinton has gotten _ from a standing ovation at the United
Nations to the affectionate way Prodi called him Bill _ seemed sure
to bolster his mood.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whenever he has been confronted by scandal, Clinton has tried to
direct attention instead toward his devotion to confronting the
problems facing the country. That technique did not work Monday, at
least in the view of White House aides, who were seething over the
wall-to-wall broadcast coverage of the president's testimony, which
took place on August 17.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, said he was not
surprised that Clinton's speech at the United Nations, a call for a
global crusade against terrorism, received less media attention
than his testimony. The testimony, he said, ``has had that impact
of fewer electrons dispersed in the air on that very vital and
important subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Decrying the release by the Republican-dominated Congress of
Clinton's videotaped grand-jury appearance, he called Monday
``arguably an unnecessary day in the life of our country, an awful
day.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Hillary Rodham Clinton presided over a two-hour
panel discussion at NYU on the topic ``Civil Society and the Future
of Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a room packed with professors, visiting policy-makers, law
students (and more reporters than usually sit through academic
discussions), Mrs. Clinton was greeted with especially loud and
long applause. And the other members of her panel took pains to
show their regard for her.
</P>
<P>
   In her own short and sober remarks, Mrs. Clinton emphasized the
need to nurture citizenship, and to find new ways to govern at a
time when the old ways of governing are no longer effective.
</P>
<P>
   Warning that neither government nor globalization should be
blamed as the root of all evil, Mrs. Clinton said, in what sounded
very much like a personal creed, that we have to take the world as
we find it and do what we can to improve upon it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
