<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-MEXICO-PRISONERS-H     09-21 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-PRISONERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., MEXICO TO SWAP PRISONERS UNDER EXCHANGE PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Champaign, Ill.) 
(See optional trims) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An East Texas gun dealer who has spent six months in a Mexican
border jail will be among 14 Americans returned to the United
States as early as Tuesday under a routine prisoner exchange,
officials confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Bean, a 59-year-old retired car dealer and gun show
exhibitor from Vidor, was sentenced by a Mexican judge to a
five-year prison term for illegally importing 203 rounds of
ammunition last March. Bean said his crime was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican police in Nuevo Laredo found the ammunition in the back
of Bean's Suburban as he and four companions crossed the border to
eat dinner following a Laredo gun show. His friends were held
briefly and released, but Bean, as the owner of the vehicle, was
charged and eventually convicted. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bean's case and those of scores of other Americans jailed for
taking guns and ammunition across the border have spotlighted the
comparatively harsh laws concerning the possession and importation
of weapons in Mexico. Private gun ownership is generally outlawed
in Mexico. Even taking a small amount of ammunition or a pocket
knife across the border can result in an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Possession of a weapon can be punished by up to five years in
prison, while those caught with firearms or ammunition reserved by
Mexican law for military use face five- to 30-year sentences and
hefty fines. The punishment is the same for Mexicans caught with
such weapons.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, more than 120 Americans have been arrested in
Mexico on weapons charges and 69 are jailed, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Watkins, the American consul in Nuevo Laredo, said Bean
was moved last Friday with three other Americans from the ``La
Loma'' prison in the Mexican border town to a prison outside of
Monterrey to be processed for the expected transfer to the United
States. They could arrive at the El Paso International Airport as
early as Tuesday, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Six other Americans remain jailed on weapons charges in Nuevo
Laredo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Mexican) prison director called me ... He hoped that
sometime this week they'd be in the United States,'' Watkins said.
``It's in the hands of the U.S. Department of Justice and the
Mexican authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner exchange, which will send home at least 89 Mexican
citizens who are being held in U.S. custody, is part of a routine
exchange under a 1977 treaty with Mexico. About 1,500 Americans and
2,118 Mexicans have been exchanged under the treaty. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at her home in Vidor, Bean's wife, Sadie Bean,
declined to comment on his expected release.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watkins confirmed that another American being exchanged along
with Bean was convicted on weapons charges, but he said he could
not release his name. However, press reports have quoted Mexican
prison officials as saying the man is Jose Lerma, a carpet
installer from Waco, who was convicted for possession of nine
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   As in past prisoner exchanges, American citizens are flown by
Mexican authorities to El Paso and then taken to La Tuna, a
minimum-security U.S. federal prison outside El Paso. They are held
there until their Mexican sentences are reviewed and they are given
an equivalent U.S. federal sentence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, U.S. Parole Commission attorney Richard Preston
said the American prisoners must be interviewed by federal
probation officers, who translate their Mexican court sentences and
other legal documents and conduct an extensive review of the
prisoner's criminal history, employment and family background.
After a 25- to 30-page post-sentence report is completed _ a
process that can be delayed for months by the probation
department's workload _ it is forwarded to the parole commission in
Washington for review.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a hypothetical, I would say at least a month, no more than
four months before his case is reviewed,'' Preston said, referring
to a hypothetical example of a case similar to Bean's. ``If it
turns out he had bazookas or nuclear (bomb) triggers _ I don't know
what he had _ we might not let him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, all I can say is, we don't have his file,''
Preston said of Bean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jose Barron, the associate warden of La Tuna, said prison
officials are expecting the prisoners' arrival by Saturday at the
latest. Until the Americans arrive, prison officials are not
certain of their crimes, although in past exchanges the majority of
Americans were serving drug sentences in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The files come with them,'' Barron said. ``We have an idea,
but I wouldn't want to speculate. We're not 100 percent sure until
they step off the plane and we ID them and get their files.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
