<HEADER>
A7014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAL-MARKETPLACE-5     09-21 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MARKETPLACE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CONSOLIDATION AMONG MEDICAL-DEVICE MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A note to shareholders of all medical-device manufacturers: This
is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to ratchet up market share, the United States'
medical-device makers are out to snap up their weaker brethren at a
startling pace.
</P>
<P>
   In two long-anticipated deals, Guidant Corp., one of the world's
leading makers of cardiac defibrillators, announced Monday that it
would buy the pacemaker division of Switzerland's Sulzer Medica
Ltd. for as much as $850 million.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had investors received word of that deal than General
Electric's medical-systems unit said it would buy Marquette Medical
Systems Inc., a maker of heart-monitoring machines, for about $808
million in stock. What was especially odd about this deal was that
GE had divested itself of the same business in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Has the world gone mad?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. With several of the nation's small medical-device makers
struggling, the industry's larger players are making what analysts
call prime acquisitions _ deals to get sophisticated products at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guidant was really getting overwhelmed in the pacemaker
market,'' said Kurt Kruger, a medical-device industry analyst with
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities. ``But with the acquisition, they
picked up several market share points. And they got it at a very
good price, less than three times sales. You could almost say it
was a discount.''
</P>
<P>
   Both acquisitions were boon deals. Aside from merging to gain
girth for price battles with health-maintenance organizations,
medical-device companies need size for research dollars and
technology. Larger companies also steal accounts from smaller ones,
since most of the nation's large hospitals like to buy their wares
from only a few suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Guidant, which is based in Indianapolis, and GE,
already the world's largest maker of magnetic resonance equipment,
pick up more financial heft, they will also enormously expand their
product lines. Medtronic Inc., based in Indianapolis, controls
about 46 percent of the cardiac-defibrillator market, according to
Kruger. Guidant, with a 21 percent market stake, will raise that to
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GE's medical-systems division, meanwhile, gets a product that it
doesn't have: heart-monitoring machines. Analysts said GE wanted
Marquette Medical Systems to expand its offerings to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no product overlap with the acquisition by GE,''
said Suey Wong, the vice president of research at Robert W. Baird &AMP;
Co. ``These acquisitions make sense in that it is easier to acquire
a company to get technology than to develop it on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though analysts applauded both deals, Wall Street had a
mixed reaction. The shares of Marquette Medical Systems soared 55.3
percent to close at $42.50 each, a 52-week high. General Electric
closed at $79.25, up $1.375.
</P>
<P>
   Guidant shares, however, fell $1.1875, to $74, while Sulzer
Medica's American depository receipts, worth one-tenth a share,
dropped $1, to $17.875. Analysts said the two stocks tumbled
because investors had long anticipated the deal's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are confident that these acquisitions will not be the
industry's last. With low price-earnings ratios and a bounty of
sophisticated products, several small medical-device companies
appear to be prime takeover targets. What is especially noteworthy
is that several make cardiac equipment, a field that is
consolidating faster than many others.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most innovative of the cardiac-equipment suppliers is
Arterial Vascular Engineering in Santa Rosa, Calif. The company,
which makes stents and balloons for angioplasty, is in one of the
fastest-growing segments of the health-care industry. Better yet,
the company's stock has a price-earnings ratio of 23.7, slightly
below the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 at 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``AVE is what we call one of the single-product companies,''
Kruger said. ``They have $500 million each year in stent sales and
have a substantial sales force. It would be an attractive buy.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to name any potential acquisition target, it's common
for analysts to single out companies that have recently completed
an initial public offering. One popular pick this fall is
Cardiothoracic Systems, based in Cupertino, Calif. The company, a
maker of disposable instruments for minimally invasive
cardiothoracic surgery, has a market capitalization of just $64
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts say that some of the likely candidates for
acquisition may appear surprising. Analysts are pondering the
future of St. Jude Medical, one of Guidant's competitors and a
leading maker of pacemakers and defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   What makes St. Jude Medical a likely player? Not only is the
company a leader in pacemakers, Kruger said, but it is also
struggling. But with a price-earnings ratio of 22.4, two points
below the S&AMP;P, the deal may be too good to pass up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
