<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-OBUCHI-800&AMP;ADD-N     09-21 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-OBUCHI-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOKYO LEADER BLAMES MANY FOR BANKS' CRISIS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Japan's prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, Monday blamed
his predecessor, Japan's powerful finance ministry and the heads of
the country's huge financial institutions for wasting years before
facing up to the crippling banking crisis as well as a deep
recession that is worsening the world's economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's comments, in an interview Monday as he prepared to
address the United Nations, amounted to an unusual acknowledgment
by a Japanese leader that the government and private sector had
made huge errors that have ricocheted through economies around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he failed to lay out any new initiatives, and
appeared to acknowledge that an agreement on the banking crisis
reached late last week with opposition leaders failed to work out
critical details about how the government will deal with bank debts
of nearly a trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   That accord was fraying in Tokyo even as Obuchi prepared for
what promises to be a tense first meeting with President Clinton
Tuesday at the Rockefeller family estate in Tarrytown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As politicians in Tokyo bickered over whether the accord limits
the ability of the Japanese government to pump billions of dollars
in public funds into failing banks, the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell
drastically, hitting its lowest point since mid-1986.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi arrives here a besieged man. Both Britain and Germany
have joined the United States in urging Japan to act immediately,
and Japanese officials fret these days that they are being blamed _
unfairly, in their eyes _ for the economic meltdown of Southeast
Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the International Monetary Fund, which is normally
extremely cautious about criticizing a nation that is also one of
its largest sources of funds, declared in its annual report that
one of the leading risks to the world economy now is that Japan
``will not move promptly and resolutely to address its financial
sector problems while insuring adequate domestic demand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is becoming increasingly critical,'' the Fund's report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was clearly prepared Monday for the inevitable criticism:
His briefing papers included a small tab to bring him directly to
his talking points on the mounting criticism. The handwritten tab
was marked ``Too little, too late.''
</P>
<P>
   He volunteered, however, that ``unfortunately, the Japanese
people in general still lack the awareness'' of how the country's
economic troubles are affecting the rest of the world. He said the
lack of awareness has contributed to problems with Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's portrayal of the Japanese political system as insular
is hardly surprising _ critics of the country have been offering
similar analyses since Commodore Perry forced the country to open
to foreign trade 130 years ago _ but it is a sharp contrast to the
way Japanese politicians spoke during the height of the country's
prosperity in the late 1980s. Then, they justified Japan's
worldwide buying spree as natural for a country that had used the
power of the yen to internationalize.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Obuchi gave a very different interpretation of those
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no wonder the Japanese financial institutions are
criticized,'' the longtime Japanese politician said. Pointing to
the view of the New York skyline outside the floor-to-ceiling
windows of his hotel suite opposite the United Nations, he said:
``Someone even bought Rockefeller Center. What did they produce?
Losses. And now they impose them on the Japanese people.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point Obuchi even took a mild jab at Japan's finance
ministry, which would see some powers stripped away under last
week's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He also indirectly criticized the performance of his
predecessor, Ryutaro Hashimoto, describing how his policies of
austerity and higher taxes were overwhelmed by the economic crisis
that began in Thailand 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan was not able to make a rapid turnaround in its policy,''
he said. But he insisted that now Japan has made a major shift in
policy. ``Instead of `too little too late' we want to deal with
this in ways that people say `too big, too fast,' `' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, he is at little risk of facing that criticism. While the
Parliament passed legislation during Hashimoto's term that
authorized spending of more than $100 billion to inject capital
into failing banks, the accord reached last week scraps that
system. It is unclear what will replace it, though Obuchi insisted
Monday that ``public money will be used to buy up the shares'' of
failing banks.
</P>
<P>
   Whether and how that happens, however, is likely to be the
subject of considerable debate at the meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin was quite specific in
congressional testimony last week, arguing that Japan's problems _
and Asia's _ cannot be solved without the use of taxpayer dollars
to pump capital into otherwise insolvent banks. The United States
has also called for the management of those banks to be dismissed,
for the shareholders to be wiped out, and for their assets _
property held as collateral for loans _ to be auctioned off
quickly, to revive a frozen property market.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi skirted most of those subjects, however, saying ``those
matters are not yet worked out.'' But he did argue that Japan could
not risk the uncertainty of letting major banks fail. He noted, for
example, that the total liabilities of the virtually insolvent
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, known as LTCB, are ``worth 1.2 or
1.3 times the total economy of Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we cannot tell LTCB to quit operating simply
because the management of that bank was incompetent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics of bailing out banks is not the usual stuff of
meetings between prime ministers and presidents, but the session
Monday is bound to focus on those subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be highly specific,'' one of Clinton's top economic
aides said last week. ``No one has the luxury for the kind of
happy-talk generalities we've had in most of these meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   But Obuchi and Clinton, in a break from past practice, are
making no joint public appearance to help calm the markets. Some
White House officials say that the Japanese are not eager for their
leader to stand before the press silently while Clinton receives
questions about the Monica Lewinsky matter. The Japanese say that
the White House did not appear eager for a joint appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have their problems,'' one Japanese official said, ``and
we have ours.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
