<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIDEO-INTERNET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET HANDLED CLINTON VIDEO PRETTY WELL, OVERALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Record crowds mobbed the Internet Tuesday to see video of
President Clinton's grand-jury testimony. And while the network
generally bore up well under the strain, it wasn't problem-free.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNEWS.com, whose Internet presence is managed by Starwave
Corp. in Bellevue, Wash., ``became inaccessible between 10 a.m. and
11 a.m. Pacific time,'' according to Keynote Systems, a Silicon
Valley company that monitors Internet performance.
</P>
<P>
   Both ABC and Starwave are owned by the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNEWS.com remained ``largely inaccessible and unresponsive''
into the afternoon, Keynote said, ``indicating a severe problem
with its Web-server infrastructure or Internet connectivity.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for ABC News said she was unaware of the problem
or the report and couldn't comment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Keynote said, CNN.COM performed
spectacularly, delivering its home page to Internet users quickly
and with a failure rate of less than 1 percent, even better than
its 40-site performance index.
</P>
<P>
   CNN teams with three outside companies _ including Seattle-based
RealNetworks _ to serve up video over the Internet, spokeswoman
Alison Rudnick said.
</P>
<P>
   It also shifts into ``breaking news mode,'' streamlining its Web
site for maximum performance by removing graphics and other
features that can undermine performance, Rudnick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN's Web site is just such an integral part of their overall
news operation these days,'' Keynote spokesman Gene Shklar said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has enough online experience to have mastered an
important lesson, he added: ``You have to build a Web site to serve
peak demand, not average demand.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN said that about 8 am PDT Monday, almost 20,000 people were
simultaneously watching either the live or the on-demand version of
Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com, which provided audio and video for CNN.com,
MSNBC.com and CourtTV, said it served as many as 50,000 users at
once between the Clinton coverage and its regular programs.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks distributed more than a 500,000 copies of its media
player, a record number, over the weekend as people readied their
computers to watch the Clinton video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a determining event for video on the Web, said
Mark Bretl, vice president of RealNetworks' media systems division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumors of it taking down the Internet have been dispelled,''
Bretl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet gets a grade of A,'' Keynote's Shklar said. ``I'm
really impressed with how it has responded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
