<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DU PONT RELATIVE ACCUSED IN DEATH OF HEIR'S GIRLFRIEND  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ For the second time in two years, a relative
of the du Ponts, Delaware's first family, has been charged in a
killing.
</P>
<P>
   In the new case, Christopher Moseley, the stepfather of a du
Pont heir, Dean MacGuigan, was accused last week of arranging the
killing of Patricia Margello, who the police said was MacGuigan's
girlfriend. The police said Moseley confessed to the crime when he
was arrested in nearby Greenville, Del., as he was about to greet
guests at the site of a golf course that he had proposed building.
</P>
<P>
   Three other people have been charged in connection with Ms.
Margello's death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, John du Pont killed David Schultz, an Olympic wrestler,
in suburban Philadelphia. He was sentenced last year to 13 to 30
years in prison or a mental hospital, depending on his condition.
</P>
<P>
   In the new case, Henry Schlumpf, a special agent for the FBI,
has filed a complaint in federal district court, saying that
Moseley had waived his right to remain silent and had confessed
that he had arranged to pay to have Ms. Margello killed in Las
Vegas, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Margello's body was found in an air-conditioning duct at the
Del Mar Motel in Las Vegas on Aug. 2. She had been beaten and
strangled, and her body had been bound with wire and tape and
covered with garbage bags before being placed inside the duct,
Schlumpf said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that Ms. Margello, who was also known as
Patricia Howarth, was the girlfriend of MacGuigan, the son of Lisa
Dean Moseley, a du Pont descendant who lives on an estate in
Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moseley married Christopher Moseley, who had been the
gardener on her estate, after the death of her second husband. The
estate is known as ``chateau country'' because of the magnificence
of the du Pont estate, and Mrs. Moseley's place was once included
in estate tours.
</P>
<P>
   At the arraignment before Magistrate Judge Mary Pat Thynge, the
FBI did not offer a motive and the U.S. attorney's office here
declined to comment on the case Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley is being held until he returns to court on Tuesday, on a
charge of conspiracy to use interstate facilities in the commission
of a murder-for-hire. The maximum penalty is life in prison or a
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI complaint, Moseley asked Diana Hironaga in
July to kill Ms. Margello, telephoning her from Greenville when she
was in Las Vegas. The telephone call and other communications
established the interstate aspect of the crime and allowed federal
officers to enter what would otherwise have been a local
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, the police and federal agents charged Ms. Hironaga
and two others they said were hired by Moseley, Ricardo Murillo and
Joseph Balignasa, to lure Ms. Margello to the motel. The police
said that Murillo and Balignasa had killed her there.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, according to the FBI complaint, Ms. Hironaga
``notified Moseley by phone that Margello had been murdered as
requested.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, the complaint says, Ms. Hironaga and Murillo flew to
Philadelphia ``where they were paid a fee for committing the
murder,'' and then the two flew back to Las Vegas. The complaint
did not give the amount of the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Ms. Hironaga confessed to the murder, the FBI
said.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the du Pont wealth in the area roughly between
Wilmington and Philadelphia can only be estimated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when John du Pont was sentenced last year for
killing Schultz, his fortune was estimated at $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Du Pont used his family fortune to build a training camp and
surround himself with outstanding wrestlers who were preparing for
Olympic competition.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Media, Pa., found du Pont guilty of third-degree
murder but mentally ill. After the verdict was announced, Schultz's
widow, Nancy, said, ``It's comforting to know du Pont was not above
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
