<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PRISON-HEALTHCARE-     09-21 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-HEALTHCARE-ART-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATE DEATH RAISES QUESTIONS ABOUT HEALTH CARE IN CITY'S JAILS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on medical care at Rikers Island is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Late last month, Jose Ubano, an inmate on Rikers
Island, checked into a jail clinic with high fever and abdominal
pains. City officials say Ubano, 29, was hallucinating and seemed
suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   A blood test showed that his liver was weak. But instead of
checking his liver more closely, several officials say, the clinic
sent him to a jail mental health center, where a psychiatrist
placed Ubano on an antipsychotic drug that can create severe
strains on the liver. And 18 hours after taking the drug, Ubano was
rushed to a hospital emergency room, where he died of what one
doctor called ``full-blown liver failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Several city and state agencies are reviewing Ubano's Aug. 31
death, and New York City's Board of Correction, a jail oversight
panel, is examining whether a series of medical errors caused or
hastened it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said some doctors who had reviewed Ubano's medical
charts questioned whether St. Barnabas' physicians had done enough
tests to assess the extent of his liver damage. They also noted
that he could have been given antipsychotic drugs that would have
filtered through his kidney instead of his liver.
</P>
<P>
   But the questions surrounding his death also have quickly taken
on much larger dimensions: A number of Correction Board officials,
present and former Rikers doctors and public health experts say his
case illustrates how the quality of health care has deteriorated
since a managed care system was installed in the city's jails last
January.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Board of Correction are also looking into the
deaths of at least three other inmates earlier this year. And while
top city health executives insist that the quality of care remains
high, many critics say that pressures to cut costs, as well as a
large turnover of doctors, have plunged the sprawling jail health
system into its worst crisis in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen a stream of complaints like this before,''
said John Horan, acting chairman of the Board of Correction, which
sets minimum health standards for the jails.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints started after St. Barnabas Hospital in the Bronx
won the three-year, $342 million contract to provide health care
for city jails. In seeking bids for the contract, the city said it
would change the way it paid for health care in an effort to save
millions of dollars: Instead of paying each time an inmate was
taken to the hospital, it would provide an annual lump sum for each
inmate's care. Now, though, that approach has become a central
issue in the debate over health care in the jails, with many
critics wondering if the Giuliani administration has given a
private contractor too much financial incentive to cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic change is that since St. Barnabas took over on
Jan. 1, the number of trips by inmates to some city hospitals,
which have traditionally treated the most serious illnesses, has
dropped by 57 percent, to 1,496 through August, down from 3,456 in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at St. Barnabas point to these statistics as a sign
of success, saying they have reduced these trips without
compromising care by expanding the types of care in jail clinics
and treating more inmates on Rikers itself. But the critics say St.
Barnabas has not broadened the services as quickly or as much as it
promised. And they contend that it is waiting too long to send some
inmates to hospitals or medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, more than a dozen current and former health care
workers at Rikers said that some inmates, like Ubano, had been
placed in serious jeopardy by failures to take enough diagnostic
tests, delays in sending them to emergency rooms and other mistakes
by harried or inexperienced medical personnel. Several doctors and
medical assistants said some inmates with less critical problems,
like eye and nerve conditions, had also received too little
treatment, adding that shortages of medical supplies had
occasionally interfered with care.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the death of Ubano, the Correction Board is
looking into whether delays in treatment contributed to the deaths
of the three other inmates _ including one whose family has filed a
claim charging that his death from a ruptured aorta could have been
averted if he had been treated sooner for chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Ubano's death has prompted some
disciplinary action, St. Barnabas executives insisted that there
was no problem with their care in the other deaths.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The correction system's foray into managed care is being closely
watched because it has implications that stretch far beyond the
jails. The Giuliani administration has cited the St. Barnabas
contract as a model for containing costs in public health
operations, and it has made similar moves to save huge sums in the
public hospital system that serves many of the city's poor.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the complaints at Rikers echo many of the
concerns that have accompanied the expansion of managed care among
private health insurers. The new contract basically calls for St.
Barnabas to receive a lump sum to run more than 15 clinics treating
the 130,000 inmates who pass through Rikers Island and the
Manhattan Detention Complex each year.
</P>
<P>
   St. Barnabas must cover any hospital costs and visits to outside
specialists from that pot of money. So the less it spends, the more
it can earn, and St. Barnabas officials have said they could make
more than $10 million in profits this year.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Giuliani administration sees this approach as a
way to place a lid on costs, some oversight officials believe that
St. Barnabas has clamped down too much. After the Board of
Correction discussed the problems at a meeting last week, board
member David Lenefsky said, ``There has been a prima-facie case
made that St. Barnabas could be below the minimum standards.''
</P>
<P>
   He said those rules require that inmates _ most of whom are
being held awaiting trial _ be offered access to the same kind of
care that they could obtain if they were not incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials at the Health and Hospitals Corporation, which
awarded the jail contract, and St. Barnabas executives disputed
that the problems were widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will shape up,'' Joseph Erazo, executive director for
correctional health services at the Health and Hospitals
Corporation, said at the Correction Board meeting. ``You've just
got to give me a little more time.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Barnabas' president, Dr. Ronald Gade, dismissed the level of
complaints as ``markedly low,'' given the complexity of health
issues in the jails, where many inmates have AIDS, tuberculosis and
drug addictions. Referring to some of the deaths and other cases
that have been questioned, he said, ``It seems like people are
looking to see some sort of problems with the patients when I tell
you there was nothing wrong with the care.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Barnabas officials noted that the overall number of
nonviolent deaths in city jails had dropped from 42 in 1997 to 17
so far this year, and Gade said his staff deserved some of the
credit for that. Other medical authorities attribute the drop in
deaths to new drug treatments that help AIDS patients live longer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harry Shuman, who runs the jail program for St. Barnabas,
acknowledged that there had been some problems. Shuman said that
since May, he had dismissed five doctors, including some who
endangered patients with poor care. But he would not give details
of those cases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts say that public hospital and jail systems across
the country are facing similar difficulties in balancing cost and
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how do you guarantee the safety that is
essential for vulnerable populations,'' said Dennis Andrulis, a
department director at the New York Academy of Medicine. ``Cost
containment, if not carefully monitored, can fall out of balance.
You must find that balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7033 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MONICA-1STLD-     09-21 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MONICA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA BONDED WITH GRAND JURY MEMBERS, WHO FELT HER PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to remove quotes from affirmative reply five grafs from
end.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-KOHL,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-NY, CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA,
CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER, CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA,
CLINTON-EVIDENCE, CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) (JT) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three days after the president spoke to the country
about his affair with Monica Lewinsky, the former White House
intern told grand jurors that she had been in love with him up
until the minute he went on television and told the world that
their involvement was purely sexual. And where was his apology to
her?
</P>
<P>
   With prosecutors pressing her for more and more graphic detail,
she supplied it. And yet, she also said that although she was upset
and confused, she had no appetite for hurting the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a beautiful soul,'' she told the grand jurors
on August 20 in testimony released by Congress Monday. ``I just
thought he was just this incredible person, and when I looked at
him I saw a little boy. And I don't know what the truth is
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The country may not like Monica Lewinsky; a recent poll showed
that only 5 percent of Americans held a favorable view of her. But
grand jurors obviously did, urging her to forgive herself, forget
Linda Tripp and get on with her life in a court appearance that
often seemed more like a counseling session.
</P>
<P>
   When first asked about sex with the president, Ms. Lewinsky _
who asked the grand jury to call her Monica _ was so embarrassed
that she had to close her eyes and force herself to answer the
question. And with prosecutors pressing her to specify what body
parts went where, grand jurors seemed to become more and more
sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of her testimony on Aug. 20, a juror asked her if
there was anything she wanted to add, and Ms. Lewinsky defended the
president while offering a blanket apology for her own behavior:
``I would just like to say that no one ever asked me to lie and I
was never promised a job for my silence. And that I'm sorry. I'm
really sorry for everything that's happened. And I hate Linda
Tripp,'' she said, and began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Several grand jurors tried to comfort her. One told her, ``We've
all fallen short. We sin every day. I don't care whether it's
murder, whether it's affairs or whatever. And we get over that. You
ask forgiveness and you go on. So to let you know from here, you
have my forgiveness. Because we all fall short.''
</P>
<P>
   Several others agreed. One advised her to let go of her feelings
for Ms. Tripp, saying, ``Whatever goes around comes around.''
Again, others chimed in, with ``It comes around'' and ``It does.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before she was excused from the grand jury, the forewoman
told her, ``Basically what we wanted to leave with, because this
will probably be your last visit to us, I hope I'm not going to
have to do this any more and I hope you won't have to come here any
more, but we wanted to offer you a bouquet of good wishes that
includes luck, success, happiness and blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   She again burst into tears and responded in kind, continuing the
lovefest: ``I appreciate all of your understanding for this
situation and your ability to open your heart and your mind and
your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony and evidence released by Congress Monday
frequently presented Ms. Lewinsky in terms that make it easy to see
why the grand jury responded the way they did.
</P>
<P>
   She is shown surrounded by federal agents in January at the Ritz
Carlton Hotel and berated by assistants to special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr who wanted her to testify against the president. They
threatened her with jail and made fun of her for wanting her
``mommy.'' (The evidence also makes clear that Ms. Lewinsky did her
part to lighten the load on the American taxpayer, paying for her
own dinner with the agents at Mozzarella's American Grill that
evening and even forking over $2 for coffee to the men who were
pressing her to wear a wire.)
</P>
<P>
   She had enough presence of mind to respond to the surprise
appearance of Starr's team with legal questions: If the Paula Jones
sexual harassment suit went away, would she still be in legal
jeopardy? What if, theoretically speaking, she had not always told
Ms. Tripp the truth? She also thought to question the choice of her
father's friend and lawyer Bill Ginsburg as her attorney, worrying
because he was a medical malpractice lawyer inexperienced in
criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when her mother, Marcia Lewis, finally did arrive, she
was clearly worried sick for her daughter, telling the Starr team
that Ms. Lewinsky had been suicidal six years earlier and was young
for her age. Ms. Lewinsky later said she had been on
antidepressants since early in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In all of her grand jury testimony, she comes across as
unfailingly loyal to the president, calling him her ``sexual
soulmate'' and saying of the affair, ``I think back on it, and he
always made me smile when I was with him. He was sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   And she defended the president in a number of ways, insisting,
for example, that he would never have had sex in the Oval Office
itself. When asked whether the president said she should deny a
relationship, she answered, ``I think I always offered that.''
</P>
<P>
   She even cut him a break on what she refers to as ``D-Day _ Dump
Day,'' the day the president broke off their affair, saying he was,
``just really wanting to do the right thing in God's eyes and do
the right thing for his family.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She is hard on herself in many ways, taking responsibility for
hectoring Clinton to get her a job, and presenting herself as so
pushy that she even dared suggest to the president what Hillary
Rodham Clinton should do to get him out of the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit:
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that first Mrs. Clinton should do something
publicly, maybe on a TV show or something, and talk about how
difficult the case had been for her and on her daughter and that
she just wished that he would settle it and it would go away. And
then the president should unannounced and unexpectedly go into the
briefing room'' and say that against his lawyers' advice, he had
decided to pay Mrs. Jones whatever she wanted just to get it over
with.
</P>
<P>
   She does defend herself on such subjects as why she kept the
blue dress stained with the president's semen. Ms. Tripp, she said,
suggested that she keep it as evidence. And when Ms Lewinsky
refused, Ms. Tripp told her she looked fat in it, so she never wore
it again, and didn't get around to having it cleaned. She says she
wore ``the infamous beret'' as the result of a bad-hair day.
</P>
<P>
   In her first grand jury appearance on Aug. 6, prosecutors were
much more willing to settle for a general description of what
occurred between the president and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   By the Aug. 20 appearance, however, when prosecutors were
obviously matching Ms. Lewinsky's responses to the president's
grand jury testimony in an attempt to prove perjury, they were
asking such questions as, ``Were there times when the president
would touch you either on the breasts or in the genital area
directly to the skin or was it always through clothing?''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors seemed more interested in understanding Ms.
Lewinsky's motivations. One asked, ``Was it love or sexual
obsession?'' She answered that it was both, but ``more love.''
Another asked if she had truly believed ``anything real could have
come from this relationship?'' Yes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And when she grew embarrassed, they were sorry for her. One
suggested that she try closing her eyes again, and another said,
``We won't look at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky responded ``Can I hide under the table? I had ...
and wanted ... I tried to ... I placed his genital next to mine and
I hoped that if he ... oh, this is too embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the last questions put to her was whether she for any
reason would want to hurt the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``I'm upset with him right now, but no, that's
the last thing in the world I want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
