<SLUG> BC-FOREX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forex doesn't challenge request
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorneys for Austin Forex International Inc.
and former University of Texas kicker Russell Erxleben on Monday
did not challenge the state's request to put the company into
receivership.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a Travis County judge granted a request by the Texas
State Securities Board to put the foreign currency exchange trading
company into receivership and seize its bank accounts. Monday was
the first time Austin Forex could have filed for a hearing to
challenge the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided yet'' whether to ask for a hearing to
dissolve the receivership, said John Stratton, Erxleben's attorney.
``It will be several days before we decide what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14, Austin Forex suddenly closed its doors, alarming
hundreds of investors and prompting the action by the state.
</P>
<P>
   According to former investors and employees, the company did
business with between 600 and 800 investors and handled as much as
$60 million before closing.
</P>
<P>
   In its Friday civil suit seeking the receivership, state
securities regulators claim Erxleben misled and defrauded
investors. The agency claims that besides losing investors' money
in bad foreign-currency trades, Erxleben personally used some of
the money to pay for a boat, health-club membership, cars and
personal investments.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorneys, Erxleben has denied the claims.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
