<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      09-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DAMAGED CLINTON LIKELY TO REMAIN IN OFFICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whatever Americans thought before the videotape
about President Clinton and whether he should stay or go, they
probably feel almost exactly the same way today.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary four-hour display of a president under oath,
who was, by turns, defensive, dissembling and disingenuous,
probably does not move the bottom line. Clinton is likely to remain
in office, but his presidency has been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton decides he wants to hang on at all costs _ and the
evidence points in that direction _ he can probably do that. But if
he believes he can retain a significant hold on the nation's trust
or belief in his word or character, he is likely deluding himself.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will be watching the polls to confirm that the public
is locked into its view that Clinton should remain in office. They
will also be on the lookout for the prospect of a public backlash,
which would not only help the president in his quest to survive,
but also bolster the party's chances in critical elections Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will look for a long-awaited drop in Clinton's 60
percent job-approval ratings. Their hunt probably will be in vain,
for there was no smoking gun in Clinton's testimony or, as far as
can be ascertained quickly, the remainder of the evidence that was
released.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was there some magic exculpatory bullet to let the
president off the hook. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clinton's grand jury testimony should confirm for even the
president's sturdiest defenders his extensive word-twisting
attempts to conceal the sleazy nature of his interludes with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If doubts remain, they can consult the accompanying tomes of
details that were released by the House Judiciary Committee with
which the president's lawyers have not taken issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's partisans will argue that no matter how
deplorable his actions _ ``reprehensible'' was the White House's
word of choice Monday _ they were not impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defenders also will see the tape of Clinton's Aug. 17
grand jury testimony as evidence that independent counsel Kenneth
Starr and his deputies were overzealous and fixated on sex. They
will view it as harassment and humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The president's detractors, on the other hand, will see his
testimony as an extended advertisement for why they believe he is
unfit to lead the nation. They think the videotape provides strong
proof of Clinton's moral turpitude and direct evidence of perjury
and witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
   The president's opponents will see the Starr team's probing,
insistent questions as the only way to attempt to break through
Clinton's continuing, impermeable stonewall.
</P>
<P>
   There seems little doubt that the House of Representatives is
headed toward a formal impeachment inquiry to explore those issues.
And both sides, nourished by their selective reading of national
polls, are likely to see that as an excuse for political blood
sport that will further alienate average Americans from the
political process.
</P>
<P>
   If his poll numbers hold, Clinton will stick to the ``this is
about you'' theme he used with a union crowd last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make this a season for doing things for you, not
idleness and indulgence,'' Clinton told a friendly audience of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers on Thursday. The
intended translation, of course, is that Republicans are too busy
wallowing in details of the scandal and their personal distaste for
Clinton to get on with the nation's business.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on Capitol Hill do not assume that will do the trick,
either with the voters or in Clinton's attempt to govern for the
next 28 months. And while many Democrats in Congress will defend
Clinton in principle, they may be less eager to embrace him
personally.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was cheered by Clinton's favorable reception
Monday when he walked onto the podium at the United Nations to give
his annual address to the General Assembly. But presidential aides
also knew that Clinton was about to address a room full of
politicians who may have been thinking: ``There, but for the grace
of God, go I.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House is not conceding the inevitability of the House
moving to a full impeachment inquiry, but Clinton advisers are
looking for a way to short-circuit the process.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Monday that the
administration is ``actively talking to a range of people who are
in leadership roles in this country about how we can get the right
course of action to occur.'' In other words: let's make a deal
about censure.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempts to reach some negotiated conclusion to the scandal
depend in large part on the public's attitude, as reflected in
upcoming polling. But as things stand, the public wants this to end
more quickly than it is likely to.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, in wringing its hands about the release and
airing of the videotape, tried to tap into public disgust with the
affair as well as the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said it was ``an unnecessary day in the life of our
country, an awful day.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a day brought on the nation by an irresponsible
president as much as an aggressive independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The tape also raises the question of how much humiliation this
president can take. And the answer, if the alternative is
relinquishing office, is a lot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
