<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPAN'S PRIME MINISTER CITES OTHERS' COSTLY ERRORS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan blamed his predecessor, the
nation's powerful Finance Ministry, and the heads of the country's
huge financial institutions for wasting years before the country
began to deal with its crippling banking crisis and a deep
recession that is worsening the world's economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's comments, in an interview as he prepared to address the
United Nations, was the first acknowledgment by a Japanese leader
that his country's leadership, both in government and in the
private sector, had made huge errors that have now ricocheted
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL PROMISES IN RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Russia's leaders offered assurances that the country's fiscal
crisis could be tamed without provoking high inflation or social
unrest. But few people seemed convinced. Neither President Boris
Yeltsin nor his new prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, has settled
on a choice for finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   NASA wants to spend up to $660 million over five years to bail
out its Russian partner in building a planned space station.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW AIRLINE-MARKETING LINK
</P>
<P>
   British Airways and American Airlines announced a new marketing
link called oneworld with Canadian Airlines, Qantas Airways and
Cathay Pacific. It is intended to compete with the Star Alliance
headed by Lufthansa and United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED MARTIN STOCK FALLS 5%
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Lockheed Martin fell 4.9 percent amid concern that the
world's largest military company is putting earnings at risk with
its $2.7 billion bid for Comsat. Created by the government, Comsat
is the U.S. gateway to Intelsat, among the world's largest
providers of commercial satellite services.
</P>
<P>
   A RIFT AT NATIONSBANC MONTGOMERY
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Weisel resigned as chairman and chief executive of
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities LLC after months of bitter
quarreling with his new bosses in Charlotte, N.C. Nationsbank
bought Montgomery Securities of San Francisco, which Weisel
founded, for $1.2 billion in October.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPS ELECTRONICS SHARES OFF 17 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Royal Philips Electronics shares fell 17 percent, to the
equivalent of $43, in Amsterdam after the company warned of a
significant decline in profits.
</P>
<P>
   CONCESSION OFFERED ON MERGER
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products and Monsanto offered to scale down their
proposed $37.8 billion merger to overcome European Union antitrust
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   BLAIR CALLS FOR NEW PROCEDURES
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain called for modernizing the
way of dealing with global economic turmoil. The International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank, which were created 54 years ago,
``were constructed for a world of fixed exchange rates and capital
controls, when capital flows were much smaller,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   RULE EASED ON CASH REPORTS
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department said it was trimming its requirements
for reporting large cash transactions to ease the paperwork load on
banks. Bankers will still be responsible for reporting any sign of
criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PRESSURES ON LABOR MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The tight labor market _ unemployment nationwide is just 4.5
percent _ has put new pressures on many economic hot spots like
Florida and California. BellSouth Telecommunications of Miami, for
example, says it took more than six months to fill 500 newly
created jobs.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURY BOND YIELDS DECLINE
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond yields declined for the fourth consecutive
session, with no significant economic reports to move the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
