<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-FLOJO-HNS &LR;      09-21 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FLOJO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER OLYMPIC CHAMPION `FLOJO' DIES AT AGE 38 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DANNY ROBBINS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Olympic sprinter Florence Griffith Joyner, who combined
speed and style a decade ago to become one of the most enduring
figures in her sport, died suddenly Monday in Southern California
at the age of 38.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Hector Rivera of the Orange County (Calif.) sheriff's office
said Griffith Joyner, who won three gold medals at the 1988
Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, had ``passed away during the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the sheriff's office, a 911 call was received early
Monday from Griffith Joyner's husband, Al Joyner, also an Olympic
gold medalist. Joyner reported that his wife was ``unresponsive and
not breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy was being conducted to determine the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Foster, a three-time world champion in the 110-meter
hurdles who was at one time engaged to Griffith Joyner, said he was
told by family members that Griffith Joyner died of a heart-related
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Griffith Joyner suffered a heart seizure on a
flight from California to St. Louis, where she was due to appear at
a track meet for high school athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her history of heart trouble, Griffith Joyner's death
was stunning news to those who knew her as ``FloJo'' and had seen
her dominate the women's sprints 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have to realize we're just people with a certain
talent,'' said Carl Lewis, who was a member of the 1984 and '88
U.S. Olympic teams with Griffith Joyner. ``It's a tremendous blow
to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner became a prominent figure on the world track and
field scene in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic Trials that year in Indianapolis, she lowered the
world record in the 100 meters to 10.49 seconds; no woman has
approached that time since. In Seoul, she captured gold medals in
the 100 and 200 meters (taking the final in 21.34, a world record
that also still stands) and the 400-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner's husband was the 1984 Olympic gold medalist in
the triple jump. Her sister-in-law, Jackie Joyner-Kersee, is a
six-time Olympic medalist and the world-record holder in the
heptathlon. Joyner-Kersee's husband, Bob Kersee, served as Griffith
Joyner's coach until after the 1988 Olympic Trials, when Al Joyner
took over the job.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, Griffith Joyner made a name for herself
with a style that included colorful, skin-tight bodysuits and long,
elaborately polished fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   One of the outfits she wore at the 1988 Olympic Trials was a
purple bodysuit with a bikini brief over it.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow American sprinter Gwen Torrence once said of Griffith
Joyner: ``If you're going to be wearing those outfits, you'd better
be doing something in them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, she painted three of her fingernails red, white and
blue. She painted a fourth gold, signifying her goal for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``She revolutionized the way athletes dress,'' said Craig
Masback, executive director of USA Track and Field. ``Her flair and
everything else she did captured the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The sleek outfits also underscored Griffith Joyner's
bodybuilder's physique _ a physique she did not appear to have in
1987, when her only medal at the world championships was a silver
in the 200 meters. Although the transformation led to talk of
steroid use, Griffith Joyner insisted she did not use
performance-enhancing drugs, and she never failed a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Ashford, who competed with Griffith Joyner in the sprints
throughout the 1980s, was still in awe of her rival's 1988 efforts
when she reminisced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever be able to put it in perspective,''
Ashford said. ``She just had a great year. I don't know what to
say. She changed the way a lot of people perceived the women's 100
meters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashford added that Griffith Joyner's performance in 1988 gave
track and field ``a flash and a flair that we didn't have, which
was probably good for the sport and got attention for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Primo Nebiolo, head of the International Amateur Athletic
Federation (track's international organizing body), said: ``I will
never forget this extraordinary athlete who stunned the world in
Seoul 10 years ago with her amazing sprints and spectacular
outfits. Sadly, her life has passed as rapidly as her races.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner retired from track and field after the Seoul
Games. She designed and modeled clothes, wrote children's books,
performed in movies and on television, endorsed products and was a
public speaker. One of her projects was designing uniforms for the
Indiana Pacers of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   She also served for a time as co-chair of the President's
Council on Physical Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she was flying from California to St. Louis when she
suffered a seizure. She was hospitalized for one day. At the
family's request, no other details were released.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner was accompanied on that trip by her husband and
the couple's daughter, Mary. They were traveling to the St. Louis
area to attend the Jackie Joyner-Kersee Relays for high school
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner grew up in the Watts section of Los Angeles in a
family of 11 children. She graduated from Jordan High School in Los
Angeles in 1978, attended Cal State Northridge for two years and
graduated from UCLA in 1983 with a degree in psychology. She and Al
Joyner were married in October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, issued a
statement calling Griffith Joyner's death a jolt to the sports
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence Griffith Joyner will be remembered among America's
greatest Olympians,'' he said, ``and she will be recalled with the
legends, like Wilma Rudolph and Babe Didrikson Zaharias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic movement is saddened and stunned by her passing.
She was a role model for young girls and women in sport, and her
legacy will be one that includes kindness and interest in children
and their dreams. `FloJo' will be missed tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a statement released in New York, also
noted Griffith Joyner's commitment to helping youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though she rose to the pinnacle of the world of sports, she
never forgot where she came from, devoting time and resources to
helping children _ especially those growing up in our most
disadvantaged neighborhoods _ make the most of their own talents,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer Scott Kaiser and The Associated Press contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
