<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     09-21 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LA, HER DEATH HITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Calif. _ Standing on the track where they trained
together for eight years, Jeanette Bolden talked about Florence
Griffith Joyner, the mercurial ``FloJo'' who died of apparent heart
seizure at the age of 38 Monday morning in Mission Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bolden and FloJo first met when they were in high school,
competing against one another in meets around Los Angeles. In the
late 1970s, they joined forces at Cal State-Northridge where they
lived and trained together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence could cook very, very well,'' said Bolden, now
women's track coach at UCLA. ``We looked forward to the nights when
it was her turn to cook. I remember one night she made seafood. I'm
allergic to seafood and my eyes got all swollen. She got me
sunglasses. I remember that. I remember the laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   All around Greater Los Angeles Monday, people were remembering
the laughter, the speed, the style, and the mystery of FloJo.
Griffith Joyner became a worldwide star when, often wearing
one-legged tights, she won three gold medals at the 1988 Seoul
Olympics. She was ``Flo Glo,'' but folks in Los Angeles still think
of her as the hometown girl who impressed and shocked the world.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner was born in LA, seventh of 11 children, and
raised in the rugged Jordan Housing Project of Watts. Her parents
split when she was 4, and two years later, riots almost burned
Watts to the ground. Still, in interviews before and after the '88
Games, Griffith Joyner recounted happy memories of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   She hooked up with Bolden at Cal State-Northridge and both moved
over to UCLA, where they helped the Bruins win a couple of NCAA
track championships. Bolden won a gold medal in the 1984 LA
Olympics, while FloJo settled for a silver in the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, FloJo shattered the 100-meter world record,
won three golds, and created a legacy with outrageous outfits that
made her an international star. She put women's sprinting on the
map, and two of her records (100 and 200) were still standing when
she died.
</P>
<P>
   On the UCLA campus, students were stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in the best shape of anybody in the world,'' said a
student standing outside Elvin C. Drake Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Mehlberg, a senior member of the track team, said, ``I
remember her running in the LA Olympics. It's shocking. She was so
young and seemed so fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolden, at 38 the same age as FloJo, said, ``I was pretty
shocked. Greg Foster called me at 7:30 this morning. I had talked
to Florence about three weeks ago. She had just come back from
overseas. She seemed fine.''
</P>
<P>
   FloJo is scheduled to be enshined in the UCLA Sports Hall of
Fame during a football game against Washington State at the Rose
Bowl in two weeks. She is one of 12 new inductees, and will take
her place alongside Bill Walton, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Jimmy
Connors, Dot Richardson, Rafer Johnson, Jackie Robinson, and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, in life and death, FloJo was stalked by rumors of illegal
substance use. She never failed a drug test, but her stunning
performances in Seoul prompted suspicion of anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Bolden, a good friend to the finish line, was evasive _ almost
Clintonesque _ in her response to speculation about steriods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what to say about that,'' said Bolden.
``Athletes are determined individuals. Anything other than that is
something I don't want to comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. If Bolden was convinced FloJo was 100 percent clean, it
would be easy to spike the speculation. Instead, she wavered,
making us wonder whether she fears what might come out. Bolden,
after all, is a championship track coach at a major university.
Good friend or no, she has to be able to answer to her young
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence was a very dedicated person,'' remembered Bolden.
``She's still a world record-holder and that's what athletes aspire
for. And, of course, her flair for fashion was always there. I
remember in high school, I saw her team and they were all in white
tights. They were the only team dressed like that and it was her
idea. It was the same when we lived and trained together. Before a
meet, everyone would be nervous, but Florence would be painting her
fingernails.''
</P>
<P>
   While she spoke on this gray Monday in Los Angeles, the UCLA
track was sprinkled with dozens of college athletes _ all of them
young women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
