<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7065 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-SECURITY-1STL     09-21 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-SECURITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.8 BILLION SOUGHT FOR SECURITY AT U.S. EMBASSIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Adds info. on balancing security needs against maintaining
accessibility of embassies; polishing and tightening throughout.)  
(See also TANZANIA-BOMBING) 
(js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration will ask Congress this
week for $1.8 billion for emergency security improvements at most
of the nation's 260 embassies and consulates worldwide, a
downpayment on protecting U.S. missions against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   That money, about twice the amount Congress has appropriated for
diplomatic security since 1985, reflects the administration's
conclusion that no country can be considered safe for U.S.
diplomats following the fatal bombings in East Africa last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the request is far below the full amount the State
Department has said is needed to modify or build embassies meeting
the security standards established in the 1980s. In 1985, the
department put the cost of converting or replacing all embassies at
$3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at the United Nations on Monday, President Clinton
spoke briefly of the new financing, saying that it would go ``to
repair our embassies, to improve security, to expand the worldwide
fight against terrorism, to help our friends in Kenya and Tanzania
with the wounds they have suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $1.8-billion request, which the White House is expected
to send to Congress on Tuesday, about $200 million would go toward
building embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
to replace those demolished in the Aug. 7 bombings. Because the
construction could take two to three years, the money would also
finance temporary missions.
</P>
<P>
   Also, $1.2 billion was earmarked for emergency security
improvements in embassies worldwide, including additional security
guards, video cameras and other equipment to enhance security,
particularly around the perimeters of diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the money would go toward reimbursing the
Pentagon for its costs in dealing with the bombings in East Africa;
increasing Secret Service protection of traveling U.S. dignitaries;
providing new anti-terrorism programs in countries where the United
States has diplomatic missions; and giving disaster relief for
Kenya and Tanzania, including payments to families of those killed
in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep big bombs from entering inside our compounds
and embassies, we'll reduce the risk of catastrophic collapses of
buildings,'' said an administration diplomatic security official.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are expected to approve the request, half the sum that
the administration had originally suggested it would seek.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides said the proposed upgrades are likely to
fall short of the recommended security standards the State
Department set in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't barricade our way out of this new terrorist threat,''
said a senior House Republican aide. He said ``we need better and
timely intelligence'' on terrorists like those believed to be
associated with Osama bin Laden, the exiled Saudi accused of
orchestrating the embassy bombings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The emergency spending request was based largely on reports by
diplomatic security experts at U.S. missions worldwide and by
counterterrorism experts dispatched by the administration to 30
embassies worldwide. Administration officials, speaking on
condition that they not be identified, described the spending
proposal to reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials refused to identify the most vulnerable
embassies and declined to give details about the countermeasures
that they planned to deter and detect terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the administration champions better security, U.S.
officials noted that they were trying to balance U.S. diplomats'
safety against their concerns of turning some compounds into
formidable fortresses. ``There's an inherent need for our people to
be accessible,'' said a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, White House and State Department officials have
negotiated with lawmakers over how much Congress would approve as
an emergency spending measure, and for what purposes.
Administration officials said Monday that after the first wave of
emergency improvements are made, other ongoing steps will be needed
to upgrade security in later appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Even with strong bipartisan support, discussion of how to
finance the new security measures could become entangled in a much
broader political brawl over how to spend the government's budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has argued that the new security measures
should be considered emergency spending. In reality, Clinton would
have to pay for the new measures by dipping into the budget
surplus. That would put him at odds with his pledge to save every
penny of the surplus to finance Social Security. It would also open
him to criticism from Republicans who want to use some of the
surplus for big tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal hawks on Capitol Hill vowed Monday to vote against the
embassy security measures unless they are paid for by cuts
elsewhere in the administration's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll certainly vote no, and will do everything in my power to
stop it,'' said Rep. Mark Neumann, R-Wis. and a member of the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind. and head of the Conservative Action
Team, a group of about 45 House Republicans, said through a
spokesman that he supports the bolstered diplomatic security but
would oppose paying for it with the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department survey conducted after the East Africa
bombings found that about 220 of the 260 embassies and consulates
fall short of security standards and need improvements, an
administration official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   From 60 percent and 70 percent of all U.S. diplomatic missions
need to be farther from busy streets or sidewalks, adding that the
embassy in London and the consulate in Bombay were especially
worrisome. They are both located on busy thoroughfares and ``may
need to be relocated,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
