<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COMMENTARY: DEATH AT 38: REVIEWING A VIBRANT LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, Bob Kersee and his wife, Jackie
Joyner-Kersee, had touched down in Los Angeles and were headed down
the freeway, headed toward the home that Jackie's brother, Al,
shared with his wife, Florence Griffith Joyner, and their 7-year
old daughter, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   They had taken this trip so many times for so many celebrations;
one triumph after another. The Joyners, the Griffiths, the Kersees.
This was a marriage of track nobility. Al Joyner, Jackie
Joyner-Kersee and Florence Griffth Joyner _ FloJo _ had shared so
many spectacular moments with each other, with the world. Now,
sudden and devastating news had ripped them all apart, and Monday's
trip down the freeway was one of the most dreaded drives of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, Jackie had received a phone call from
home. FloJo was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie's brother called her and said that he was trying to
wake her up this morning,'' Bob Kersee said from his car phone.
``He couldn't wake her up; they called 911, the paramedics came
out. She had passed away.''
</P>
<P>
   There was silence on the line. What do you say at a time like
this? Florence Griffith Joyner was always alive, always fresh,
always vibrant. She was also flamboyant and controversial.
</P>
<P>
   FloJo ran like the wind; critics said she was wind aided. FloJo
ran with power; they say it was drug aided. FloJo ran with style;
critics said that with six-inch fingernails and bodysuits, her
career was a triumph of style over substance.
</P>
<P>
   Now Florence Griffith Joyner is gone, dead at the age of 38, and
there is nothing else to say. As news of her sudden death spread,
the collective reaction was disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked,'' Kersee said. ``You don't expect to receive this
news, particular about one of your family members and an athlete
that you're coaching. You're just not prepared. It's pretty
difficult, it's devastating. Right now the family's got to come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kersee said that Al was so devastated that Mary, his daughter,
was the one who was calling people. ``When you've got a 6- or
7-year-old calling you and telling you that her mom's dead, it's
just difficult to take'' Kersee said.
</P>
<P>
   This month marks the 10-year anniversary of Joyner's stunning
performance at the Olympic Games. She won the 100- and 200-meter
races, breaking the world record in the 200. She had already set
the mark in the 100 in the Olympic trials. Each still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those triumphs also marked the beginning of a controversy
that followed her, as it turned out, to her grave. Suspicions arose
that her performance was enhanced by steroids. How could she make
such a leap to such fast times _ a silver medalist in 1984 at 200
yards to a gold medalist and record-holder four years later? One
runner accused her of using growth hormones. Florence Griffith
Joyner never failed a drug test, never tested positive. She denied
ever using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   She left the sport for three years after 1984 and came back
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   There were also the running suits _ purple, covered by turquoise
bikini briefs _ and the 6-inch fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that her time was in '84,'' Kersee said. ``I
thought her time was in 1988. That's what happens in sport: how you
handle a loss will determine how great a champion you are going to
be or what kind or perennial loser you're going to become. She
handled the loss in 1984 in a way that told me she wanted to be a
champion in 1988.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa earlier this month Marion Jones became the only
other woman to run the 200 in under 21.70. Some feel that Jones may
be FloJo's salvation, that once Jones breaks the record, critics
will believe that you can surpass records, or hit home runs,
without drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Kersee doesn't think the cloud will ever go away. ``To be
honest with you, no,'' he said. ``I think that people are going to
believe what they're going to believe. I thought that for a while.
People don't realize that what it comes down to desire and hard
work. There is something about human potential that we as humans
don't even understand about ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kersee said that over his career as a triner and coach, he hd
seen a lot athletes retire, some before their prime, some after
their prime. But the notion of losing his sister-in-law at such an
early age was hard to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to deal withe that part of life's reality,'' Kersee
said. ``It's a great athlete that passed away today, but more
importantly it's a great human being. It's a mother, it's a wife,
it's a sister. That's what hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
