<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-ALLIANCE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 AIRLINES IN MARKETING PACT TO RIVAL STAR ALLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Lower case for `oneworld' cq.) 
(nk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Frustrated by regulatory delays as the airline industry
forms global alliances, British Airways PLC, American Airlines and
three other carriers announced a new marketing linkup Monday that
is intended to challenge the Star Alliance, spearheaded by Deutsche
Lufthansa AG and the UAL Corporation's United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance _ called oneworld _ will not require regulatory
approval, the airlines say. It will link British Airways and
American Airlines, which is owned by the AMR Corp., with the
Canadian Airlines Corp., Qantas Airways Ltd. of Australia and
Cathay Pacific Airways of Hong Kong providing the group a long-term
reach into Asia despite that region's economic free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it's not a fantastic time for the region at the
moment, but long term it's positive,'' said Andrew Light, an
airlines analyst at Salomon Smith Barney here.
</P>
<P>
   AMR already owns one-third of Canadian Airlines, and British
Airways has a stake of roughly 25 percent in Qantas.
</P>
<P>
   Along with franchise and partner airlines, the five carriers
will serve a total of 632 destinations in 138 countries. Last year
they carried 174 million passengers among them and employed 220,000
people. They will operate a total of 1,524 aircraft, according to
British Airways, which added that the arrangement would not mean
job losses for its staff of 60,500.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership rivals the slightly larger Star Alliance, which,
along with Lufthansa and United, embraces Thai Airways
International, Varig Brazilian Airlines SA, Air Canada and
Scandinavian Airlines System. Air New Zealand plans to join that
alliance next year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ayling, the British Airways chief executive, said at a
news conference that the new grouping was not a substitute for
British Airways' more far-reaching alliance with American Airlines,
which has been awaiting regulatory approval for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The new tie-in does not involve equity swaps and, unlike the
Star Alliance, will not initially offer code-sharing _ the system
by which one airline sells seats on allied airlines' flights, thus
drawing revenue from one another and facilitating the transfer of
passengers among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marketing agreement,'' said David Turnbull, chief
executive of Cathay Pacific, Asia's second-largest airline.
``Code-sharing requires regulatory approval. We want to work
together for a while first.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, questioned the effectiveness of the
alliance without code-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement nonetheless reflects the trend among airlines to
widen their reach through alliances that do not require investment
and that are expected to create a handful of huge, global
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's competition watchdogs raised no immediate
objections to the new alliance but did not exclude intervention
later if they found its operations to be hostile to competition _
as some of its critics already contend.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Branson, chairman of the Virgin Group of Britain, which
owns Virgin Airlines, criticized the new agreement because of its
dominance on routes to Australia and Hong Kong and suggested that
Virgin might also seek alliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the consumer's point of view, it can't be good news,''
Branson told a television interviewer. ``Instead of oneworld you
could say: one company.''
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the announcement brought little if any relief:
British Airways shares, which are well down from a high closing
price of 703 pence on July 7 and have persistently underperformed
London's FTSE index, lost 25 pence Monday to close at 386 pence.
Cathay Pacific shares rose by 30 cents, to $6.75 (Hong Kong).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the participants, the tie-in will link the five
carriers' frequent-flier programs and enable them to reduce costs
through shared baggage-handling and other ground services, along
with linked reservation and flight-scheduling systems. Other
airlines thought likely to join the alliance include Iberia Lineas
Aereas SA of Spain, Finnair of Finland and Hong Kong Dragon
Airlines. The Japan Airlines Company rejected membership,
participants said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next year, the participants said, the tie-in will offer
passengers smoother transfers among flights on the five carriers.
It will also strengthen networks in Asia, where airlines are
looking for strong growth after the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As a brand name, oneworld will supplement, but not replace, the
five carriers' existing logos. ``These are airlines with incredibly
strong brands and brands that work well in the marketplace,'' said
Donald Carty, the chairman of American Airlines. ``We're not going
to damage these brands.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the participants put a figure to their expectations of
increased profit.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Star Alliance, which includes Varig, the oneworld
lineup does not include a South American carrier. It is apparently
relying on American Airlines' routes to penetrate the region.
</P>
<P>
   While oneworld is separate from the British Airways-American
Airlines alliance, some analysts said the continuing regulatory
challenges to that arrangement could hamper the new linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Office of Fair Trading has urged that the two airlines
should be allowed to sell off, rather than surrender, 267 weekly
landing and takeoff slots in return for approval of their alliance.
But the European Commission maintains that such sales would be
unlawful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
