<SLUG> BC-TV-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS DECIDE CLINTON VIDEO GOOD TELEVISION, AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhat to their surprise, the broadcast networks joined their
cable brethren Monday in televising President Clinton's grand jury
testimony, rather than simply airing excerpts as they had planned.
</P>
<P>
   The chief reason: a transcript of Clinton's videotaped testimony
that was delivered to the networks just a few minutes before they
began broadcasting it. Armed with the transcript, the networks were
able to ascertain in advance that the testimony was not as sexually
explicit as they feared.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the networks simply found that the four hours of
presidential testimony about Clinton's relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky made for good television. (Not everyone agreed: Boston
television stations were deluged with hundreds of calls from
viewers complaining that their favorite soap operas had been
preempted).
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that only NBC broke away from the testimony,
declining to broadcast two segments where prosecutors asked Clinton
about particular sexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a holiday, with a lot of families together and a lot of
young children potentially watching, we just decided to err on the
side of conservatism,'' said Beth O'Connell, executive producer of
special events for NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   When NBC broke away, WHDH-Channel 7, the Boston NBC affiliate,
immediately switched to CNN's coverage. ``We wanted to make sure
our viewers could have the choice to decide if they wanted to turn
down the sound,'' said Channel 7 news director Mark Berryhill. ``We
just wanted the best coverage, whether that comes from NBC or
CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the segments of four and six minutes, respectively,
NBC aired the rest of Clinton's testimony. ABC and CBS broadcast it
in its entirety, along with the cable networks CNN, MSNBC, Fox News
Channel, and C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   For the broadcast networks, it was a day of scrambling to keep
ahead of the videotape. Even as the testimony was broadcast to a
national audience, network personnel raced through hundreds of
pages of transcript. At NBC, O'Connell said, a news division vice
president, numerous correspondents and producers, and even the
network ombudsman were enlisted in the network's ``very elaborate
system'' for reading the transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which had planned last week to air only the first five
minutes of Clinton's testimony before cutting away and then airing
excerpts, ended up broadcasting the entire testimony unedited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it started, it was simply more compelling than we thought
it was going to be,'' acknowledged ABC spokeswoman Eileen Murphy.
``And there was really less explicit and graphic material than we
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, although ABC employed a 5-second delay so it could edit
out anything the network deemed offensive, no editing occurred. The
network did air an onscreen advisory warning of ``graphic sexual
content.''
</P>
<P>
   The availability of a transcript made the decision easier at
CBS, which last week said it would make no decision on airing the
testimony until network executives got a look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the feed of the tape started coming in, we had a
transcript, so we were able to look ahead and get a sense of what
was in the tape,'' said CBS spokeswoman Sandy Genelius.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony videotape was broken up into seven parts; CBS
aired the first three parts live, the next three with a 10-second
delay and an advisory warning of ``strong language and sexual
content,'' and the last part live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
