<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EVIDENCE-BOS &LR;      09-21 1560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPED CLINTON SHOWN FIGHTING FOR POLITICAL SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, in a videotape destined to
provide an enduring image for history, described Monica Lewinsky as
a ``good young woman with a good mind and a good heart,'' even
while repeatedly lashing out at his political opponents for trying
to ``take a wrecking ball'' to his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give anything in the world not to be here talking about
it,'' Clinton somberly said of his affair with Lewinsky, in the
videotape of his federal grand jury testimony released Monday.
``I'd give anything in the world not to be admitting what I've had
to admit today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning spectacle: The president of the United States,
his cheeks flared pink and his forehead glistening, seeking legal
meaning in word tenses, evading grand jurors' questions, and
dancing around his own awkward definition of sexual relations _ one
based on a definition given him by Paula Jones's lawyers, which did
not include oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared at turns amiable and angry, confident and concerned,
but at no point, predictions to the contrary, did he lose his famed
temper on camera. He sipped Diet Coke, Canada Dry ginger ale, and a
tumbler filled with ice water, and much of the four hours and three
minutes of videotape was interesting to watch, but produced few
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   From this testimony and the seven months of investigation that
led to it, Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr sent a detailed
report to Congress on Sept. 9 outlining 11 possible grounds for
Clinton's impeachment. Among the allegations were a series of
perjury counts, including one accusation that Clinton lied about
the nature and extent of his sexual relationship with Lewinsky
before the federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The footage of Clinton's testimony, taken on Aug. 17 in the
White House Map Room and beamed to the grand jury room across town,
was fed directly to an international audience Monday morning by at
least four cable television networks that broadcast it in its
entirety. It was part of a massive public release of information
from the House Judiciary Committee, including Lewinsky's own
sexually explicit testimony to the grand jury in August.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid, uncensored release of the tape and the accompanying
transcripts marked a significant risk by Republican leaders on
Capitol Hill, who faced the possibility of angering an uncertain
public increasingly wary of the criticism of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic allies and White House aides immediately said the
airing of Clinton's testimony might boost his public standing,
because it shows a relatively composed president persevering
despite an onslaught of invasive and sexually explicit questions
from prosecutors bent on cornering and embarrassing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't like to see a president go through this, but
at the same time I don't think most people learned anything new
about this matter,'' said Michael McCurry, the White House press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans agreed that little new was learned from the
videotape, given the numerous leaks and the prior publication of
the Starr report, and, in the words of one, no ``knockout blow''
was delivered. Still, others said Clinton's sometimes artless
interpretation of the definition of sexual relations and his
curious reliance on word tenses and meanings would show him to be
the conniver that critics have called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After viewing this videotape, no reasonable person could
conclude that the president did not knowingly lie to the grand jury
and to the court,'' said Representative Bob Barr a Georgia
Republican and a member of the House Judiciary Committee. Barr has
long sought Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa voiced a concern that many
others on Capitol Hill have kept private: That Clinton is afflicted
with some more consequential disorder than irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming around to the belief that there's something deeper
here, that the president maybe has something wrong with him in
terms of how he approaches this,'' Harkin said in an interview with
a Des Moines television station. ``I don't know whether it's an
illness or something like that, but I don't know how else to
explain what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his testimony by pulling a folded sheet of paper
out of his jacket pocket, putting on a pair of reading glasses, and
reading a statement to prosecutors and grand jury members
acknowledging for the first time his relationship with Lewinsky,
despite seven months of adamant denials that preceded his
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I engaged in conduct that was wrong,'' he said. ``These
encounters did not consist of sexual intercourse. They did not
constitute sexual relations, as I understood that term to be
defined at my Jan. 17, 1998 deposition'' in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they did involve inappropriate, intimate contact,''
Clinton said, reading from his notes. ``These inappropriate
encounters ended at my insistence in early 1997. I also had
occasional telephone conversations with Ms. Lewinsky that included
inappropriate sexual banter. I regret that what began as a
friendship came to include this conduct. And I take full
responsibility for my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, he refused to elaborate on the extent of his
sexual contact with Lewinsky, though he implied that he received
oral sex from the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm not trying to be evasive here,'' Clinton said. ``I'm
trying to protect my privacy, my family's privacy.'' At another
point Clinton added that he was trying ``to preserve the dignity of
the office I hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in an assertion that likely led to one of Starr's perjury
allegations, Clinton contradicted Lewinsky's testimony that he
repeatedly fondled her breasts and other parts of her body, in
effect denying any sexual touching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not my recollection,'' Clinton said. ``My recollection
is that I did not have sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky. And I'm
staying on my former statement about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At another time, asked how he could fail to believe that oral
sex does not fall within the definition of sexual relations,
Clinton pointed to the definition of sexual relations used when he
was deposed on January 17 in the Jones suit and maintained that,
under its terms, a person receiving oral sex is not involved in
sexual relations. In the Jones case, sexual relations was defined
as the touching of the breasts, buttocks, and genitalia for the
purposes of arousing or gratifying a partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if the deponent is the person who has oral sex
performed on him, then the contact is not with anything on that
list, but with the lips of another person,'' Clinton said. ``It
seems to be self-evident that that's what it is. Let me remind you,
sir, I read this carefully. And I thought about it. I thought about
what `contact' meant. I thought about what `intent to arouse or
gratify' meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed to become angriest when he repeatedly diverted
the topic to Jones and her team of financial supporters who have
pursued her sexual harassment case for several years. The case was
dismissed by a federal judge on April 1, in a decision that is now
under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the Jones case that Clinton was first asked about his
relationship with Lewinsky. At the time, he denied having sexual
contact with her and said he could not recall ever being alone with
her at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal in this deposition was to be truthful, but not
particularly helpful,'' Clinton said in the grand jury appearance.
``I did not wish to do the work of the Jones lawyers. I deplored
what they were doing. I deplored the innocent people they were
tormenting and traumatizing. I deplored their illegal leaking. I
deplored the fact that once they knew our evidence, that this was a
bogus lawsuit, and that becuse of the funding they had from my
political enemies, they were pushing ahead. I deplored it. but I
was determined to walk through the minefield of this deposition
without violating the law. And I believe I did.''
</P>
<P>
   At various points throughout the appearance, Clinton essentially
acknowledged that he realized his affair would eventually become
public, displaying a penchant for risk that has both baffled and
infuriated his closest allies in the White House. The affair was
conducted during his 1996 reelection campaign and could have
potentially crippled his efforts if discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that the minute there was no longer any contact, she
would talk about this,'' Clinton said, somewhat matter of factly.
``She would have to. She couldn't help it. It was, it was a part of
her psyche. So, I had put myself at risk, sir. I was not trying to
buy her silence or get Vernon Jordan to buy her silence. I thought
she was a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke of Lewinsky only in flattering terms. He seemed
contemptuous when he spoke of former Lewinsky colleague Linda Tripp
as having ``stabbed her in the back'' by secretly recording
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Clinton and his personal attorney, David Kendall,
seemed to foreshadow the events that were to come, hinting that
they expected the videotape would someday be released, even though
grand jury testimony is secret by law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
