<SLUG> BC-FEDS-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS ARREST WOULD-BE SUCCESSOR TO MISSING MOBSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY AND PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A reputed gangster who allegedly muscled his way into
the South Boston drug business in the absence of fugitive crime
boss James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger was nabbed Monday in a cocaine
sting.
</P>
<P>
   Philip J. Myers, 44, a convicted bank robber and killer, and
reputed leader of a violent white supremacist group rooted in
federal prisons, faces drug charges that could send him to prison
for 10 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken a foothold in Southie,'' said a source familiar
with the investigation. ``He's moved right in. Even the bad guys
want him off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Myers' arrest, a federal indictment was unsealed
charging his brother, Paul Myers, and Stephen A. ``Buttsy'' Carr,
both 43 and of Boston's Charlestown section, with conspiring to
distribute cocaine and related charges. They appeared in federal
court and were ordered held pending a detention hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Myers brothers are members of Teamsters Local 25 and work at
the loading dock at the Boston Herald. Paul Myers was arrested
shortly before noon Monday near the newspaper's loading dock.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests followed an investigation by the federal Drug
Enforcement Administration, &UR;  &LR; the US Housing and Urban Development's
Inspector General's office, the Department of Corrections,
Somerville, Everett and Cambridge Police.
</P>
<P>
   The Myers brothers allegedly operated their drug business out of
the Mishawam &UR;  &LR; housing development in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, an unidentified witness who was cooperating with the
DEA met with Philip Myers _ a meeting recorded on video and audio
tape _ and told Myers that he knew of a drug trafficker who
regularly stored packages of cocaine in his car, according to an
affidavit filed by DEA Special Agent Joseph W. Desmond.
</P>
<P>
   The witness told Myers that his brother, Paul, had mentioned
that Myers might be interested in stealing one of the shipments.
Philip Myers signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, DEA agents parked a maroon Mercedes in the parking lot
of the Best Western Hotel in Cambridge and placed a package large
enough to hold six kilograms of cocaine inside.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the package, Philip Myers was arrested on a
complaint charging him with attempting to possess cocaine with
intent to distribute.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Myers, a tall, lanky man with brown hair and a droopy
mustache, shuffled into federal court in shackles, wearing a baggy
blue jersey and black shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US Attorney George W. Vien said the government wants
Myers jailed without bail pending trial on the grounds that he
would pose a danger if released and might flee the area.
</P>
<P>
   US Magistrate Judge Robert B. Collings, who scheduled a
detention hearing for Thursday, told Myers that they had met 23
years ago when Collings _ then an assistant US attorney _ had
prosecuted Myers for bank robbery. He volunteered to recuse himself
from the case, but Myers' attorney, Frederick Ford, said that would
not be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt 23 years ago you were fair and would be so today,''
Ford said, quoting Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Myers was a promising young hockey player when he was
arrested by Boston Police in July 1974 for possession of a
sawed-off shotgun. Two months later he was charged with bank
robbery, and later convicted and sentenced to 13 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Myers was paroled. But a month later, he was charged
with trying to kill a Boston Police officer after threatening to
blow his head off. The parole violation was enough to send Myers
back to federal prison to finish his bank robbery sentence.
</P>
<P>
   While in a federal penitentiary in Memphis, Myers killed an
inmate on Feb. 9, 1982 over a cocaine debt. The victim, Steven
Horvath, had bought cocaine from Myers in prison, but failed to pay
him, according to federal court records.
</P>
<P>
   Myers was convicted by a jury of voluntary manslaughter and
sentenced to an additional eight years in prison. He was sent to
the federal penitentiary in Marion, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In a federal appeals court decision denying Myers' request for
appeal, the court wrote that Myers struck Horvath in the head and
neck with a sharpened steel rod and ``one of the blows from the rod
or `shank' went into Horvath's skull, through his brain and into
his brain stem.''
</P>
<P>
   While in federal prison, according to sources, Myers was
recruited by the Aryan Brotherhood and eventually became a leader
in the white supremacist group that boasts about 2,000 members
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Killing is an integral part of gang membership, according to a
federal inmate who prepared a detailed report on the Aryan
Brotherhood for the government during the 1981 trial of a leader of
the gang.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Myers was released from federal prison in June 1993, then
served the rest of his state sentence in Cedar Junction in Walpole.
He became a free man in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past year, Philip Myers teamed up with a crew from
South Boston that had been challenging a crew loyal to Bulger for
control of the area, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   It was Myers' brazenness and his reputation for violence that
made him a prime target of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had enormous influence,'' said a source familiar with the
investigation. ``He was using intimidation and threats. You drive a
rod through somebody's brain and word gets around pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellement and Mitchell Zuckoff of the Globe Staff
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
