<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDIT TESTIFIES IN BOEING DISCRIMINATION LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing Chairman Phil Condit was the witness the TV
cameras were waiting for at the federal courthouse in Seattle
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the courtroom, Condit was upstaged by the company's
former director of Equal Opportunity, Viola Keith, who accused
Boeing's lawyers of trying to slant her testimony in the racial
discrimination lawsuit brought by Jesse Jones against the aerospace
giant.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's lawyers immediately denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Although it seemed like a bombshell at the time, Judge Edward
Rafeedie said Keith's allegations would essentially require a new
trial; he ruled at the end of the day that they would not be
admissible.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jones, a former manager in security investigations for
Boeing, sued the company alleging the company discriminated against
him by denying him raises and promotions and retaliating against
him after he complained about it.
</P>
<P>
   Though Keith is still receiving $89,000 per year from Boeing,
she said she had been relieved of her duties after her deposition
did not support the company's position in the case, and is now ``on
loan'' to the Urban League. She was called as a witness friendly to
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black suit and white blouse, Keith testified
calmly, waiting while Boeing attorney Lawrence Hannah and Jones
attorney John Sheridan sparred repeatedly over what Sheridan could
ask. Hannah wanted to limit Keith's testimony only to things she
had seen and heard, and Sheridan wanted her opinions, feelings,
professional knowledge and anything else helpful. At one point,
Keith cried out, ``I don't know what I can say and what I can't
say.''
</P>
<P>
   But she continued, and at noon, Judge Edward Rafeedie let the
jury leave for lunch. Keith stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers weren't quite finished. Sheridan said that one
of Keith's comments suggested that she had been ``pressured to
change her testimony.'' He wanted to know more.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing attorney Lawrence Hannah leapt to his feet, ``That's
nonsense and a flat-out lie, Your Honor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan suggested they ask Keith. She was standing right there.
</P>
<P>
   The judge put Keith back on the stand, out of the presence of
the jury and asked whether she had ever been pressured to change
her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that during my deposition by Mr. Hannah and Ms. Clarke
that they would prefer that I not be forthcoming with the truth,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rafeedie asked her to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your honor, no one is going to come out and ask you to lie in
a court of law,'' Keith said. What the Boeing attorneys had said,
Keith asserted, was ``You don't have to say this,'' and ``You could
say this,'' and ``Maybe you could take a trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge snapped back, ``Who told you that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Clarke,'' said Keith, referring to Boeing co-counsel Joan
Clarke of the Perkins Coie firm.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke spoke up. ``Your Honor, that's outrageous!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What else did she tell you?'' Rafeedie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was anyone present when she told you this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.'' Keith said she had heard it during preparation for her
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The judge questioned Keith a second time. She told the same
story, adding that she had told John Curry in Boeing's legal
department about the inappropriate suggestions. She said the
company had known of all this.
</P>
<P>
   Rafeedie was angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All witnesses are prepared for testimony,'' the judge said.
``Even President Clinton. But they are not prepared to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the trial, Boeing seemed to realize the bombshell
nature of Keith's testimony and issued a brief comment to
reporters:
</P>
<P>
   ``Through an independent investigation into allegations brought
by Ms. Keith, including those shared in court today, it was
determined by the independent investigator that at no time did
outside counsel act improperly or pressure Ms. Keith into
testifying untruthfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the independent investigator, in her report, states
Ms. Keith denied that she had ever been instructed not to be
truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said the investigator is an African
American attorney who works at a Seattle firm other than Perkins
Coie or Davis Wright Tremaine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Boeing's chairman, Condit, dressed in a blue
suit, strode rapidly to the witness stand and began answering
Sheridan's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he had met with Jesse Jones in September 1996 for
about an hour. But he couldn't remember much about the meeting.
(Condit said later on the courthouse steps, ``That was a drop-in
visit. I have an open-door policy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he did not recall instructing the other Boeing
person at that meeting, Michael Stewart, vice-president for
employee relations, to ``fix it,'' as Jones has said in
depositions. The Boeing chief executive said, ``That would surprise
me. That would not be the way I would approach the problem. I just
don't say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he did not recall saying to Stewart after the
meeting that he did not want executive protection from a man as
emotional, unstable and intense as Jones, as is indicated by a
document from Stewart. ``I have no memory of that at all, and it
does not sound like anything I would say,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Condit had apparently been e-mailed by Jones several times
later in 1996. Jones was complaining about Stewart's investigation
and asking Condit to step in. Those e-mails were not answered, and
were instead forwarded to Stewart. Condit said they had probably
been forwarded by a screener. ``Any e-mails that come to me, with
the exception of a very few people, get reviewed first. I have
someone who reads all of that and forwards it and responds for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it your practice to forward complaints such as this without
reading them?'' Sheridan asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases _ in most cases, yes,'' Condit said. ``If I had
to look at every single piece of information that came in, that's
all I would do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The one note of levity in Condit's testimony was when Sheridan
asked him about how big Boeing is, how many airplanes it is
building and how much money it makes. Wasn't it true, Sheridan
said, that the company has forecasted double digit profits?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Condit, in one of his few flat-out denials. ``I
would love that. But we aren't. There are almost no companies in
the world that make that kind of profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2206EDT &QL; 
