u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PERJURY-1STLD     09-21 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PERJURY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ARE THE LIES IMPEACHABLE OFFENSES? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Correcting typo in 17th graf, quote by Rep. Zoe Lofgren) 
(JT) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the nation watched President Clinton on
videotape Monday, many members of Congress on both sides of the
aisle had already decided that he lied under oath. Now the
question, which Congress is already starting to debate, is whether
that is grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, certainly
seemed to think so. In his report to Congress, he held that perjury
and obstruction of justice by any citizen ``are profoundly serious
matters'' and that ``when such acts are committed by the president
of the United States, we believe these acts `may constitute grounds
for an impeachment.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the Constitution's description of an impeachable offense as
treason, bribery and other ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' is
subject to continual reinterpretation.
</P>
<P>
   That constitutional ambiguity has sent Congress looking through
precedent, law, public opinion polls and Clinton's parsings to
decide whether his attempt to cover up his affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky should bring his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said Monday: ``The president cannot
go before a grand jury and say things that are not true. What will
happen to the rule of law if he did that?''
</P>
<P>
   But he is only one member of the House Judiciary Committee,
which is in the vanguard of impeachment deliberations. And while
many members of the committee now say they are certain to recommend
that the House open an impeachment inquiry, the spectrum among its
36 members shows that the ultimate decision on whether to impeach
Clinton is not likely to be clear or easy.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the preponderant view in Congress that Clinton lied.
But is that perjury? Not every committee member agrees. Nor do all
members of the Judiciary Committee put the same weight on the
president's deposition in the sexual harassment case brought by
Paula Corbin Jones as on the four hours of grand jury testimony,
which was broadcast Monday. In fact, some members of Congress are
asking whether a perjury case based on Clinton's Jones deposition
is one that most prosecutors would bring to court.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., draws a distinction, for example,
between Clinton's testimony before the grand jury and his earlier
deposition in the Jones case. The Jones civil case was ultimately
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always bothered me,'' said Graham, a Judiciary
Committee member who was once an Air Force prosecutor. ``Would I as
a prosecutor spend time and money to prosecute a guy who lies in a
deposition in a case that was dismissed?
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to set the standard that if the average citizen
engaged in like conduct they would have severe legal
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida, one of Graham's Republican
colleagues, does not share his qualms about the Jones deposition.
``I have no doubt in my mind, based on other cases,'' McCollum
said, ``that it doesn't make any difference if the case was thrown
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the other side, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., is not even
certain that a prosecutor would bring a perjury case against
Clinton based on the grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, `he said, she said,''' Nadler said. He noted that Starr
had presumed that Ms. Lewinsky had been the one telling the truth
when her testimony deviated from the president's. ``It's all based
on Monica Lewinsky's testimony,'' he said. While Starr found that
Ms. Lewinsky's testimony matched contemporaneous accounts she gave
to 11 friends of her affair, Nadler said that she may have been
exaggerating to all her friends.
</P>
<P>
   To sort through precedent and the Framers' intent, the
Republican and Democratic staffs of the Judiciary Committee have
independently given their members extensive legal research. The
panel's members say they are studying the writings of legal
scholars, the report on impeachment drawn up by the Judiciary
Committee staff in the Watergate proceedings and other documents.
But impeachment proceedings have been so infrequent that even these
materials can lead to different interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., who was an aide to the House
Judiciary Committee in 1974, has posted on her Web site the 1974
report on Constitutional Grounds for Presidential Impeachment. In a
sign of her own thinking, she pointed her constituents toward its
observations and its conclusion as ``pretty relevant today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all presidential misconduct is sufficient to constitute
grounds for an impeachment,'' that 1974 report concluded. ``Because
impeachment of a President is a grave step for the nation, it is
predicated only upon conduct seriously incompatible with either the
constitutional form and principles of our government or the proper
performance of constitutional duties of Presidential office.''
</P>
<P>
   That might seem to suggest that evasions about illicit sex would
not rise to the level of impeachment. But Canady looks elsewhere
for a model: the precedent set by Congress in the impeachment and
conviction of Judge Walter Nixon of federal district court in
Mississippi in 1989 for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had been criminally convicted of lying to a grand jury
about his talks with a prosecutor in a marijuana-smuggling case. He
had been accused of concealing his attempt to help the son of a
business partner. ``He was impeached and removed from office
because he committed perjury,'' Canady said, ``and the interesting
thing is he committed perjury before a grand jury on matters where
if he simply told the truth there would have been no legal
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Should a judicial impeachment be considered relevant to a
president? Federal judges are not elected but under the
Constitution have lifetime tenure subject to ``good behavior'' in
office. ``It's certainly the case that impeaching a judge and
impeaching a president has two different standards,'' said Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
