<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEMEANOR-AZR &LR;      09-21 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMEANOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TESTIMONY DOESN'T MATCH THE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For days, the White House said it was bracing for
public reaction to the broadcast of President Clinton's sometimes
defiant, sometimes elusive grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But both in its tone and probable impact, the testimony turned
out not to be the tinderbox it was hyped up to be.
</P>
<P>
   The president showed flashes of indignation, waving his hand or
index finger at the camera. Gesturing so emphatically may have been
a tactical error, recalling as it did his infamous, finger-wagging
statement in January that he ``did not have sexual relations with
that woman, Miss (Monica) Lewinsky.'' He later conceded to an
``improper'' relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, what Americans saw on television Monday was their
president sweating.
</P>
<P>
   This was a chief executive unaccompanied by the usual totems of
his office. He shifted uncomfortably in his chair, his eyes darted
from side to side as he awaited his swearing-in. His face appeared
pinched.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, had earlier accused
House Republicans of releasing the videotape to ``embarrass the
president.'' The media reported White House anxiety at Americans
seeing a testy Clinton answering prosecutors' questions.
</P>
<P>
   But when the tape was shown, it was clear that the White House
and the news media had overstated the potential for damage.
Compared to what the public had been led to believe about Clinton's
temper, he emerged from the deposition relatively unscathed. The
president generally managed to hold his anger beneath the surface,
making him appear firm but not overtly hostile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read a lot of things about what the president's demeanor
would be and how the whole thing would look on television, and it
did not match any of that advance speculation,'' said White House
Press Secretary Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   The video, which was taped at the White House on Aug. 17, seemed
more likely to reinforce existing opinions about the president than
to change minds, according to lawmakers of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political scientist, said
a White House official told him Monday that the White House had
deliberately tried to overstate Clinton's anger on the tape so they
could later say it wasn't so bad, after all.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House did not confirm such a strategy, Sabato
said the official, whom he would not name, ```was bragging about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the White House) won the PR spin, no question about it.
It's an old political trick,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the White House may have, at least temporarily,
slowed impeachment momentum on Capitol Hill by minimizing the
tape's damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is the reaction (to the videotape) will be less
significant than news people over the weekend were suggesting it
might be,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways Clinton's demeanor was difficult to pin down. He
was often slippery in a legal sense, insisting his intimate
activities with Lewinsky didn't qualify as ``sexual relations''
under the definition he adhered to.
</P>
<P>
   In one exchange, the president quibbled about the definition of
the word ``is'' regarding a previous statement by one of his
attorneys suggesting there ``is no sex of any kind'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what the meaning of the word `is' is,'' said
Clinton, a Yale-educated lawyer and former Arkansas attorney
general and governor.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans seized on Clinton's word plays as evidence he
had something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, said Clinton had invoked ``minute areas of the law which
to the average person just sound absolutely ludicrous and silly.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all of Clinton's testimony relied on legal intricacies.
He may even have elicited some sympathy by depicting himself to the
grand jurors as a defender of the youthful, idealistic Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been accused by Lewinsky in prosecutors' documents
of using her for an affair, and then dumping her.
</P>
<P>
   But on the videotape, he testified that ``she's a good young
woman with a good heart and a good mind.'' He said, ``It breaks my
heart that she was ever involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also may have scored public-relations points by saying
his chief accusers are politically motivated, and by invoking his
privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm not trying to be evasive here,'' Clinton testified.
``I'm trying to protect my privacy, my family's privacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show many Americans, while believing Clinton did something
wrong, are tired of the whole spectacle. The White House was hoping
that four hours of testimony pushed the public past the saturation
point.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Barker can be reached at 202-662-7264 or via e-mail at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
