<SLUG> BC-NY-GLOBAL-SUMMIT-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY RELISHES VISIT FROM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jay Oliva, the president of New York University,
likes to describe the school as a reflection of the city: a world
compressed into a village that is at once neighborly, multicultural
and second to none when it comes to self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that if you're doing something interesting,
you ought to tell people about it,'' Oliva said. ``And if you're
blowing your own horn, do it loudly. There's no sense giving it a
little toot.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrappy university, always looking to raise its profile in
the intensely competitive world of higher education, made some big
noise Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The NYU School of Law played host to President Clinton and
Hillary Rodham Clinton, as well as other stars of the political and
academic worlds, at a forum on globalization just as the
president's videotaped testimony before the Starr grand jury was
released to the public on network and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Some university officials had worried that the latest disclosure
from the independent counsel's investigation might upstage what the
law school called its ``megasummit,'' which was beamed by satellite
to 20 universities around the United States and in Europe and
simultaneously shown live over the NYU Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But having Clinton and the first lady on campus at a time when
dozens of American and foreign journalists were on hand to
scrutinize their every move, exchange and reaction, turned out to
be a happy convergence of events for the university.
</P>
<P>
   The place was packed, monied alumni were in great abundance, and
Clinton joined such political figures as Prime Ministers Tony Blair
of Britain and Romano Prodi of Italy in expressing effusive thanks
for having been invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is literally a unique moment on this extraordinary day,''
responded John Sexton, the dean of the law school, who had
conceived of and organized the high-profile event.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton, who described himself as ``the P.T. Barnum of legal
education,'' said the forum, which was called Strengthening
Democracy in the Global Economy, was meant to showcase what the
school calls its global law school initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The global law program was created five years ago, he said, and
incorporated into the traditional NYU Law School to infuse the
school with an international outlook that takes into account the
increasing globalization of political and economic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Sexton said, his colleagues at other schools
teased him that he was dean of ``the first intergalactic law
school.''
</P>
<P>
   But by hiring top foreign legal experts from the Middle East,
Asia and Europe, and revamping the way some law subjects are
taught, he said, New York University's law school has become a
pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now clear we went to a place where the rest of legal
education is going to strive to be five or 10 years from now,''
Sexton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the daylong forum, which featured three panel
discussions on civil society, economics and democracy, ``is a
visible manifestation'' of what the law school has been doing on a
less glittery scale.
</P>
<P>
   Oliva, the NYU president, said that the university had begun
organizing the forum less than two months ago, and that from the
start, it was to revolve around the Clintons.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Life around Washington Square, across from the law school, came
to a standstill for the day. The western half of the square was
closed, several Greenwich Village streets were closed to traffic
and the streets around the law school were clogged with enormous
vans that held the digital production equipment needed to broadcast
the forum by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Several students who had won a lottery for seats to watch the
forum on closed-circuit television in the law school said they had
the technical advantage of seeing Clinton twice _ and in any order
they wished. The forum was beamed into dormitory rooms and student
centers on the university network, while the presidential testimony
was available on commercial television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the Clinton videotape on TV all morning,'' said
Jasmine Campirides, a third-year student who attended a panel
session to see the president. ``And I have a VCR, so I taped the
first panel from the forum so I can watch it at home later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
