<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-21 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY LESSONS IN TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ What's this? The Ryan Minor Era has come and gone
already?
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from his 1-for-3 showing against the Yankees Sunday night,
the former University of Oklahoma basketball star was riding the
pine again at SkyDome Monday night. The old guy with the thinning
gray hair was back in the lineup, batting sixth and playing third
base. For those of you counting at home, the new Cal Ripken streak
is 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting out against Orlando Hernandez was one thing, but taking
a seat when Roger Clemens was trying to nail down a record-breaking
fifth Cy Young Award (not to mention attempting to keep his team's
fading wild card hopes alive) was quite obviously another. Cal had
done what he had to do in Baltimore. Now he could resume what
passes for normal in his life.
</P>
<P>
   And what Cal did in Baltimore on Monday was clearly the right
thing for all concerned. Let there be no mistake about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major thing is that he did it himself,'' observes Pat
Gillick, the soon-to-be ex-general manager of the Orioles. ``He did
it of his own volition. It now gives the manager the flexibility to
pull him in and out of the lineup. No matter what anyone says, the
streak was intimidating to the manager. Since the streak is broken
now, Ray (Miller) is free to use Cal as he wishes. It was a pretty
good deal for him.''
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't such a good deal for Baltimore was the presence of
Clemens on the mound. They probably had no right to hope that
Monday night's game would turn out to be much different from most
of the 20 since Roger sustained his last loss back on May 29 (think
of what we didn't know about Monica way back when). And it wasn't.
In eight innings of work he allowed seven hits and one run. He
struck out 15. Having thrown 134 pitches, he departed in favor of
Paul Quantrill with a 3-1 lead, but not before getting B.J. Surhoff
looking for K No. 15 to close out the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   That gives him a reasonable claim to his fifth Cy, wouldn't you
say? He is 20-6. He leads the league in wins, strikeouts (260),
earned run average (2.58), and a half-dozen other categories they
didn't know about 50 years ago. And, oh yes, he has won 15
straight. I'd say case closed, wouldn't you?
</P>
<P>
   As for Cal, whatever options the beleaguered skipper of
baseball's single most disappointing team will choose to exercise
lie in the future. There, as usual, was Cal, joining such veterans
as Roberto Alomar, Brady Anderson, Harold Baines, Rafael Palmeiro,
Surhoff, and Mike Bordick in the lineup against a man whose every
appearance nowadays signifies an assault on the record book.
Against a lineup like that, Roger was engaged in the resumption of
some personal rivalries with a little mold on them.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that among the seven aforementioned vets, there had
been an accumulated 81 career Clemens strikeouts. On the plus side,
these guys had managed to reach the Rocket for a total of 13 home
runs. He knew all about them, and vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is at the stage of his career where each game has a
double inference. There's the here and now and there's the Clemens
place in history. By the end of the fifth inning he had thrown a
few more logs on the record book fire, having struck out 10 men for
the 92d time in his career and having fanned the side for the 117th
and 118th times in his fairly amazin' career (13th and 14th times
in '98).
</P>
<P>
   The fourth inning was somewhat, well, you know, routine, as
Roger allowed a leadoff double to Palmeiro and then got Willie
Greene, Ripken, and Surhoff on 14 pitches. But the fifth was a
Clemens special. In the midst of allowing two hits and a run, he
huffed and puffed his way through four full counts and 37 pitches.
But did he fan Charlie Greene, Alomar and, finally, Willie Greene?
Uh-huh, uh-huh.
</P>
<P>
   Solo homers in the third by Shawn Green and Carlos Delgado in
the third had given him a 2-1 lead over Scott Erickson, but it
didn't appear very likely he'd be picking up his sixth complete
game, not after throwing 106 pitches through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken is likewise linked with more than the mere present. Just
about every time he manages to get a base hit he finds himself
entwined with someone of note. Monday night, for example, his
second-inning single to left gave him career base hit number 2,873,
and you'll never guess whom he passed on the all-time list. Some
guy named Ruth; that's all.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Cal's night. It was Roger's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
