<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-DETAILS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY'S TESTIMONY WAS CANDID, DETAILED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the end of her grueling appearance before the
grand jury investigating her relationship with President Clinton,
Monica Lewinsky began to cry as a juror asked her if there was
anything she wished to add to her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would,'' she said. `` ...I would just like to say that no
one ever asked me to lie and I was never promised a job for my
silence. And that I'm sorry. I'm really sorry for everything that
has happened. And I hate Linda Tripp.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day dominated by release of the videotaped testimony of her
paramour, Lewinsky's full, painful account to the grand jury of her
relationship with the president also was released.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 500 pages of her own words, Lewinsky reveals
herself as a vulnerable but self-assured young woman who goes to
Washington as an intern at the White House and ends up betrayed and
in tears, being questioned by a team of determined lawyers about
her intimate secrets.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any one thing that distinguishes Lewinsky's
testimony from that of Clinton's, it is that while Clinton relies
on his vast experience and legal training to spar with prosecutors,
bemoaning on occasion the fact that his celebrated memory had
abandoned him, Lewinsky's is studded with the kind of detail the
young and in love tend to remember.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers dates, times, names, what was said to whom and who
gave what to whom. She recalls the weather on particular days that
she visited the Oval Office. She virtually memorized every message
the president left on her machine. She sometimes apologizes to the
jurors and the prosecutors questioning her for providing too much
detail, for going on too long in response to their probing.
</P>
<P>
   And she remembers the sense of betrayal when she realizes that
the love she felt for the president was not reciprocated and that
Tripp, a former colleague at the Pentagon and a principal
confidant, had taped their telephone conversations. In those
conversations, Lewinsky revealed her relationship with Clinton.
Tripp turned the material over to independent counselor Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In return for immunity from prosecution, Lewinsky agreed to
cooperate with the prosecutor. Her testimony was recorded in two
sessions before the grand jury on Aug. 6 and Aug. 20 and in a
deposition to Starr's prosecutors on Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But even without that cooperation, it was revealed Monday, Starr
already had a pretty good picture of the relationship, gleaned from
evidence Lewinsky left behind.
</P>
<P>
   A message on her computer, for instance, revealed a young woman
whose relationship was slipping away from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the time has finally come for me to throw in the
towel,'' she wrote. ``I give up. You let me down, but I shouldn't
have trusted you in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the more salacious details revealed by Lewinsky in
describing her sexual encounters with Clinton have already been
released in the main body of Starr's report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The release of all the material Monday does not significantly
add to what is already known. And what is known is that on at least
10 occasions, between the time the relationship began in the fall
of 1995 to its conclusion in early 1997, Lewinsky and the president
had sexual relations in the White House, although, as they both
testified, they never had intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified that it was both hers and the president's
desire to keep their relationship secret. He never told her to lie
about it, she said, but he also never told her not to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure, as everyone can imagine, that this is a kind of
relationship that you keep quiet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite that, Lewinsky testified that she told numerous
people about the relationship, including her mother, her aunt and,
perhaps most fatefully, Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of relationship was it? When questioned by a grand
juror whether she loved the president or whether theirs was simply
a relationship based on mutual lust, Lewinsky said Clinton had a
``beautiful soul. I just thought he was just this incredible person
and when I looked at him I saw a little boy and _ I don't know what
the truth is anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very compatible sexually,'' she said ``I've always
felt that he was sort of my sexual soul mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is ambivalent about most of the characters in this
saga. The president is ``handsome'' or ``delicious'' or
``heavenly'' when the relationship was going well, but ``schmucko''
and ``creep'' when he is trying to break it off. Vernon Jordan, the
president's close friend to whom Lewinsky turned when she was
subpoenaed in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against the
president, is the one person she believes did right by her.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her anger is reserved for Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during her testimony, one of the prosecutors says
he would like to return to the subject of Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ugh,'' Lewinsky replies.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not she was prompted by the president she doesn't
say, but, Lewinsky repeatedly sought out Jordan for help in finding
a job in New York after her employment prospects at the White House
faded and for advice on what to do about being subpoenaed in the
Jones case. At first, Lewinsky did not tell Jordan she was having a
sexual relationship with Clinton, only that they were having phone
sex and that she was concerned someone may have listened to their
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jordan said, `Well, you know, so what? The president's
allowed to call people.' And I said, `Well, we've had phone sex.'
And so Mr. Jordan said `Well, what's phone sex?' And so I said,
`Well, you know what phone sex is.' And he said, `No I don't. I'm
just an old man. I don't know what phone sex is.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he did find out later that Lewinsky and the president were
having a lot more than telephone sex, Lewinsky testified that
Jordan's response was ``Mmmph.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again in her testimony and in other evidence collected
by Starr, Lewinsky reveals her petulance at not getting her way
with the president, on one occasion throwing a tantrum outside the
White House until being admitted to see him.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, when Clinton is trying to end the relationship,
she wrote a note that read: ``Please do not do this to me (all
seven words underlined). I feel disposable, used and
insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, Lewinsky was trying to get to talk to the
president about an affidavit she was preparing in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Michael Emmick asked Lewinsky about her frame of mind
that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh! You really want to embarrass me,'' Lewinsky replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I just want to get the mood right,'' Emmick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been peeved by the photo and the footage that was in the
media from the president and first lady being romantic on their
holiday vacation,'' Lewinsky said, referring to a picture of the
Clintons on the beach. ``I was jealous and it just seemed sort of
something he had ... never really revealed to me and it made me
feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all her peevishness, Lewinsky just as often reveals her
vulnerability, nowhere more so than toward the end of her testimony
when she described the day in 1997 when, with the world closing in
around her, she had lunch with her friend Tripp, who was wearing a
hidden microphone for the Starr team. Lewinsky was later
``detained'' by Emmick and FBI agents who threatened her with up to
27 years in jail for perjury, subornation of perjury and witness
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   In tears, and wanting to talk to her mother, Lewinsky testified
she felt ``so bad'' because she had pulled the president into this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just cried for a long time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
