<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAN-AFGHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN FAILS TO APPEAR AT THE AFGHAN TALKS ATTENDED BY ALBRIGHT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ What was expected to be the first high-level
meeting in two decades between Iran and the United States did not
occur Monday because Iran's foreign minister did not show up for a
conference on Afghanistan attended by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the meeting that the Iranians announced why
their foreign minister, Kamal Kharazi, was represented by one of
his deputies. He was said to be occupied accompanying Iran's
president, Mohammad Khatami, on his New York rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, rejected the suggestion that
the secretary of state had been snubbed by the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a U.S.-Iranian meeting,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was a higher-level version of at least half a dozen
consultations attended over the last year by Russia, the United
States and the six neighbors of Afghanistan _ Iran, Turkmenistan,
Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, China and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Those nations decided Monday to support a mission to the region
by Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special envoy for Afghanistan,
Lakhdar Brahimi, and by the Islamic Conference Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The group also called for international investigations into the
killings of Iranian diplomats and a journalist, as well as
unconfirmed reports of massacres in areas recently conquered by the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the conference room was any representative of
Afghanistan, which is now almost completely controlled by the
Taliban movement. It has been denied the country's seat here until
it meets a number of conditions on human rights and power sharing
being pushed by the United States. The seat is held by an alliance
of opposition groups that hold almost no remaining territory.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the Taliban said after the meeting that
being frozen out of discussions on the country's future only made
cooperation less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all legitimate standards applied to other countries,'' said
Noorullah Zadran, deputy representative of the Taliban office in
New York, ``we are the government of Afghanistan. It is ridiculous
to think that anyone can claim to solve Afghanistan's problems
without addressing us. They aren't even willing to concede that we
control over 95 percent of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as broad-based a government as Afghanistan has had in
over 20 years,'' Zadran said. ``We have the overwhelming support of
the population across ethnic lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting has continued in Kabul, the Afghan capital; this
weekend more than 50 people were killed and nearly 200 wounded from
rocket attacks. The opposition leader Ahmed Shah Masood denied that
his group was responsible, but said it had fired rockets near the
airport on Sunday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Iran, which has massed more than 100,000 troops near the
Afghan border, the United States has taken the hardest line against
the Taliban. Rubin characterized their goals as the imposition of
``narrow and autocratic fundamentalism.'' Albright has called their
treatment of women despicable.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting was opened by the secretary-general, who
suggested that it might be time to confront reality and think more
about how to deal with the Taliban, ``the side that appears to have
made sizable gains and _ for the moment at least _ is in control of
most of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taliban need to be told what the international community
expects of them by way of minimum standards of behavior, and this
group is well placed to start the process,'' Annan told ministers
from the eight nations.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is pressing for a Security Council resolution condemning
the Taliban for the murder of diplomats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
