<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL NO LONGER SINGS THE BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to stop Brett Hull from smiling, but the sight of a
St. Louis Blues jersey did at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Hull often drew attention from fans and autograph seekers last
week, and one youngster asked him to sign a Blues sweater with
``Hull'' and the traditional No. 16 on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. You're lucky because I'm only going to do this one time,''
Hull said, seemingly joking with the youngster. ``This is the last
time I ever sign anything from the Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   After the crowd cleared, a reporter asked Hull if he had been
joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said with a straight face to emphasize his decision.
``I don't play for them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years in the Blues' organization, Hull walked away July
3, signing a three-year contract with the Stars. He returned to the
Gateway City for last night's preseason game wearing a star on his
chest and No. 22 on his back instead of the famed Bluenote and No.
16.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he hoped to get the hoopla of
Hull's return out of the way in a meaningless game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it done both ways before, and it definitely works
best when you get them in early,'' Hitchcock said. ``There's just
so much to deal with, friends, media, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull's break with the Blues was not without controversy. Before
the Cardinals' Mark McGwire came to town, Hull was the
most-celebrated athlete in St. Louis. He said he wanted to stay
with the Blues but refused to do so without a no-trade clause in
his contract. Blues management offered a three-year, $15 million
deal but not a no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scooped him up with a $17 million deal that includes a
modified no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what (the Blues) just decided was it wasn't going to
work out and they didn't want an unhappy Brett Hull there,'' Hull
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Hull at times had the blues in St. Louis. In two years with
coach Mike Keenan, he was miserable, he said. He was frustrated
when the organization traded away talent such as Adam Oates, Curtis
Joseph and Brendan Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody stuck around to develop any chemistry,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Hull saw the team leaning toward rebuilding again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean they're strong on getting a great defense, and they'll
pay for that, but they'll build with youth on offense,'' he said.
``It's not a bad way to build, but sooner or later you have to
build on offense, as well. ``This team (the Stars) is to the point
where they have the perfect balance... I haven't been this excited
about playing hockey in a long time.'' &QL; 
STARS MAKE CUTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars sent six players back to their junior teams yesterday
and sent another to the training camp of their International Hockey
affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich. Returning to their junior teams are
Steven Gainey (Kamloops), John Erskine (London), Tyler Bouck
(Prince George), Lance Galbraith (Ottawa), Darryl Hay (Tri-Cities)
and Jeff McKercher (Barrie). Goalie Harlin Hayes went to the
K-Wings. &QL; 
FINAL LEG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars play their third preseason road game in three nights
tonight when they meet the expansion Nashville Predators in Little
Rock, Ark. The Predators are playing all their preseason games on
the road to try to build a following.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
