<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7113 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-21 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CONTROVERSIES. NO DOUBTS. FLOJO WAS THAT GOOD.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Florence Griffith Joyner's bane, as well as her blessing,
to be too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Too fast. Too sudden. Too stylish. Too ... FloJo.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't just break women's sprinting records in 1988. She
reinvented them.
</P>
<P>
   News of her death, yesterday in Mission Viejo, Calif., after a
history of heart trouble, unleashed a flood of memories.
</P>
<P>
   She was the most spectacular female athlete that some of us ever
saw in person. In some ways, with her lacy, one-legged outfits, she
was the most outrageous. Beneath the frills and the 9-inch
fingernails, she might also have been the most fearless.
</P>
<P>
   To put her 1988 season into perspective, you have to remember
that in the Olympic years between Wilma Rudolph and FloJo, American
women had been dominated _ no, intimidated _ in track and field by
their Eastern European counterparts. There had been a breakthrough,
of sorts, at the 1984 Games, but those sprinters ran against a
boycott-diluted field.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at the Seoul Games in 1988, the new breed of U.S. women
athletes lined up against the East German and Soviet Olympians for
the first time. They had a new, confident look. They had a new
attitude. A FloJo attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women have not seemed intimidated since.
</P>
<P>
   Griffth Joyner was already well known to the U.S. track media
before that summer of '88. She had been a silver medalist at the
Los Angeles Olympics in '84. But that was supposed to be her
zenith, even though everyone knew that she had been training
earnestly under coach Bob Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   When she took her place in the starting blocks that July day at
the Olympic Trials in Indianapolis, she caused an immediate titter.
Though it was dreadfully humid and the Midwest was in the throes of
a record heat wave, as I recall FloJo was wearing an orange
bodysuit. A blast furnace breeze was blowing at her back.
</P>
<P>
   Until that first-round heat, Griffith Joyner's personal best in
the 100 meters had been 10.96 seconds. The world record was 10.76.
</P>
<P>
   But FloJo flew to a 10.60 clocking, the fastest that a woman had
ever run. The wind kept it from being considered a record.
</P>
<P>
   The next round of the 100-meter heats would both immortalize
FloJo and haunt her until her sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing another body-hugging outfit _ was it the silver one or
the white lace one? _ Griffith Joyner blurred across the finish
line in 10.49.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Indy track stadium immediately turned to the
wind gauge. We all felt a warm breeze. But the sign board at the
gauge flashed ``0.0.''
</P>
<P>
   We blinked. In a sense, the entire world of track and field
blinked.
</P>
<P>
   The record was ratified, but the stories about the suspect wind
reading persist to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Questionable record. Questionable FloJo?
</P>
<P>
   Though Griffith Joyner went on to run three more legal 100-meter
times that summer of 10.70 or better, the suspicions prompted by
the 10.49 stirred the air of suspicion around FloJo.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to win three gold medals and a silver at the Seoul
Olympics. She lowered her 200-meter personal best from 21.96 to
21.34.
</P>
<P>
   Too much. Too fast. The Eastern Europeans were heard grumbling
about FloJo's sudden muscles, her sudden new look.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of the whispers, Bob Kersee leaned against a wall one day
in Seoul and pointed to the new first lady of track and field. She
had on red, white and blue fingernails. Her long dark hair and her
makeup were perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about Florence,'' Kersee asked, ``would make you think
she wasn't all a woman?''
</P>
<P>
   It is inconceivable that Griffith Joyner would have escaped
those 1988 Games _ the Ben Johnson Olympics _ without being tested
several times for banned substances. But FloJo never failed a drug
test.
</P>
<P>
   Her only aberrant behavior, as far as we could tell, was that
she was talking too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The typical FloJo postrace remark, as I recall, went something
like, ``Ijustwantedtogetagoodstart, drivehardtothefinish and go for
the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   She went for the gold, all right. Her records from 1988 remain
Ruthian. No _ they may well last longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of her sudden death, suspicions are sure to
surface. Those who knew FloJo and who know Kersee would be shocked
if any of the whispers are proven true.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us would rather believe that Florence Griffith Joyner
was just a driven woman, a tireless worker, who found the right
coach at the right golden time _ and happened to have a wardrobe of
dazzling sprint suits to fit the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Too good to be true? Can't be. I saw her myself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
