conversations for two years before his death. The resulting book is
the younger Dickey's ``Summer of Deliverance: A Memoir of Father
and Son,'' coming out this month. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- NY-RIALTO-HERITAGE-2-B&AMP;W,
9-21 -- In 1970, pornographic movies played in the Rialto Theater's
auditorium downstairs while programs like ``Romper Room'' were
broadcast from the WOR-TV studios upstairs. Back in '20s, the
theater called itself the ``temple of the motion picture.'' (Larry
C. Morris/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- NY-RIALTO-HERITAGE-1, 9-21
-- Showmen, con men, impresarios, prelates and hustlers have all
found their way to the Rialto Theater in Times Square. But now, the
theater is about to be consigned to history. In its place, a
30-story corporate nerve center called the Reuters Building is to
begin rising next year. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SEOUL, South Korea -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
OBIT-GRIFFITH-JOYNER, 9-21 -- Florence Griffith Joyner falls to her
knees after winning and setting a world record of 21.34 seconds in
the 200m Gold medal at the 1988 Seoul Olympics. The record still
stands. Griffith Joyner, the three-time gold medalist in Seoul who
revolutionized women's sprinting with her searing speed and
flamboyant fashion sense, died early Monday morning at her home in
Mission Viejo, Calif. She was 38. (Todd Buchanan/1988 New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- U.N.-IRAN, 9-21 --
President Mohammad Khatami of Iran addressing the General Assembly
on Monday. His main proposal was that the United Nations declare
2001 the ``year of dialogue among civilizations.'' But so far Iran
has rejected an American proposal for an official political
dialogue with the United States, and Khatami made no mention of it
in his speech. (Marilyn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- U.N.-MANDELA, 9-21
-- President Clinton, United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan
and President Nelson Mandela of South Africa heading to lunch at
the U.N. on Monday. ``I have reached that part of the long walk
when the opportunity is granted, as it should be to all men and
women, to retire to some rest and tranquillity in the village of my
birth,'' says Mandela, addressing the General Assembly for
``probably the last time.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ROOSEVELT FIELD, N.Y. -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
BRITISH-SHOPS-2, 9-21 -- An empty bed linen department at Laura
Ashley in the mall at Roosevelt Field. The company has been through
management turmoil in the last two years. ``Laura Ashley is a
disaster,'' says Mark Husson, a Briton who is an analyst at Merrill
Lynch in New York. ``There was a period when every design magazine
had their fabrics and it was highly successful. But frilly English
styles were a trend and fad.'' (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- BRITISH-SHOPS-1, 9-21 --
Customers perusing the wares at the Body Shop in Manhattan. Body
Shop International recently was forced to form a joint venture with
Bellamy Retail Group L.L.C. to stay in business in the United
States after bleeding cash for years. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- CLINTON-MEDIA, 9-21 --
Bob Torpey, right, senior engineer for Fox News, hands off a
videotape of President Clinton's deposition Monday. The three major
broadcast networks changed plans and decided to join the all-news
cable networks in televising all four hours of Clinton's testimony.
NBC News briefly cut away from it twice, because of the explicit
discussion of sexual activity. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- LINCOLN-CENTER-JAZZ-2,
9-21 -- Wynton Marsalis leading Lincoln Center's orchestra as it
performs for a PBS special. By almost any conventional measure,
Jazz at Lincoln Center has been an astounding success. The
program's budget has grown in three years from $3 million to $9
million, and this year it will present nearly 400 concerts,
lectures, classes and workshops in New York and around the world.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- LINCOLN-CENTER-JAZZ-1,
9-21 -- Lincoln Center's orchestra provides the music for dancers
in a PBS special. In just a decade Jazz at Lincoln Center has
become the flagship jazz organization in the United States. Led by
Wynton Marsalis, the most celebrated jazz musician of his time, it
is scheduled to move to the kind of coveted location that comes
along only once every few decades. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) URBANA, Ill. -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- JAZZ-SINGER, 9-21 --
The Krannert Center for the Performing Arts, at the University of
Illinois in Urbana. On Wednesday night, the center, which has
flourished as a performance hall and as a showcase for young
artists and new works, will celebrate the opening of its 30th
season with fireworks and choruses. Jazz singer Dee Dee Bridgewater
will be onstage for a sold-out performance. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- U.N.-CLINTON-2, 9-21
-- President Clinton receiving a rare standing ovation Monday as he
is introduced at United Nations headquarters. White House aides
were quick to say that Clinton was moved by the warm greeting,
which offered a measure of support for a beleaguered president
whose videotaped grand jury testimony in the Monica Lewinsky matter
was playing on TV even as he spoke. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- U.N.-CLINTON-1, 9-21
-- Hundreds of delegates giving President Clinton a rare standing
ovation Monday as he is introduced in the cavernous hall at United
Nations headquarters. ``This is a threat to all humankind,'' says
Clinton, renewing a global call to arms against terrorism. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ASPEN, Colo. -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- SCI-SUPERSTRING-2, 9-21
-- ``We've yet to find a convincing logical structure,'' Dr. Steven
Giddings says of the latest in M theory. He attended a workshop on
M theory and black holes that was held this summer at the Aspen
Center for Physics in Colorado. (Brian Payne/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ASPEN, Colo. -- Sept. 21, 1998 -- SCI-SUPERSTRING-1, 9-21
-- A workshop on M theory and black holes was held this summer at
the Aspen Center for Physics in Colorado. In recent months, a new
wave of discoveries is fomenting what some physicists are excitedly
hailing as a third revolution, leading toward a day when all the
laws of creation may fit into a single, elegant frame. (Brian
Payne/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MONTAUK POINT, N.Y. -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCI-SAFINA-SHARKS, 9-21 -- Dr. Carl Safina, 43, with a shark jaw.
The sea here once boiled with sharks. But today, the sharks are
fewer, and catching one of the killers can frustrate even
professionals like Safina, who is one of the world's leading
exponents of fishery restraint. ``I love the hunt and know the
thrill of the kill,'' he says. ``But I'm not sure we should be
doing it. They need a break.'' (Courtesy of Dr. Carl Safina/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-4, 9-21 -- Robbie Hughes shows how the wort is
fermented in huge tanks at the Tormore Distillery in Glenlivet.
Even in the high-tech age, malt scotch is made pretty much the same
way its has been made for 300 years. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-3, 9-21 -- Bottles of single malt whiskey line
the shelves of a hotel bar in Glenlivet. Guests often joke that
they wish to sample each scotch at least once - with the intent of
testing them all before industrial consolidation leaves the world
with only a single brand of single malt scotch. (Bert Roughton/Cox
Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-2, 9-21 -- Not far from the hamlet of Glenlivet
is the distillery that produces one of the most famous single malt
scotches. The distillery has been on the glen of the River Livet
since 1858. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-1, 9-21 -- The Tormore Distillery in Glenlivet.
The 31-year-old Speyside distillery was founded on this site in the
Highland hills so as to be near a source of fresh peaty spring
water. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
