<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRING-FASHION-ART-NY     09-21 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLD TO REAL AND VICE VERSA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As brain transplants go, the one that seems to have
taken place between Donna Karan and Helmut Lang is a most startling
swap. Ms. Karan, evidently, has become the bold experimenter and
Lang, the comforting, hard-nosed realist.
</P>
<P>
   Casting the final presentations of last week's fashion shows in
this way is of course a contrivance. But it best illustrates the
positions of these two influential designers. Wrapping up a week of
earlier showings for spring 1999, American designers, from marquee
names like Karan to unknowns like Diva Pittala, proved with
confident singular collections that they, too, can be
trend-setters.
</P>
<P>
   Karan has long given up any pretense of commerciality in her top
collection. In the 1980s, she was in lock step with her customers,
providing them with clothes that defined their career-driven lives
in grand style. Now, Karan is scurrying a bit too far ahead of her
muse.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying idea of the collection, a story of comfort
clothes, of languishing romance and spiritual recognition, rang
true. Ms. Karan has always come across as sincere. The ethereal
taffeta layers in shells and jackets over loose trousers, the
oversize cashmere sweaters in flattering makeup shades of pink,
peach and chamomile, appeared delicate and cocooning.
</P>
<P>
   But amid this intuitive and experimental collection, something
was also terribly wrong. So many of these clothes could be pictured
only in repose. The twisted skirt, an air-filled ballooning of
ankle-length taffeta, was both unwearable for most women and
unappealing, a deadly combination. Where Ms. Karan failed with this
adventurous show was to make her provocative ideas flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Experimental, contemplative fashion is not where Ms. Karan made
her name. Certainly no one has the audacity to insist she stay on
the horse she rode in on. There are, however, few designers who are
able to fuse commercial imperatives with creative ones. Most
designers are clustered at one of two extremes of fashion: the
unapologetic commercialist who will never set a trend, and the
creative wonders who effectively make fantasy clothes _ for if you
wear them, you will be laughed at for all the wrong reasons.
Because Ms. Karan has so often been one of the few successful
centrists, it is disappointing to see her move to anxx extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Lang eased comfortably into the area vacated by Karan, offering
innovative and wearable clothes. It is Lang's triumph that what
once seemed startling in his hands is now familiar. He clearly sees
his job as positing a credible way for worldly women to dress.
</P>
<P>
   His collection presented the dichotomy in today's woman _ her
necessary tough side, and her natural vulnerability. He captured
the opposites best with white feathery knee-length coats over
relaxed cotton trousers. And he went further with padded knees
borrowed from avant-garde Belgian designers and holster handbags
strapped on at the hip and around the leg. The look is sly, ominous
and sexy.
</P>
<P>
   There were delicate fuchsia tulle tank tops layered over
T-shirts _ a patchwork of stark white and deliberately kitsch
animal prints. Veiled, too, some with a pretty spray of accordion
pleats at the back, were white knee-length sheaths.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Calvin Klein's collection looked nothing like
Lang's, to answer the obvious question hanging in the air like a
bubble about to burst. In the past. Klein has been accused of
copying Lang's work. On that score alone, one could have deemed his
show a success. But Klein is doing more these days than glancing to
his right and left. He is determined to be part of any significant
shift in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In a wonderful and emphatic ode to American insouciance, he made
the dress _ shimmery, fluttery and windborne _ a refreshing key to
spring dressing. A richness of color, unusual for Klein, permeated
the collection. In one pivotal look, a silken jersey tent dress in
jewel green melted over one in fire red. He showed this on Kate
Moss; other models, in leather mules with low stiletto heels of
stainless steel, were swathed in guava green over mustard, or china
blue over guava green.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts, paired with scooped tanks or gossamer sweaters, sat
cheekily on the hips, held safe with wraps or large zippers that
darted across a hip or down one leg.
</P>
<P>
   But the vegetable hues that worked in languorous dresses did not
translate well to cotton suits. Their noncommittal shapes branded
them as an afterthought of a designer interestingly consumed with
femininity in dresses and skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Suits, in fact, have come to be unimportant on runways and in
many women's wardrobes. It was one of the strong points of Mark
Eisen's stellar collection that he made one actually want to wear a
suit again.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard not to feel a little smug at first over Eisen's
staging his show at Chelsea Piers, proven to be among the most
inconvenient sites for a fashion presentation. The show started
almost an hour late, and at least 30 percent of his front-row
audience did not make it.
</P>
<P>
   But Eisen did not allow himself to be dismissed. The suits were
one triumph in a significant show. What was so winning about this
collection was its effective mix of both Old World and preppy
fragments with New Age high-performance fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The show vaguely invoked some classic fashion icon _ Babe Paley,
perhaps, or Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis vacationing on Capri. Yet,
it avoided the specificity of either of these references. Instead,
it was a modern interpretation of dressed-down luxury _ pretty and
practical with intriguing touches, like the use of water-repellant
silk.
</P>
<P>
   Eisen offered powder blue, sleeveless funnel-neck shirts with
waterproof silk pants softened at the hem with drawstrings; a
mackintosh coat, and a body-conscious, classic shirt and crisp,
relaxed trousers.
</P>
<P>
   With 25 collections on the roster last week, Americans looked
fresh, vibrant and viable as business people and as creators. There
was a welcome lack of slickness to the week, even from houses like
Searle, which in the past has tried for a trend-driven
commerciality. Vivienne TamTam, Han FengFeng, Sara Kozlowski for
Cake, Mary Jane Marcasiano and Ms. Pittala, who designs under the
label People Used to Dream About the Future, all presented lines in
the image of their own houses.
</P>
<P>
   Folkloric innocence in the form of smocking, apron dresses and
wool embroidery were a unifying theme throughout the collections,
which yielded important trends, although before the week began,
some fashion insiders predicted otherwise. Color is sure to be
important for the spring season, with designers as influential as
Lang, Ms. Karan and Klein endorsing it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feng utilized bold hues to present a collection of soothing
femininity washed in aquamarine, sky blue and rose. A thoughtful
and meticulous designer, Ms. Feng gave simple jersey tops a subtle
drape on one side. She took striped fabric and made it dreamy with
large smocking, and her simple fluid evening gowns worked matte
against shine in black, gray or pale green.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feng's fulsome showing contrasted with Ms. Tam's playful but
sparse collection. Perhaps some depth was lost in the punishing
crunch to have her collection ready for September rather than
November. In between the bead-fringed dresses, the
athletic-inspired paper jackets and the miniskirts enlivened with
turquoise zippers, one would have liked a suggestion for women at
work. It was not long ago that Ms. Tam was merely a promising
talent. She has grown in stature, and it is not too much to expect
a line reflective of her maturity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
