fewer, and catching one of the killers can frustrate even
professionals like Safina, who is one of the world's leading
exponents of fishery restraint. ``I love the hunt and know the
thrill of the kill,'' he says. ``But I'm not sure we should be
doing it. They need a break.'' (Courtesy of Dr. Carl Safina/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-4, 9-21 -- Robbie Hughes shows how the wort is
fermented in huge tanks at the Tormore Distillery in Glenlivet.
Even in the high-tech age, malt scotch is made pretty much the same
way its has been made for 300 years. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-3, 9-21 -- Bottles of single malt whiskey line
the shelves of a hotel bar in Glenlivet. Guests often joke that
they wish to sample each scotch at least once - with the intent of
testing them all before industrial consolidation leaves the world
with only a single brand of single malt scotch. (Bert Roughton/Cox
Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-2, 9-21 -- Not far from the hamlet of Glenlivet
is the distillery that produces one of the most famous single malt
scotches. The distillery has been on the glen of the River Livet
since 1858. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GLENLIVET, Scotland -- Sept. 21, 1998 --
SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-COX-1, 9-21 -- The Tormore Distillery in Glenlivet.
The 31-year-old Speyside distillery was founded on this site in the
Highland hills so as to be near a source of fresh peaty spring
water. (Bert Roughton/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
