<SLUG> BC-FORBES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GOP FORGETS FORBES; '96 PRIMARY WINNER GETS ZERO IN 2000
POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Forbes made Arizona history in 1996 by spending $4 million
to win the state's first GOP presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   But a new poll suggests Arizona Republicans may have all but
forgotten about the wealthy publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single Republican voter picked the wealthy publisher in
the 2000 presidential preference survey taken last month by Arizona
Chamber Info. Inc., a subsidiary of the Arizona Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a preposterous poll,'' Forbes said Monday
after his latest Arizona stop. ``This goes in the fiction
category.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have broad-based support for our views in Arizona and
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans in the statewide poll, 52 percent, were
undecided. But among those with an opinion, former vice
presidential candidate Jack Kemp came out on top of seven potential
GOP presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp had 18 percent, followed by House Speaker Newt Gingrich, 14
percent; Sen. John McCain, 9 percent; former Vice President Dan
Quayle, 3 percent; Elizabeth Dole, 2 percent and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters read the names of seven potential GOP presidential
candidates, including Forbes', but not a single person polled chose
him.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 231 Republicans had an error margin of plus or
minus 5.4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore was the choice of
48 percent of 213 Democrats polled, easily outpacing Nebraska Sen.
Bob Kerrey, 11 percent, and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, 9
percent. The Rev. Jesse Jackson polled less than 1 percent, and 31
percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who spoke Monday to a health-care conference sponsored
by Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., said the poll is ``fatally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a random selection (of Republicans) just doesn't cut
it,'' Forbes said, noting that the results have not been confirmed
by ``any other reputable survey, either in Arizona or elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell Quinlan, the Arizona Chamber's vice president for
communications, said he, too, was shocked that Forbes did not even
register in the poll, but defended its accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what it says more is that it's a wide-open race,''
Quinlan said. ``The fact that someone like Steve Forbes didn't poll
well doesn't say he can't win it here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has become a fixture on Arizona's political landscape
since he won the state's 1996 GOP primary, stunning challengers Bob
Dole and Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he spoke at fund-raiser for the state GOP, after a
recent fund-raising appearance for Rep. J.D. Hayworth. In October,
he will keynote the Arizona Christian Coalition's annual
fund-raising dinner, and will appear before the Pima County
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Forbes called portions of President Clinton's
videotaped grand jury testimony ``absolutely devastating,'' and
predicted Clinton will not finish his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see them close the trap,'' Forbes said of the
prosecutors. ``That's why it's important the House hold hearings as
soon as possible, so this crisis can be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Once members begin looking at the ``whole array of abuses'' _
from travelgate to campaign finance _ Clinton ``won't survive,''
Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they hold those hearings, and people get to see for
themselves the pattern and how long it's been going on, he will be
removed from office,'' Forbes predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five minutes before the Senate (conviction) vote, he'll step
down.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
