A7121 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-21 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE MOST PART, CLINTON KEPT HIS COMPOSURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation Monday watched a lawyerly, tense and
combative President Clinton spar with prosecutors about his affair
with Monica Lewinsky as his videotaped grand jury testimony was
made public.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major television networks and cable news outlets
pre-empted their regular morning programming to carry just over 4
hours of Clinton being grilled on whether he lied under oath about
his sexual relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   During the Aug. 17 questioning at the White House, the
president's responses varied from evasiveness, at times quibbling
with his questioners over the definition of sex, to outright anger
at his investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have made this the most important issue in America,''
Clinton told Starr's prosecutors at one point.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed resentment when the questioning continually
returned to his denials of sex with Lewinsky in a sworn deposition
from the Paula Jones sexual harassment case, vehemently denouncing
the lawsuit as politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton disputed the simplest premises raised by
prosecutors, such as what it meant to be alone with Lewinsky in the
Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   But the president generally maintained his composure and held
his own during the lengthy session. His testimony produced few
bombshells, in part because so many details had been included in
Starr's own report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was just part of a massive release of evidence by the
House Judiciary Committee. Lawmakers and the media pored over 3,183
pages of information that contained more explicit details from
Lewinsky about her affair with the president, including photos of
her semen-stained dress.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, trying to escape the storm of scandal, was in
New York addressing the United Nations, where he was greeted by a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House issued a statement condemning the release of the
new material, saying that congressional Republicans merely wanted
to rehash salacious details of an affair the president had already
admitted was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rank partisanship that led to the wholesale release of
these materials, most of which are irrelevant, is regrettable,''
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, however, have defended the public's right to
view a tape they contend may show the president committed
impeachable offenses, such as perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has a license to lie,'' said Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., a member of the Judiciary Committee, which would hold
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear in recent days that House Republicans have
been paving the way for an inquiry that could be approved before
they leave for fall recess in October. They view the videotaped
testimony as helpful in building their case.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, however, countered that there was nothing new
on the tape. Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, said after viewing the
testimony that he could not support an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turned into a political battle instead of a
constitutional battle,'' he said. Republicans, Green said, were
``more concerned about winning the November elections and picking
up seats than removing the president based on his wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders have voiced optimism that Clinton's problems will
boost their candidates' chances in the upcoming elections. But the
release of the videotape was not a risk-free proposition for
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls showed that a majority of Americans did not
want the videotape aired, particularly if it contained a rehash of
the intimate details already included in Starr's report that was
released last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the event, which has dominated news programs for days,
proved almost anti-climactic as the testimony shed little new
information about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Although the questioning showed Clinton occasionally becoming
agitated and angry, there were no remarkable outbursts. The
president blunted the prosecutors' ability to question him by
giving lengthy responses that used up much of the agreed-upon time.
</P>
<P>
   While the videotaped testimony may have not added much new, it
does show a sometimes evasive president who makes fine legal
distinctions and pleads a loss of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly refused to agree to prosecutors' suggestion
that he had committed perjury by testifying that he did not have
sex with Lewinsky in the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging he had an improper relationship, Clinton
argued that he did not believe oral sex fit under the definition of
sexual relations offered by Jones' lawyers, which include touching
a person's genitals for the purpose of arousal.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions from jurors about the distinction,
Clinton said, ``I'll bet the grand jury, if they were talking about
people they know and said they had a sexual relationship together,
they meant they were sleeping together; they meant they were having
intercourse together.''
</P>
<P>
   On another issue Clinton was asked why he did not turn over to
Jones' lawyers personal letters from Kathleen Willey, who has
accused the president of intimately touching her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded that Jones' lawyers had asked for personal
rather than White House correspondence. His lawyers considered the
Willey letters White House correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   The president and prosecutors sparred over chronology of events.
Clinton insisted that his top adviser Bruce Lindsay had initially
told him that Lewinsky had been subpoenaed by Jones' lawyers.
Prosecutors, however, said it was his friend Vernon Jordan, who
eventually tried to help Lewinsky get a job.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Clinton also blamed the demands on the presidency
and Starr's investigation for hampering what he admitted had been a
good memory.
</P>
<P>
   The president's anger at those investigating his conduct came
through during the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why he did not fully respond to Jones' lawyers during
his deposition, he angrily retorted he did not want to help people
he believed were out to hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deplored what they were doing. I deplored the innocent
people they were tormenting and traumatizing. I deplored their
illegal leaking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His ire at the independent counsel was also apparent, as he
sniped that ``we have seen this four-year $40 million investigation
come down to parsing the definition of sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared sympathetic to Lewinsky, even though he
said several times that he had tried to break off the relationship
because he knew it was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's basically a good girl,'' he told prosecutors. ``She's a
good young women with a good heart and a good mind. I think she is
burdened by some unfortunate conditions of her upbringing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said there was nothing improper about the gifts
that he had given Lewinsky over the years. The president said he
had given gifts to many people over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has claimed that Clinton's secretary Betty Currie's
efforts to retrieve gifts subpoened by Jones' lawyers may have
amounted to obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   During the session, the president sat behind his desk in the
White House as he fielded questioning from a team of seven lawyers
from the independent counsel's office. Starr only asked a few
questions, leaving the grilling largely to his deputies. Three
lawyers for the president were also in the room
</P>
<P>
   During the questioning the president reached often for a glass
of water, regularly cleared his voice and asked for a number of
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton said he could not remember all of the details of
his relationship with Lewinsky, the former intern's testimony is
peppered with detail.
</P>
<P>
   In the newly released material, Lewinsky, in three sessions with
prosecutors, details the 10 sexual encounters she had with Clinton
at the White House as well as her conversations with Clinton friend
Jordan about getting a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She also aimed some of her most vitriolic commentary at Linda
Tripp, her former colleague at the Pentagon who tipped off Starr
about her affair.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp taped her conversations with Lewinsky regarding the
president and then turned them over to the independent counsel.
Lewinsky testified that it was Tripp who urged her to save the blue
dress with semen stains that she later turned over to the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate Linda Tripp,'' she told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
