<HEADLINE>
WANNSTEDT CAN COACH, BUT IS HE CUT OUT TO BE A HEAD COACH?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I like Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   I know he's devoted to Catholicism, sometimes going to church
every morning. I know he's devoted to family, fighting the
scheduling demands of an NFL coach to sneak away when possible for
a romantic dinner with his wife, or to see one of his daughters
perform in a play or a volleyball game. I know he's devoted to his
friends, so much so that his warmth urges uncharacteristic kindness
from all of them, even Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   I like Dave Wannstedt. But I'm not sure he's cut out for this.
</P>
<P>
   I've got a million more things to learn about pro football. But
so much of the knowledge I do have comes from the generous
teachings of Wannstedt, so giving during his 1989-92
defensive-coordinator stint in Dallas and continuously so since he
took the Chicago Bears' top job.
</P>
<P>
   I saw first-hand Joel Collier's work in Denver. I saw first-hand
George Seifert's work in San Francisco. I saw first-hand Butch
Davis and Dave Campo's work in Dallas. I have some familiarity with
what Buddy Ryan did with the old Vikings and Bears, with what
Richie Petitbon did with the Redskins, with what Dom Capers did
with the Steelers, with what Greg Robinson is doing with the
Broncos, with what John Fox is doing now with the Giants, with what
Green Bay's Fritz Shurmur has done since forever.
</P>
<P>
   And Dave Wannstedt is the best defensive coordinator I've ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the X's-and-O's stuff? Even the worst of 'em have that
mastered. But Wannstedt had more. He was an old offensive lineman,
so he was a smart guy. He was a Jimmy protege, so he learned the
art of quick calculation. He was a native Pittsburgher, so he was a
tough guy. He was a great friend, a great teacher, an intimidating
presence, a leader of men.
</P>
<P>
   On those great Cowboys teams, Wannstedt never begged oddballs
Charles Haley and James Washington to perform. He just ordered them
to, and they did. In those days, Wannstedt had a magic touch on
draft day. Look it up: Those teas rarely missed on the important
defensive puzzle pieces, linemen and cornerbacks. Some of that was
Dave.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear: If Jimmy Johnson was king, Dave Wannstedt was the
heir to the throne.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so clear now: In 1992, the Pittsburgh Steelers were
shopping for a replacement for Chuck Noll. They interviewed three
finalists, Kevin Gilbride, and local boys Wannstedt and Bill
Cowher. Cowher got the Steelers; Wannstedt got the Bears the next
season.
</P>
<P>
   The two faced off a week ago. Cowher's Steelers won, and even
with Pittsburgh's disappointing loss to Miami on Sunday, his career
mark is 66-33, and his club is marching to a probable sixth playoff
berth in six years. Meanwhile, Wannstedt has made the playoffs
once. And even if you want to give him credit for keeping his 0-3
Bears in games this year against powerhouses Jacksonville,
Pittsburgh and Tampa Bay, you cannot ignore his career mark of
36-47.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our three highest-paid players last year were (Alonzo)
Spellman, (Bryan) Cox and Rick Mirer, and none of them is on the
team (this year),'' Wannstedt says. ``We missed on way too many
draft picks. We've made mistakes in the personnel area and free
agency. ... That kind of sums up why we're backed into a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh hired, by reputation and record, one of the best head
coaches in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago hired, by reputation and record, well. ... the best
defensive coordinator I've ever seen. &QL; 
QUOTABLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still at a point where I don't even know what I don't
know.'' _ Panthers rookie defensive lineman Jason Peter. &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In large part due to that Week 1, game-winning 96-yard touchdown
run by Garrison Hearst in overtime to beat the Jets, the 49ers are
averaging 530 yards per game on offense. But the run has more
significance. ``NFL Films'' boss Steve Sabol, whose entire life is
to know such things, says Hearst's effort is ``the greatest run
ever.'' ... Somebody suggests to Saints linebackers coach Zaven
Yarallan that his troops were a bit thin, that he could use another
linebacker. Responds Yarallan: ``I'm not a chicken. I can't hatch
one.'' But something's going right in New Orleans: This is only the
third time in the club's 31-year history the Saints have started
2-0. ... Before this season, the 2-0 Falcons hadn't won a September
game since 1995. ... Beware, struggling kickers: Every NFL team has
the phone number of temporarily unemployed Cary Blanchard. ... In
my review of running backs taken ahead of Denver sixth-rounder
Terrell Davis in the '95 draft, I left off the immortal Patriots
fifth-rounder Dino Philyaw. Sorry. How could I forget?.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
