<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPHILL CLIMB, WITH ANKLE WEIGHTS 
IN NORTH CAROLINA, THE NAME GAME 
AN ACE BEATS A JACK ANY DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., has known almost from the day she
took office that winning a second term would not be easy. As one of
the most liberal Democrats on Capitol Hill, she is a polarizing
figure who attracts critics more easily than most politicians, and
her resulting ``negatives'' in the polls have always been high.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Election Day just six weeks off, her already tough
battle against her Republican opponent, state Treasurer Matt Fong,
is looking even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll, conducted by The Los Angeles Times, found her
leading Fong by roughly eight points among registered voters _ at
first glance, a fairly comfortable edge. But when the poll was
narrowed to cover only registered voters ``likely'' to vote, Fong
took a five-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The implication: Ms. Boxer must find some way to energize her
supporters to turn out in greater numbers. That will be no easy
task in a year in which primary voting in general has been near
record lows and, looking toward November, increasing numbers of
Democrats seem more and more dispirited and many Republicans seem
poised to dash to the nearest voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, Ms. Boxer, like many Democrats, has been
damaged somewhat by fallout from President Clinton's relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. About one in seven voters in the Times poll
said the president's behavior had made them more likely to vote,
and two-thirds of that group said they intended to vote for Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that Boxer had compounded the damage by not
being as critical of the president's behavior as many voters would
like. About a third of the respondents said they were less likely
to vote for her because of her low-key response.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, one of the most extensive to date that looks closely
at the possible effect of Clinton-Lewinsky on fall voting, was
taken last week. It covered more than 1,600 Californians, almost
1,300 of them registered voters, and has a margin of error of plus
or minus three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, The Name Game
</P>
<P>
   What's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   In politics, name recognition can sometimes be the difference
between winning and losing. And in North Carolina, the pundits are
saying that that explains in good part why Democratic voters
nominated Jim Martin to represent their party this fall in a
contest for a seat on the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. In the Tar Heel State, there's Jim Martin and then
there's Jim Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The former _ the nominee Jim Martin _ is a state district judge
from the little crossroads town of Ayden. He came out of political
nowhere in May to trounce the much better known candidate in the
primary, Judge Joe John of the state Court of Appeals. Before that,
the only consequential headlines Martin had made resulted from
being reprimanded several times by higher courts for failing to
follow various legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The latter Jim Martin is the former (no word play intended)
two-term Republican governor. He says voters mistakenly thought
they were voting for him when they went to the primary polls four
months ago and voted for Judge Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure they did,'' the judge agrees with Cheshire cat candor.
</P>
<P>
   How about those Judge Jim Martin election placards that were
plastered about during the primary campaign, the ones that looked a
lot like the signs that once helped re-elect Gov. Jim Martin? Mere
coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' Judge Martin told The News &AMP; Observer in
Raleigh. ``I just picked a color.''
</P>
<P>
   The former governor worries that if voters could vote for the
wrong Jim Martin once, they could do it twice. And the next time,
he says, they might end up putting a Democrat on the Supreme Court
rather than just nominating one to run for the job.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, he called on Republican leaders around the
state, including state House Majority Leader N. Leo Daughtry, to do
all possible to clear up the Martin confusion, lest the Republican
candidate in the fall be overwhelmed. That would be Mark Martin, no
relation to either Jim but a former aide to the governor and now a
member of the state Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Daughtry forthwith sent out a fund-raising letter that included
a reprint of a story in the current Reader's Digest. The story
ranks Judge Martin as one of America's worst judges, a ranking he
is quoted as saying ignores his record of ``perfect judgeship.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that mailing, a number of the state's leading Democrats,
including two former state party chairman, have backed away from
Judge Martin. And some have begun raising money for Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   An Ace Beats A Jack Any Day
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Democrats nominated John Cox, a former professor
and management consultant, to take on Rep. Matt Salmon, the
two-term Republican who represents Arizona's First District. But it
was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who had no primary opposition, died two days before voting
took place. The 8,000 votes he won came mainly from voters unaware
that he had succumbed to a stroke only hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Democratic leaders from the district, which covers
much of the eastern edge of Phoenix, convened to pick a
replacement, as provided for by the state Constitution. Three
candidates stepped forward and the balloting began.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round, none of the candidates got a majority but
the one who came in third was eliminated. In the second round,
there was a tie. Same for the third round.
</P>
<P>
   That meant, under the state Constitution, that a game of chance
_ any game of chance _ would be used to settle the issue. The
candidates, David Mendoza, a labor lobbyist, and Victor Aronow, a
teacher, settled on a hand of five-card stud.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza won, ace of clubs high to Aronow's jack of spades.
</P>
<P>
   He'll likely need another ace, perhaps one up his sleeve, come
November. The First is rated a solid Republican district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
