<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS VIEW DUEL BETWEEN CLINTON, INTERROGATORS WITH PROFESSIONAL
EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix-area lawyers said Monday that they viewed the televised
give-and-take between President Clinton and his interrogators with
professional interest.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned by anger and disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Debus said it made him sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a registered Republican for 40 years, and I'll never
give them another nickel,'' the prominent criminal attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole interrogation wasn't intended to get information for
Congress to determine whether to impeach or censor. The entire
purpose was to embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Debus noted that when the president refused to answer
interrogators' questions about sexual encounters with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, ``They didn't follow up as they could have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had thought they were on proper ground, all they do is
say `We're going to continue this until we get these questions
answered.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a proper grand jury setting, he said, prosecutors could have
said Clinton was in contempt of court because he was not answering
the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they knew their questions weren't relevant or material and
were meant only to embarrass the man,'' Debus said. ``The proof of
that is they didn't try to force him to answer the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Arizona Attorney General Bob Corbin said he was disgusted by
Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Lord, he was so evasive,'' Corbin said. ``If he'd have
been in a court of law, he never could have gotten away with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they have him in a box. If he admits to aspects of the
sexual relations thing, then he admits to committing perjury, and
that's a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the office of the presidency, but I don't respect
this man. He is a disgrace to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   William French, who was called upon 10 years ago by Arizona
legislators to prosecute then-Gov. Evan Mecham, said he thought
``the president was understandably argumentative and evasive at
times.''
</P>
<P>
   French said the president's evasions were understandable
because, ``the questions were in such depth, such detail, they were
extremely difficult to address.''
</P>
<P>
   French said the testimony and grilling left him feeling angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `This is so humiliating!' And I think this could
come back to haunt the prosecutors,'' he said. ``There was an
overkill. They were rubbing his nose in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley thought Clinton's
performance ``wasn't as bad as it was portrayed by the press; there
was no loss of temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley felt prosecutors didn't always follow up their questions
to good effect: ``It was evident some doors were open, but they
didn't follow up and tie him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Romley said, ``The president was very evasive.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix defense attorney Gary Klahr said Clinton ``did better
than you'd expect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He smiled and generally performed well _ LBJ would have gotten
angry,'' Klahr said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's performance wasn't quite good enough, Klahr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid the sizzle was better than the steak,'' he said.
``Clinton obviously was splitting hairs in respect to events, and
he was very evasive. He came close to committing perjury. In fact,
I think he did commit perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's story has all sorts of holes in it. The only way you
can believe him is if you can believe he really doesn't remember
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's pretty hard to accept.'' &QL; 
William Hermann can be reached at 444-4875 or at
william.hermann(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
