<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SIBERIA WITH JEWELS  
 THE OLIVE &AMP; BETTE'S CATALOG  
 FASHION FROM A CAR COMPANY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jewelry From a Model
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a child, Irina Pantaeva used to accompany her
uncle, a geologist, on rock-hunting trips in their native Siberia.
``I grew up playing with precious stones,'' said Ms. Pantaeva, a
model, whose Asian beauty has taken her to the runways.
</P>
<P>
   With hands accustomed to the feel of diamonds, Ms. Pantaeva has
begun her own jewelry collection, called Irina. The line, which is
represented by Apropo, had its public coming-out party last Friday
at Mary Jane Marcasiano's fashion show, where Ms. Pantaeva's simple
organic earrings were a fitting flourish to relaxed sporty clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of Ms. Pantaeva's jewelry was on her finger. Her
wedding band _ emeralds and 18-karat gold in the form of a dragon _
inspired the line. Her husband, Roland Levin, is her business
partner.
</P>
<P>
   The line, from $500 for earrings to $8,000 for a necklace, has
four groups: the dragon, the lotus, the elements, and snowflakes
and icicles. ``I wanted to create jewelry that will be worn like
amulets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pantaeva was absent from the runways last week. She was on
tour promoting her memoir, ``Siberian Dream,'' published by Avon
Books. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Of-the-Minute Catalog
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several companies are carving out a youthful area in
fashion, the edges of which can be traced by designer-driven,
reasonably priced clothes. And companies quick enough to scope out
the scene, like Olive &AMP; Bette's, Club Monaco, Tocca and Scoop, seem
to be expanding nicely.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of its latest store opening last month, at 1070
Madison Avenue (81st Street), Olive &AMP; Bette's has introduced a
catalog for the fall. With its focus on less prominent designers
and of-the-minute fashion, there's simply no other book like it.
</P>
<P>
   By nature, catalogs tend to cater to older customers or feature
traditional clothing. What's the fashionista in search of fast,
sophisticated clothes to do? In these pages, she will find a
cashmere turtleneck for $200, Jussara Lee's pleated skirt for $104
and Frou's tartan bag for $196. There are purple Birkenstocks, Free
People's ankle-length skirt, athletic Daryl K pants and, yes, cargo
pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry for fashion,'' said Stacey Pecor, the owner
of the three Olive &AMP; Bette's stores (one in Vermont and one at
Columbus Avenue and 72nd Street) and an owner with Karen Greenberg
of the catalog. The book was originally conceived with a test
catalog in March, to serve women far from the fashion hubs. But in
the three weeks during which the fall catalog has been out, most
orders have come in from Dallas and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Urban women, too, are probably grateful for a quick, edited
buying experience that reflects their sensibilities. ``We summarize
what you need,'' Ms. Pecor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes-Benz Look
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Does the appropriation of fashion to sell everything
from cars to liquor enhance fashion or cheapen it? It's a question
that has arisen as a proliferation of nonfashion companies begin
fashion lines. The latest is Mercedes-Benz. Prestigious, sure, but
are its offerings fashion?
</P>
<P>
   ``The car has always been something of a fashion statement,''
insisted Wade Hubbard, who as the general manager for service,
parts and accessories is in charge of the development of a Mercedes
clothing line.
</P>
<P>
   Like most car brands, Mercedes has always sold promotional
goods, like T-shirts with its logo. Beginning in October, it will
sell products in its showrooms and catalogs that complement each of
its four car categories: golf wear, outerwear, leather wallets and
sportswear. ``Each car has a personality, and we wanted to create a
line of accessories around that,'' Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is it's hardly fashion that companies like
Mercedes-Benz or Johnnie Walker, which recently started a clothing
line, are selling. What they are bent on is brand extension. And
which industry knows more about that than fashion?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
