<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AZDELEGATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA REP. HAYWORTH SAYS CLINTON VIDEO WILL VALUABLE TOOL FOR LAW
STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN AND CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's videotaped testimony wasn't exactly must-see
TV for Arizona's congressional delegation Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's six congressmen and two senators were
reportedly traveling or too busy to catch the four hours of
testimony on television.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., the one congressman who did find
time to watch most of the testimony, acknowledged that the tape
wasn't a ``smoking gun'' that would prove that Clinton committed
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayworth said the video would provide great material for law
students on a witness ``who does anything and everything to avoid''
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a masterpiece of prevarication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., who was attending meetings most of the
day in his southern Arizona district, said he didn't think it was
necessary to watch the testimony Monday. He said that any decision
on whether the House Judiciary Committee will pursue impeachment
proceedings against Clinton is still a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll watch it eventually,'' Kolbe said. ``I think it's an
important piece of all the evidence we have received. We can see
how he answers questions, what his body language is like. That's
useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Reps. John Shadegg and Bob Stump and Sen. Jon Kyl, all
Republicans, said they hadn't had time to view the testimony, so
they couldn't say whether it would affect their opinions on
possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the Judiciary Committee has a chance to work, I'm not
going to say he should be impeached or resign or anything,'' Stump
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Stump signed a congressional petition earlier this year
supporting a call of impeachment against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., and Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., said through
spokesmen that they would have no comment on the video. Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., was traveling and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did comment were hesitant to speculate on how the
American public would react to the public airing of the testimony.
There have been concerns that some people would turn on Republicans
for making the videotape public.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg said most callers to his office Monday were opposed to
the release of the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people aren't anxious to hear about this for the
rest of their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kolbe said Congress had no choice but to release the
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little like shooting the messenger, like we're somehow
responsible by releasing it,'' he said. ``But in this day and age,
you can't keep information away from the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth predicted that voters would not lose interest in the
case just because the testimony wasn't a Perry Mason-type
interrogation. He added that he wasn't worried about polls that
show continued strong support for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president lied under oath, it's impeachable,'' Hayworth
said. ``I don't predicate my designs on polls, but principle.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
