<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JAPAN'S PARALYSIS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   A political deal on how to close insolvent Japanese banks
appears to be unraveling rapidly, raising the specter of continued
inaction on the financial crisis facing the world's second-largest
economy. That would constitute an abdication of responsibility not
only to the Japanese people but to the global economy that needs a
healthy Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who is to meet with President
Clinton on Tuesday, supposedly had worked out a deal with
opposition parties in the Japanese Parliament to have the state
take over insolvent banks, but it is now in doubt because of
opposition to the use of public money to keep such banks afloat
before they are taken over. Moreover, the prime minister, in an
interview with editors and reporters from The New York Times, said
on Monday that he believed that stockholders in the banks should be
compensated by the government, a misguided position that is likely
to be unpopular in Japan, and deservedly should be.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government needs to make it clear that it will bail
out depositors, but not owners, of failed banks. The government
also needs to move promptly to determine which banks must be closed
and which can continue. Protecting depositors will cost large
amounts of public money, and the political opposition needs to
understand and accept that.
</P>
<P>
   Without action, the credit crunch, which has made loans hard to
come by for Japanese businesses, will continue indefinitely,
delaying recovery from Japan's severe recession and thereby making
recovery even less likely in other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   The bad-debt problem for Japanese banks is huge, but it is
manageable in an economy as wealthy as Japan's. Japan would benefit
from quick action, but even if there were agreement, it would take
time to institute a plan. With the risk of Japanese inaction high,
it is more necessary than ever for the other major economies _
particularly Germany and the United States _ to take steps such as
lowering interest rates in an effort to stimulate world growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
