<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' KIDS FACE DIFFICULT ADJUSTMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The good news for the Kings over the weekend was
the play of some of their young prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news was that it didn't mean a whole lot.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players aged 19 to 22 collected three goals and five
assists, and a number of other young prospects also played as the
Kings split a pair of exhibition games with the Colorado Avalanche
at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas. But for all of them, the work is
just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:35 tonight, when the Kings play the Mighty Ducks at the
Forum, it will be the third game in four nights for 19-year-old
center Olli Jokinen (who had an assist against Colorado) and
20-year-old left wing Josh Green. Other young prospects slated to
see action include right wing Pavel Rosa (21), center Chris Schmidt
(22) and winger Joe Corvo (21).
</P>
<P>
   Centers Matt Zultek (19), Scott Barney (19), Donald MacLean (21)
and Roman Vopat (22), and defensemen Richard Seeley (19), Sean
Blanchard (20), and Peter Hogan (20) all played in one or both of
the games over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play them,'' Robinson said. ``Even if they make
mistakes, now is the time to play them. They're learning from the
experience and from their mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The player with perhaps the greatest adjustment is the 6-foot-2,
210-pound Jokinen, the third player selected in the 1997 NHL draft.
Jokinen was held pointless in eight games with the Kings last year
before returning to play in his native Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big jump,'' Jokinen said. ``Last year, I had played
only one year in the top league in Finland, and after that I had to
go to the NHL. Every guy is stronger and bigger here. Everything is
different here. I wasn't ready to play last year. I feel good
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jokinen's adjustment may be the greatest, all the
prospects are having to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to adjust to another level,'' Robinson said. ``And
all these kids were head and shoulders above the other players in
junior. Now, they have to adjust to playing in a situation where
everyone is at their level. They have to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Double trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Two referees will be used for tonight's game, part of the
experiment that will see each team play 20 of 82 regular-season
games with two referees.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend games in Las Vegas were played with two referees,
and were not bogged down by a preponderance of penalties, as some
had feared they would be. Rob Shick and Lyle Seitz called 21
penalties for 60 minutes on the Kings in the two games, and 24
penalties for 66 minutes on the Avalanche. Twelve of the penalties
and 60 of the minutes were for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he liked what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' Robinson said. ``It eliminates the
chippiness behind the play and also will save on wear and tear on
the referees. It forces the players to play hard, with no
retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel, sidelined since the first day of
camp with an ankle sprain, skated Monday, but is not expected to
play tonight or Friday against Phoenix. Rookie center Jason Morgan
remains sidelined with knee tendinitis, but may skate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stand in-line
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will hold a season-long in-line hockey tournament for
the first time, with games to be played on a portable rink in the
Forum parking lot before 11 of their weekend games. There will be
youth, adult, coed and women's divisions.
</P>
<P>
   For information or to sign up, call Patty Twogood at (714)
740-0414.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
