<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMWORKS-NEW-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS AND DEVELOPER AGREE ON MOVIE STUDIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ending contentious negotiations that appeared
doomed as recently as last month, the fledgling movie studio
Dreamworks SKG and a real-estate development company backed by New
York investment houses reached an agreement Monday for the studio
to build its new home in a coastal development heralded as the
future of urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks, the first new Hollywood studio in 60 years, is
headed by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen. It
has been negotiating to build on the coastal site since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The studio is critical to the 1,087-acre development, which will
also include housing and commercial space, because it brings with
it at least $75 million in city and state tax incentives.
Dreamworks expects to spend $200 million on the studio, building 15
sound stages and using the latest technology, on the site where
Howard Hughes built his ``Spruce Goose'' seaplane.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks and the developer, Playa Vista, announced Monday that
they had agreed to terms laying out how many acres and how much
money any deal would involve. The studio and the developer said the
term agreement was a significant step toward a final agreement and,
ultimately, construction.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Denniston, the president of Playa Vista, said he expected
the land to become available to Dreamworks for construction in the
first quarter of next year, with an opening in mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Parcel size, control over development and price were hard-fought
issues that nearly led the negotiators to walk away from the table
last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter on Aug. 12, Katzenberg informed the project's
investors, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., and Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co., that Dreamworks had made its final offer, a $20 million
payment _ in addition to the tax credits _ for full control of the
development on 48 acres of land.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Katzenberg said in the letter, the developers had
agreed to the $20 million price tag, only to raise it to $48.7
million. After receiving the letter, the developer suggested
building some of the studio space on its own and leasing it to
Dreamworks.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither side would comment publicly on the terms of the
deal, a source close to the negotiations said the two sides agreed
on the $20 million purchase price for 48 acres of land, with full
development control to the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to believe that every good deal may die several deaths
before it closes,'' Denniston said, ``and part of the process with
the deal dying a partial death is testing the limits of the other
party. I think this deal is clearly one where Dreamworks' limits
were tested and where our limits were tested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0533 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RIPKEN-800&AMP;ADD-NY     09-21 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RIPKEN-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RECORD THAT RULED THE ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Not long after Cal Ripken surpassed Lou Gehrig's
consecutive-game record on Sept. 6, 1995, a consensus began
building among the Baltimore Orioles' staff and front office
officials that the team would be better off if the streak ended.
The goal was simple: to restore the normal hierarchy that governs a
sports team.
</P>
<P>
   With other teams, the pecking order ranks as follows: owner,
baseball executives, manager, players. With the Orioles, Ripken
loomed over everyone, untouchable because of the magnitude of his
record and the popularity it provided him. His recent managers,
from Phil Regan to Davey Johnson to Ray Miller, never seriously
considered benching him unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was bandied about constantly by club officials. In a
meeting before the All-Star Game break in July, an Orioles official
announced his belief that the team would never win a World Series
championship until Ripken's record and corollary autonomy ended.
``This record has nothing to do with the team,'' the official told
others. ``Its only meaning is to Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   But the official conceded aloud that no change could be made
until Ripken decided to end the streak himself. No one in a
position of authority was willing to throw themselves into the path
of his legendary willfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Sunday night at Camden Yards, Ripken took the
responsibility upon himself, volunteering to sit out the game
against the Yankees and thus ending his streak at 2,632 games. He
was back in the lineup at third base last night, but his record
streak, an achievement that gripped the baseball world three years
ago and helped restore the sport's popularity after years of
divisive labor troubles, had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken is so resolute in his approach to playing the game that
some of his closest friends on the team said in recent years that
they could never imagine him voluntarily removing himself from the
lineup _ even with the vague knowledge that others in the
organization wanted him to sit. But Ripken is also very protective
of his image, and he was well aware of the mounting criticism that
his record no longer contained relevance. He had gone far beyond
Gehrig's record, his run production was among the worst in the
American League, and the Orioles had young players waiting in the
wings. Whose purpose did it serve to have Ripken play every single
game?
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Peter Angelos, the Orioles' owner, received a phone
call from Joe Foss, the team's vice chairman. Foss related a
conversation he just had with Miller, who had met privately with
Ripken. ``Cal is thinking about ending the streak,'' Foss told
Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Angelos said: ``I was somewhat surprised. Cal will
always be a legend, and I can't believe anybody will ever come
close to touching his record. I thought it was a good idea to end
it, at this time _ but at the same time, we didn't want to do
something damaging to Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken said after Sunday's 5-4 loss to the Yankees that he
thought during the summer about ending his streak, and tried to
identify the best possible timing, in the best possible place. He
spoke to his wife, to his close circle of friends, to his parents.
Ripken considered ending his streak on the season's final day, when
the Orioles are to play in Boston. But ultimately, he determined
closure would come here, in Baltimore, in the final home game of
the year, with the Orioles out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it and decided, `Let's end it in the same
place it started,''' Ripken said. ``In my home state, in front of
the best fans in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken called his parents earlier in the day and received ``the
answer I expected to hear'' _ they supported whatever decision he
made. He did not tell teammates after arriving at Camden Yards on
Sunday, and he went through his usual pre-game routine. Miller
penciled Ripken into his lineup, though the manager acknowledged,
``I had a feeling,'' based on their previous conversation.
</P>
<P>
   About half an hour before the game, Ripken walked into Miller's
office and said, ``Today's the day.'' Miller responded. ``Are you
sure?'' The manager repeated that question twice more before he
scratched Ripken's name from the lineup and replaced it with that
of Ryan Minor. Ripken called Angelos at home to deliver the news
directly.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Ripken said: ``Baseball has always been a team
game, and I've always thought the focus should be on the team, and
there have been times during the streak that the focus was on the
streak, and I never felt totally comfortable with that. It just
reached a point where I firmly believe it was time to change the
subject and restore the focus back where it should be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ripken always plays catch in front of the Orioles' dugout before
each game, but when he did not appear, some of the Yankees began to
wonder whether they were about to witness history. ``He was sitting
over there, waiting like a possum for something to happen,'' said
Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chambliss, the hitting coach, usually carries the Yankees'
lineup to the umpires before each game, but Torre, suspecting
something, went instead. Miller walked out of the Orioles' dugout,
and when Torre reached eagerly for his counterpart's lineup card,
Miller pulled back. ``And then I saw Minor's name in there,'' Torre
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Torre returned to the dugout, some of his players examined
the lineup card like a priceless relic _ a Baltimore lineup without
Ripken's name included. Joe Girardi, the Yankee catcher, suggested
to others that after the first out they should all step out and tip
their caps to Ripken. Later, Ripken would say that this gesture
touched him deeply.
</P>
<P>
   In the Baltimore dugout, the phone rang. Alan Mills, a relief
pitcher, called to ask Ripken what he was doing and why he did not
tell anybody, and so Ripken made a point of spending some time in
the bullpen, chatting with fans. When Ripken was in the dugout, he
fidgeted constantly, shifting his hands and his feet, not sure what
to do or how to kill time. So that's what a day off feels like, he
remarked later.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he intended to start Ripken in the rest of the games
this season. Ripken said he still viewed himself ``as an everyday
player,'' and he will go into next year preparing to play every
game, as he has his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the streak is over, Ripken will have more freedom
to take a day off, and Miller will have more freedom to incorporate
other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a realist,'' Ripken said. ``At some point, it was going to
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
