<DOCNO> NYT19980921.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RIALTO-HERITAGE-AR     09-21 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RIALTO-HERITAGE-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMISE OF ART DECO TEMPLE OF LESS-THAN-HIGH ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Rialto Theater, ``Romper Room'' and ``Liquid
Lips'' were neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   No other building so jauntily symbolized the bewildering
confluence in Times Square of showmen, con men, impresarios,
prelates and hustlers than the Jazz Age jewel box called the
Rialto, at ground zero, Broadway and 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Like the square itself, the Rialto catered to every taste;
sometimes simultaneously, as in the 1970s, when X-rated films
played in the auditorium downstairs while ``The Joe Franklin
Show,'' ``Bowling for Dollars'' and ``Romper Room'' were being
broadcast from the WOR-TV studios upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   And like the square itself _ at least those Runyonesque,
dime-a-dance, quarter-a-peep vestiges of an imperfectly remembered
era _ the Rialto is about to be consigned to history.
</P>
<P>
   In its place, a 30-story corporate nerve center called the
Reuters Building is to begin rising next year.
</P>
<P>
   While other buildings have been razed to make way for the
redevelopment of 42nd Street, the Rialto stands out for its
exuberant architecture, historical roots (an earlier Rialto was
built on the same spot in 1898) and inimitable cast of characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a place near and dear to my life,'' said Geraldo
Rivera, whose nose was broken there. Now the host of ``Rivera
Live'' and an anchor on CNBC, Rivera broadcast from the Rialto
between 1986 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Franklin's talk show was based at the Rialto for
more than a dozen of its 43 years on the air. ``I'm going to miss
the organic, from-the-bones feeling I got from the Rialto,''
Franklin said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Already, demolition crews are at work. But no one is surprised
by the theater's demise. That was as good as guaranteed in 1981,
when state and city officials drew up plans to build four office
towers at the crossroads of 42nd Street, Broadway and Seventh
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Preservation fever scarcely touched the Rialto. Its distinctive
features _ columns of milky-white glass blocks, chevronlike
casement windows, round-edged aluminum fins and cobalt-blue glass
panels _ are on the second and third floors. New Yorkers rarely
gaze that high.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, with ground-floor tenants like the Funny Store, an
emporium of rubber chickens and whoopee cushions, who could blame
them?)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was written off as not important when the fate of 42nd
Street was decided,'' said Francoise Bollack, an architect and
architectural historian. ``It was so hidden behind boards and signs
that it took more imagination than was available to remember it or
see what it looked like.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A century ago, Oscar Hammerstein built a theater called the
Victoria at Broadway and 42nd Street. It was renamed the Rialto,
calling itself the ``temple of the motion picture and shrine of
music and the allied arts'' after a remodeling in 1916, and was run
by S.L. (Roxy) Rothafel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, the present four-story structure was built. The
manager, Arthur Mayer, promised an ``ultramodern'' theater with
``perfect acoustics and sight lines in preference to grand
stairways, fabulous restrooms and marble atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosario Candela and Thomas Lamb were the architects. They
included a connection to the subway through an underground shopping
arcade, and at the corner, an 80-foot glass-block tower that
advertised Schenley whisky.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Buck's ``Fang and Claw,'' an animal picture, opened the
Rialto in December 1935. Mayer soon earned the nickname Merchant of
Menace for the steady diet he offered of mayhem, murder, mystery
and melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a flower of evil,'' The New York Times declared in 1936,
``the new Rialto Theater has endeared itself to a little coterie of
necrophiles that haunt the area as a perfect rendezvous for
Witches' Sabbats and Walpurgis Eve celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   And those were the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The postwar transformation of Times Square into a realm of
drug-dealing and prostitution took a toll on the Rialto. Its arcade
was so notorious that it was closed in 1961 by Mayor Robert Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   WOR-TV moved into studios above the auditorium in the late
1960s. Even as ``stamp out smut'' rallies were held outside,
``Romper Room'' was produced within.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hell of a place to bring 5-year-olds,'' allowed Rick
Miner, the executive director of production and engineering at
WWOR, successor to WOR.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't ideal for the elderly, either. Miner's father was once
propositioned by a young hustler at the front door. Corinne
Griffith, a silent-screen star known as the Orchid Lady, refused to
enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she saw it was a porno theater downstairs,'' Franklin
said, ``she wouldn't come to my studio.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other perils, like unreliable elevators. Neil
Borrell, now a director at WWOR, remembered a day that Terence
Cardinal Cooke, in the studio to tape a sermon, was stuck in the
elevator with a group of teen-age girls. Franklin was trapped in
the elevator for four hours with the director Otto Preminger.
``Ooooh, he was furious,'' the host recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief spell in the early '80s, the theater downstairs was
a legitimate playhouse. But the first production closed after 20
performances, the second after 14 and the third never made it out
of previews. Soon, movies like ``Hot Dog Kung Fu'' were back on the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the Rialto was turned into a first-run movie house and
renamed the Cineplex Odeon Warner. Where Arthur Mayer promised
perfect acoustics, Garth H. Drabinsky, then president of the
Cineplex Odeon chain, made a promise more in keeping with the time
and place: ``No one's going to smoke crack here.''
</P>
<P>
   That same year, after WOR moved to Secaucus, N.J., Rivera moved
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shed some blood there,'' he said, speaking of a 1988 episode
when fists and chairs were thrown and his nose was broken after a
white supremacist insulted Roy Innis, chairman of the Congress of
Racial Equality.
</P>
<P>
   New York State took possession of the Rialto in 1990. After a
renovation in 1995, several interim tenants were installed to
maintain a sense of vitality on the block.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the Reuters Building will pay homage to the
Rialto, said William C. Rudin, whose family is developing the new
tower in a joint venture with Reuters, the news and information
agency.
</P>
<P>
   An undulating band of windows and columns above the storefronts
will recall the rhythm of the Rialto facade, said Bruce Fowle of
Fox &AMP; Fowle Architects, designers of the new tower. ``We think it
will develop its own historic nostalgia over time,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Miner, however, is not convinced the Rialto can be replaced.
``It was the old Times Square milieu, which I'll miss,'' he said.
``If I wanted to live in Disneyland, I'd move to Orlando.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
