<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEYCHAIN-AD-COLUMN-NY     09-21 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYCHAIN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN ARE DECORATING THEIR BACKPACKS WITH KEYCHAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Pa., Ohio, Calif.)  (af)  
 By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents shopping this month for pencils, notebooks, crayons and
backpacks can add a new item to the school supplies list _ key
chains, and lots of them. Dangling from the backpacks of the
country's schoolchildren, they signify a booming market that barely
existed two school years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled by the sudden demand for key chains, toy and
entertainment industry executives and analysts are questioning
their own children, who decorate their backpacks with dozens of
dangling doodads. Their explanation is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like how they look on my backpack and the sound they
make when they click together,'' said Isabel Zuckoff, 9, who owns
around 30 key chains and no keys.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the motivation is how the chains look or how they sound,
or both, the trend has translated into a hot business for a handful
of companies with names like Basic Fun Inc. and the Fun 4 All Corp.
All told, toy industry analysts say, key chains priced at $3 to $10
generate around $50 million a year in retail sales to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the children in New York City,'' said Scott
Bachrach, president of Fun 4 All, which is based in New York. ``You
can go out to middle America and see children with these on their
backpacks. Where an average kid has only two keys, they're still
going to go out and buy six to eight different key chains.''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of key chains has caught the big toy companies by
surprise. After all, it is not easy to guess that children, few of
whom carry much more than a single house key, would become some of
the nation's most frequent repeat buyers of key chains.
</P>
<P>
   The small licensee companies selling key chain toys and games
``are really trying to keep it quiet,'' said Sean McGowan, an
analyst at Gerard Klauer Mattison Inc. in New York. ``There's no
reason Hasbro couldn't do it. No one knew how big it was going to
be.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why children are buying so many key chains is a complicated
story involving cheap jewelry, the Internet and Isabel's backpack.
</P>
<P>
   It begins in 1989, with Alan Dorfman, now the president of Basic
Fun, working at Larami Ltd. in Philadelphia, selling Super Soaker
water guns and dreaming of starting his own business. After he left
Larami to start Basic Fun, Dorfman started noticing young women
wearing miniature water guns as necklaces, and he asked his former
bosses for a license to market shrunken Super Soaker key chains.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Fun began shipping Super Soaker key chains in January
1993, following them the next year with Etch-a-Sketch key chains,
made under a license from the Ohio Art Co. Sales have jumped 30
percent to 60 percent a year since 1993, orfman said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's products now range from those made under license,
including cartoon characters like Nickelodeon's Rugrats and toys
like Hasbro's Potato Head, to public domain games like Tic Tac Toe.
Most of the new key chains have one thing in common: as the
grade-school set might say, they do stuff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adults are generally satisfied with key chains that look nice or
serve as mementos or souvenirs. But for children raised in the age
of computers, the most popular key chains are, of course,
interactive. That includes all of the miniature games and most of
the licensed characters.
</P>
<P>
   Curious George was fun as a quizzical little monkey, but as a
key chain, he is more fun because the hat he wears comes off.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of toy and game key chains initially sent
established purveyors of old-fashioned key chains scrambling to
catch up. Mickey Mouse and Winnie the Pooh key chains have been a
staple at the gift company Applause Inc. for years, but sales went
soft for a while after Basic Fun started luring children to
interactive key chains, a spokeswoman for Applause said.
</P>
<P>
   Then gift companies like Applause added moving parts to some of
their offerings in an effort to reclaim part of their lost sales,
and the interactive key chains settled in as a separate category
from the souvenir and trinket key chains.
</P>
<P>
   The story might have ended there, except for Isabel's backpack.
Because it seems that when children became interested in key chain
toys and games, they turned the products into a new kind of
collectible _ the nirvana of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Key chain-sized Monopoly is not easy to play. But that's no
longer the point, according to Stevanne Auerbach, a San
Francisco-based analyst who writes a syndicated column under the
name Dr. Toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be miniaturizing everything they can get their
hands on,'' Ms. Auerbach said. ``What teens like to have is
conversational items that allow them to have status in their
groups. This is the current craze.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some bygone crazes, like pogs, stickers and lunch
boxes, key chains can be marketed outside an identifiable niche.
Boys and girls both buy key chains to attach to their backpacks,
and adults will sometimes buy them to, well, attach to their keys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bachrach pitches Basic Fun's key chains to toy stores, clothing
outlets and drugstores, among others. For the big toy makers, sales
of key chains licensed from established products can mean increased
exposure without the need to develop miniatures on their own or
take the initial risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting exposure in higher traffic areas of the store
where our products are placed,'' Dorfman said. ``They're also
getting exposure in places like girls' clothing and accessory shops
where they would never sell an Etch-a-Sketch.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the toy giants may have passed up a
profitable venture. The thing is that for all their advertising
muscle, big toy makers and entertainment companies cannot create a
collectible. Only the 9-year-olds can.
</P>
<P>
   In the board rooms of the big companies, executives consider new
products. Industry staples like key chains are considered a
stagnant but reliable market best left to licensees. But with key
chains reaching collectible status, major toy makers have started
to take notice, approaching the niche companies with licensing
offers.
</P>
<P>
   But while the key chain makers have stumbled upon a collectible,
it is not necessarily the stable kind, which can be expected to
increase in value. Not even Bachrach would say that is likely to be
true of key chains. And so opinion is divided on how long the
market can be expected to remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to guess at the whims of adolescents, McGowan, the
analyst, predicted that key chains _ if not miniaturized toys _
would remain popular for some time. But Ms. Auerbach and some
retailers pointed to the start of the new school year as the big
test for any product aimed at young consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend may be over before you know it, or it may be the
second wave,'' Ms. Auerbach said. ``It's really impossible to know
what's going to catch the fancy of children.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
