<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      09-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD PUTS HIMSELF ON OUTSIDE LOOKING IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For one night, Evander Holyfield is trying a new
profession: fight analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``I like talking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will work with Sugar Ray Leonard and blow-by-blow
announcer Kevin Harlan Tuesday night for TNT on a boxing show in
the Theater at Madison Square Garden. Dressed in black for a
production meeting yesterday in a sixth-floor office at the Garden,
Holyfield looked unscathed from his unanimous yet uninspired
12-round decision over Vaughn Bean 36 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield insisted that he would fight his next mandatory bout,
against Henry Akinwande, and then seek to unify the heavyweight
championship against Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council
titleholder. Mike Tyson is not in his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is the undisputed championship,'' said Holyfield, who
holds the International Boxing Federation and World Boxing
Association titles. ``I want to get there as quick as possible. I'd
only fight Tyson if he has a title.'' Jim Thomas, Holyfield's
lawyer, said, ``He has no need or desire to fight Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield appeared energized at the production meeting, talking
to boxers about nutrition, electrolytes, making weight and having
candid advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're at the top, you're alone,'' he told Sugar Shane
Mosley, the IBF lightweight champion, who is scheduled to fight
Eduardo Morales. ``I have a trainer who I have to listen to. You
need people who are always adding something to improve you. You
need a corner that tells you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mosley, the fighter's father, said: ``That's what I've told
him since he's 8. If he's looking bad, I have to tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen you box,'' Holyfield told Mosley. ``I've seen the
way you shift gears. Go up one level, then two more levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But with control,'' Jack Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be in great shape to make your heart rate go up
and down, up and down,'' Holyfield said. ``It's easy to fight a
fast fight or a slow fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cranky when I'm not doing something,'' Shane Mosley said.
``That's why I went to the gym in the first place. I was 6,
bouncing off the walls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You were 6, I was 8,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was quiet as Leonard talked to Angel Manfredy, the
World Boxing Union super featherweight champion, a fiercely
confident personality with a torso full of tattoos, a religious
conversion and numerous car accidents on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in 13 car accidents,'' Manfredy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same car?'' Leonard asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, 13 cars,'' he said. ``My last one I didn't walk away from.
That's when I met the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many tattoos do you have?'' Harlan asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me to count?'' Manfredy asked as he doffed a tank
top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one,'' said Leonard, and he pulled aside his pullover to
show it on his chest. ``It's the most pain I ever felt. Especially
in the soft tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Del Valle, a Bronx light heavyweight who lost a fight last
July to Roy Jones Jr., confessed to Holyfield and Leonard that he
had ``choked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have fought better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you learn?'' Leonard asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I have to be more disciplined,'' Del Valle said. He said
he has let his weight soar between fights, forcing him to lose too
much to make weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``How high have you gone?'' Leonard asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two twenty-eight,'' Del Valle said. ``It all goes to my
thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a heavyweight,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle nodded, seemingly abashed at trying to restart his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you knocked Jones down, what did you think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dollar signs,'' Del Valle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hurt him and really raised him off the canvas,'' Leonard
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd hurt him more,'' Del Valle said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Armstead, a bouncer from Evansville, Ind., will face Del
Valle. After discussing how he came to accept the fight two days
before, his laconic face lit up. He had finally noticed Leonard,
sitting to Holyfield's left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey man, I didn't recognize you,'' Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen Del Valle fight?'' asked Dave Harmon, the
producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know who he is,'' Armstead said.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon expects to have few problems in quickly molding a
credible team out of Harlan, who is calling only his second fight,
Holyfield, who last called a fight for TBS in 1988, and Leonard, a
former HBO commentator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's part will come naturally,'' he said. ``I've talked to
Kevin about how to get Evander and Ray involved. My job is to make
sure they get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlan, Holyfield and Leonard, with the reporter Craig Sager,
will be hard-pressed to match Steve Albert, Ferdie Pacheco and
Bobby Czyz, who called the Holyfield-Bean card Saturday night for
Showtime. Suddenly, they have become blisteringly candid
commentators who question boxers' credentials to fight.
</P>
<P>
   And the reporter Jim Gray's interviews with Don King, Holyfield,
Bean and Shelly Finkel, Tyson's adviser, were models for the
profession.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: among King's guests Saturday were eight of the
jurors who acquitted him last July of Federal insurance fraud
charges, said Billy Murphy Jr., one of King's lawyers. King also
treated them to a Bahamas getaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
