<HEADLINE>
WITH JOBS GOING BEGGING, FLORIDA COMPANIES ADAPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS BLANK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ BellSouth Telecommunications of Miami, a unit of
BellSouth Corp., says it has taken more than six months to fill 500
newly created jobs in Florida. Even more surprising, it went
through 10,000 applicants before getting the people it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The story is the same for other big corporate employers
throughout the South but particularly in Florida, where a lot of
companies have largely abandoned normal recruiting procedures such
as classified advertising to rely on giving signing bonuses,
putting notices on the Internet and offering prizes to employees
who bring in new workers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lacher, president of the BellSouth unit, is frustrated that
high schools and colleges are not turning out more qualified
people. ``We have made 10,000 contacts, and we cannot find a
sufficient number of people,'' he said. ``That certainly raises
questions about our education system.''
</P>
<P>
   It also says something about the tightness of the labor market
at a time when unemployment nationwide is just 4.5 percent; it is
even lower in many economic hot spots such as Florida and
California.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Telecommunications now has a work force of 12,000 in
Florida, and customer demand for more phones forced the company to
create the new jobs last December. Starting pay for phone service
representatives is $19,200 a year and for installers, $21,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a virtual explosion in people adding second
lines,'' said Spero Canton, a company spokesman. ``Growth has gone
beyond people's expectations. The demand for second lines for
modems, fax machines and a kid's line is standard now.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has a very ``demanding'' test, which results in a
high number of failures, Canton said. In addition, most applicants
do not have enough technical education or do not pass the company
drug test, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, it has taken longer than we expected,'' Canton
said, ``but we are still making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The pool of qualified applicants for both skilled and unskilled
jobs continues to shrink as the state's unemployment rate rides at
a low 4.3 percent, with Orlando the lowest at 3 percent, according
to the latest figures. It is common for major employers like Walt
Disney Co., Harris Corp. and Stein Mart to have thousands of
vacancies posted all the time.
</P>
<P>
   More employers are extending their searches to other states and
scouring the Internet job boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is tight up and down the skill levels,'' said Kevin
Brickey, an economist with the Florida Department of Labor. ``We're
seeing quite a lot of employers expand their efforts to a larger
radius than they once did.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in some less skilled jobs, such as those in fast-food
restaurants, employers are raising wages for new workers by 25
cents an hour or more to attract help. And many jobs still go
unfilled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Disney, the largest employer in the state at a single site _
with 51,000 workers _ has more than 1,000 job openings and is
looking at ways to improve recruiting. ``We are constantly
reinventing ourselves,'' said Kelly Frank, Disney's director of
employment in Orlando. ``We are constantly evaluating our
recruiting tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney frequently offers signing bonuses of $2,000 and in some
cases up to $10,000 for hard-to-fill high-technology jobs.
Moreover, seasonal workers now get a full 40-hour work week with
benefits and more flexible schedules. A few years ago, most got
part-time hours and no benefits.
</P>
<P>
   At Stein Mart Inc., a chain of 900 family clothing stores in 30
states that is based in Jacksonville, Fla., its stores are ``never
totally staffed,'' said Hunt Hawkins, the human resources director.
``It is like spitting in the wind, to put out expensive classified
advertising,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stein Mart replaced classified advertising with a reward program
for employees who refer new store clerks, who start at $5.50 to
$6.50 an hour. The recruiting employees are given shirts and hats,
and managers get annual $100 bonuses. Even so, the chain says it
takes at least 10 interviews to hire one person.
</P>
<P>
   A task force is putting together a plan to ``identify creative
approaches'' to recruiting the workers needed, especially in major
population centers such as Atlanta, Chicago and San Jose, Calif.,
Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   At Harris Corp., a military contractor and manufacturer of
communications equipment that is based in Melbourne, Fla., and
employs 29,000 worldwide, it usually takes six to eight weeks to
fill an opening, Ronald Hutt, senior manager of human resources,
said. Computer-related high-technology positions may go unfilled
for four to five months.
</P>
<P>
   While Harris continues to use classified advertising, job fairs
and $2,000 signing bonuses, it has also found a new conduit by
opening a Web site for college graduates. The candidates can look
over available jobs and file their resumes electronically. In
addition, Harris has built up an internship program with specific
schools that refer top students who alternate working for a
semester and going to school for a semester.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers have also established junior college branches at
work locations to allow workers to take courses in the evening so
they can advance. The Peabody Hotel in Orlando, which employs 800,
has expanded its offerings from food service to marketing,
accounting and convention management courses under a cooperative
agreement with Valencia College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
