<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CURRIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL CURRIER, 37, RANCHER WHO HELPED TIBETANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Pa., Va.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Stephen Currier, a rancher and philanthropist who was
the manager of the Economic Development Fund for the Tibetan
Community in Exile, died on Wednesday at St. Vincent's Hospital in
Santa Fe, N.M. He was 37, and lived in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was injuries suffered in a fall in Santa Fe, his
family said through a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years before his death, he was the manager of the exiles
fund, which he established. The revolving loan fund provides
technical and other aid for small businesses operated by Tibetan
refugees and their descendants in India and the United States.
Those businesses include various Tibetan crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Currier, who visited Tibet and made many trips to meet with
Tibetans in India, wanted to help make Tibetan refugees
economically self-sufficient and to help preserve Tibetan religious
and cultural traditions. The fund was a major recipient of his
philanthropic largess in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   His family said that they had received a message from the Dalai
Lama, whose headquarters are in India. ``He has been especially
generous in the help he gave us Tibetans,'' the message said, ``and
we will always remain grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the Dalai Lama presented the Light of Truth Award, a
high honor, to Currier.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, he was the son of Stephen Currier and the
former Audrey Mellon Bruce, co-founders of the Taconic Foundation,
whose operations have included programs to further equal
opportunity with emphasis on housing and jobs for young people.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Currier's mother was the granddaughter of Andrew Mellon,
the financier, industrialist and philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   Currier's parents vanished in 1967, while in a private plane
flying over the Caribbean Sea. They were never found.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised by a guardian, graduating from Collegiate School
in New York, Putney School in Vermont and Williams College. In his
early 20s he was a patron of the Morgan Library and of the Gauchos,
a basketball program for children in New York.
</P>
<P>
   An orphan himself, he was devoted to his own children and gave
many grants to programs providing nurturing for children. A grant
from him in 1985 helped expand a community foundation founded by
blacks in Pittsburgh. Other grants from him in the same period
helped found a mental-health crisis center and a wild horse
sanctuary, both in California.
</P>
<P>
   After he moved to Santa Fe, his philanthropies, mostly
anonymous, came to include Southwestern charitable organizations
concerned with the environment, rural economic development, care
and education for needy children and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the boards of the Taconic Foundation, the Putney
School, the Forest Trust of New Mexico and the Santa Fe Waldorf
School.
</P>
<P>
   He also collected art, chiefly drawings of the old masters and
Chinese works.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Karin Griscom; two sons
and a daughter; two sisters, Andrea Currier and Lavinia Currier of
Plains, Va., and a grandmother, Mary Warburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
