<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS-HARRIS LAUGH-IN LOOSENS THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all that they have given the New York Mets on the
field, the biggest contribution Lenny Harris and Tony Phillips have
made this season may be the smile they have helped put on Mike
Piazza's face. And on the faces of most of their other teammates,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to do it,'' John Franco said of Harris'
sometimes merciless, always good-natured needling of Piazza, who
admits he is now enjoying his stay with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just keeping him loose is a big contribution,'' Harris said of
Piazza. ``He's been asking me, `Are you coming back?' And I keep
saying, `If you are, I definitely am. If not, I'll have to go
somewhere else.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mike will be back. He keeps asking me. And I keep
telling him, `I want to be right there behind you. It will be your
spare change.'''
</P>
<P>
   If Harris, who like Piazza can be a free agent after the season,
does not re-sign with the Mets, who will play Motown CDs and do
Temptations dance steps for his teammates? And if Piazza re-signs
and Harris does not, who will be all over the All-Star catcher's
back?
</P>
<P>
   Harris said on Sunday that he will be keeping in touch with
Piazza during the off-season, because Piazza is planning on buying
a house in Harris' native Florida. As if Piazza doesn't get enough
of his former Dodgers teammate now.
</P>
<P>
   When Harris isn't all over Piazza, he is usually going at it
with Phillips, and everyone within earshot is laughing at the class
clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're veteran guys, they've been around and they keep
everyone loose,'' Franco said. ``They've been through this before.
So they know what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' is a playoff race, something Franco, 38, has never
really been through before. But the Mets, who begin a two-game
series at Shea Stadium Tuesday night with the Montreal Expos, have
a one-game lead over the Chicago Cubs in the National League
wild-card race with five games to go.
</P>
<P>
   And Harris and Phillips are two of the reasons why. Phillips,
39, who was acquired from Toronto at the July 31 trading deadline,
played in two World Series with the Oakland Athletics. Harris, 33,
who was obtained from Cincinnati on July 3 for John Hudek, has been
in the playoffs once. Aside from Al Leiter and John Olerud, who won
World Series rings with the Florida Marlins and the Toronto Blue
Jays, and Dennis Cook, Carlos Baerga and Piazza, the Mets are
lacking in postseason experience.
</P>
<P>
   Which adds to Phillips' and Harris' value.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great veteran players who are terrific guys,'' Manager
Bobby Valentine said after Phillips went 2-for-3 with a run batted
in and a run scored and Harris went 3-for-4 with a run batted in on
Sunday, when the Mets regained the wild-card lead with a 5-0
victory over the Marlins. ``I think that helps immeasurably. They
are good guys added to a good mix. And they are good players.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, said Phillips, is the only contribution that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To heck with that contributing in the clubhouse,'' Phillips
said. ``That doesn't keep you playing. If I don't get the job done,
I'm going to be back at my home in Arizona. I don't fall for that
trash, that the reason I'm around is because people like me. The
reason I'm here is that they think I can get the job done. And I
can get the job done.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, Phillips has provided the Mets with the lead-off hitter
they had lacked. Even though he is batting only .235 in 47 games,
Phillips' 35 walks are the fifth most on the team. And Phillips has
played only 30 percent of the Mets' 157 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great for the ball club that he's been here,''
Harris said of Phillips. ``Without a doubt. Everybody thinks he has
an attitude. But he has an attitude toward the game. Nobody is more
prepared than him.''
</P>
<P>
   High praise. Which, of course, did not stop Harris from taking
one last shot at Phillips. ``He's the best at the joking part,''
said Harris, who has solidified the Mets' outfield since Butch
Huskey went down with an ankle injury and Todd Hundley was taken
out of the starting lineup. ``But Tony's got the worst laugh I've
ever heard in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   One that the Mets have heard frequently with both Harris and
Phillips around.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, who has reached base in 14 consecutive plate
appearances, was named the National League player of the week. It
was the second time this year he had been honored and the fifth
time he had been player of the week, three times in the NL and
twice in the American League. The last time a Met won the award
twice in a season was 1985, when Dwight Gooden and Darryl
Strawberry both won twice. ... Mike Piazza will re-sign with the
Mets if co-owner Nelson Doubleday has any say in it. ``We have
decided to make every effort we can to sign him,'' Doubleday said.
``The way things are going now for Mike here in New York is better
now than it has been. It's really his call. But lord knows, I want
him to stay.'' Will the Mets offer Piazza the $100 million contract
he has indicated he will be seeking? When asked if money was the
issue, Doubleday said: ``From the sublime to the ridiculous, to
that extent it's an issue. But any numbers we've seen or heard are
not ridiculous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
