<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WATCH-NY-1STL     09-21 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WATCH-NY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS SPEND LITTLE TIME ON CLINTON VIDEO  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Inserts sentence in graf that begins ``I think it's interesting.''
No other changes.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-PERJURY,
CLINTON-IMAGE, CLINTON-MONICA, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-TACTIC,
CLINTON-WATCH-SEATTLE, CLINTON-WATCH-ATLANTA, CLINTON-WATCH-DENVER,
CLINTON-TV-REVIEW, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-EVIDENCE,
CLINTON-MONICA-TEXT, CLINTON-LETTERS-TEXT) 
(lb) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finally the anchors and pundits fell silent, the tape
rolled, a fuzzy image of President Clinton came on the screens, and
...
</P>
<P>
   And most people continued doing what they were doing on a mild
morning in a city slowed somewhat by the Jewish new year holiday.
When they did pause to watch, whether in a cafe, in an electronics
shop or on the screens at the News Corp. building on 48th and
Sixth, it was often with fatigue, shame and a distinct dollop of
sympathy for a man being painfully humiliated before their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother, what a screwball, what a sick man,'' muttered Albert
Navarrate, a jeweler from Queens, more in sadness than in anger,
after a particularly legalistic riff by Clinton outside News Corp.
``I mean he's a good president, he just screwed up. But children
shouldn't be exposed to this,'' he added, as the words ``oral sex''
echoed from the screen and flashed by again and again on the
electric ribbon above.
</P>
<P>
   Like Navarrate, most people listened a few minutes and moved on.
The shock value had long worn off, and everyone knew that the
testimony would be shown again and again all day, that the ordeal
was far from over. When a reporter approached one man and explained
that he was trolling for comments, the man wagged his head in
sympathy: ``Oh, I feel sorry for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have already made up their minds, and what they're
seeing is only reinforcing their opinions,'' said the man, Thomas
Karle, a lawyer with McGraw Hill from Wilton, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   His opinion? ``I'm an attorney, and I view perjury and the
ability of the courts to punish it as the basis of law. It's all
sex and juicy, but it's still perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement home in Seattle, residents expressed a grudging
respect for Clinton, at his ability to maintain control under hours
of questioning, but they also expressed a clear sadness that the
country was being put through such a spectacle. ``We live in a
different world these days, I guess,'' said Nancy Cadley, 77, a
retired nurse who served in a medical unit in World War II and the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   On the campus of Emory University in Atlanta, a group of six
students, who already had strong opinions on Clinton before the
video was released, saw its airing as just more embarrassment
heaped on the man, his office, and the nation he leads.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in New York, by far the more common reaction was sympathy
and even support for the president. Not absolution, certainly not
approval for what everyone agreed was gross and silly behavior, but
a sense that the public humiliation was out of all proportion to
his human weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad and cruel that he should go through this, that all
this should be made public,'' said a woman in her 30s. ``I don't
understand where they get the right to release this. It's
incredibly wrong. I mean, if the grand jury sat us all down and
asked about that topic, sex, how many people wouldn't commit
perjury?'' As if to punctuate the point, the woman resolutely
refused to give her name or job.
</P>
<P>
   In an admittedly unscientific sampling of street opinion, women
seemed more apt to show sympathy for the president than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political analysis I'm hearing during the breaks in the
coverage is contrary to my opinion,'' declared Joan Gilbert, a
public relations specialist. ``I am very sympathetic to Clinton. I
think he's being harassed and I think he is handling himself with
great diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's apologized, hasn't he?'' said a woman waiting for a
flight at Newark Airport, who said she was 80 and gave her name
only as Anna. ``He's been a good president. I'm sick of it. It's
his own personal business what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, Deborah Campbell, a corrections officer from Queens,
echoed the sentiment over breakfast at Sylvia's Restaurant. ``In my
eyes it really doesn't matter. It's his personal life, and he's
doing a great job,'' she said. ``It shouldn't be shown on TV _ but
since it is, New Yorkers want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all did. Dominic Romero, a chauffeur from White Plains, said
he was listening to the testimony only because he had nothing
better to do while waiting in his car outside the Colony Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired of this,'' he said. ``I'm so disgusted with
Republicans and Democrats that I'm going to vote for a third party
next time. We've got no leader. We're the laughing stock of the
whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those few who took a stern position toward the president,
like the attorney Karle, the usual reason was the public lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton just dissembles too much,'' said David Pocock, a
music-festival director who watched the testimony at Newark Airport
while waiting for a flight to Indianapolis. ``When you see him on
television like this, it's just remarkable how smooth and slick he
can be. He's been too smooth and too slick for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the drama on the screen, there was no sense across the
city that life had stopped, or even slowed, for the four-hour
broadcast. A random check of smokers outside office buildings
suggested that the only major obstacle to business-as-usual was the
Jewish holiday and the streets closed in midtown because of
Clinton's presence at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're too busy watching the market go down to watch the
president go down,'' said Bill Takos, while taking a break for a
smoke outside the Oscar Gruss brokerage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Fifth Avenue nearby, Peter Katz was checking his window
display at the Alfred Dunhill shop. ``Watch TV? Of course not. I'm
at work,'' he declared with a note of indignation. ``I think when
you look at everything we're read and seen, the American public
would just as soon see the whole scenario end. It's not what the
American people want.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Borders book store on Fifth Avenue, signs everywhere
proclaimed, ``The Starr Report Is Here.'' But the latest
installment of the Clinton saga was not there. The television at
the espresso bar was showing another video, said John Hinte, a
manager at the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself get information overload from the whole inquiry, the
whole rigmarole,'' he said. ``I'm a little overwhelmed by all this
information.'' But the Starr report, he admitted, was selling quite
briskly.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wiz, a large electronics store on Third Avenue, a wall of
television screens was showing an action movie. Only one 9-inch
screen at the end of the row was tuned, badly, to President
Clinton. ``The manager didn't want a crowd in here,'' explained a
salesman.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three people watching, only one said he had actually
dropped in for a quick gulp of testimony _ in the hope, he said, of
seeing Clinton get angry. ``We've had very few opportunities to see
Clinton showing strong emotions, and I read in The New York Times
that the tape could show that side of Clinton,'' explained Roberto
Sarmento, a manager of business planning with Philip Morris. He ran
out of time before Clinton got angry, but he said his wife was
taping the entire appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The manager at the Electronic Factory in the Bronx took the
opposite tack and tuned all his television sets to the president's
testimony. ``It's been on all morning, but customers aren't
interested,'' said the manager, J.D. Sabatt. ``Who cares? I've been
looking at his facial expressions, but really, it's because it's
the only channel that comes in clear.'' By noon, Sabatt said, he
had yet to sell a single set.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent refrain in the streets was concern that children were
being exposed to all the frank sex talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's interesting that whoever chose to release these
tapes chose the time when every child in America would be home from
school for the Jewish holiday,'' said Jeanne Pedro, watching the
testimony at her home in Mamaroneck. While most schoolchildren in
the nation were in classes on Monday, many children in the New York
region were out of school because of the holiday. ``I don't think
it's necessary for children to be listening to conversations about
oral sex and intercourse,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But few adults themselves seemed shocked by what they heard, at
least not any more.
</P>
<P>
   On the TV at a coffee shop in Newark Airport, the president was
being questioned about where his secretary was during a visit from
Monica Lewinsky, when an elderly woman turned around and said for
all to hear, ``President Kennedy did worse!''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he seems sincere and actually appealing,'' said Ruth
Finn, 78, a retired real-estate salesperson from Rye, after
watching the first two hours of testimony. ``Also, I don't see so
far what's so raunchy and graphic about this. Dan Rather gave a
warning at the outset, but so far, it seems fairly tame. The
average MTV video is far, far worse in terms of raunch and bad
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a psychological point of view, it's fascinating to see so
private a side of so public a person. His reactions, his responses
_ we're seeing something we're never seen before in a president.
It's really a historical moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a drug,'' said Howard Enders, a professor of writing
at Purchase College. ``It keys into our own need to face the dark
side of ourselves _ if, indeed, we have to face it. Everyone says
they're sick of it, and then they go and watch it. We're watching a
drama unfold, a tragedy of Greek proportions. As I watched,'' he
added, ``I felt sympathy for Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
