<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 MONTGOMERY CHIEF QUITS IN DISPUTE WITH NATIONSBANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Weisel, one of the best-known investment bankers on the
U.S. West Coast, resigned Monday as chairman and chief executive of
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities LLC after months of bitter
quarreling with his new bosses in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The parent Nationsbank Corp. of Charlotte, N.C., the country's
third-largest bank, bought Weisel's company, Montgomery Securities
of San Francisco, for $1.2 billion last October to form Nationsbanc
Montgomery, as it sought to build itself a bigger and more
lucrative investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, which Weisel founded, grew rapidly in recent years,
particularly by acting as an investment banker in the
fastest-growing industries, like high technology and
telecommunications, including many Silicon Valley companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Nationsbank, with a button-down culture born in successful
commercial banking, and Weisel and his coterie, with a West Coast
entrepreneurial culture, almost immediately fell into squabbling
over who would run what at the newly formed Nationsbanc Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel and his colleagues thought they had an agreement, as part
of the sale, that gave them the right to manage, from Montgomery's
San Francisco offices, specific areas of investment banking,
including high-yield bonds, equity investing and the business of
providing services to big investors like leveraged-buyout funds.
</P>
<P>
   Nationsbank, however, arguing that it was responding to changing
business conditions, wanted to manage such businesses more from
Charlotte as part of its overall banking business.
</P>
<P>
   It also maintained that it had the right to organize its
businesses after paying $1.2 billion to acquire Montgomery. Around
the same time, Nationsbank's top managers were becoming
increasingly preoccupied with trying to manage the huge-scale
acquisition of BankAmerica Corp., which was announced in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that I've resigned,'' Weisel said Monday, ``is that
we just have a difference over vision and strategy for the
organization.'' He declined to make any further comment about his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Brown III, Nationsbank's managing director for global
capital-raising and global markets, said: ``We are driven to have
investment banking businesses that are in sync with our whole
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take a look at the power of our franchise, we will miss
him, but we will go forward,'' he said of Weisel. ``He was good at
attracting a very successful group of people who are joining our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Coleman, chief operating officer of the Montgomery
division of Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities, is expected to
succeed Weisel as chief executive, according to people at the
parent company and the investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to end the squabbling and to allow Weisel to
depart, Nationsbank also recently agreed to accelerate its payments
to him and to at least some of his partners from Montgomery. Under
the original agreement signed last year, these payments were to be
made over a three-year period. But according to Montgomery
executives, those payments are being made now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
