<SLUG> BC-SHORT-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOVERED SHORT SALES RISE TO A RECORD ON THE BIG BOARD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions of short sales on the New York Stock
Exchange rose 2.6 percent last month, to a record 4.21 billion
shares, the exchange said Monday. On the smaller American Stock
Exchange, uncovered short sales fell seven-tenths of 1 percent, to
204.28 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered short sales, or those with open positions, are those
shares that have been borrowed and sold, but not yet covered by
repurchase. If the share price falls, an investor can profit by
buying shares at a lower price to replace the borrowed ones.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, the short-interest figure for the month ended
Sept. 15 was equal to 1.8 percent of the total shares listed on the
exchange. The total surpassed the previous record of 4.13 billion
shares in July. The August decline was the first monthly drop since
January.
</P>
<P>
   American International Group, the insurance and financial
services giant, showed the largest increase in short interest on
the Big Board, with the number of shares sold short more than
tripling, to 17,547,925.
</P>
<P>
   While high short-interest positions may indicate a rise in
bearish sentiments, short interest can also increase as a result of
complex trading strategies involving options, futures and other
stock-related derivatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
