<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE APPEARS ON LEWINSKY LIST  
 ADULT VIDEO STORE WITH STANDARDS  
 TEMPORARY HOME FOR THE HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John F. Kennedy Jr. and his editors at George
magazine were surprised to learn Monday that George had been on
Monica Lewinsky's wish list of potential jobs in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   George was one possibility she mentioned in a note about her
aspirations that was described in the report Kenneth Starr sent to
Congress on Sept. 11. Among other choices, she said she would take
``anything at George magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd certainly consider her,'' said Lisa Dallos, a spokeswoman
for the magazine. ``She's had a unique political experience.'' But
Ms. Dallos said that no one had approached the magazine about Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the note, Ms. Lewinsky also expressed interest in a job in
television. ``Kaplan _ CNN has a N.Y. Office,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   This was apparently a reference to Rick Kaplan, who joined the
all-news network in August 1997 as president of CNN/U.S. Steve
Haworth, a spokesman for CNN, said that the network had not been
approached about finding a job for Ms. Lewinsky and would not
consider hiring her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's note also mentioned ``news/political segments at
MTV.'' A spokeswoman for that network said she had been unaware of
Ms. Lewinsky's interest until a reporter called on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Adult Video Store With Standards
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``That's like a pornography thing, but with their
clothes on,'' said Ralph Testa, watching the president's grand jury
testimony from behind the counter at the Playpen, an adult-oriented
video store on Eighth Avenue near 45th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The picture on Testa's ceiling-mounted television was snowy _ it
was not connected to cable, which could have delivered clear
reception. But the sound was fine. The prosecutor's questions and
the president's answers were loud and clear, and Testa did not like
what he was hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion, I think they should leave the man alone,'' Testa
said. ``Of course if he'd told it the way it was, he wouldn't have
this problem now.'' Testa said that most customers had paid little
attention to the president's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Would Testa sell a videotape of the president's testimony if
copies were available? He paused and looked up at the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would,'' he said. ``He's the president. I feel
it would be wrong to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Temporary Home For the Holidays
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Isabell, the Manhattan party and floral
designer, relaxed Monday after creating a sanctuary for the Central
Synagogue inside the cavernous Seventh Regiment Armory on the Upper
East Side. The congregation, whose 126-year-old architectural
landmark home was badly damaged in a fire last month, celebrated
the first day of Rosh ha-Shannah in a temporary sanctuary that
looked anything but makeshift, what with the elaborate painted
backdrop that Isabell had installed in time for the Sunday night
service that opened the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an antique show in there 16 hours before our
service,'' he said, ``so we had 16 hours to transform the armory.
We had to do all the lighting and rigging and walls, and give it a
sense of a religious sanctuary. Everybody who was coming would feel
a sense of loss and mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   He filled the armory with 3,800 seats _ the synagogue's old
sanctuary seated only about 1,200 people _ in rows with
16-foot-wide aisles (city regulations required only 8-foot aisles,
he said, but he took no chances). He also arranged for
air-conditioning in the armory, which the congregation will use for
Yom Kippur services next week. Then Isabell's work will be stored
in a warehouse until next year, when it will be brought out again.
Repairs to the synagogue are expected to take two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing was it was a little brighter than the original
Central Synagogue,'' Isabell said. ``Everybody always said it was
too dark to read the prayer books. We gave them a little more light
this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
