<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-QB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS SAYS FOLEY IS THE STARTER, BUT MUST PROVE HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Late last week, as the Jets prepared for their
meeting with the Indianapolis Colts, Bill Parcells sneaked up
behind Glenn Foley and delivered a blow to the quarterback's torn
rib cartilage. It was not a hard shot, just barely a touch, but
Foley said he nearly collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   To Parcells, that settled the issue of who was going to start at
quarterback. Vinny Testaverde got the assignment and delivered a
nearly flawless performance, throwing four touchdown passes to lead
the Jets to their first victory of the season after two defeats, a
44-6 rout of the hapless Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The steady handling of the team by Testaverde, a 12-year
veteran, raised a question as to whether he would remain as the
starter. Foley's most strenuous physical activity on Sunday came
when he raced onto the field to congratulate Testaverde on a
first-quarter touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells quashed the notion of a quarterback controversy,
declaring after the game that if Foley was ready for the Jets' next
game, Oct. 4 against the Miami Dolphins, he would be the starter.
And while Parcells repeated that Monday, he also gave the same
message verbally that he had delivered to Foley physically with the
jab last week: Foley must prove he is ready on the field, not just
declare himself fit.
</P>
<P>
   Foley has mouthed the brave words before, including in the days
leading up to last season's finale against the Detroit Lions. He
could not play, though, and in the end Parcells had to give the
ball to Neil O'Donnell. The Jets lost, 13-10, and were knocked out
of a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   When informed that Foley said after Sunday's game that he would
be ready for the next game, Parcells said: ``I've heard that
before. There was no doubt before the Detroit game last year,
remember? I remember those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what I look for: I've got to see he has enough
wherewithal to stand in there, throw the ball, and be willing to
take contact without the fear of that contact influencing how he's
going to perform. If I feel like the fear of that contact is going
to influence how he's going to perform, I'm going to take the other
guy and play him in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about how the ball flies spiral-wise. It's when
somebody runs into him, what happens? Can he take it or can't he
take it? If he can take it, he's going to play. If he can't take
it, he's not going to play and I'll use him in spot duty.``
</P>
<P>
   With the team just meeting Monday, not practicing, and then
taking a day off on Tuesday, Foley's word is all Parcells has for
now. But beginning Wednesday, Foley will have seven days of
practice to prove to his coach that he can do the job, at least
soothed by words of support from Parcells, even if the physical jab
stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten a lot better,'' Foley said of the pain in his
ribs. ``Bill tested it the other day when he came up behind me and
gave me a little rap on the side to test it and see how it was. I
nearly collapsed. He just wanted to make sure I wasn't faking it.
He said, `I guess you're not ready.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have practiced today, I think I could practice.
But again, we've got a couple days here to relax, let it heal up a
little more, and then go out in practice and see how it is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until it is proven to Parcells that Foley can perform at a
higher level than Testaverde can, the assignment is up for grabs.
The notion that a starter cannot lose a job to injury is not part
of Parcells' beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my quarterback plans are yet, really,
because I don't know what the facts are yet,'' Parcells said.
``When I find out all the facts, I can make the plans. Now we've
discussed about three or four hypothetical situations and I told
you, if everything is status quo and everyone is healthy, then I'm
going to play Glenn in the game and that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm going to need both of these guys throughout the
course of the season. There isn't any doubt about it. Just look
around the league. Everybody's doing it. It's just like last week,
we needed the guy and he came through and he did heck of a job. He
threw four touchdown passes, he made good decisions, and didn't do
anything to hurt us. I was very pleased with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm more fortunate than most coaches that you have
a guy like this who's experienced and has talent and you can put in
the game and he can do something for you. I'm glad I got the guy. I
like the guy personally. He works hard. He's a diligent preparation
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens, but I don't have the facts at this
moment. I don't know how Foley's going to be. I've got to see
myself that everything is good with Foley. I can't just hear it.
I've got to see it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
