<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHERE Y2K IS NOTHING BUT THREE KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You have probably already read, and you can expect to
read a lot more in coming months, about something called Y2K.
Sounds like the secret ingredient for a miracle hair restorer.
Actually, it is a problem that is supposed to leave all us moderns
quaking in our Nikes, but has to bring a smile to anyone with mild
Luddite tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is shorthand for the programming bug that will prevent
zillions of computers from recognizing the year 2000 when it comes
around because they were weaned on a two-digit system for dates.
This year, for instance, is rendered simply as 98, with the 19
assumed. Expectations are that many machines will go cross-eyed
with the approaching double-ought rollover, believing that we are
back in 1900 and not in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Terrible consequences have been predicted, from airplanes
falling out of the sky to investment portfolios being wiped out.
But even if you are among those who suspect the world will somehow
muddle through, you have to sneer at a technology that lacks the
sense God gave a desk calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Tytell had to laugh. Y2K? ``To tell you the truth,'' he
said the other day, ``it doesn't bother me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it doesn't. Computers are meaningless to Tytell, who
at 85 is one of the few remaining typewriter repairmen in New York
City. ``A dying breed,'' he will tell you. But dying is not dead,
and this breed is not ready for its obituary, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Tytell has been building and repairing typewriters for 70 years,
the last 30 in a crowded shop up a flight from Fulton Street in
lower Manhattan. In his bow tie and white lab coat, a pen planted
in the breast pocket, he is master of a realm of cogs and key caps,
of rollers and ribbons, all competing for space with hundreds of
typewriters in English, German, Russian, Greek, Hebrew, Arabic,
Farsi, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Every few years, someone with a pen and note pad climbs the
stairs to see how this throwback to the precomputer age is getting
along. The visitor is always rewarded with grand tales of how
Tytell and his wife, Pearl, verified documents by the typewriters
that were used, how during World War II they built machines in 145
languages for the U.S. Army, how an upside-down letter in Burmese
inadvertently installed by Tytell became the accepted standard for
all Burmese typewriters.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the journey this time was to see if computers had
finally dealt typewriters a fatal blow. Happily, the answer was no.
</P>
<P>
   Young people, women in particular for some reason, have shown
new interest in the old machines, Tytell said. ``Some gal graduated
from Barnard, and her family decided to make her a present of the
typewriter that her grandma used, with Champagne and everything,''
he said. ``Something's going on there.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, a young man from Brooklyn carried in a slightly
battered Mercedes Selecta, an antique manual typewriter that he had
bought at a yard sale as a gift for his girlfriend, an aspiring
author. ``She wants to write with the same tools Hemingway wrote
with,'' the Brooklyn man explained.
</P>
<P>
   Some writers _ no names mentioned _ come to the shop when words
fail them, having convinced themselves that the fault lies not in
the stars but in the typewriter. ``They tell me that the machine is
not responding properly, even when it is in perfect shape,'' Tytell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Who is to say they are wrong? Certainly not Tytell, who believes
that typewriters have a soul, unlike you know what.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any question which kind of machine is healthier for
you? In the typewriter's heyday, you never heard about mass
outbreaks of repetitive stress injury, or about eyestrain from
staring too long at blinking images.
</P>
<P>
   Typewriters also fostered mental health. Nothing relieved a
struggling writer's frustration like ripping the paper out of the
roll and crumpling it. Think of all the computer weirdos you read
about these days, like the cybercultists who committed mass suicide
last year. You never had anything like that with the Smith-Corona
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As for durability, don't waste breath making comparisons. ``You
show me the computer that's going to last 15 years,'' Tytell said.
``But with these'' _ his hand swept across a row of old Olympias _
``you wipe them off and they're good for another 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And he expects to be around to nurse them, if not for decades
then certainly beyond the irrelevant Y2K.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
