<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DICKEY-PROFILE-ART-NY     09-21 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A SON, `DELIVERANCE' THROUGH A MEMOIR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Christopher Dickey is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When James Dickey _ the hard-drinking, hard-living
Southern poet and novelist _ died of liver disease in 1997, his son
Christopher forgot everything he had ever known about his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strange thing,'' the younger Dickey said,
sipping a cup of unsweetened tea (orange pekoe) at the Algonquin
Hotel last week. (He had asked for honey to soothe a bad case of
book-tour throat, but the newly reopened Algonquin could only offer
unsatisfying pink packets of Sweet 'n Low.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My memory completely blanked out,'' he said. ``But it's not
unique to me. I got an e-mail from a friend who had worked in the
same law office with his father for 20 years. And when his father
died, he said he looked at the desk where his father used to sit
and it was suddenly as if the only memory he had left was of a
cut-out silhouette he could hang on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dickey, who is the Paris bureau chief for Newsweek, had been
working with his father, taping their conversations for two years
before his death to put together some sort of memoir. The resulting
book is the younger Dickey's ``Summer of Deliverance: A Memoir of
Father and Son,'' published by Simon &AMP; Schuster this month.
</P>
<P>
   During their conversations, they talked about ``Deliverance,''
the novel that the senior Dickey published in 1971 and that was
turned into a movie in which he got to play the sheriff. They
talked about the elder Dickey's infidelities (many) and habitual
lying (like when he told his children he had once been married to a
woman who died, a story he later admitted he made up) and awards
(he won the National Book Award for his fourth book of poems) and
brave moments (rescuing Christopher's brother, Kevin, from a ski
lift) and writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had really gone back to be reconciled with him,'' Dickey
said. ``To try to reconcile myself with him. And you know you just
can't go home and walk in the door and say, `Hi, Dad, let's get
along.' So it seemed that working on a book together would be a way
to go back over our lives and talk and reach that point where
you're not just talking but make some real contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many literary families, the Dickeys _ who included Maxine,
Christopher's mother, and another son, Kevin, a radiologist who
teaches at Yale _ suffered because their lives became fodder for
James Dickey's writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roughly two-thirds of my father's poems are about fathers and
sons,'' Dickey said. For an interview after an appearance on the
``Today'' show and before one on ``The Charlie Rose Show,'' Dickey
wore khakis, a blue blazer and an Hermes tie printed with zebras.
``My father was literally in the business of imagining himself and
imagining us from before the time we were born. Look, my father was
describing me as `the parricidal vision from the loin' while I was
still in my mother's womb.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Dickey was born on Aug. 31, 1951, in Nashville. His
father moved the family to Texas, France, Italy, Florida,
California, Georgia, South Carolina, Mississippi _ wherever he
could teach or write or take advantage of a fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   But James Dickey's infidelities, his son said, cursed the
marriage. ``Our life was so public,'' he said. ``It's not as if my
father was a CEO and we were leading sheltered private lives that
anybody was talking about outside the country club. That's not the
way we ever lived our lives. I just got a letter the other day from
another woman who said she was his mistress in Atlanta. And she
said _ oh, you know, something like: `It was a great experience
knowing him. He was a wonderful man. Yes, he got drunk. Yes, he was
difficult.' And you know, I've gotten several of those kinds of
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rocky times at home and the moving, Christopher got
through Exeter, married at 18 and graduated from the University of
Virginia before going to The Washington Post. In 1976, Maxine
Dickey died at 50. Christopher was unprepared for her death, but
even less prepared for his father's marriage two months later to a
recent acquaintance, Deborah Dodson.
</P>
<P>
   That tormented marriage _ they were both alcoholics and at times
the sons feared for their father's life _ drove his sons away. In
the meantime, Christopher got divorced and began to write about
wars, terrorism, the contras. He remarried. He drifted away from
his father. He became Newsweek's Cairo bureau chief; he wrote a
couple of nonfiction books and a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years before his death, James Dickey stopped drinking.
He divorced his wife. And Christopher started talking to him again.
``He wanted to stop playing these endless mind games,'' Dickey
said. ``When he was dying, when I was helping him up and down the
stairs with his oxygen generator, and he would say, `You know you
could construct a whole book out of just the dialogue on these
landings.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey had two reasons for the book: First, it was a form of
survival. Journalist to the core, Dickey needed to record the
events happening before him. ``That exercise of him going up and
down the stairs and being in such terrible condition was hard to
know what to do with,'' he said. ``Except take notes, to do
something that could give me a little bit of distance.''
</P>
<P>
   The other reason: He loved his father. He misses him. ``I wanted
to bring him back,'' he said, his voice low. ``I wanted to write
about him with affection and honesty and love. I want him to live
on the page.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
