<SLUG> BC-NY-ROSH-HASHANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLEAK SPACE IS COLORIZED FOR PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 2 a.m. Sunday, just 18 hours before the start of
the Jewish new year and the High Holy Days, volunteers from Central
Synagogue entered the vast, bleak space of the empty 7th Regiment
Armory on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, an antiques show had moved out, ending its run a
day early to accommodate the congregation and its plan to turn the
airplane-hangar-sized armory into a place filled with warmth,
color, calm and spirituality before sundown.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish new year was observed by the thousands of synagogues
throughout the city. And for the third consecutive year, Temple
Emanu-El on Fifth Avenue put a shortened Rosh Hashana service on
the Internet, beginning at noon on Sunday to coincide with sundown
in Israel, said Mark Weissguch, the synagogue's administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Central Synagogue struggled with feelings of
loss and trepidation at the approach of the High Holy Days. Three
weeks ago, a fire heavily damaged their 126-year-old synagogue, an
architectural treasure on Lexington Avenue and 55th Street in
midtown Manhattan, and Gov. George Pataki ordered a state of
emergency to allow the congregation to use the New York State
Armory for the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   As one congregant said, ``I didn't have any idea what to
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of Monday's morning service, the majority said
they were more than satisfied by the transformation. Somehow, they
said, Robert Isabell, who designs expensive parties and receptions,
had managed to create in the huge, bleak space at 66th Street and
Park Avenue an atmosphere conducive to prayer and penitence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very sacred,'' said Paul Koren, an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt holy,'' said Marlin Potash, a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   But creating a contemplative feeling required 16 hours of
``impressive chaos,'' said Livia Thompson, Central Synagogue's
administrator. Because the antiques show did not begin to vacate
the armory until Saturday at midnight, the Isabell design staff and
volunteers began working at 2 o'clock on Sunday morning and did not
quit until 7 o'clock that night.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, when congregants entered the armory, they saw
a gigantic deep-red space with a stage and a towering backdrop that
was painted to resemble the familiar, dazzling colors and intricate
patterns of the original synagogue's Moorish designs. The rabbi, at
the fire-damaged lectern, was framed in a wooden arch. In the back,
a slide of the synagogue's rose window was projected on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly nobody mistook it for the original, but while many
congregants said they missed the glorious art of Central Synagogue,
they also said they felt comforted by the presence of one another.
The synagogue building could accommodate only 1,000 people. In the
armory, for the first time in memory, all 3,000 or so members could
pray together. And many expressed gratitude for the help of the
hundreds who had created the makeshift synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, the workers discovered that a donated ark _
which contains the Torahs, the temple's most sacred objects _ could
not be used. The workers had a half-hour to create and erect
another ark, Ms. Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Schlechter, a congregant coordinating the work, ran out
and bought curtain rods. The five Torahs were placed on chairs and
enclosed in red curtains, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The result, said Robert Friedman, a congregant and the president
of New Line Cinema's television operation, was a ``space that
works, but feels different _ dynamic. There's a specialness.
Everyone is coming through this together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
