</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOSLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUCCESS STORY DEFENDS HIS LIGHTWEIGHT TITLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shane Mosley, the International Boxing Federation
lightweight champion, is the antithesis of everything that is wrong
with boxing. He is a superbly talented boxer who fights all comers.
He gets along great with his father, Jack, who is also his manager
and trainer. And he is a good citizen whose name does not end up on
a police blotter once a month.
</P>
<P>
   And what has all that got Mosley? The title of the best
pound-for-pound fighter no one has heard of, even though he has
held his title since defeating Phillip Holiday on Aug. 2, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't create havoc or have any adversity in my life,''
Mosley said. ``Maybe that's what I have to do to get some
recognition. But I can't, because that's not who I am. This sport
needs success stories, and I feel I am successful. I'm a world
champion and I've accomplished the goals that I've set out to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, of Pomona, Calif., will headline a show at the Theater
at Madison Square Garden Tuesday night. It will be broadcast by
TNT. Mosley (28-0) will meet Eduardo Morales of Argentina (26-0) in
a 12-round title bout in the cable network's first foray into
boxing. Two junior lightweights, Angel Manfredy (24-2-1) of Gary,
Ind., and John Brown (18-4) of Atlantic City, will meet on the
undercard.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have not seen Mosley fight on HBO's ``Boxing After
Dark,'' this will be an opportunity to see one of the brightest
young boxers on the scene today and still get a good night's sleep.
Although on the West Coast Mosley is lost in the vast shadow of
Oscar De La Hoya, the World Boxing Council welterweight champion,
his profile has risen in the East. He has defended his title in
Atlantic City and in Philadelphia and has fought twice on the same
card as another brilliant young boxer, junior middleweight David
Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking up 125th Street the other day and this guy said,
`Hey, I can't believe the champ was going to walk right past me and
not say anything,''' Mosley said of a recent stroll in Harlem.
``That has never happened in Los Angeles. Even some of the police
officers here recognized me. That really surprised me. I feel like
an East Coast fighter. I get a lot of ink and a lot of hype here.
People here are very excited about the way that I fight.''
</P>
<P>
   There should be plenty of excitement and few surprises in the
ring tonight against Morales, whom Mosley described as a technical
fighter. ``He relies on his left hook a lot,'' Mosley said. ``He
doesn't give you any feints or razzle-dazzle.''
</P>
<P>
   While they were in Manhattan to promote the fight, Mosley and
Morales worked out at the Kingsway Boxing Center. Last Wednesday
their workouts overlapped. Mosley was finishing up his workout,
while Morales was just beginning. Mosley and his father watched
Morales spar. Typically, boxers do not want the opposing camp to
see what they are working on. But Mosley's presence did not seem to
bother Morales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of strange,'' Mosley said. ``But he really didn't
show anything that we haven't seen on tape from his last fight. He
wasn't really teeing off on his sparring partner or anything. He
really wasn't showing anything. He is a hard puncher, which his 24
knockouts show.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is also a hard puncher, with an affinity for working the
body. He has power in both hands. His footwork is magnificent, and
he can throw dazzling combinations. If he ever decides to get a
shtick, he will be sensational, because, right now, he has all the
moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
