<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA REVAMPS SECONDARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two days after Houston's second-class offense
gained 442 yards and scored 24 points against UCLA, the Bruins
revamped their sagging secondary, moving All-American Larry Atkins
while benching Marques Anderson and Eric Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   Only junior cornerback Jason Bell was left untouched in the
purge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well on defense,'' coach Bob Toledo said
Monday. ``If you're not playing well, you have to look beyond the
wins and get things corrected before something else happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins switched Atkins from strong safety to free safety,
where he replaces Whitfield, now a reserve cornerback.
Traditionally, strong safety is a run-support position, while free
safety defends the pass and roams the defensive backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Atkins) hasn't had the opportunity to make as many plays as
we'd like,'' Toledo said. ``By moving him, he'll be involved in
more plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-year senior Tod McBride will replace Atkins at strong
safety. A former receiver, McBride switched to safety last year and
is fully recovered from operations on both patellar tendons. He's
not the fastest man for the job, but he's the most physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves the opportunity to see what he can do,'' Toledo
said. ``He has waited his turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Roques, who was burned for one touchdown Saturday but
scored another, has replaced Anderson as the starting left
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anderson) did not play well at all,'' Toledo said in his most
stinging critique of a player this season. ``He didn't show a lot
of intensity. He didn't cover guys. He didn't tackle guys. Somebody
else deserves a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirty tricks? He kept quiet immediately following the game, but
two days and 2,000 miles later, Bruins quarterback Cade McNown
loosed a blistering attack on Houston's sportsmanship and stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt they played us dirty,'' McNown said. ``They had a lot
of cheap shots. They were going for our knees. They had late hits,
intentional stuff that doesn't have any place in college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Robertson Stadium) field was a joke. It was terrible.
There were sprinkler heads sticking up; I felt for (kicker) Chris
Sailer. It was like a fairgrounds. As soon as the venue shifted
from the Astrodome, we should have dropped them.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown said he tripped on uneven field before the game and
believes that may have caused Freddie Mitchell's broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the tackle he starts to run unevenly, and there was a
huge dip next to our sideline,'' McNown said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo refrained from criticizing Houston, instead directing his
ire at the Conference USA officials. ``The control of the game was
very poor,'' he said. ``We lost our poise, and they tried to
intimidate us.... But in (Houston coach) Kim Helton's defense, he
was irate after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Other changes: In all, the Bruins will have new starters at six
positions for Saturday's game at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale College transfer James Ghezzi has replaced Leona
Valley's Matt Phelan at left guard. Both are playing for starter
Oscar Cabrera, who's out at least a week with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to spark the Mitchell-less receiving corps, Brian
Poli-Dixon will start at split end. Former starter Brad Melsby is
the No. 2 flanker behind Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   With Kenyon Coleman out 3-4 weeks (sprained knee), Travor Turner
is the new starter at defensive end. Turner, dubbed the Sack Master
by teammates, had seven tackles against Houston and was named
UCLA's defensive player of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-98 2327EDT &QL; 
