<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-STEELERS-625&AMP;ADD-     09-21 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEELERS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: LET STEWART BE SLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MIAMI _ Kordell Stewart did not field questions after Pittsburgh
was dusted by Miami, 21-0, here on Sunday. He made a statement
about how his team was not at its best, how the offense did not
click, how his team got socked, how it is early in the season and
how changes need to be made. But no questions, please.
</P>
<P>
   Good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart knew what was coming after he passed for 3 yards in the
first half and then 82 for the game, spiced with three
interceptions, one that led to a Miami offensive touchdown and
another that the Miami defense returned for a touchdown. He knew
what was coming after an afternoon at quarterback where he looked
harried and distracted and plucked.
</P>
<P>
   Questions like these:
</P>
<P>
   Kordell, what went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Kordell, was this one bad game or the real you?
</P>
<P>
   Kordell, will the offense lose faith in you?
</P>
<P>
   Kordell, Kordell, Kordell.
</P>
<P>
   It happened, anyway. Stewart could not be asked, but it did not
stop those type of questions from being floated at the rest of the
Steelers, and particularly at running back Jerome Bettis.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome, do you think this team is losing confidence in Kordell?
</P>
<P>
   Bettis answered: ``No, not at all. It's just a situation where
we could not get anything going, that's all, and it happens like
that. We just have to go back and look at what we can do to take
the pressure off him, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, indeed, pressure on Kordell Stewart. His team is 2-1,
has struggled mightily on offense and has the unbeaten, high-flying
Seattle Seahawks (3-0) visiting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is evident on every National Football League
quarterback. Among them, Gus Frerrote in Washington and Scott
Mitchell in Detroit lost their starting jobs after one and two
weeks worth of games, respectively. Bobby Hoying is learning brutal
lessons in his first season as the Philadelphia starter. Rookie
Ryan Leaf won his first two games in San Diego and then made
1-of-15 passes (14 consecutive incompletions), fumbled three times
and was intercepted twice against Kansas City on Sunday. Rookie
Peyton Manning in Indianapolis looks awfully ordinary in the Colts'
awful 0-3 start, the latest a 44-6 drubbing by the Jets on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, though, has pressures external and internal that
differ. He is only 25 and has made only 23 regular-season starts.
But he produced early success and now he is expected to routinely
produce. Never mind the growing pains. He has done it. So, keep
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Or else the pressure swells. The whispers start. All of that old
garbage about a black quarterback and his thinking in the pocket
starts to surface. All of the trash about him being a scrambler and
not a passer rises.
</P>
<P>
   It is a no-win battle. So, Stewart must win to win. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two elements in the Pittsburgh loss to Miami that the
Steelers must recognize to bolster Stewart's confidence. First,
don't allow him to be boxed in the pocket. Second, script a handful
of running plays for him each game.
</P>
<P>
   What earned Stewart his nickname Slash was that he could rush
the football, play receiver and play quarterback.
Runner/receiver/quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   But Pittsburgh played into Miami's hands and allowed Stewart to
be limited primarily to pocket passing. This was a mistake,
especially back near the Steelers' own goal line, where Stewart was
trying to throw from the pocket over the middle into a layered zone
pass defense and was intercepted by Miami linebacker Zach Thomas
for a 17-yard touchdown return. It would be a lot to ask of Joe
Montana and Joe Namath in their prime, let alone Stewart, to read
that kind of defense and throw the ball into the middle of the
field under pressure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No, Stewart is better on the edges. A few more rollouts and
rotating pockets. What strikes fear in a defense is his mobility.
He needs to be outside the pocket frequently so that defenses are
struck with a bewildering question: Will he run or will he throw?
That moment of indecisiveness by the defense makes Stewart a better
passer and the offense a stronger threat. There was no reason that
Pittsburgh should have allowed Miami to put Stewart in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Stewart needs to run it more. Some think this opens a
can of worms, but, really, it opens more possibilities for the
Pittsburgh offense.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, after Miami was up by 14-0, Pittsburgh
faced a third-and-3 from its own 26. Stewart took the ball, rolled
right and easily dashed for 13 yards. First down. Out of a total of
60 Pittsburgh plays, he ran the ball only once more, for 4 yards.
He needs about five scripted runs a game. This helps keep defenses
on their heels. It makes them respect the running threat and
loosens the passing lanes. So what if people think he has become
more of a scrambler than a passer?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and the Steelers are sensitive. Both want everyone to
know he is a quarterback, a passer, first, and a scrambler, a
runner, occasionally. Both fight him being stereotyped, being put
in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Better that happen in perception than in reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
