<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE NOT LOOKING FOR NO. 1 PITCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers won't be seeing right-hander Kevin
Brown in their upcoming series with the San Diego Padres, and it is
probably for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Brown a leading candidate for the National League Cy
Young Award, he and Houston's Randy Johnson are the two top
pitchers in this winter's free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dodgers players say privately that acquiring a No. 1
starter should be the club's top offseason priority, new general
manager Kevin Malone says that isn't going to happen. Malone, whose
task of rebuilding the Dodgers is complicated by $53 million
already committed to 12 players, said it is not realistic to sign a
top pitcher to a multi-year contract worth $10 million when
pitching is not the club's most glaring weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to put labels on pitchers, No. 1 or No. 2 or No.
3,'' Malone said. ``I think we have a strong starting staff right
now, and adding to that might not be the best use of our resources.
I'd much rather have five No. 2s than a No. 1, three No. 4s and a
(No.) 5.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will go with Chan Ho Park in tonight's series opener
against the Padres. Since Dodgers ace Ramon Martinez was lost in
early June with a torn right rotator cuff, Park has been as close
as anyone to a No. 1 starter on the club.
</P>
<P>
   In his last three starts, Park has thrown 136 pitches twice and
137 in last Tuesday's 5-4 loss to Colorado. He has back-to-back
complete games, which has taken pressure off the Dodgers' tired and
injured bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not been overpowering the way he was during stretches
of last season, when he tied Hideo Nomo for the club lead with 14
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Carlos Perez has four consecutive complete-game
victories, the most since Orel Hershiser in 1988. He also has two
shutouts during that span and sounds as if he wants the No. 1 job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be a leader of the pitching staff,'' Perez said after
beating the San Francisco Giants 1-0 on Sunday. ``I learned a lot
watching (Cy Young winner) Pedro Martinez last year (in Montreal).
It took a few starts to get comfortable here, but I feel I am right
where I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek, who came over with Perez from the
Montreal Expos in a July 31 trade, is not sure Perez fits the mold
of a true No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of an ace, I think of one of those hard-throwing
right-handers like Roger Clemens or a Kevin Brown or a Ramon
Martinez,'' Grudzielanek said. ``Guys who are there to take the
ball. That is not a knock on any of our guys. We have pitchers who
could step up to be that guy someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the organization are hoping that guy will one day be
right-hander Darren Dreifort. Although he lost 12 games and will
miss the final three weeks with a sore shoulder, Dreifort struck
out 168 in 180 innings during his first year in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, Dreifort never pitched more than 63 innings in
a season. He is eligible for salary arbitration this winter.
Dreifort earned $685,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mlicki and Brian Bohanon, acquired from the New York Mets
in separate deals, have been impressive. Mlicki will earn $2.25
million in 1999. Bohanon is a free agent. With all the money
already locked up, and with Grudzielanek, catcher Charles Johnson
and pitcher Ismael Valdes eligible for salary arbitration, Bohanon
probably would get a better contract on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Valdes, who couldn't get out of the third inning in
Saturday's 18-4 loss to the Giants. He pitched well in three starts
after coming off the disabled list, but there still are concerns
about his grit during games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were worried enough about Valdes not reaching his
potential that they tried to package him last June in a deal with
Seattle. The Mariners wanted Dreifort.
</P>
<P>
   For a No. 1 starter named Randy Johnson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
