<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players back coach after tough Bengal loss
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ While Bruce Coslet was being crucified on a sports
talk-radio station Monday, Bengals players stood behind their coach
in the wake of Sunday's 13-6 loss to the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 10-3 just before intermission, Coslet ordered an option
play that failed on third-and-goal at the Packers' 1-yard line,
then _ instead of going for a TD _ Doug Pelfrey kicked a 19-yard
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said the option should have resulted in a Jeff Blake TD.
There was only one problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a key block or we walk in. It's just simple,'' he
said. ``(The Packers) were poorly deployed to even attempt to stop
that play. It didn't work because of a missed block. We have
everybody else sealed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pelfrey, ``You've got to play the percentages and that's
what Bruce was doing. If we would have left at halftime and not
gotten those three points, that would have been more demoralizing
than getting the three points.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Brian Milne said, ``You can't second-guess your head
coach. You have to be one as a team, do what he says and go from
there. It was the right decision, especially if you don't make (a
touchdown) in the first three shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet kept his composure, refusing to lash out at the tidal
wave of criticism against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some were saying (the field goal) was because I had no
confidence in our offense,'' Coslet said. ``Not true. It's that I
had confidence in our defense. I told the defense that at halftime.
I said: `Defense this is why I took the three. I have confidence in
you. You're playing 'em tough. Keep it up.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a chance to put points on the board against the
Packers, you better do it. Sure, it would have been nice to get a
touchdown. But you've got to understand the ramifications of let's
say we go for it and don't make it. Now we get no points. So you
pick and choose. That's what I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second guess me all you want. I really don't mind that. That's
your prerogative. But you have to know all the preparation that
goes into getting ready for an opponent like this, the struggles we
did have up to that point offensively and how well our defense was
playing. I'd do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
