<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-Q-AND-A     09-21 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with Evander Holyfield
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield spoke with Atlanta
Journal-Constitution staff writer Jeff Schultz for nearly two hours
at the boxer's estate in Fairburn, Ga. on Sunday night about the
recent birth of two out-of-wedlock children, infidelity and the
difficulties of his marriage. Also present was Holyfield's
attorney, Jim Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What led to your infidelity during your current marriage and
the births of two other children?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wasn't happy with the decision I made to get married. After
the fight against Mike Tyson (in 1996), I talked to my pastor
(Creflo Dollar). He said I need to work at it, but I was still very
confused. I wondered if I just wanted to get out of the marriage.
During that period of time, when I was down, both of these women
got pregnant. When each woman told me, I told Janice, but she
didn't want to leave me. So we continued to go to counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long had you been going to counseling?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since just after the Tyson fight (one month after the
marriage). Then when the other two women got pregnant, I told
Janice we could just quietly get out of the marriage before the
babies were born because I was concerned she would be humiliated
and the grief she was gonna get. One thing I realized was, I was
going to take care of the kids even though I didn't intend to have
them. I knew I would be there for the kids. I tried to get her to
see that it would be a good reason for her to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did it surprise you that Janice wanted to stay married?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Janice and I were friends before we got married. She knew
everything about me, all the women I had kids with, everything. We
prayed together. I could tell her anything. When I got married, I
said, ``Hey, I feel I did this for the wrong reasons. I'm sorry.
What can we do about this?'' I got married because I thought it was
what God wanted me to do. But sometimes we do things because it's
what God wanted and later we realized it was wrong. Everything
turned upside-down. Everything that I felt I had overcome, I
slipped back and went down the same road. . . . If Janice had said,
``Well, let's go (divorce),'' it would've made things a lot easier.
I thought it would be better to do it right away than wait five
years and then say you made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is your marital situation now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not going to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You could have supported your children financially but not
publicly acknowledged them. Why are you admitting this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kids shouldn't suffer from the ignorance or mistakes of their
parents. They're my kids and I don't put nothing before my kids
except God.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How have they reacted to all of this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I talk to them. I don't want them to make the same mistakes
that I made. I want them to realize sometimes parents make wrong
decisions. I teach them that their life doesn't have to be this
way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You realize, of course, that your image is going to be
damaged by this.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not overly concerned. I've overcome this. People need to
realize when they look at my life that I've had a lot of situations
that I've overcome. This is just one more thing I will overcome. My
kids won't end up this way and that's what's important _ when your
kids don't make the same mistakes you make.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You consider yourself a devout Christian. Isn't your
infidelity in conflict with your religious beliefs?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I believe in is what will allow me to overcome it. A lot
of people don't get on board (religiously) because they think other
people will say, ``Y'all will think I'm a hypocrite if I make a
mistake.'' But the family you come from, your community, your
father, his father, what values you were taught as a kid _ these
are where bad habits come. I've made mistakes before but I didn't
have a big name. Now I have a big name, so everybody knows my
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you also have put your Christianity in the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but that's what allows people to know, ``If he overcomes
this, I can overcome it too. He's a Christian man.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has sexual responsibility always been a problem for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: It started when I was 20 years old (while dating his first
wife, Paulette). I've never thought what I did was right. Wrong is
wrong. Putting on a condom is just as wrong as not having one. I'm
a Christian. Being with another woman with a condom on is wrong.
Until someone learns to abstain, that's the only way they can never
make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You married Paulette in 1985 because Evander Jr. had been
born?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wanted to do the right thing as a father. Of course, I
wasn't really happy then and I made the same mistake. But I was so
young and irresponsible. Once I got out of that marriage (and had
other relationships), it was, ``Trust me. I'm on birth control.''
But whether it's (the woman's) irresponsibility or my
irresponsibility, I have to take care of the baby. And I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe other women have tried to trap you into
marriage?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't say that. I would say that everybody I had a baby
with desired to marry me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: President Clinton's sexual indiscretions dominate the news.
What would you tell people who say you are no better than he is?
</P>
<P>
   A: The difference is people have the opportunity to know me for
who I am. I never said I haven't made a mistake in this area. I've
let them know I have. I've even told companies, ``I don't mind you
signing me up (for endorsements), but these are things I have
done.'' I didn't want them to find something out later and say,
``Oh, he deceived us. We thought he was a perfect person.'' I'm not
the type of person stealing someone's trust by telling them
something that I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is fidelity still a struggle?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I feel like I've overcome it all now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How have you been able to mentally shut out your personal
life while boxing, particularly before the (first) Tyson fight,
which was the biggest of your career?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't let one aspect of your life weigh on another aspect
of your life. But the reason I've been more successful in one area
than another is I'm not applying the same discipline. I pray over
my boxing. I work hard. I haven't been in that mode in my personal
life. I make excuses, like, ``I ain't got no father (who raised
him).''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What changes have you made?
</P>
<P>
   A: I realize now I have to spend more time with my kids, like
going to see my sons play football the other day (before last
Saturday night's bout). I didn't want to be there, but I realized I
needed to be. I have to break the habit of just doing what I want
to do in my spare time. I didn't become great overnight in boxing,
but I kept my focus. Now I think my family is getting better
because I'm focused on them like I always focused on fighting. I've
got to save my family.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
