<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mere mortals pale in the shadow of Ripken's accomplishment
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On the clubhouse television, Baltimore's Cal
Ripken, Jr., sat in front of a camera, his sea-blue eyes flashing
under his receding gray hairline.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Orioles uniform off and somebody might ask, ``Who's
that, Mark McGwire's high school principal?''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's The Graphite Man. Iron Man? Ripken far surpassed the
iron age with his unfathomable run of 2,632 straight appearances on
a baseball field. Not even a robot could play in 2,632 straight
baseball games without blowing a circuit and getting an arm knocked
off on a slide.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati shortstop Barry Larkin watched the television as he
dressed for Monday night's game, a game in which he wouldn't play
due to a sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what is more significant, what Mc-Gwire and Sammy Sosa are
doing to the home-run record, or what Ripken did over the course of
the past 16 baseball seasons, Larkin pointed to the television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely what that man did,'' Larkin said. ``Not to slight
what the other boys are doing, but you can't even do what Ripken
did on Nintendo. You can hit 65 home runs on Nintendo.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Taubensee, who has started only one of the last
six games because he is exhausted after catching in a career-high
127 games, smiled as he watched Ripken and said, ``He and I have
one thing in common. Neither one of us has ever been on the
disabled list. I've never been on the DL, not even in the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an amazing accomplishment for a catcher, but Taubensee
realizes it doesn't come close to Ripken's streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat out Sunday's game because Cal sat out,'' Taubensee said
with a laugh. ``Hey, 2,632 straight games? He deserves a day off. I
can't imagine that. On our team we see Barry Larkin and Bret Boone
try to play every day . . . but every day for 16 years? Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone leads the Reds by playing in 151 games this season and had
played in all until August. He realizes the difficulty of playing
every game in one year, not to even consider 16 years of never
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine that,'' he said. ``At one time, about
three or four years ago, I thought I could play every day of my
life. No way and good luck. There are times you just hit the wall
and you have to take a day off . . . and that doesn't even take
into consideration getting hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon says it will never happen again. That's what
they said, too, when Lou Gehrig played 2,130 games. But times have
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term contracts, bad advice from other people . . .
players these days who are just hanging on want out of the
lineup,'' McKeon said. ``They won't play hurt. A lot of days Ripken
had to be hurt, a sore ankle or something. It's a tribute to him
that he set an example for young players on how to play the game.
Hurt? Tired? You persevere and play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of self-determination, discipline and desire to
do that,'' McKeon added. ``Somebody do it again? Never. Not even
close. You have to be tough, real tough and be a gamer who wants to
come to the park and be ready to play every day. I don't see that
these days . . . and he'll probably be in the Hall of Fame because
he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader now is Albert Belle of the Chicago White Sox, 327
games, and he burst out laughing (and Belle never laughs) when
asked about somebody playing 2,633 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one record Ripken doesn't have to worry about anyone
breaking,'' Belle said. ``That's one record I 've never thought
about. That's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
